<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 00:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4302 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROCKIES-ASTROS-HN     05-28 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKIES-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
Chris Holt was so close to victory Thursday afternoon he could
almost reach out and touch it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But again, the Astros did everything inhumanly possible to
snatch victory from the grasp of the hard-luck righthander, losing
4-3 to the Colorado Rockies before a crowd of 25,146 at the
Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   No offense.
</P>
<P>
   No relief.
</P>
<P>
   And one disgruntled clubhouse leader.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros departed on their longest road trip of the season
with their four-game winning streak a distant memory and questions
surfacing about an offensive unit suddenly weakened by a rash of
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're scoring a lot of runs, nobody's complaining,'' said
All-Star second baseman Craig Biggio, who went 0-for-5 and
committed a first-inning error that led to two unearned runs. ``But
when we're not, everyone is saying `Why, why, why.'''
</P>
<P>
   Biggio's remarks came in response to postgame comments by
manager Larry Dierker regarding the Astros' struggles at the plate
during the four-game series with the Rockies, which produced three
victories.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had just four hits Thursday and scored 13 runs in the
series while batting .224.
</P>
<P>
   And while the offense was an easy target after the Astros missed
an opportunity to sweep the Rockies, the bullpen also was culpable.
Namely, Trever Miller.
</P>
<P>
   The little-used lefthander walked three batters, threw two wild
pitches and gave up the go-ahead run on a sacrifice fly by Henry
Blanco in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deserved the loss today. I didn't get it done,'' said
Miller, who has walked seven in 9 innings this season. ``Three
walks to three lefties. Those are supposed to be guys I'm supposed
to get out. That's terrible. I've never done that my entire
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado starter Bobby Jones held the Astros to four hits and
three runs in six innings, and Jerry Dipoto (1-2) and former Astro
Dave Veres combined for three scoreless innings of relief.
</P>
<P>
   Facing the top of the Astros' batting order, Veres pitched a
perfect ninth for his fifth save. He struck out Biggio, got Bill
Spiers to line out and struck out Jeff Bagwell.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado relievers have blown nine saves this season, but Veres
was untouchable for the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting Biggio out was the key,'' Veres said. ``If he gets on
base, who knows what happens?''
</P>
<P>
   Holt, trying to snap his 0-6 start, took a 3-2 lead to the
seventh but gave up singles to Jeff Reed and pinch hitter Lenny
Harris to start the inning and was replaced by Brian Williams.
Darryl Hamilton's sacrifice fly tied the game at 3.
</P>
<P>
   Holt allowed seven hits and three runs and struck out five.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just got a lot of bad luck,'' said Holt, who sat out last
season recovering from shoulder surgery and hasn't won since Aug.
21, 1997. ``I've just got to go out and change it myself. It's not
like nobody's battling. It's just that the monkey's on my back
right now. I'm just snakebit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies snapped the 3-3 tie in the ninth when Miller (0-1)
walked Todd Helton and Chris Petersen reached on a fielder's
choice. Petersen later advanced to third on a pair of wild pitches
and Blanco drove in the eventual winning run with a fly to deep
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lesson to all young kids out there: Don't walk the
leadoff batter,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Larry Dierker defended using Miller in the ninth inning,
saying he was cautious because his bullpen was depleted and he was
saving closer Billy Wagner for potential extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt with the hitters they had due that if Trever could
throw strikes, he would probably get them out,'' Dierker said.
``But he didn't throw strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough day at the plate. I think we missed some
opportunities against (Jones) to really give Holt some cushion
there. We just couldn't get the key hit. In the end, all the walks
and wild pitches. Once again we were right there at the end of the
game with a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado took a 2-0 lead in the first inning when Hamilton led
off with a single and advanced to second on a sacrifice. Biggio
dropped shortstop Spiers' throw on Larry Walker's fielder's-choice
grounder, allowing one run to score, and Vinny Castilla doubled in
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros sliced the lead in the second on an RBI single by
Russ Johnson and went ahead in the third when Jones walked Derek
Bell with two outs and Richard Hidalgo followed with his seventh
home run. Hidalgo had seven home runs during his rookie season last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo also threw out Walker at third base in the third inning
for his league-leading eighth outfield assist.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros managed just one hit after the third inning _ not
exactly the desired send-off for a team that won't return home
until June 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really haven't hit the last six, seven games,'' said
Bagwell, who celebrated his 31st birthday Thursday. ``We did have
some opportunities today and just didn't get the big hit. It's been
this way lately, and we're still winning. That says a lot for our
pitching staff. We win as a team and lose as a team. We just have
to go battle. If we don't start swinging the bats a little better,
it's going to be a problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
