A4303 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     05-28 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
CRAIG Biggio made a bad error early and perhaps a worse one later.
As usual, Chris Holt couldn't buy a break _ early or late. Worse,
the wrong team got the timely hits while the home team barely got
any hits.
</P>
<P>
   Their adrenaline apparently spent from the previous evening's
ninth-inning rally, the Astros played tired and succumbed
listlessly 4-3 to the Rockies on Thursday, leaving town for what
seems forever on a sour, atypical note. This wasn't the team that
leads the National League in winning percentage.
</P>
<P>
   These guys were a bunch of impostors. Crabby ones, too. Most
uncharacteristically, perhaps unprecedentedly, an internal squabble
erupted afterward between the designated team leader, Biggio, and
his boss, Larry Dierker. Or maybe it's the other way around.
Sometimes that's open to question, given Biggio's stature in the
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker, who is only the manager, expressed concern with the
Astros' recent offensive doldrums. A mere 13 runs crossed the plate
in the four Colorado games, and Dierker noted same afterward. He
also mentioned, in passing, how he had considered giving Biggio the
day off, saying: ``He's been playing hard. In hindsight, I should
have rested him.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Nobody suffered the slings and arrows of the night-game,
early-day-game turnaround more than Biggio, whose two-out RBI
single in the ninth beat the Rockies on Wednesday. But just three
batters into Thursday's series wrap-up he was the goat-in-waiting,
erring on a routine play that led to a pair of unearned Colorado
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Walker's grounder to Bill Spiers at short should have
trapped Darryl Hamilton between the bases, but Spiers' toss to
second _ it wasn't on the money, either _ smacked off Biggio's
glove and rolled into short center, allowing Hamilton to score.
Walker came home on Vinny Castilla's double.
</P>
<P>
   Because the final score was 4-3, and it also set in motion
another winless outing _ his eighth this season _ for the snakebit
Holt, tensions lingered afterward. Biggio's 0-for-5 day, which
included leaving a man on second and ended with a strikeout, put
him in a surly mood. Hence, Dierker's routine, innocuous, accurate
comments about the lack of clutch hitting must have scraped an
exposed nerve.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't specifically directed at Biggio, but you know how
that goes sometimes. Anyway, the second baseman suggested perhaps
the skipper should pick up a bat and go drive in a few runs
himself.
</P>
<P>
   No, Dierk wasn't later spied in the batting cage, taking cuts
while he waited for the bus to the airport. Nor did he so much as
raise an eyebrow about Biggio's ire. It's well-documented that ol'
Sluggo's ego is ever-manageable. The biggest upset of the season
will be if this lover's spat becomes anything more than yesterday's
news tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are things were sorted out by the time the Astros landed
in Pittsburgh late Thursday. Dierker, for his part, promised it
wouldn't become ``a New York thing,'' i.e., blown out of
proportion.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the matter is newsworthy because the Astros under Dierker
always have been, relatively speaking, the happiest of campers, a
bunch of hail fellows well met tugging in the same direction.
</P>
<P>
   Biggio and Dierk's predecessor, the tightly wound Terry Collins,
were in each other's faces on a frequent basis, but peace and quiet
has been the order of the day under the current regime.
</P>
<P>
   So why the outburst? Maybe fatigue was to blame. Well before he
had been informed of Biggio's snippy outburst, Dierker's fanny was
dragging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to bed at 2 (a.m.) and was up at 8,'' Dierker said. ``I
was beat, and I don't have to do anything physical. I was not that
proud of how we played today, but I can understand it. I don't
think it's a good idea to start day games at 12:30 after night
games. They must think it helps the gate, but I don't like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the getaway-day circumstances _ Colorado headed to
Philly _ the start was mandated by baseball's rules. But 12:35, as
opposed to, say, 1:35, is management's call. To compensate, Dierker
canceled batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we did was run and play some catch to loosen up the
bones,'' he said. ``We've got a long trip coming up, too.''
</P>
<P>
   But not a particularly demanding one, given the level of the
competition. The next 12 games are divided evenly among four
sub-.500 teams _ Pittsburgh, Milwaukee, Minnesota and the Chicago
White Sox _ with no vast distances to cover between series. Even
short-handed, even with the superstar second baseman in a temporary
snit, the Astros' wheels are hardly in any grave danger of coming
off.
</P>
<P>
   ``At worst,'' Dierker said, ``we should be able to hang in
there. We've got a chance to win enough to not lose any ground.''
</P>
<P>
   We won't see the Astros live and in person again until June 11.
Hopefully, they can still be in first place and Thursday's
disharmony will be long forgotten. The smart money says it will be.
</P>
</TEXT>
