<HEADER>
A4304 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-LUYENDYK-HNS &LR;      05-28 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-LUYENDYK-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
INDIANAPOLIS _ Arie Luyendyk was no wide-eyed kid when he first
arrived at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway in 1985, although his
shoulder-length blond hair made him appear younger than a man who
had been a race-car driver for 12 years.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In truth, many of the old-timers around the Brickyard looked at
Luyendyk as some kind of Dutch hippie who was out of his league
trying to compete with the likes of A.J. Foyt, Bobby and Al Unser,
Mario Andretti, Johnny Rutherford and Rick Mears.
</P>
<P>
   But looks can be deceiving. Luyendyk was 31, married and a
father. He also was a determined and quiet man who was all business
when it came to his racing career, and he had the talent to prove
it.
</P>
<P>
   From Rookie of the Year in 1985 to the Indianapolis 500 winner
in 1990 and 1997, Luyendyk is one of the best to ever make a lap at
the famous speedway. Sunday will be his 15th start at Indy and the
final race of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a difficult process, because it means walking away from
the only way of life I've ever known,'' Luyendyk said. ``I grew up
in the sport as a road racer, but people know me for winning the
Indy 500.''
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk holds or shares many of the records at Indianapolis,
including $5.2 million in earnings in his 14 previous starts. He
has been on the front row five times and is a three-time pole
winner, including this year. Luyendyk is the 12th driver to start
from the pole in his last Indy 500 start, but Bobby Unser is the
only driver to win from the pole in his final Indy 500 in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk holds IMS records for fastest race average speed
(185.981 mph in 1990) and fastest official lap (237.498 mph, 1996).
It was those stunning speeds three years ago that first caused
Luyendyk to consider retiring from the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made it no secret that one reason I'm retiring is that at
age 45 I'm not willing to take the same risks I took in previous
years,'' Luyendyk said. ``When you come right down to it, this is a
sport where a driver is constantly weighing the risk vs. the
reward. For me, that ratio started to tip in the wrong direction.''
</P>
<P>
   With four kids, a wife of 20 years and a beautiful home in
Scottsdale, Ariz., Luyendyk's priorities were changing. The one
incident that clearly altered his outlook came when close friend
Scott Brayton was killed in a practice-session crash in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott's accident really struck me, because of who he was and
how the accident happened,'' Luyendyk said. ``It really was out of
Scott's control entirely, and I was thinking, `Man, it can happen
to me. It could have been me. It could have been anybody.'''
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk told his wife, Mieke, he would retire if he won Indy
again. He lied. Not intentionally, but he didn't believe he was
ready to quit after he won the race in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel I could stop cold turkey,'' Luyendyk said.
``Driving is always going to turn me on, always going to get me
excited. But just like my wife said, `When you're 60, it's still
going to turn you on, but at 60 you shouldn't be driving a race
car.' As a driver, you always want to compete, you always want to
be part of it. But there comes a time when you have to say to
yourself, `Stop.' I don't want to wait for signs like my reaction
time isn't there anymore. I wanted to get out before that.''
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk also wanted more time with his family. Arie Jr., his
17-year-old son, is beginning his racing career and Luyendyk wants
to be there to help him.
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk also will continue to be involved in Treadway Racing
with team owner and close friend Fred Treadway. Luyendyk will be a
spokesman for Sprint PCS and will work as a commentator for Fox
Sports during the telecasts of the other Indy Racing League events
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether Luyendyk gets a third Indy 500 win Sunday,
his place in the history of the sport is set.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes without saying that Arie ranks right up there with all
of the great drivers that have won this race,'' said IMS president
Tony George. ``He is among the distinguished few who have won here
more than once. It's safe to say that when his name comes up on the
ballot for induction into the Hall of Fame, he will be elected on
the first ballot.''
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk is trying not to think about the finality of the moment
until after the race ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to stay focused on the racing part,'' Luyendyk said.
``I've never met John Elway, Wayne Gretzky or Michael Jordan, but
I'm certain I'm feeling the same emotions they were earlier this
year when they decided to retire. The Super Bowl provided the
perfect stage for Elway to bid farewell. Indianapolis does that for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk wants to win, but realistically he just hopes his car
is still on the track when the checkered flag waves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the high point of the emotional roller coaster will
be, hopefully, being around at the end of the race,'' Luyendyk
said. ``That's probably going to be the point where I might get a
little emotional in my helmet. Then I will realize I just drove 500
miles to my retirement.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
