<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
 
DiSARCINA WON'T RUSH IT 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Shortstop Gary DiSarcina continues to make steady
progress toward returning to the field, but says he won't rush
himself.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina, who sustained a broken bone in his left forearm Feb.
21 and later had surgery on the arm, took batting practice Tuesday
and Wednesday for the first time since the injury. He had already
been fielding ground balls and hitting soft toss.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina probably will begin a rehab assignment in three or
four weeks, but says as good as he's feeling it wouldn't make sense
to come back sooner than what was initially anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing I'm going to do after sitting patiently for
eight weeks is to do something stupid ... like hitting off Troy
Percival,'' DiSarcina said. ``I don't want to destroy the work
that's been done by the doctors.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina took off batting practice Thursday to give his body a
chance to recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have all the spring training symptoms,'' he said. ``I have
sore feet, sore hands, a sore mid-section. For me, having those
things this time of year? Gosh, it's not right. But I've gone home
the last couple nights pretty happy. I'd rather have that soreness
than soreness in my (rear). I've picked up enough splinters to have
firewood in the offseason.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina had a four-inch plate inserted into his forearm to aid
in the healing, but says now recovery is a matter of building
strength and endurance in his hand and wrist.
</P>
<P>
   Is Angels manager Terry Collins becoming senile? Although
Collins turned 50 Thursday, his lineup wasn't anything but an
effort to shake things up a little and give a few bench players an
opportunity to play.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Palmeiro started in right field and hit leadoff, bumping
regular leadoff hitter Darin Erstad to the No. 6 spot. Shorstop
Andy Sheets moved from ninth to second, and Randy Velarde went from
second to fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Huson got a rare start at first base and batted eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to put out the best lineup I can,'' Collins
said. ``You put these guys in a situation where they've got to
perform, and it they don't get some at-bats along the way, it's
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Angels' pitchers took batting practice in preparation
for their games in National League ballparks, the Angels position
players held a hitters meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Hitting coach) Rod (Carew) wanted to get everybody together
and go over our game plan on (Orioles starter Juan) Guzman,''
Collins said. ``And they also reviewed the last couple of days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have lost to injury their Gold Glove center fielder
(Jim Edmonds) and two of the league's better defensive players in
right fielder Tim Salmon and DiSarcina.
</P>
<P>
   Yet going into Thursday's game they were tied for first in the
A.L. in fielding percentage (.985).
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played great,'' Collins said. ``Garret (Anderson) has
done the job in center, Andy Sheets at shorstop and Troy Glaus has
played tremendous at third base.''
</P>
<P>
   The pitching also has been big for the Angels. At 4.39, the team
ERA ranked second only to Boston (4.09) in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels and Royals begin a three-game series beginning
tonight at 7:05. Chuck Finley (3-4, 4.45 ERA) will start for
Anaheim against Kansas City's Kevin Appier (5-2, 4.00).
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS VS. KANSAS CITY
</P>
<P>
   Time: 7:05 p.m. at Edison Field
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: No TV; KLAC-570, XPRS-1090
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: Chuck Finley (3-4, 4.45 ERA) is coming off his best
start of the season -- nine scoreless innings in the Angels' 4-0,
10-inning victory against Tampa Bay last Sunday. Finley has had
success vs. the Royals during his career, going 13-8 with a 2.78
ERA. Kevin Appier (5-2, 4.00) will start for Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   -- Joe Haakenson
</P>
</TEXT>
