<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4306 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-BIGGIO-HNS     05-28 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BIGGIO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
On Wednesday, Craig Biggio was the hero, smashing the game-winning
hit in the bottom of the ninth.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Thursday, after going 0-for-5 and committing an error that
led to two unearned runs in the first inning, he was offended by
manager Larry Dierker's comments that he wasn't satisfied with the
team's offense in the four-game homestand against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the game of baseball; that's the way it goes
sometimes,'' Biggio said. ``He's not complaining when we're scoring
eight or nine runs. We've got a lot of guys hurt right now. If he
can hit, let him go hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said all along you have to win some games 2-1 and you
have to win some games 9-8. Last year, we did that pretty good. So
far, we're doing that pretty good this year. That's baseball.
That's the way it goes. Maybe there was a lack of offense right
now, but their pitchers pitched outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll get our offense going in Pittsburgh. Maybe
Larry (Dierker) will be hitting first.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros managed four hits in losing 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed opportunities against their starting pitcher (Bobby
Jones) that would have given (Astros starter Chris) Holt a
cushion,'' Dierker said. ``We've got to find ways to get him
wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's lack of offense came just hours after Biggio's
game-winner in a 3-for-5 performance Wednesday. After that game,
Dierker gave some of the credit to pinch runner Glen Barker for
helping Biggio get a good pitch to hit, in an at-bat in which
Biggio fouled off several two-strike pitches before delivering the
decisive hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That whole situation at first base (pinch runner Glen Barker
playing cat-and-mouse with pitcher Pedro Astacio and eventually
stealing second), maybe Biggio got a pitch to hit because of it, or
maybe he (Astacio) just made a mistake,'' Dierker said Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   That, too, may have gotten under Biggio's skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get about four hours of sleep and you come out and try to
play today, and it's tough on both sides,'' Biggio said. ``Today we
just didn't get it done. We have a lot of guys that are hurt.
That's just the way it goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you score a lot of runs, nobody's complaining. When you
don't score, everybody's going, `Why, why, why?' But if we go on a
run and get hot, nobody will say anything anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the four games against the Rockies were decided by one
run. The Astros scored five runs in the opener Monday, then totaled
eight in the other three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got some good pitchers over there,'' Biggio said. ``If
he (Dierker) wants to hit, let him hit. He can hit first if he
wants. If he's so worried about our offense, let him hit for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said he wasn't upset by Biggio's comments and said he
was willing to sit down with his second baseman on the road trip to
clear the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me,'' Dierker said. ``It doesn't bother me
at all. Biggio and I are fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker considered giving Biggio the day off Thursday, and after
his leadoff hitter went 0-for-5 he second-guessed his decision not
to. Biggio, who is hitting .282 for the season, went 4-for-18
(.222) on the homestand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about giving Biggio a day off, but he'd been playing
pretty hard and swinging the bat so well,'' Dierker said. ``He was
lunging at the ball and swinging at bad pitches a week or so ago,
and I thought he had gotten out of it and gotten locked in pretty
good. Today he went back to the way he was.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros took three of four during the brief homestand, but
the expected offense was missing. The Rockies brought the National
League's worst pitching staff (team ERA of 5.92) to the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros boast the best team average, .281. That staff held
the Astros to a .224 average this week.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Astros have had a slew of injuries recently and
have recalled several players from Class AAA New Orleans. Biggio,
however, didn't want to use that as an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't replace a lot of these guys who are hurt right now,
but we have a lot of guys who are good,'' Biggio said. ``But we
have a lot of guys who are really good, and they're going out and
battling. If you're in the big leagues, you're here for a reason,
and that's because you can play. It's not who's in our lineup or
who's not in our lineup.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
