u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-CLEMENS-NYT     05-28 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CLEMENS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DELIVERING A MESSAGE, WITH A LITTLE CHIN MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Roger Clemens has insisted that Thursday night's
start against the Red Sox did not have any special meaning for him.
Sure.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens has recited these words, but one wonders if he had also
crossed his fingers and toes as he spoke. No special meaning?
Sorry, Roger. That is impossible to fathom.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine being a salesman for 13 years and selling more products
than anyone else in the company. Then the company decides that it
no longer needs you. Three years later, you are still a dominant
salesman and are working for your old employer's main competitor.
Would you think there was special meaning to outselling your old
employer? Of course you would.
</P>
<P>
   The best pitcher in Red Sox history wore a Yankee uniform
Thursday night and pitched against the franchise that had no use
for him after the 1996 season. Even though there are only a handful
of players on the current team who played with Clemens in Boston,
that is irrelevant because Clemens is motivated by his disdain for
the front office. That is why there was special meaning for Clemens
after he steered the Yankees to a 4-1 victory. Stubborn on and off
the mound, he just would not concede it.
</P>
<P>
   Every win is important for us now,'' said Clemens, who addressed
reporters for a few minutes and dodged talk about the
attractiveness of the matchup.
</P>
<P>
   The night started with Elton John crooning ``Rocket Man'' over
the public address system while Clemens trotted to the mound, a
song that was indirectly suggested by Mike Stanley. After Stanley
asked the Yankees if they planned to play the song for the Rocket,
team officials stammered that they had not and then pounced on the
neat idea.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Clemens claimed this was another game on the schedule,
he still pumped his fist after Stanley struck out in the fifth.
When Clemens got Damon Buford to slap into a double play to end the
inning, he clenched his fist again. It was not another game. It was
Clemens sending a high and tight message to the Red Sox after
spicing his seven powerful innings with seven strikeouts. Do you
miss me yet?
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have finished his career with the Red Sox,'' said
Bill Fischer, the pitching coach in Boston when Clemens was there.
``He's like Yastrzemski, Williams and Pesky. If you've got a Hall
of Famer, you don't treat him like a second-line citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   When Fischer, who is now the pitching coach for the Class AAA
Richmond Braves, was asked what it is like to see Clemens pitching
for the Yankees, he said, ``That's like Babe Ruth playing right
field against the Red Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   Three hours before the first pitch, John Valentin studied
videotape of Clemens from last season when he was pitching for
Toronto. It must have worked as Valentin had Boston's only two hits
and only run batted in off Clemens, who is 3-0 with a 1.64 earned
run average against the Red Sox and has also won an American League
record 19 straight decisions overall. Still, Valentin was in awe.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's most amazing about Roger is, for all the games I've
played behind him, every time I see him he's better than I think he
is,'' said Valentin. ``He's a great pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin grew up in Jersey City and adored the Yankees, so he
understood from the time he was a boy that it is natural for Yankee
fans to hate the Red Sox and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   He was immersed in the rivalry after joining the Red Sox in 1992
and admitted that Thursday night would make Boston fans queasy and
gave him mixed emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to realize that playing behind him and the work ethic
that he puts into each start, it's pretty incredible,'' Valentin
said. ``By doing all of that, you tend to want to play behind him.
It's a sign of respect for him. Now to face him these last three
years, it's always a tough thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   When Valentin was told that Clemens had minimized the importance
of the game, he grinned and called Clemens coy. The reason Clemens
called the game unimportant was to avoid distractions and because
it was critical.
</P>
<P>
   The first time Clemens opposed the Red Sox at Fenway Park after
signing with the Blue Jays, he struck out 16 in a 3-1 victory in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   When Clemens left the game, he gazed up to a box he thought
belonged to Boston's general manager, Dan Duquette. That was
personal. It still might be personal toward the Red Sox executives
who infielder Jeff Frye said Clemens felt wronged him in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't see see eye to eye with the front office people,''
Frye said. ``Maybe he feels there's no animosity toward the
players, but he wants to show the front office they made a
mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, the Red Sox got to see Clemens from 60 feet 6
inches away and in pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never seen him in that uniform, face to face,'' Frye
said. ``It was different to see him in a Toronto uniform, but this
is magnified a little more because it's the so-called rivals. It's
going to be exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Frye sounded like Clemens and said, ``As much as people
like to read into it, it's just another game in May.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Roger. Sorry, Jeff. No, it was not. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 0017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
