<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-SUSPENSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT SUSPENDED FOR JOKING ABOUT LITTLETON IS REINSTATED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Snezan Cebic, a Manhattan high school senior,
downloaded the joke a month ago from an Internet chat room
frequented by students at the University of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   It was a parody of those treacly, ubiquitous TV commercials that
invite viewers to use their Mastercards in search of ``priceless''
moments _ a father and son at a ballgame, a daughter's pilgrimage
to her ancestral home in Ireland. Only this time, the punch line
zoomed into the high-school shooting rampage in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   On April 27, Snezan, 18, passed the joke around to several
friends and teachers on a scrap of paper.
</P>
<P>
   By fourth-period physics, he had been turned in to the dean of
discipline at Environmental Studies High School on the West Side of
Manhattan. And three days later he was suspended. The charge,
according to the official incident report: He had ``threatened his
school.''
</P>
<P>
   That suspension ended Thursday, after Snezan was summoned to a
formal hearing where witnesses were prepared to testify against
him. After Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, intervened on his behalf, the charges were
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   It was just one of hundreds of suspensions for alleged threats
of violence that have been reported across the country since the
shootings in Littleton and in Conyers, Ga. On Thursday, civil
libertarians said Snezan's case illustrated the dark side of often
well-intentioned efforts by school administrators anxious to
fulfill the impossible mission of spotting violence before it
occurs.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the suspensions, said Ann Beeson, a staff attorney
for the American Civil Liberties Union, are ``for behavior that in
any other environment would be considered childish pranks.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Corbluth, the principal of Environmental Sciences,
could not precisely articulate how Snezan had threatened the school
or violated any Board of Education policy. But he said the
suspension had been approved by the Manhattan high school
superintendent. ``These are extremely difficult times,'' he said.
``We have youngsters who need to be educated as to the seriousness
of this issue, and we have a responsibility to insure their
safety.''
</P>
<P>
   In a different place, a different time, Snezan Cebic would seem
the unlikeliest of potential criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Serbian immigrant, he came to this country when he
was 11, and has become perfectly assimilated, a popular boy who
listens to both Mahler and anarchist music, has won several
debating trophies and has a 95 average. He has been admitted to the
College of William and Mary in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The only previous blemish on his record is for showing
disrespect to a school security guard, by disobeying an order to
stay in the lunchroom when he wanted to go to the library. For that
infraction, he got ``three or four demerits,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was seven days after Littleton that Snezan gleefully
circulated the credit-card parody, scribbled on a piece of notebook
paper, to friends and teachers. The punch line said, ``The feeling
you get when you blow your classmate's head off: priceless.''
</P>
<P>
   His advanced placement history teacher, Victor Greez, was among
those who read it. ``I thought it was funny, the kind of thing that
you would see passed around Wall Street,'' he said in an interview
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the joke found its way to Dan Andrews, a physics teacher,
who reported it to the school administration, describing it in a
statement as a ``sick thing to write.'' Andrews declined to comment
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Called in for a conference with Phyllis Sacks, a dean, Snezan at
first thought he was just being dressed down. When Ms. Sacks
complained that children these days were exposed to too much
violence, Snezan recounted, he could not resist retorting that in
her day, Westerns and World War II movies had been pretty violent,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does my joke threaten `violence, injury or harm' to anyone
else?'' he said Thursday, quoting from the Board of Education's
disciplinary code. ``The joke doesn't refer to anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   He stubbornly insisted on continuing to attend school, taking
three advanced placement tests over the next week or so.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Ms. Sacks confronted him, and this week, after a
preliminary hearing, Snezan agreed to stay home.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing that his suspension would damage his college plans,
Snezan called the New York Civil Liberties Union and a reporter.
Thursday morning, Siegel of the Civil Liberties Union agreed to
represent him.
</P>
<P>
   Two hours later, Snezan and his father, Nenad, made their way
from Queens to a crowded Board of Education hearing room in midtown
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel asked the Board of Education's supervising attorney,
Shirley Rowe-Gordon, for a postponement so he could prepare a brief
and call character witnesses, which Ms. Rowe-Gordon granted.
``Don't you feel this is rather cut and dried?'' wondered Ms.
Sacks, the Environmental Sciences dean.
</P>
<P>
   Siegel did not, and explained that if a scribbled parody of a
credit-card commercial was a threat, then another student might be
disciplined for bringing a newspaper article about violence into
school.
</P>
<P>
   Several hours later, Siegel received a call from a lawyer for
the Board of Education. The charges were being dropped, the lawyer
said, and the record of Snezan's suspension expunged.
</P>
<P>
   ``On thorough examination, this was not deemed a serious
matter,'' said Phil Russo, a spokesman for the board. ``This was a
good kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Snezan, for one, was glad the suspension was over. ``I hope this
will cause them to think a little,'' he said, ``before they put
other students through the same hassle they put me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 0021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
