<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-SPEEDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRL SLOWING CARS FOR SAFETY REASONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ In an effort to rein in escalating speeds on
high-banked tracks, the Pep Boys Indy Racing League has mandated an
engine rules change designed to slow the cars by three mph.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the June 12 night race at Texas Motor Speedway in
Fort Worth, IRL engines will be limited to 10,000 revolutions per
minute (RPM). IRL cars have been competing with a limiter set at
10,300 RPM this season and will operate at that figure during
Sunday's 83rd running of the Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   The reduced RPM should translate into a loss of 20 to 25
horsepower, and approximately three mph, at the seven IRL events on
the schedule after Indy, IRL officials said. Two of them, including
the season-finale, are at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is if you reduce the RPMs, you slow the
cars down. We feel it will definitely slow the cars down,'' said
Leo Mehl, the IRL's executive director. ``There are obvious reasons
for doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   This change is the latest instituted by the IRL in the wake of a
three-car accident during the league's VisionAire 500 at Lowe's
Motor Speedway in Concord, N.C. Three spectators were killed and
eight injured by a wheel and flying debris that cleared a
15-foot-high fence May 1.
</P>
<P>
   feet to 6 feet to control debris at those tracks, which play
host to five IRL events. The tracks in Fort Worth, Concord and
Hampton, Ga., are 1.5-milers with 24-degree-banked turns originally
designed for stock cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just need to show Bruton and Humpy and all those guys that
we're responding to the tragedy in Charlotte,'' Mehl said. ``This
is one of the ways we're going to do it.''to here ]
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Gossage, the executive vice president and general manager
of TMS, said he was pleased by the new rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the business of speed, but the show is better when
speed is reduced,'' Gossage said. ``But four miles per hour really
makes no difference. This was in the planning stages long before
the Charlotte wreck. I don't see it being a safety issue. It's a
competition issue. Racing at 225 is blinding fast. But you won't be
able to tell the difference in two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the IRL announced implementation of its ``suspension
wheel energy management system'' of space-age cable designed to
keep parts from flying off the cars during a crash. The system will
make its racing debut in Sunday's Indy 500.
</P>
<P>
   The revised RPM limit is expected to keep qualifying speeds at
TMS at around 220-221 mph for the Longhorn 500 presented by MCI
WorldCom on June 12. Last June, Tony Stewart won the pole at TMS
with a hot lap at 224.448 mph. But Billy Boat clocked the fastest
in-race lap at 227.273 mph en route to his first IRL victory.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Cheever, the reigning Indy 500 champion, said the RPM
reduction is significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can compare lowering our revs from 10,300 to
10,000 to what they do with restrictor plates in NASCAR,'' Cheever
said. ``There is no reason in the world why you should not emulate
a successful racing series when they make decisions on safety.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR mandates the use of horsepower-reducing carburetor
restrictor plates for its races on the 2.5-mile Daytona
International Speedway and 2.66-mile Talladega (Ala.)
Superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Controlling speeds is a package,'' Mehl said, ``and we want to
work on all parts of the package.''
nn
</P>
