<HEADLINE>
AVALANCHE'S ROY CLEARLY NOT BEST GOALIE IN SERIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ ``If you win on the road in the playoffs, your
goaltender has to be your best player,'' a wise coach said the
other night.
</P>
<P>
   And with each victory that moves his team closer to the Stanley
Cup finals, coach Ken Hitchcock of the Stars seems to get a little
wiser.
</P>
<P>
   His goaltender, indeed, has been the Stars' most important
player in this postseason.
</P>
<P>
   And the Colorado Avalanche's?
</P>
<P>
   ``Quel surprise.'' His name clearly hasn't been Patrick Roy.
</P>
<P>
   Cut off the head _ the old boxing axiom _ and the body follows.
Cut off Patrick Roy's smiling noggin, and what's left of the Avs?
</P>
<P>
   An intriguing question, as this Western Conference final series
swings into tonight's fourth game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's played well,'' Colorado's 41-goal scorer Joe Sakic said
after yesterday's practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's had a great playoffs for us. He's giving us a chance to
win games.''
</P>
<P>
   That praise is noteworthy because Roy, who can be ``tres''
blunt, hasn't likewise been heaping bravos toward the star center.
</P>
<P>
   Outplayed in Game 3 by Hitchcock's Ed Belfour, Roy dismissed it
yesterday by noting, ``I thought he could have played on a chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a tough game for him. The only high shots we had
hit the crossbar and the post. And there was no traffic in front of
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy said this with no apparent malice in his heavily accented
voice. In fact, he grinned often and, at one point, professed, ``My
responsibility is to answer your questions as honestly as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy, it seems, wears a mask only on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   For Stars fans, it has nonetheless been a revealing week. The
Avalanche thundered into the series having humbled the Detroit Red
Wings. The Avs' strengths, it was written, were a Hall of Fame
goaltender and talented centers like Sakic and Peter Forsberg.
</P>
<P>
   But in Game 2, the Stars carpet-bombed Monsieur Hall of Fame and
came away with four goals. In Game 3, on his home ice, the proud
Roy gave up three.
</P>
<P>
   He needs to ``make adjustments,'' Roy admitted. But neither he
nor his team, he said, is anywhere near the ropes that old teammate
Guy Carbonneau claimed after Game 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, I'll turn that around,'' Roy said. ``I thought we had them
on the ropes after two periods in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things change so fast in a series. Detroit thought it had us
on the ropes after two games.''
</P>
<P>
   Verbally, Roy shoots. And in his mind, he always scores.
</P>
<P>
   This is the man who carried his Montreal Canadiens team to
Stanley Cup titles in 1986 and 1993. A native of Quebec, Roy was
more than a favorite son.
</P>
<P>
   But as the story goes, when coach Mario Tremblay left Roy in the
game one bloody night against Detroit in 1995 to absorb nine goals
in the first 32 minutes, Patrick stormed off the ice and told the
owner that his days in Montreal were done. General manager Rejean
Houle drew the line in the ice and stood by his coach and what he
called ``a century of tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy's former agent, Pierre Lacroix, now the Avalanche general
manager, was on the phone before the night was done.
</P>
<P>
   To save face, in effect, Roy walked out on a two-time Stanley
Cup winner and the most storied franchise in hockey.
</P>
<P>
   He remains no wallflower in the net, even with Joe Nieuwendyk
and Jamie Langenbrunner whizzing around him. Throughout the series,
Stars fans have seen Roy snatch a shot with his glove and then
brandish the puck high _ another trophy.
</P>
<P>
   But the act looks weak when you've given up four and three goals
in the past two games and your team looks as if it's on the verge
of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first game, I think we were all trying to make the
perfect shot, the perfect play,'' Stars center Mike Modano said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think we've been good about staying mentally strong with
whoever we face in goal. You can't start second-guessing yourself,
because that's what goalies want you to do. They want you to start
worrying about where to put the puck, rather than just getting it
on net.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever awe of Roy, it can be said, that the Stars may have had
in Game 1 has vanished by now. The emperor has no clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They feed off his energy,'' Modano said of the Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   But Roy has been mostly half show and only half substance in
these conference finals. You can argue over who has been the best
player in a Colorado uniform, but Roy has not even been the series'
best goaltender.
</P>
<P>
   The ``head'' has been unmasked. Now the body?
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
