<SLUG> BC-RAC-CHARISMATIC-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM A CLAIMER TO ACCLAIMED: THE SAGA OF CHARISMATIC
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The day after Charismatic won the Kentucky Derby, less than
three months after he had run in a claiming race for the second
time, the telephone rang in the Hollywood Park barn of Richard
Mandella, the world-class trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of my owners,'' Mandella recalled the other day,
with a wry little smile. ``He said he was simply calling to ask:
why didn't you claim Charismatic?''
</P>
<P>
   Mandella might have replied that nobody had claimed Charismatic
on Feb. 11, not even Bob Baffert, who had won the Kentucky Derby
the last two years before Charismatic exploded onto the scene this
year and who had even ran a horse against Charismatic in
Charismatic's first claiming race last Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   But Mandella knew that the owner was reacting the way any sane
person might. For the price of $62,500, any licensed trainer at
Hollywood Park last November, or at Santa Anita this past February,
could have entered a claim for Charismatic and, on behalf of a
client, taken a horse who has since won close to $2 million and
needs to win only the Belmont Stakes next Saturday to sweep the
Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   The rules of claiming races may sound complex, but they are
simple enough. Claiming races establish a relatively accessible
market for horses that are already racing, just as auctions or
private sales frequently do for younger horses and richer buyers.
</P>
<P>
   If you enter a horse in a claiming race, you stand to lose him
to anyone who enters a claim before the race. In some states, such
as California and New York, the claim can be entered by any trainer
who has run a horse at that meeting. Other states restrict the
claims to trainers who have a horse entered in the race.
</P>
<P>
   Some trainers enter a horse in a claiming race because the level
of competition is lower and the horse might gain some momentum if
he wins. Then again, the owner may lose the horse, although he may
not mind doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like a game of poker,'' Mandella said, meaning
the business of claimers, which is a lot like the business of
scouting and drafting baseball and football players. ``I once got
$40,000 for a filly that way, and later she won the Del Mar Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``My stable now is always so full of horses that I don't have
room or time to look for claimers. But you can't mourn the horse
that got away. If all the horses had to win the Kentucky Derby to
make your judgment stand up, you'd have one winner and 10,000
losers.''
</P>
<P>
   One winner, that's Charismatic. One huge winner. And maybe 100
trainers who did not detect his potential when he ran as a claimer
or who didn't want to spend $62,500 of somebody else's money to
claim him.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   At New York's major tracks, four or five of the nine races each
day are claiming races, run for price tags ranging from about
$10,000 to about $50,000 or more, with the price even exceeding
$100,000 on rare occasions.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Lakow, the racing secretary for the New York Racing
Association, reports that only two or three horses are claimed on
any given day. Last Nov. 21, when Charismatic won, 6 of the 10
races at Hollywood Park were claiming races.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hindsight,'' said Allen Jerkens, a New York trainer who
rarely deals in claimers. ``We put Kelly Kip in a claiming race the
first time he ran, and nobody took him. Why did we do it? His
mother hadn't produced anything yet. He had bunchy knees. We could
get $35,000 if he won the race, or if he was claimed. He won, and
broke the track record at Belmont Park.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more hindsight came into play later when Kelly Kip won the
Eclipse award as the country's leading sprinter. But Kelly Kip is
not the only champion who rose from the ranks of the lowly claimer.
The list is long and distinguished.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Spoon, a daughter of Citation owned by C.V. Whitney, had
a left foot that dragged and was put up for a claiming ``tag.'' She
later outran colts to win the Santa Anita Derby in 1959, and ran
fifth in the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   The great John Henry ran five times as a claimer early on, then
raced until he was 9 years old, won 39 of his 83 starts and earned
$6.5 million. At one time, you could have claimed him for $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Stymie ran 12 times as a claimer for as little as $1,500, then
ran in the money 90 times in 131 starts. Seabiscuit, who started
his career with a 17-race losing streak, ran four times in claiming
races in 1935 on both coasts, then won 33 times.
</P>
<P>
   They were to racing what Don Mattingly, drafted in the 19th
round by the Yankees, was to baseball, and what Terrell Davis,
drafted in the sixth round by the Denver Broncos, was to pro
football: overlooked but marked for greatness.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   So, why was Charismatic first placed in a claiming race at
Hollywood Park last Nov. 21? Probably because he had lost the first
five races of his career, had run ninth in his last race the month
before and was beginning to cost more than he was worth to his
owners, Bob and Beverly Lewis, and his trainer, D. Wayne Lukas.
Both are pillars of racing, but both realize that it costs maybe
$100 a day plus veterinary and blacksmith bills just to keep a
horse.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bob Lewis, who has also owned Silver Charm and Serena's Song
among dozens of other star horses, put it bluntly, if a bit
ruefully, when he said, ``I just felt we had to stop the
bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Wayne came to me and said: `There's an element of
risk in this. But he needs to be out front to get his confidence.'
Look, if I had picked him up for $62,500, I'd be overjoyed right
now. We paid $200,000 to buy him as a weanling. If somebody had
claimed him, we'd be getting back one-third of our investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas, who is closing in on the financial landmark of $200
million in earnings by his horses, admits that this one fooled him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've ever been fooled so much by a horse,'' he
said. ``I just didn't have any grasp on where I was going with him.
I felt there was something I was missing all the time. I felt I
wasn't pushing the right buttons. But I felt he hadn't won a race
and needed some confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas paused, and then uttered the understatement of the year.
``We were lucky nobody took him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Penny Chenery, the owner of Secretariat, took the high view.
``To run as a claimer tarnishes a horse's record,'' she said. ``If
Wayne had recognized Charismatic as a Secretariat-type of horse, he
wouldn't have run him in those claimers.''
</P>
<P>
   But Arthur Hancock, the owner of Menifee, who has finished
second to Charismatic in both the Kentucky Derby and the Preakness,
said with understanding: ``Horses are like people. Some kids don't
mature until college.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
