<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTOROLA BEGINS EXPANSION OF WAFER  PLANT IN CHANDLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By REBECCA ROLWING  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a yearlong delay caused by a tremendous slump in the
semiconductor industry, Motorola Inc. said Thursday that it is
starting a $90 million expansion of its Chandler plant that will
ultimately create up to 500 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The construction plans are part of the previously announced $1.1
billion development of its MOS-12 waferfabrication plant. The
expansion is scheduled to be completed in 2002, and the new
employees will earn an average of $45,000 to $50,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``When completed, the Chandler facility will be our largest
manufacturing campus in the world,'' said William Seiferth, chief
of staff for Motorola's Semiconductor Products Sector.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion will triple the number of processors,
microcontrollers and other devices made at the campus. The tiny
silicon devices go into everything from cars to cellular phones to
cable modems.
</P>
<P>
   The growth follows a year in which Motorola, the state's largest
private employer, slashed 2,075 jobs throughout its Valley
facilities as it implemented a brutal restructuring to save money.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts believe that after a few false starts, an
upturn in the semiconductor industry has begun in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The semiconductor industry has bottomed out,'' said Martin
Goslar, an analyst with Cahner's In-Stat Group in Scottsdale.
``Prices for semiconductor chips and components are starting to
come back to normal prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorola, the world's No. 3 chip manufacturer, already has
completed basic construction of the buildings on the 80-acre campus
at 1300 N. Alma School Road, between Warner and Ray roads.
</P>
<P>
   The company came to the site in 1983, when it built a
200,000-square-foot research and design facility.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Motorola built a 260,000-square-foot manufacturing
building and equipped the north half of it within three years. The
south half of the building wasn't fully constructed until last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the $1.1 billion expansion, Motorola said it will now
spend $50 million on robots and other technology to fully equip the
133,000-square-foot South Fab. Some equipment is already in, and
production has begun in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Motorola will spend $40 million to complete the interior
construction of the campus' 300,000-square-foot East Fab. Plans
call for installing heating, piping, gas lines and other equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The work is to begin in the next few weeks and should be
completed early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Almost $500 million will have been invested at the site by the
end of this year.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of next year, Motorola will begin to use the
remainder of the $1.1 billion as it equips the two-story East Fab.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion project has already created about 60 jobs and is
expected to add 60 more by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola originally anticipated to complete the $1.1 billion
expansion in 2001. However, a steep drop in demand for chips
prompted the company to shelve its plans temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials didn't anticipate this phase of the expansion
to begin until later this year, but a strong demand for its chips
by the automotive and wireless industries rekindled the plans.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler Mayor Jay Tibshraeny cheered Motorola's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've kind of managed to weather the storm,'' he said. ``This
news reinforces what I'm feeling, that our economy in Chandler
remains very strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Seiferth said the new jobs have some insulation from the
fluctuations in the chip industry because they are used in a
variety of products.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs will be available for a variety of workers, including those
on the manufacturing line, process and design engineers and
supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   However, many of Motorola's furloughed employees will not be
eligible to rejoin the company at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Most accepted voluntary severance packages, which prevent them
from returning to work for the company for two years. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
