<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-970&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS FINISH CASE AGAINST REMAINING OFFICERS IN TORTURE
TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add much new material and rewrite extensively following
3rd graf.)  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The prosecution wrapped up its case Thursday against
the four police officers still on trial in the Abner Louima
brutality case, but without presenting the kind of directly
incriminating evidence that it amassed against Officer Justin
Volpe, who pleaded guilty in mid-trial this week and threw himself
on the mercy of the court.
</P>
<P>
   The case appears to be speeding toward a quick conclusion. After
the prosecution rested, just two days after Volpe pleaded guilty to
all the charges against him, the defense case began _ and quickly
ended for two of the defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for Officer Thomas Bruder called no witnesses, and
Officer Charles Schwarz's lawyer called only one. Officer Thomas
Wiese's lawyers said they would call a couple of character
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Only Sgt. Michael Bellomo intends to testify in his own defense,
his lawyer said. Judge Eugene Nickerson told the jurors Thursday
that closing arguments could begin on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution's case against three of the four defendants is
based in part on Louima's own account of being beaten and
brutalized in the 70th Precinct station house in Brooklyn on Aug.
9, 1997, though he did not directly identify any of the officers
aside from Volpe. Prosecutors also used testimony from fellow
officers and police records to try to tie the other defendants to
the abuse of Louima, a 32-year-old Haitian immigrant, and
subsequent efforts to cover up what happened.
</P>
<P>
   In concluding its case Thursday, the prosecutors sought to end
with a flourish by presenting what they suggested was the rest of
the broom _ bristles attached to a stick that had been broken off _
that had been used to torture Louima. It was found a week after the
torture of Louima behind a locker in the station house.
</P>
<P>
   Later, speaking with reporters, Schwarz's lawyer, Stephen Worth,
contended that the display was ``a typical prosecutorial cheap
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's absolutely no proof this is the other half of the
notorious stick,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the evidence presented against the four remaining
defendants, in three weeks of testimony in U.S. District Court in
Brooklyn, focused on Schwarz. He is charged with holding Louima
down while Volpe rammed a stick into Louima's rectum, inflicting
severe internal injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Two witnesses testified that they saw Schwarz with Louima
shortly before the attack, and prosecutors sought to link him with
Volpe, who was fired from the force following his guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Thompson, an assistant U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, told
the jury at the beginning of the trial, ``Justin Volpe and Charles
Schwarz began to inflict their own special brand of punishment,
their own special brand of torture.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiese and Bruder are charged with joining Volpe and Schwarz in
beating Louima, either after he was arrested in a melee outside a
nightclub or in a police car before he arrived at the station
house, although Louima could not identify any of the officers he
says beat him, except Volpe. Bellomo is accused of trying to cover
up the beating in the police car.
</P>
<P>
   The main evidence against Schwarz, 33, came from Louima himself
and two police officers who broke the ``blue wall of silence'' and
testified for the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Louima did not directly identify Schwarz, but said that the
officer who held him down during Volpe's attack in the restroom was
the same officer who had driven him to the station house. Police
records show that Schwarz was the driver.
</P>
<P>
   The two officers, Eric Turetzky and Mark Schofield, testified
that they saw Schwarz walk Louima, handcuffed and with his pants
down, toward the the restroom area.
</P>
<P>
   Worth vigorously cross-examined the prosecution's witnesses.
Worth has said that Schwarz was never in the restroom and that
Louima was wrong in saying it was the driver of the police car who
had held him down. He also underscored that Turetzky and Schofield
did not testify that they saw Schwarz taking Louima into the
restroom.
</P>
<P>
   Wiese's lawyers, Joseph Tacopina and Russell Gioiella, also
largely waged their cases through cross-examination, and when
Thursday's court session ended, they were in the midst of
presenting character witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence against Wiese, 35, includes Louima's testimony that
two of the officers who beat him in the police car were the same
officers who took him to the station house. He did not identify
those officers, but police records show that he was taken by Wiese
and Schwarz, and forensic evidence showed that DNA in blood found
in their car was consistent with Louima's DNA.
</P>
<P>
   Wiese's lawyers contend that Louima's account of being beaten in
the police car could not be believed and that the blood had come
from injuries Louima received outside the nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Bruder's lawyer, Stuart London, had told the jurors in his
statement at the start of the trial that they would not be hearing
much from him: ``There will be many witnesses in this case that I
may not cross-examine or that I may not cross-examine for a lengthy
period of time. That's not because I accept their testimony. It is
because it doesn't affect my client.''
</P>
<P>
   Louima testified that Volpe and a second officer, whom he did
not identify, approached the police car in which he said he was
beaten and joined in the assault. Police records show that Bruder,
33, was Volpe's partner that morning, and police records also place
Bruder at the scene of the reported beating.
</P>
<P>
   London also said that Louima was not credible in his account of
being beaten in the police car. He argued that the only reason his
client was even charged was that ``he was Volpe's partner that
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Bellomo's lawyer, John Patten, has said that he will put the
sergeant on the stand when the trial resumes on Tuesday, which
would make him the only defendant in the case to testify.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The prosecution evidence against Bellomo, 37, includes a report
he filled out about the events and a statement he later made to the
FBI, both of which prosecutors said contained false accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution also cited telephone calls the sergeant made to
other officers and investigators that they say indicate he intended
to discourage Schofield from going to investigators with his
information, and then tried to obscure that intention.
</P>
<P>
   Patten said the sergeant believed what he said in his report and
statements, and if they contained any errors it was because he had
relied on Volpe and the other defendants for information about a
chaotic situation _ the street melee. The phone calls, Patten said,
showed that the sergeant had in fact urged Schofield to cooperate
with investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Bellomo was not charged in the assaults on Louima.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors, from the office of Zachary Carter, the U.S.
attorney in Brooklyn, have told the jury that Louima was beaten in
the police car and attacked in the station house restroom because
Volpe and three of the other officers mistakenly believed he had
punched Volpe in the face, knocking him down, during the street
melee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
