<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ABC AND INDIANAPOLIS 500 STILL A TWOSOME
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATT: Ind., N.C.)  (rk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When ABC Sports officials began planning their Indianapolis 500
coverage four months ago, they viewed Sunday's race, which begins
at 11 a.m. Eastern time, as possibly their last after 35 years. Fox
looked like the favorite to grab the rights.
</P>
<P>
   The interest existed despite ratings that have fallen since the
Indy Racing League and Championship Auto Racing Teams petulantly
split in 1995. Neither did the lack of Indianapolis 500 stars who
are capable of rivaling NASCAR's Jeff Gordon and Dale Earnhardt
reduce ABC's ardor.
</P>
<P>
   This remains a storied yet diminished sports event that ABC
needed to keep. Even the 5.5 Nielsen rating for last year's race
(down from 8.4 in 1995 before the IRL-CART split) is enviable these
days.
</P>
<P>
   The contractual uncertainty did not prevent the production crew,
led by Bob Goodrich, from making improvements for the viewing of
this year's 83nd edition of the race. With auto racing a terrific
laboratory for TV technology, it's almost impossible to resist
upgrading coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve cars, up from six last year, will carry two cameras
apiece. Ten cameras will be placed above the pit crews, a common
perch at Nascar telecasts but never employed before at Indy. Al
Michaels will be the host, and Bob Jenkins, who called the race on
radio for 20 years, replaces Paul Page. There will also be an
attempt to talk to one or two drivers, like Arie Luyendyk, during
the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like Jekyll and Hyde,'' Eddie Cheever, the 1998 champion,
said in an ABC conference call. ``I don't think you'd want to hear
what I say.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that the enhanced production scheme led to ABC's
retention of the Indianapolis 500 through 2004 for $13 million
annually, up about 40 percent. The deal includes 10 Indy Racing
League races (half to be seen on ESPN) starting next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox Sports Net's nine-race IRL cable deal this season looked
like a precursor to a longer contract that would include the
Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``But ABC had the right of first negotiation, and they made an
offer we couldn't refuse,'' said Barry Frank, the International
Management Group executive who negotiated the deal for the
Indianapolis Motor Speedway. ``This is a major event, no matter how
you slice it.''
</P>
<P>
   The expectation that Fox would take over undoubtedly persuaded
Jack Arute, once ABC's best reporter from the pits, to become an
analyst for Fox Sports Net's IRL races and a sideline reporter for
college football games.
</P>
<P>
   Also gone from Indianapolis 500 coverage is Page, who is calling
CART races for the network, including the Motorola 300 tomorrow. In
his place is Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the ultimate in my career,'' said Jenkins, who sounded
a smidgen boosterish about the race. ``This is the greatest
motorsports event in the world,'' he said. ``I know it. Bob
Goodrich knows it.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone does. The Indianapolis 500's slipping fortunes
since the split from CART has focused attention on the
better-marketed auto-racing domain of NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   The 9.5 rating for last February's Daytona 500 was nearly double
the 1998 Indianapolis 500's. NASCAR garners lengthy, usually
admiring treatment in magazines like Fortune and Newsweek, while
the Indianapolis 500 struggles to prove that drivers like Cheever,
Tony Stewart, Buddy Lazier and Luyendyk can maintain a one-day grip
on race fans' hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of competition in the IRL races has been very
good,'' Jenkins said. ``There is a misconception that drivers in
the Indianapolis 500 are picked off the street. They're extremely
talented drivers.''
</P>
<P>
   But the drivers, and open-wheel racing, have come under intense
scrutiny since May 1 when three spectators attending the IRL's
Visionaire 500 at Lowe's Motor Speedway in Concord, N.C., were
killed when a tire and other debris from a three-car crash carried
over a 15-foot fence.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, the IRL temporarily barred Ed Hinton of
Sports Illustrated from the Indianapolis 500 for his coverage of
the tragedy. He had the temerity to write that ``flying debris,
including loose tires that aren't contained by fenders, can be
deadly to bystanders _ especially those at oval layouts.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodrich said the I.R.L. has never chastised ABC for its
coverage of crashes or what its announcers say. ``Our only
direction is to journalistically cover what has to be covered and
do it in good taste,'' he said. ``I try to use good judgment, not
over-replay things, and do what's best.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
