<P>
   GACHET-FORGERY (Undated) _ Western attitudes to forgery have
changed over the centuries. In the 16th century, Vasari admired
Michelangelo for faking antiquities. The most famous forger in this
century, Hans Van Meegeren, went to jail for painting fake
Vermeers. Fakery thrives when people are beginning to understand an
art that they therefore prize unquestioningly, a situation akin to
new love. History being full of odd coincidences, it happens that
Van Meegeren was born right around the time when Van Gogh was
moving to a village called Auvers-sur-Oise, near Paris, where he
was to be under the care of a homeopathic physician, art collector
and amateur painter named Paul-Ferdinand Gachet. I mention Van
Meegeren because the Gachet legacy, which is the subject of a new
exhibition at the Met, ``Cezanne to Van Gogh: The Collection of Dr.
Gachet,'' for decades has been vexed by questions of deception and
fakery. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   IMPRESSIONISTS-WINTER (New York) _ Think of the Impressionists
and chances are you think green (or possibly pink, or lavender, or
bluebird-blue in the case of Monet). They were painters of lawns,
hedges, and fertile fields, of a deciduous nature caught at full
leaf. But like artists anywhere with rents to pay and mouths to
feed, they were year-round workers. And inevitably winter
landscapes, rendered in the frosty open air or through the glass of
a studio window, figured in their repertoire. ``Impressionists in
Winter: Effects de Neige,'' which opens Friday at the Brooklyn
Museum of Art, brings together some 60 such paintings. And if ever
a show were tailor-made for summer viewing, this one is. By Holland
Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   MUSICALS (Undated) _ During rehearsals for ``I Married an
Angel,'' a 1938 musical comedy about a Hungarian banker, the show's
lyricist, Lorenz Hart, a quick-witted master of the last-minute
fix, decided to add a new number called ``At the Roxy Music Hall.''
When Joshua Logan, the director, asked anxiously how a number
filled with allusions to contemporary New York personalities could
possibly be made to fit into a comedy set in old Budapest, Hart
answered airily: ``Well, just bring up the subject of New York. You
can't sing about Budapest all night. We've got to give people a
little fun.'' To Hart's mind, no musical comedy, whatever its
putative locale, could be inhospitable to a mention of New York.
Dependent on a lavish flow of cash and illusion, too loud and
fast-moving for introspection or tragic denouements, the city is
not only the birthplace of the musical comedy form but also its
primary exemplar. By Ann Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   DAY-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Eternity and a Day'': Theo
Angelopoulos, director. In Greek with English subtitles. Reviewed
by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
