<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-SCHOOLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FAILING THE TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, May 28:
</P>
<P>
   The dismal results of the new reading and writing test for New
York state's fourth-graders reveal how much needs to be done to
improve schools everywhere. Less than a third of New York City
students passed, and many city schools had failure rates above 90
percent. But the results are not reassuring for affluent suburban
districts either.
</P>
<P>
   The new test, replacing the multiple-choice third-grade reading
test, required students to listen to passages, read for
comprehension and respond with grammatically correct essays. This
is the first time fourth-graders have been tested on writing. The
scores may come as a shock to places like Westchester and Nassau
Counties, where nearly 95 percent of students passed the old test.
This year only 61 to 65 percent in those counties passed.
</P>
<P>
   But as disappointing as the results are in many suburban
communities, the outcomes in New York City are harrowing. Of
students there, 21 percent scored at the very lowest level,
compared with 6 percent in the rest of the state. Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani called this week for the removal of principals at the
bottom third of the city's elementary schools. Schools Chancellor
Rudy Crew should work toward that goal, but he can make headway
only if state law on principals' tenure is changed. Even dismissing
incompetent principals will not turn the whole system around. High
levels of poverty, dilapidated buildings and a shortage of
qualified teachers and principals remain huge impediments.
</P>
<P>
   The abysmal test scores suggest that Crew's proposal to end
social promotion next year may not be practical. Even spending $160
million on more summer school may not be sufficient. It may be
wiser to put off that goal until all classrooms have resources to
teach these children.
</P>
<P>
   Crew is also considering placing about 50 of the worst schools
directly under his control. That is a good idea, but the long-term
answer is to improve teacher training, increase salaries so that
the city can compete with the suburbs for staff, reduce class sizes
and provide good preschool programs.
</P>
<P>
   These costly efforts need the sustained political and financial
commitment of city leaders as well as Gov. George Pataki, who is
reneging on commitments made in 1997 to improve school financing.
State Education Commissioner Richard Mills has called the new test
an exercise in truth-telling. Part of that truth is that there is
no cheap, one-shot cure for educational failure of this magnitude.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
