<HEADLINE>
DODGERS WIN A NAIL-BITER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ When the organization fires its pitching coach to
spark the team, a blister on the tip of a finger seems nothing more
than a hangnail-type dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe a fingernail-type dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   Ismael Valdes' latest start ended like many of the other ones
this season. He pitched well and had a low pitch count, but had to
leave the game early because of blister problems. The latest
episode came in the Dodgers' 4-3 win against the Cincinnati Reds on
Thursday at Cinergy Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was over the blister, but evidently he trimmed
his nails and that caused a big blister to come up underneath (his
middle finger),'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``I don't
know about blisters. It's way over my head. I told him to get with
(Kevin) Brown and Chan Ho (Park) and see what they do. I have
enough problems without worrying about a damn blister.''
</P>
<P>
   As trite as it seems to be talking about blisters the day after
Charlie Hough was fired, it's become a main focus for any start
involving Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed two runs on four hits in five innings, but like many
of his outings, it ended prematurely. The blister pains Valdes
(5-2) particularly on his breaking pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing I've done in the past I haven't done this year
(to remedy the blister),'' said a frustrated Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers won their second straight game and their first
series since they took two of three from Chicago May 10-12. But
Valdes is yet to pitch beyond the sixth inning in five outings this
month despite allowing more than three runs only once.
</P>
<P>
   It's gotten to the point where Valdes is ready to go to the
local 99-Cent Store for some press-on nails to remedy the problem.
In 1996, Valdes used an acrylic fingernail to combat a blister
problem, and he's thinking of doing it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm used to (the blister), but at the same time I'd like to go
deep into games,'' Valdes said. ``You do your best, but there's
always a reason something happens. We scored runs. I would have
liked to keep pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he pulled Valdes because if the blister broke it
would cost the 25-year-old at least one start, and he turned to the
bullpen. Pedro Borbon was fine for 11/3 innings, but set-up man
Alan Mills and closer Jeff Shaw had to battle. Mills walked four
and allowed a run in 12/3 innings. Shaw, the former Reds closer,
got Sean Casey to fly out to center field with two runners on in
the ninth for his 10th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you can go on the road and get a series, especially
the first series of a three-city road trip like we're on, it's a
good thing,'' Shaw said. ``That's how you put distance between
teams, winning the close ones.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Eric Karros hit his seventh homer in the fourth
for the Dodgers' first run. The Dodgers (24-22) added three runs in
the fifth to take a 4-2 lead as Eric Young doubled in two runs and
scored on Raul Mondesi's single.
</P>
<P>
   Reds starter Pete Harnisch (4-5) gave up eight hits and four
runs in 41/3 innings, his second shortest outing of the season.
</P>
<P>
   It's the Dodgers' eighth one-run win, but only their third in
May. However, it does send them to Atlanta for a three-game series
(followed by three in Pittsburgh) with a much better feeling than
they had before arriving in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won two out of the three games because we played well and
we go to Atlanta and have to try and do the same thing,'' said
Mondesi. ``We have a real good team and we're supposed to play
better than they way we've played.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
