<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A LONG DAY OF VENTING ABOUT NEW YORK CITY'S POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ELEANOR RANDOLPH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The issue of ``Police Practices and Civil Rights in
New York City'' seemed too deep, too massive for one hearing by the
U.S. Commission on Civil Rights in an undersized hotel meeting room
in Manhattan. The torture of Abner Louima and the shooting of
Amadou Diallo by police have made this historic issue altogether
too current. And so the hearing on Wednesday brought out a large
and unhappy crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those who came to wave angry banners were penned behind
police barricades on Seventh Avenue, safely out of the way of
tourists trying to see ``Beauty and the Beast.'' Others squeezed
into a few dozen public seats in the hearing room. Their turn to
speak would come long after the cameras were gone.
</P>
<P>
   But the success of the commission's session should not be judged
entirely by the 15-hour marathon of statistics and complaints. The
real advantage may well be the commission's ability to find small,
concrete possibilities for improvement in the avalanche of
conflicting words about an emotional subject. Moreover, the
commissioners are demanding the kind of hard data about police
practices that is too often difficult to get from the New York City
Police Department and City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani started the long day by explaining why
New York City was so much safer now than when he arrived in 1995.
Amid hisses and groans from the audience, a red-faced mayor argued
that the reason so many blacks and minorities were being stopped
and frisked was that they fit the descriptions given to police by
the victims.
</P>
<P>
   While such tense moments attracted the media, commissioners were
focused on other less rhetorical matters such as a comment by James
Savage, president of the Patrolmen's Benevolent Association.
Savage, who is running for re-election, has been arguing that
police officers are under too much pressure to increase arrests.
These quotas, he said, are designed to satisfy the city's
statisticians who want to show how well police are fighting crime.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Savage argued, police ``never get a good
report for protecting someone's civil rights.'' The commission's
chairwoman, Mary Frances Berry, began taking notes and later asked
the police commissioner, Howard Safir, why there were no incentives
for protecting civil rights. Respecting a person's civil rights is
an integral part of an officer's job, Safir explained.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the possibility of asking for incentives for protecting
civil rights, the commissioners made it clear they would look at
the 48-hour rule that allows a police officer to postpone any
statements in an investigation of a police incident. They
questioned whether the Civilian Complaint Review Board was strong
and independent of police influence. Frank Wohl, the board's
chairman, argued that its independence was assured because members
were not appointed by the police commissioner but by the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoa,'' somebody in the audience yelled, as others merely
booed.
</P>
<P>
   It was a fractious crowd, its size restricted by the small room,
but the commission could hardly miss its testimony of momentous
frustration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
