<SLUG> BC-BBA-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON: ANOTHER BIG ERROR BY DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ You look at the catcher the Dodgers threw away and
mark it down as a big, fat ``E''. No need to check with the
official scorer on this one. It's obvious the Dodgers erred when
they traded Charles Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   It has been almost six months since the gaffe and you're still
shaking your head in disbelief. It pains you to see Todd Hundley's
labored motion to second. You miss Johnson's quick release and
cat-like reflexes.
</P>
<P>
   You think back to all the curves thrown at Johnson last season,
on the field and off, and you wonder how it was he finished with
only eight errors. That was a tad on the high side for him but
still fewer than the Dodgers' brass made in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Many nights last summer you could see the strain on Johnson's
face. It was a heavy load he carried, replacing Mike Piazza and the
death soon after the trade of a grandmother he considered his
second mom, along with the impending birth of his first child, a
son who arrived in L.A. a mere month after Johnson did.
</P>
<P>
   He did a superlative job by anybody's standards except his own,
earning his fourth consecutive Gold Glove award. That should have
been enough to make all the hardened hearts in the Dodgers' front
office crack with pride.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-one years had come and gone since John Roseboro, the only
other catcher on the club to be so honored, had won the second of
his two Gold Gloves. As such, you expected the Dodgers to act
swiftly, maybe commission an artist to paint a mural of Johnson at
Dodger Stadium or something.
</P>
<P>
   But erase his name from the roster? That, you didn't anticipate.
Truth to tell, neither did Johnson. He had narrowed his choice of
semi-permanent residences in L.A. to an agreeable few and was
looking forward to many more summers of high expectations and low
humidity.
</P>
<P>
   He says he was shocked when the Dodgers' new general manager
Kevin Malone telephoned him in Miami this past Dec. 1 and told him,
ever-so-politely, that the Dodgers no longer would be needing his
services.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, Johnson wanted to believe it was April 1 and this
was somebody's cruel idea of a joke. Alas, it was true. Johnson was
going to Baltimore by way of the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers got Hundley in the deal and the Orioles, well, they
got measurably better.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 27, has been everything manager Ray Miller envisioned
the four-time Gold Glove winner would be and more. Not only has he
been a dependable _ and indefatigable _ presence behind the plate,
he has been delivering  &UR; !ital! &LR; at &UR; !off! &LR;  the plate, too.
</P>
<P>
   Going into the Orioles' game against the Angels Thursday,
Johnson led Albert Belle and the rest of his teammates with 10 home
runs. ``I'm just trying to do what I can do,'' says Johnson, who
admits he pressed in an effort to produce at the plate when he was
with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a lot more relaxed. I can truly admit that now,'' says
Johnson, who had 12 home runs in 102 games as a Dodger. ``I tried
to do too much when I was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's just too much. All that defense and 10 homers, too!
You'll have to forgive Miller if he feels like the guy who gets set
up at the prom with the class valedictorian, only to have her named
prom queen.
</P>
<P>
   Miller credits Orioles hitting coach Terry Crowley for Johnson's
hitting makeover. Ever since Crowley encouraged Johnson to shorten
his swing, the catcher's numbers have been anything but compact.
</P>
<P>
   After mustering just one RBI in April, Johnson has produced 19
in 21 games in May. He was batting .343 for the month before
Thursday's game against the Angels. And lest anybody had forgotten
what Johnson's real strength is, he threw a perfect strike to
second in the fifth inning to stop the Angels' Orlando Palmeiro
cold in the Orioles' 6-3 win.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson had a spiteful bone in his body, he might be tempted
to send the videotape of that throw to the Dodgers. Alas, he's
nothing but class.
</P>
<P>
   You listen to him talk about his days with the Dodgers and you
start to see why Johnson didn't fit into the Dodgers' plans. He has
far too much character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed L.A.,'' Johnson says. ``I was a little bit upset
when I found out I was being traded. It was very disappointing to
me. The Dodgers brought me over for defense and I won a Gold Glove
for the organization and yet everybody seemed to be disappointed in
my offense. I could never understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it's easier to hit a grand slam these days than fathom the
Dodgers. Just ask Charlie Hough. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
