<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MO CAN'T GET ANGELS PAST GUZMAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Anaheim Angels manager Terry Collins looked in
the mirror Thursday morning and saw a 50-year-old man staring back
at him.
</P>
<P>
   So what did Collins do to celebrate this milestone birthday? He
shook up his lineup, only to find out no matter how much he moved
things around, the results were similar to those when he was 49.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels offense sputtered again in a 6-3 loss to the
Baltimore Orioles before 24,724 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Brady Anderson's grand slam off Angels reliever Mike Magnante in
the seventh inning broke open a 2-1 game and paved the way for the
Orioles' second win in the three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Guzman (2-4) gave up one run and three hits in six innings
to get the victory over Angels starter Ken Hill (1-4).
</P>
<P>
   Collins got a few fresh bats in the game and moved some others
around in an effort to change the fortunes of an offense that went
into the game ranked 11th out of 14 American League teams in
hitting. But with Orlando Palmeiro and Jeff Huson among those
getting a chance to play, it ultimately came down to Mo Vaughn
providing the bulk of the offense once again.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn homered (No. 11) and doubled twice, driving in two runs.
Randy Velarde drove in the Angels' other run with a single in the
eighth inning, but the late rally proved futile.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had a chance to jump all over Guzman early but missed
their chance. Guzman walked three batters in the first inning and
gave up a double to Vaughn, but all the Angels had to show for it
was one run. It had to bother Collins, who before the game said the
key to getting Guzman was to get him early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Hill went into the game having walked 41 batters, the most in
the majors. ``But even when he's walked guys this year, his stuff
has been good enough to get him through,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Through six innings, Hill walked only one, but he found trouble
in the seventh. With one out, Will Clark and Cal Ripken singled
before Hill walked Delino DeShields to load the bases. Charles
Johnson followed with a grounder that appeared headed down the
left-field line. Instead, third baseman Troy Glaus made a diving
stop, but his throw to first was too late. The runners advanced and
the Orioles had a 2-1 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
