<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY MAYOR'S CAMPAIGN AIDE WORKED ON PLAN TO PRIVATIZE
DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GROMER JEFFERS JR.  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The top consultant for Mayor Kay Barnes
during her campaign was working at the same time for a St. Louis
company that wants to take over the operations of the Kansas City
Water Services Department.
</P>
<P>
   Political consultant Pat Gray was hired to develop a plan to buy
or manage the Water Services Department if it's ``privatized,''
said Chris McKee, a director at Environmental Management Corp.
Barnes has helped lay the groundwork for privatization since taking
office April 10.
</P>
<P>
   A document outlining a plan for taking over the department was
obtained by The Kansas City Star. It called for the department to
be sold or leased by Nov. 1, 1999, to EA2//Systems, a consortium of
three companies that includes Environmental Management.
</P>
<P>
   The document included a detailed strategy to discredit the Water
Services Department's reputation so that the public would support a
private takeover. It also outlined the need to overcome opposition
from labor unions and minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said the document could have been stolen from his office
and declined to comment about it. McKee confirmed that Gray worked
for his company and on the mayor's campaign at the same time.MDNM/,
but he also declined to comment on the document.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't get into specifics about our strategy,'' McKee said.
``But we are interested. We would be crazy not to be interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray's involvement with both Barnes' campaign and the St. Louis
company does not violate any laws. But some city officials
privately said that it may give the appearance the company has an
unfair advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said that she was aware of EA2//Systems' desire to manage
the Water Services Department, but that steps she has taken since
assuming office had nothing to do with Gray's work for the company.
She said she knew of Gray's involvement with the company during her
campaign, but would not comment on whether it was appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said she could support a public//private partnership in
running the Water Services Department but opposed its sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to maintain our employee base,'' she said. ``But
maybe there could be changes in the management and marketing
levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes said that her interest in public//private partnerships
extends beyond the Water Services Department to facilities such as
Kemper Arena. But she said her position on privatization was not
influenced by Gray.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said that EA2//Systems, which operates several city-owned
water departments throughout the United States, was interested in
running the Water Services Department.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he would not comment on a contractual relationship
or the document because it's ``part of an ongoing investigation,''
a reference to a reported break-in at his office before the
municipal election. A police report on a break-in March 5, however,
indicated only petty cash was taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why the The Star would base a story on a document
that could have been stolen,'' Gray said. ``Who knows what happened
to it? It could have been doctored.''
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper provided Gray with a copy of the document,
obtained anonymously through the mail, but he repeatedly refused to
look at it. ``I don't want to see it,'' Gray said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the plan document, Gray and Steve Glorioso, who
also worked on Barnes' campaign, would direct a public relations
effort to overcome expected resistance from labor unions and
minorities. Those groups make up a large part of the Water Services
Department's roughly 1,000-person work force.
</P>
<P>
   Listed as local advisers to EA2//Systems were Gray, political
consultant; Glorioso, news media consultant; and Jack Holland,
financial consultant. Holland, a local executive with Fahnestock &AMP;
Co., a brokerage firm that handles bond issues, has worked for
municipalities and Jackson County as a financial adviser. He also
was an informal adviser to the Barnes campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Glorioso and Holland said they had no knowledge of the document
and couldn't comment on it.
</P>
<P>
   Michael T. White, a Kansas City lawyer representing
EA2//Systems, said the company was interested in either buying or
managing the Water Services Department, but said he has not seen
the document.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing was stimulated by the city auditor's report a
couple of years ago,'' said White, a political supporter of Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1995 report, City Auditor Mark Funkhouser suggested
possibly selling the Water Services Department for $80 million to
$180 million. In a recent interview, however, Funkhouser said the
city could retain ownership by leasing the department's assets and
charging a large up-front fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Privatization) is a good thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Water Services Department is one of the city's largest and
most profitable. Its operating budget is about $122 million, and it
has projected revenues of $182 million.
</P>
<P>
   According to the document, one goal was to elect a mayor and a
majority to the Kansas City Council that favored privatization of
municipal services such as the Water Services Department, a
strategy McKee acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are just waiting for some direction from the city,'' McKee
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he hired Gray 18 months ago and spoke with Barnes six
months ago about the possibility of his company managing the
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spoken with Kay and she understands that other cities
have benefited from outsourcing,'' said McKee, who said that he
didn't know Barnes until after hiring Gray.
</P>
<P>
   McKee also declined to comment on a copy of the plan document
given him by The Star.
</P>
<P>
   On May 6, Barnes announced that the Water Services Department
and the Public Works Department would be the first City Manager Bob
Collins would analyze in an effort to cut costs and improve
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt those two departments are far-reaching in their
activities and that they present some unusual considerations as to
how they are run,'' Barnes told the City Council at the time.
</P>
<P>
   On May 20, the council authorized Collins to study privatizing a
full range of city services, including Kansas City International
Airport operations and the Water Services Department.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 27,000 water systems in the United States are
privately owned, including St. Louis County's water plant. It's
operated by EA2//Systems, which in addition to Environmental
Management includes a British firm, Anglican Water Co., and
American Waterworks of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The plan document obtained by The Star anticipated opposition to
privatizing Kansas City's Water Services Department. The document
listed six obstacles, including an ``If it ain't broke, don't fix
it'' public attitude and overcoming minority and union opposition.
</P>
<P>
   To sway public opinion, the document outlined a media campaign
to take place between Jan. 1 and June 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The document called for using ``standard media channels'' to
discredit the Water Services Department by alleging mismanagement
of funds, violation of EPA standards, deception on bond issues and
patronage.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said Thursday, however, that the department ``makes
money, is efficiently operated and is a model for the way water
companies should operate.''
</P>
<P>
   The document stated that the goal of the campaign to discredit
the department would be to ``trigger a new city audit of the Water
Services Department.'' After the audit was finished, the document
said, the department would become a major issue in the municipal
election. Other issues identified were privatization of city
services and rebuilding infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   Although privatization and infrastructure became issues in this
year's municipal election, no audit was triggered.
</P>
<P>
   The plan document called for the new mayor and council to work
on privatizing the Water Services Department immediately after the
1999 election with ``the sale of the Water Services Department and
its assets to EA2//Systems taking place by Nov. 1, 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   The document even contained a mock-up of a Star article about
the sale under the fictitious byline of ``Joe Shiester.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
