<SLUG> BC-NAME-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSAL WOULD PUT BARTLE HALL NAMING RIGHTS UP FOR SALE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ By year's end Bartle Hall could become the
city's biggest billboard.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine ``H. Roe Bartle Hall at the Sprint Convention Center
Complex.'' Or the Hallmark complex. Or the Gateway 2000
complex...or even (shudder) H. Roe Bartle Hall at the Trump
Convention Center Complex.
</P>
<P>
   It's been happening in other cities for almost three decades,
and it could happen here if the City Council approves an idea
advanced Thursday by its Convention &AMP; Entertainment Centers
Management Advisory Authority to sell naming rights to some
deep-pockets local corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about six figures a year,'' said Bill LaMette,
director of the city's convention facilities. ``That's the going
price. A lot of cities are going to it. It's something we can't
afford to ignore.''
</P>
<P>
   LaMette said other public buildings in Kansas City weren't under
consideration for similar deals _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we'll certainly discuss,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's action authorized a city advertising consultant to
begin soliciting reaction and preliminary proposals from interested
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year the issue could be presented to the council for
a decision on whether to proceed with a formal contract process.
</P>
<P>
   No council consensus has formed on the issue, said Councilman
Evert Asjes, chairman of the advisory authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at the viability of it,'' he said Thursday. ``We
want to look at the numbers and the caliber of companies interested
in buying.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, though, the revenue would be substantial _ more than
$500,000 a year, Asjes said.
</P>
<P>
   A consultant for the city, Ken Krogman of Des Moines, Iowa, said
preliminary survey work already had documented exactly what
name-buyers wanted to hear: that their corporate moniker on a
high-profile public building such as Bartle would generate tens of
millions of annual consumer ``impressions'' _ from news reports,
traffic driving by the facility and the millions of people who
annually attend events at Bartle Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sponsors get more bang for their buck,'' he said of name
selling, which is one of the hottest tickets in the advertising
world right now.
</P>
<P>
   Krogman is the driving force behind new marquee signs that soon
will grace the outsides of Bartle Hall and Kemper Arena _ complete
with advertising side panels featuring Coca-Cola, Coors beer and
UMB Bank, among others.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision to sell naming rights to Bartle Hall won't come
without some municipal soul-searching, LaMette said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think there may be some sensitivity toward renaming the
convention center. We don't want to tamper with the integrity of
the name....We would never stop using the name Bartle Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Krogman said he has been there before in similar building
re-naming campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people do choose to let it turn into a billboard,'' and
that offends the local population, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City officials already have laid down the law regarding
marquees and building names, Krogman said. ``It has to be done with
taste.''
</P>
<P>
   There is precedent in Kansas City for trading dollars for a
high-profile name.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, local banker R. Crosby Kemper Jr. donated millions to
help finance the development of an arena in the city's West Bottoms
area. The next year the Crosby Kemper Memorial Arena was named by
the council in honor of Kemper's father, R. Crosby Kemper Sr.
</P>
<P>
   Miles Prentice, the presumptive next owner of the Kansas City
Royals, has made no secret of his intention to increase advertising
revenues at the stadium _ and to take a hard look at naming rights.
</P>
<P>
   Half the teams in baseball's major leagues have sold stadium
naming rights. Major League Baseball itself is exploring whether to
sell advertising space on players' jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   And the outfield wall at Kauffman Stadium is now a collection of
billboards _ for Pepsi, Price Chopper and others _ a la
turn-of-the-century baseball parks.
</P>
<P>
   LaMette and Asjes agreed that the city certainly could use the
money that renaming rights would bring.
</P>
<P>
   It costs about $12 million a year in tax money to staff and run
Bartle Hall and its companion facilities.
</P>
<P>
   LaMette said a mayor's task force two years ago identified about
$60 million in needed or desirable repairs, upgrades and
infrastructure improvements to keep the convention property
competitive with other convention facilities in other cities. Those
needs range from new paint and carpeting to new seating and
plumbing and electrical system upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things we need,'' LaMette said, ``and this
(corporate naming rights trend) isn't going to last forever. We
need to strike while it's hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, city officials are debating expansion plans for
Bartle Hall before the complex becomes hemmed in by other buildings
and can't grow.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time the council is exploring wholesale
privatization of the management of facilities such as Bartle Hall,
parking garages and the like, which promises to put an entirely new
twist on the commercialization of public property.
</P>
<P>
   According to Amusement Business magazine, the modern era of
corporate sponsorships for public buildings began in 1973, when a
dairy company bought naming rights to Buffalo (N.Y.) Stadium and
called it Rich Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium is still home to the National Football League's
Buffalo Bills. The dairy outfit reportedly paid $1.5 million over
25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The price has gone up.
</P>
<P>
   By 1996 the Tropicana beverage company agreed to pay $40 million
over 30 years to rename the Thunderdome in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A year later the Bank One corporation signed a $66 million,
30-year deal to have its name associated with the home of Major
League Baseball's Arizona Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   When Columbus, Ohio, built a new civic arena, the Nationwide
insurance group stepped up to the plate with 90 percent of the
estimated $125 million construction tab _ and got to name the
place.
</P>
<P>
   One of the world's foremost practitioners of corporate vanity _
New York real estate mogul Donald Trump _ is headed to Kansas City,
perhaps just in time to put in his bid for Bartle Hall naming
rights.
</P>
<P>
   According to public records, he already operates several Trump
golf clubs, Trump Palace, Trump Plaza, Trump Tower, Trump Castle,
Trump Village and Trump Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Trump's bid to buy the Flamingo Hilton Casino in Kansas City is
expected to be approved by the Missouri Gaming Commission sometime
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone expects him to call it Trump Casino.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 0136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
