<SLUG> BC-CHARGE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAY-CARE OWNER CHARGED IN ATTACK OF TWINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE LAMOY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Kan. _ One felony and three misdemeanor charges
were brought Thursday against the owner-operator of a Kansas City,
Kan., day-care center where twin 6-year-old girls said they were
sodomized and raped earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Hardridge, 55, was not in custody Thursday evening, but
she has a lawyer who has been in contact with police. Hardridge has
not cooperated in the investigation, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The felony charge _ ``aiding a felon'' _ alleges that Hardridge
tried to help two of the suspects avoid arrest, Wyandotte County
District Attorney Nick Tomasic said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our allegations are that after it was made known that the
girls were sexually molested, she was able to get some of the
participants to lie and say it didn't happen,'' Tomasic said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Tomasic said Hardridge was able to influence two boys who are
related to her. The boys are among five charged with numerous
counts of sexually assaulting the twins.
</P>
<P>
   The misdemeanor charges against Hardridge include two counts of
endangering the girls and one of violating state child-care
regulations. Under guidelines of the Kansas Department of Health
and Environment, which issues licenses for day-care operations, no
children over the age of 3 may play outdoors without the
supervision of an adult who remains within hearing distance at all
times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, they (the victims) were left alone out in the yard,
unsupervised, and something did happen to them,'' Tomasic said.
</P>
<P>
   Conviction upon the felony charge carries a maximum punishment
of nearly two years in prison. None of the misdemeanor charges
carries a punishment of more than a year in jail. Hardridge has no
record of any felony convictions in Wyandotte County.
</P>
<P>
   Tomasic has said that Hardridge was on the premises when the
attack occurred but that investigators don't know where. They also
don't know if any other adults were on the premises, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's talking,'' Tomasic said.
</P>
<P>
   Tomasic said Hardridge had retained a Kansas City, Kan., lawyer,
Marcus B. Potter Jr. Potter did not return two phone messages left
with his office Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Tomasic filed charges against four 13-year-old boys
and an 11-year-old boy alleging that all of them sodomized the
girls. One 13-year-old and the 11-year-old were charged with rape.
A sixth boy who was present but not involved was not charged.
</P>
<P>
   The five suspects, all Kansas City, Kan., residents, are in
juvenile custody. If found guilty, they could be sentenced to state
custody until they turn 21.
</P>
<P>
   Police sent the files involving the boys to Tomasic last week,
but police did not complete the investigation involving Hardridge
until this week. Tomasic said it was not unusual for cases
involving several suspects to arrive at his office in segments.
</P>
<P>
   The twins, who live with their mother in the Armourdale area of
Kansas City, Kan., told police on May 16 that they had been raped
and sodomized at the day-care center the previous day. The girls
later said that several boys attacked them in a backyard shed and
the basement of the facility, which operated in side-by-side
houses.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the attack, the boys were in the back yard of the
facility playing basketball, and the girls were playing on swings.
</P>
<P>
   The girls apparently said nothing to their mother after she
picked them up on May 15. But they did tell her the next day, when
the girls again went to the day-care center.
</P>
<P>
   The mother took the girls to the University of Kansas Medical
Center, where they were treated and examined and police were
called. Tomasic said one of the girls was traumatized.
</P>
<P>
   Hardridge had been licensed to operate the day-care center since
March 23, 1998. Under that license, she was allowed to care for up
to six children at a time, said Don Brown, spokesman for the Kansas
Department of Health and Environment.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Hardridge requested a license to keep up to 12
children at once, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   She was granted a temporary permit to operate with the greater
number of children until the Public Health Department of Wyandotte
County's Unified Government could inspect the facility, he said.
The state agency contracts with the local department to inspect
day-care centers.
</P>
<P>
   The state agency ordered Hardridge's center closed on May 19,
two days after the allegations surfaced.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
