<SLUG> BC-CROSS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN ARRESTED FOR KANSAS CITY AREA CROSS-BURNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN BORMANN and TONY RIZZO  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A 20-year-old Lenexa, Kan., man was arrested
Thursday in a cross-burning in the yard of a black Overland Park,
Kan., family. Police were investigating whether it was a form of
retaliation for a fistfight between two teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County District Attorney Paul Morrison said a felony
charge of making a criminal threat would be filed today against
Brian J. Hoffman, who also was identified as the suspect in a
statement by Overland Park, a suburb of Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI is considering whether to seek federal hate-crime
charges against Hoffman, who is white. He was being held Thursday
night in the Johnson County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in a lot of trouble because of an incredibly stupid,
hateful act,'' Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   A 16-year-old youth also was questioned but was not arrested.
</P>
<P>
   About 9:15 p.m. Wednesday, two males placed a cross on the front
lawn of the house, a neighbor told police. The two lighted the
cross, then ran down the street and drove off in a red car, the
neighbor said.
</P>
<P>
   The description of the car led officers to Hoffman and the
16-year-old, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Morris Harris Sr., who lives in the ranch-style house with his
two children and wife, said he thinks the two waited for the family
to leave before approaching the yard. He believes a school fight
Wednesday involving his son, Maurice, played some part in the
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Maurice Harris, 17, fought with another student at
Shawnee Mission North High School. That student is not a suspect,
but all four individuals are acquaintances, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Harris said the school fight was not racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson County authorities take cross-burnings and other hate
crimes seriously, Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to ask yourself, does a person that does something
like this have any idea how bad it is or how it affects other
people?'' Morrison said. ``It never ceases to amaze me that in this
day and age people are thoughtless enough or stupid enough to do
something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Kansas does not have a specific hate crimes law, a
judge can double a sentence if it can be proved that a crime was
motivated by racial or ethnic hatred, Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Hoffman could face six months to three years in
prison under state sentencing guidelines, depending on his record,
Morrison said. Hoffman does not have a criminal record in Johnson
County, according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   Federal charges would carry a sentence of up to 10 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Hate crimes are increasing across the country, FBI spokesman
Jeff Lanza said. But, he said, ``I believe this is the first time
in recent history that we've had one in Johnson County.''
</P>
<P>
   Overland Park Mayor Ed Eilert called the cross-burning
despicable and vulgar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as neighbors and friends of the Harris family find this
unbelievable to comprehend, we too have little understanding why
anyone would commit such a vicious and hateful act,'' he said. ``On
behalf of the citizens of Overland Park, I want to firmly state
that such hate crimes will not be tolerated in this community.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris Harris Sr., who recently graduated from the Overland Park
Citizens Police Academy, said the family had no intention of
leaving the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very serious act,'' he said. ``But at the same time
we're going to try to live and go on with our lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 0138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 01:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4376 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HUD-KAN &LR;      05-28 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER CONGRESSMAN LAMENTS PERSISTENT HOUSING DISCRIMINATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Former U.S. Rep. Louis Stokes was in Kansas
City on Thursday to talk about housing discrimination in terms the
banking community best understands: It costs everyone, including
mortgage lenders, money.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Department of Housing and Urban Development,
2.5 million instances of housing discrimination occur against
minorities every year. Congress has earmarked $47 million for
fiscal 2000 to root out those practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's $47 million right there, right off the top, that it's
costing Americans,'' Stokes said. ``I think that figure would
appeal to mortgage lenders, particularly when they're making more
money than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Stokes, who for 30 years represented a Cleveland district in the
U.S. House, addressed about 100 people attending ``Breaking Down
the Barriers,'' a home-ownership symposium put on by HUD and the
Economic Development Financial Corp. Stokes encouraged the crowd to
continue the crusade to right discriminatory wrongs in America.
</P>
<P>
   Discrimination in housing or any other area of life is an
attitude problem, Stokes said, and it's hard to change people's
attitudes. So, he said, some people need to be talked to on a level
they understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody who is a bigot wants to be known as a bigot,'' Stokes
said. ``But they will respond to leadership ... and regardless of
where they are in their hearts, they will understand the
economics.''
</P>
<P>
   Stokes told about an apartment manager receiving HUD money who
proudly boasted of his ability to keep African-Americans out of his
complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought when my children became adults there wouldn't
be discrimination in our society,'' said Stokes, 74. ``Instead I
have grandchildren facing the same issues I did as a young man.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to believe as we enter a new century that we
are still grappling with discrimination in all facets of our
society in the greatest country in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   But progress is being made, Stokes said.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter of this year, 72.8 percent of white
households owned their own home. That compares with 46.9 percent
for black households and 46.2 percent for Hispanic households.
</P>
<P>
   Though the gap is substantial, home ownership among black and
Hispanic people is growing faster than for the population as a
whole. For instance, from 1994 to the present, 39 percent of new
homeowners were minorities, although they accounted for just under
a quarter of the total population.
</P>
<P>
   Stokes still despairs, particularly after reading a recent
series in The Kansas City Star about housing discrimination in this
area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cited that rejection rates (for mortgages) of upper
middle-class African-Americans is tantamount to that of low-income
whites,'' Stokes said. ``To me, that showed the blatancy of
discrimination.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
