<HEADLINE>
HIGHER FUEL PRICES WON'T DETER MOTORISTS THIS MEMORIAL DAY
WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Moderately higher gasoline prices won't deter
motorists from hitting the road this Memorial Day weekend, predicts
Charlie Barr, assistant director of the Clay County Parks and
Recreation Department.
</P>
<P>
   The unofficial opening of the summer driving season also is the
first time in months that many families have had three days in a
row during which no one has had to be at school or work, said Barr,
who has been watching recreationists flock to Smithville Lake north
of Kansas City, Mo., each summer for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Upward of 45,000 people are expected there if this weekend's
weather is as pleasant as forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Fourth of July or Labor Day, when travel costs
sometimes sway travel plans, ``Memorial Day is a `get me out of the
house' holiday,'' Barr said.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, a record 33.3 million Americans will travel at least
100 miles this long weekend, according to the American Automobile
Association and the Travel Industry Association of America, a trade
group in Washington. Most plan to travel by car, despite higher
gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists traveling in or through the Kansas City area aren't
likely to find fuel prices alarmingly higher, price watchers say.
</P>
<P>
   AAA Automobile Club of Missouri, in its most recent Kansas City
area survey, taken last week, found lead-free regular gasoline
selling for an average $1.08 a gallon at self-service pumps. That
is up from $1.01 a gallon during Memorial Day weekend last year.
</P>
<P>
   Regional prices for lead-free regular range from $1.34 in the
far western United States to $1.06 in the Southeast, according to
the auto club survey.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, production problems that contributed to an April
increase in prices at the pump now appear to have eased, said
Trilby Lundberg, Los Angeles publisher of the Lundberg Survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time, what seems most likely is further drops in pump
prices, pre-Memorial Day and beyond,'' Lundberg said last week
after her organization's weekly poll of 10,000 service stations
across the United States found the first decrease in prices since
early March.
</P>
<P>
   But she said there were two unknowns: crude oil prices and extra
strong gasoline demand.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Energy Department forecasters in Washington say gasoline
demand this summer will increase about 2.4 percent from
year-earlier levels, mostly because more drivers will be on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   But crude oil prices generally have been falling from peaks in
April and are expected generally to stay flat or rise only slightly
through September, the forecasters say.
</P>
<P>
   Their bottom line? Retail prices will dip slowly starting next
month, but motorists on average will pay about 9 cents a gallon
more than a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Prices that motorists pay will depend on where they travel this
weekend, other observers say. Informal spot checks around Kansas
City suggest that many stations have dropped their prices a penny
or two since the auto club's most recent survey last week.
</P>
<P>
   Area residents who travel to the Lake of the Ozarks will be able
to fill up for the trip home for under 98 cents a gallon, if the
prices that prevailed at midweek don't change, said Joel Pottinger,
executive director of the Lake of the Ozarks Convention and Visitor
Bureau.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
