<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS NOW A SIGHT FOR EYESORES 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This was nothing like watching Roger Clemens pitch
for the Toronto Blue Jays. This was Clemens in Yankee pinstripes.
This was swan boats in the Harlem River, Legal Seafood chowder at
P.J. Clarke's, Ted Kennedy summering in the Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   The bad karma goes all the way back to a drunken gentlemen's
agreement struck between Red Sox owner Harry Frazee and Yankee
owner Jacob Ruppert _ both New Yorkers. It has outlasted almost
every other sports hex and frustrated Red Sox Nation for eight
decades.
</P>
<P>
   Now Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees bought Babe Ruth and held the mortgage on Fenway
Park. Then they won all the games that needed to be won. There was
'49 and there was '78. Boston had a DiMaggio, but New York had the
best DiMaggio. The Yankees swiped Sparky Lyle and Luis Tiant. Bucky
``Bleeping'' Dent. Then they made us watch Wade Boggs, in
pinstripes, riding a horse after winning a World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Now Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   The scoreboard reads like this: world championships won since
1920 _ Yankees 24, Red Sox 0. Sounds like a Jets-Patriots final.
</P>
<P>
   It was against the black crepe backdrop of Hub hardball history
that Clemens performed his artistry Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, beating the
Red Sox, 4-1, with seven innings of two-hit pitching.
</P>
<P>
   It was Clemens's first appearance against Boston while wearing
the uniform of the hated Yankees and gave him an American
League-record 19 consecutive wins over two seasons (the major
league record is 24 by Carl Hubbell in 1936-37). He also pulled the
Yankees within a half-game of the Sox in the AL East. Since his
furious departure from Boston, Clemens is 3-0 with a 1.64 ERA in
five starts against All Duquette's Men.
</P>
<P>
   As ever, Clemens downplayed the impact of sticking it to the
Sox. There was no Duquette executive box to glare at, and he simply
won't acknowledge that he loves to kick the spit out of his former
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every win is a nice win for me,'' he said. ``It's not just
Boston. I've pitched against Boston. They've got a good club. They
put the ball in play. Being over here, a lot of teams come at you
extremely hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Let Clemens pretend it's no big deal. It's like when Bill
Parcells tells us he gets no extra kick from continually
embarrassing the Bob Kraft Athletic Club.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Clemens in pinstripes against the Sox was a little like
watching Parcells with the Jets or Arthur Fiedler with the New York
Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   After warming up in the home team bullpen in The House That Ruth
Built, Clemens skipped around the corner to Monument Park and wiped
sweat from his brow on the Babe Ruth plaque. This was part of his
routine when he wore a Red Sox uniform. In those days, it was
Roger's humble attempt to break the Curse of the Bambino. Now his
job is to perpetuate the Curse.
</P>
<P>
   Fans were treated to a stirring national anthem by Robert
Merrill, then Clemens took the mound at 7:06 p.m. while the public
address system bounced Elton John's ``Rocket Man'' off the Yankee
Stadium facade.
</P>
<P>
   He fanned the first Sox batter, fellow Texan Jeff Frye. Patrons
upstairs pinned a special-edition Clemens K card (featuring a photo
of a space shuttle launch) to the front wall of the upper deck.
</P>
<P>
   After Frye struck out, John Valentin drilled a hard hopper to
the right of Derek Jeter. Jeter made no attempt to get in front of
the ball, and when it ricocheted off his glove, the official scorer
awarded Valentin a hit. It should have been an error. It looked as
if the scorer was protecting Jeter, but his decision would prove
controversial when Clemens allowed no other hits through the first
five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter loves playing behind Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tells the infield where they're going to hit it,'' said the
shortstop. ``He'll verbally tell you, `Here it comes.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Boston starter Pat Rapp hit Chuck Knoblauch in the third, and
you didn't need Peter Gammons to tell you that some payback was en
route. Clemens could not let that go unchecked. Knoblauch is a
teammate, a Texan, and a fellow Hendricks client.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin led off the fourth, but the Rocket spared his longtime
teammate. After Valentin grounded to third, Clemens threw at Reggie
Jefferson's head on an 0-2 pitch. Jefferson ducked, saved his life,
then struck out. Clemens had five K's in the first four innings.
</P>
<P>
   He had trouble with his location in the fifth and sixth. After
two Clemens walks in the sixth, Valentin tied the game with a sharp
single to left. Clemens threw 25 pitches in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disappointing when guys are fighting to give you one
run, then you turn around and give it back,'' he said. ``I was
fortunate to get out of that inning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was mad at himself,'' said Yankee manager Joe Torre. ``He
figured, `They got me a run; that should be enough.' That's what
the great ones do.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens got the side in order in the seventh, and that was it.
He threw 105 pitches, 62 strikes.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee crowd was fairly tame about the whole matter. As
always, most of the emotion was being felt by folks back home in
Boston. At times, the New York-Boston rivalry is a little like the
Humphrey Bogart exchange in ``Casablanca.'' Peter Lorre
(representing Boston) says, ``You detest me, don't you, Rick?'' and
Bogart (New York) says, ``If I gave you any thought, I probably
would.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the rivalry is more of a big deal to the fans now than
it is to the players,'' said Don Zimmer, a man who has played no
small role in baseball's Hatfield-McCoy feud. ``Back in the '70s
when I was coaching and managing in Boston, the Red Sox and Yankees
really hated each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Zim has been with Clemens in Boston and in New York. He knows
that New York is where the rings are won. That's why Clemens is
here, another living monument to eight decades of Boston torture at
the hands of the evil New York empire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 0146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
