<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 01:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4381 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-REDSOX-BO     05-28 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS HAUNTS RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As a portrait in pinstripes, he was no different than
when he flaunted a Canadian bird above the bill of his cap.
</P>
<P>
   Once more with feeling, Roger Clemens reduced his former mates
to an exercise in frustration, mastering the Red Sox with the same
alacrity with which he fled Yawkey Way 29 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who in the first two seasons of his voluntary exile won
more games (41) than in his last four years in the Fens (40), beat
his old team for the first time Thursday &UR;  &LR; night as a Yankee, 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens allowed just one run and two singles, both by John
Valentin, struck out seven, and threw one pitch at somebody's head
(Reggie Jefferson) in seven innings before departing to the cheers
of 27,631 in Yankee Stadium who happily cursed his name in years
gone by.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing about Roger,'' said Valentin, who drove in the
Sox' run in the sixth. ``All those years I played behind him, but
the more I see him, the better I think he is. He's a great pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``That doesn't mean you can't beat him. But he was quite
different when I was playing behind him. He was more of a power
pitcher, and for a couple of years, I didn't think he had the
command he now does with his offspeed pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether he would say that, I don't know. But when you've
played behind him, then see him again as a batter, you can see the
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, the Yankees had lost seven of eight, including two
straight to Boston, before El Duque, Orlando Hernandez, tamed the
Sox in Fenway. Now, after a double dose of Hernandez and Clemens in
the last two nights that ended a four-game Boston winning streak,
including the opener here, the Yankees have won five of seven to
draw within a half-game of the Sox, whose lead in the American
League East may be sorely tested by a three-day weekend in
Cleveland, the hottest team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't overmatched,'' Sox first baseman Mike Stanley said
of splitting six games in the home-and-home set against the
Bombers. ``The last two nights, we had pretty good pitching
performances against us.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, we've pitched well. We haven't been blown out of the
water. We know we can play with them.''
</P>
<P>
   But so far, they have yet to beat the Rocket, who not only
benefited from the fifth straight errorless game turned in by the
Yanks but made two fine defensive plays, barehanding a ball by Jeff
Frye in the third and starting a double play in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who has three wins and two no-decisions in five starts
against the Sox, extended his AL record to 19 straight decisions
without a defeat, a streak that began one year ago Saturday. He is
within five of the major league record set by another New Yorker,
Carl Hubbell of the Giants, 62 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   While he relied more on his split-fingered fastball and slider
to keep the Sox off balance, he wasn't above uncorking his fastball
at Jefferson's nose an inning after Boston starter Pat Rapp hit
Chuck Knoblauch in the back with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson ducked out of harm's way, but there was no mistaking
the message.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the devil,'' Valentin acknowledged after first
saying that hitters can't worry about being hit by a Rocket thrust.
``It creeps in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee offense did some creeping of its own to score two
runs off Rapp, who was not overmatched by Clemens as much as he was
undone by New York baserunners, who stole three bases and hurried
rookie catcher Creighton Gubanich into a throwing error that led to
the go-ahead run in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees snapped a scoreless tie in the fifth, which opened
with Chili Davis's ground single up the middle. Davis broke early
for second on an apparent run-and-hit play, then came to a stop,
but his premature move went unnoticed by Rapp, who delivered to the
plate. Gubanich still nearly got him, but Davis kicked the ball out
of the glove of Nomar Garciaparra, back at shortstop after missing
a game with a finger injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see (Davis) getting edgy,'' Stanley said, ``and when
he broke early, I screamed, but I guess it was too late. How often
do you see a play like that? I think it caught (Rapp) off guard.''
</P>
<P>
   One out later, Tony Tarasco drove a single up the middle,
scoring Davis.
</P>
<P>
   With Clemens enduring a stretch in which he went to a full count
against five of six batters, Valentin tied the score in the sixth
when he drove a single through the left side to bring in rookie
Trot Nixon, who ignored Jefferson's frantic admonition to slide and
was nearly tagged out by Jorge Posada.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees seized the lead for good in the bottom of the inning
when Jeter singled, stole second, and went to third when Gubanich's
throw sailed into center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was his first day back,'' Rapp said of Gubanich. ``He
didn't get good throws down all three times. I guess he was a
little nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Rapp almost waded through, retiring the next two hitters before
Tino Martinez lined a single low off the wall in right to score
Jeter. That brought Jimy Williams out of the Sox dugout and a
summons for lefthander Mark Guthrie.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't go over well with Rapp, who hadn't walked a man all
night. He snarled at pitching coach Joe Kerrigan when approached in
the visitors' dugout, then slammed his glove against the bat rack
as he made his way to the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a man on first, I didn't think I was coming out,'' Rapp
said. ``There were two outs and a chance to get an out to go to the
next inning, but Jimy made his move and we didn't give up another
run there.''
</P>
<P>
   The reprieve was short-lived. Posada homered off Guthrie in the
seventh to make it 3-1, and Bernie Williams singled home the fourth
run off Jim Corsi in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was in the clubhouse long before three relievers,
including closer Mariano Rivera (13th save), finished off the Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he was as powerful as I've seen him before,''
Valentin said. ``But he's just a polished pitcher now.''
</P>
<P>
   And that polish now glows in the Apple.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
