A4382 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-SABRES-MAPLELEAFS     05-28 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-SABRES-MAPLE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PECA SPARKS SABRES 
</HEADLINE>
 LEAFS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO _ Ottawa found out. Ditto the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's Toronto's turn.
</P>
<P>
   A few too many mistakes and a little too much Michael Peca. That
combination of booboos and the relentless buzzing of Peca and his
fellow checkers did in the Maple Leafs Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, resulting
in a 4-2 Buffalo victory that gave the Sabres a 2-1 advantage in
the best-of-seven Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were the better team tonight,'' said Toronto
captain Mats Sundin, who, like Alexei Yashin and Jason Allison
before him, was silenced by Peca's dogged checking. ``There was a
stretch there of five or six minutes when they made less mistakes
than we did _ and our mistakes cost us the game.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since their opening playoff series vs. the
Senators, the Sabres were working with a full lineup. They had
Dominik Hasek back in net, along with Michal Grosek and Miroslav
Satan up front. When the night was over, they also had their 10th
victory of this playoff season, tying a franchise record and
leaving them only two victories shy of returning to the Stanley Cup
finals for the first time since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great _ I always said we're a good team when we're
healthy,'' said Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff, whose club is 10-3 in the
playoffs. ``We're still good even when we're not quite so
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest addition was Hasek, who sat out Games 1 and 2 of
this series with a strained groin. Hasek, it turns out, reinjured
himself in Game 4 of the Boston series, which was by far the
Bruins' worst performance of the postseason. He was still hurting
in Games 5 and 6 against the Bruins. If they had been able to push
the series to the limit, Hasek might not have been able to play.
Now there's some added summer agony for Boston fans.
</P>
<P>
   Satan's return was a big boost to the Buffalo offense. He led
the club with 40 goals in the regular season but went down in Game
3 of the Ottawa series with a badly bruised ankle (courtesy of an
Alexei Zhitnik slapper). Thursday &UR;  &LR; night he touched off a
three-goal second period in which the Sabres erased a 1-0 deficit
and took a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're standing and watching,'' said Leafs coach Pat Quinn,
whose club managed only three shots in the first period _ one of
them good for a Yanic Perreault goal. ``We don't pursue as well as
we'd like. All three games, we haven't done what we want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In large measure, Toronto's inability to make plays and score
has been because of the Sabres' supreme checking line, centered by
Peca and with Dixon Ward and Vaclav Varada on the wings. Peca
figured in only only goal Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, a tiebreaking strike by
ex-Bruin Joe Juneau that came with Buffalo killing a penalty.
Otherwise, Peca's chief assignment was minimizing Sundin's
effectiveness. The big Toronto captain still managed five of his
club's 26 shots but didn't make the scoresheet. Sundin also fouled
Peca twice, resulting in four minutes in the penalty box for the
most valuable Maple Leaf.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres essentially won it with their run in the second,
beginning with Satan's tying strike against Curtis Joseph at 3:07.
The Leafs were guilty of a poor pass exchange between defensemen
Sylvain Cote and Tomas Kaberle, resulting in a loose puck that
Satan swatted in with a quick backhand. Only 38 seconds later, Peca
bolted out on a penalty kill and hit CuJo with a long-range slapper
off right wing. Juneau cruised in for the easy conversion, not a
Maple Leaf defender in sight. Next, at 7:38, Stu Barnes popped in a
power-play goal (Sundin in the box for holding, you guessed it,
Peca).
</P>
<P>
   The Leafs cut it to 3-2 before the period ended when former
Ranger Alexander Karpovtsev drilled in a power-play goal while
Hasek was trying to recover his stick. With 28.1 seconds to go in
the game, Curtis Brown connected into an empty net, with CuJo
pulled for an extra attacker.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the old-time flavor of the postseason, a nasty
punchfest broke out with 12.6 seconds to go, featuring the Sabres'
Erik Rasmussen vs. Kevyn Adams, the former Bruins first-round draft
pick. The Sabres were rankled by the fact that Quinn rolled out
tough guys Tie Domi and Kris King with the game essentially
finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Classless!'' said Ruff. ``I don't think we did anything for
them to react that way. I guess they don't think they can beat us
in the goal-scoring department, so they thought they'd go about it
that way.''
</P>
<P>
   When play resumed, Dwayne Roloson was in net for Hasek. The No.
1 Buffalo netminder was already in the dressing room, the victory
safely put away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
