<SLUG> BC-NCAASOFTBALL_ARIZ </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO GIFTS FOR SUN DEVILS  
 ASU FAILS TO SEIZE OPPORTUNITIES AT CWS 
</HEADLINE>
 ST-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ The lesson Arizona State softball should have
learned during its 8-20 Pac-10 season still is being taught at the
Women's College World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to earn the game,'' ASU Coach Linda Wells said
after a deceptive 4-1 loss to Washington at Don Porter Hall of Fame
Stadium. ``We were waiting for the game to be given.''
</P>
<P>
   The 16th-ranked Sun Devils had Huskies starting pitcher Jamie
Graves of Phoenix in trouble for the first three innings Thursday
night but stranded four runners. No. 6 Washington then switched to
Jennifer Spediacci, who was mostly untouchable until the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Huskies (49-17) had four runs, all unearned off
Kirsten Voak because of a Missy Hixon throwing error in the top of
the sixth. More than enough to advance into tonight's 6:30 winner's
bracket game against No. 3 Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ASU (41-27), playing in the CWS for the first time since 1987
and still seeking its first win since '82, drops into an
elimination game against No. 17 California at 12:30 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the game in our hand and didn't play it out,'' said
Wells, who used a pinch-runner and pinch-hitter in the second in an
attempt to push at least one run across. ``When you go to the
bench, baby, you'd better get something out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Gill grounded out to the third baseman to end the first
and third innings, and pinch-hitter Jennifer Gall struck out to end
the second.
</P>
<P>
   A three-time Arizona Player of the Year for Moon Valley High
School, Graves limited the Sun Devils to one run in two
regular-season decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But she wasn't getting low strike calls from umpire Dan Morrow,
so Washington Coach Teresa Wilson switched to Spediacci, who like
Voak is out of Washington High School in Fremont, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found out the zones were not compatible, so we switched,''
Wilson said. ``I have two really great pitchers. They really
complement each other. As a coach, I could not be luckier with what
I have to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   While Spediacci (22-8) throttled ASU with her rise ball, the
Huskies kept probing for an answer to the hard-throwing Voak
(24-14). It came after Becky Newbry reached on Hixon's error, then
stole second.
</P>
<P>
   With first base open and two outs, Voak intentionally walked
Melissa Downs only to have both runners advance on a passed ball.
That changed the dynamics as Erin Helgeland, a .220 hitter who was
0 for 2, came to bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kirsten throws a screaming ball,'' Voak said. ``With a runner
at third, you want to be careful (not to throw a wild pitch) so
you're trying to walk that line. She (Helgeland) has nothing to
lose by swinging at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The junior center fielder took a whack at an outside and high
1-2 pitch to double just fair down the left-field line. Christie
Rosenblad and Graves followed with hits, icing Washington's fourth
win in five tries vs. ASU.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make the outs yourself,'' said Voak, not pinning
blame on her teammates. ``You can't count on anything else. You get
a couple of tough breaks and the balls get through and there you
are.''
</P>
<P>
   A single by Holly Smith, double by Erin Wardein and sacrifice
fly got the Sun Devils on the board in the seventh, but with too
little to offset the damage.
</P>
<P>
   ASU now takes a fifth crack at Cal (49-21) after previously
splitting with the Bears. Erica Beach (16-13), named to the
All-America first team as a designated player, no-hit Cal on May 2
but has pitched only seven innings in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Also making the National Fastpich Coaches Association
All-America team were Graves on the second team and Voak on the
third team. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
