<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-LEE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEE GETTING BACK IN SWING OF THINGS  
 STRUGGLING D-BACK MAKING PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Travis Lee took two steps forward earlier this week before
taking another one back. But that's OK, as far as the Diamondbacks
are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   That their first baseman made progress was a welcome sign at
Bank One Ballpark during the three-game sweep over San Diego and
last week while the club was on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``God has given me a beautiful swing,'' said Lee, who celebrated
his 24th birthday Wednesday. ``But hitting a baseball is all about
all kinds of adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been obvious through the early going that pitchers have
adjusted to Lee. They're trying to pitch him high and tight with
fastballs before going away with breaking balls.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's Lee's turn to return the volleys and adjust to what
he's seeing at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Lee had his first three-hit game of the season Monday night
against the Padres. He followed with another three-hit performance
on Tuesday before going 0 for 4 with three strikeouts Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travis Lee is the last thing I worry about,'' said Manager
Buck Showalter, who will lead the Diamondbacks into the first of a
three-game series in New York tonight. ``He has great mental
toughness. I have a lot of faith in him. We just want him to be
what he's capable of being. But I don't think anyone knows yet who
he's going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who carries the added burden of being known as the $10
million signing bonus kid, burst onto the major league scene early
last season, showing signs of being a dominant hitter early but
fading as the season progressed.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for that was a nasty groin injury that landed
him on the disabled list and then hindered his swing during the
final two months, when he hit a combined .227. Another factor was
the 162-game season, a taxing proposition for any first-year
player.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, though, Lee wound up with above-average rookie
numbers. He batted .269 with 22 home runs and 72 RBIs and finished
behind Chicago's Kerry Wood and Colorado's Todd Helton for National
League Rookie of the Year. Before combining for just five home runs
and 26 RBIs in his final 65 games, Lee was considered the
front-runner for NL rookie honors.
</P>
<P>
   He began this season showing signs of zooming again before
hitting a slump that saw his average dip below .220, a scary sign
considering he had more than 100 at-bats at the time. But a recent
surge, accompanied by a slight change in his batting mechanics, has
seen Lee's average soar to .246, still low but headed in the
direction the Diamondbacks want to see.
</P>
<P>
   Several major league scouts noticed Lee had dropped his left
elbow quite a few inches during his slump, a problem that may have
occurred if Lee was trying to hit for more power, which one
American League scout said he believed to be true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked into a (Diamondbacks team shop) a few weeks ago and
noticed a picture of Travis with his elbow way up,'' hitting coach
Jim Presley said. ``His hands were higher in the picture. So we
immediately started working on it. He's loading up and letting it
go now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's too good to fall too far. You don't see many Travis Lees
come down the road very often.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter also got Lee to start lifting his front foot a bit and
straying it forward before hitting. It's used to create a kind of
pendulum effect that has his body going toward the pitcher, rather
than stationary, when he's swinging.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's ability to hit to the opposite field is what scouts
immediately noticed about him last year. But for a monthlong
stretch, Lee was pulling the ball to right field more than he
should have been.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 10 days or so, Lee has started using the entire
field again, an obvious sign that his approach and swing are
returning to the level he demonstrated last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I feel locked in and I'm on, it doesn't matter what they
throw,'' Lee said. ``When I'm on, I'm not really thinking about
where my elbow is, or lifting my foot. When I'm not, I'm thinking
way too much and my confidence goes down. What got me here is my
ability to hit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
