<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS LOSE 6-3
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Angels manager Terry Collins looked in the mirror
Thursday morning and saw a 50-year-old man staring back at him.
</P>
<P>
   So what did Collins do to celebrate this milestone birthday? He
shook up his lineup, only to find out no matter how much he moved
things around, the results were similar to those when he was 49.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels offense sputtered again in a 6-3 loss to the
Baltimore Orioles before 24,724 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Brady Anderson's grand slam off Angels reliever Mike Magnante in
the seventh inning broke open a 2-1 game and paved the way for the
Orioles' second win in the three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Guzman (2-4) gave up one run and three hits in six innings
to get the victory over Angels starter Ken Hill (1-4). Hill left
the game with one out in the seventh, the bases loaded and Anderson
due up. He said he felt good and had been throwing well all game,
but Collins and the Angels are trying to be careful with Hill, who
had elbow surgery last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a thing with him to keep making sure he doesn't
extend himself,'' Collins said. ``We want to keep him in games all
summer long.''
</P>
<P>
   Countered Hill, who threw 102 pitches: ``I understand it in
terms of pitch count. But sometimes you've got to throw it out the
window. I was throwing the ball good.... You worry about today
right now, you worry about tomorrow, tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins got a few fresh bats in the game and moved some others
around in an effort to change the fortunes of an offense that went
into the game ranked 11th out of 14 American League teams in
hitting.
</P>
<P>
   But with Orlando Palmeiro and Jeff Huson among those getting a
chance to play, it ultimately came down to Mo Vaughn providing the
bulk of the offense once again.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn homered (No.11) and doubled twice, driving in two runs.
Randy Velarde drove in the Angels' other run with a single in the
eighth inning, but the late rally proved futile.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, my game's not going to change, I'm not going to add
pressure to my game (because others aren't hitting),'' Vaughn said.
``My thing is to talk to the guys, be confident and positive with
the team. I can't do more than the situation dictates.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I've still got Garret (Anderson) behind me and he's
swinging the bat well. I'm not thinking I have to carry the load on
my back. That's how you get yourself in trouble. I've got a good
approach right now and I'm going to stay with that approach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
