<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4404 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBC-ARIZONA &UR; STATE-AZR     05-28 1811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-ARIZONA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU'S BASEBALL GLORY DAYS FADE 
</HEADLINE>
  STATE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JAVIER MORALES  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gone are the days when Pat Brock accompanied her husband, the
late Jim Brock, on recruiting trips to sway the mothers of high
school baseball players.
</P>
<P>
   The road to Omaha is no longer paved with victories over Air
Force, Colorado State, Idaho, Weber State, Denver and Gonzaga. A
battalion of wealthy programs in Texas, Florida and the Southeast
now presents a roadblock.
</P>
<P>
   Packard Stadium, showing its age after 25 years, has lost its
standing as the crown jewel of college baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona State's reputation as a pipeline of major league talent
_ funneling the likes of Rick Monday, Reggie Jackson, Floyd
Bannister, Ken Landreaux, Bob Horner and Barry Bonds into
professional prosperity _ has faded.
</P>
<P>
   An entire generation has passed since ASU last won a College
World Series title in 1981. It has only one conference title in the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The good old days for ASU baseball have become a distant memory.
Further evidence came in the form of another snub from the NCAA
tournament selection committee Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ASU has failed to reach the tournament three of the past five
years under Coach Pat Murphy, after it went seven of Brock's final
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   ``ASU is feeling the pinch like a lot of schools,'' said Texas
Coach Augie Garrido, formerly at California State-Fullerton.
Garrido said the predicament Murphy faces is not unlike what he's
come up against in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up until the mid-1970s, Southern Cal dominated college
baseball,'' he said. ``Then came scholarship limits, and
immediately, teams with the best facilities got the upper hand.
Texas dominated the game for the next decade. Then everybody
started to build great facilities. That's when Texas' dominance
began to fade.''
</P>
<P>
   Expectations remain high for the Sun Devils, but reality says
otherwise. A double-edged sword has thinned the talent pool
dramatically since the program's golden era: fewer scholarships to
give, many more quality programs competing for players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of respect for Pat Murphy because it is a tough
program to coach,'' said Jeff Pentland, a former ASU player and
assistant coach who is now the Chicago Cubs hitting instructor.
``The excellence of the program creates problems. It creates
expectations that are way off the charts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program, in my mind, is still steeped in tradition, but
it's harder to maintain a dynasty with so few scholarships to work
with. The days of going to 11 straight College World Series, like
USC once did, are over.'' &QL; 
Reduced scholarships &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scholarships have been reduced from 25 during Brock's heyday to
11.7 in the 1990s. A total of 1.5 were allotted this season to
ASU's 14-player pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the NCAA started putting limits on things, I thought that
was totally un-American, and it drove me out of college baseball,''
said Pentland, who played at ASU for Bobby Winkles from 1966 to
1968 and coached under Brock from 1983 to 1992.
</P>
<P>
   There are other factors that have contributed to ASU's slipping
from prominence on the college baseball map:
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA's increasing reliance on the Ratings Percentage Index
to determine the NCAA tournament bracket.
</P>
<P>
   Competition for top talent from major league teams, which are
now offering signing bonuses in excess of $3 million and packages
that cover college tuition costs.
</P>
<P>
   Reduced participation by African-American players. Less than 4
percent of Pac-10 players are Black. ASU has a rich tradition of
exceptional Black players such as Bonds, Landreaux, Jackson, Hubie
Brooks, Alvin Davis, Oddibe McDowell, Mike Devereaux and Mike Kelly
that has seemingly expired.
</P>
<P>
   A shift of power from the West to the South, where facilities
are being built or upgraded and college baseball has less
competition for interest from the pros. &QL; 
SEC vs. Pac-10 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Southeastern Conference has five national championships this
decade _ four by Louisiana State and one by Georgia _ and none
before 1990. Pac-10 schools have one title this decade _ USC over
ASU in last year's title game _ after eight in the '70s and five in
the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama sold out its tickets before the season started and
averaged 4,007 fans a game. LSU led the nation by averaging 7,132.
Arkansas (2,496) and Auburn (2,811) each set school records for
average attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Packard Stadium, with a capacity of 4,000, averaged 2,170 fans
this season. Since leading the nation in attendance in 1984 with
3,349 fans a game, the Sun Devils have not averaged more than
2,800. They dipped to 1,356 in 1994, Brock's last year.
</P>
<P>
   Competition from the Suns, Coyotes, expanded spring training in
Arizona and the Diamondbacks has taken a toll.
</P>
<P>
   ASU officials want to help Murphy's recruiting efforts and the
atmosphere at Packard Stadium by allocating $3 million of their $20
million capital improvement campaign on renovations over the next
two to three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our master plan is to expand the clubhouse, with a new locker
room and training room,'' said Vic Cegles, ASU associate athletic
director for external affairs. ``We're going to build a new
entranceway with a Walk of Fame, and we're going to expand our
grandstand area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The press box will also be renovated. At Wichita State, they
are building sky boxes. We have to keep up with the times. Packard
Stadium is outdated compared to some of the SEC schools.'' &QL; 
Ratings `absurd' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ASU Athletic Director Kevin White believes the most absurd
development in college baseball is the RPI, which was not in the
sport's vocabulary less than 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The rating reflects strength of schedule by factoring the
winning percentage of a team and its opponents' winning
percentages.
</P>
<P>
   Without the RPI, ASU would not have been excluded the past five
years, school officials argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``The RPI was created for college basketball to provide a
national comparison because it is competed on a national scale,''
White said. ``College baseball is much more regionalized in scope.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NCAA is using a mechanism that was created for one sport
and using it on another, and it doesn't work. It's simply wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   As an example, at-large teams Northeast Louisiana and Rutgers
have better RPIs than ASU because they beat an abundance of
non-NCAA tournament teams with winning records in the South and
East.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't tell me Rutgers has a better shot at a title than
Arizona State,'' said Mikel Moreno, a former Sun Devils player who
is now an assistant coach. &QL; 
Changing course &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the sport understands that within the different
regions, there are different levels of competitive programs,''
White said. ``Because the selection is driven by the RPI, we will
have to change our course.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to travel more and import more teams with better
records. That means it will cost more money, but we can't continue
to beat up on one another in the West.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU and Arizona are the only Division I baseball programs in the
state. In Louisiana, where White was the athletic director of
Tulane, 18 schools have Division I teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats, in the NCAA tournament for the first time since
1993, and the Sun Devils attempt to schedule tough non-conference
teams in the West such as Cal State-Fullerton, Pepperdine, Long
Beach State, Loyola Marymount and Fresno State.
</P>
<P>
   But many of those programs schedule in-state series with USC,
Stanford, UCLA and California, and they do not stretch themselves
against the Arizona schools. Arizona and ASU are left to schedule
regional foes such as Brigham Young, Utah and New Mexico, teams
with unfavorable RPIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the Los Angeles basin, and there are a number of
good teams right there,'' Arizona Coach Jerry Stitt said. ``But
it's less expensive for those teams to drive 25 to 30 miles to
play, so they stay close to home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The closest Division I team other than ASU for us is five
hours away. We can't load up on teams close to home, like teams can
in the South and the East.'' &QL; 
Recruits go pro &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although the Sun Devils want the RPI to R.I.P., they are aware
of the other elements that have diminished their dominance since
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything, the face of college baseball has
changed,'' Murphy said. ``The NCAA has tried to create parity with
the RPI and the reduction in scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pro baseball is doing more research, a better selling job in
the homes. They offer individualized programs, like sports
psychology and speed enhancement, that we don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   Murphy has been victimized more than many coaches by recruits
signing pro contracts, according to ``Baseball America'' college
baseball editor John Manuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and (Florida coach) Andy Lopez recruit that kind of
top-level player more than anyone because they are young and
ambitious,'' Manuel said. ``Sometimes, it pays off like last year,
with Ryan Mills (who spurned an offer by the Yankees out of high
school). Sometimes, it doesn't pay off, and the draft kills a
class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murphy and Lopez roll the dice with those kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils, beset by pitching problems this season, lost
four prospects last year, including right-hander Mike Nannini, a
``sandwich pick'' between the first and second rounds by Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Nannini and Joe Orloski, a pitcher selected in the sixth round
by Toronto, led Murphy to believe they would choose college over
pro ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least 30 percent of the kids we recruit, we lose to the
draft,'' Murphy said. ``If I get criticized for shooting too high,
what can I say? That's my personality. I like to go after the
best.'' &QL; 
Consistent program &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Murphy defends his five-year record of 188-108 at ASU by saying
the program is among the most consistent of the top three sports _
men's basketball, football and baseball _ in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils have been ranked in the top 25 each year. The
only other such program is the Arizona men's basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1996 survey, before ASU advanced to a regional final in
1997 and the College World Series final last year, ``Baseball
America'' ranked the Sun Devils as the third-best program in the
country behind LSU and Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine combined a formula of winning percentage,
tradition, player talent through the years and fan support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still not satisfied,'' Murphy said. ``I don't think we
have done an exceptional job. We've done an OK job. There is tons
of room for improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   White supports Murphy, who was chosen ``Baseball Americ''a's
national Coach of the Year in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything, I'm deeply disappointed for the players
that we did not get into the tournament this year,'' White said.
``Personally, I think it's a strong sense of violation for the
student-athletes.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
