<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4408 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-TRAILBLAZERS-JAZZ     05-28 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-TRAILBLAZERS-JAZZ-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERMANIA IN, JAZZ OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. _ Isaiah Rider flapped both arms as though he
could literally fly the Portland Trail Blazers to the next round.
</P>
<P>
   The sweat-drenched dreadlocks on Brian Grant's head whipped
around with his every motion. A number of other teammates were
grabbing their chests just to signal they have heart.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Portland's 92-80 Game 6 victory against Utah
Thursday night at the Rose Garden was clear, Blazermania ran wild.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the commotion is headed to San Antonio for the Western
Conference finals. The Blazers are this far in the postseason for
the first time since 1992, when they advanced to the NBA Finals
against the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Blazers celebrated their 4-2 conference semifinals
win by taking off their jerseys and flinging them into the seats.
</P>
<P>
   After throwing aside the two-time defending Western Conference
champion Jazz, the Blazers just did what came natural in a stirring
mood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great accomplishment for us,'' Portland reserve guard
Greg Anthony said. ``We're going to celebrate and then we're going
to show we still have a lot of basketball left.''
</P>
<P>
   Those Blazer uniforms go on again in a hurry. Portland and the
well-rested San Antonio Spurs square off in Game 1 Saturday at the
Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   However, Portland will savor a fulfilling series for the moment.
</P>
<P>
   As they have been throughout this best-of-seven matchup, the
Blazers stayed together, relentless and poised until the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we shocked the world,'' said Rider, who led the
Blazers with 24 points, including eight straight free throws in the
final 33 seconds of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of emotions in this series,'' said Grant, who
finished with 7 points and 12 rebounds. ``It's a real satisfaction
to beat a team with so many seasoned veterans. They've been through
this a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah was eliminated from the playoffs without reaching the
conference finals for the first time since losing Game 7 at Seattle
in 1996. The Jazz battled the Bulls the past two seasons. Many
considered this season to be Utah's best chance with a Michael
Jordan-less NBA.
</P>
<P>
   But that was taken away by a deep Portland team, which rode
Utah's Karl Malone into one of his worst playoff performances.
Malone played a big role in Utah's 6-1 record in its past seven
elimination games.
</P>
<P>
   He never got going against Portland and finished with a career
playoff-low 8 points on 3-of-16 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was certainly a great feat,'' Portland coach Mike
Dunleavy said. ``Brian was phenomenal. He was just determined to
hold his position. He wanted it so badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant played Malone tough. The Blazers also used center Arvydas
Sabonis to throw quick double teams at Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grant sacrificed his offense to play great defense,'' Malone
said. ``Give him credit. I just didn't get it done. It's something
I'll be man enough to say. My teammates did a good job and I
didn't. This ranks up there as one of the toughest losses in my
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Hornacek's 21 points and John Stockton's 14 points and 10
assists kept the Jazz kicking.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers clung to an 80-78 lead after Hornacek split two free
throws with 1:05 left. Then, Jackson made four straight free
throws, and Rider added two more clutch foul shots that put
Portland ahead 86-78 with 33 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   From there, the outcome was a formality. Utah fouled until the
final buzzer, and Portland made 12 straight free throws to close
out the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blazers had our number from the first game of the series,
and they kept it up,'' Utah coach Jerry Sloan said. ``Portland is a
good basketball team _ young and lively. They deserve to be where
they are. The thing that counts is defense and Portland broke us
down tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers held the Jazz to 38-percent shooting. Portland was
also big on the boards and finished with a 42-29 rebounding
advantage. Just as they did in each game except Game 5, the Blazers
attacked the ball and did not allow the Jazz to run its offense.
</P>
<P>
   Portland was not perfect, just better.
</P>
<P>
   The Blazers' offense took a seven-minute hiatus that allowed
Utah to take an eight-point lead behind a 17-1 run in the second.
Still, Portland seemed to have an answer for everything the Jazz
executed. Perhaps most impressive was the Blazers' cohesion. They
showed a team that employs a 10-man rotation regularly can go far.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at some of the great teams in the past _ Boston,
New York, Chicago and Detroit _ they had a group of guys who all
could go somewhere and play more,'' Jackson said. ``But we go out
there and play together and play for each other. This is an
enthusiastic group.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what advice he would give the young Blazers, Malone said:
``I don't think I have to give them any advice (for the next
round). They're going to be just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   However, one has to wonder if Portland officially closed Utah's
window of opportunity for winning a championship?
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I think this is the end of the Jazz era? We've been
answering that question for six years,'' Sloan said. ``We may be a
step slower, but we'll have to wait and see what happens. We still
have a pretty good team in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   All the questions about the Blazers seem to have been answered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 0212EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
