<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASSTEVENS-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORSES BEAT INDY CARS BY A NOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Howdy Holmes once tried to convince me he had an advantage over
other drivers in the Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're 5-foot-5,'' Holmes said, smiling, ``the impulse
goes from the brain to the foot quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Howdy seemed to suggest that if his mind said, ``Mash the
throttle'' or ``HIT THE BRAKE!!'' he could react to the command in
less time than a driver who was several inches taller.
</P>
<P>
   The shorter the person behind the wheel, the better his chances
of avoiding danger and winning the big race.
</P>
<P>
   If this is true, Eddie Gaedel wasted his time playing baseball.
In 1951, Gaedel, who stood 3 feet 7, made one pinch-hit appearance
for the St. Louis Browns. He walked on four pitches.
</P>
<P>
   If Eddie had gone into auto racing and applied himself, the
little guy might have won five or six 500s.
</P>
<P>
   Same for jockeys like Eddie Arcaro.
</P>
<P>
   This leads us to today's discussion: Car racing vs. horse
racing. Which is better?
</P>
<P>
   Given a choice, would you attend Sunday's Indy 500 or next
week's Belmont Stakes?
</P>
<P>
   Horse racing has betting windows.
</P>
<P>
   Car racing doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   The Indy 500 drones on for hours. The Belmont, the longest of
the Triple Crown races, is over in 2{ minutes.
</P>
<P>
   One lap is sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   Horses know when to stop.
</P>
<P>
   If a horse starts leaking, no one waves a caution flag to slow
the field to a trot.
</P>
<P>
   Horses don't need to refuel.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing goes faster than the money you put on a race horse. If
Paul Revere had ridden my Derby pick, we still would be under
British rule. But unlike at Indy, you don't have to ask of the colt
you bet on, ``What is he now? Two laps down? Three? Who's leading?
I'm confused.''
</P>
<P>
   At the first raindrop, the Indy 500 is delayed. Horses will run
on tracks that look like chocolate mousse.
</P>
<P>
   Belmont Park doesn't require a signature on a media release
form. The one at Indy reads, in part, ``I understand that my
presence on the premises . . . can expose me to dangers both from
known risk and unanticipated risk.''
</P>
<P>
   You can sit in the stands at a horse race and not worry about
being struck by a flying shoe.
</P>
<P>
   Horses rarely explode.
</P>
<P>
   Indy racing is exciting, entertaining, unpredictable. But horse
racing may be even more so. No one is more surprised by
Charismatic's magical year than the owners of the claiming horse,
Bob and Beverly Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Horse racing doesn't have the acrid smell of fuel and burning
rubber.
</P>
<P>
   Horse racing doesn't have green flags. Yellow flags. Black
Flags. White flags. Checkered flags.
</P>
<P>
   Race cars run out of gas. So do horses, but usually you don't
have to push them off the track.
</P>
<P>
   Horses aren't machines, the product of technology. They don't
get faster every year. Secretariat won the Kentucky Derby in under
two minutes. The 1973 record still stands.
</P>
<P>
   A race car has a engine.
</P>
<P>
   A horse has a heart.
</P>
<P>
   A horse also has a personality and a brain, albeit a small one.
I once asked a trainer at the Derby about his horse's intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, he's a real smart horse,'' came the reply.
</P>
<P>
   Is he as smart as, say, a canary? A dog?
</P>
<P>
   The trainer said he never owned a canary so he couldn't speak
about birds, but he did have a dog. He reluctantly admitted his pet
was smarter than his horse.
</P>
<P>
   He based the opinion on the fact that his dog could fetch and
roll over.
</P>
<P>
   Horses are quieter than race cars.
</P>
<P>
   But best of all, horses aren't plastered with decals advertising
liniment, shampoo, hoof polish, oats, alfalfa pellets and other
additives.
</P>
<P>
   When Charismatic won the Derby, jockey Chris Antley didn't need
to say, ``The Absorbine Veterinary Supershield Fly &AMP; Tick Repellant
horse did everything I asked of him. He ran flat out all day.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at david.casstevens(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 0215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
