<HEADLINE>
MAGIC TO TALK TO SUNS' SKILES  
 BUT PAPER SAYS RIVERS IS PICK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Orlando Magic General Manager John Gabriel has official
permission from the Suns to talk with assistant coach Scott Skiles
about the vacant Orlando head coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   It might not be anything more, however, than a courtesy gesture
on the Magic's part if published reports out of Orlando are
accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Orlando Sentinel'' reported Wednesday that the Magic is
close to hiring Turner Sports analyst Glenn ``Doc'' Rivers after
his broadcasting commitment ends. Rivers did his last scheduled
broadcast Thursday night on the Portland-Utah playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation Wednesday with Gabriel, Phoenix General
Manager Bryan Colangelo gave the Magic permission to speak with
Skiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked if they were going to officially ask to talk with him,
and we agreed that he officially has permission to talk with
Scott,'' Colangelo said. ``But I don't know what they're going to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Skiles could not be reached for comment. However, he apparently
is a popular choice in Orlando. ``The Sentinel'' ran a readers'
survey asking fans which coaching candidate they preferred to
replace Chuck Daly, who resigned Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Included on the list were Skiles, former San Antonio Spurs Coach
Bob Hill, Rivers and former Chicago Bulls Coach Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Skiles got 38 percent of the vote. Jackson was second, Hill
third and Rivers last, with 2.6 percent of the votes.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday afternoon, agent Keith Glass, who represents
Skiles, had not been contacted by the Magic, and he said Skiles had
not heard from the club either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've got a deal done,'' Glass said.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers also was considered a candidate for the vacant Washington
Wizards job _ another club Skiles formerly played for _ and former
Phoenix forward Garfield Heard now is considered the front-runner. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
