<HEADLINE>
LEMKE, COLLINS LEAD UA'S VICTORY  
 WASHINGTON UP NEXT FOR NO. 3 CATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Becky Lemke and Lindsey Collins are not to be
confused with Nancy Evans and Leah Braatz, but they proved Thursday
night they can lead Arizona softball at the highest level.
</P>
<P>
   Lemke (29-7), a sophomore pitcher from Scottsdale, gave up four
singles and Collins banged a pair of solo home runs as third-ranked
UA blanked California, 3-0, before 2,401 at the Women's College
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats (53-14) will try to remain in the winner's bracket
and on track for a ninth straight title-game appearance at 6:30
tonight against No. 6 Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious it was a great performance by Becky Lemke,'' UA
Coach Mike Candrea said. ``She started getting stronger at the end
(striking out the side in the seventh inning). Then Lindsey Collins
showed the power I've been waiting to see for a couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   Lemke, one of three All-America third-teamers from UA, worked
just two innings at the 1998 CWS as Evans, the national Player of
the Year, carried almost all of the load. But even that brief
appearance with a team that was the national runner-up took away
the nerves Lemke said she felt here a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I was going to have this game, and I was excited to
step up,'' Lemke said. ``I felt more relaxed, and I knew what I had
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That showed against a team that UA and Lemke split with during
the Pac-10 season.
</P>
<P>
   She coaxed ground balls to short from Holly Yost and Kirsten
Drake in the fourth after Cal put runners on second and third with
one out, and fanned Paige Bowie and Maiko Bristow to strand a pair
in the fifth. Megumi Takasaki flied deep to left with a runner
aboard in the sixth, then Lemke used her changeup to completely
fool the bottom of the order in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Collins increased her team-leading homer total to nine with pops
off Jocelyn Forest (23-7) in the fourth and sixth after striking
out in the second. The sophomore catcher has hit four homers in the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Braatz and another former Wildcat, Laura Espinoza, are tied for
the NCAA career homer lead with 85. Collins, with 14 in two
seasons, has a long way to go but said, ``I've learned if I swing
the bat, the ball might go somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Bauer, also an All-American, doubled with two outs in the
third then scored on an infield single by Toni Mascarenas after
running through a stop sign from Candrea. The throw to first by
shortstop Katie May didn't get Mascarenas, and the relay home was
too late to catch Bauer.
</P>
<P>
   Cal (49-21) drops into an elimination game against Arizona State
at 12:30 p.m. Saturday. Total attendance for both sessions on
opening day was 6,309. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
