<HEADLINE>
SELECT THEATERS SNAG EXCLUSIVE DEAL TO SHOW `SHAGGED'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' already
has scored at the box office, two weeks before the comedy sequel
opens.
</P>
<P>
   In an industry first, tickets for dozens of advance screenings
in 14 cities have gone on sale exclusively through the Internet in
a partnership among New Line Cinema, America Online and MovieFone.
AOL proclaims, in Austin Powers lingo, that the site is ``powered
by GroovyFone, Baby!''
</P>
<P>
   Three Los Angeles area theaters, including an AMC multiplex in
Burbank, have scheduled 9:30 p.m. showings for June 10, the day
before the film officially opens. Should the shows not sell out,
regular tickets will be available through the box offices a few
days before the screenings.
</P>
<P>
   As promotional pushes go, this one is quite a bit smaller than
the ticket scramble for ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom
Menace.'' But it's a big promotion for AOL, which completed a $525
million buyout of MovieFone two weeks ago. More exclusive deals
like the ``Austin Powers'' tickets will help AOL differentiate
itself from the vast array of Internet service providers and
portals, according to analyst Joseph Butt Jr. of Forrester
Research.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very nice way to keep the AOL membership happy,'' he
said. ``You'll see them beginning to offer whole series of
membership benefits. The deal also makes sense for MovieFone
because they'd gone about as far as they could go as a stand-alone
company.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL and New Line, which is owned by Time Warner, had announced
in early May a 16-month, multimillion-dollar marketing deal that
they characterized as the largest online-only media buy by a
studio. Under the deal, New Line will have a major presence on the
AOL Movies main screen and promote its films through several AOL
locations.
</P>
<P>
   Butt also said such promotions might help dispel some of the
negative reaction to MovieFone's problems in dealing with the
opening-day crush of advance ticket orders over the phone and Web
for ``The Phantom Menace'' on May 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that it's a turnoff when people can't get
through,'' he said. ``We think there is such a thing as bad PR.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL products have been placed in both the 1997 original ``Austin
Powers'' and the sequel, which is expected to be one of this
summer's biggest hits.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
