<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PRESCOTT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATES OPEN SATURDAY AT PRESCOTT DOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Horse players in search of a reprieve from summer's dog days are
in luck.
</P>
<P>
   The Prescott Downs summer race meet begins a 56-day run Saturday
and continues through Sept. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a week beginning June 30, when the Prescott rodeo
assumes control of the Yavapai County Fairgrounds, live racing will
be held Saturday through Tuesday each week. Simulcast racing is
scheduled Wednesdays through Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   Post time is 1:45 p.m. on the weekends and 12:30 p.m. on Mondays
and Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in its history, Prescott's signal will be
beamed to a bevy of racetracks scattered throughout several states,
said Tom Harris, director of racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to New York, Illinois, Florida, Texas, Louisiana,
New Jersey, New Mexico and some others that are on the burner right
now,'' said Harris, hired last October following a 17-year stint as
an announcer at several racetracks, including Garden State (N.J.)
Park and, most recently, Retama Park in San Antonio. ``As far as I
know, Prescott's signal has only gone to Montana and Wyoming in
past years.''
</P>
<P>
   A larger out-of-state betting network will lead to increasing
wagering activity and larger purses for horsemen, Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took quite a sales job to get these states to come on, but
what we've got going for us is we can dodge most of the competition
by running on Mondays and Tuesdays,'' Harris said. ``Those are dark
days for a lot of tracks. Everybody who has done it has come out a
winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Prescott's post times also should spur more interest from East
Coast gamblers, who will have somewhere to turn once races there
conclude for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Although Prescott's percentage take from wagers made outside the
state are minimal (about 3 percent of the total handle), any little
bit helps.
</P>
<P>
   Jockey Scott Stevens, who recently won a fourth straight riding
crown at Turf Paradise, also has decided to ride at Prescott for
the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, I take a lot of the summer off, but I feel good
enough to keep riding this year,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   Prescott Downs is expected to move to a new location in Prescott
Valley within about three years, Harris said. Although a new site
has been talked about for more than two decades, this time it
apparently will become a reality as the Yavapai County Fair
Association Board of Supervisors recently voted to relocate about
15 miles from the present location.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to build 800 to 1,000 stalls, up from 650 at the
present site, and a 1-mile racing surface to replace Prescott's
antiquated half-mile bullring.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mile track will greatly enhance efforts to attract more
horses,'' Harris said. ``There's also plans for a ~-mile turf
course. Eventually, we'd like to have 1,500 stalls.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 0221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
