<HEADLINE>
ALL'S QUIET ON THE INDY FRONT  
 CARBURETION DAY PASSES WITHOUT INCIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Nothing unholy occurred Thursday inside the
cathedral known as Indianapolis Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Amen.
</P>
<P>
   Carburetion Day, which traditionally is the final two-hour
practice session held before Sunday's Indianapolis 500, came and
went without so much as a peep of discontent.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two drivers made it onto the 2.5-mile oval, completing
713 total laps, and all returned to pit road with their sleek
machinery intact.
</P>
<P>
   Good.
</P>
<P>
   Although the practice session was the first time drivers drove
cars affixed with the newly mandated suspension and wheel energy
restraint system, which was designed to reduce flying debris from
crashes, no one, understandably, wanted to test the new safety
device.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no intention of being that person,'' said Billy Boat,
who crashed three times before successfully qualifying for an
outside front-row starting position.
</P>
<P>
   To their credit, IRL officials almost immediately began burning
the midnight oil in search of a safety remedy after the tragedy a
month ago at Lowe's Motor Speedway, where three spectators were
killed and eight others injured after a tire/wheel/suspension
assembly was knocked into the grandstand following a wreck during
the race.
</P>
<P>
   The system is specifically designed to keep suspension parts and
tires from separating from cars during accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Championship Auto Racing Teams also has a similar safety device,
as does Formula One.
</P>
<P>
   Even NASCAR is considering a system to prevent tires and hoods
from getting airborne.
</P>
<P>
   IRL Executive Director Leo Mehl also announced a new engine rule
that goes into effect at the June 12 Longhorn 500 at Texas Motor
Speedway. The rule stipulates engines must operate at 10,000 RPMs
or lower, down from 10,300 and 10,500 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incident at Charlotte makes us realize we have to contain
the speeds,'' Mehl said.
</P>
<P>
   Engine manufacturer spokesmen said the rule should translate
into a reduction of 20 to 30 horsepower _ a reduction that will
continue next season when engine sizes drop from 4-liter to
3.5-liter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the engine rule) is a very good idea,'' said
defending Indy 500 champion Eddie Cheever, a Phoenix native. ``I
think you can compare lowering (the RPMs) to what they do with
restrictor plates in NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, going five miles an hour slower won't make it a
worst product.''
</P>
<P>
   The wheel restraint system, however, might be the IRL's greatest
contribution to improving safety.
</P>
<P>
   Although Boat initially balked at the thought of wheel tethers,
he believes the restraint system is much more favorable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the optimum compromise,'' Boat said. ``We had to
do something because of the way the wheels, especially the rear
wheels, were coming off cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing has never been 100 percent safe, but I think we were
seeing a little bit of a pattern happening and something had to be
done. It's the league's job to ensure the safety of the drivers,
but also ensure the safety of the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   The CART circuit suffered a similar tragedy last July, when
three spectators were killed and several others were injured by
debris after a crash at Michigan Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   As a deterrent, catch fencing was raised at several racetracks.
</P>
<P>
   But when it happened again nine months later, it became apparent
to CART and IRL officials that additional precautionary measures
were needed.
</P>
<P>
   CART's drivers will race for the first time its version of the
tethers in Saturday's Motorola 300 at Gateway (Ill.) International
Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a large accident, you'll probably still see some debris,''
said Greg Ray, who is sandwiched between pole sitter Arie Luyendyk
and Boat on the front row. ``But if the wheel comes off, instead of
it coming off at 200 miles an hour, it should only be 50 miles an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brightest minds in the world are working on this, and to
me, this is a step in the right direction.'' &QL; 
Notes &QL; 
Indianapolis Mayor Stephen Goldsmith proclaimed Thursday as Arie
Luyendyk Day. Luyendyk is making the Indy 500 the final Indy car
race of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Schmidt was fastest during Carb Day practice, reaching
222.458 mph. Ray was next at 221.822.
</P>
<P>
   Galles Racing and driver Davey Hamilton defeated A.J. Foyt
Racing and driver Kenny Brack and won the Coors Indy Pit Stop
Challenge. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
