<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-CART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE RUMORS, IRL-CART PEACE NOT AT HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Forget whatever you may have read or heard about
a possible reconciliation between the warring Championship Auto
Racing Teams and the Indy Racing League.
</P>
<P>
   There's still a war.
</P>
<P>
   Although Indianapolis Motor Speedway President Tony George
confirmed that he met with CART President and Chief Executive
Officer Andrew Craig, NASCAR President Bill France and CART car
owner Roger Penske last week in Indianapolis, he said the meeting
had proved fruitless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing came out of that meeting that made me believe we were
close (to reconciling),'' George said Thursday during an impromptu
news conference. ``I don't think anything substantial was
addressed. There's still a very big gap where we are
philosophically.''
</P>
<P>
   George was responding to recent reports suggesting the two sides
were engaged in talks that could lead to a reconciliation as early
as 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're (CART) trying to shift some of the attention to
themselves,'' George said. ``They continue to need to give some
glimmer of hope that something is in the offing.''
</P>
<P>
   But as long as the two circuits disagree on such obstacles as
engine rules and chassis specifications, there appears to be no
hope of merging the two series into one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no indication I've picked up on that suggests we're
closer in philosophy,'' said George, who created the IRL four years
ago as a result of being disillusioned with CART's rising costs,
few oval races and alleged lack of opportunity for young American
drivers. ``Talking may lead to something, but nothing leads me to
believe we're close to anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm not going to compromise our philosophies to get them
back here.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest philosophical differences are engine rules.
CART machines are turbo-charged, and IRL motors are normally
aspirated.
</P>
<P>
   A larger obstacle, however, is that George insists on allowing
teams to buy motors. CART employs an engine-lease program.
</P>
<P>
   And the engine-buy package is non-negotiable, IRL executive
director Leo Mehl said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no room for compromise,'' IRL Executive Director Leo
Mehl said. ``We will never change to leasing.''
</P>
<P>
   Although George and Craig share similar sentiments, which is
that open-wheel racing would be better off with one series, it
appears to be the only thing in which they are in agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The recent acquisition of Penske Motorsports by International
Speedway Corp. led some to believe ISC President Bill France Jr.,
who also heads NASCAR, would be a strong influence in brokering an
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   France couldn't be reached for comment, but George warned not to
read anything into France's involvement. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 0224EDT &QL; 
