<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 03:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4472 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-I-SPY-GONE-AWRY-ECONO     05-28 1177
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-I-SPY-GONE-AWRY-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PUNISHED CHINA COULD PROVE EVEN MORE DANGEROUS TO AMERICA  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 900-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 29 May 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taken at face value, the findings are shocking. Over 20 years,
according to the report of an investigating committee chaired by
Congressman Christopher Cox of California, Chinese spies stole
information on every warhead currently deployed in America's
ballistic-missile arsenal, including the W-88, the most
sophisticated yet devised.
</P>
<P>
   They stole missile-guidance technology, and probably got hold of
design information for an enhanced neutron bomb. Their appetite for
the stuff was ``insatiable,'' their energy ``enormous,'' and they
have not stopped yet.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the report concludes, China has been able to leap
in a few years from 1950s-era weapons to the most modern
thermonuclear technology; and America is left with its security in
a shambles.
</P>
<P>
   So much for the headlines. Behind them, the Cox report is not
quite that chilling for Americans.
</P>
<P>
   First, it is unclear just how much weapons expertise China has
really acquired, or from where. Since China steals from many
different countries, and even does a little original work of its
own, not all its progress can be credited to America.
</P>
<P>
   The most sensitive material is in the third of the Cox report
that is still classified, but in any case no weapon derived from
the stolen American information has been deployed _ yet.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of comparative nuclear strength, China remains way
behind America, with a few dozen warheads to America's thousands.
</P>
<P>
   The most dangerous effect of the stealing is the strength it
gives China within Asia, not only compared with Taiwan but also
compared with Japan and other nuclear powers, such as India.
</P>
<P>
   It is also suspected that some of these secrets were passed on
to others.
</P>
<P>
   The fact of Chinese spying _ though it is hotly denied by China,
of course _ comes as no surprise. Nor, alas, does America's chaotic
openness. Chinese agents have poured for years into this sprawling
treasure chest, and not much has got in their way.
</P>
<P>
   China's borers and grubbers did not merely download material
from slipshod government laboratories; they also worked through
joint ventures, front companies, official exchanges, downloading of
secrets from drunken American visitors, even a careful reading of
American technical journals.
</P>
<P>
   American spies tried to do the same in China, but with far fewer
agents and probably much less to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   Once the security lapses were made public, calls came for the
resignation of the officials in charge, especially Sandy Berger at
the National Security Council and Janet Reno at the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Both had received reports of spying at the laboratories some
years ago, but took no action and apparently did not tell the
president. They appear not to have thought it serious enough, and
there was probably the usual lack of communication between
departments.
</P>
<P>
   The remedy for that is simple: more vigilance and more
information-sharing.
</P>
<P>
   A top-level sacking or resignation, given the laxity displayed
by Berger and Reno, might usefully underscore this point. The
consequences should not, and almost certainly will not, stop there.
</P>
<P>
   The policy of engagement with China, even a constantly pilfering
China, is as right now as it has been since 1972 when that policy
began. Yet the Clinton administration's approach to China has been
both more expansive than that, and more erratic _ even by this
administration's standards.
</P>
<P>
   Although, as the Cox report says, China has been enjoying pretty
unrestricted access to America for 20 years and in Republican and
Democratic administrations alike, it was under Clinton that the
program of official military exchanges was revived, and that
supervision of export sales of satellite technology was removed
from the State Department to the far laxer Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   Sales contracts to China were sought with official support, and
celebrated. And it was also under Clinton _ ably assisted by
Vice-President Al Gore _ that Chinese officials pumped money into
the Democratic Party machine in the 1996 election in the confident
hope of a quid pro quo.
</P>
<P>
   Confusingly _ not least to the Chinese _ the administration also
has moments of toughness on China. These occur whenever Clinton
feels that softness is going down badly.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is split several ways on China, between
business-friendly ``engagers'' and those, on both the right and the
left, who want China rapped for its human-rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, with his typical desire to play all sides of the court,
accommodates the so-called ``moralists'' when he can.
</P>
<P>
   That is why from time to time he encourages Taiwanese who want
to be a fully independent country, despite his general endorsement
of a ``one China'' policy; and why, after Zhu Rongji's hopeful and
warmly welcomed visit in April, Clinton suddenly turned cool on
China's bid to join the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The Cox report, which has given Republicans an ideal election
rod with which to beat the president, will no doubt inspire more
grit for a while. That would be no bad thing, if it lasted.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking lesson of the Cox report is that Clinton needs
to get his China policy straight. He is dealing not with a friend,
but with a rival whose interests are different from those of the
United States and the rest of the democratic West.
</P>
<P>
   To engage with this rival _ to trade, talk, consult _ is
essential. To drop one's guard, even for a moment, could prove
fatally wrong. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
