<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Drivers on freeways in California's Silicon Valley
were startled to see, last summer, giant billboards exhorting them
to ``upgrade to Minnesota.''
</P>
<P>
   The message, sponsored by the Minnesota High Tech Council,
sounded desperate, and it was. This year, the council is trying a
subtly different tack: billboards in Minnesota imploring high-tech
workers not to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the point is clear: the state's labor shortage is
acute.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment in Minnesota plunged to a seasonally adjusted 2.1
percent in April, the lowest ever recorded in the state and the
lowest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Twin Cities of St. Paul and Minneapolis have become a
workers' paradise: unemployment there hit an all-time low of 1.6
percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   But the state's labor pool is growing at only half the rate it
did in the 1970s. The result is a labor market that is tighter than
at any time since the Second World War.
</P>
<P>
   As national economic growth sputtered and died in the early
1990s, Minnesota clawed onward. Manufacturing defied national
trends and grew, while service companies sprang up all over the
place.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment in the state therefore lingered a point or so
behind the rest of the country, and, when the time came for the
American economy to reawaken, Minnesota found itself without the
excess capacity the rest of the nation had.
</P>
<P>
   Today, indicators of an ever-tightening labor market are legion.
Companies are offering stock options to every employee, from CEOs
to shipping clerks.
</P>
<P>
   Over loudspeakers in department stores, reminders of special
offers are being replaced by announcements of job openings.
Entry-level wages, as seen on notices papered on storefronts, are
ticking ever upward.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of qualified entry-level workers, some companies
have started using prison labor.
</P>
<P>
   In this workers' market, anyone with a measurable pulse and two
fingers to peck at a keyboard is employable.
</P>
<P>
   Employees have lost their reluctance to ask for better benefits
or more money.
</P>
<P>
   What they have also lost is the desire to join a union. Both
nationally and locally, union power has eroded as non-union
employers offer bonuses to newly hired workers, and thick
wage-and-benefits packages to retain them.
</P>
<P>
   The age of the average union member is approaching 50, which is
near the time when many choose to take their pension.
</P>
<P>
   The construction industry, one of the most heavily unionized, is
having particular problems. To keep building sites fully staffed,
unions are strengthening their apprenticeship programs, with some
success: programs for cement masons, pipe fitters and the like are
said to be bursting.
</P>
<P>
   Some unions are recruiting ``non-traditional'' workers (such as
women), and are calling local branches around the country to lure
those who want to travel.
</P>
<P>
   But labor is tight everywhere, and work is plentiful. The call
for new labor has reached immigrants in Honduras and Mexico, from
which a trickle of workers both legal and illegal are travelling
north to find work.
</P>
<P>
   On May 18, the Senate voted to let 30,000 more foreign computer
programmers, health professionals and other skilled workers into
the United States to relieve local labor-market shortages.
</P>
<P>
   In Minnesota they cannot come too soon.
</P>
<P>
   In a February 1998 survey of information-technology companies by
the Minnesota Department of Economic Security, 57 percent of
respondents said they were having trouble finding qualified
workers.
</P>
<P>
   More important, 42 percent said they were having trouble filling
work orders.
</P>
<P>
   If this persists _ and there is every reason to think it will,
especially as telecommunications and information technology become
the twin pillars of this economy _ a shortage of labor may soon
strangle growth.
</P>
<P>
   As for California's high-tech workers, they still seem reluctant
to heed those billboards and move east. It is not just Minnesota's
winters that deter them, but its high income tax.
</P>
<P>
   So, despite the state's genuine allurements, such as the beauty
of its lakes, the renowned placidity of its people and its
top-notch public-education system, it has yet to see a big influx
of new, highly skilled workers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 net immigration dropped sharply as unemployment
plummeted all across the country. Local economists are now
beginning to worry that the job market may be tight for as long as
the next ten years. &QL; 
