<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 03:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4488 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALLSY-BULGARIA-NATO-     05-28 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLSY-BULGARIA-NATO-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULGARIA'S BRAVE _ AND DANGEROUS _ GAMBLE  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 625-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 29 May 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOFIA _ Unlike several of its neighbors, Bulgaria has been
surprisingly unshy about backing NATO in the war for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Ivan Kostov, its center-right prime minister, has let NATO
aircraft fly through a large part of Bulgaria's airspace.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish F-16 fighters, which Greece has refused to allow over
the Aegean, can fly across Bulgaria to attack targets in Yugoslavia
from the east. This, say NATO's planners, weakens Serbia's air
defenses, prepared as they are to repel attacks from across the
Adriatic to the west.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Bulgaria may be playing a more dangerous game than other
Balkan states. It has been almost literally caught in the cross
fire. Its capital, Sofia, is less than 50 kilometers (30 miles)
from Bulgaria's border with Serbia, and within range of Serbian
antiaircraft guns.
</P>
<P>
   At least half-a-dozen NATO missiles that were meant to hit
Serbian air defenses have strayed off course into Bulgaria _ one
hitting a house in a Sofia suburb.
</P>
<P>
   The war is just as unpopular in Bulgaria as it is in Macedonia
and Greece, which both, however, refuse to let the alliance use
their airspace for combat missions. The Greeks and Macedonians are
also firmly against letting NATO troops move through their
territory to attack the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Over 90 percent of Bulgarians, say pollsters, are against the
war. Moreover, the number of those who want Bulgaria to join NATO
is down, from 60 percent before the war to barely half now.
</P>
<P>
   Bulgaria's feelings for Serbia, however, are far from friendly.
A shared attachment to the Orthodox church, which seems to bind the
Serbs and Greeks together emotionally, counts for little with the
Bulgarians, whose quarrelsome bishops have damaged the church's
image.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Bulgars and Serbs have fought on opposite sides in four
wars this century.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before fighting erupted over Kosovo, Kostov annoyed the
Serbs by handing over 150 Soviet-era tanks to Macedonia, which
Serbia's rulers still view as an upstart province rather than an
independent state.
</P>
<P>
   Both Kostov and Petar Stoyanov, Bulgaria's pro-western
president, who has a big say in defense and foreign affairs, see
the war as a chance to strengthen Bulgaria's bid to join NATO and
the European Union. They were disappointed not to get a timetable
for membership at the alliance's summit in Washington last month.
</P>
<P>
   They also worry that Albania and Macedonia will soon catch up in
the race to join the EU, though, unlike Bulgaria, neither country
has an association agreement with it that is supposed to precede
eventual membership. Both, however, expect to get one as soon as
the fighting stops.
</P>
<P>
   The war is hurting Bulgaria's economy. Most Bulgarian exports go
through Serbia or along the Danube, now blocked by debris from
bridges bombed by NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The economy, which was expected to grow by over 5 percent this
year, is now thought unlikely to expand by more than 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF and other western donors have promised $750 million to
support Bulgaria's balance of payments and keep market reforms on
course. But that will probably not prevent many more jobs being
lost in Bulgaria's decrepit factories.
</P>
<P>
   That is particularly galling for Kostov because western
businessmen, after years of viewing post-communist Bulgaria as a
disaster, were just beginning to take another look.
</P>
<P>
   The currency has been stable, Kostov has shown that he is
genuine about reform, and an array of state assets were to be sold
off this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Now it looks as if the only big sale _ to a Greek-Dutch
partnership _ will be that of the state telecoms company; the war
will probably make the price much lower than it would have been.
</P>
<P>
   For Kostov and Bulgaria, a speedy NATO victory in Kosovo is
vital. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
