<HEADER>
A4490 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANGOLA-AGONY-AHEAD-EC     05-28 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGOLA-AGONY-AHEAD-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARVATION IS NEW LETHAL WEAPON IN ANGOLAN CIVIL WAR  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 900-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 29 May 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you prefer, she can be
reached via her e-mail address:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUANDA _ Aid workers in Angola have a hard time suppressing
their bitterness at the nonstop coverage of events in Kosovo as
they struggle to contain their own, equally grim but largely
ignored, disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Angola should not become a forgotten emergency,'' says an
exhausted Francesco Strippoli, the director of the World Food
Program (WFP) in Angola. ``This is a very real tragedy of massive
proportions.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how massive should soon become clear.
</P>
<P>
   After a week-long tour of the country, a U.N. assessment team is
now back in Rome calculating how many Angolans may starve to death
in the next few months if help is not provided.
</P>
<P>
   Six months after the resumption of the civil war between the
Angolan government and Jonas Savimbi's UNITA rebels, the Angolan
people are suffering as they have not suffered before, even in 25
years of fighting.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, hunger is being used as a weapon in this
war.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, peasant farmers stayed on their land while the two
armies battled back and forth around them. Nowadays, rebel soldiers
are forcing them to leave their farms empty-handed, killing them
horribly if they try to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 1 million people, about 10 percent of the total
population, have been driven off their land since the fighting
resumed.
</P>
<P>
   They have been herded by UNITA into the government-controlled
cities, which now stand, like besieged islands, surrounded by
hostile UNITA-controlled countryside. The only way out of the towns
is by air: the roads have been turned into impassable death traps
by rebel ambushes and land mines.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels' aim, it would seem, is to starve the population into
rebelling against the government.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there is no sign of such a rebellion. And starvation is
being staved off _ for the moment. Food aid, supplied by the WFP,
is keeping 800,000 people alive. Others are still surviving on
local produce.
</P>
<P>
   The rains this year were exceptionally good; in normal
circumstances, the farmers would now be harvesting bumper crops. In
fact, since so many farmers are being held hostage in the cities,
most of their crops have been stolen by soldiers, burned, or left
to rot. What little has been harvested is being instantly sold or
consumed.
</P>
<P>
   Angola's rainy season has now ended. The leaner dry season
started in mid-May. The crops harvested in the rainy season will
last a month or two at best, and nobody has been able to get to the
fields to plant for the next crop.
</P>
<P>
   People are being forced to eat their seed-corn, so that when the
next rainy season starts there will be nothing left to plant.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few months, an alarmingly large proportion of Angola's
more than 11 million people will be almost entirely dependent on
food aid.
</P>
<P>
   Since the government is pumping all of its considerable oil
earnings into fighting the war, the job of feeding (and housing and
clothing) Angolans falls to the WFP and the aid donors. But the
relief agencies do not have nearly enough money to meet Angola's
constantly rising demands.
</P>
<P>
   In their annual appeal for Angola last autumn, before the
resumption of all-out war, all the U.N. agencies working there,
including the WFP, asked for $67 million for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the donors _ rich countries' governments that are tired
of pouring money into Angola _ have come up with only $25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the number of Angolans in need of urgent assistance
has tripled and the cost of distributing food and other aid has
doubled, since, with the roads blocked, everything has to be
transported by air.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N.'s 1999 appeal is to be raised to $110 million and the
WFP has launched a separate appeal for $8.8 million, solely for air
transport.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the unlikely event of the donors responding quickly to
these appeals, the situation will remain perilous.
</P>
<P>
   UNITA has already shown that it can close the airports of
provincial cities by shelling as and when it chooses. It is
prepared to attack cargo planes as well: at least six have been
shot down since the war restarted. If the rebels bring down just
one WFP plane, the whole food-aid operation will be grounded.
</P>
<P>
   Given all this, the question is asked why more is not being done
to bring an end to the war.
</P>
<P>
   Angola returned to fighting while still being monitored by a
$1.5 billion U.N. peacekeeping mission. The peacekeepers failed to
notice that UNITA was using the four-year lull in hostilities to
rearm and retrain its forces.
</P>
<P>
   The mission's mandate was finally ended in February by the
Security Council, which made vague promises about replacing it with
a small political mission.
</P>
<P>
   Prospects of the two sides talking to each other are poor. The
Angolan government has vowed never to negotiate with Savimbi again,
citing the fact that he has broken every peace promise he has ever
made.
</P>
<P>
   But does it have an alternative? The rebels have proved
surprisingly strong on the battlefield, defeating the government's
forces, in both conventional and guerrilla warfare.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the government's promised dry-season offensive were to
succeed in wiping out UNITA's conventional forces (itself
improbable), the rebels would still be able to use guerrilla
tactics to make the country ungovernable.
</P>
<P>
   Angolans, meanwhile, will be facing starvation. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this excellent 900-word ECONOMIST article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If you
prefer, she can also be reached via e-mail at:
Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms.
Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: Please note that this article is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 0342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 03:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4492 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANGOLA-AGONY-AHEAD-EC     05-28 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGOLA-AGONY-AHEAD-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARVATION IS NEW LETHAL WEAPON IN ANGOLAN CIVIL WAR  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 900-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 29 May 1999) ECONOMIST magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
