<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0090 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4623 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN01-COX     05-28 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: This is the column that usually moves Monday. It is being
moved early because of the Memorial Day holiday.
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Low male self esteem? Blame GI Joe
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At last, an explanation for the low-level emotional miasma that
I've dragged along all these years like swamp fog _ uncomplaining,
even saint-like if I do say so myself, in my silent martyrdom,
bearing my own angst with debonair grit.
</P>
<P>
   It's all GI Joe's fault.
</P>
<P>
   I have for this insight no less a source than one Dr. Harrison
Pope, Harvard psychiatrist, writing in the International Journal of
Eating Disorders. He says GI Joe and other superhero toys have been
bulking up over the last 30 years to the point where their
improbable proportions have become as daunting to men as Barbie's
wasp waist, ship's prow bosom and El Greco legs have been to women.
</P>
<P>
   In a proper I'm OK/you're OK world, I would be at ease with my
body type (old), condition (iffy) and silhouette (cylindrical). But
it is so hard to be comfortable in an intimidating atmosphere that
constantly throws up impossible models as the ideal and, in effect,
mocks those of us, victims of a sour genetic fate and a cultivated
sloth, who cannot measure up.
</P>
<P>
   GI Joe, it turns out, has seen his original 1960s biceps expand
from the equivalent of a reasonable 12 inches to the current
equivalent of 26 inches _ six inches more than the real-world
biceps of professional baseball-abuser Mark McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is GI Joe the only show-off in the gym. Star Wars' Luke
Skywalker, for 20 years a plausible fellow, now poses on toy
counters with robe pulled open to show a chest that would leave
Arnold Schwarzenegger whimpering in the locker room. Batman,
Superman and the rest of the action figures have been slowly
swelling, too, beyond stock superhero fitness to a kind of
mega-humanity.
</P>
<P>
   (In answer to your question, yes, there are people who actually
measure such things. No, I don't know why.)
</P>
<P>
   Martin Zelin, psychology professor at Tufts University, says,
``It seems perfectly reasonable that just as women who are anorexic
have been influenced by the images of thin models, boys could be
influenced by muscular men.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it does. I now understand that it was in service of
avoiding the dangerous anabolic-steroid shortcut that I logged all
those barbecued ribs, breaded veal chops, imported beers and
sweetbreads in cream sauce. I was desperately eating in hopes of
catching up with GI Joe.
</P>
<P>
   These are tough times for guys trying to live up to today's
glamour images.
</P>
<P>
   Lovely Dan Quayle is being touted as the new intellectual _ no,
really _ and the political phenom is Jesse Ventura, the ex-wrestler
governor of Minnesota who could pop footballs in his armpit. In his
new autobiography, ``The Body'' boasts of losing his virginity at
16 to win a bet, patronizing Nevada prostitutes (and selling his
shell-casings swagger belt to one for seconds), using steroids and
wearing no underwear.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think I'm ever going to catch up. Somehow _ and it will
be a challenge but I am determined to meet it _ I'm just going to
have to reconcile with my body and learn to live in emotional
equilibrium with my underwear.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
