<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4629 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CIVILIANS-$ADV     05-28 1766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CIVILIANS-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CIVILIAN CASUALTIES OF NATO CAMPAIGN ERODING ALLIES' 'MORAL
IMPERATIVE'
 &HT;    1100&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With CIVILIANS-SIDE-$ADV30.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 30 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Major General Curtis LeMay, commander of the U.S.
air raids that purposefully killed more than half a million
Japanese civilians during World War II, took a succinct view of his
profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what war is about,'' the hard-bitten, B-29 pilot
once said. ``You've got to kill people, and when you've killed
enough, they stop fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   As the American Century staggers toward an unsettling close --
and graphic images of dead civilians invade American living rooms
with increasing frequency -- LeMay's remarks stand chillingly
emblematic of an era that has seen the slaughter of the innocent on
an unprecedented scale.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 100 years, more than 62 million civilians have
been killed in wars around the world. That's more, historians
believe, than in the previous two millennia combined.
</P>
<P>
   Many -- such as the 330,000 civilians killed by U.S. attacks on
60 Japanese cities during World War II and the 200,000 or so killed
by the nuclear strikes on Hiroshima and Nagasaki -- were
deliberately slain, in hopes of breaking an opponent's will. All
were killed in violation of one of the most basic tenets of
civilization: respect, if not mercy, for the defenseless.
</P>
<P>
   The limited, almost surgically restrained air strikes the United
States and its NATO partners are conducting against Serb forces in
Yugoslavia could hardly be more different from the total war LeMay
was charged with waging against Japan.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, on this Memorial Day, when Americans pause to remember
those who have died in uniform, the NATO air war against Yugoslavia
is taking a mounting toll on that Balkan republic's civilian
population.
</P>
<P>
   At least 320 civilian deaths have been documented, and Belgrade
claims more than 1,200 have been killed, a charge that is
impossible to verify or refute.
</P>
<P>
   It's certain, though, that each civilian who dies takes with
them a bit of the righteous authority President Clinton claimed
when he announced the strikes on March 24, citing ``a moral
imperative'' to counter Serb repression of majority ethnic
Albanians in Serbia's southern province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For unlike any other major war of this century, perhaps in
history, the current NATO campaign is centered exclusively around
limited humanitarian objectives, a justification that is sorely
undercut whenever NATO bombs take innocent lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no ordinary conflict. It's not a fight over territory
or money or markets. It's a struggle for the future shape of
civilized society,'' Defense Secretary William Cohen said Wednesday
in commencement remarks to the graduating class at the U.S. Naval
Academy at Annapolis, Md. ``What is convulsing the United States
and our NATO allies is the face of evil, an ethnic and religious
nationalism that has at its core a hatred of everything our great
democracies treasure.''
</P>
<P>
   If civilian casualties are a tragic by-product of the NATO
strikes, they are the very purpose of the campaign of terror Serb
troops and police have waged for the past year and a half targeting
Kosovar Albanians -- civilians as well as armed fighters pressing
for independence.
</P>
<P>
   Since NATO strikes began, the repression has escalated into the
single worst rampage of bloodshed and destruction to be visited
upon Europe in 50 years, precisely what the United States and its
NATO allies had hoped to avert through air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Failing that, they are now bent on pounding the Serbs until
their leader, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, agrees to
peace on terms he has so far rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, whose military and police forces have executed more
than 5,000 ethnic Albanians, according to State Department
estimates, and forced perhaps 1.5 million others to flee their
homes, has shown little regard for the Geneva Conventions that
protect non-combatants from military force.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has systematically and intentionally turned Kosovo into a
killing field,'' Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said earlier this
month, ``and this was no accident.''
</P>
<P>
   In a campaign being waged to reverse that, NATO's democracies
aren't likely to tolerate high levels of civilian losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts every time it happens,'' said retired Army Maj. Bill
Stuebner, advisor to the rule of law program at the U.S. Institute
of Peace, a government-backed research group. ``You can only so
many times say, 'I'm sorry.'''
</P>
<P>
   Western analysts believe, moreover, that Milosevic is buoyed by
civilian casualties and errant strikes -- like the inadvertent
bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade -- which he hopes will
wear down support for the NATO air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Milosevic has ever prayed in his life he's praying for
things like that,'' said Stuebner, who has served in civil
peacekeeping operations in Bosnia. ``He wants to show dismembered
mothers and babies on television.''
</P>
<P>
   As the NATO strikes continue, so does the risk of mounting
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real enemy is time,'' said Army Col. James F. Holcomb,
professor of national security strategy at the U.S. Army War
College in Carlisle, Pa. ``Over time, you're going to see these
images coming out more and more. Milosevic knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   To minimize civilian deaths, U.S. and allied military officials
are taking a complex set of precautions -- from a painstaking
target approval process to the bombing tactics pilots employ -- on
a scale never before seen in a major conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon lawyers weigh in to ensure that each target has a valid
military value and is not protected under international conventions
on war or human rights.
</P>
<P>
   Military targeting and weapons experts use sophisticated
computer models to assess the expected blast radius of a specific
type of bomb hitting a designated target, then calculate the
likelihood that such a strike might damage surrounding facilities
or put civilians at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a calculus here that is employed, and you do that for
every target,'' said U.S. Navy Cpt. Stephen Pietropaoli, spokesman
for the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   Tactics mandate further caution. Allied pilots are instructed to
verify their targets before each attack and are under strict orders
not to release bombs if there's the shadow of a possibility of
hitting civilians. In most cases, so-called forward air controllers
in warplanes accompanying the bombers must also sign off on a
target before it's struck, often in communications with yet a third
aircraft flying reconnaissance over the target area.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of strike missions have been scrubbed when pilots
feared they might kill civilians, forcing warplanes to return to
aircraft carriers and land-based air fields with their bombs still
hanging perilously from their wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no desire to inflict any more casualties, even on the
enemy, than is necessary, and certainly not among innocent
bystanders,'' said Pietropaoli.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added, ``It will always be a business of risks, to our
side, to the enemy and, unfortunately, to those innocent civilians
caught in between.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   That's particularly true in an environment in which Serb troops
and police intentionally mix with civilians and position armor and
other military equipment near schools, churches and homes as
protection against allied attacks.
</P>
<P>
   After dropping nearly 15,000 bombs in more than two months of
attacks, roughly a dozen have caused civilian deaths, according to
NATO officials, as alliance bombs either went awry or blasted areas
or facilities where children, journalists, diplomats and even the
very ethnic Albanian refugees the NATO strikes are designed to
protect were present.
</P>
<P>
   The record has drawn harsh criticism from some quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite NATO's rhetoric, there can be no doubt that these
killings and injuries were perpetrated willfully,'' alleges a
complaint that a group of international lawyers filed with the
United Nations tribunal investigating alleged war crimes in the
former Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The complaint calls on the tribunal to indict President Clinton,
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and 65 other officials from
NATO countries for violating international humanitarian law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've charged them with willful killing,'' said Michael
Mandel, a party to the proceedings, who teaches law at York
University in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is lying to us,'' Mandel said in a telephone interview
with Cox Newspapers. ``It's not taking care. In fact, it's trying
to terrorize the civilian population into bringing down the
Milosevic regime.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon dismisses such charges, insisting that NATO has
never intentionally targeted civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton warned the country early on, however, that the campaign
would carry risks to civilians as well as to NATO pilots, and U.S.
military officials insist that the civilian casualty rate so far --
tragic though it is -- has been well below what planners had
feared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is an extraordinary record, but it's not a
perfect record,'' Bacon said. ``We never promised a perfect record.
I doubt if there's been a military force in history that has, one,
set as a goal a reduction or a minimizing of civilian casualties to
the extent that this NATO force has, and that, two, has achieved
that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 10 percent of the bombs being dropped in Serbia are
so-called gravity bombs that simply tumble from warplanes and fall
to their targets. The other 90 percent are precision-guided weapons
steered to their targets by laser beams, global positioning
satellites, infrared sensors, nose-mounted video cameras or other
means.
</P>
<P>
   That's the reverse of the proportions in the Gulf War, when only
10 percent of the bombs dropped were precision guided weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced navigational aides, combined with computerized cockpit
information systems, mean that gravity bombs can be dropped with
accuracy unheard of just a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Modern guidance systems, however, a full generation advanced
from the so-called ``smart bombs'' of the Gulf War, enable pilots
to routinely ram 2,000-pound bombs into a target bull's-eye just a
few feet square firing from five miles or more away.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 1038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4630 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-$ADV30-CO     05-28 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO COALITION ENDURES SIGNS OF STRAIN AS WAR GRINDS ON
 &HT;    1000&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-ALBANIA-$ADV30.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 30 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME, Italy _ In a working-class neighborhood near the Coliseum,
the writing is on the wall regarding NATO's air war against
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``No to the American War,'' reads the graffiti scrawled on a
public building. ``Clinton the assassin. D'Alema (the Italian prime
minister) the accomplice.''
</P>
<P>
   In Greece, the sentiment is the same. A message spray-painted
along the NATO supply route from Greek ports to the Macedonian
border reads: ``Adolf Clinton, call off your dogs and stop the
war.''
</P>
<P>
   Few thought it would last this long -- the two-month-old war
over Kosovo, or the unity of the 19-country NATO coalition.
</P>
<P>
   The governments of Italy, Germany and Greece -- NATO countries
vital to the air war or to the effort to build up ground forces in
Macedonia and Albania -- have faced intense pressure at home to
halt their support for the campaign. Their governments,
particularly in Italy and Greece, have maintained their qualified
support for the bombing despite fierce public protests from the
outset of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Their task may have been made easier by the announcement
Thursday by the United Nations War Crimes Tribunal of indictments
against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic for the ethnic
cleansing of the Kosovo province's Albanian majority.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the indictments reinforce the NATO argument that
the war is necessary and serve to authoritatively rebuke the
strident anti-war rhetoric from pacifists, Communists and Serb
sympathizers.
</P>
<P>
   On the streets of Rome, some agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO should go through with this until Milosevic is kicked
out,'' said Morelli Pasquale, 63, a barber who initially opposed
the war. ``I don't want war. I don't like this war. But sadly the
behavior of Milosevic requires it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in Germany, Italy and Greece, the leaders are on shaky
political ground. They are seeking on the one hand to remain loyal
NATO partners and on the other to maintain their ruling center-left
coalitions, which include factions vehemently opposed to the NATO
action.
</P>
<P>
   Those domestic strains have had a direct effect on NATO policy
as the alliance has searched for an end-game to force Milosevic's
capitulation.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO military planners have eyed the possibility of a
ground troop invasion of Kosovo, the option has effectively been
shelved, for the time being, because of the political realities for
key NATO states.
</P>
<P>
   German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder has called the possibility
of a NATO ground offensive ``unthinkable.'' Italy has said it could
only take place if sanctioned by a United Nations Security Council
resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Italy and Greece have pressed for a temporary suspension of the
air war in order to allow Serb forces the opportunity to withdrawal
from the province. The United States, Britain and France have
refused to consider a bombing pause.
</P>
<P>
   But last week, there was no disagreement on a NATO decision to
boost forces in the region to 50,000 troops for future peacekeeping
duty. There is no quarrel on the need for a secure means to return
the more than 1.5 million displaced Kosovo refugees to their homes.
The tough question is whether NATO soldiers would go in before or
after a negotiated end to the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Problems arise more toward the way the war is being conducted
by the NATO military rather than to its end purpose,'' said Cesare
Merlini, head of the Rome-based Institute for International
Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   How the coalition has remained intact despite the political
differences reveals much about European politics today. At stake in
NATO's war against the Serbs is the very definition of European and
trans-Atlantic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Failure could have far-reaching implications on the future
effectiveness of European unity at a crucial time as the continent
seeks to implement a single currency and other steps to political
and economic integration.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is supposed to be the model of the way the new Europe
works -- security cooperation, economic unity -- and to divide
would be to lose all credibility for this new order,'' said Patrick
McCarthy, a professor of European studies at Johns Hopkins
University in Bologna, Italy(CQ).
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, NATO's credibility, perhaps its very existence, has
become intertwined with the war against Serb-dominated Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Europeans are trying to keep their act together. But they
won't be able to do it if they set themselves up as patsies to be
had by a two-bit dictator such as Milosevic,'' said McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   Most combat sorties against Yugoslavia are flown from NATO bases
in Italy, whose left-wing and Communist parties have been vocal
opponents of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-American sentiment in Italy is high and U.S. forces here
have been targets of death threats and street assaults. Security
has been tightened at bases and military personnel have been warned
to keep a low profile and wear civilian clothes when traveling in
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is not the sheriff of the world,'' complained Moresco
Vittorio, an airline clerk who lives in the predominantly
left-wing, working-class neighborhood of Testaccio in Rome. ``We're
just being used. We must make our own decision to do what is
right.''
</P>
<P>
   His sentiment reveals what political analysts say is
double-edged discontent with the war: First, that NATO is bombing
Yugoslavia, a sovereign country and longtime Communist friend. And
second that Italy, because of its NATO obligations, is powerless to
stop it.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian perception of its role as America's pawn was further
fueled recently when Italian fishermen protested because they have
been snagging unexploded NATO bombs in their nets. NATO jets, upon
returning to their bases in Italy, routinely jettison their
undelivered bombs in the Adriatic Sea before landing. The U.S. and
NATO failed to notify Italy of the practice.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema, meanwhile, presides over a precarious left-center
coalition that includes Greens and Communists opposed to NATO's air
campaign. Further significant pressure in Italy comes from the
Vatican, where Pope John Paul II has spoken out against the war.
</P>
<P>
   Yet NATO's five original demands for a halt to the airstrikes
remain the basis of Italy's policy. These include a verifiable
cease-fire; the withdrawal of Yugoslav security forces from Kosovo;
the unconditional return of all refugees; deployment of an
international peacekeeping force in the province; and the
acceptance by Belgrade of a political process that will restore
broad autonomy to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``D'Alema is under tremendous pressure and he has played it very
well so far. He has remained very loyal to NATO while allowing
people to speak out against the bombing. It leaves the impression
within the coalition that there's nothing to worry about, it's just
the Italians being the Italians. But the pressure is very real and
I don't know how long the government can last,'' said McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   From the outset of the air campaign, Greece has demanded a
48-hour bombing pause as public opinion there remains
overwhelmingly opposed to the airstrikes. Many Greeks feel sympathy
for their fellow Christian Orthodox Serbs and fear conflict in the
Balkans could spread south and shatter Greece's current political
stability and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   During a visit this week to Washington, Greek Foreign Minister
George Papandreou said a temporary suspension could promote
diplomacy and eventual approval of a U.N. Security Council
resolution on a settlement of the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   His government also expressed disappointment with the indictment
of Milosevic, the only NATO member to do so. ``This move is
politically wrong because it will not help the peace process,''
government spokesman Dimitris Reppas told reporters in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
