<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PARTNERS (San Francisco) _ A federal judge, ruling in two cases
involving San Francisco's equal benefits ordinance, has backed the
landmark law that requires companies doing business with the city
to provide the same benefits to employees with domestic partners as
they provide to married couples. By GREGORY LEWIS and LARRY D.
HATFIELD.
</P>
<P>
   DOMESTIC (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Despite an ad campaign financed
by conservative Christians targeting Democratic lawmakers in
centrist districts, the California Assembly has passed two measures
to grant domestic partnership benefits to unmarried couples, gay
and straight. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   ASSISTED-SUICIDE (Sacramento, Calif.) _ A bill in the
legislature to legalize assisted suicide in California was put on
hold for the rest of the year after the assemblywoman who sponsored
it said she couldn't muster enough votes among her colleagues. By
ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   AREA-CODES (San Francisco) _ California state regulators,
consumer groups and the Pacific Bell telephone company applaud the
Federal Communications Commission's proposal to curb the manic
growth of new area codes in California and the rest of the nation
and stem confusion among consumers. By WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   ADAMS-OBIT (San Francisco) _ Alice Adams, whose novels and New
Yorker short stories about strong women and life in San Francisco
made her a celebrated writer, is dead. She was 72. By LARRY D.
HATFIELD.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ZELNICK (San Francisco) _ After three decades covering
political battles from Tel Aviv to Moscow to Capitol Hill, it
seemed natural for journalist Bob Zelnick to write a book about one
of America's foremost politicians: Vice President Al Gore. But the
decision cost him his job as an ABC News correspondent and has made
him a target of attacks by Gore supporters. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GRADUATES-FAMILY (San Francisco) _ If the story of Scott, Toni
and Junile Smith was made into a movie, the last scene would be
filmed Saturday during graduation ceremonies at San Francisco State
University. The Smiths are college roommates who share apartment
rent and food expenses equally, who have studied, partied and
attended classes together. They are also father, mother and
daughter and they've survived a long family feud. By MICHAEL
DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   MUSEUM-DREAM (North Adams, Mass.) _ It seemed preposterous a
pie-in-the-sky fantasy as extravagant as it was bizarre: Turn an
abandoned plant in a remote factory town into the country's largest
museum for minimalist, postmodern and conceptual art. Yeah, right.
Now, 13 years later, the naysayers are eating their words as the
Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art opens. By TIMOTHY CAHILL.
(For release Sunday, May 30.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ Windows 98 SE (Second Edition) will
not only replace the current boxes of Windows 98 now on store
shelves, but users of existing Windows 98 systems will be able to
order a $20 upgrade CD via Microsoft's Web site in the coming
weeks. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader asks, ``I have a computer
that has Netscape Communicator set up as the browser for my
Internet service provider. However, I have AOL now, but I still
want to use Netscape with it. How do I go about changing from AOL's
browser to Communicator?'' Assorted Q&AMP;As. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WORKING -COLUMN (Houston) _ A look at doctors and managed care.
By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-NOTTING (Undated) _ As lovers go, William Thacker
(Hugh Grant) and Anna Scott (Julia Roberts) are a pair to root for
in ``Notting Hill.'' You have to thank your lucky stars _ both of
them _ for a film as warm, as romantic and as ticklishly festive as
this one. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   TV-SPIN (New York) _ Every network except UPN and Pax has touted
how their numbers clearly showed they are where the advertising
dollar should go. Even those bottom-rung networks trotted out stats
supporting their causes. It's all lies, damn lies, statistics and
network statistics. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTO-EXHIBIT (San Francisco) _ Carleton Watkins (1829-1916) is
widely regarded as the finest American landscape photographer of
the 19th century. But many do not know his name. The San Francisco
Museum of Modern Art retrospective of his work, which continues
through Sept. 7, aims to finally give Watkins his due. The show
will travel to the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York and the
National Gallery of Art in Washington, D.C. By DAVID BONETTI.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-REVIEW-RING (San Francisco) _ You've seen the opera, ``Der
Ring des Nibelungen'' and now you want to derive the maximum
pleasure of hearing it on CD without taking out another loan.
Fortunately, the record industry is ready to oblige. A complete
``Ring'' spreads over 14 compact discs, and you should own one that
takes advantage of contemporary technology. By ALLAN ULRICH.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-REVIEW-SEAL (Undated) _ Seal talks about his latest album,
``Human Being,'' and his music. By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-MAMET (Undated) _ Much has been made of filmmaker
David Mamet going against his usual style with his new,
much-praised ``The Winslow Boy.'' Mamet, known for his caustic
R-rated dialogue, mature themes of deceit and enigmatic, clipped
characterizations, has produced a G-rated version of a popular play
(by the late Terence Rattigan) in which everyone behaves with great
restraint and uses oh, so proper language. By LOUIS PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-DIVORCE (San Francisco) _ ``Divorce Iranian Style,''
chafes with outrage over the sexism rampant in Iranian society. By
WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GUADALUPE-RIVER (New Braunfels, Texas) _ Visitors to the
Guadalupe River this weekend can expect clean, clear water, lots of
new facilities and dozens of police. By ROGER CROTEAU and RALPH
WININGHAM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ Even in fat times like this,
Congress and the Clinton administration are starving the Veterans
Administration. At a time when World War II veterans are deep into
old age and need medical care _ and at a time when veterans of
Korea are getting old and the Vietnam guys are showing signs of
mileage _ services are being moved around and trimmed. By DAN
LYNCH.
</P>
