<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Poor-quality tools are good for making holes in your wallet
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A query on the Internet raises perhaps the biggest question any
woodworking newbie has _ what tools to buy and how much to pay.
</P>
<P>
   A fellow asks the subscribers to the rec.woodworking news group
which three bench power tools they consider necessary and if it's
worthwhile getting them used.
</P>
<P>
   He mentions a line of tools he saw in a a discount department
store _ $100 for a 10-inch table saw and $140 for a compound miter
saw.
</P>
<P>
   Then he mentions a couple of jigsaws he noticed in a pawn shop,
name brands running between $89 and $300. ``What are the brands to
stay away from?'' he asks.
</P>
<P>
   I have been on this Earth for more than 60 years now, spending
money hand over fist for most of that time, and I have never failed
to get burned when I tried to go cheap. I have known people who had
an uncannny knack for finding bargains, but these were good buys on
good equipment _ not cheaply made stuff.
</P>
<P>
   With woodworking, as in most areas, there is a scale of prices
for a given item that starts very low, reaches a sort of
equilibrium with good quality at a certain level, and goes on up
with diminishing returns.
</P>
<P>
   A table saw is the first major tool a woodworker needs. A $100
table saw, however, is not even going to make a decent toy. A
compound miter saw is a carpenter's tool, not a woodworker's.
</P>
<P>
   There are two basic kinds of table saw, the smaller ones known
as contractor's saws and the full-size jobs. People who do not
intend to work with sheets of plywood, or get into heavy timbers,
can often get by with a contractor's saw. These run around $800.
The Jet brand has a good reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The next level is the Delta Unisaw and its clones at around
$1,500. These are massive saws suitable for almost any kind of work
short of heavy commercial production. You can go on up to $5,000
and more. What you get for all that extra money varies, but it can
include automated features for production shops, added functions,
and generally even beefier construction. They're dandy if you can
afford it, but it's a rare woodworker who couldn't do just fine
with a basic Unisaw type.
</P>
<P>
   The reason this stuff costs so much is that it must be
accurately built and heavily constructed in order to maintain that
accuracy. A table saw whose blade cannot be kept in alignment with
the miter slots is useless. So is a table saw that cannot easily
and smoothly cut through a two-inch-thick plank of oak. A $100
table saw? Lord, a good miter gauge costs more than $100.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as for the pawn shop jig saws, these are scarcely essential
tools in the woodworker's shop. I'd guess that $89 is at the bottom
end of a decent quality tool and $300 is in the area of overkill.
</P>
<P>
   The basic bench tools, in my opinion, are the table saw, the
jointer and the planer. The bench-top planers, generally in the
area of $300, do an adequate job if you aren't going into
production or planning on running extremely long planks through
them. The jointer is going to cost you as much or more than the
table saw if you get one of a good useful width _ say, 10 inches. I
always recommend looking into a two-in-one jointer/planer. What
brands to stay away from? The brands I stay away from are legion,
far too numerous to name, and then there are a great many tools,
usually Taiwanese clones, that suffer chiefly from poor quality
control. Some can be very good, some pretty bad. Luck of the draw,
don't you know.
</P>
<P>
   The best way to buy tools is to go to woodworking stores, and
get catalogs from every one you can. Generally speaking,
woodworking specialty stores are run by woodworkers and they cater
to professionals as well as amateurs. They are not going to stock
poor tools.
</P>
<P>
   You will find, I wager, that there won't be $5 difference in the
price of the same tool with the same configuration between any of
these places. They're selling them as cheaply as they can while
still making money. You will get an idea, however, which tools are
good. If you can't afford one, see if you can't find it used. But
don't waste your money on junk that will hinder rather than help
you.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jwarner(at)ajc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
