r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX     05-28 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LABBE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT DOES JANE FONDA HAVE TO SAY OF ANY IMPORTANCE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By J.R. LABBE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Confession, as the saying goes, is good for the soul. This
Memorial Day weekend is as good a time as any to confess to the
nation's veterans that I did not watch the ABC/Barbara Walters
special on the century's 100 great women, which was the topic of a
column earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   I won't watch anything that includes Jane Fonda. I knew she was
going to be part of the program after reading a preview written by
the paper's TV critic.
</P>
<P>
   Having not watched the program, I didn't know precisely the
scope of the traitor-turned-exercise-maven's participation.
Regardless, the very idea of Walters and ABC including Hanoi Jane
on a program showcasing significant women of the 20th century was
stomach-turning.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the more than 300 e-mails, 100 phone calls and scores of
letters I received about the column, only one caller said she
actually watched the show.
</P>
<P>
   She said Walters asked Fonda to comment about the contributions
of one of the chosen 100. Fonda, like talk-show hostess Rosie
O'Donnell (who was asked about her friendship with Madonna, who WAS
recognized as ``great,'' if you can believe it), was not herself a
woman of greatness.
</P>
<P>
   Although that provides an iota of relief about ABC's judgment,
it's not enough to change my original premise that Fonda doesn't
belong in anybody's spotlight, unless it's that of the House
Committee on Un-American Activities.
</P>
<P>
   According to the caller, Walters asked Fonda about the impact
that birth control, an invention pioneered by a woman, had on
society.
</P>
<P>
   Why, pray tell, ask Fonda? Why not a doctor or a sociologist or
the surgeon general or someone with some credentials beyond being a
personal friend of the interviewer? (Walters and Fonda are old
pals, dating back to the 1988 ``20/20'' interview in which Fonda
``apologized'' to America's veterans for going to Hanoi during the
Vietnam War and cavorting with the enemy.)
</P>
<P>
   Which brings up the next puzzler: Why would the American Bar
Association book Fonda to speak on Aug. 10 at its annual Silver
Gavel Awards in Atlanta? Can't they afford someone from out of
town?
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Weixl of the ABA's media relations department in Chicago
explained that the annual awards are designed to recognize members
of the media _ not just news, but movies, TV and radio _ for
excellence in providing information about the legal system to the
public. According to a statement released by the ABA, Fonda was
invited to speak because of her ``contributions to the arts and her
important work with young people.''
</P>
<P>
   Wonder if that includes the torture of young American soldiers
by their Viet Cong captors because they didn't show the proper
deference when Fonda traipsed her way through Hanoi in 1972?
</P>
<P>
   What lessons are America's young people learning from Fonda _ to
betray your country for fun and profit? That there's absolutely no
consequence for denouncing your nation during war and consorting
with the enemy?
</P>
<P>
   The ABA made it clear _ very clear _ that Fonda will not be a
recipient of any award at the $40-a-plate luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ABA doesn't take positions,'' Weixl said. ``We invite
people with all kinds of opinions _ speakers who haven't agreed
with the ABA, controversial people ...''
</P>
<P>
   If controversy is what the ABA was aiming for, then it hit the
bull's eye with Fonda. Who'll be invited next year _ Slobodan
Milosevic?
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys get knocked pretty hard in this country _ some of it
deserved, most of it not. They're easy to criticize until you need
one _ sorta like police. But here's a sure way that a bunch of them
could crank up their standing a couple of notches in the eyes of
scores of veterans: Don't shell out the 40 bucks for the optional
meal ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Go to your convention, have a wonderful time, learn the latest
tricks of the litigation trade. But take a pass on lunch with the
traitor.
</P>
<P>
   (Jill ``J.R.'' Labbe is senior editorial writer and columnist
for the Fort Wsorth Star-Telegram. She can be reached via e-mail at
jrlabbe(at)star-telegram.com or by phone at (817) 390-7599. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
