<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4807 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-     05-28 1341
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAAB ROLLS OUT FIRST WAGON IN 25 YEARS: THE LUXURY 9-5
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are station wagons coming back?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's just wishful thinking on the part of automakers who
don't have a sport-utility vehicle or minivan in their product
lineups, but the word from these companies is that consumers are
ready to embrace wagons again.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us grew up in the '60s and '70s when our parents had big
station wagons to haul the family around in. My parents had a '66
Chevy wagon for us five kids, and before that, a '56 Ford.
</P>
<P>
   But beginning in the early '80s, big wagons began to be replaced
by minivans, and by the mid-90s, minivans were being replaced by
sport-utility vehicles such as the Ford Explorer and Jeep Grand
Cherokee.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, such automakers as Audi, Saab and Saturn are adding
midsize wagons to their fleets to satisfy what they believe is a
trend back toward wagons. They are not the huge models like the
Chevy Caprice and Buick Roadmaster that General Motors discontinued
a couple of years ago _ the last really big wagons.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the new wagons are smaller, sleeker and more sedanlike
than ever. The new entries are coming on line to compete against
the handful of midsize wagons that remained on the market during
the onslaught of sport-utilities and minivans, including entries
from Volvo, Mercedes, BMW, Volkswagen, Subaru and Ford/Mercury.
Volvo, by the way, is the world leader in wagon sales.
</P>
<P>
   I recently tested both the 1999 Saab 9-5 Wagon, which went on
sale in April, and the midsize 2000 Saturn wagon, which will debut
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, both of these cars are derived from the same vehicle
platform, developed originally for the German Opel Vectra. The
Saturn will cost about half as much as the Saab wagon, but it's not
quite as luxurious. All three vehicles are GM products, since GM
owns Saturn and Opel, and has controlling interest in Sweden's
Saab.
</P>
<P>
   For Saab, introduction of the 9-5 Wagon is something of a
historical occasion. The company last produced a wagon a quarter of
a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Saab, with base prices ranging from $31,850 to $36,900
depending on engine choice, will compete against the high end of
the wagon segment, which includes the Volvo V70 all-wheel-drive,
BMW 5-series, Audi A6 Avant and Mercedes E-class. Saab says the
U.S. luxury wagon market ``has quietly grown by 40 percent'' since
1988. It's still not a very big segment, however; just 60,000
vehicles are expected to be sold in the United States this year.
</P>
<P>
   The 9-5 wagon isn't planned to be a mass-market vehicle like the
Saturn; Saab's goal is to sell 3,800 wagons in the United States
for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Saab and Saturn officials made much to do about their respective
vehicles' styling, telling automotive journalists that they went to
great lengths to refrain from designing another ``box,'' which of
course is a reference to the boxy Volvo that wagon fans worldwide
have come to know and love.
</P>
<P>
   True, neither one is boxy like a Volvo, with squared-off edges,
but both of these cars look like wagons. They are, after all,
wagons.
</P>
<P>
   The Saab is a good-looking wagon, though. But if you don't like
wagons, you probably won't like the 9-5 no matter how rounded and
aerodynamic it is.
</P>
<P>
   Does it truly ride and handle like a sedan? Absolutely. If your
main complaint about wagons isn't their boxy appearance, but
instead, their boxy handling characteristics, then you'll probably
be pleasantly surprised.
</P>
<P>
   I put a 9-5 wagon through its paces on freeways, curvy mountains
roads and even some sandy trails best left to the sport-utility
vehicles, and other than a scare or two when the front-wheel drive
got bogged-down in deep sand momentarily, the Saab was a real treat
to drive.
</P>
<P>
   The wagon has essentially the same suspension as the 9-5 sedan,
which debuted last year as the most expensive, safest and most
impressive Saab ever. Both vehicles are powered by either a
2.3-liter, turbocharged four-cylinder engine rated at 170
horsepower and 207 foot-pounds of torque, or a 3.0-liter,
turbocharged V-6 rated at 200 horsepower and 229 foot-pounds of
torque.
</P>
<P>
   The higher-priced V-6 model comes with a four-speed automatic
transmission, while the four-cylinder is paired with a five-speed
manual (the automatic is a $1,150 option on the four-cylinder
model).
</P>
<P>
   Unlike some competitors, the Saab is not available with a third
seat or all-wheel drive. Saab officials said the decision to leave
out a third seat was made on the basis of safety; it's hard to
protect occupants riding in what is essentially the cargo area of a
station wagon in a rear- end collision. As for all-wheel drive:
that's expensive to design and manufacture, and Saab officials
don't believe it would be worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   There is ample room for five adults and 37 cubic feet of cargo,
and with the back seat removed, the cargo area expands to as much
as 72.9 cubic feet. A unique feature is a loading floor that slides
out as far as 20 inches from the rear of the hatch, and there are
study cargo rails on the floor to help secure your stuff so it
doesn't go flying around during an accident. A rigid parcel shelf
is included to cover the cargo and keep it out of view.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other safety features are antilock brakes, a steel
safety cage surrounding the passenger compartment, next-generation
front and dual-stage side air bags for front seat occupants, and
Saab's active head-restraint system, which instantly moves the head
rests forward to stop whiplashing of the occupants' heads in a
rear-end collision.
</P>
<P>
   A leather interior is standard on the V-6 model, but costs
$1,350 extra on the four-cylinder model. Ventilated front seats,
which have perforations and little fans to push air out of the seat
bottoms and backs, cost $1,025 on the V-6 wagons and $1,800 on the
four-cylinders. It's a nice feature, especially for climates like
that of Texas, but I'm not sure it's worth the price.
</P>
<P>
   Standard features on both models include power everything,
anti-theft system, walnut-veneer interior trim, electric sun roof,
automatic climate control (with separate controls for driver and
front passenger), refrigerated glove box (perfect for soft drinks,
sandwiches and chocolate bars), cruise control and lots more.
</P>
<P>
   EPA fuel-economy ratings are better than most sport-utilities
and minivans: 19 miles per gallon in the city and 25 mph on the
highway for the V-6 model; 22 city/29 highway for the four-cylinder
with manual transmission; and 19 city/28 highway for four-cylinder
automatics.
</P>
<P>
   The tank holds 18.5 gallons of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   At A Glance:
</P>
<P>
   1999 Saab 9-5 Wagon
</P>
<P>
   THE PACKAGE: Midsize, five-door, five-passenger,
inline-four-cylinder or V-6 powered, front-drive luxury station
wagon, the first wagon from Sweden's Saab in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   HIGHLIGHTS: Ride and handling take no lumps in this stylish
conversion of the premium 9-5 sedan into wagon form. Unlike its
cross-country rival, Volvo, the Saab wagon is well-rounded on the
edges and aerodynamically clean; the interior is well done, with
obvious attention to detail; and there are two engine choices _
both turbocharged and good performers.
</P>
<P>
   NEGATIVES: No all-wheel-drive version offered to meet the Audi,
Volvo and Mercedes-Benz competition.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR COMPETITORS: Mercedes-Benz E320, BMW 528iT, BMW 540iT,
Audi A6 Avant, Volvo V70.
</P>
<P>
   EPA FUEL ECONOMY RANGE: 22 miles per gallon city/29 highway (I-4
manual); 19 city/25 highway (V-6 automatic).
</P>
<P>
   BASE PRICE: $31,850 (four-cylinder, manual); $36,900 (V-6,
automatic), plus $575 transportation.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD RATING: A.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (G. Chambers Williams III is the Star-Telegram's transportation
writer and automotive columnist. Contact him at 3201 Airport
Freeway, Suite 108, Bedford, TX 76022; telephone (817) 685-3810;
e-mail chambers(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
