<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-NOTTING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANK YOUR LUCKY STARS FOR `NOTTING HILL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood is, as always, fascinated with itself. From the soapy
noir of ``Sunset Boulevard'' through the witty plotting of ``The
Player'' on into the pulpy low-lives of ``L.A. Confidential,''
Tinseltown has always been its own best subject.
</P>
<P>
   So it doesn't seem the least bit awkward to describe ``Notting
Hill,'' a gracefully funny romance from the team that made ``Four
Weddings and a Funeral,'' as a movie about movie stardom starring
movie stars. As evidence of just what a Mobius strip this is, the
film's one-sheet poster consists of a man walking past the
one-sheet poster for ``Notting Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   The joke here _ and it is indeed a joke _ is that a movie about
a mega-wattage quasar actually stars a mega-wattage quasar, in this
case Julia Roberts. This lends a self-mocking, origami quality to
much of the film, as though the entire thing were folded in on
itself; when average folks bump into Anna Scott, the actress played
by Roberts, they react with the geeky enthusiasm you'd expect from
average folks bumping into you-know-who.
</P>
<P>
   And when Anna talks privately about the agonies of fame, it's
impossible not to assume that our own, dear Julia is suffering the
same fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to meet you. Surreal, but nice,'' says a
starstruck suitor, and he might have just as easily been talking
about the film.
</P>
<P>
   The suitor is William Thacker (Hugh Grant), a travel bookstore
owner in the culturally mishmashed London neighborhood of Notting
Hill. Thacker's the kind of sad-eyed chap that Grant has made his
career out of, a hesitating underachiever whose very allure is his
complete lack of self-confidence. When Anna glides into his
bookstore, he regards her with the quiet amazement that befits
encounters with remote natural wonders the Grand Canyon, an aurora
borealis, Niagara Falls.
</P>
<P>
   And when he accidentally sloshes orange juice all over her
skimpy blouse, his shock at being that up-front-and-personal with
the luminous Anna is both emotionally transparent and charming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you like something to eat? Something to nibble? Apricots
soaked in honey?'' he babbles, after lending her his flat to change
clothes. She beats a polite but hasty exit, only to return moments
later and kiss him, long and seriously.
</P>
<P>
   So caught off guard is William that he can't pull his hands out
of his back pockets to embrace her. He just stands there, stunned.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Michell directed ``Notting Hill'' from a script by Richard
Curtis, and the film has the same, sweet hex on it that the
filmmakers brought to ``Four Weddings and a Funeral.'' The main
difference is the absence of Andie MacDowell, whose icy bearing
didn't mix well with Grant's stuttering nerd. Few sparks flew
between those two.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Grant's chemistry with Roberts is wholehearted and
utterly believable, trading on Roberts' grace before the camera and
Grant's dithering (but dorkily seductive) unease. Roberts has never
been better; as Anna's romance with William starts and stalls, her
poise begins to crack, and simple human yearning streaks through.
</P>
<P>
   So much works in ``Notting Hill'': Curtis' affable, asymmetrical
dialogue (which includes a debate on the usage of
``whoopsadaisy''); Michell's pacing, which never lusts after
consummation but leads up to it naturally; and the ensemble
contributions of a bull's-eye supporting cast, including Emma
Chambers as William's pop-eyed sister, Tim McInnerny as his
empathetic best friend and Rhys Ifans as his slacking, unhygienic
flatmate.
</P>
<P>
   Grant makes a perfect Everyman and a delightful nobody, which of
course he isn't. In the matter of mega-wattage, his sun is only
slightly less brilliant than Roberts'. But ``Notting Hill'' is a
movie, and more than that, it's a fairy tale: Not since ``Roman
Holiday'' has a film so winningly paired royal and peasant, pixie
queen and common mortal. (Now it's beginning to sound like ``A
Midsummer Night's Dream.'')
</P>
<P>
   As lovers go, William and Anna are a pair to root for. You have
to thank your lucky stars _ both of them _ for a film as warm, as
romantic and as ticklishly festive as the spirited ``Notting
Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Amy Biancolli is the film critic for the Albany Times Union,
P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. Her e-mail address is
abiancolli(at)timesunion.com, or call 518-454-5738.)
</P>
</TEXT>
