<HEADLINE>
WHERE THERE'S SMOKE, THERE'S NETWORK SPIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Drew Carey nailed what was going on all over New York
City last week, as networks threw shows and parties for
advertisers, and touted their new lineups as the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it always amazing how every year the world gets saved by
a network schedule?'' Carey told the Madison Avenue types asked to
risk millions on new sitcoms and dramas. ``Every year you get so
much smoke (your way) you get cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Every network except UPN and Pax touted how their numbers
clearly showed they are where the advertising dollar should go.
Even those bottom-rung networks trotted out stats supporting their
causes.
</P>
<P>
   Lies, damn lies, statistics and network statistics. CBS ended
the season on top with total viewers, but lagged behind the other
top networks in the key demographic, namely those 18-49.
Demographics, the age/gender/income groupings that advertisers look
for when rates are set and decisions are made on when to buy, trump
total viewership.
</P>
<P>
   This leads to different networks giving different spins, the
most outlandish coming from WB head James Kellner, whose
youth-oriented network skews the youngest of all:
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be No. 1,'' he said. ``We don't care about
household ratings.''
</P>
<P>
   What a relief. As if he had to worry about it.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to tell what new shows will be artistic or commercial
successes based on a brief synopsis, a short clip, a cast roster
and a Roget's-load of adjectives the networks offered (I have some
hints, but let's give them a chance). But you can see some trends
developing:
</P>
<P>
   _ Thursday's up for grabs: Smelling blood, the other networks
are going to counter-program on Thursdays, once considered the
unassailable bastion of NBC. This is the night UPN hopes to make
some inroads by bringing the WWF back to network television (it
will also continue to run on USA Network).
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``Providence'' factor: NBC believes
whiter-than-Wonderbread dramas can work on Fridays, which is why
the new ``Cold Feet'' is being paired with ``Providence,'' the
surprise ratings winner of 1999. Meanwhile, Fox is
counter-programming with a pair of new blood-and-guts guy dramas.
</P>
<P>
   _ Spin control: Spinoffs abound next year, including at NBC
(``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit,'' from ``Law &AMP; Order''), Fox
(``Ally,'' from ``Ally McBeal,'' and ``The Time of Your Life,''
from ``Party of Five''), WB (``Angel,'' from ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer'') and UPN (``Mo'Nique,'' from ``Moesha''). ABC has also
added another edition of ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   _ In Kelley they trust: David E. Kelley is returning to
``Chicago Hope'' to help revamp the show for CBS. He also has a new
show on ABC, ``Snoops,'' which will be paired on Sundays with his
other drama for the network, the brilliant ``The Practice.''
</P>
<P>
   When Kelley told Fox entertainment head Doug Herzog he wanted to
do a half-hour version of ``Ally McBeal,'' the young exec almost
had a coronary until he realized it was an additional half-hour
show.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how many David E. Kelleys are there?
</P>
<P>
   _ Buy a program: The networks, with the exception of NBC, have
all done some major reshuffling of their lineups. Start studying
now.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark McGuire is the television and radio writer for the Albany
Times Union, P.O. Box 15000, Albany, NY 12212. His e-mail address
is mmcguire(at)timesunion.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
