<HEADLINE>
VETERANS DESERVE BETTER MEDICAL CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Chauncey Robinson was 32, working as security
guard, when he decided to be all that he could be. He joined the
Army.
</P>
<P>
   His military career turned out to be a bit disappointing. During
basic training in Missouri, he injured his eye. It took stitches.
The Army stuck him at a desk. Then a drill sergeant decided that he
wanted Robinson on KP instead.
</P>
<P>
   If you've been in the service, you might recall your drill
sergeant. In fact, I'm certain you recalls yours as vividly as I
recall mine. As a breed, drill sergeants are not noted for their
conspicuous gentility. This one found Robinson asleep and awakened
him by turning over his bunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit my head against the locker,'' Robinson told me the other
day. ``I went to the medical clinic. They checked my heart and
found out my heart was racing ...
</P>
<P>
   ``They sent me out to a major hospital. Then the chest X-rays
they gave me before my eye operation showed an enlargement of the
heart. So they sent me home. I went to the doctor, and the X-rays
and the EKG and everything showed the same.''
</P>
<P>
   The drill sergeant was admonished. Robinson was honorably
discharged on medical grounds. A doctor at the Albany Medical
Center told him that not only did he have heart problems, but he
also suffered from a panic disorder. Robinson applied for Veterans
Administration disability payments.
</P>
<P>
   That was seven years ago. Robinson is still waiting for an
answer to his application. I talked to somebody in the office of
Rep. Michael McNulty, D-N.Y., who's familiar with this case.
Robinson is legitimate, I was told. All his paperwork is there. The
VA just can't get its act together, is all.
</P>
<P>
   What's disturbing is that Robinson is in no way a unique case. A
federal audit released a few months back revealed that the VA makes
errors in as many as 36 percent of its benefit decisions _ and
that's when the applicants can get those decisions made at all. The
audit indicated that as many as 3 million veterans, their
dependents and survivors are still waiting for $19 billion in
benefits due them.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this seems due to decisions by Congress and the Clinton
administration to starve the VA. At a time when 7.5 million World
War II veterans are deep into old age and need medical care _ and
at a time when veterans of Korea are getting old and the Vietnam
guys are showing signs of mileage _ services are being moved around
and trimmed. Even in fat times.
</P>
<P>
   At the Stratton VA Medical Center in Albany, for example,
funding has been cut by millions. Hundreds of workers have been
laid off, including doctors and nurses. Eighteen months ago, the
hospital needed a $30,000 laser dental drill. It took an employee
auction to help pay for the thing.
</P>
<P>
   So it's probably not surprising that on Memorial Day, veterans
are staging rallies across the country to protest what Washington
politicians are doing to the VA and to the millions of men and
women who risked their lives for their country.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gibney of the Disabled American Veterans is an organizer of
a rally at the Stratton VA Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people don't want this,'' he said. ``Our studies
show that 95 percent of Americans want veterans to get the care
they were promised ... Because veterans have been given such a low
priority in the federal budget, many sick and disabled veterans die
before they're able to access health care or obtain a correct
claims decision ...''
</P>
<P>
   It's just not right, Gibney says.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
