<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Saturday,
May 29. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News Desk
at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   TEEN: Missouri lawmakers, with no fanfare, have passed a law
that makes major changes in Missouri's driver's license system. The
change was part of a 262-page bill that won approval on the last
day of the session. If the governor signs it, Missouri will join
two dozen or so other states with graduated driver's license laws.
For kids there is one big gain: they can get a learner's permit at
the age of 15 instead of 15.5 starting Jan. 1, 2001. But they will
have to be 18 to get an unrestricted license, not 16, and will have
to clear several hurdles to do so. Backers say the change is just
common sense, especially since young drivers make up a
disproportionate number of fatalities. Story also includes comments
from parents and kids and what they think about the changes and
what has happened on the issue in Kansas. Will Sentell, Winston
Ross. 25 inches. Photo possible.
</P>
<P>
   CHICK: The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention's
advisory committee on vaccines recommended Thursday that states
make chicken pox vaccinations mandatory for children entering
school or a licensed day care. The new vaccine has been found to be
quite effective. And getting chicken pox is not only no fun, it can
be dangerous. We're trying to get a photo and interview with
parents of a 4-year-old who got chicken pox and developed a strep
infection from it. As a result, the boy now needs a heart valve
replacement. The child is at Children's Mercy Hospital. Graphic.
Alan Bavley. 20-25.
</P>
<P>
   MEDVET: Did Old Sparky, the family cat, bite an electric cord?
Was Max the Mastiff stabbed in the chops during a burglary? Did you
back over Fifi on your way to work? Then you probably know about
Mission Med Vet, the place specializing in emergency medicine for
pets. If you don't, you will, as we spend a few evenings watching
latter-day Dr. Doolittles save the beasts. Joe Popper. 30 inches.
Photos.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE (tentative): A Clay County man decides to build a nice
rustic log cabin _ only problem is, he picks a space on another
man's property. He also goes about getting the lumber and fixtures
for his house by stealing it from seven other houses in the area
currently under construction. Man is arrested and charged Thursday.
Shawna Hamel. Photo
</P>
<P>
   GUN: Man pleads guilty Friday in Jackson County to leaving a gun
around so a 6 year old kid could shoot a 1-year-old to death. Ruth
Igoe. 12.
</P>
<P>
   REFUGE. Edmond Rugova of Overland Park finally gets his
relatives out of Yugoslavia. It's the first time he's seen his
sister in 18 years. Stacy Downs. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   LIGHT (Business) _ The Power &AMP; Light District jumped off the
drawing boards into the bright neon lights of Las Vegas at this
week's annual convention of mall developers. By Mark Couch, Photos
</P>
<P>
   Y2K (Business) _ Y2k column by David Hayes, Finn Bullar
</P>
<P>
   CERNER (business) _ Cerner Corp. annual meeting. Julius Karash
</P>
<P>
   INDYCART (sports): The split between Indy and CART has cost both
organizations dearly, and it doesn't appear to be going away
anytime soon. Jim Pedley. 25-30. Photo
</P>
</TEXT>
