<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 13:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4843 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSEUM-DREAM-ART-$ADV     05-28 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-DREAM-ART-$ADV30-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD OF ART ARISES FROM ABANDONED FACTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 30)   (EDs: Photo available on the Wieck database.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIMOTHY CAHILL  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH ADAMS, Mass. _ It seemed preposterous a pie-in-the-sky
fantasy as extravagant as it was bizarre. Talk about your old mill
dreams: Turn an abandoned electronics plant in a remote Berkshire
factory town into the country's largest museum for minimalist,
postmodern and conceptual art. Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   That was 1986. Now, 13 years later, the naysayers are eating
their words and hoping the rest of the world has a short memory.
MASS MoCA, the Massachusetts Museum of Contemporary Art, is now
reality.
</P>
<P>
   The massive arts center, in a 13-acre, 27-building factory
complex in North Adams, Mass., opens to the public Sunday. With
facilities for both the visual and performing arts, MASS MoCA bills
itself as the largest venue of its kind in the country.
</P>
<P>
   MASS MoCA is more than an art museum. In fact, it isn't a museum
in the conventional sense at all. It doesn't own any art, and has
no plans of maintaining a permanent collection. MASS MoCA is more
like an interdisciplinary laboratory, designed to foster
collaboration among artists and art forms. The planned programming
is staggering, and includes site-specific artworks, sound-art
installations, multimedia theatrical performances, cutting-edge
animation showings, dance and music concerts, premiere film
screenings even a show of artist-designed billboards.
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire arts institutions, including the Clark Art Institute
and Jacob's Pillow, have affiliated themselves with the project, as
have prestigious museums like the Guggenheim Museum in New York and
the Philadelphia Museum of Art. Among the major avante-garde
artists whose work will inaugurate the complex are Robert
Rauschenberg, Joseph Beuys, James Rosenquist and Dan Flavin, as
well as composer Philip Glass, director Robert Wilson and
choreographers Trisha Brown and Bill T. Jones.
</P>
<P>
   MASS MoCA director Joe Thompson sees his museum as a catalyst, a
place where art and artists can throw off sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission is to be a platform for new work that might not
happen anywhere else,'' Thompson says. ``We don't bring a
collection or assets to the table. We bring time and space.''
</P>
<P>
   MASS MoCA's great asset and its great promise amount to one
thing: raw space. A ton of it. Generous, affordable space, which
permits art to happen in a way that only large spaces really allow.
Total space available: 700,000 square feet, only about a third of
which is currently in use. Some 120,000 square feet is devoted to
performance spaces, rehearsal studios, fabrication shops and public
areas such as a restaurant. An additional 100,000 square feet is
devoted to exhibition space, in 19 separate galleries.
</P>
<P>
   One of the galleries at MASS MoCA is 40 feet high, with
clerestory windows and both balcony and mezzanine viewing levels.
Another, at more than 100 yards long, is bigger than a football
field. From one vantage point, the visitor can sight through a
series of galleries across a distance spanning the equivalent of
two and a half city blocks. Its large galleries will house
monumental artworks, pieces that weigh a ton or measure a quarter
of a mile.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not a great number of places where the kind of work
that will be shown there can be seen regularly,'' observes Michael
Kimmelman, chief art critic for the New York Times. ``Most urban
centers don't have that much room.''
</P>
<P>
   Space has always been the attraction of the MASS MoCA complex.
</P>
<P>
   Originally a textile factory, the century-old red-brick plant
housed the Sprague Electric Co. from 1942 to 1985. Sprague's
closing devastated North Adams, leaving 4,000 people out of work in
this western Massachusetts city of 16,000.
</P>
<P>
   It was around the same time that Thomas Krens, the then-director
of the Williams College Art Museum in nearby Williamstown, began to
eye his blue-collar neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   Krens, now director of the Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum, is a
man of baroque ambitions he set the art world abuzz a couple years
ago by opening an architecturally flamboyant ``branch'' of the
Guggenheim in the Spanish factory town of Bilbao. But his first big
idea was MASS MoCA, which he envisioned would house one of the
world's finest collections of minimalist art in the Sprague plant.
</P>
<P>
   Krens recently explained that around the time Sprague closed, he
had come to the conclusion, ``that contemporary art museums were
insufficient to the task of showing contemporary art. I saw
something in Europe where they had done an exhibition in an old
factory building, and it struck me that North Adams had an old
factory.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Krens soon left for the notoriety of his current
position, and his protege Thompson was named to head it, the
cockeyed genius of the original vision has remained pretty much
intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability to respond to contemporary culture is a function
of how much space you have,'' Krens said. ``Space leads to
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MASS MoCA will allow work to be seen that simply doesn't get too
much exhibit time. Such a work is Joseph Beuys' ``Lightning with
Stag in its Glare,'' a multipiece sculptural installation dominated
by a 22-foot, 2,000-pound bronze abstract form suspended from the
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   The piece, on loan from the Philadelphia Museum of Art, had been
stored in an abandoned subway station and not exhibited because the
museum didn't have the facilities to show it. In North Adams, it
comfortably and effectively hangs in what is, by MASS MoCA's
standards, a fairly smallish space.
</P>
<P>
   Oversized works have plenty of elbow room in North Adams.
Rosenquist's 160-foot painting ``The Swimmer in the Econo-mist''
gets its own gallery, as does Rauschenberg's ``1/4 Mile or 2
Furlong Piece,'' a visual stream-of-conscious journal of paintings,
prints, sculpture and assemblages that covers the floor and three
walls of the football field-sized Building 5 Gallery. Under the
direction of Rauschenberg himself, a crew of 15 worked the better
part of a week installing this single piece.
</P>
<P>
   Inside MASS MoCA's vast space, the usual rules of engagement at
a museum don't apply. Viewers are surrounded by the oversized
artworks, making it difficult to stand back and take them in
passively.
</P>
<P>
   The philosophy of art as a force rather than an artifact is a
central theme of contemporary artists, but one that's often
misunderstood. MASS MoCA is designed to give the visitor an
opportunity to ``get it.'' Because the museum does not exhibit
traditional paintings or sculpture, there's no competing aesthetic
to distract the viewer, making it somewhat easier to confront the
art that is there on its own terms.
</P>
<P>
   Much of what's displayed makes demands on the viewer's
intellectual imagination: Carl Andre's sculpture of 36 brushed
aluminum floor tiles arranged to create a 54-foot runway in an
otherwise bare gallery, for instance, or Mario Merz's constructions
based on the mathematical symmetry of the Fibonacci series, or
Natalie Jeremijenko's installation of six live maple trees
suspended upside-down over an outdoor courtyard.
</P>
<P>
   MASS MoCA gives the viewer time to get into the mindset of such
work, making it possible to appreciate its conceptual beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson says that to meet expenses he needs to attract 100,000
visitors a year. That's not just to the art shows, but to
everything, including planned pop concerts and polka parties.
</P>
<P>
   As for his art exhibitions, he is guardedly confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they're up, lit, installed, they become playful and
visual,'' he says of the works. ``They have a real theatrical
quality that, if people have an open mind, they'll warm to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 1306EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
