<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 13:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4851 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICS-SOUTH-$ADV30     05-28 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-SOUTH-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DESPITE TIME ELSEWHERE, GORE AND BUSH ARE POLITICAL SONS OF
DIXIE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The longstanding joke about Al Gore was that at
Harvard he took ``Southern'' as a foreign language. But Bob Squier,
a longtime maker of his campaign TV ads, says it has been
impossible to wring the Tennessee twang out of Gore's voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a Southern boy, no doubt about it,'' Squier said last
week as he accompanied the vice president on part of a three-day
campaign swing through the South.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, when George W. Bush came to Washington to work on his
father's campaign for president in 1988, he surprised a lot of the
Beltway ``suits'' by showing up chewing tobacco, a habit he had
cultivated in the oil fields of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bush attended Yale University and Harvard Business
School, ``I am a product of the West and I think that way,'' the
second-term Texas governor said in a recent interview with The
Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was born in Washington, D.C., and Bush on the Yale campus
in New Haven, Conn. Even though their down-home roots have been
questioned, the themes and policies Gore and Bush are developing as
they pursue their parties' 2000 presidential nominations fit the
politics of the modern-day South like a glove.
</P>
<P>
   Both are political centrists, with philosophies of limited or
``reinvented'' government. They are openly religious and support
government cooperation with ``faith-based'' organizations in
attacking social ills. They promote the importance of family,
education and community. They recognize the importance of
technology in the new economy. They are tough on crime. They are
free traders. And they are military hawks.
</P>
<P>
   Both men are battling for the votes of a region that has changed
a lot since 1972, when President Nixon's campaign devised a
racially tinged ``Southern strategy'' for his re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even Southern voters are clearly moving on'' from wedge-issue
politics of pitting a minority, such as blacks, against a fearful
majority, such as Southern whites, said Richard Tafel, executive
director of Log Cabin Republicans, a nationwide group of gay
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the change has come from rapid growth. In 1998, five of
10 fastest growing counties in the nation were in the South. The
other five were in the West. That growth has produced an explosion
of suburbs that are less willing to accept polarizing racial
politics or the moralizing of the GOP's religious conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suburbs have become the key battleground in national
elections,'' said Al From, president of the Democratic Leadership
Council (DLC), the centrist organization which Gore helped found
after Walter Mondale's disastrous loss to Ronald Reagan in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bush ``both have their eyes on the suburbs'' in the
South and the West, said Merle Black, a political science professor
at Emory University and co-author of the 1992 book, ``The Vital
South: How Presidents are Elected.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore is trying to extend the Democratic political inroads that
Clinton made into Republican-leaning suburbs by pressing a
``liveability'' agenda aimed at voters in such cities as Atlanta
and Austin, Texas, that are choking on urban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   And following student shootings in suburban schools in Colorado
and Georgia, Gore has touted gun control measures while also
lecturing the entertainment industry about violence in movies and
television.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who faces the prospect that a decades-long Republican
``rising tide'' may be ebbing across the South, is also adjusting
to new political realities as he steps up from statewide candidacy
to a run for national office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party is at a crossroads,'' said Mark Miller,
executive director of the Republican Leadership Council, a centrist
group founded in 1997 and modeled after the DLC.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now face a situation similar to that of the Democrats of
the 1980s, who were dominated by a vocal minority from the far-left
liberal wing of their party,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   That is especially true in the Sunbelt, where religious
conservatives, the driving force in Republican presidential
nominations since 1980, are concentrated.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Bush, while opposing abortion rights, avoids any
suggestion that the U.S. Constitution be amended to abolish
abortions. And unlike his father, who railed against racial
``quotas'' and ``affirmative action,'' the Texas governor advocates
``affirmative access'' _ admission to college based on performance
only.
</P>
<P>
   It is on the issue of guns, long a staple of Southern and
Western politics, that seems to divide Gore and Bush the most.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, during a two-day stay in Texas last week,
challenged all political leaders to allow local governments to sue
gun manufacturers and to oppose expanding laws allowing citizens to
carry concealed weapons.
</P>
<P>
   He did so as Bush, who had signed a concealed weapons law in his
first term, was preparing to sign into law a bill that would
prevent local governments in Texas from joining other cities in
suing gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a dangerous society _ people feel like they need to
defend themselves,'' Bush said recently in explaining his position
on gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
