<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4866 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-REVIEW-RING-HNS     05-28 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-REVIEW-RING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECORDING INDUSTRY GIVES WAGNER'S `RING' DESERVED ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALLAN ULRICH  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ You've finally done it, and now you're having
second thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   You've invested a month's rent in tickets for the San Francisco
Opera's production of Wagner's ``Der Ring des Nibelungen'' (the
four cycles run June 9 to July 3 at the War Memorial Opera House),
and since you've made four lengthy evenings worth of commitment, a
great adventure in anybody's musical life, you want to derive the
maximum pleasure without taking out another loan.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the record industry is ready to oblige; a complete
``Ring'' spreads over 14 compact discs, and you should own one that
takes advantage of contemporary technology. Historical recordings
of the ``Ring'' are another matter. Some are most illuminating, but
sonics and pitch accuracy vary and, because they are published by
independent companies, these sets are often hard to find, even in
the biggest stores.
</P>
<P>
   If you've already blown the budget, spend at least $25 more and
get ``Der Ring des Nibelungen _ An Introduction'' on two mid-price
Decca/London CDs (443 581), originally recorded in 1967. The late
musicologist Deryck Cooke delivers a no-nonsense, unfailingly
pertinent analysis of Wagner's tangled skein of leitmotifs and
their transformation throughout the four operas. The booklet
reprints the 193 musical quotations Cooke highlights and musical
excerpts are drawn from the complete Vienna Philharmonic/Georg
Solti recording.
</P>
<P>
   As for complete ``Ring'' recordings, the most recent arrival _
EMI Classics CDZN-72731 _ is also one of the greatest bargains in
the catalog; you should pay no more than $99 for it. This is the
soundtrack of an NHK video production by Nikolaus Lehnhoff (the
original director of the San Francisco ``Ring''), taped in Munich
in 1993. Heading the cast are Hildegard Behrens (Brunnhilde), Julia
Varady (a most touching Sieglinde), Rene Kollo (Siegfried) and
American Robert Hale (Wotan/The Wanderer).
</P>
<P>
   Wolfgang Sawallisch conducts the Bavarian State Orchestra
solidly and idiomatically, in a manner that suggests he's more
storyteller than philosopher, and the few sound effects shouldn't
disconcert anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, at this price, EMI has economized by omitting a copy of
the Wagner libretto. You will need one, if only to understand how
he uses Stabreim, an archaic German alliterative device, as a major
element in his prosody.
</P>
<P>
   The most economical solution is Andrew Porter's superb singing
translation (in Norton paperback, with the original on facing
pages), which has been used by opera companies from London to
Seattle. If you're looking for something more elaborate, there's
Rudolf Sabor's translation and analysis in five (one for each
opera, one for the ``Ring'' as a whole) beautifully designed and
illustrated Phaidon paperbacks, available separately.
</P>
<P>
   Wagnerites who want to splurge on a more costly ``Ring'' will
find three contenders selling in stores for virtually the same
price, in the $170 (mid-price) range.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Wagnerites would probably choose the Philips (20325),
recorded during 1966-67 performances at the prestigious Bayreuth
Festival and conducted by Karl Bohm. The album spotlights the
foremost Brunnhilde and Siegfried of their time, Birgit Nilsson and
Wolfgang Windgassen, who, when heard in live conditions, always
excelled their studio efforts. Leonie Rysanek's ardent Sieglinde,
screams and all, is a major plus. The casting is uneven, Bohm
doesn't rise to the heights until ``Siegfried,'' but the unique
blend of voice and orchestra possible at Wagner's own festival hall
is something everyone should experience.
</P>
<P>
   Recently remastered digitally in the ``Originals;; Series
(Deutsche Grammophon 457 780), the illustrious Berlin
Philharmonic/Herbert von Karajan) ``Ring'' (taped piecemeal in the
late 1960s) offers the most luscious and balanced orchestral
account of any set, and the beautifully textured ``Das Rheingold''
is terrific by any standards. This is not, pace contemporary
commentators, a chamber music ``Ring.'' Yet, after ``Die Walkure''
(starring Regine Crespin, Join Vickers and Gundula Janowitz), the
singing from Siegfrieds Jess Thomas and Helge Brilioth and
Brunnhilde Helga Dernesch simply can't compare with the best of its
generation.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Georg Solti's best-selling Vienna Philharmonic
``Ring'' (London 14100, and stretched to 15 CDs). The project,
launched in 1959, introduced three of the operas in stereo. Kirsten
Flagstad (the ``Rheingold'' Fricka), Nilsson, Windgassen and Hans
Hotter (Wotan) were all titanic Wagnerians. But Solti's
overemphasis often precludes lyricism and poetry. Yet, in the
absence of another, it's the ``Ring'' on which an entire generation
was weaned.
</P>
<P>
   In the most expensive category, the DG Metropolitan Opera studio
version of the ``Ring'' is, foremost, a tribute to the world-class
orchestra artistic director James Levine has built over the past 25
years, and it does feature James Morris, who will sing Wotan again
in San Francisco. As a statement of the score, it's a glorious
effort, stately and sonorous. As music drama, however, it's a bit
chilly for this taste, and the singing can be spotty.
</P>
<P>
   Behrens is more interesting with Sawallisch, and nobody should
be forced to listen to Gary Lakes' Siegmund.
</P>
<P>
   Also at top price, but with the components available separately,
is Daniel Barenboim's Bayreuth set, taped (and shot for video) in
1991. Harry Kupfer's production was controversial, but Barenboim
seems more alert to the implications of the music drama than any
recorded conductor in decades.
</P>
<P>
   The Brunnhilde _ Anne Evans, who was a disaster here as Elsa 20
years ago _ is warm and lyrical. Siegfried Jerusalem is an
intensely involved hero, and John Tomlinson delivers an incisive
Wotan.
</P>
<P>
   The live ambience and sense of risk-taking is powerful.
</P>
<P>
   But you, the listener, will take no risks by acquiring ``The
Anna Russell Album'' (Sony MDK 47252), wherein that paragon of
musical enlightenment dispatches her hilarious analysis of the
``Ring.'' Russell does it all in under 22 insightful minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 1320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
