u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-BLAKE-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-B     05-28 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-BLAKE-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 ATHENS, Ga.: ... current level.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``His older brother Tommy hit the ball so hard, we used to call
him `Tommy Gun,' '' said Harvard coach Dave Fish. ``When little
James came along, he was a half-pint, so they nicknamed him `Squirt
Gun.' And he went from `Squirt Gun' to being the No. 1 player in
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``As he gained some height, he began practicing with Mats
Wilander (who resides in Greenwich, Conn.), and (Wilander) started
telling people, `Hey, this kid is the real deal.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cooking under pressure
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, facing an opponent against whom he had split two
previous meetings, Blake jumped out to a 4-0 lead, then struggled
and found the first set tied, 4-4, before closing it out. He
trailed three times in the second set, including at 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   But he didn't fret or falter, battling to force the tiebreaker,
then beating Bohaboy with an array of dazzling serves and passing
shots.
</P>
<P>
   In his first-round match, Blake beat Asaf Tishler of Nevada-Las
Vegas, the 33d-ranked player in the world, 6-2, 6-3, in one hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``He controls the points,'' said Tishler. ``He doesn't let you
have an opportuntity to become more aggressive and control the
point. You are on the defensive side on every point. He hits the
ball really hard on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge this week is monumental. Should Blake win in
singles, he must also play a fourth-round contest. He also has a
final exam scheduled here.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the player who once considered himself a brat has been
composed throughout.
</P>
<P>
   ``One tournament isn't going to make or break my year,'' said
Blake. ``I feel like I've proven myself and reached my goals
throughout the year, so if I have an off week at the NCAA
tournament and don't play well, it's not going to be the end of the
world. I know I still proved I played my hardest. That's the only
thing I can guarantee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, the better James does, the more humble he is,''
said Barker. ``At each step, when he's done something great, he has
become more mellow and more and more humble. What's interesting is
that most kids are the exact opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A showcase and a decision
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of his showing in the NCAA tournament, the
6-foot-1-inch, 155-pound Blake will continue to be a focal point of
tennis after the season.
</P>
<P>
   He has been named to the US Davis Cup team as a practice partner
and will help the team prepare to face Australia July 16-18 at
Longwood Cricket Club in Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   ``James has an extremely great future in men's tennis; he is one
of the most promising American prospects,'' said US Davis Cup coach
Tom Gullickson. ``He's very athletic on the court. He's a very
difficult shotmaker. He has a good mind for tennis. He's very
composed on the court, which I like a lot. I think he's only going
to get better as he plays higher levels of competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a little bit of a late bloomer. For his age, he doesn't
have a terrific amount of experience at the higher levels of
competition. To expose James to the Davis Cup team, the Davis Cup
atmosphere, the best players in the world there, will be terrific
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Blake said that following the tournament, he will
announce whether he will forgo his final two seasons of college
eligibility and turn professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping to try to make a decision early to be fair to all
the people involved, the coaches here and agents and everyone
else,'' said Blake. ``My brother has told me it's another big step,
where everyone is a really tough player and they're all fighting
for a living, so they have that added level of intensity. You have
to be ready to fight in every match you're in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a tough decision. I'm having such a great time
here. But luckily, the good thing about this school is that they
have a policy where you can come back at any time; once you're
accepted, you're accepted forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I do decide to leave, I would love to put some money away
and come back here whenever I decided to quit playing tennis. If I
feel like there's not much I can do at the college level and there
aren't too many people coming back who can push me to that next
level in college, then I might have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blast from past
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Blake began teaching clinics at the Trumbull
club and encountered a 10-year-old Barker described as ``a
nightmare.'' Blake wanted to take the youngster under his wing, but
after a few lessons, the boy turned on Blake and yelled, ``You
jerk. I don't want you to teach me. You're an idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``James didn't know what to do,'' said Barker. ``He wanted the
kid to like him. He wanted to do a good job. He wanted us to ask
him to teach again. He looked at me and said, `Brian, what do you
do to a kid like this?' And I said, `James, you're now me, and that
kid was you.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I was probably that bad when I was that little and
Brian said I was five times worse,'' said Blake. ``That was one of
the things that kept me in the learning process, learning how to be
humble and act like a sportsman on the court and not a pain. I
didn't feel like dealing with those kids, and I'm sure no one felt
like dealing with me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
