<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-EXHIBIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTO EXHIBIT EXPOSES THE SPLENDOR OF THE WILDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAVID BONETTI  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Carleton Watkins (1829-1916) is widely regarded
as the finest American landscape photographer of the 19th century;
many judge him to have been the most important photographer to have
worked in Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   And considering the competition in that category _ Edward Weston
and his sons, Imogen Cunningham, Dorothea Lange, Ansel Adams, John
Gutmann, to name the most prominent _ that's saying something.
</P>
<P>
   Yet until the 1980s, Watkins' achievement _ his photographs of
Yosemite were so astonishing that they directly contributed to its
early designation as a national park _ went widely unacknowledged.
Even now in the broader world interested in photography, his name
doesn't resonate fully.
</P>
<P>
   So, the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art retrospective,
``Carleton Watkins: The Art of Perception,'' which continues
through Sept. 7, aims to finally give Watkins his due. That the
show will travel to the Metropolitan Museum in New York and the
National Gallery in Washington, guarantees that it will receive the
national audience it deserves.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition looks splendid installed in the museum's
loft-like, fifth-floor galleries, miraculously transformed by wall
colors and moldings into a 19th century salon. It includes more
than 150 of Watkins' images, both the mammoth plates (up to
18-by-22 inches) that brought him fame and the stereo views that
entered almost every middle-class American home. At the end of the
galleries, banks of computers simulate the stereo viewing
experience.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the show is extraordinarily persuasive of
Watkins' originality and talent.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by Douglas R. Nickel, the museum's associate curator
of photography, the exhibition comes with a thesis. Nickel, who
wrote an impressively erudite essay for the catalog (Abrams, $60,
hardbound; $34.95 paper), says Watkins was a modernist involved in
creating ``an art of perception'' in his work, which, in his mind,
he made for frankly commercial purposes.
</P>
<P>
   If I understand him correctly, what Nickel means by ``an art of
perception'' is the new way of seeing that came into being in the
19th century _ evident in work of French artists such as Edgar
Degas as well as in Watkins' _ in which pure opticality replaced
the more narrative or symbolic mode of representation that
previously prevailed. The camera's objective, non-hierarchical,
non-picturesque vision, was crucial to this new way of looking, and
Watkins responded to his medium's demands intuitively.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Watkins, who was uneducated in art and theory, said
about his practice merely that he sought ``the spot which would
give the best view.'' And the exhibition demonstrates that again
and again Watkins had a knack for finding exactly that right spot.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins remains best known for his Yosemite pictures, which
still strike us as filled with awe for an untrammeled wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   In these pictures, Yosemite appears to be the handiwork of a
rather stern and theatrical deity _ even if Watkins' intention was
merely to go about getting what was to his eye the best view, which
would guarantee him success in the fierce competition of selling
images.
</P>
<P>
   (While Watkins might have been an unconscious genius as an
image-maker, he was a dramatic failure as a businessman. He lost
his gallery and all his negatives to a rival in the bank panic of
1875. In the 1890s, he and his family ended up living in a boxcar,
until his childhood friend, railroad tycoon Collis Huntington,
bailed him out.)
</P>
<P>
   The story of Watkins' Yosemite treks verges on the heroic. A
young man from Oneonta, N.Y., who came to California looking for
fortune during the Gold Rush, Watkins fell into taking photographs
by chance. But in 1861, he dragged a wagon full of cumbersome
equipment through the still roadless Yosemite Valley in order to
make pictures of the natural wonderland that was the subject of
much mythologizing in California cities.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins used the wet-negative process, and the large glass
plates that served as negatives had to be kept evenly wet with
collodion medium while taking the picture and during its subsequent
development. Then, after image-capturing was completed, the glass
negatives had to be brought back to San Francisco for printing.
Needless to say, the possibility of breakage was very real.
</P>
<P>
   But the results of that first trip _ he ultimately visited
Yosemite eight times _ at least 30 mammoth plates and 100
stereographs, galvanized the world. East Coast philosophers,
preachers and professors, including Oliver Wendell Holmes, were
awed by Watkins' achievement, and in 1864, largely on the evidence
of Watkins' photographs, President Abraham Lincoln signed
legislation protecting Yosemite from development. By 1867, Watkins
won a bronze medal at the Paris International Exposition for
landscape photography.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although photography's subsequent technological development
means that we have to work a bit to appreciate the
unprecedentedness of what Watkins did, the Yosemite pictures remain
awesome. Not only did Watkins capture the big picture, the best
view he spoke about as his goal, he also created images in which
details speak. The shimmering light off turned-over leaves, the
sparkle of water, the hardness of rock are all plainly evident in
these great pictures.
</P>
<P>
   But Watkins' greatest works might be those that show the steady
encroachment of civilization on the wilderness. His photographs,
some of them multiple- panel panoramas, of San Francisco, Salt Lake
City and Portland, Ore., are riveting documents.
</P>
</TEXT>
