<HEADER>
A4888 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-BOS &LR;      05-28 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING FINDING TRINIDAD, DAD A HARD SELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN _ It is difficult these days, but Don King is trying.
He is trying to sell the paying public a fighter he believes is the
best welterweight in the world. The fighter is not named Oscar De
La Hoya, so it is a tough sell anywhere but here, in a ballroom at
the El San Juan Hotel not far from where the fighter grew up.
</P>
<P>
   King is trying with all the bombast and bluster he can muster,
which is considerable under any circumstance but more so under
trying ones. But it is trying to try so hard for someone who
doesn't seem to understand what you are trying to do.
</P>
<P>
   Selling is something that comes naturally to King, as natural as
the rocketry of his hairdo. Closing the deal is his specialty, and
this he thought he had done for Felix Trinidad, the International
Boxing Federation champion who will defend his title Saturday night
in front of a packed house at Roberto Clemente Coliseum and before
a cable TV audience in the United States expected to be
considerably smaller than the one that watched De La Hoya a week
ago.
</P>
<P>
   King has brought The Fighter Nobody Knows and his father a
guaranteed $8 million purse to fight De La Hoya next; they have
never made more than $3 million before (and usually less than $1
million). And he has brought them the head of the man they insist
will be rendered unconscious if the two meet in the ring Sept. 18.
</P>
<P>
   King has done his job, working to make more out of a fighter
than the fighter has made of himself, although admittedly, the
promoter stands to pick up $2.5 million plus $6 per household for
every pay-per-view home over 850,000 that watches Trinidad-De La
Hoya _ if he can just get father and son to sign the piece of paper
in his pocket.
</P>
<P>
   That is the sticking point. The piece of paper and the numbers
on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the fight,'' Trinidad (34-0, 29 KOs) insists as he sips
cold water and then hot coffee with warm milk. ``If you told me the
father of Oscar De La Hoya doesn't want him to fight me, I would
believe you. But my father wants the fight. This problem is just
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will we fight on Sept. 18? That is up to Don King. That is up
to Bob Arum. We have been very flexible. Very flexible.''
</P>
<P>
   If you ask King, Trinidad's father has been about as flexible as
a block of cement. First he insisted on $500,000 in training
expenses to work at the same gym his son has always worked at, a
gym in Puerto Rico that looks like no one has put $50 into
preserving it, let alone $500,000. Lately, the father has reduced
the demand to $350,000, to which King shakes his head in
bewilderment and then laughs a laugh that carries more menace than
merriment.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not the real problem. When King got Arum to up the
ante from $10 million to $10.5 million while also lowering the
required pay-per-view sales from 1 million to 850,000 before
Trinidad and King begin to share equally in the revenue, Trinidad's
father still refused to sign because the promoter kept the extra
$500,000.
</P>
<P>
   King claims he is entitled to a $3 million promotional fee but
has cut it by $500,000 and is willing to share any upside of
pay-per-view sales even though ``that is my money. He wants the
guaranteed money, so I get the overage if there is any. That's the
promoter's gamble. I'm willing to share it, but Don Felix don't get
it. I can deal with treachery, man. It's abject ignorance that
gives me trouble. But I will work this out.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, people close to the promotion say, King and Don
Felix were ``working it out'' at about 200 decibels. It was not the
kind of business discussion you expect among partners on the cusp
of splitting $10.5 million plus an upside, but this is boxing,
where fighting is the point.
</P>
<P>
   Through all this, the fighter sits tranquil, refusing to make
any demands on his father. Instead, he struggles to make 147
pounds, a weight that in recent fights has been a stiffer opponent
than the men in front of him, and concentrates on the challenge, a
young man with no chance named Hugo Pineda.
</P>
<P>
   No one expects much from Pineda even though he has only one
loss, and that was against former junior welterweight champion
Kostya Tszyu, a man Pineda knocked down but couldn't knock out.
Considering that Trinidad has been knocked down five times in his
career, that might be a concern to some, but not to Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I am the best welterweight in the world,'' he declares
regally, sounding the way people who have grown up with money all
their lives do when they talk about paying the bills. ``I know I
have to win Saturday night to show the people that I am the best
pound-for-pound fighter in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already know this, but the fight with De La Hoya is a fight
the world wants, so I am ready to do it. But I don't believe he
wants to fight me. He knows what will come. He knows he will visit
the canvas.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does know this, De La Hoya has a good way of hiding his
fears. He is the one who ordered Arum to give Trinidad the $10
million his father first demanded to make the fight. Now Don Felix
has it but says it's not enough to put his son in with an opponent
he claims will visit the canvas not long after the first bell
tolls. King hears this and shakes his head.
</P>
<P>
   He is incongruous! He is amazed! He is stupefied and mortified!
He's also mad as can be, but he's trying not to show it.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid that, he's doing something else. He's selling his
fighter. Or at least his fighter's fruit juice.
</P>
<P>
   It is a hot day in San Juan, but it is always hot where King
stands, so he is unfazed by the wilting humidity or the melting
television lights bathing him and Trinidad in sweat. King is not
fixated on the heat of the moment or the heat with Don Felix now.
</P>
<P>
   He's fixated on the camera and on the tiny box he is holding in
front of it as Trinidad speaks. It is time to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a refreshing drink that will make you think!'' King is
shouting as he waves a box of Tito's Punch. ``So drink it now!''
</P>
<P>
   As King roars and young Trinidad smiles, Don Felix sits in the
corner wearing a business suit and a frown. As he glowers, Don King
wishes for only one thing.
</P>
<P>
   He wishes Don Felix would try a drink that makes him think.
Before it's too late.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
