<HEADLINE>
LOOK AT PORTFOLIOS AS ONE, THEN CREATE PERFECT BALANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 30, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. My husband and I notice that most people who write to you
share our problem _ asset allocation. We are in our late 30s and
early 40s and plan to retire when we are 62 and 65. We both
contribute 15 percent of our pretax salaries to 401(k) plans; I
work part time and am able to contribute approximately $2,600 a
year and my husband now can max out at $10,000 a year. My husband's
plan invests through American Funds family, and 50 percent of his
contributions go to Washington Mutual Investors (large-cap domestic
stocks), 20 percent to New Perspective (global stocks) a like
amount to Investment Co. of America (large-cap US and foreign
stocks), and 10 percent to Income Fund of America (balanced). His
other options are Europacific Growth, an income fund, and a money
market fund. My 401(k) is 50 percent invested in Vanguard Index
500, 30 percent is in Janus Balanced, and I have 10 percent each in
Janus Worldwide and T. Rowe Price Mid-Cap Growth. The other options
are a guaranteed interest fund, Harbor Bond, Vanguard Windsor II,
T. Rowe Price Small-Cap Stock, and Janus Overseas funds. What do
you suggest?
</P>
<P>
   R.V., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, both of you have done much better than the average
401(k) investor. I think there are a few things, though, that you
can do to improve the balance. First, both of you have chosen
global funds _ New Perspective and Janus Worldwide _ to diversify
into overseas stocks. That diversification is fine, but by choosing
world stock funds rather than international stocks, you have to
some extent duplicated your large-cap domestic stock position _
according to the Morningstar Mutual Funds reports, New Perspective
fund has 43 percent of its portfolio in US stocks, while Janus
Worldwide has 30 percent. By switching to Europacific Growth and
Janus Overseas, you will get 100 percent international stocks in
those segments of the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the way I would handle the overall situation: Your 401(k)
has a broader selection of funds, and I suggest you lump the two
portfolios together in your minds so you can take advantage of
that. You might consider creating what appears to be an unbalanced
portfolio in your 401(k), but one which will, when combined with
your husband's, turn out to be in perfect balance.
</P>
<P>
   Between the two of you, I would suggest 50 percent in domestic
large caps and 12 1/2 percent each in T. Rowe Price Mid-Cap Growth,
T. Rowe Price Small-Cap Stock, either Janus Balanced or Income Fund
of America, and either Europacific Growth or Janus Overseas. Don't
be daunted by the lowly two-star Morningstar rating for the Price
Small-Cap Stock fund _ that rating reflects the woes of the
small-cap sector as much as the fund's performance. Over the long
haul, the fund has been a solidly above-average performer in its
peer group, and given your long-term investment time frame you
should be willing to wait for the small cap sector to finally wake
up and likely far outperform its larger peers.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. When I left my job in 1993 at age 50, I left my 401(k)
account with the firm. The money was earning very little, so in
June 1994 I rolled over the $111,508 account into an IRA with
Fortis investments. As of April 1, it had a $183,692 balance. I
also have an IRA invested in a large cap growth fund, now worth
$6,995. During the past five years I have moved money from one fund
to another, based on returns. I do not receive guidance from my
account representative. I would like to retire at age 65, and am
making prepayments on my home mortgage so it will be paid off by
then. My current occupation provides sporadic income, and I have a
money market account to provide for month-to-month expenses. My
current allocation for the rollover IRA is: $24,514 in asset
allocation, $28,280 in global growth, $5,251 in aggressive growth,
$44,799 in growth and income, $19,099 in global asset allocation,
$53,257 in a Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index fund, $4,078 in mid-cap
stock, and the rest in a fixed account earning 4.67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   S.D., Laguna Niguel, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. My guess is that through your various moves over the past
five years you've probably cost yourself some money. Calculating
your returns over 58 months, I get a 10.86 percent average annual
portfolio return. Not bad in many markets, but you were operating
in an almost unremitting bull market during that period; according
to Morningstar Mutual Funds, the average domestic stock fund
returned a little more than 16 percent a year over the 5 years; the
Standard and Poor's 500 index had average annual return in excess
of 26.5 percent for the period. In fact, had you simply put your
money in the very conservative Fortis Asset Allocation fund back in
June of '94, you'd have done better, with Lipper Analytical
Services Inc. reporting a 118.03 percent total return for the fund
during the five years from May 12, 1994 through May 13, 1999. My
suggestion is to stop churning yourself _ select a solid long-term
portfolio that suits your needs and appetite for risk and stick
with it. There's no need to leave Fortis to do this; just stop
chasing Thursday's highest-performing funds.
</P>
<P>
   If you achieve average 10 percent returns during the next nine
years, the combined value of your IRA and the 401(k) would be
$449,695. If such a sum were then invested to produce an income
stream, you could expect about $29,250 a year, presuming an average
6.5 percent yield from a fixed-income portfolio. If you will
qualify for Social Security benefits, you don't seem to be in very
tough condition. But there are two unpleasant factors to think
about, both involving inflation. The first is the fact that a
$29,250 income stream in the year 2008 would have the buying power
of only about $21,465 in today's money, presuming average 3.5
percent inflation. The second is that you should leave some of your
retirement savings invested in stocks after you retire, so as to
provide capital growth.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds to me as though you've been relying entirely on that
old 401(k). You don't give much information about your current
income or finances, except that income is irregular. I suggest you
begin a program to augment your retirement savings; even if you
have to start at a modest level, the critical thing is to adopt a
savings discipline and stick to it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address, and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA 02107-2378.)
</P>
</TEXT>
