<HEADLINE>
STEVENS EXPECTS LOUD FINISH ABOARD REAL QUIET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Jockey Gary Stevens is heading to England to ride on a
regular basis, but he'll keep an appointment in Boston first.
Stevens will ride 4-5 morning line favorite Real Quiet in
Saturday's $600,000 Massachusetts Handicap at Suffolk Downs, with a
post of 5:40 p.m., then catch a 7:20 flight from Logan to Heathrow
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Since Stevens is committed to ride for British trainer Michael
Stoute at least through November, this could be his last race in
the United States for some time. And Stevens intends to exit by way
of the winner's circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real Quiet rates right up there with the best horses I've
ridden,'' said Stevens, 36. ``He's a great athlete with tons of
ability. Unfortunately, he had some setbacks at the end of his
3-year-old season. He had a chronic problem with body soreness. His
last race in the Pimlico Special (a victory over Free House, who
was leading the handicap division), I thought, was a very special
race.''
</P>
<P>
   For Stevens to rank Real Quiet, who won the Kentucky Derby and
Preakness last year, near the top of his list is high praise,
because he has been the best rider in this country for at least the
last three years. He was elected to the Hall of Fame in 1997, and
in 1998, he won a record $19.6 milion in purses and was voted the
Eclipse Award. He has ridden three Kentucky Derby winners (Winning
Colors, 1988; Thunder Gulch, '95; and Silver Charm, '97) and has
ridden six winners in the Breeders' Cup. Stevens has also developed
a reputation as a thinking man's rider and is president of the
Jockeys' Guild.
</P>
<P>
   Kent Desormeaux was the original rider aboard Real Quiet, but
after winning the Derby and Preakness, he made a precipitous move
in the Belmont and Real Quiet was caught at the wire by Victory
Gallop, ridden by Stevens. When Real Quiet was beaten in his '99
debut, trainer Bob Baffert and owner Mike Pegram replaced
Desormeaux with Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   Most observers think the MassCap is a two-horse race, with 6-5
second choice Behrens, winner of two straight Grade I handicaps,
standing in Real Quiet's way. ``We're more or less going to his
home court,'' said Stevens of Behrens, who is stabled at Saratoga.
``He doesn't have to travel much. But I'm not scared of anybody on
Real Quiet. In the Texas Mile, I was just getting to know Real
Quiet (who finished second); I'd like to think that knowing him
better contributed to the win at Pimlico. No disrepect to Behrens,
I know what kind of horse he is, but I'm very confident in our
chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think having Real Quiet at Suffolk is a continuation of the
great quality of horses involved in the MassCap the last five years
(Cigar won in 1995 and '96, Skip Away in 1997 and '98). It's not as
if the Boston fans haven't been exposed to great horses in past
years. Cigar and Skip Away were great horses, and Real Quiet is
another great horse coming to this race.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens has never ridden at Suffolk, but he's watched the recent
MassCaps and knows that the East Boston oval is not as kind to
speed horses as some of the major tracks he's used to, especially
those in sun-drenched California. That should suit his horse well,
because while Behrens has early speed, Real Quiet is strictly a
stalker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to put it together the last couple of years in the
hopes that Silver Charm (also trained by Baffert) could race there,
but it never happened,'' said Stevens. ``I'm really looking forward
to it. It's a great day of racing for the fans of Boston. I try to
do my homework. I've watched the races there and I have noticed
that it's not a particularly fast racetrack. It's a notoriously
tiring track. It's going to be in the back of my mind to reserve
plenty of horse for the finish.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons Stevens has decided to go to England
while still at the peak of his game. He's had three knee operations
and is taking a pounding in the American-style crouch. He can ride
much higher in Europe. He battles weight, and he can ride much
heavier in Europe. And, perhaps most important, his wife, Nicola,
is English and hasn't been home in four years. Stevens will ride
his first race in England Tuesday, guiding Greek Dance for Stoute
in the Brigadier Gerard Stakes at Sandown. Then it's on to the big
show as he rides favored Beat All in the Epsom Derby, one of
Europe's most prestigious races, the following Saturday. If Stevens
is happy being based in Britain, he may extend his agreement with
Stoute for two more years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I didn't decide casually,'' he said. ``I want
to realize my full potential. I've been blessed with special
skills. To me, life is an adventure, and this is just another
chapter in my life. I've made it a rule not to make long-term plans
and to live each day to the fullest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Epsom Derby is the same day as the Belmont Stakes, and the
first important mount that Stevens will lose is that on champion
filly Silverbulletday, who is trained by Baffert and will be ridden
by Jerry Bailey as she takes on colts in the Belmont, a race not
won by a filly since 1905 (Tanya). But Stevens will be rooting in
the Belmont. He'll be rooting for close friend Chris Antley to win
the Triple Crown aboard Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Off the racetrack, Chris is like a little brother to me,''
said Stevens. ``I went through trying to win the Triple Crown (with
Silver Charm in 1997) and fell three-quarters of a length short
(beaten by Touch Gold in the Belmont). It is very difficult to
accomplish. The media really started hounding Chris after he won
the Derby, and he's tried to do as many interviews as he can. He's
done a great job, but my advice to him is that three or four days
before the race, he should go into his own little world and focus
on the Belmont. He's handling it all in stride right now. But there
is a hunger out there, from both the press and the fans, for a
Triple Crown because it's been so many years since there was a
Triple Crown winner (Affirmed in 1978). When it comes down to the
final eighth of a mile in the Belmont, I'm rooting for a Triple
Crown winner.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens has been among the top 10 money winners every year since
1985; he has won 14 races with $1 million purses; he took the $4
million Dubai World Cup with Silver Charm in '98; and he had a
streak during which he rode at least one winner on 31 straight
programs in California. But his induction into the Hall of Fame at
Saratoga was his biggest thrill in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most spectacular time of my career,'' said Stevens,
who rode one race at Hollywood Park Thursday, the fourth, and won
in his farewell appearance, his 1,200th victory at the track where
he has competed since 1984. ``I feel privileged to have been
inducted at a fairly young age. It's what I'm the most proud of.
It's great to be appreciated, not just by the other jockeys, my
peers, but by the whole spectrum of racing, the whole industry. It
is something I never would have dreamed of growing up in Boise,
Idaho.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet stretched his legs with a jog over the Suffolk strip
Thursday morning. ``He's had no problems since he shipped in,''
said exercise rider Larry Damore, who was aboard for the gallop.
``He put a smile on my face. We are just going about the normal
routine, but he is probably better than normal now. He always plays
a little bit when you get him on the track. He has a measure of
class and a bounce to his step.'' . . . Also out for a gallop was
European invader Running Stag, the third pick at 6-1, who went a
brisk 7 furlongs under assistant trainer Roger Teal. Running Stag
galloped in company with Lonesome Dove, a local allowance horse,
but it was not an official workout. ``He went very well out there,
just perfect,'' said Teal. ``He was not bothered by the dirt in his
face at all. He is used to all this by now. It always takes him a
day to get adjusted to surroundings, but he is as good as ever
right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
