<HEADLINE>
DILEMMA FOR MILOSEVIC'S PROSECUTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ In Canada, they're calling it ``Arbour's Choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Louise Arbour, the UN chief war crimes prosecutor who made
history Thursday with the indictment of Yugoslav leader Slobodan
Milosevic, faces an agonizing personal and professional decision _
one the world is watching.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, the 52-year-old Ontario judge, on special leave from
that province's Court of Appeals to serve with the United Nations
tribunal, is likely to be offered a seat on the Supreme Court of
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Appointment to the nation's nine-member high court is the honor
of a lifetime, the greatest professional achievement to which any
Canadian judge can aspire. If she passes on the opportunity now, it
will likely be years before another vacancy occurs.
</P>
<P>
   But anxious human rights advocates warn the loss of the
highly-regarded Arbour could throw a monkeywrench into efforts to
hold Milosevic's Serbian regime accountable for genocide, and are
urging Arbour to stay with the tribunal for humanity's sake. In the
long run, they fear, the departure of the iron-willed, high-octane
prosecutor might even cripple the fledgling process of
international prosecution of crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her departure would be very, very bad news for the tribunal,''
said Stefanie Grant, director of programs for the New York-based
Lawyers' Committee for Human Rights. ``It's not only the loss of
her tremendous talents, energy and focus, although that would be
bad enough. The real concern is that her departure would slow the
process, perhaps even drag it down.''
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, many observers say, Arbour's departure would
effectively halt the prosecutorial effort for months and even years
as the UN casts about for a politically-suitable replacement.
Russia, which opposes the US-led bombing campaign against
Yugoslavia, is expected to use its seat on the UN Security Council
to block appointment of any proposed prosecutor from a NATO nation,
such as Canada.
</P>
<P>
   But sources in Canada's government and legal community, as well
as media speculation, suggest Arbour is leaning strongly toward
accepting the Supreme Court position, if it is offered.
</P>
<P>
   The Quebec-born judge, little given to public musings, has
declined to deliver the verdict on her future. ``I don't think it's
fair to speculate on what I might or might not do with my life,''
she told the Toronto Star.
</P>
<P>
   The situation poses a dilemma for Canada.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, to have a Canadian serving in such a prominent and
powerful post fits perfectly with the country's policy of
international activisim. But delaying appointment of a new justice
to fill a Supreme Court position would hamper the high court's
work, and likely become a major political controversy for the
government of Prime Minister Jean Chretien.
</P>
<P>
   A decision by Arbour and Canda will have to be made soon since
Supreme Court Justice Peter Cory is scheduled to retire next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such a critical situation, such a historical juncture,
we're hoping the Canadian government can find some other option,
one that would let her to stay on the tribunal'' while still
keeping the Supreme Court seat open, said Kenneth Roth, executive
director of Human Rights Watch.
</P>
<P>
   Roth recently wrote a personal note to Arbour, imploring her to
continue working for the war crimes tribunal. ``But there's
recognition that this must be extraordinarily difficult personal
decision,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arbour is one of Canada's best-respected jurists, and it doesn't
hurt, politically, that she is also of French-Quebec heritage,
fluently bilingual and female. ``There is a kind of consensus in
the legal community that Louise Arbour is an ideal candidate, or,
if not ideal, then clearly the leading candidate,'' said Patrick
Monahan, a professor at the prestigious Osgoode Hall Law School in
Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Arbour, the mother of three, is separated from her husband, and
is said to yearn for a return to Canada. The 1971 graduate from the
University of Montreal, whose special expertise is in criminal law,
is known as much for her graciousness as her unswerving integrity
and resolve. She was appointed to the Ontario Supreme Court in
1987, and to Ontario's Court of Appeals in 1990. In 1996, at the
special request of the UN, she was given a leave to work for the
war crimes tribunal and has been based in The Hague, Netherlands,
ever since.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
