<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BU'S `ULYSSES' SCHOLAR TO EMBARK ON JOB ODYSSEY? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are we seeing the last days of Boston University's famous James
Joyce Research Center, run by the brilliant, nutty Joyce scholar
John Kidd? Kidd, possibly the world's foremost expert on Joyce's
novel ``Ulysses,'' tells me that he has resigned from the
university, effective next year, and that his resignation has been
accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the world of academe, Kidd is viewed as a
high-maintenance oddity. (I detailed his ministrations to the
wounded squirrels and pigeons of Commonwealth Avenue in ``The Long,
Strange Voyage of BU's `Ulysses' Man,'' Oct. 1, 1997.) But Kidd's
departure is a blow to BU not only because of his scholarship, but
also because he owns all 6,000 volumes in BU's Joyce Center. Where
he goes, the Joyce Center goes, and he says numerous universities
(why do I suspect Boston College is one of them?) have made him
``seven-figure offers'' for the book collection, plus promises of a
job for him.
</P>
<P>
   Why is he leaving? BU officials say Kidd's grading practices _
he flunked a few students, a no-no in the modern university _ have
been under investigation. And of course he is embroiled in a
controversy with the campus police over his efforts to rescue dying
pigeons on BU property. Whatever the cause, Kidd says ``I'll be
gone'' after he takes a sabbatical next year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Follow-up on the news &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several people called me after reading last week's item ``The
Lost History of the Wall Street Journal'' and said I left out the
best part of the story. It's true that Random House is stuck with
an unwieldy, unfinished history of the paper, partly written by the
late Richard Clurman and partly finished by Newsweek managing
editor Jon Meacham. But I did leave out the part about the
Journal's offering to finance completion of the manuscript, because
I didn't know about it.
</P>
<P>
   The Journal's vice president for corporate communications
Richard Tofel says he called Meacham's agent, Amanda (Binky) Urban,
after he learned that Meacham wouldn't have time to finish the
project. ``We had a certain interest in preserving part of the
manuscript,'' Tofel explains. ``I told Binky that if we were going
to play some role in this, either by buying copies or publishing
the manuscript privately, we would have to read it.'' Tofel's
primary interest was in the material from the 1920s and 1930s that
the writers had dug out of the WSJ archives, not in the Journal's
more turbulent, recent years of corporate strife.
</P>
<P>
   Urban did let Tofel read the manuscript earlier this year. More
than one writer was surprised to learn that what had started out as
a top-drawer, $300,000 project involving a prestigious publishing
house and well-known writers had devolved into a
bought-and-paid-for piece of corporate shilling. But that's not
exactly what happened. Tofel passed on his proposed deal, probably
because the jury-rigged manuscript was unsalvageable. ``I didn't
think there was any deal to be had from our perspective'' is all he
will say about his decision. Urban, a longtime friend of the
Clurman family, just wants to get the manuscript finished and says
she was grateful for Tofel's input: ``Dick was trying to do us a
favor.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Inside baseball &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the New Fenway games begin, meaning the endless flurry of
posturing around plans for a new Fenway Park, it helps to have a
program to know who the players are. The story behind the stories
that you read in the paper _ about property owner Stephen Mindich's
need to be compensated for his venerable Fenway-area properties,
etc., etc. _ is that many local businessmen wish ill upon John
Harrington, who manages the Jean Yawkey Trust, which owns the Sox.
And they hope the constant spitballing of the New Fenway, and the
cost of building a new stadium, will exhaust Harrington and the
trust financially, forcing the team to seek new owners.
</P>
<P>
   It would be wrong to suggest that the influence peddlers seeking
``input'' into the New Fenway _ people like the estimable and
upright George Regan, and former congressman Chester Atkins _ are
acting in concert or have a secret agenda. And at various times,
Fleet's Terry Murray, developer Joseph O'Donnell, and O'Donnell's
friend and fellow developer Steve Karp have denied any interest in
owning the Red Sox, or have declined comment. But anything can
happen when you're playing inside baseball.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
