<HEADER>
A4904 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCK-BOX-$ADV30-COX     05-28 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCK-BOX-$ADV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESSIONAL LOCK BOX FOR SOCIAL SECURITY _ HOW SECURE IS IT?
 &HT;    For release Sunday, May 30.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As lawmakers left the Capitol for the Memorial Day
holiday, Republicans boasted they had protected Social Security
from government ``raids.'' Democrats grumbled nothing has been done
_ or is likely to be done _ to solve the federal retirement
system's long-term financial problem.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans plan to use the holiday to whip up support among
their constituents, blaming Senate Democrats and the White House
for twice blocking their ``lock box'' bill. The issue is likely to
be among the first on the Senate floor when lawmakers return June
7.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is primarily symbolic, with a heavy dose of politics.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, approved Wednesday in the House, would subject any
legislation that would spend more money than is available in budget
_ not counting the Social Security or Medicare trust funds _ to a
parliamentary ``point of order.''
</P>
<P>
   Raising a point of order would mean that a majority of the
House, and at least 60 members of the Senate, would have to
specifically approve dipping into the trust funds.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said their action was a first step toward protecting
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   This bill ``will impose a discipline on us'' that will make it
difficult to break budget limits until Social Security is reformed,
said Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., a co-author of the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This puts us on the spot,'' he said. ``If we don't solve
Social Security, sooner or later this will bite us and bite us
bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said the bill was designed to help Republicans
politically by making it look like they were saving Social
Security. In reality, they say, the bill is weak because it does
nothing to extend Social Security beyond 2034, when the trust fund
is expected to be depleted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of making the tough decision to do something
substantial, my Republican colleagues are taking a pass,'' said
Rep. Joseph Moakley, D-Mass. ``Instead of acting, they are offering
this country this point of order which the Democrats already
enacted some 14 years ago, and which merely restates congressional
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Both parties voted overwhelmingly for the bill, with Republicans
claiming it would help and Democrats suggesting that it couldn't
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   During decades of federal deficits, the government has spent
Social Security _ and to a lesser extent, Medicare _ surpluses and
replaced them with IOUs in the form of special Treasury bonds. Now
that the budget is beginning to run a surplus _ still composed
primarily of Social Security reserves _ Republicans worry that the
extra money will also be spent unless it is locked away.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans argue that without their bill, President Clinton and
congressional Democrats would spend $138 billion from the surplus
over the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats argue that Clinton's plan _ to use 62 percent of the
surplus for Social Security reform, 15 percent for Medicare reform
and 12 percent for individual investment accounts _ will do more to
resolve Social Security's long-term problem than putting the money
is a parliamentary ``lock box'' that, they say, can be too easily
opened.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats note that the threshold is ridiculously low. Any bill
must have at least a majority of the House, and 60 votes in the
Senate is the margin any bill must attract to break a filibuster by
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   They also note that the lock box could be opened by declaring
any bill to be one that reformed Social Security or Medicare _
regardless of whether the bill actually strengthened those
program's financial situation.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Reischauer of the Brookings Institute, a former head of
the Congressional Budget Office, called the bill a ``statement of
intent that suggests we should be saving the Social Security
surplus. To the extent that's practical, that represents good
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Reischauer said that regardless of whether there is a lock
box, Social Security benefits will be paid. The question is how
hard it will be for the government to pay them.
</P>
<P>
   Both the lock box and the Clinton proposal would reduce the
federal debt. The surplus money would be used to offset marketable
Treasury bonds which would simply not be refinanced, according to
Reischauer.
</P>
<P>
   Lowering the debt now, government economists say, would make it
easier in the future to issue more Treasury bonds to finance Social
Security and Medicare benefits when the programs need the money.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
