<SLUG> BC-MA-POLITICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH QUERIES TEST TEXAS GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH AND FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The once-easy atmosphere in the Austin restaurant
began to grow tense as Alexander ``Sandy'' Tennant questioned
Governor George W. Bush of Texas about rumors concerning his
``youthful indiscretions'' and his hot temper.
</P>
<P>
   Tennant, former executive director of the Massachusetts
Republican Party, was part of a delegation of Massachusetts money
people who made the pilgrimage to meet the Republican presidential
front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   The others hadn't expected a question as direct as Tennant's,
and they listened nervously as the governor related that he had
already said what he planned to say about once having been, in his
oft-repeated words, ``young and irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have never been unfaithful to my wife, I haven't had a
drink in 10 years, and as far as I am concerned, it is a
non-issue,'' Bush declared emphatically, according to several
people who attended the late-March meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Bush said, he had faced those concerns in the 1994
Texas campaign in which he defeated Governor Ann Richards. All of
those issues had been brought up, and he had dealt with them all.
</P>
<P>
   From both mien and manner, Bush made it clear he didn't care to
discuss the issue further. Neither did the group of 30 or so
sitting around the table in the private room at Austin's tony
Shoreline Bar &AMP; Grill. Having winced through Tennant's question,
they were ready to move on.
</P>
<P>
   Now, to be sure, some Republican insiders worry there might be
more to the rumors, just the way Bill Clinton's backers did in
1992, when he assured them that reports about problems in his
personal life were nonsense. After all, one politico who has known
the Texas governor for years says Bush told him that before he
finally quit drinking, his tippling had gotten so bad that it came
to a point where he had ``to choose between Laura and Jack.'' Laura
is his wife; Jack as in Jack Daniels.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this was a meeting of basic Bush fans, more than a dozen
Massachusetts fund-raisers from the Weld/Cellucci operation who are
pulling together to help the Texas governor, plus some operatives
from Ohio and California. (Most of the Massachusetts group had
jetted down in the private plane of Richard Egan, chairman of EMC
Corp. of Hopkinton, Mass.)
</P>
<P>
   In short, they had come to praise George W., not to query him.
Which is why, if some were made uneasy by Tennant's first question,
they were even more nonplussed when Tennant pressed on. Some
remember him asking two pointed followups; others say there was
only one.
</P>
<P>
   But most everyone agrees that Tennant, a political pitbull,
wasn't about to drop the issue. Saying his own experience had
taught him the political opponents would never let the facts get in
the way of a good electoral argument, he insisted questions about
Bush's personal life and his temper would be the issues in the
presidential campaign. Are you going to be able to control
yourself, he wanted to know?
</P>
<P>
   By the time the exchange was over, Bush, sources say, was
staring daggers at Tennant, and some others in the room were
squirming in their seats. ``You mean, can I smile when a bunch of
jerks asks me questions?'' Bush asked, affecting an icy smile.
``The answer is yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Few at the table were left in doubt as to whom the Texas
governor considered the jerk asking importunate questions at this
particular moment.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, sources say, former Massachusetts governor
William F. Weld, obviously uncomfortable at Tennant's
cross-examination, tried to break the tension, quipping that if
Bush could handle Tennant, he could certainly finesse the press.
</P>
<P>
   Blunt though he may be, Tennant is also cagey. As executive
director of the Republican State Committee in late 1980s, he helped
conceive and execute the plan that revived the GOP as a force in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   And he knows firsthand the damage the allegations can do. In
1989 and 1990, he was a one-person battering ram assaulting the
Democratic bastion that Massachusetts politics had become.
</P>
<P>
   As the state's economy slid into recession, creating a fiscal
crisis, Tennant pounced on each new bit of bad news, citing it as
evidence of the ``waste, cronyism, and corruption'' the Democrats
had supposedly visited upon ``the working people of
Massachusetts.'' Abrasive and bombastic though he could be, Tennant
was so effective that when the Democratic Party searched for a new
executive director in 1991, they remembered the lesson, and looked
for someone _ they chose Steve Grossman _ who could offer an
equally tough critique of the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Tennant downplays the exchange. ``I am 110 percent
behind George Bush,'' he said. ``I was just raising what the
initial issues were in this campaign. I thought his answers were
very good.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, sources say Tennant has offered a more interesting
rationale when friends pressed him on why he had grilled Bush so
hard. He wanted to test Bush's composure; if the candidate couldn't
stay cool in front of a friendly group of Republicans at a private
lunch in Austin, what would he do under the white-hot glare of the
campaign klieg lights?
</P>
<P>
   Cast in that light, some conceded that, awkward though the
moment was, there may have been a method to Tennant's badness. For
if some of his fellow Bay State Republicans were uncomfortable
about Tennant's impromptu stress test, they were also left a little
uneasy about George W.'s smoldering response.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Frank Phillips and Scot Lehigh are members of the Globe's state
house bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
