A4907 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MASSCAP-BOS &LR;      05-28 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MASSCAP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T COUNT THIS DARK HORSE OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Once again, the hype is hot: Saturday's Massachusetts
Handicap at Suffolk Downs will be a match race between Bob
Baffert's Real Quiet and James Bond's Behrens. As usual, the hype
has a hole in it.
</P>
<P>
   For the fifth year in a row, to the amazement of many, Suffolk's
Lou Raffeto has schmoozed and cajoled and talked and persuaded the
connections of America's best horses to come to East Boston, this
year's prizes being Real Quiet and Behrens. But a third horse also
is here, inviting himself more or less, and that horse is Running
Stag. Remember his name.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Mitchell, Running Stag's trainer, was asked what his
strategy might be to dethrone America's kings of older racehorses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shoot them,'' replied Mitchell pithily.
</P>
<P>
   That comment was delivered from England, in an English accent
and in the familiar blunt English manner. And therein the tale.
</P>
<P>
   For the second year in a row, Running Stag has left Europe, as
so many Europeans have done, and for the familiar European reason _
to go after that easy money that's just piled on the streets of the
United States, there for the picking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a very, very versatile horse,'' said Mitchell.
``There aren't many horses racing who maybe are as good on the
grass as they are on the dirt. But he's shown that he is. We wanted
to try him on the dirt because he won our premier UK race on the
dirt (at Lingfield in 1998) very easily, and that's what set our
mind in motion.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray Cochrane, Running Stag's jockey in Europe, scoffed at this
idea, saying in England's Racing Post that Running Stag is better
suited to the ``righthanded'' (clockwise) racing that predominates
in Europe, not the ``lefthanded'' (counterclockwise) racing that is
an American staple.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a remark that Ray made hoping the horse would stay in
Europe and not come to America,'' Mitchell scoffed back. ``He was
trying to con me that he was better going righthanded because he
knows all the tracks in America are lefthanded.''
</P>
<P>
   Although it seems Running Stag is a Grade II horse at best _ a
notch below US Grade I winners Real Quiet and Behrens _ he made a
most respectable showing last year against America's best at the
time, Skip Away and Silver Charm. Specifically, Running Stag may
have run his best race in his first US race, as so many foreign
invaders do.
</P>
<P>
   That race was the Grade I Woodward Stakes at Belmont Park Sept.
19, when he was in the hunt and ran a credible third behind Skip
Away and Gentlemen. ``He came off the turn and he was breathing
right down Skip Away's neck,'' said Roger Teal, his assistant
trainer. ``And Ray took him to the inside and they said the inside
was slow. There was no way he was going to beat Skip Away, but he
might have finished a little closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Running Stag did not take to the mud in the Jockey Club Gold Cup
at Belmont Oct. 10 when Gentlemen and Skip Away dueled each other
suicidally, allowing Wagon Limit to upset the favorites.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in the Breeders' Cup Classic at Churchill Downs, Running
Stag finished seventh among 10 horses in the race won by Silver
Charm. Finally, in his fourth race in the United States, Running
Stag finished fourth in the Clark Handicap at Churchill in late
November, but only 1 1/2 lengths behind Silver Charm, the winner.
At least Running Stag proved he belongs on the same tracks as
America's best horses, even if he didn't threaten to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``He jumped a shadow in the Clark Handicap,'' said Teal.
``(Jockey) John Velasquez said he was very unlucky not to win the
Clark; he jumped the shadow about a furlong out.''
</P>
<P>
   Running Stag last ran May 8, finishing second in the Shergar
Stakes at England's Goodwood racetrack, ``and that was a good
second to Handsome Ridge, a Group II horse,'' said Mitchell. ``He's
ready and he's happy and he's big and he's bursting.''
</P>
<P>
   In his only other race this year, Running Stag finished seventh
in the $5 million Dubai World Cup in March, won by Almutawake over
the Americans Malek and Victory Gallop. But that race taught
Mitchell a lesson, and the man seems open-minded enough to realize
that maybe the Americans do know something about training horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were in Dubai with him, we would take him out on the
track in the morning, when the weather was nice,'' said Mitchell,
``and we would notice that (California trainer) Richard Mandella
would take his horse out at night. We thought this was so he would
be used to racing under the lights, but now we can see why he did
that. It was the humidity over there. When we took him out for the
race, the heat was really bothering him. He was in position
throughout the race but came up empty, and we think the heat played
a part in that.''
</P>
<P>
   (For sure, Mitchell said, Running Stag loves to travel. ``He's
an ace traveler,'' said the trainer, ``and he loves it. He puts his
feet up and watches the movie on the way over.'')
</P>
<P>
   There are great cultural battles between the rest of the world
and the US in most areas of life, but few seem as great as the
philosophical divide between the training of horses in Europe and
America. Americans snicker at the European style; Europeans scoff
at the American way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the stopwatch,'' said Teal, pointing to the greatest
divide between Old World and New. ``Every time that (American)
horse goes on the track, there's a stopwatch on him. And if he
doesn't do a certain time, that horse isn't worth much. Back home,
we ride the horses and we don't overtrain him. We'll get permission
to take him to tracks (where the horse will race) and work him
there, but we do not train him on the clock.''
</P>
<P>
   The other difference, Teal believes, ``is that Americans don't
see that a horse can be beat. Before a race, ``they just don't see
that a horse can lose. But horses don't run the same every race and
you cannot go there and say, like Skip Away last year (in the
Jockey Club Gold Cup), everyone was saying he can't be beat. And
people couldn't accept that Skip Away was beaten by Wagon Limit.''
</P>
<P>
   But the worst difference, said Teal, was how racegoers in
America react to a loss by the horse they fancy. ``They booed Skip
Away after the Breeders' Cup,'' he said, ``and we couldn't handle
that at all. We came back with our horse after the race, and there
were guys booing Skip Away. It was horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   On their second tour of American dirt, the Running Stag crowd
has also learned that perhaps an American jockey might be
beneficial for a race in America, so Cochrane was left at home to
ride his righthanded races. Shane Sellers, one of America's better
jockeys, will be aboard Running Stag.
</P>
<P>
   ``We originally wanted Velasquez because John rode him in the
Breeders' Cup and in the Clark Handicap, but John was committed to
ride in New York,'' said Teal. ``So we then asked for (Jerry)
Bailey, but he had commitments. But then Shane Sellers' agent
phoned up and we got Shane.''
</P>
<P>
   Running Stag is here because Mary Pitt, a Bostonian who is an
American correspondent for the Racing Post, was in England over the
winter and suggested to Mitchell that Boston might be a bit easier
for Running Stag than New York and there was this race in Boston
called the Massachusetts Handicap. And of course, money made in
Boston is just as spendable as money made in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But, said Teal with a laugh, ``we thought it'd be easier this
year'' than it was in 1998 running against Skip Away, Silver Charm,
and Gentlemen. But all the talk about a match race between Real
Quiet and Behrens is not irksome to the British.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes the pressure off us a little bit,'' said Teal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
