<HEADER>
A4913 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-28 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIAMONDS ARE HIS PASSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; He is out there somewhere, off in some corner of this vast
cocktail bar called America, doing what he does best, or at least
most _ tossing back a Bud tallboy, delighting over a plate of
nachos, informing a stranger that his bachelor party is an
uninspired disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   His name? Stephen Pecevich. His home: South Boston. His goal?
Visit every Major League Baseball stadium on the continent in May
and June, dollars and sense be damned.
</P>
<P>
   Some people take spiritual journeys to pray in the Holy Land,
kneel in the Vatican, or absorb the wonders of history along the
Great Wall of China. Pecevich, 35, is a spirit of a slightly
different sort, evidenced in this e-mail dispatch from Atlanta's
Turner Field this month: ``Beer? Stands everywhere. Lines NOWHERE.
I almost felt obliged to order a beer at each stand I passed.''
</P>
<P>
   His is a journey not of faith but of hope _ hope for an
old-fashioned pitcher's duel, hope for the perfect ballyard hot
dog, hope for an uncommonly cold draught beer. All the while, he
e-mails his thoughts and experiences daily to friends and saves his
notes for posterity _ and possibly a book.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   April 30. South Boston. At sunrise, I went to my roofdeck for
motivation and I sang, in this order, America the Beautiful, God
Bless America, The National Anthem and Take Me Out to the Ballgame.
I was officially on my way now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Thursday found him in Milwaukee, at County Stadium, watching an
afternoon game between the Brewers and the Atlanta Braves. Tomorrow
brings him to Chicago, where he will sit with friends in the famed
Wrigley Field bleachers and watch the Cubs and Sammy Sosa face the
St. Louis Cardinals and Mark McGwire. As of today, he is 17
stadiums into a 30-park crusade that will end with a hero's welcome
at Fenway on June 26.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he has caught a foul ball and received a standing
ovation at Pro Player Stadium in Miami, narrowly avoided a cable
car crash in San Francisco, and drunk an afternoon away with a
trucker at the Anheuser-Busch plant in St. Louis. He has had a
cabdriver confess an extramarital affair to him, swum with a cell
phone in his pocket, seen his laptop driven to Tucson without him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   May 5, St. Louis. As I was finishing my meal, a group of nuns
were seated beside me. As their conversation evolved, I had to
procrastinate. Topics ranged from the ``Independence of
Sisterhood'' to the ``Mother House not allowing them to wear slacks
or hosiery,'' to one nun stating that ``balsamic vinaigrette gives
me a buzz'' _ after which she ordered that specific dressing for
her salad. That's one crazy nun.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All in all, he confides, he's a little worse for the wear. ``It
is killing me,'' he says on the phone from Milwaukee. ``I can't
wait to go home and not eat. The point for the book is that I'm
trying to find the best places to eat. I order everything at the
park.''
</P>
<P>
   Is he normal? ``Well, no,'' says Stephen Flynn, one of his best
friends. ``He's crazy,'' says his wife of two years, Cathy.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, crazy like a fox. He's a venture capitalist, Quincy born
and Catholic school bred, who made his fortune early and knows how
to enjoy it often. He is a patron of Catholic Charities, a former
baseball player at Holy Cross, a bon vivant who has persuaded a
sainted wife to bless this singular trek.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   May 25. San Diego. Our first stop inside Qualcomm Stadium was
not the game, but Randy's Ribs. When they handed me my order, I
thought the picnic table would fall over like Fred Flintstone's
car. For the next 15 minutes, there was silence. Two men on a
mission. As long as neither of us put our hands near the other's
mouth, we were out of harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His favorite stadiums so far: The Ballpark at Arlington, Bank
One Ballpark in Phoenix, and Coor's Field in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   The stodgier among us will roll their eyes in condescension.
They will decry the money _ 15 to 20 large, by his estimate _ spent
on what amounts to a two-month version of ``Ferris Bueller's Day
Off.'' They will read his daily dispatches _ ``Next stop,
Killebrew's Blues, a bar that served its purpose (as well as
Jagermeister)'' _ and relegate him to the status of eternal frat
boy.
</P>
<P>
   But they miss the point. He is not just seeing the parks, but
meeting the people in them. He is not only living the moment, but
celebrating a life. He is not merely a man on a mission, but a
living excuse for anyone in need of a break. As we kick off the
summer, practice these words: ``For God sakes, honey, all I want to
do is go to one lousy game. It's not like I'm this guy Pec who left
for two months straight.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
