<HEADER>
A4916 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLEEPWALK-TRIAL-1-AZR     05-28 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWALK-TRIAL-1-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPWALKING TRIAL BEGINS: WIFE STABBED 44 TIMES, DROWNED  
 (ADV: FIRST OF FOUR STORIES RECOUNTING WEEK'S TRIAL ACTION) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By VICTORIA HARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Scott Falater, known to all as a loving husband, went
berserk one night when his wife made the fatal mistake of
interrupting him while he was sleepwalking, his attorney said
Monday in Maricopa County Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``He immediately went into a rage, a total frenzy, and stabbed
her 44 times,'' lawyer Michael Kimerer told the jury during the
opening of Falater's murder trial Monday (May 24) before Judge
Ronald Reinstein.
</P>
<P>
   With a knife and flashlight in hand, he likely was drawn to
their broken pool pump while in a deep sleep state, Kimerer said.
Falater had been trying to fix the pump before he went to bed,
Kimerer said, and his mind likely was still fretting over it.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Yarmila, must have come outside from the den where she
had been watching television, Kimerer said. Maybe she tapped him on
the shoulder. Maybe she asked him what he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   But county prosecutor Juan Martinez believes the killing was
premeditated. He's seeking the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Falater, an engineer, family man and leader in his church, was
too deliberate and calculating in his movements to kill his wife,
then cover up his crime, Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He began stabbing her over and over and over and over again,''
Martinez said. ``She went down to the ground and he continued to
stab her in the back.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't like she didn't struggle or scream, Martinez said.
Self-defense wounds were found on her hands. Neighbors heard
Yarmila's screams for up to 30 minutes before the sounds turned
into low groans.
</P>
<P>
   And if stabbing her was not enough, Martinez said, Falater
dragged her to their backyard pool, pushed her in and held her head
down with both hands.
</P>
<P>
   But first, he went in the house to change clothes and clean up,
he said. Falater packed the knife, an athletic mouthpiece that had
his saliva on it, boots and his bloody clothes in a plastic
container. He stuck it in a garbage bag before hiding it in the
wheel well of his Volvo hatchback.
</P>
<P>
   A neighbor peeking over their adjoining fence watched Falater as
he walked through the house, turning lights on and off, then going
down to the kitchen to wash his hands.
</P>
<P>
   The neighbor, Greg Koons, testified Monday that Falater even
opened the sliding-glass door to signal his dog to lie down. At one
point, Falater spun around toward the fence as if he heard a sound
from where Koons stood, concealed by a large pine tree, Koons said.
</P>
<P>
   Falater stood still for about five to 10 seconds before
returning to the house.
</P>
<P>
   Koons testified that he stayed put to see Falater come back
outside to finish off his wife in the swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   Those are not the movements of a sleepwalker, Martinez told the
jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``This individual here . . . in a sense baptized his wife,
Yarmila Falater, into the afterlife,'' said Martinez, referring to
Falater's Mormon beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   As Martinez recounted the gruesome details, Falater's face
remained blank. At times during the hearing, he dropped his head,
his eyes downcast. But his face never showed any emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a gray suit, he looked less frail than in previous court
hearings when he wore jailhouse stripes and handcuffs. He smiled
and waved to friends who were in court Monday to show their
support.
</P>
<P>
   His attorney, Kimerer, spoke at length about Falater's love for
his wife and family. The two met while sophomores in high school,
later married and had two children.
</P>
<P>
   They devoted their lives to family, church and home, he said.
Under their guidance, their children excelled. Their daughter was
the valedictorian of her graduating class this year; their son, a
straight-A student.
</P>
<P>
   Yarmila was a talented artist and president of the state chapter
of a basketweaving association.
</P>
<P>
   Falater, 44, was a member of his church stake's high council.
</P>
<P>
   The couple had no financial problems. He and Yarmila shared the
same religion, the same politics. They never fought. They always
sat down and discussed any problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But all was not idyllic.
</P>
<P>
   Court records show that Yarmila was depressed at times about not
having a career in nursing. She was not as happy with the Mormon
church as her husband. He had joined it first. She later. He wanted
more children. She did not.
</P>
<P>
   Kimerer, meanwhile, insists there was no motive for the slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Sleepwalking is the only explanation for the killing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a senseless crime. There was no reason for it,'' he
said in court. ``There was no reason why Scott Falater would kill
the woman he loved more than anything else in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not as farfetched as it sounds, to kill while under the
dark spell of sleepwalking, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He listed several homicides committed by sleepwalkers, including
a man who was disturbed while sleeping in his car by two young
women wanting a ride. He drove off, turned around, hit one of the
girls with his car, then turned around and hit her again, killing
her, Kimerer said.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the French detective who was assigned to a
homicide case only to discover he was the person who had killed the
victim while sleepwalking.
</P>
<P>
   Falater also fits the profile of a sleepwalker who can become
violent, Kimerer said.
</P>
<P>
   Not only do he and his family have a history of sleepwalking,
sleep-talking and bed-wetting, Falater was in the state of mind
that is typical of sleepwalkers who become violent, Kimerer said.
</P>
<P>
   They are usually male, under stress and have trouble sleeping,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Falater had been living for days on little sleep and was under
tremendous stress from his job at the time of the killing, Kimerer
said. A new computer chip was a failure. He was worried he would
have to lay off the employees he loved and who loved him in return,
Kimerer said.
</P>
<P>
   He is calling three national sleep disorder experts who will
testify that Falater was not aware of what he was doing that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did it without any consciousness,'' Kimerer said. ``In
fact, his brain was asleep.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Victoria Harker can be reached at victoria.harker(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
