r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REVIEW-DIVORCE-H     05-28 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-DIVORCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM TAKES A RIVETING LOOK AT DIVORCE IN IRAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Divorce by any other name is still a divorce. Ugly, volatile,
nasty, inevitable. The circumstances don't matter _ divorce stinks,
especially if you happen to be a woman looking for one in Iran.
</P>
<P>
   With harrowing conviction, Kim Longinotto and Ziba Mir-Hosseini
unfurl an incensing reel of D-I-V-O-R-C-E candids, in which a
country's judicial system and religious customs conspire against
its unhappily _ no, miserably _ wedded women, keeping them in
loveless, sexless relationships because it's what the man wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Divorce Iranian Style,'' which was runner-up for the audience
award at this year's San Francisco International Film Festival,
chafes with outrage over the sexism rampant in Iranian society.
</P>
<P>
   What begins at first as a grainy, possibly academic (read:
patronizing) anthropological study in an ``otherized'' culture
quickly evolves into a document of vexing (and vexed) immediacy.
</P>
<P>
   That single camera perched adjacent to the judge's bench remains
there for most of the film, and the things it sees defy anything
you've seen in ``Divorce Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Women fill the closet-size courtroom with their weeping,
pleading and conniving to be liberated from dismal misalliances in
front of old, incredulous judges resolved to play conspirator to
oppression by not finding ways to evade the bureaucracy and
circumvent the laws that side almost exclusively with the husband.
When a court clerk's daughter climbs into the judge's chair and
starts emphatically presiding over an imaginary case, the film just
grows downright despondent with the impossibility of that girl, or
any woman, legally granting divorces.
</P>
<P>
   Had Longinotto and Mir-Hosseini, who's also an Iranian
anthropologist, just shown us a few pitiful, distraught wives
desperate for the single life, the film would have veered into the
sort of the hands-off, souped-up, victim-as-subject dramamentaries
that Christiane Amanpour uses to bring that urgent, crunchy center
to the occasionally candy-coated ``60 Minutes.'' Many of the women
shown in ``Divorce'' are as self-empowered as they are victimized,
greedy as they are desperate.
</P>
<P>
   All Tina Turner wanted in her iconic split from Ike was her name
_ at least that's what she told Kurt Loder in ``I, Tina.'' A couple
of the wives in this film want to break up all the way to bank.
They're backed by an arbitration process that grants them a $10,000
marriage gift if given a divorce. But the provision floats before
them like a bachelorette mirage they'll never get their hands on _
or they'll get so disgusted with the procedure that they'll
renounce any interest in monetary or proprietary consolation prizes
just to be single again.
</P>
<P>
   The film is careful in its display of the assortment of husbands
as well. An abusive father beseeches his family to believe that his
cruelty will end once the divorce request is dropped, while his
unmoved wife expresses her doubt off-camera, presumably to the
filmmakers. Another attempted divorce makes it to arbitration, a
limbo for dead marriages, and during a settlement palaver held over
an argumentative family tea, the camera repeatedly lands on the
dejected face of the husband who's been whittled down to his wick
by the enveloping pettiness.
</P>
<P>
   But in the scheme of things, it's fury that compels Longinotto
and Mir-Hosseini to leave their fingerprints on the trajectory of
the fate of Maryam, a woman whose husband accuses her of destroying
a court order _ an offense that could land her in jail. When Maryam
turns to the filmmakers to corroborate her innocence, they do,
knowing minutes before that she'd giddily confessed to them that
she had torn it up. It's a riveting, rule-breaking violation in
which a little white lie is an unpronounced but searing moment of
truth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
