<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4920 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARTUP-EXPERIENCE-AR     05-28 1277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARTUP-EXPERIENCE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG ENTREPRENEURS CALLING ON VETERANS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Andrew Perlman and Mark Land formed Cignal Global
Communications in 1995, they expected to run the operation
themselves, adding technical and management talent as they grew.
</P>
<P>
   One major problem: Perlman, then 19, and Land, 20, both college
dropouts, had lots of energy and determination but no business
experience. While they managed to launch a low-cost overseas phone
service using Internet technology, they were quickly running out of
$1 million in capital from a private investor and a close friend's
father.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just about gone,'' said Perlman, citing a series of
mistakes and the defections of several managers who left once the
money started running out.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Christopher Rooney, 58, former president of Global One, a
consortium of Sprint International, Deutsche Telecom and France
Telecom, who became Cignal Global's chief executive last May and
helped stabilize the fledgling company.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their technological know-how, great ideas, and big
ambitions, entrepreneurs in their 20s are discovering that they
still need older, experienced executives to provide business focus,
credibility, and management leadership to help a start-up succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors looking to bring in adult supervision is not an
uncommon scenario,'' said Charles A. Polachi, office managing
partner of the executive search firm Heidrick &AMP; Struggles/Fenwick
Partners in Lexington. The firm seeks out chief executives who will
earn between $150,000 and $300,000 and could own up to 10 percent
of a young company's equity.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with younger and younger entrepreneurs who have often
spent 10 years with computers and are technically savvy, plus the
huge flows of venture capital money,'' he said, ``the need for an
experienced CEO who can provide leadership along with marketing,
sales and brand awarenesss has never been greater.''
</P>
<P>
   And these business leaders _ some of whom serve as mentors to
their younger colleagues and others who are viewed as father
figures _ are in big demand. In New England alone, Polachi said,
there are about 50 chief executive openings, of which about half
are for start-ups with young founders.
</P>
<P>
   Wellie Chao knew from the start he needed a chief executive with
a consumer marketing background. Along with two others, he formed
Crimson Solutions, an on-line job placement service for new college
graduates, while the three were still students at Harvard College.
</P>
<P>
   One of Crimson's early investors met Sharon Whiteley at a
conference and persuaded her to meet with Chao and his team.
Whiteley was instrumental in putting pushcarts in Faneuil Hall
Marketplace nearly 23 years ago, and since then had formed and run
four companies in specialty retailing and consumer product
manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never worked with entrepreneurs this young,'' said Whiteley,
now 50 and chief executive of the 18-employee Boston-based
start-up, which recently received $3 million in venture capital
financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is like the Wild, Wild West, and I was drawn to
it, along with a true appreciation for the entrepreneurial
spirit,'' said Whiteley. ``Entrusting an outsider with your dream
and vision is something I know and am very respectful of.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Perlman and Land of Cignal Global realized they
needed help after several rejections from venture capital companies
questioned their lack of experience. Finally, New York-based
investment banker Spencer Trask agreed to put up $10 million under
one major condition: that they build a management team led by a
seasoned telecommunications executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really did not know where to look for one,'' recalled Land,
who before starting Cignal Global wanted to create a carpet
business for students living in the Washington University
dormitories.
</P>
<P>
   Once the word got out, Perlman was flooded with phone calls and
e-mails. But when prospective candidates learned how young the
controlling shareholders were, they bowed out. Others could not
keep pace with Cignal Global's ambitious growth plans.
</P>
<P>
   But Perlman remembered attending a telecom conference at which
Christopher Rooney spoke, and he had been impressed. So when
Rooney's name emerged, he having left Global One, Perlman made an
all-out effort to recruit him, including persistently calling his
home in Fredericksburg, Va. But his calls were not returned.
Finally, Perlman reached Rooney's wife by phone and pleaded his
case that Cignal Global was the company her husband needed to run
after spending a career at big corporations and stuffy
bureaucracies.
</P>
<P>
   ``She made the pitch for us, and thanks to her he returned our
phone calls,'' said Perlman. He and Land each talked to Rooney to
get a grasp of his management style, knowledge of networking
software, and family (seven grown children in a still strong
35-year marriage).
</P>
<P>
   ``They basically said to me, `We have gone this far, recognize
we cannot go much further, and feel you can help us,' which is
quite different than what you hear from flesh-peddling
headhunters,'' said Rooney, who before entering the
telecommunications field spent 20 years in the Marine Corps.
</P>
<P>
   But no sooner did they meet Rooney than the Cignal founders
began to have reservations about their future leader, fearing his
Marine career and experience at a large telecommunications company
would make him too rigid to lead an entrepreneurial company.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military background scared us,'' said Neal Isaacson, 37,
the company's chief financial officer, who remembers a Sunday
afternoon walk with Perlman and Land during which they discussed
whether they were making a mistake hiring Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   After several more meetings and a dinner with Rooney and his
wife in Boston, Land and Perlman offered Rooney a competitive
salary, stock options totaling about 5 percent of the company, and
an unusually long, five-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, a key question was: Could the young founders adapt to
having a leadership style within an organization that would be
other than their own?'' said Rooney.
</P>
<P>
   Rooney _ after learning that two of the young founders still
rode their mountain bikes to work and listened to their mothers _
cautiously accepted, with a stipulation that that there be a trial
period to determine if everyone could work together.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting on three Friday afternoons, they discussed business
issues and company progress to gauge how the relationship was
going. Soon both sides felt comfortable, and Rooney and his wife
relocated to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now see his military background as an asset in providing
structure to a young company,'' said Land. ``He is focused on
getting tasks done, and he gives us latitude to build out for the
future. I am thrilled to have him on board.''
</P>
<P>
   Perlman agreed, noting Cignal Global has added such big
customers as Harvard University, Thermo Electron Corp., the
Christian Science Monitor, and Sprint Canada. He predicts revenues
will reach $25 million this year. Rooney, however, is more
cautious, forecasting $15 million to $20 million in revenues.
</P>
<P>
   And while Perlman could be the most promising tycoon from his
Newton (Mass.) South High School class of 1993, potentially
following the famous footsteps of Bill Gates and Michael Dell, his
mother still hounds him about when he'll finish college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing it a little less nowadays,'' Perlman said with a
smile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
