<HEADLINE>
HUSBAND `CALM' AT SCENE OF MURDER  
 (ADV: SECOND OF FOUR STORIES RECOUNTING WEEK'S TRIAL ACTION) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY JERRY KAMMER and VICTORIA HARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Scott Falater, who says he was sleepwalking when he
killed his wife, appeared strangely ``confused and calm'' a few
minutes after the bloody attack at the couple's Phoenix home, an
emergency medical technician testified Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked to me kind of in a daze and was acting kind of
confused,'' said John J. Nettles Jr., a defense witness in the
Maricopa County Superior Court murder trial that has drawn
nationwide attention.
</P>
<P>
   Nettles was on the crew of Phoenix firefighters that sought to
aide Yarmila Falater after her husband stabbed her 44 times and
dragged her into the backyard pool.
</P>
<P>
   Nettles, who estimated that he has responded to 200 homicides in
his 10-year career, said he was struck by Scott Falater's atypical
calm after the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't match up to me _ from what I'd seen outside _ that
this person had just done this,'' Nettles said. He said assailants
in such bloody attacks are normally ``sweating, pumped up'' and
agitated.
</P>
<P>
   Nettles' description contradicted testimony Monday from a
Phoenix policeman who described Scott Falater as out of breath, as
if he had just finished a physical workout.
</P>
<P>
   County prosecutor Juan Martinez aggressively challenged Nettles'
account. He suggested that the murder scene was too tense and
turbulent for Nettles to have given careful attention to Falater's
demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your attention was more geared to what you were doing, wasn't
it?'' Martinez asked.
</P>
<P>
   Nettles held his ground. ``We are taught to be aware of our
surroundings because we are in the middle of a violence incident,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor also challenged Nettles' testimony that Falater
had asked, ``What's going on here? Where's my wife? What's
happening?''
</P>
<P>
   But Nettles insisted he had either heard Falater's expressions
of confusion or had heard another firefighter repeat the questions
in a post-incident discussion designed to help the firefighters
deal with their stress.
</P>
<P>
   Nettles recollection in court squared with testimony of the
Phoenix police officer who arrested Falater. ``He said `What's
wrong? What's going on?' '' Officer Kemp Layden testified.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez then pursued questions that aimed to show that Nettles
was sympathetic to Falater. Nettles acknowledged that he and
Falater are members of the same Mormon stake and that his son had
received math tutoring from Falater's daughter, Megan. But Nettles
also said that he had never seen Scott Falater before that bloody
evening.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor also attempted to undermine Nettles' credibility
by reacting skeptically to the firefighter's claim that he didn't
know the murder victim was Yarmila Falater until the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   Defending his inability to recognize the victim, Nettles said,
``Let's put it this way. When somebody's alive, sometimes they put
off a different look than when they're in that state.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Falater, 44, an engineer, showed emotion for the first
time in trial Tuesday. He dabbed at at his eyes as the county
medical examiner described Yarmila's wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorneys are expected to call some of Falater's friends
and relatives to testify this week that Falater has strong
character and that the couple had a loving marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Michael Kimerer has told jurors that Yarmila
was the ``only woman'' Scott had ever known.
</P>
<P>
   But court records and statements made in pretrial hearings
indicate that strains had developed in their 20-year marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Although the two were virgins when they married, Yarmila went to
the medical office in 1990 and discovered she had a sexually
transmitted disease, Martinez said at a pretrial hearing Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez asked Judge Ronald S. Reinstein to allow a medical
worker to testify that when Yarmila asked how she got the disease,
the worker replied that Falater was probably cheating on her.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Reinstein, however, refused to allow the witness to
testify during the trial, saying the incident was so long ago, it
could not be considered a motive for murder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
