<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BACKSTREET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKSTREET BOYS' ``MILLENNIUM'' JIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   That high-pitched wail you hear isn't the new Backstreet Boy.
It's the sound of Garth Brooks spilling tears in his beer over
having his record for opening-week album sales toppled by five
pretty boys from Florida. The Backstreet Boys' new CD
``Millennium'' released last Tuesday, sold 1,133,505 copies in its
first week of release. That beats the country superstar's record of
1,085,373 in first-week sales, set late last year for Brooks'
``Double Live'' CD.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millennium'' moved an astounding half a million copies the
first day of release. Which means that plenty of people are moved
by the Backstreet Boys. Most of them are young, female, and
floating in that ether-like state of pubescent delirium where cute
boys who can sing inspire a passion of frightening proportions. And
don't the Boys know it. There's a theme to this project: ``It's
Gotta Be You,'' ``I Need You Tonight,'' ``Don't Wanna Lose You
Now,'' ``Back To Your Heart,'' ``No One Else Comes Close.'' And
that's not even the half of it.
</P>
<P>
   Wisely opting not to mess with a winning formula (imagine if
they'd made a go at credibility), the Boys roll out tender
heartbreakers and R&AMP;B-Lite tracks that play like shiny new toys hot
off the assembly line. With the help of Swedish hit-meister Max
Martin (Britney Spears), the Boys follow the buffed-to-a-glow dots
to the lowest common dance-pop denominator. In other words, there
is nothing even remotely inventive about these tunes.
</P>
<P>
   That said, the Backstreet Boys bring it off with irresistible,
pristine, teen-idol style. You can almost see the billowing smoke
and flashing lights as the album's opening cut, ``Larger Than
Life,'' rotates like prime cut on its swaggering, synthesized axis.
That's followed by ``I Want It That Way,'' a sleek,
acoustic-guitar-based love song that courses along,
meandering-river-like, in eternal midtempo.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the album generally toggles back and forth between
the two models _ a Spanish flourish here, a bona-fide rock riff
there _ anchored by the sweet, tight harmonies that power this
speeding train. As far as lyrics go, suffice it to say the themes
are simple and self-evident (see song titles), with the exception
of ``The Perfect Fan,'' which is about _ and this should seal the
Boys' destiny as every good little girl's dream date _ none other
than their moms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 1349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4927 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BORAS-2TAKES-SPI &LR;      05-28 1575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BORAS-2TAKES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAL MAKER, DEAL BREAKER
 &HT;    WITH SUPERAGENT BORAS BY HIS SIDE, ALEX RODRIGUEZ FACES FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Almost as soon as it happened, the richest contract in
baseball history _ $105 million! Seven years! _ was old news.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Boras, the agent who had secured it from the Los Angeles
Dodgers for pitcher Kevin Brown, stepped away from the podium at
the winter meetings in Nashville. The press conference was breaking
up, and it was time for follow-up questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There must have been 100 reporters,'' Boras recalled recently
at his office in Irvine, Calif. ``First question, `What's Alex
Rodriguez worth?' The ink wasn't dry on Kevin Brown, and the focus
was Alex.''
</P>
<P>
   Boras called Rodriguez that night. It was incredible where the
market had gone, he told Rodriguez, who suspected that his agent
had surprised even himself. Boras advised the Mariners shortstop to
be prepared: His future was becoming an issue before it had even
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, when the Mariners struggled early this season,
trading Rodriguez became the latest solution. He can't possibly
re-sign when his contract comes up after the 2000 season, the
thinking went _ not with Ken Griffey Jr. due the same year, not in
this market, not with that agent.
</P>
<P>
   But trade A-Rod? It's not as easy as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alex may be the most difficult player to trade in major league
history,'' Boras said. ``The Mariners, to trade him, are going to
want what? Not one, not two, maybe three premium young players,
established major league players, a whole package of things. What's
the other team going to require? A contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is, if it came to that, Alex would have to want to
sign and do something and go, so it's really going to boil down to
Alex's decision anyway. So when you say you can trade the player, I
would say, not unless you're going to really trade Alex for
something that is wholly below his marketplace, because that team
isn't going to give that much unless they knew they could sign him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're this good, you control the steering, the brake and
the gas pedal of this car. I really believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez hears the trade talk _ which amounts not so much to
rumors as to opinions and predictions _ and said he's surprised by
how little it bothers him. In the third year of a four-year, $10.6
million contract, he's not only secure for life, but secure in his
conviction that whatever happens, he's done right by Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I've been good to this city, I know this city's been
good to me and I have a clean conscience,'' Rodriguez said. ``I've
had a great time here and I really, sincerely want the best for
Seattle. And if it's going to take a championship team to get me
out of here, then that's what I want for Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can go somewhere else and help another team, but if they can
go out and get three good pitchers for me or two good pitchers and
a young shortstop or whatever, that's fine. I just know, what I
feel most great about is they've only invested $11 million in me,
and I would have played six years here and given them a lot for
their money.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have said all along they will not trade Rodriguez
this year, and will resume talks on a contract extension this
winter. No offers have been made, but when they met with Boras
during spring training, the Mariners tried to convey how much
Rodriguez means to their future, and how much they respect him.
</P>
<P>
   That message came through, said Boras, who expects such respect
to be ``the foundation to a good negotiation.'' When the Mariners
said they intend to re-sign Rodriguez, that told Boras they believe
they have the money.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, everything will depend on how the Mariners'
assessment of the market matches Boras'. Only now, Boras said, is
he beginning to seriously prepare, searching for comparable players
throughout history, getting a gauge on exactly why Rodriguez is so
valuable.
</P>
<P>
   And when Scott Boras goes to work, that's when things get
interesting.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXXX
</P>
<P>
   When Jerry Colangelo came into baseball, the Arizona
Diamondbacks chairman learned about Boras by way of comparison.
Colangelo, who also owns the NBA's Phoenix Suns, was told that
Boras was the ``David Falk of baseball,'' a reference to the agent
for Michael Jordan, Patrick Ewing and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``My attitude toward Scott Boras was, if we're going to be
successful in our business, we're going to need to develop a
relationship with Scott Boras,'' Colangelo said. ``He represents a
number of players in the league that could somewhere, somehow have
a real impact on us. And that was true.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Colangelo's team ever threw a pitch, it threw significant
dollars at three Boras clients. Before its inaugural season last
year, Arizona signed shortstop Jay Bell, pitcher Andy Benes and
catcher Jorge Fabregas, who got a two-year deal immediately after
losing to the Diamondbacks in arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   There is no denying Boras' influence on the industry. His cause
celebre is the draft, where he has represented five No. 1 overall
picks and memorable holdout J.D. Drew. His often drawn-out
negotiations and industry-rocking demands cause scouts to warn
players against choosing him. Boras believes the draft is behind
much of the venom directed at him, like the headline on a New York
Times profile calling him ``The Most Hated Man In Baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Boras knows that comes with the territory, but the 46-year-old
still chafes at the characterization. He was, he said, an Illinois
farmboy with nothing who has built a life from the game.
</P>
<P>
   A former infielder/outfielder, Boras still wears a ring Stan
Musial gave him for winning the minor league player of the year
award in the Cardinals' organization in 1976. When his four-year
career ended in 1977, Boras earned a doctorate in industrial
pharmacology and a law degree at the University of the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   A class on contract law led him back to baseball, and his first
clients were Mariners pitcher Bill Caudill and Cleveland infielder
Mike Fischlin, both former teammates. His company now employs 24
people, including several former major leaguers, a former NASA
computer engineer and a sports psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   Boras gets his infamy from the draft, but he makes his money in
the majors. His 41 major-league clients will make nearly $100
million this year, and include some of the game's top players. Five
percent of those earnings _ a common commission for agents _ comes
to roughly $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows what every athlete makes, but no one knows what
an owner makes,'' Boras said. ``And as long as that stands that
way, the villain will rest in this chair. I tell my clients, that's
my job. Don't worry about that. My job is to make sure that you are
able to focus, that you are comfortable and that you will be
received in the (proper) manner. If I'm held accountable for being
this perceived greedy, money-oriented person, so be it. You and I
both know who I really am.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariners first baseman David Segui thought he knew who Boras was
before Rodriguez introduced them over lunch last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so different from the public perception,'' Segui said.
``Before I knew him, I didn't like him. People say he's greedy and
arrogant, but he's the complete opposite of that. He's the most
down-to-earth, respectful guy, and he loves and respects the game
of baseball. That's very important. He believes in playing the game
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing that impressed Segui, he said, was that Boras
didn't talk about money at their first meeting. That would come
soon enough, after Segui fired his agent and hired Boras.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very good at being able to forsee market changes,'' said
Segui, a free agent-to-be who turned down a three-year offer worth
about $12 million from the Mariners this spring. ``You know you're
going to get what you're worth.''
</P>
<P>
   Fischlin, who works for Boras out of Georgia, said Boras
routinely works until 2 or 3 in the morning and has every contract
in the majors committed to memory. He lives in the numbers, both
financial and statistical, and his preparation is legendary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very hard worker, and he out-works most other agents,''
said Roger Jongewaard, the M's vice president for scouting and
player development, who has wrangled with Boras several times.
``He's very aggressive, and he's been very successful. He's taught
me a lot, that leverage is everything, that without a deadline,
nothing gets done. He uses the things that work best for him to the
fullest.''
</P>
<P>
   His ability to wait and wear down makes Boras successful, if not
popular with teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in a lot of instances, Scott creates more of an
adversarial relationship with clubs than some other agents do,''
said Philadelphia Phillies general manager Ed Wade, whose team
drafted Drew, then lost him after a year-long contract dispute.
``It's not at all times and it's not in every circumstance, but the
fact of the matter is, sometimes when negotiations are concluded,
there are some ill feelings between Scott and the club.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what Boras' clients want.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you rather go to war with a poodle or a bulldog?'' said
Boston Red Sox catcher Jason Varitek, who held out for a year
before signing his first contract. ``He's a bulldog; I chose the
bulldog.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
