<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-THIRTEENTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THIRTEENTH FLOOR' TAKES UNLUCKY LEAP INTO THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE THIRTEENTH FLOOR 
Directed by: Josef Rusnak 
Screenplay by: Rusnak, Ravel Centeno-Rodriguez (based on Daniel
Galouye's novel, ``Simulacron 3'') 
Starring: Craig Bierko, Gretchen Mol, Vincent D'Onofrio, Dennis
Haysbert, Steven Schub, Armin Mueller-Stahl 
Running time: 120 minutes 
Rated: R (violence and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vintage LA, circa 1937, steals ``The Thirteenth Floor,'' an
overwrought but underwritten sci-fi item that could have been a
witty metaphor for movies driven by special effects morphing, but
plummets pretty quickly out of contention. The subject of
make-believe universes has been pretty much exhausted for the
moment by ``The Matrix'' and``eXistenZ'' conceptually, and by
``Dark City'' visually, and this earnest but hopelessly foursquare
and depressingly humorless effort doesn't take it anywhere new.
About the best that can be said is that it begins promisingly, with
an elegantly dressed Armin Mueller-Stahl making his way through art
deco LA until he runs into trouble.
</P>
<P>
   We soon learn that he's a virtual reality guru inhabiting a
simulated universe of his own invention. Before long, his
assistant, played by Craig Bierko, stretches out on a table in the
mastermind's present-day downtown skyscraper, rolls into a sort of
CAT scan device, and beams himself back to 1937 to find out what
went wrong. We don't know it yet, but the best part of the film is
about over. It peaks after Bierko's searcher rides down La Cienega
Boulevard, with the HOLLYWOOD sign at his back, past uninhabited
hills dotted with oil derricks. When he gets back to the present,
he tells his aide, played by Vincent D'Onofrio, that the
simulations are good but the colorization is still a little off.
</P>
<P>
   It's true, it's amusing, and it's the only part of the film
that's amazing. It's not just that the color is off, it's the way
in which it's off. The views of prewar LA we see are essentially
sepia-toned, as if they've been lifted off old postcards and
crudely colorized in the way that postcards of the time were. A lot
of the action takes place in a stylish old invented hotel. And the
simulated world is inhabited by dead ringers from the present.
Bierko's character is a bank clerk. Mueller-Stahl's is a Pasadena
bookseller. And D'Onofrio's is a bartender who sneaks a look at a
letter and becomes enraged when he learns he's not real, but only a
character in a game. There's also a tres '30s femme fatale, played
by Gretchen Mol, and a murder.
</P>
<P>
   Mueller-Stahl emerges with dignity, even as the script seems to
evaporate around him, and D'Onofrio, that most versatile and
underappreciated of actors, finds ways to jolt the angry
bartender's role to life. But Bierko is a blank and Moll brings
only her iconographic looks to the table _ and nothing much else.
What are supposed to be love scenes between them are embarrassingly
devoid of anything even remotely suggesting vital impulse, which
guarantees that the already weak ending is a total letdown. ``The
Thirteenth Floor'' looks great, at least when it stays in the past,
and especially when the bartender sees the truth. But it
self-destructs in the present, which mostly unfolds in a cavernous
penthouse with all sorts of money for decor but none for lighting,
to judge by the absence of candlepower. As for the future, ``The
Thirteenth Floor'' has no future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 1351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 13:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4929 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BORAS-2NDTAKE-SPI     05-28 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BORAS-2NDTAKE-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE: ``I chose the bulldog.''
</P>
<P>
   So did Rodriguez, whom Boras first spotted at a tournament in
Monterrey, Mexico, when Rodriguez was 14. The two met a year later,
before Rodriguez's junior year of high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had so much information and knowledge and wisdom,''
Rodriguez said. ``It was all facts, everything he said was backed
up by numbers and facts. Other agents were making just a lot of
empty promises, not telling me anything bad. He told me both sides
of everything. His truthfulness was what separated him from
everyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Mariners took Rodriguez first in the 1993 draft, Boras
took the M's to the last possible day before securing a $1 million
signing bonus. Other agents approached Rodriguez during his brief
stay in the minors, but Boras and Fischlin were never far from him,
seeing him about two days every two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The close relationship continues. On vacation with his family
for the first time in two years this April, Boras left early to be
with Rodriguez after his knee surgery. Boras' own career had been
cut short by a knee injury, and he knew Rodriguez's family was far
away, in Miami. The visit meant a lot, Rodriguez said, and he
doesn't make any life decisions without consulting Boras.
</P>
<P>
   That includes his 1996 contract. Boras advised Rodriguez he was
forfeiting some $10 million by letting the Mariners buy out his
arbitration years, but Rodriguez wanted to secure his family. He
presented his plan, explained that he knew what he was doing, and
promised to defend Boras if people criticized the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying to make me feel good,'' Boras said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who never has complained about the contract, thinks
people forget that the same agent who negotiated the game's biggest
contract also negotiated its biggest bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the easiest contract in Mariner history was the one
that I did,'' Rodriguez said. ``It was about a month and a half of
conversation and we got it done, that quick. And I didn't read this
huge article about how nice Scott was and how helpful he is to the
teams. I must have missed it. No one wrote about how generous he
was with the Mariners. But as soon as he gets the Kevin Brown
contract or whatever, they call him the biggest demon in baseball.
That's not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez's point is that Boras works for the player, not the
other way around. It's a belief shared by others like Ben McDonald,
the No. 1 pick in the draft four years before Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, it's going to be Alex's decision,'' said McDonald,
recovering from a shoulder injury with the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
``Scott's not going to take Alex away from Seattle if Alex wants to
be there. He's going to give the information to him and tell him,
`It's your call, do what you want to do.'''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball executives have heard that before.
</P>
<P>
   ``His clients are very well-prepared on what their position
should be in the media,'' Wade said. ``They say that they control
the situation, and that Scott works for them, and I think a lot of
things are well-scripted. I'm not saying that's a bad thing or
underhanded, not at all. What I am saying is he prepares his
clients very well for what the process should be and how it should
be handled.''
</P>
<P>
   If Rodriguez hits free agency, it should be an unprecedented
financial bonanza _ in tandem with a Griffey free agency, of
course. That was the case with Brown, who left the San Diego Padres
and broke the $100 million barrier. Looking back, said Padres
general manager Kevin Towers, San Diego never had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Scott and Kevin would have just said, `Hey, listen. We're
gonna take the highest dollar. We don't care where it is, we're
going to take what they're going to pay us,' that would have been
fine, because I know we couldn't have been the highest,'' Towers
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``...If Scott's got leverage, he's going to use it. If we would
have approached Kevin Brown when we first got him about a
four-year, five-year deal, $10 million (per year), I don't think he
would have taken it. I think he would have said, `Hey, I've got
confidence in my player that he'll have a big year, I'm going to
take him out on the market and we'll set records.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll take his chances with his players, and if he's got a
chance to take him out on the free-agent market, he will. And if
he's got leverage, he's tough. He knows he's holding the golden
egg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know Alex's situation, (but my guess is) he'll
definitely wait. Because the closer you get to free agency, the
more the dollars go up. I mean, A-Rod's value is not going to come
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez maintains that he'd love to stay in Seattle, under the
right circumstances, and the biggest factor is the Mariners'
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   But dollars will be an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``His contract will be very unique, because there are things
that I believe this type of player requires to assure his stature
economically, apart from most major league players, because he
brings so much value to a franchise,'' Boras said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be terms and conditions that apply to Alex that
probably a club would never do in any other situation, because my
job is to place him in a position that is worthy of what he's done
and his commitment. I don't mean just the dollar figure, I mean
other elements that relate to the term of the contract and what his
stature would remain in the marketplace, all those kinds of
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Boras would not specify what he meant by unique, but it's worth
noting that Brown's contract came with 12 annual flights on a
private jet for his family. Mariners president Chuck Armstrong also
is unaware of the specifics.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's meetings with Boras have been ``very cordial,'' he
said. But when negotiations move into the specific, Armstrong is
hoping to get feedback from Boras along the way. One of Boras'
stated strategies _ ``You have to provide a lot of `No's' to get to
`Yes''' _ could make things difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott's very creative, very smart,'' Armstrong said. ``He
negotiates more contracts than we do, and he knows his player. So
what does his player want, what does it take to make him happy,
what would he want to have to stay here or why would he want to go
someplace else?
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to tell us those things to see if we can match goals
with him. I mean, one of the frustrating things in some contract
negotiations is they just kind of receive offers and they just say
no, and then you ask, well, what is it you want me to say?''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong points out that Boras has returned players to the same
club before. The Yankees re-signed Bernie Williams last winter for
seven years and $87.5 million, and Atlanta re-signed Greg Maddux
(five years, $57.5 million) during the last year of his contract,
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Boras could bring Rodriguez back to the Mariners. Or he could
take him elsewhere. The only certain thing is that a 23-year-old
megastar belongs to Seattle through 2000. And to hear Boras tell
it, the Mariners might be wise to keep him here.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were times when nobody ever believed the Yankees would
sign Bernie, and they did, and they used him that year to win a
world championship,'' Boras said. ``The one thing I would say to
the Mariners and everyone else _ and I don't know what Alex's
decision is going to be _ but I would keep every door open in every
way to allow for the player's decision to evolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``You run the risk in that scenario of not getting something for
the player, but remember what you're getting from him. You lose the
player for a year, you may lose a world championship. They've never
won one up there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
