<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWALK-TRIAL3-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESSES PAINT SLEEPWALKER AS KIND HUSBAND  
 (ADV: THIRD OF FOUR STORIES RECOUNTING WEEK'S TRIAL ACTION) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Six witnesses Wednesday helped defense attorneys paint
a portrait of Scott Falater as a kind, conscientious and
unflappable man who had no plausible motive for brutally murdering
his wife at their Phoenix home.
</P>
<P>
   Their testimony, at times conveying bewilderment and anguish,
deepened the mystery surrounding the 1996 night when Falater claims
to have been sleepwalking when he stabbed his wife 44 times,
dragged her into the backyard pool, then hid his blood-splattered
pajamas.
</P>
<P>
   The third day of testimony in the Maricopa County Superior Court
trial also probed one of the first-degree-murder case's underlying
themes _ the couple's relationship with the Mormon Church.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Yarmila Falater described frequent recreational
walks at a mall when Scott's wife talked contentedly about family
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the things she said, it seemed to me that they were doing
everything according to how you'd wish your life could be, by
having a good job and kids and savings and your church,'' Sarah
Elizabeth Biggs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like that was the All-American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Daryl Williams, who described Scott, 44, as ``easygoing, calm
and unflappable,'' said the former Motorola engineer was bewildered
in the aftermath of his wife's death.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in a state of trying to figure out what happened,''
said Williams, who became friends with Scott when they taught
early-morning seminary classes for Mormon youth. ``Scott had no
recollection of what happened, in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Balls, a former Mormon bishop who worked closely with
Scott in church affairs, said the couple ``cared for each other,
went places together and were happy.``
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like a good relationship to me,'' said Balls, who
told of attending the surprise party that Scott had for Yarmila's
40th birthday, about a year before her death.
</P>
<P>
   Like Wednesday's other witnesses, Balls said he had been stunned
to learn that Yarmila had died so violently and that Scott had been
charged with murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't fit,'' he said. ``It was as far off the wall as
anything I could ever think of. . . . It's not the Scott I knew in
my 10-year relationship with him.''
</P>
<P>
   During his cross-examination, prosecutor Juan Martinez reacted
skeptically to the glowing descriptions of the Falaters' marriage
as a contented relationship rooted in devotion to the Mormon
Church.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had earlier told jurors that Yarmila, 41 at her death,
was a restless woman who resented the church's demands on her time
and resisted Scott's desire to have more children.
</P>
<P>
   Biggs acknowledged that Yarmila had complained about the church,
saying, ``The more you do, the more they want you to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``She felt overwhelmed sometimes,'' said Biggs, recalling
Yarmila as a strong-willed, independent woman who had decided
firmly against having more children. The Falaters had a boy and a
girl, both teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   But Biggs downplayed Yarmila's discontent with the church,
calling it a typical reaction of a woman who feels stretched too
thin.
</P>
<P>
   Biggs also disputed Martinez's claim that Yarmila expressed her
unhappiness with a physical appearance that became ``unkempt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She always had nice clothes and was always fussing, wondering
if her hair was good,'' Biggs said. ``I can't imagine why anyone
would say she was unkempt.''
</P>
<P>
   In an exchange with defense attorney Lori Voepel, Biggs attacked
the core of the prosecution's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you believe that what occurred was the result of major
marital problems?'' Voepel asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's totally false,'' Biggs responded firmly.
``There were no problems that were that major.''
</P>
<P>
   Voepel asked if Biggs would tell the jury if Yarmila had spoken
of troubles in the marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' Biggs replied, near tears. ``Anything to make some
sense out of it (Yarmila's death).
</P>
<P>
   Under Martinez questioning, former bishop Terry Lee Call
acknowledged he had seen a tearful Yarmila at the back of the
church shortly after a change in local church boundaries cut her
off from old friends.
</P>
<P>
   Call said Yarmila had declined his offer to talk about the
problem. But he acknowledged receiving a letter from Yarmila that
he had refused to show the prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Call said the church's ``priest-penitent privilege'' prevented
him from showing Martinez the letter. He insisted that he would not
have testified that the Falaters had a solid marriage if
confidential information suggested otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   A Motorola shipping clerk who worked under Scptt spoke glowingly
of the engineer, who claims a history of sleepwalking and says
work-related stresses had disrupted his sleep patterns at the time
of Yarmila's death.
</P>
<P>
   Wyvaughna Mullins said that in her 35 years at Motorola she had
never had a manager who matched Scott's consideration and kindness.
</P>
<P>
   Mullins said that if she were asked to pick her top five bosses,
Scott ``would be number 1, 2, 3, 4, 5.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody who comes close to his attitude and the way he
treated people,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 1352EDT &QL; 
