<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4931 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-NOTTING-BOS &LR;      05-28 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-NOTTING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S A LOT TO LOVE ABOUT `NOTTING HILL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
NOTTING HILL 
Directed by: Roger Michell 
Screenplay by: Richard Curtis 
Starring: Julia Roberts, Hugh Grant, Hugh Bonneville, Emma
Chambers, James Dreyfus, Rhys Ifans, Tim McInnerny, Gina McKee 
Running time: 123 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (sexual content and brief strong language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Notting Hill'' is the winning romantic comedy every summer not
only awaits, but counts on to offer escape from the big-bang action
movies and other Hollywood offerings that come on like heavy
machinery and play like something written by a committee. This one
has enormous charm, a luminous Julia Roberts, and a confidently
self-deprecating Hugh Grant as the commoner and bookstore owner who
dares hope he can get something romantic going with the closest
he'll ever get to real-world royalty. We refer, of course, not to
an inhabitant of the House of Windsor, but the House of Warner. Or,
in this case, Universal.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts is an American film goddess cleverly set to work playing
both sides of her real-life film-goddess status. To buy into
``Notting Hill,'' we have to suspend disbelief that a star would
really want to opt out of the whole paparazzi craziness, and not
just hire extra security while soldiering bravely on, paying the
price of being on the A-list. But there is a genuine impulse in
Roberts to just bolt from it all, and the public has seen enough of
it to believe in her skittishness. In short, the role wouldn't work
with a lot of stars in it, but it does work with Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   It also works for another reason. She's among the most
thin-skinned of actors. She's emotional litmus, able to convince us
of the force of her longing. Lucikly for the film, we believe
what's in her eyes when she plays her big romantic scene. She's
also poised enough to convincingly project the cool take-charge
manner a star of her magnitude must project in public. She's
touching in the wisely few moments of romantic yearning she's given
because. Otherwise, she's pretty composed, not only in her scenes
of professional dispatch, but in those where she finds ways to
relax and be gracious to people who aren't stars.
</P>
<P>
   The most warming scene is when Grant's bookseller takes her to
dinner with his sister and a houseful of his old pals, and it's
brought off with rare and disarming warmth. How they get together
is immaterial. They're the stars, so you know they're going to be
brought together. In this case, Roberts' Anna Scott, shopping
Portobello Road in sunglasses, wanders into Grant's bookshop,
enjoys a bright, friendly exchange, and wanders out, only to
collide with him a few moments later, have him drench her in orange
juice, and accept his offer to come to his nearby house to dry off
and change.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the film's biggest challenge is to keep bringing them
together in ways that don't demolish our wish to hold onto the
fantasy. This it does, in ways more confident and conventional and
less idiosyncratic than ``Four Weddings and a Funeral.'' This new
caper not only essentially asks Grant to play the same role he
played in the film that launched his career, but reunites him with
that film's producer (Duncan Kenworthy) and writer (Richard
Curtis). It also gives him a much more substantial American over
whom to pine than Andie McDowell was handed in ``Four Weddings and
a Funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   But although ``Notting Hill'' is more conventional and its
eccentricity has been toned down, Curtis still gives us the
impression that he's drawing us into a longtime circle of London
pals and in a neighborhood so unproblematically diverse that it
becomes part of the film's fairy-tale world. Neither Roberts nor
Grant are given high farce to play. The eccentricity is mostly
attended to by Rhys Ifans as Grant's scruffy Welsh housemate and
Emma Chambers as Grant's ditzy sister. Still, a more naturalistic
tone prevails here, most persuasively anchored by Gina McKee's
wheelchair-bound married friend. In short, there's a lot of warm,
simpatico social solidity against which the jangly life of the
American film star (amplified by a funny cameo from an unbilled
Alec Baldwin) is contrasted.
</P>
<P>
   Grant recaptures the career ground lost in his offscreen
peccadillos by coming on hesitantly and pretending to be surprised
at his character's high self-regard. But it's the sum total of the
persona Roberts puts before us that makes the film sublime. She's
not all gossamer longing for magical interludes in a moonlit park.
At times, she's impulsive, even destructive. But she convincingly
inhabits both the public situations she has learned to navigate and
a wistful longing for an emotional purity to which she can never
return. Roberts's character may be fictional, but she's not all
that fictional, and her nerve endings are the real thing. Finally,
here's the '90s equivalent of Audrey Hepburn in ``Roman Holiday.''
Even in its big mass-market moments, Roberts makes ``Notting Hill''
tender as well as trendy, and it makes all the difference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
