<HEADER>
A4932 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-MARTIN-BOS &LR;      05-28 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-MARTIN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING LA VIDA BUENA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ricky Martin was the center of the pop universe, at least for a
week. He's a former child star whose performance at the Grammy
awards signaled a flood of interest in his hip-shaking Latin pop.
That interest may not be sustained, given the fickle nature of the
marketplace _ remember Gerardo's short-lived ``Rico Suave'' or Los
Del Rios's ``Macarena''? _ but don't bet against it this time.
</P>
<P>
   Martin's English-language debut album _ simply titled ``Ricky
Martin'' _ just sold 660,000 copies in its opening week, although
that record was topped this week by the Backstreet Boys. His
Spanglish single, ``Livin' La Vida Loca,'' hit No. 1, pumped up by
a Latin horn arrangement and a theme of ``the millennium party song
from hell,'' cowriter Desmond Child says. ``She'll make you live
her crazy life until you go insane,'' the lyric says.
</P>
<P>
   Child, however, believes that the recent chart frenzy ``doesn't
mean a Latin music explosion, but it's a Ricky Martin explosion.''
He adds: ``Some people are trying to tie it in with a lot of other
Latin artists who haven't even released records yet . . . but most
of that is the same old generic stuff that's been coming out of
Miami for years _ the stuff that you listen to and then want to
kill yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Another faction believes, however, that Martin's runaway success
_ he also just did ``Saturday Night Live'' and has lined up Oprah
Winfrey, Jay Leno, and David Letterman like a bunch of dominoes _
marks a milestone for Latin inroads into Anglo pop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world is becoming smaller, and people now understand
different cultures,'' says Emilio Estefan, the dean of Latin
producers (he helped produce five tracks on Martin's album) and
husband of crossover star Gloria Estefan. ``Latin music is going to
stay. There will be a lot more fusions, but definitely Latin
percussion will remain.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Latino radio stations are basking in Martin's glory.
``It's great for us. It's giving Latin music a very high profile,''
says Alberto Vasallo, vice president of Boston's Radiolandia (1330
AM). ``For many people who are not Latinos, this is their first
immersion in this very hot music. It's kind of like when rap and
hip-hop hit in the late '70s. You're going to hear a lot more
crossover artists.''
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Martin is so big on Radiolandia that his hit
``Livin' La Vida Loca'' has led to a parody version in which on-air
personnel offer their own lyrics above the music. A sample from
morning DJ Johnny Peguero: ``Johnny, who wakes you up in the
morning, is also living `La Vida Loca.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Even apart from Martin, it's hard to deny the emergence of Latin
music into the mainstream. Latin record sales increased from $491
million in 1997 to $571 million last year, according to the
Recording Industry Association of America. That's still a small
part of the overall $14 billion domestic market, but it's an
increase that has record labels, notably Sony Records (which has
Martin under contract), flocking to sign Latin artists with
crossover potential.
</P>
<P>
   How times change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen years ago, when I did `Conga','' Estefan says of his
wife's first hit, ``I was almost thrown out of Sony Records. They
said, `Take the congas out and the trumpets out of the song.' . . .
But now, Gloria and me and Ricky are living the American Dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Estefan recalls a fateful conversation with Martin seven years
ago. ``I told Ricky then, `You're going to cross over.' He said,
`It will never happen.' I said, `It's going to be hard, but let's
start making demos.' And we stayed with it, and you could see that
it was going to happen. He became famous with his last two Spanish
albums, and when you saw him play in places like France, Germany,
and Brazil, where they don't speak Spanish as a first language, you
could see them react with the same excitement. You knew the wave
would come to America, too. And then came the Grammy awards.''
</P>
<P>
   Estefan has also become the pivotal figure for English-speaking
artists looking for credibility in the Latin market. He did a Latin
remix of Will Smith's ``Welcome to Miami'' and a recent Latin remix
of Lenny Kravitz's ``Hey Mama,'' which went to No. 1 in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never erase your heritage. I'm proud of where I came
from,'' says the Cuban-born Estefan. ``I feel very Cuban, but I
also feel very Anglo. We are immigrants who grew up listening to
Motown and the Beatles.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin has a similar bilingual bent and has soaked up the
influence of many cultures. He was born in Puerto Rico (his dad was
a psychologist, his mom an accountant) and became a member of the
teen group Menudo when he was 12. Menudo was a formula-prone group
whose management required that you leave by age 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Puerto Rico, you either joined the Little Leagues or you
joined Menudo. It was every kid's dream,'' says Robi Rosa, a former
Menudo mate who stayed in contact with Martin and wrote and
co-produced half the songs on Martin's new disc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky's always been an even-keeled guy _ very focused and very
positive,'' says Rosa. ``He offers a new energy, and everyone is
embracing it right now. He represents a new beginning, new hope.
And what I appreciate about Ricky is that he is interested in
finding a way to maintain his roots in pop, but also to push the
envelope.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who is expected to tour the US in the late summer or
fall, is most respected for his work ethic. ``He's a multitalented
guy. He can sing anything from Broadway to rock to salsa,'' says
Child, noting that he first met Martin two years ago after the
latter sang in ``Les Miserables'' on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always prepared,'' adds Child. ``Even if he's just flown
18 hours from Australia, he'll still stand there and sing for 12
hours. He wants to make sure he doesn't drop the ball on his end.''
Adds Rosa: ``He's a workaholic.''
</P>
<P>
   Child brought to Martin's new album some of the ``anthem-style''
hooks that he previously brought to Bon Jovi (on Bon Jovi hits
``You Give Love a Bad Name'' and ``Livin' on a Prayer''), to
Aerosmith (Child wrote ``Dude Looks Like a Lady,'' ``Angel,'' and
``Crazy''), and to Kiss.
</P>
<P>
   The new album was actually a long time coming and wasn't just
done after Martin's mega-exposure at the Grammys. ``We took our
time. It was a melding of different genres. It was very carefully
crafted,'' says Child, who grew up in Miami and whose mother, Elena
Casals, recorded a number of Latin songs. (His aunt, Olga Guillot,
made 56 albums.)
</P>
<P>
   Martin's new disc indeed ripples with a fresh energy at times
but is a guilty pleasure at others (especially in the teen-idol
knockoff ``Shake Your Bon Bon''). There are rock tracks, pop-salsa
dance tunes, two Diane Warren ballads (talk about going for the
commercial brass ring), a tasteful love song with Madonna (``Be
Careful,'' produced by William Orbit), and a reprise of the ``The
Cup of Life,'' the World Cup theme song. Martin sang it before 1.5
billion viewers of the World Cup in Paris and then for another
billion-plus watching the Grammys. The tune went to No. 1 in 22
countries.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the next Latino crossover wave? Observers say to
look for Jennifer Lopez, who starred in the film ``Selena'' and has
a new album next week; the Argentinian Giselle D'Cole and
Colombian-born Shakira, who both write their own songs; Elvis
Crespo, whose Spanish-language album just debuted on the Billboard
charts at No. 49; Menudo-like teen group MDO; and Marc Anthony, who
is about to record a duet with soul star Maxwell. (For another
duet, look for Gloria Estefan and `N Sync to do a song on the
soundtrack to the Meryl Streep film ``Fifty Violins'' this fall.)
</P>
<P>
   While the Ricky Martin phenomenon has given new juice to the
Latin surge, there may be an inevitable cloning that could tarnish
it. Of course, this is the same thing that happens to Anglo stars
as well, so perversely, it may be another sign that Latin music has
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of Ricky, we'll probably see a female Ricky Martin and
a Ricky Martin all-boy group and a Ricky Martin all-girl group,''
says Child. ``It will be like the time when Bon Jovi hit it big.
Bon Jovi's success unleashed leagues of hair bands that we couldn't
get rid of until Kurt Cobain came along. Just watch: People are
going to ride Ricky's coattails, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
