<HEADER>
A4933 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-MEMOIR-BOS &LR;      05-28 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MEMOIR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE COVERS OF THE PUBLISHING WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ANOTHER LIFE 
A Memoir of Other People 
By Michael Korda 
Random House, 530 pp., $26.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Start on Page 475 of this how-to book if you're a writer, or
even if not a writer but only a reader who's interested in the
writing process. At a press conference, Ronald Reagan is discussing
``his'' memoirs. ``I hear it's a terrific book!'' he says,
cheerfully. ``One of these days I'm going to have to read it
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   That is this book's theme in a nutshell. The image of Reagan, a
``writer'' not known for any interest in reading or writing _ or
even, intimate friends conceded, introspection _ dovetails nicely
with the image of absent-minded Simon &AMP; Schuster founder Max
Schuster. He advises stripper/author Gypsy Rose Lee, at the party
celebrating the publication of her novel: ``One of these days you
ought to write a book.''
</P>
<P>
   Korda, editor in chief of Simon &AMP; Schuster, has buried inside
this garrulous, sometimes plodding memoir a brisk, fast-paced and
somewhat comic how-to about book publishing, which sounds like a
sort of out-of-town tryout for Hollywood and Hollywood celebrities.
Nobodies need not apply. In Korda's world, publishing is all about
deals, about the arcane process of (dis)assembling books, the
perversion of verbs like ``writing'' and the business itself. It's
a business, as opposed to, say, editing, which, Korda writes, is a
profession. This book is a study in the behavior of characters who
seem to be kindred anal obsessive-compulsives drawn to the
publishing process and determined to survive in it. If indeed
``process' is what it can be called.
</P>
<P>
   Korda is at his best when he's wry, often when he's listening to
people confiding in him. Playwright Sidney Kingsley describes in
excruciating detail his method of writing, prompting Korda to muse
that ``on no subject more so than their own writing are writers
more likely to be self-deceived, or, in conversation, more
boring.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the editor's job is not listening but maintaining the
``extracurricular'' reading of the ``sheer volume of material that
(has) to be read.'' It's analogous to the monk's ``getting up to go
to mass in the middle of the night.'' Editors, writes Korda,
``overwork and underachieve,'' spending weeks and months ``lovingly
rewriting a manuscript that was never worth anything in the first
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while something resembling a literary
transaction occurs, as in the inspired reconstructive editing that
hallowed editor Robert Gottleib and assistant Nina Bourne performed
on Joseph Heller's manuscript of the legendary ``Catch-22.''
Gottlieb, in fact, is the closest to a universally beloved figure
in the book. All it requires for him to sell commercial fiction is
the ``energy and sincerity'' of the writer. Gottlieb is also a
pivotal figure, not least because he's not above applying to a
novel the antic show business dynamic of the movie business.
</P>
<P>
   With fiction, as Korda writes, the ``only limits are set by the
editor's energy and the author's willingness to live with big
changes. Character, motivation, and plot can be changed, subplots
and minor characters can be thrown out, whole scenes eliminated or
created from scratch.'' It's easier to do this with first
novelists, Korda writes, ``whose major anxiety is whether . . .
their book will ever get published at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Bestselling authors operate at a higher level. Congenital
bestseller Harold Robbins unwittingly submits to S&AMP;S two halves of
separate novels as one whole one that's due. He insists, to Korda's
anguish, that despite the incongruity, it's a novel that can be
published as is, that no one will notice. It's published as is. Not
a reader complains.
</P>
<P>
   Korda, who came from a moviemaking family, has a high opinion of
the screenwriter's approach to writing books. Screenwriters, he
writes, know how to do ``all the things that puzzle many novelists:
how to cut to the chase, how to maintain a consistent point of
view, how to work out motivation for every action and to prepare
the reader for sudden changes of plot, how to avoid flashbacks,
and, worse still, flash-forwards. A strong story line, divided into
clear scenes,'' is ``exactly what works for most readers of
fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   He also advises writers not to become trapped by their research.
Korda recalls what Robbins said about his bestselling rival Irving
Wallace, who, Robbins thought, wrote his fiction essentially to
justify his voluminous, fastidious research. Wallace wrote about
sex, Robbins believed, ``as if he had never experienced it.''
</P>
<P>
   Editors loom large in the picture, with, Korda writes, their
approach to the written word, starting with questions like ``How
can we fix this?'' and, more fundamentally, ``How . . . did we get
into this . . . and why?'' Editors are usually pivotal in the
decision/determination of whether a book works or requires massive
cutting. This book, although poorly titled and itself a candidate
for hefty cutting, is useful. A suggested better title: ``Bonfires
of the Vanity Press: How We Publish and Sell People Who Can't Write
_ or Won't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
