<HEADER>
A4935 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-SOUTHIE-BOS &LR;      05-28 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-SOUTHIE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOUTHIE' CAPTURES NEIGHBORHOOD SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
SOUTHIE 
Directed by: John Shea 
Screenplay by: James Cummings, John Shea 
Starring: Donnie Wahlberg, Rose McGowan, James Cummings, John Shea,
Anne Meara, Lawrence Tierney, Steve Koslowski, Amanda Peet, Will
Arnett, Josh Marchette, Robert Wahlberg, Jeffrey Cook, Lenny Clark,
Jere Shea 
Running time: 95 minutes 
Rated: R (violence and pervasive language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Authenticity and a collective feeling of heartfelt urgency carry
``Southie'' past a certain lack of originality and technical
finesse. Although it was filmed before ``Good Will Hunting,''
``Monument Ave.,'' and ``Next Stop Wonderland,'' it's only now
finding its way to filmgoers looking for the next movie that speaks
in a convincing Boston accent. In the case of ``Southie,'' it's not
what it says but how it says it that generates its appeal. There's
no question that Jimmy Cummings, who wrote the film with director
John Shea and who also stars in it, has successfully captured the
flavor of his South Boston world, or that Shea's direction
transfers it to the screen with gritty intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the actors bring to their roles the kind of rightness
that can't be learned in an acting school. They need it to carry
them past contrived structuring and more than a few melodramatic
gangster-movie-plot cliches. Donnie Wahlberg's central character,
Danny Quinn, relies on a sort of anguished caring in the role of
the guy who returns to the old neighborhood knowing what a
minefield it is, especially if he's going to stay sober and avoid
the violence that caused him to leave in the first place. Guiltily,
he feels obliged to replace his late father, killed while working
for the local godfather, Lawrence Tierney's impressively stony old
patriarch, Colie Powers. By himself, Danny is tough enough. His
problem is that his family is vulnerable and his friends are weak.
</P>
<P>
   His two younger brothers are in thrall to a vicious rival crime
lord, whose son is Danny's old enemy. Danny's sister has an alcohol
problem. His mother, played by the ever-valuable Anne Meara, has a
gallant heart but a damaged one, and no medical insurance. And his
lifelong neighborhood pal is desperate to draw him into a
get-rich-quick scheme running an illegal after-hours club. He
resists, but when the bad guys freeze him out of the union, he's
pushed into the deal. That puts him on a collision course with his
old nemesis, the gangster prince, played by Cummings with a
brashness born of knowing he's got a tough father covering his
back. Cummings brings to the role a slightly crazed quality that's
an enjoyably over-the-top throwback to old gangster movies, while
Wahlberg satisfyingly balances toughness against conflicting
demands of honor.
</P>
<P>
   Wahlberg succeeds in making us feel that Danny's internal
struggle counts for more than the inevitable tough-guy face-offs.
Tierney and Meara anchor ``Southie'' with authority at either end
of the emotional spectrum, giving lessons on how to skirt cliche,
strongly embodying the past in a film that's in large part about
the tug of the past. Rose McGowan will get to you, too, as Danny's
suffering sister herded into detox. Shea is a plus as a police
officer cousin vainly trying to supply a voice of reason. The
smaller roles are done with idiomatic rightness, both those within
the neighborhood and a few from outside it, such as Amy Stiller's
note-perfect overworked doctor in a hospital scene. There are
technical rough patches, and a few too many actors wear a few too
many caps _ the only costuming lapse. But juicy acting and an
intense individual and communal commitment that seems to boil up
from the streets carry ``Southie'' past its structural and
technical limitations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
