<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEREST RATE WORRIES COOL HEELS OF HOT INTERNET STOCKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZipLink Inc., a company that connects customers to the Internet,
was hoping to cash in on the Web stock craze when it went public
this week.
</P>
<P>
   But ZipLink's $49 million initial public stock offering, which
hit the market on Wednesday, was greeted by investors in a way that
would have been unimaginable just weeks ago. The stock of the
Lowell, Mass. company actually dropped in value by the end of its
first trading day. The shares, initially priced at 14, finished
Thursday at 12 1/8.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks suddenly are not the sure thing they have been
for most of the last year. Fears of higher interest rates are
pulling all Web stocks down, even the most familiar names that have
become known as the blue chips of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't the first time Internet stocks have slumped. Just last
month, they fell hard when investors started to worry about the
earnings potential of many Web companies. But those shares bounced
back, nearly to their old levels, in short order.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the slump looks more like a slow leak of confidence
rather than a blowout. Put the two declines together and the losses
mount for even the biggest Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com Inc. is down about 45 percent from its high, recorded
a month ago. Yahoo Inc. is off about 40 percent since its April
peak and America Online Inc. has slipped more than 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But a flood of new stock ginned up to meet voracious investor
demand has become a kind of wet blanket of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The incidence of failed deals is much more frequent,'' said
Brian Stack, a mutual fund manager at MFS Investment Management in
Boston. ``Everyone thought it was their birthright to see a stock
go up 100 percent on Day One.''
</P>
<P>
   The rash of IPOs and additional stock offerings by public
Internet companies is sating much of the demand. More importantly,
the rush has generated more IPOs than there are solid, seasoned
companies suitable for public markets.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 Internet-related companies have gone public and
raised in excess of $4 billion so far this year. Another 82 are in
the pipeline, having filed papers to go public with the Securities
and Exchange Commission, according to BT Alex Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The tide of capital flowing into the Internet stock sector has
been dramatic, but hardly a new phenomena. It is a basic function
of the market and investment bankers who work there to latch onto
demand for any type of shares and supply them, usually to excess.
</P>
<P>
   They continue to pump out new stocks for buyers until the
process breaks down and the market becomes swamped with shares of
declining quality that investors no longer want to buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Supply and demand has changed,'' said Linda Killian of
Renaissance Capital's IPO and Aftermarket fund. ``Even when
Internet companies were going public in the first quarter of this
year, there was a tremendous supply-demand imbalance. Investors
have certainly started to attach more discipline to the valuation
of these stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, Web companies going public are more likely to be
pigeonholed into small market niches or have other business plan
faults. But often they are solid companies that are simply being
brought into the market too soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investment marketplace to some degree is playing a
late-stage venture capital role in today's market,'' said Anurag
Pandit, a small-stock portfolio manager at John Hancock Mutual
Funds.
</P>
<P>
   What's still in favor? Companies with lots of name recognition
working in a broad Web market and possessing the potential to grow
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   DLJ Direct, a well-known on-line stock brokerage, went public at
20 on Tuesday and finished Thursday's session at 38. EToys Inc.,
the web toy retailer, launched its public stock at 20 last week and
now trades at 50 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   And just in case you worried that sanity had completely
overtaken the Web stock market, consider Barnes
</P>
<P>
   &AMP;noble.com, the relatively new on-line bookseller operated by
Barnes &AMP; Noble.
</P>
<P>
   It went public Tuesday at 18 and has since gained modestly,
finishing at 24 Thursday. But at that price the market has valued
Barnes&AMP;noble
</P>
<P>
   .com at about $3.5 billion, or roughly two-thirds more than its
parent firm, which operates brick-and-mortar stores and still owns
a huge chunk of the on-line operation.
</P>
<P>
   Among established Internet companies, the big names are still
wildly successful stocks when viewed in the bigger picture.
</P>
<P>
   For all its recent problems, Amazon.com is still up 693 percent
in the last year. Shares of CMGI Inc. of Andover, the leading Web
venture investing business, have slipped by about a third since
April but have gained 759 percent in the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is ZipLink, a relatively narrowly focused company
cursed by bad timing. It wasn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Online Inc., which uses the Internet to retrieve corporate
disclosure documents for on-line customers, hit the market the same
day and has barely moved since.
</P>
<P>
   Other smaller, niche Internet companies that were once hot new
IPOs have since cooled. Retailer Cyberian Outpost Inc., which
traded near 40 in January, was worth 11 1/4 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps all Internet stocks will bounce back again, as they have
before. But the threat of higher interest rates, which hurt small
stocks, is a serious problem for Web investors. And then there are
all those other Internet companies in the pipeline, waiting to go
public before it's too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can rest assured, they (investment bankers) are going to
try to clear that calendar before mid-August, when they go on
vacation,'' said Stack.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can also be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
