u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-28 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORK IN HUNT FOR RATINGS WITH MASSCAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pete Macheska has overseen professional football and basketball
game coverage for years, but the Fox producer finds horse racing
more of a challenge for one reason.
</P>
<P>
   The race lasts all of two minutes, and most of the time,
Macheska is producing an hour-long show.
</P>
<P>
   How does one keep the show exciting?
</P>
<P>
   Macheska said it's a balancing act between informing the
hard-core fans and educating new ones. ``We're trying to build a
bigger audience,'' he said. ``But we don't want to insult the
diehard fans.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been an uphill climb. Fox's cable network launched its
horse racing coverage last year with the Santa Anita Handicap. The
race pulled a 2.4 rating and 5 share on Fox Sports New England in
Boston. It didn't do as well nationally, earning only a 1.3 rating
and 4 share. Ratings for the Santa Anita race in March dropped a
bit nationally to a 1.1 and plunged in Boston to a .5.
</P>
<P>
   Macheska is looking to stem the ratings slide in Saturday's
Massachusetts Handicap at Suffolk Downs in Boston. New England
Sports Network, an affiliate of Fox Sports Net, will televise the
event, starting at 5 p.m. with host Kenny Albert and analysts Caton
Bredar, Ron Ellis, and Jay Privman.
</P>
<P>
   The MassCap is part of the National Thoroughbred Racing
Association series, and its $600,000 purse makes it the top event
in New England. Post time is 5:40, and the race features 1998
Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner Real Quiet against NTRA series
points leader Behrens.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's hour-long coverage also includes the 5:15 Metropolitan
Mile from Belmont. The added race, to be called by Barry Tompkins,
gives Macheska a little breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   Macheska said the announcing team brings different perspectives
for all levels of viewers. Ellis, for instance, is a horse trainer,
and during the Santa Anita race, he explained the term ``quarter
crack.'' Diehard fans probably already knew that the injury is akin
to a broken fingernail or turf toe, but the novice definitely
appreciated the information. Ellis has also been quick to point out
his problems with handicap races, the ones when horses are assigned
a weight. Initially used as a way to balance the field, handicaps
have caused owners to shy away from races in which their horses are
given more weight than they want.
</P>
<P>
   Macheska said graphics are designed to give information in
understandable terms. Instead of showing just the odds, Fox's
graphics will indicate that 2-1 odds, for example, will pay $6.
</P>
<P>
   Albert hosted his first horse race broadcast last year. The son
of Marv Albert usually does football play-by-play for Fox. Kenny
enjoys the chance to host an event as exciting as a horse race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm basically a traffic cop,'' he said. ``I'll introduce the
features and set up our three analysts. But I tell you, it's
something to be down on the track when the horses are running. At
the Santa Anita, there were about 40,000 people in the stands and
the buzz from the crowd was incredible, absolutely incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry speaks
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry talked with CNN/SI's John Giannone and
apologized to Yankees owner George Steinbrenner for the April 14
incident in which he was arrested on charges of cocaine possession
and soliciting a prostitute. He pleaded no contest to the charges
Wednesday and received 18 months probation. ``I probably wasn't in
the right state of mind,'' Strawberry said.
</P>
<P>
   Giannone listened to Strawberry's mea culpa, then asked a
tactless question about whether Strawberry had contemplated
suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, no, I didn't really contemplate anything of that
nature,'' Strawberry said. ``I didn't really care too much about
life at that time. It was just some type of thought going through
me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blackledge on board
</P>
<P>
   Todd Blackledge is leaving ABC to join play-by-play man Sean
McDonough on CBS as the network's lead college football analyst.
Blackledge replaces Terry Donahue and will work 12 regular-season
games plus the Sun Bowl . . . ABC will air its 17 ``Monday Night
Football'' games this season, as well as the Super Bowl, on HDTV .
. . HBO's broadcast of Oscar De La Hoya's title defense against Oba
Carr last Saturday night pulled a 14.6 rating and was seen in
approximately 4 million homes. HBO's boxing ratings are up nearly
20 percent from last year. Felix Trinidad defends his International
Boxing Federation welterweight title against Hugo Pineda on HBO
Saturday at 11 p.m.
</P>
