<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4955 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-BLAKE-2TAKES-BOS &LR;      05-28 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-BLAKE-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN COLLEGE TENNIS, JAMES BLAKE IS IN COMPLETE CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Sometimes he applied what he figured was the
proper force and technique to deliver a textbook volley. But
apparently, the ball opted to do its own thing: It chose not to
land where 12-year-old James Blake had sent it. For that, the next
available ball got whacked clear out of the court, a stern warning
for any other sphere that considered acting up.
</P>
<P>
   That went double for the racket. Often it chose to return serves
into the net, and the youngster threw it or slammed its head
against the surface. Other times, the air was kicked. The walls
were attacked. The floor was stomped.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, no one anticipated that the undersized youth from
Fairfield, Conn., would someday become the first player in Harvard
history to earn a No. 1 ranking in men's tennis as a sophomore.
That he would be within four matches of becoming only the second
player in history to take three legs of the Intercollegiate Tennis
Association Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   He began playing the sport regularly at age 7, in a youth
program at a Harlem armory that also served as a homeless shelter.
Often he would watch people sleeping on the floor and remind
himself how fortunate he was, and he sought to use his talent to
the best of his ability.
</P>
<P>
   Yet once he developed a passion for the sport, Blake uncovered
an insatiable desire to succeed, confused potential with perfection
_ and wouldn't stand for anything to get in the way of a command
performance. His motto was ``spare the rod, spoil the elements.''
</P>
<P>
   And vent frustrations against the person on the opposite side of
the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``James, you should just say, `Nice shot,' and keep going,''
Betty Blake would often say to her son, waiting for their tennis
match to resume, lamenting that another moment of mother-son
bonding had soured because James was too temperamental for a
friendly game.
</P>
<P>
   ``James, don't get angry,'' said coach Brian Barker of the
Tennis Club of Trumbull, Conn., who began working with Blake when
the boy was 10 and asked to be assigned to another player the
following day.
</P>
<P>
   ``James, if you don't curb your attitude, you won't be playing
tennis anymore,'' warned his father, Thomas Sr., who introduced
James and his older brother, Thomas Jr., to the sport while
volunteering in a Harlem youth program when the family lived in
Yonkers, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the boy rebelled against his father's threat. Then,
following the urging of Barker and Thomas Jr., he gradually relaxed
on the court, played through adversity, complimented opponents,
accepted defeat as part of the game. As his physical attributes
developed, so did his maturity, his humility.
</P>
<P>
   Then an amazing thing happened. The more humble he became, the
more unbeatable Blake got. So much so that after he had a growth
spurt at 18, he began a meteoric rise to the top of amateur tennis.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The top man
</P>
<P>
   Blake has been the nation's top-ranked men's Division 1 player
since Dec. 8. He is the top seed in the 115th NCAA Men's Tennis
Championships at the University of Georgia. In addition, he and
teammate Kunj Majmudar rank third nationally in doubles and are the
second seed here.
</P>
<P>
   A singles title would enable Blake to join Sargis Sargsian of
Arizona State (1995) as the only men to capture three ITA Grand
Slam events.
</P>
<P>
   Blake did not compete in the first leg, the National Clay Court
Championships, then won the ITA Rolex Indoor Championships Feb. 7
and the ITA All-America Championships Oct. 20, becoming the first
Ivy League player to do so. On Jan. 9, he captured his first title
in a professional event, the US Tennis Association Futures of
Seminole County in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   The son of an African-American father and British mother, Blake
is also attempting to become only the second player of
African-American descent to capture the NCAA singles championship;
Arthur Ashe did it while at UCLA in 1965. And he would be the first
Ivy player to win the title since Lucien Williams of Yale in 1921.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was younger and I wasn't really good and I thought I
was good, I was probably arrogant then. I thought I should never
lose and that I knew everything,'' said Blake, who Thursday
defeated Doug Bohaboy of Northwestern, 6-4, 7-6 (7-5).
</P>
<P>
   ``After I worked with (Barker), I realized that's not the
approach you take to tennis, and I would be so much better if I
just relax a little and realize there are so many more matches in
my career and that every match isn't the end of the world, every
practice isn't the end of the world. And that I really don't know
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake has become one of the most likable, approachable athletes
around _ so much so that most folks who didn't know him then are
taken aback to hear he was once so temperamental. Among the awards
his parents take pride in are several he's earned for
sportsmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as he accepted losing, he started to win more,'' said
Betty Blake. ``If things didn't happen his way, he would lose his
temper, and it made it difficult for everyone around him. Brian
Barker and Thomas (Jr.) helped to calm him down. I don't think he
wanted to be seen as a jerk anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A splash at Harvard
</P>
<P>
   At Fairfield High School, Blake finished with a four-year record
of 80-3, winning his last 40 matches. At 18, he won 49 consecutive
matches and became the USTA's top-ranked player in the 18-and-under
division.
</P>
<P>
   James was Thomas's doubles partner at Harvard last season and
became the school's first freshman singles All-American in men's
tennis. He finished the season ranked 14th in the nation with a
singles record of 37-5. He had a 23-4 doubles mark with Thomas, who
graduated and is now on the ATP Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``He used to be the smallest person around wherever we went, so
I think he wanted to be everyone's equal,'' said Thomas Blake Sr.
``His game improved, but he still had a problem with size. Then he
hit a growth spurt at 18 and his physical strength caught up with
his game.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he was smaller than his brother, and few people,
including his parents, figured Blake would ever reach his current
level.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
