<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4956 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIGDIG-POLITICS-BOS &LR;      05-28 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGDIG-POLITICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIANS' RIVALRIES ARE UNCOVERED BY BIG DIG SPAT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and a coding)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the end, it seems the digs had very little to do
with the Big Dig itself.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, members of the Massachusetts congressional
delegation were seizing on a federal auditor's report that accused
state officials of improperly funneling $150 million of federal
money into a trust fund for the Central Artery project _ money the
congressmen said should have been spent on the state's decaying
roads and bridges. State officials countered that the trust fund
was an innovative self-insurance plan to protect the Big Dig from
catastrophic losses.
</P>
<P>
   But as the charges and countercharges were being sorted out, it
appeared to be mainly a war of personalities and personal issues,
not to mention political grudges from both parties.
</P>
<P>
   And by Thursday _ as Massachusetts Turnpike Authority head James
Kerasiotis fired off a nasty letter to Representative James P.
McGovern _ the fight seemed to be as much the product of a
dysfunctional relationship between the Democratic congressional
delegation and the Republican governor as about a highway project
that is hardly half complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, Jim, stop whining,'' read Kerasiotis's letter, which
was immediately distributed to the entire delegation. ``More
importantly, find a constructive way to act out.''
</P>
<P>
   This week's incident follows another skirmish between
Massachusetts' elected officials. Two weeks ago, Senator John F.
Kerry and McGovern were caught circulating a letter that complained
about the way Governor Paul Cellucci was talking about them.
</P>
<P>
   And yet both public spats _ as well as a series of more private
ones between Democrats in Washington and Republicans in Boston _
seem to have much deeper roots, entangled in the nebulous world of
infrastructure appropriations and the politicians who take credit
for them.
</P>
<P>
   The ongoing conflict stems from a single source, according to
congressional and gubernatorial aides: last year's federal
transportation bill, in which Massachusetts saw its highway funding
slashed, providing the state's tiny Republican Party a giant hammer
with which to beat Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the bill, Cellucci has held the delegation
responsible for fiscal woes in Boston. Boston Republicans have
gleefully used it as a symbol of the ``cloutless Democratic
delegation.''
</P>
<P>
   And the delegation's Democrats, still smarting from their slide
into the minority in the House in 1994, have gotten agitated. They
have tried to puncture the argument time and again, arguing that
Massachusetts was bound to lose money after the Big Dig stopped
receiving new funds, that the state lost less money than expected,
that it still took in more federal funds than most other states.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats complained. They wrote letters. They said that they
were frustrated by the arrogance of the Cellucci administration,
and said that state officials refused to work with them and would
not stop torturing them with an inaccurate assessment of how they
did their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   This week, then, seemed to be payback.
</P>
<P>
   The transportation audit _ titled ``Overpayments of Premiums for
the Central Artery Project's Owner-Controlled Insurance Project'' _
was performed for the Federal Highway Administration by the
inspector general of the US Department of Transportation. It was
given to congressmen Tuesday, and was circulated among reporters
Wednesday. By Thursday, an arcane audit had sparked a full-scale
political war.
</P>
<P>
   The state set up an insurance company that invested in corporate
bonds as a means of building up a trust fund that could be used to
cover major losses during Big Dig construction. According to the
audit, $150 million in federal money was improperly used to buy the
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   State Republicans said they were simply using a creative method
that generated income, which would not only insure the Big Dig, but
end up saving taxpayers as much as $1 billion over the life of the
project.
</P>
<P>
   Kerasiotes's letter said the Treasury Department endorsed the
concept in 1995. And even the executive director of the FHA,
Anthony Kane, disagreed with the report and said the inspector
general had misunderstood the purpose of the trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   Some delegation members stayed quiet _ afraid the damaging
report could be used during the congressional appropriations
process as proof Massachusetts does not deserve more funding.
</P>
<P>
   But others, according to McGovern, got ``a little excited.''
Although he noted the audit was not commissioned by the delegation,
he did not altogether deny his rage was connected to a longtime
disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the delegation trying to pick a fight,'' McGovern
said. ``We have been incredibly patient and silent for a long time
_ some say too long. The reality now is, it's time to set the
record straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Moakley agreed. ``It's always the same thing,'' he said.
``Cellucci and his minions go around saying there's not enough
money because Congress didn't get us enough money. Here, he's got
$150 million in a slush fund.''
</P>
<P>
   A Cellucci spokesman indicated Thursday that the spat was not
going to immediately disappear. Asked why the audit turned into
such a contentious issue, Jose Juves said: ``Some members are still
upset they were unable to secure Massachusetts' fair share of
highway funds.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
