<HEADER>
A4958 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-28 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON'S MISSILE DEFENSE SYSTEM IS ON A LONG LOSING STREAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Withdrawing $110 billion from the ATM to play craps would seem
penny dumb and pound nuts, even if the ATM is Capitol Hill's
bottomless automatic teller for the military. This week reminded us
why.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Pentagon held a test of its Theater
High-Altitude Area Defense missile. THAAD is the latest in
congressional science fictions to knock enemy missiles out of the
sky.
</P>
<P>
   The only sound from THAAD is ``thud.'' In seven years, all six
previous tests have failed. You would not know this from the
Pentagon. Like a disbelieving loser who needs to be dragged out of
a casino, the military insists it is about to hit the jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   The last failure was March 29. A test missile whizzed past a
test attacker, missing by less than 90 feet. Nonetheless, the
Pentagon bragged that the missile achieved 16 of 17 objectives. ``I
am encouraged by the test,'' said Army Lieutenant General Paul L.
Kern. ``We are much closer to achieving success.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to the vaporized residents of whatever metropolis was
the incoming target of that warhead. Never mind that the ``only''
failure was merely the worst thing that could happen, the
malfunction of the infrared seeker. The Pentagon keeps walking the
implausible thin line between telling us how complex the problems
are (the more to get defense dollars), yet how soon they will solve
them (also the more to get defense dollars).
</P>
<P>
   Brigadier General Daniel Montgomery said the March 29 failure
was possibly due to debris on a plug that caused disruptions so
small ``you can't see them without a microscope.'' The disruptions
cause the failure of a thruster and the telemetry. Yet, Montgomery
declared these to be ``low-tech problems, and we can correct
those.'' He promised that on the next test, ``we will hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The hit was supposed to be Tuesday. It was so bad, it did not
even register a thud. The Pentagon aborted the test entirely when
the ``attacking'' missile zoomed out of control. Of course, the
incurable gambler did not see this as more evidence of utter
incompetence. It was just a nonevent, a test that did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this case, the target failed,'' said Defense Department
spokesman Kenneth Bacon. ``Therefore, the THAAD was never launched.
It's life. They will come back and try again.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to the vaporized residents of whatever metropolis was
the unintended target of the misguided warhead. You would think in
a real attack, THAAD would have to go after not only missiles
launched as straight arrows, but also errant mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   There is no reason to let the Pentagon come back to the ATM to
try again. In three decades, there has been $110 billion of
spending and 16 test launches of missile defense systems.
</P>
<P>
   Out of the 16, the Pentagon claimed two hits in 1984 and 1991.
But after each ``hit,'' embarrassed officials later confessed that
the tests were rigged. In 1984, the heat was artificially increased
in the attack missile to help the infernal infrared seeker. In
1991, the computer of a test missile received precise programming
beyond the bounds of reality for a real attack.
</P>
<P>
   Despite being 0-for-16 record in untainted hits, the ATM
withdrawals continue, fueled by our arrogant belief in technology,
the arms lobby, and the politics of fear that has supplanted
militaries in Asia and the Middle East for the old Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the House voting overwhelmingly to pursue missile
defense. This week, the Senate Appropriations Committee proposed to
add $200 million to President Clinton's six-year, $10.5 billion
project to determine if missile defense is feasible. Despite the
fact that it is nowhere close to feasible, NATO last week signed a
$300 million contract with THAAD's maker, Lockheed-Martin, to
develop a similar system for Europe.
</P>
<P>
   If the United States decides missile defense is feasible, it may
cost up to $28 billion to deploy. If NATO decides it can work, its
contract with Lockheed Martin can balloon to $20 billion by 2010.
</P>
<P>
   But feasibility seems a long way off since the United States is
currently in the worst slump of disasters in a decade in
old-fashioned space rocketry. In the last nine months, the United
States has had six major failures, costing $4 billion in lost,
destroyed, or misplaced military and communications satellites.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably one of the worst times in the launch history
of the country,'' said Howell M. Estes III, the former head of the
US Space Command. ``Even the old rockets aren't working, and some
of the newer rockets aren't working. That's the concern, and it
comes at the very time we most need to get the launch costs down
and assure access to space.''
</P>
<P>
   If it has become so hard getting satellites into space, then
missile defense is an impossible science fiction. It has less
chance hitting targets than ordinary gamblers have hitting the
number. The military keeps saying ``We will hit.'' We need to take
the ATM out of service and the Pentagon to Gamblers Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
