<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BJT29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Saturday, May 29,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-STRIKES _ WASHINGTON _ The latest developments on the
diplomatic front as the U.S.-led NATO bombings continue to pound
Yugoslavia. Russian special envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin returns to
Belgrade despite the war crimes indictment of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to continue efforts at a diplomatic settlement.
Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service). 30.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RIVALS _ TIRANA, Albania _ One of the biggest problems
facing post war Kosovo will be resolving the conflict between two
rival groups, both of which claim to be the legitimate government
of Kosovo. This confusion is already a problem as the groups are
battling to get contributions from foreigners, including
Albanian-Americans who are asked to give 3 percent of their
salaries to support the cause. The problems between the rival
governments are so deep that they accuse each other of criminal
acts including murder. (Roughton, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   GUNS _ Vice President Al Gore called today for quick House
action on gun control and accused Republicans of plotting to please
the gun lobby by delaying a vote on Senate-passed restrictions.
Meanwhile, everyone from Wayne LaPierre of the NRA to parents of
the Columbine shootings appearbefore the House Judiciary committee
to discuss gun control. (Foskett, Atlanta journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SENTENCING _ WASHINGTON _ The seven offices have posh
furnishings, a magnificent view of the U.S. Capitol grounds and a
budget of $10.2 million. All that's missing at the U.S. Sentencing
Commission is commissioners. Political sparring has left a headless
agency with no one to fulfill the function of setting guidelines
for 51,000 criminal sentences a year. (Malone, Cox News Service).
25.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   FAGAN _ Long-awaited court date for Stephen Fagan, the father
kidnapper. Will he plead, and will the judge accept it? Developing.
(Bennett, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   ANCIENT _ Ancient stone tools discovered along the Savannah
River are shattering long-held notions about the arrival of the
first Americans. New evidence unearthed from what may be the oldest
site of human occupation in the South, suggests that humans were
here at least 12,000 years ago - an idea that, until recently,
would have been considered archaeological heresy. On Friday, some
of the country's leading aerchaeologists converge on an ancient
flint quarry near Allendale, S.C. to inspect that latest bombshell
in the rapidly changing picture about the peopling of America.
(Toner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   DRAGGING _ KINGSTREE, S.C _ Two white men were jailed after
being accused of dragging a black man a quarter-mile alongside
their pickup truck. Sheriff's investigators had yet to determine a
motive, although Sheriff Kelvin Washington said today he asked the
FBI and state police for help in investigating possible civil
rights violations. (Riddle, Atlanta Journal-Constitution
freelancer; not for use by NYTNS clients).
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE-CURES _ ATLANTA _ As carnage piles up in school yards
and war zones, a group of scholars is gathering at Emory University
in Atlanta to look at the causes and possible cures of violence.
(White, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 17.
</P>
<P>
   VETERANS-CELEBRATE _ ATLANTA _ World War II veterans of the U.S.
Navy's Asian fleet from across the country gather tonight to
celebrate surviving the war and, for some, like metro Atlantan Pete
Burnette, years in a wartime prison. The annual reunion is under
way at the Holiday Inn in East Point. (Simpson, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   PROSTATE-CANCER-STAMP _ AUSTIN _ The new 33-cent prostate cancer
awareness stamp will be issued as part of the Ride for the Roses
fund-raising weekend hosted by the Lance Armstrong Foundation. The
ceremony is at noon in the main exhibit hall of the Austin
Convention Center. (Roser, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
