<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4963 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-REDHOT-BOS &LR;      05-28 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-REDHOT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILI PEPPERS HEAT UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We are the grand old statesmen of alternative rock,''
pronounces Red Hot Chili Peppers drummer Chad Smith, with mock
pride and a laugh. ``We were just playing in St. Louis with Blink
182 and all those guys come up to me and the drummer says, `Oh man,
I started playing drums because of you, man!' And, I'm like, `Oh my
God what am I, Led Zeppelin or something?'
</P>
<P>
   ``But hey, you know what: We're still making great music and
we're having a great time. We may be old farts, but we're not
boring. We want to be like Neil Young.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Hot Chili Peppers making great music and having a great
time in 1999. . . . This was not preordained, by any means. The
rock 'n' roll life is often a roller coaster, and the Peppers have
boarded it big time. There are highs, there are lows, there are
breathtaking turns. But the roller coaster keeps going around the
same track.
</P>
<P>
   Cut back to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Hot Chili Peppers make a hot album and go out on tour.
Things fall apart, drugs become involved, the band is in disarray.
``Emotionally bottomed out,'' in the words of bassist Flea,
discussing the period between ``BloodSugarSexMagik,'' their 1993
mega-breakthrough CD, and ``One Hot Minute'' in 1996. Flea
described a period of being ``bitter, upset, lonely.'' Some in the
band move on to other projects or drop out. Band status: Iffy at
best.
</P>
<P>
   Back to 1999. The Red Hot Chili Peppers are on the verge of
releasing a terrific, expansive album called ``Californication.''
This week, the hook-packed emphasis track, ``Scar Tissue,'' was
added by all 91 radio stations with a modern rock format. (The last
song to achieve that was U2's ``Discotheque'' in 1996.) ``Scar
Tissue'' was also added by 168 mainstream and heritage rock
stations. The Peppers are out on the road, having just completed a
five-city tour called ``Teen Tolerance,'' where the band played
clubs for high school kids. The price of admission? Suggestions on
how to end hatred among students in high schools. (It was inspired
by the school shootings at Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Peppers are in the middle of several radio
station-sponsored shows. Yet getting to this point was, once again,
a familiar, frustrating, and difficult process. There was a lot of
down time between 1996 and 1999. ``Toward the end of '96 we stopped
touring for `One Hot Minute,' '' says drummer Chad Smith, ``and
then we had to take a break and tried writing songs, and went to
Hawaii to try and write, and that didn't pan out too well.''
Guitarist Dave Navarro joined the Jane's Addiction Relapse Tour and
worked with Smith on a group called Spread; Flea had his projects,
including Banyan. As for singer Anthony Kiedis, Smith says, ``You
know, he's had his ups and downs with the (drug) addiction thing. I
can't really talk for him, but it's an ongoing thing, a disease.
It's always there.''
</P>
<P>
   Plus: ``We didn't have the real excitement of working
together,'' says Smith of that period. ``It felt more like a job.
Having fun is what it's all about for the Chili Peppers.''
</P>
<P>
   Guitarist John Frusciante had exited the Peppers in 1992,
replaced by Navarro, who held the position from 1993-1997. ``When
he left,'' says Smith, of Frusciante, ``he was really unhappy with
the whole music industry and how the band had gotten really popular
and we were playing really big places and it wasn't about the art
for him anymore. It felt like it was all about the big machine, the
touring and the money.'' He stepped out of the band, painted, read,
and ``it worked for a while,'' says Smith. ``Drugs were a part of
that. You know how it works for a little bit and after a while it
doesn't? He ended up going `Ok, I did that.' '' He rejoined the
band and Smith says, ``He is all focused. I was really surprised to
hear he was clean and ready to go. As soon as we started playing in
Flea's garage, we just started rocking. There was such good
chemistry with the four of us there.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith says Frusciante's involvement was pivotal, both for
songwriting _ he's a more melodic writer than Navarro _ and from a
personal point of view. ``Playing with John,'' says Smith, ``it was
all about music. It felt so good, so right. Anthony has been so
great. There hasn't been any relapses. I don't know what's going to
happen tomorrow, but we just go with what's happening today and
what feels really good now.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith can't really explain how the magic works. ``We just all
get in a room and jam off the top of our heads, just make noise,
and the seeds of a lot of songs happen that way. If we hit on a
groove, and everybody is smiling, we'll tape it and do another.
We'll give tapes to Anthony so he can ride around in his car and
listen to them. He'll get inspired by something and come back with
melodies and words. (Producer) Rick Rubin comes in and we hone it
down, try to make the best songs we can.
</P>
<P>
   ``A very big part of the band is the love and respect we have
for one another, not just musically, but as people. It's the whole
brotherhood thing. It might sound hippie-ish, but it's sincere. We
are all so completely, spastically, different _ we're freaks _ but
there's balance and it just works for us. It's kind of an
intangible. You can't analyze it too much. I don't see how other
bands do it, riding separate buses and never seeing each other.
There's no vibe. And people pick up on that.''
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be the Chili Peppers without some deep funk grooves,
and there certainly are those on the new CD, beginning with the
first track, ``Around the World.'' But the album continues along
the more melodic direction the Peppers have been headed in for some
time. The title track is the centerpiece, a look at their home
state, particularly Los Angeles. Sings Kiedis: ``It's understood
that Hollywood sells Californication . . . Hard-core soft porn /
Dream of Californication . . . Space may be the final frontier /
But it's made in a Hollywood basement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Anthony is the principal lyrics writer,'' says Smith, ``and
it's really his take on how he sees the influence that Hollywood
and California have on the outside world. Some of it's very
negative, and some of it's beautiful, but it's got to such a point
where (Hollywood) makes the world so much smaller. Little kids,
wherever they are, watch the E! channel and say `I should be
dressing like this.' . . . There's some ugly, disgusting, terrible,
ridiculous, phony stuff going on in Los Angeles, and I've had some
of those experiences. But I'm not into that scene _ what kind of
car you drive, how much money you have. It has nothing to do with
real life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
