<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4971 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-ORGY-BOS &LR;      05-28 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-ORGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MONDAY' TAKES ORGY TO THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A pulsing, angst-y, but ultimately uplifting and melodic
techno-rock song called ``Blue Monday'' has been coursing over the
airwaves for some time now, with its singer repeatedly asking,
``How do I feel? How should I feel?'' A confused young America can
relate. Girls and boys, both.
</P>
<P>
   The singer is Jay Gordon and the band is Orgy, a sharply
dressed, spikey-haired, futuristic- and good-looking quintet from
southern California that seemed to have appeared, fully formed, on
the Korn-helmed Family Values tour last year. They had not cut
their teeth in clubland, yet they had a major label debut album,
``Candyass,'' and, suddenly, there they were in the arenas with
Korn, Rammstein, and Ice Cube.
</P>
<P>
   Now the album is on the verge of going platinum (having sold
almost 1 million copies), very much on the strength of ``Blue
Monday'' _ a song written and recorded by the moody English
electro-pop band New Order. Hmmm, the skeptics say. A big hit out
of the box, (itals)but not with their own song.(unitals)
Credibility? Perhaps, it is suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Orgy shrugs. What can you do?
</P>
<P>
   Signed to the Warner Bros.-backed Korn imprint label,
Elementree, Orgy is one of the hot bands playing at WBCN's sold-out
River Rave Sunday at the Tweeter Center in Mansfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it starts to go good,'' says guitar-synthist Amir Derakh,
``everybody wants to say, `Well you guys had it too easy.' It's
always like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Derakh doesn't want to pull a suffering artist act, but says,
``All of us have done the club circuit. We've been in many
different incarnations and other bands.'' (Guitarist Ryan Shuck,
bassist Paige Haley, and drummer Bobby Hewitt round out the unit.)
Three of the Orgy guys were in a band called Lit. Derakh even
logged time in an '80s hair metal band called Rough Cutt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of everything I've done,'' he says. ``I'm not
embarrassed by it. Every band I've been in has been different.
That's just the way I am. For me to keep doing this, I almost have
to re-invent myself to keep myself interested.'' Gordon and Derakh
have also engineered and produced for years.
</P>
<P>
   Orgy is a well-packaged outfit, no question. Derakh says their
fashion sense is as important as their sound. ``We wanted to make a
statement with the image. We didn't want to be grotesque or
anything _ we weren't gonna be GWAR _ but we wanted to have like a
clean, fresh, futuristic look, but still be a rock band. We knew
what we didn't want, being like KISS or whatever. That's too much.
It's great for them, but not what we're about.''
</P>
<P>
   A role model was Pete Burns, leader of the slinky glam/goth '80s
English group Dead or Alive. ``A great look,'' muses Derakh,
``pretty, yet masculine. I liked Dead or Alive and Duran Duran.''
</P>
<P>
   Other influences: David Bowie, Kraftwerk, Joy Division, Bauhaus,
Motley Crue, Ratt, Judas Priest, drum 'n' bass, house.
</P>
<P>
   The Orgy guys like to describe their music as a collage. Even
the band name, they claim, was inspired by the idea of a musical,
not sexual, orgy. ``The name is just a name,'' says Derakh. ``If it
makes people giggle or whatever, that's cool. But everything we do
besides the name has nothing to do with the sexual thing. We didn't
want to come out with a bunch of naked chicks on our record cover.
It's too one-dimensional. (Still) it gives it that double-entendre
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Their music is a mix of grinding hard-rock and aggro-techno.
Gordon has called it ``death pop.'' ``He said that once and it
stuck for a year,'' says Derakh, with a laugh. ``We were like `If
you took `death' and `pop' and put them together, it's kind of us,
because it gives you the black and the white. We like to have good
melodies and maybe our arrangements can sometimes be of a more
simple pop type, but there's this very dark foreboding undertone to
our music as well.''
</P>
<P>
   What of the ``Blue Monday'' effect? ``Only time will tell,''
says Derakh. ``I'm not going to complain about it. At least it got
us noticed. If the general public is going to think (of us), `Oh,
it's the band that does `Blue Monday,' well, hopefully we can
change that over time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did the song because we loved it, and we had no idea it was
going to be the single, or even on the record. I think we did it
justice. I think it sounds like us. It was probably one of my
favorite songs from the '80s. I was already a New Order fan and
that song cemented it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay and I were out CD shopping and talking about it,'' Derakh
says, ``and I said, `Do you got any New Order CDs? They have a good
one here if you want to buy it.' He's like, `Does it have ``Blue
Monday'' on it?' and I said, `Yeah, it does _ hey that would be a
good song for us to cover.' We took the CD back to the house,
listened to it, and everybody was like, `That would be fresh.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Within a few days we started working on it, and it just came
together pretty easily. It took a while to get the arrangement the
way we wanted to because we wanted it to be different, but keep the
integrity of the original. The way it was orginally arranged, it
was much more dance-oriented and one-dimensional; we needed to add
more dynamics to it to make it an Orgy song. We put a chorus on it,
which it didn't have. It never had that big `How does it feel?'
(New Order's Bernard Sumner) only sings that once and it's in the
verse.''
</P>
<P>
   They tinkered with the melody slightly, grunged up the guitar
and performed it not via computers or keyboard synthesizers (a la
New Order) but live. (Orgy's synthesizer sounds come from Derakh,
who plays a guitar-synth.) Says Derakh: ``Our drummer plays all
electronic drums. We have no tapes, no sequencing, pre-recordings
or click tracks.'' The same applies in concert, he says.
</P>
<P>
   How does ``Blue Monday'' fit Orgy's ethos?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a mixture of things,'' says Derakh. ``I think there's
the darkness _ it's sort of a dark relationship song _ and we write
those, too. Aside from that a lot of our stuff is pure fantasy,
things our singer imagined. Some of it can be placed into real
situations involving people we know and some of it is just made up.
None of it paints a specific picture. Basically, it's up for
interpretation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
