   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-BILL (Yulee, Fla.) _ Hillary Clinton gets top billing at
a panel discussion on Sunday, where Bill Clinton is also scheduled
to make an appearance. It is just another sign of a shift in the
couple's dynamic balance as she decides not whether to run for
Senate, but how to run. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   FAGAN-KIDNAP (Boston) _ Stephen Fagan, the former Framingham,
Mass., man accused of kidnapping his two young daughters 20 years
ago and then reinventing himself as a Florida socialite, will plead
guilty to kidnapping today. The plea will spare him jail time. By
Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   BABY-SELLING (Dateline to kum, N.Y.) _ In the wake of charges
against two women involving the selling of babies smuggled into the
U.S. from Mexico, we talk to families who adopted children through
them. By David M. Halbfinger.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Washington) _ The column: Vice President Gore
elaborates on his idea to have churches help out the poor. By Peter
Steinfels.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HYBRID-CARS (Albany, N.Y.) _ While electric cars have so far
failed to catch on, burdened by high cost and weak performance, a
genuine market is about to emerge for clean, peppy hybrids that can
go twice as far as a conventional car on a gallon of gasoline.
These cars use batteries and electric motors, but also depend on
gasoline or diesel engines as well. Hybrids are now the subject of
intense efforts by almost every major auto maker. By Matthew L.
Wald.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Looking at a dismal week for stocks. While
stocks are higher today, the Dow Jones industrial average has
fallen 2.5 percent this week, leaving it 5 percent below its most
recent high. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-PIRACY (Hong Kong) _ Movie industry executives took it
for granted that bootleg copies of the new ``Star Wars'' would soon
turn up here. But the warp speed with which it flew from American
cinemas to Asian streets _ two days _ has left people whipsawed.
And the movie doesn't even open here until July 1. The knockoffs
are a vivid illustration of how the purloining of movies has been a
flashpoint in trade relations between the U.S. and China. By Mark
Landler.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITURST (San Francisco) _ Microsoft lawyers depose
Gordan Eubanks, a former chief executive of Symantec, in the
antitrust suit brought by the Justice Department. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-BANKS (Rome) _ Italian banks, like banks across Europe,
are struggling to merge, to cut costs and create the larger capital
bases they will need to finance customers on the big new euro
market. Yet recent efforts have failed, blocked by an unusual, if
unintended, alliance of the Italian central bank and the Milan
investment bank, Mediobanca. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   NEC-EARNINGS (Tokyo) _ The NEC Corp., the world's second-largest
semiconductor manufacturer now in the midst of an extensive
overhaul, reports a $1.3 billion loss for its fiscal year. By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
