<P>
   &UR; IDEAS PAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAN-MURDERS (Undated) _ At the heart of the analysis of the
killings last month at Columbine High School in Colorado has been a
deceptively simple question: Were the killers chillingly aberrant
monsters or were they a part, however perverse, of something in our
culture as a whole? But long before Columbine, this question and
others were being asked by professors as homicide became an
increasingly conspicuous slice of American scholarship. By Peter
Applebome. (1500 words)
</P>
<P>
   MAPS-HISTORY (Undated) _ The history of maps once seemed a
quaint preoccupation. Aged maps _ with their compass roses, their
illuminated borders and their vast blank spaces _ were sought by
collectors and historians but were otherwise considered artful
relics of ignorance, faltering steps on the way to modern
geography. No longer. In the past 25 years there has been a sea
change in the world of cartography. The study of maps has come to
seem urgently contemporary, taking on all the contours now familiar
from recent academic studies of history, literature and culture. In
this realm, they are being looked at as instruments of power. By
Edward Rothstein. (1700 words)
</P>
<P>
   TRILLING-PROTEST (Undated) _ A psychiatrist on the board of
American Scholar quits to protest James Trilling's article about
his father. By Sarah Boxer. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER CULTURE AND ENTERTAINMENT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-INHERIT-REVIEW (Undated) _ On Showtime, a 1999 TV film,
``Inherit the Wind.'' Reviewed by Walter Goodman.
</P>
