<HEADER>
A4990 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-SEAL-REVIEW-HNS     05-28 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SEAL-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAL A REAL `HUMAN BEING' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seal's latest album is ``Human Being.'' The title is a wry
commentary on the way music is labeled and marketed in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's anything that saddens me, it's the segregation
between people and music in the United States,'' Seal said by phone
from his home in Los Angeles. ``Why are there such tall boundaries
between R&AMP;B, or black music, and white music?
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming from England, that's the thing I find most stifling
about the United States. In Europe, it's not really like that.
Basically, radio stations play everything. And that's really how it
should be, man. I don't just make music for black people or for
white people. I make it for my brothers and sisters, my fellow
human beings. There should be no rules.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Seal will perform at the Cynthia Woods Mitchell
Pavilion in The Woodlands, Texas. He's bringing a band of fellow
human beings that includes studio ace Michael Landau on guitar,
former Bruce Springsteen keyboardist David Sancious, former Peter
Gabriel bassist Tony Levin and Louisiana-born jazz drummer Brian
Blade.
</P>
<P>
   The show marks Seal's first Houston-area appearance since a 1995
date in The Woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. It hasn't been that long, has it?'' he said. ``You know
something? I don't even know. You'd probably know better than I
would.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Human Being,'' which features a nude silhouette of the artist
bathed in blue light on the cover, was more than four years in the
making. Released in November, the album so far has failed to match
the multiplatinum sales of 1994's ``Seal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a difficult record, but then most of my records tend to
be quite difficult,'' Seal said in a proper British accent. ``I
think that I wrote the songs that I needed to write in terms of the
message that I'm sending out, which is one of love and harmony, a
message of humanitarianism. And so it is a success for me from a
spiritual and artistic point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he's given up on the album's commercial prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``My records tend to stay around for a long time, and they have
an unorthodox path in terms of their commercial success,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My second album had four singles released from it, including
''Kiss From a Rose,`` which was a stiff the first time around. The
album was counted out, dead and gone, then what happened was this
big movie came along called ''Batman Forever`` and basically
brought ''Kiss From a Rose`` to a lot of people's attention. Four
Grammys later, everyone's saying, `Of course, what a fantastic
song.'''
</P>
<P>
   Seal was born Sealhenry Olumide Samuel 35 years ago in London to
a Nigerian mother and a Brazilian father. Although he now projects
a stylishly erudite air, he grew up poor and on the streets. At one
point, he was put up for adoption and then reclaimed by his father.
The mysterious-looking scars on his cheeks are the result of a
childhood bout with lupus.
</P>
<P>
   Seal's 1991 self-titled debut album produced the dance-pop hits
``Crazy and Killer,'' but it was ``Kiss From a Rose'' that
catapulted him to stardom in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The songs on ``Human Being'' tend to follow in even more moody
and intricate patterns, with Trevor Horn's sleek Euro-pop
production contrasting with Seal's smolderingly soulful vocals and
philosophical lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Colour'' is a plea for racial harmony, while ``Human Beings''
refers to the deaths of rappers Tupac Shakur and the Notorious BIG.
Other songs, such as ``No Easy Way'' and ``When a Man Is Wrong,''
were inspired by his romantic travails with supermodel Tyra Banks
and another ex-flame.
</P>
<P>
   Seal says he emerged from those relationships wiser and
stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point I was trying to make was that any experience like
that is a strengthening experience, one that stimulates growth, if
you choose to see it that way. I wanted people to be able to
identify with it and say, `OK, it's not just me that goes through
that.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Both men and women, we go through all kinds of disillusion. We
go through periods of being disconnected from the self, of acting
outside of ourselves through fear and insecurity. My relation to
the album was one of constantly searching for love and harmony in
other people, rather than knowing that charity begins at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Seal has since come to better terms with himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in the most wonderful place of my entire life that I think
I could ever be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And what has brought on this change?
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, that's what brought on the change. My connection with
myself and my connection with everything around me, with God. Not
necessarily in the biblical sense, but that, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Seal promises his next album won't take as long to make as the
last one. He says the album will be a dance-oriented project
incorporating elements of his West African heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thinking of doing some Ghanian highlife, some Nigerian
juju, deeper stuff. There's a whole wealth of goodies in that
area.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, however many copies ``Human Being'' eventually sells,
Seal said he'll always be proud of the songs on the album.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very funny and fragile concept, the music business. You
can't really get too bogged down by it. Obviously, I look back on
the album and think there's one or two things I could have done
better, but I consider the work on this album to be my best work.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
