<HEADER>
A4993 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLEEPWALKER-TRIAL-4-A     05-28 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPWALKER-TRIAL-4-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER CELL MATE, CHILDREN TAKE STAND  
 (ADV: FOURTH OF FOUR STORIES RECOUNTING WEEK'S TRIAL ACTION) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Scott Falater's sleeping patterns were the focus of
Thursday's testimony at his murder trial, as a former jail cellmate
told jurors Falater walked in his sleep several times while
confined at the Madison Street Jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott got down from the bunk, went over to the door and shook
the heck out of the door,'' said Robert Bluntschly, who shared a
cell with Falater during most of 1997. He said Falater repeated the
pattern two or three times.
</P>
<P>
   Bluntschly's testimony bolstered Falater's defense in Maricopa
County Superior Court against first-degree murder charges in the
1997 death of his wife of 20 years, Yarmila.
</P>
<P>
   Falater's attorneys admit that he stabbed his wife 44 times and
dragged her into their backyard pool at their Phoenix home. But
they say he was sleepwalking at the time and therefore cannot be
held criminally liable.
</P>
<P>
   Bluntschly testified that the sleepwalking Falater moved rigidly
in the cell and did not respond when Bluntschly asked if something
was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I told him later, he had no memory of doing it,'' said
Bluntschly, who is appealing a murder conviction on charges of
killing his fiancee.
</P>
<P>
   Falater's two teenage children also testified Thursday, telling
jurors their parents had a gentle, loving relationship in which
they never fought and managed to smooth over disagreements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just like any other home,'' Michael Falater, 15, told
the jury of 10 women and five men. ``We were happy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We all loved each other and tried to support each other as
best we could,'' said 17-year-old Megan Falater, the valedictorian
of this year's graduating class at North Canyon High School.
</P>
<P>
   Both children remained poised, despite the obvious strain of
testifying in the case that stems from their mother's death and
could end with their father's execution.
</P>
<P>
   Megan, who plans to begin studies this fall at the University of
Chicago, made her feelings clear when asked what she wanted for her
brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like for him to be with Dad, so I can go to college,
and he will be with his family,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But under cross-examination by prosecutor Juan Martinez, the
Falater children acknowledged that until their mother's death, they
had not been told that their father was a sleepwalker.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez also sought to undermine Bluntschly's credibility,
pointing to his criminal record and ridiculing the testimony that
Falater moved rigidly during the sleepwalking episodes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's approximately two feet from the end of the bed to the
bars'' in the door, Martinez said. ``He was rigid for two steps?''
</P>
<P>
   When testimony resumes Tuesday, defense attorneys plan to call
other relatives of Scott Falater to talk about his history of
sleepwalking. Falater's sister has told investigators that he
lifted her and tossed her across a room during a sleepwalking
episode 20 years ago at the family's Illinois home.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors are also expected to hear testimony from Falater's
colleagues at Motorola about the work-related stresses that,
according to the defense team, played havoc with Falater's sleep in
the weeks before the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's testimony from the Falater children also indicated
that sleepwalking runs in the family.
</P>
<P>
   Megan talked about getting up in the middle of the night and
preparing for school until her father told her to go back to bed.
And Michael recalled his inability to understand an instance when
he awoke in the living room after falling asleep in his bed.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning from defense attorneys, the Falater children
undermined the defense theory that Scott and Yarmila Falater had
become estranged because of tensions stemming from their membership
in the Mormon Church.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez is attempting to convince jurors that although Scott
was a devoted Mormon, Yarmila resented the church's intrusions on
her time and Scott's desire to have more children.
</P>
<P>
   Megan testified that while her mother disliked individuals
within the church, she respected the institution. She said her
parents' disagreements on the size of the family were handled in a
light-hearted manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quite sure that was not a problem,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
