</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ZELNICK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR DEFENDS HIS BOOK ON GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ After three decades covering political battles
from Tel Aviv to Moscow to Capitol Hill, it seemed natural for
journalist Bob Zelnick to write a book about one of America's
foremost politicians: Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision to write ``Gore: A Political Life,'' cost him
his job as an ABC News correspondent and has made him a target of
attacks by Gore supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Zelnick, now a visiting professor of journalism at Boston
University, defended the book in an interview with the San
Francisco Examiner as a fair and balanced look at the Democratic
presidential hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't pull any punches, but it doesn't take any cheap
shots either,'' Zelnick said.
</P>
<P>
   The book's release March 29, about a year before Democratic
voters in California and other states begin picking a nominee for
the 2000 presidential race, has irritated the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While the biography is at times flattering, it also hones in on
what Zelnick sees as Gore's weak spots, from his questionable
campaign fund-raising tactics to his refusal to admit he reversed
his stance on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast with Gore's boss, President Clinton, the vice
president is depicted as a man of strong morals, a dedicated
husband and father of four. But as a leader, Zelnick says Gore's
high principles have made him intolerant of dissenting views,
especially on environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central weak spot in Al Gore's character is an overbearing
self-righteousness that doesn't allow for the possibility of error
and therefore doesn't allow for the possibility of well-meaning
opposition,'' Zelnick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't escape the feeling that a self-righteous person who
does not concede the possibility of another reputable point of view
poses a certain danger when he has the power of the presidency in
his hands,'' Zelnick said.
</P>
<P>
   The book ended his 21-year career at ABC News, where he had
worked as a Pentagon correspondent and foreign correspondent in
Israel and the former Soviet Union. ABC executives felt the
biography would undermine Zelnick's credibility as a Capitol Hill
correspondent and hurt the network's reputation, so he resigned
last February.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's political team has been bashing the book since before it
was released, claiming it contains no new information and is a
right-wing attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a regurgitation of old news,'' said Roger Salazar, deputy
press secretary for the Gore campaign. ``(It) represents an effort
to plow old ground in hopes of kicking up some mud.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is published by Regnery Press of Washington, which has
published books by Republican firebrand Patrick Buchanan and Rep.
Dick Armey, R-Texas. Zelnick concedes the publishing house is
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be a right-wing publisher, but I'm not a right-wing
author,'' said Zelnick, who describes his own views as
``center-right'' _ liberal on most social issues and conservative
on economic and national security issues.
</P>
<P>
   His first book, ``Backfire: A Reporter's Look at Affirmative
Action,'' also published by Regnery in 1996, angered many liberals
because of its sharp criticism of affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore biography details how the vice president, the son of a
Tennessee senator, was groomed for a role in government from the
time he was a boy. He attended the elite Washington prep school,
St. Albans, and later studied government at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief stint as an army reporter in Vietnam and as a
staff writer for the Nashville Tennessean, Gore parlayed his family
name into a seat in the House of Representatives and later the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   While his father was known as a left-of-center Southern
lawmaker, Gore billed himself as a ``screaming moderate.'' He
became one of Congress' top nuclear arms experts and was one of 10
Senate Democrats who backed President George Bush's Persian Gulf
War amendment _ a vote the hawkish Zelnick lauds as an ``act of
conscience'' that could have hurt his political career if the war
had gone badly.
</P>
<P>
   But at other moments, Zelnick charges, Gore sacrificed his
principles for political expediency. As a congressman he voted
several times for amendments banning the use of federal funds for
abortions _ part of his view that government should not be seen as
endorsing the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   But during a debate in the 1992 presidential campaign, when Gore
was the running mate of a strongly pro-choice Bill Clinton,
then-vice president Dan Quayle reminded Gore of his earlier
``pro-life'' position. ``That's simply not true,'' Gore responded.
</P>
<P>
   Zelnick credits the vice president, along with Clinton, for
``yanking the Democratic Party out of the (1972 Democratic
presidential candidate George) McGovern era and moving it to the
center.'' But especially in Gore's strong environmental views, the
author sees a streak of extremism he finds troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   In Senate hearings on global warming, Gore was hostile to
scientists who said the phenomenon of rising temperatures needed
more study before taking drastic action, Zelnick writes. And when a
former professor of Gore's from Harvard joined in an academic paper
downplaying the threat of global warming, Gore and his aides
claimed the aging educator had been coerced by the co-authors, the
book says.
</P>
<P>
   The book also rehashes disclosures about Gore's efforts to raise
money for the 1996 election _ including the claim that a Buddhist
temple fund-raiser was an ``outreach'' event.
</P>
<P>
   But Zelnick finds no fault with Attorney General Janet Reno's
decision not to appoint an independent counsel to probe Gore's
fund- raising efforts, particularly his questionable calls to
donors from the White House. Democratic and Republican lawyers told
Zelnick the law is too vague and the case against the vice
president had too many holes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
