<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-MAMET-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEREMY NORTHAM PLAYS TO TYPE IN `THE WINSLOW BOY' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Much has been made of filmmaker David Mamet going against his
usual style with his new, much-praised ``The Winslow Boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mamet, known for his caustic R-rated dialogue (``Glengarry Glen
Ross''), mature themes of deceit (``House of Games,'' ``The Spanish
Prisoner'') and enigmatic, clipped characterizations, has produced
a G-rated version of a popular play (by the late Terence Rattigan)
in which everyone behaves with great restraint and uses oh, so
proper language.
</P>
<P>
   For actor Jeremy Northam, however, the film is a return to
exactly what people expect of him. Northam plays a very British,
very gentlemanly lawyer in the early 20th century, a role similar
to many he has played before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care if I (ever) do another movie with a wing
collar,'' the actor says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   At 37, the tall, darkly handsome Northam _ one of the most
popular actors on the British stage _ has spent a great deal of his
career playing proper Englishmen in period stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have always thought of me in terms of costume drama,''
he says. ``I think I have a whiff of the previous century about me.
I must have more showers.''
</P>
<P>
   His own joke obviously amuses him.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many British actors, Northam certainly doesn't behave or
speak stuffily _ he jokes around and uses slang _ although there is
no mistaking the British accent.
</P>
<P>
   After he did ``Emma,'' the Jane Austen adaptation in which he
played Mr. Knightley opposite Gwyneth Paltrow's title character,
Northam worried that he might be too typecast as an Englishman of
the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as you do something that people respond to, then
that's what you do (all the time),'' Northam says.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he tried to break out of the mold. After ``Emma''
and another period role as a judge in Amistad, he played an
American in the offbeat horror film ``Mimic'' and an Irish thug in
``Gloria.''
</P>
<P>
   He also made the upcoming ``Happy, Texas,'' a small independent
comedy in which he plays an escaped convict who hides out as a gay
pageant organizer.
</P>
<P>
   But the switch to contemporary was temporary. In his two films
this summer he plays English gentlemen from the past, both
barristers (lawyers) with the title ``Sir'' in front of their
names.
</P>
<P>
   In ``An Ideal Husband,'' the new film version of the Oscar Wilde
play due here June 25, Northam is Sir Robert Chiltern, a politician
whose marriage and position are threatened when a former fiancee
(Julianne Moore) rattles a skeleton in his closet. That film
co-stars Cate Blanchett and Rupert Everett.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Winslow Boy,'' Northam is Sir Robert Morton, the lawyer
and politician who takes the case of a 12-year-old boy accused of
stealing at his school. The boy is expelled and denies the charges.
</P>
<P>
   There is a small irony in Northam's playing these two roles.
Morton is based on the real-life Edward Carson, the lawyer who
prosecuted Wilde.
</P>
<P>
   The 1910 case that inspired ``The Winslow Boy'' was that of
13-year-old George Archer-Shee. Rattigan changed all the names and
many of the personalities involved, although the story remained
basically true. It was filmed once before, starring Robert Donat
(``Goodbye Mr. Chips'') in Northam's role.
</P>
<P>
   There has been much speculation about Mamet's decision to turn
this particular play into a movie. No doubt he was influenced by
the chance to direct his wife, British actress Rebecca Pidgeon
(``The Spanish Prisoner''), in a British role. He also cast her
brother, Matthew Pidgeon, as her brother in the film.
</P>
<P>
   But Northam thinks it was mainly Mamet's longtime interest in
the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``David just loved the mechanics of the play, the craftsmanship
that went into the structuring and the telling of the story, the
way it worked like a perfect little machine, which it does.''
</P>
<P>
   After doing ``The Ideal Husband,'' ``Happy, Texas'' and ``The
Winslow Boy'' in a row, Northam has had more down time than he
really wants recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've actually not worked since August last year,'' he said.
``I did a play in London that finished (at) the end of February.
I'm looking forward to working again.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in a wing collar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
