<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5047 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RIVALS-0529-CO     05-28 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RIVALS-0529-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUGOVA VS THACI: KOSOVAR ALBANIANS ALSO FACE CRISIS OF
LEADERSHIP
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIRANA, Albania _If and when ethnic Albanians are returned to
Kosovo by NATO, they must confront yet another formidable challenge
to unifying their shattered province.
</P>
<P>
   Each other.
</P>
<P>
   Pushed into exile here and elsewhere by the crisis in Kosovo,
two rival groups led by two equally popular men are engaged in a
bitter campaign to gain acceptance as the legitimate government of
Kosovo, the embattled southern province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's
dominant republic.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign is beginning to worry Western diplomats, who are
pressing the two sides to resolve their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Ibrahim Rugova, who has held the title ``president of the
Republic of Kosovo'' for seven years, had been the most visible
Kosovar leader before the NATO air war against Yugoslavia. But
Rugova, who is called the ``Ghandi of the Balkans,'' is seen by
many Kosovar Albanians as too moderate in his push for an
independent Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   He earned the enmity of committed separatists in April when he
was seen on television news tapes meeting with Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic and signing a joint declaration calling for an
end to the air strikes.
</P>
<P>
   His detractors were unmoved by explanations by Rugova supporters
that he was pressured by Serb authorities, who held him captive in
his home in Pristina, Kosovo's provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova's softening support has been exploited effectively by the
more militant Hashim Thaci, who is described here as the prime
minister of the Interim Government of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Thaci is closely associated with the Kosovo Liberation Army, the
rebel force that helped elevate the struggle in Kosovo into warfare
by attacking Serb police and soldiers last spring. On Friday, Thaci
arrived in the United States to meet with government officials.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   The men couldn't be more different. Rugova is a 54-year-old,
Paris-educated literary academic. In 1992, he was elected president
of the self-proclaimed Republic of Kosovo in polls ignored by
Belgrade. He was re-elected last April but more militant and
impatient ethnic Albanians boycotted the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Thaci, 28, is a handsome former student activist who has been
sentenced to jail by a Serb court for subversion. His nickname is
``Snake.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   While Western diplomats have favored Rugova, they are finding it
hard to ignore Thaci, who has demonstrated keen political skills.
Yet, his status is complicated by his association with the KLA,
which NATO intends to disarm as part of any peace arrangement with
the Serbs when Kosovo is liberated. Additionally, Thaci and the KLA
want Kosovo to be completely independent of Yugoslavia, a goal NATO
officially opposes.
</P>
<P>
   Thaci also enjoys the support of the Albanian government and has
been making the rounds here over the past week seeking broader
political support.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the week, Thaci made a series of highly publicized
appeals to Rugova to come to Tirana so the leaders could patch up
their differences.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova refused, intensifying the rivalry. Some critics have come
close to calling Rugova a traitor. Paskal Milo, the Albanian
foreign minister, on Thursday accused Rugova of recklessly
undermining Albanian unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``By skipping his meeting, Rugova has rendered the greatest
possible disservice to the cause of Kosova and to his standing as a
politician,'' Milo told a local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   He said NATO officials had also expressed concern about the
rift. ``When foreigners see there is no unity among Kosovar factors
they are in a dilemma,'' Milo said.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova supporters here dismiss Thaci as a Marxist troublemaker
who is allowing his own ambition to create confusion over Kosovo's
leadership. They also worry that the presence of two Kosovo
governments is harming their ability to raise money abroad.
Albanians in the United States and elsewhere have funded Rugova's
government with a voluntary 3 percent income tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very difficult problem,'' said Ramadan Musliu, the
editor of Rilindja, a Kosovar newspaper printed in exile. ``Who
will win is not clear. The KLA is divided, too, but they put their
divisions away to fight the Serb criminals. Who knows what will
happen when they no longer have the Serbs to unite them.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, U.S. officials are trying to forge a
settlement but have been frustrated by their inability to talk to
Rugova, who has visited Italy and Macedonia since being freed by
Milosevic, but not Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian government officials believe Washington is beginning to
side with Thaci, who emerged as a leader during talks in
Rambouillet, France. The talks produced the peace plan, signed by
both Thaci and Rugova, that NATO is seeking to impose on Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers here reported that Thaci has been engaged in lengthy
talks with U.S. officials. ``The United States will now have their
final say and it seems that luck will be with Hashim Thaci,''
reported the independent daily, Koha Jone.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Embassy here did not respond to requests for a
clarification of the government's position on the rift.
</P>
<P>
   Musliu believes that the only solution will be internationally
monitored elections in Kosovo once its people are returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``But these people have no homes or food, no way to live,'' he
said. ``First, these things must be addressed. Only then can we
decide the politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
