<SLUG> BC-AREA-CODES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FCC CONSIDERS WAYS TO LIMIT NUMBER OF AREA CODES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Consumer groups and state regulators in
California applauded a Federal Communications Commission proposal
to curb the manic growth of new area codes.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC announced Thursday that it would look at ways to limit
the creation of area codes in the future. The boom has been created
in part by the growing number of lines dedicated to facsimile
machines and Internet connections.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most prominent measure under consideration is
reducing the size of number blocks awarded to phone companies.
Currently, companies are assigned 10,000 new phone numbers at a
time. Under that system, many numbers go unused. The FCC proposes
to reduce the number blocks to 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting the size of number blocks, the agency said, would
prevent telephone companies from controlling or hoarding unused
numbers that could be allocated to other carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Because numbers can only be assigned in huge blocks, ``There are
over 160 million phone numbers that could be available in
California, but only 30 to 40 million are being used,'' said Regina
Costa, a telecommunications specialist at the Utility Reform
Network in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Sullivan, a telecommunications adviser at the California
Public Utilities Commission, said the FCC's proposal was ``an
encouraging first step. It's been long-awaited. It appears the FCC
now understands the problems we're facing in California.''
</P>
<P>
   That problem is a potential tripling of the state's area codes
from 13 in early 1997 to at least 39 by 2001 if new federal
guidelines are not created and enforced.
</P>
<P>
   There are 215 area codes across the United States, almost double
the 119 in service in 1991. Industry officials project the need for
30 new codes a year unless changes are made.
</P>
<P>
   Adding digits to existing phone numbers could solve the problem,
the agency said, but that could take years and cost billions of
dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
