<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS HURRIED AS HMOS SET PACE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Holding his cellular phone in one hand and checking
his pager with the other, Alan Glombicki careened down the freeway,
swerving in and out of traffic.
</P>
<P>
   He nearly ran up the back end of several cars, putting on his
brakes in the nick of time. Seeing me trembling with fear in the
passenger seat, Glombicki assured me that he's a professional at
this high-speed dodge 'em game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be a cab driver in Boston,'' said the
gastroenterologist, who was in a hurry to see patients at Methodist
Hospital and Park Plaza Hospital in Houston because he had a
waiting room full of patients back at the office.
</P>
<P>
   Fast driving has become a critical skill in this environment of
managed care. Doctors need enough volume to pay their overhead
expenses because of lower managed care reimbursements. Many, like
Glombicki, actually trot from exam room to exam room.
</P>
<P>
   Employers change health plans to save money, so they sign
contracts with a variety of hospitals, said Glombicki, as he tore
down an alley marked ``wrong way.'' Glombicki logs an average of
100 miles a day in his car, seeing patients scattered around area
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   I got a chance to watch Glombicki in action because the Harris
County Medical Society has a mini-internship program that pairs
members of the community with doctors in a variety of practices.
This week I spent two days with four doctors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A DROPOUT FROM MANAGED CARE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The speed at which Glombicki worked is the reason David Miller
got out of the managed care business three years ago. Miller, an
internist whose office is at the Texas Medical Center, dropped his
health maintenance organization contracts and sees only 17 patients
a day, about half of what many doctors see.
</P>
<P>
   It was crazy seeing 30 patients a day, said Miller, who never
appears to be in a hurry and always calls his patients by their
names. ``How's your mother?'' he asked one patient. ``Is she
feeling OK?''
</P>
<P>
   When he had HMO contracts, Miller said, he didn't have enough
time to visit with his patients. Instead he was spending time with
clerks on the phone trying to get tests approved, filling out forms
and faxing them back and forth. And then he'd wait three to six
months to get paid.
</P>
<P>
   There is room for a small-town doc who doesn't do managed care,
said Miller, who is proud his patients are referred by other
patients and not from ``the book,'' the derogatory term referring
to the list of approved providers that insurance carriers publish.
</P>
<P>
   For most doctors, a constant flow of patients is a way of life.
And all that meeting, greeting and doctoring can be emotionally
exhausting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like being on stage,'' said Margaret Kinalska, a
pediatrician who saw 39 patients on a recent day. Every few minutes
she goes into an exam room to meet another child and parent and
tries to establish rapport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every five minutes it's solving a problem,'' she said with a
sigh, as she noticed she had to spend so much time on her first
afternoon patient that she was already way behind. She apologized
to all of the patients she had kept waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Kinalska tried to explain why the experience is so
emotionally draining. ``I feel the burden. I know they expect
something from me. They examine me and it's very important what I
say.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE BATTLE OVER REFERRALS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doctors seem to spend an inordinate amount of time filling out
forms proving they need to refer a patient to a specialist, then
fighting with insurance companies that refuse the request.
</P>
<P>
   It's so frustrating, Glombicki said, as he sorted through a
stack of parking access passes while waiting to enter a hospital
garage.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he said, some insurance companies don't want to pay
for liver transplants unless a patient is at death's door, even
though the plan they sell employers clearly says that liver
transplants are covered.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies know patient turnover runs 20 to 30 percent,
so if someone is a candidate for a liver transplant before getting
really sick, chances are they will be with another carrier when the
transplant becomes critical, Glombicki said.
</P>
<P>
   Back at his office, Glombicki counsels one patient, who has been
off from work, about the perils of long-term disability. Many
times, that's an excuse for an employer to fire an employee who is
seriously ill, he said.
</P>
<P>
   After the patient left, Glombicki said he gets calls from
insurance companies complaining that employers believe the doctor
is being too lenient with time off from work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not subtle,'' he said. ``They'll say: `Of course, use
your medical judgment, &QL; 
but ...'''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
