<HEADER>
A5065 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SENTENCING29-COX     05-28 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SENTENCING29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SENTENCING AGENCY HAS $9.3 MILLION, 87 WORKERS, NO BOSSES
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The seven spacious offices have posh furnishings,
magnificent views of the Capitol grounds and a staff of 87
assistants down the hall. All that's missing at the U.S. Sentencing
Commission is commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   For seven months, this agency with a $9.3 million budget has had
no one to oversee its guidelines for the 51,000 federal criminal
sentences a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the last occupant of the suite,'' Tim McGrath said this
week. As the former top aide to the last chairman, he has been left
in charge after the commissioners left one by one, starting more
than two years ago. President Clinton and the Senate have been
wrangling much of that time over who will replace them.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, unfinished work stacks up, with Congress
sending new directives for tougher sentences for sexual predators,
trafficking in methamphetamines, and cellular phone fraud. With no
commissioners, no decisions can be made on new guidelines and no
adjustments made to existing ones.
</P>
<P>
   That has frustrated lawyers and judges alike, many of whom were
already critical of the agency, which was established as a
non-political effort to bring uniformity to federal criminal
penalties. Without a commission, they say, the system becomes too
rigid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason Congress established a commission rather than
passing mandatory sentencing laws for every offense is they wanted
to build in flexibility, so that, as the commission received
feedback, the guidelines could be amended,'' said U.S. District
Judge Frederic N. Smalkin in Baltimore. ``It's pretty hard to do
that without a commission.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan J. Chaset, a Virginia attorney who chairs a sentencing
committee for the National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers,
said that without a functioning commission, there's no one to
resolve disputes among courts over sentencing guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-year-old commission, whose chairman is paid $145,000 a
year, was supposed to be non-political. But for years, vacancies
have touched off contests among politicians over whose top aide or
ally will be appointed. Senate Democrats competed with each other
for months over their four slots, and Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott, R-Miss., and Senate Judiciary Chairman Orrin Hatch, R-Utah,
have vied over the three posts allotted to Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``So they're saying, 'we can't agree on it, so we won't do
anything,' `` Chaset said. ``If it's not important enough to give
this $10 million agency the people to run it, why have it?''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to President Clinton are promising action soon. ``We're
aware of the situation. We'd like to nominate a bipartisan slate
shortly,'' said White House spokesman Jake Siewert. He said that
``shortly'' means ``in the next month or so.''
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Hatch said that the senator ``has been working with
the White House to try to get names up here who are confirmable.''
</P>
<P>
   Back at the vacant commissioner suite, McGrath said his headless
agency is continuing to enter case information into computers,
draft options for the unnamed new commissioners to rule on later,
and give briefings on sentencing rules. They also check White House
and congressional offices for news of appointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing the word 'imminent,' `` McGrath said. ``But I've
been hearing 'imminent' for the last seven months.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
