<SLUG> BC-ASSISTED-SUICIDE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKER PUTS EUTHANASIA BILL ON HOLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SALLADAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The lawmaker sponsoring a bill that would
legalize assisted suicide in California conceded that she did not
have enough support for the measure, but said she might revive the
``Death with Dignity Act'' next year.
</P>
<P>
   Modeled after an Oregon law, the measure would allow terminally
ill patients to choose death with the help of a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try to get the Legislature up to where the
general public is, because clearly the public supports this,''
Assemblywoman Dion Aroner, a Democrat from Berkeley who sponsored
the bill, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Aroner's decision came after some legislative arm-twisting in
the Assembly Appropriations Committee Thursday. Aroner had worked
all day trying to get an 11th lawmaker on the 21-member committee
to support her bill.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Antonio Villaraigosa, a Democrat from Los
Angeles, agreed to temporarily replace an unsympathetic member of
the committee with Assemblywoman Hannah-Beth Jackson, a Democrat
from Santa Barbara, and the bill was approved by the committee.
</P>
<P>
   That exhaustive effort convinced Aroner that it would be nearly
impossible to get the 41 votes she would need for the bill to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a struggle to get 11 votes, can you imagine getting
41?'' said Hans Hemann, Aroner's aide.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately after introducing her measure this year,
Aroner said she believed it would be a tough sell in the
Legislature. She said it could take years of convincing skittish
members to support such a controversial issue.
</P>
<P>
   The measure requires that two doctors certify an ill person to
be mentally competent and ``reasonably determine'' that the patient
will die within six months. The patient would have to make four
requests, some in writing, before the lethal drugs would be
administered. Doctors would not be allowed to suggest assisted
suicide as an option; the patient must bring it up.
</P>
<P>
   Aroner said recent U.S. Supreme Court rulings that directed the
states to begin addressing the right-to-die issue, and strong
public support for euthanasia, meant it was ``finally time to begin
the discussion in California.''
</P>
<P>
   Although California voters rejected a ballot initiative on
euthanasia in 1992, a Field Poll released recently showed 75
percent of those surveyed now believed terminally ill patients
should have the right to get life-ending medication.
</P>
</TEXT>
