<SLUG> BC-GRADUATES-FAMILY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRADUATION DAY IS A FAMILY AFFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If the story of Scott, Toni and Junile Smith
were made into a movie, the last scene would be filmed Saturday
during graduation ceremonies at San Francisco State University.
</P>
<P>
   A freeze-frame finale: Three diploma-waving Smiths fall into
each others' arms, their commencement gowns blowing in the breeze;
a family healed as their future is revealed.
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths are college roommates who share apartment rent and
food expenses equally, who have studied, partied and attended
classes together.
</P>
<P>
   They are also father, mother and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths will enjoy their last academic exercise as a team
Saturday, receiving simultaneous bachelor's degrees from the
university's School of Speech and Communication.
</P>
<P>
   To accomplish that they abandoned their traditional family
relationship. In doing so, they strengthened it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's helped us a lot,'' said Junile Smith, 24, who had
attended the University of San Francisco on her own after
graduating from high school near Seattle. ``Before I went to USF,
we weren't really close. We weren't a family unit.''
</P>
<P>
   They weren't ready for what three years later would become an
unconventional family experiment. ``If we had been roommates while
I was at USF, we would have killed each other,'' Junile said with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The family's troubles began 18 years ago in San Diego, when
Scott and Toni Smith, both now 43, were married, and Scott adopted
Junile, Toni's daughter by a previous marriage. But at 6 years old
Junile was unwilling to accept Scott as her father. Scott, in turn,
did not respond well to her resentment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of conflict,'' Toni Smith said, ``a lot of
stress and anger between those two. They used to just bump heads
all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   After three years the family moved to Seattle. Scott worked for
the Department of Defense as an engineering and design technician.
Toni took a job at Seattle University Law School and owned her own
insurance company. They bought a house. By the time Junile started
high school, she and Scott had achieved a truce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like a truce of love or anything,'' Junile
explained. ``We had come to an understanding, but we weren't really
as close as we are now.''
</P>
<P>
   Junile eagerly left home to attend college, to pursue her own
life unburdened by adults who loved and annoyed her. Then, she
said, reality set in.
</P>
<P>
   ``College wasn't like it is in the movies,'' she recalled. She
missed her mom and, to her own surprise, she missed Scott.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think perhaps when she went to school she felt that `this
guy's been there for me,''' Toni said. ``He is my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   Junile dropped out of school and returned home. She returned to
parents who were also not content with their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were both doing well in our jobs as far as moving along,
but we were not satisfied with where it was taking us,'' Scott
said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next year, the three Smiths hatched a plan to pursue
their educations together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked this out and realized that if we were going to make
it work, we would have to sell our house, we would have to scale
down quite a bit,'' Toni said. ``We talked quite a bit about it. I
think we went into it with our eyes wide open.''
</P>
<P>
   That sense of acceptance extended to the family relationship:
``We just came to an understanding that we all had to look at each
other as adults,'' Toni said. ``She (Junile) couldn't just look at
us as her parents, and we couldn't look at her only as our
daughter. We decided how much money each of us needed to make for
it to work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths chose San Francisco State. Four years ago, they
packed their bags, moved into a Burlingame apartment and began what
Scott calls ``an excellent adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Smiths are contemplating their careers. One idea is to start
a family consulting business.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever career path they choose, they are now a family, the
long-standing rift between Scott and Junile having been consigned
to history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
