<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV30-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE DOWN NINE TILES AS A UNIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 30, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We are about to gut a bathroom, but there are nine 1950s wall
tiles (4- by 4-inches) put together to form a 12- by 12-inch
picture of a salmon that I want to preserve and mount. Are there
any tried and true ways of removing the tiles from the wall before
or during the gut without chipping them to death?
</P>
<P>
   DERRICK JACKSON, Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If the tiles were put on the wall with an adhesive, and not
mortar, you might be able to pry or pop them off. Experiment by
trying this with tiles you don't want to save. Place a wide chisel
or stiff putty knife under the edge of a tile and tap lightly, then
pry. Tiles set with adhesive so long ago should yield. Then you do
the same with the salmon portrait tiles. Be careful, and, if in
doubt, don't.
</P>
<P>
   If the tiles were set in mud (mortar), which they might have
been that long ago, it is impossible to pop them without breaking
them.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, or if you are reluctant to try popping the tiles,
try this:
</P>
<P>
   Chip off the tiles surrounding the nine-tile portrait, cut out
the portrait as a unit, wall and all, and pull it off, keeping the
plasterboard or plaster wall intact. If the plasterboard or
plastered wall behind the nine tiles is nailed or secured to a
stud, you have to cut the nails holding the plasterboard or
plastered wall before removing the whole thing as a unit. You can't
pull the nails out the back of the wall without endangering the
tiles or tearing the wall apart.
</P>
<P>
   Build an open box of 1 x 2 boards and insert the unit in the
box. Nail 1/4-inch hardboard to the back of the box, stain and
varnish the box and mount the whole thing on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Stewart would approve.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I wrote to you last week requesting help with finding a door
hinge. This is a specialty hinge that raises a door as it opens to
accommodate sloping floors. Do you know of any such thing and, if
so, where can I find them.
</P>
<P>
   BILL MARKOS, No town
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. The hinges are called rising butt hinges, which raise
the door as it is opened. Try the Constantine catalog,
800-223-8087.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My neighbor is very nice, but odors from her cooking waft
into my house. I have soffit vents venting the attic, but it
doesn't help. Is there something that I can do?
</P>
<P>
   M. J. B., West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   A. Smells from a neighbor's kitchen, house to house, can be a
nuisance, and while the odors may be wafting into your attic via
the soffit vents, it is unlikely that they are getting into your
house through the attic floor, unless the attic floor is not
insulated. Besides, the vents in your attic (soffit vents, and
perhaps even a ridge vent) exhaust air, and any odors going into
the attic will also be pushed outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   I think odors are coming directly from the neighbor's house to
your house. If you have air conditioning and windows are closed, I
don't have an answer, because a closed, tight house should keep
odors out. If you do not have air conditioning, I think central
air, with windows and doors closed, would keep the odors out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My neighbor's kitchen odors are coming through the walls, I
think, from her condo to mine. How can I keep them out?
</P>
<P>
   P. H., Walpole, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If your neighbor's unit is attached to yours, I don't think
there is a solution, unless you close all windows and install air
conditioning. This also may be iffy if the walls between your units
are leaking air. It would be difficult to seal that wall, although
caulking all joints might help. Be thorough in caulking joints; one
joint left open will be the conduit for the odors.
</P>
<P>
   There may be hope. Install a fan in a window, exhausting to the
outdoors, with at least one other window open so you can get a flow
of air in and out. This constant, slow exchange of air might keep
the odors within tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Water is seeping through joints in my concrete-block
foundation. How can I stop it?
</P>
<P>
   BALBIR SINGH, Somerville, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Repoint the joints in the concrete block and see what
happens. That is, chip out old mortar and insert new. This should
help, even stop the water from coming in through the wall. If it
doesn't, you may have go to a pro who could pump in a waterproofing
agent on the outside, covering the wall without excavating. The
only other way is to excavate, apply hot tar or other waterproofing
material to the wall, and backfill.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. When I put up screens, I notice they are not dirty but look
dirty. How can I clean them?I.
</P>
<P>
   S., Peabody, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Try dry-sweeping with a stiff broom, on both sides. Lay the
screen on a flat, even surface (sidewalk or driveway). That will
improve things but not cure them. Second, scrub with a stiff broom
dipped in a strong solution of Spic and Span and water. That is as
clean as you will get them, short of givng them an acid bath to
reduce innate mineral buildup.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
