<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWING BEETS: IT'S NOT EASY BEING CRIMSON  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CASS PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A great many people do not like beets. The majority of them are
either adolescents or adults who formed their opinion of beets as
adolescents, probably as a result of being confronted at school
lunch counters by canned Harvard beets _ crimson cubes coated with
a sticky magenta-colored sauce.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt it is futile to suggest that hidebound beet-haters try
them roasted or baked, with a bit of butter. I served roasted beets
to a young friend, who assured me that they were wonderful. Upon
cleaning up after dinner, I discovered the vegetable uneaten,
mashed into near oblivion and hiding under a large crust of French
bread.
</P>
<P>
   Beet detesters may find solace in the fact that the ancients _
Greeks, Romans and Anglo-Saxons alike _ didn't think much of them,
either. Beets were grown for their greens. The roots, which Pliny
referred to as ``the crimson nether parts,'' were used only
occasionally for medicinal purposes.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the ancients saw so many now-common vegetables as
poison or medicine rather than food that it's a wonder they ate any
vegetables at all.
</P>
<P>
   Beets are in the goosefoot family, Chenopodiaceae, along with
spinach, chard and lamb's quarters (a tasty weed that grows
abundantly in most gardens and is nutritionally superior to spinach
and beets _ a fact worth remembering in case you need some cooking
greens and have trouble growing its domesticated relatives).
</P>
<P>
   The beet's botanical name is Beta vulgaris, beta because the
root was thought to resemble the second letter of the Greek
alphabet. It looks more like omicron to me, but it would be
difficult at this point to get used to the idea of putting up a few
jars of pickled omicrons.
</P>
<P>
   Beet lovers know that good ones are hard to find at the market.
They aren't so easy to grow, either, but are worth the trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Garden gastronomes regard beets as a treat _ greens, roots and
all. The thinnings are delicious in salads, and there are always
plenty of thinnings because beets grow from compound seeds. What
looks like a single, star-shaped seed is actually a cluster of
several seeds stuck together.
</P>
<P>
   If all the sprouts were allowed to grow, they would be too
crowded for roots to form. So the gardener thins beets, leaving an
inch or so between plants, and eats the sacrificed seedlings mixed
with other tender spring greens.
</P>
<P>
   If thinning seems too much work, there are monogerm varieties of
beets, like Mobile, which have only one seed per cluster. My
experience is that those beets germinate poorly.
</P>
<P>
   After thinning, a few more weeks of growth provide baby beets, a
delicacy to be found only in the garden or at above-standard
farmers' markets. When the roots are about the size of a quarter,
pulling every other one will provide plenty for eating and leave
the remaining beets at the correct spacing to grow to maturity.
</P>
<P>
   The greens on baby beets are too large and coarse to eat raw in
salads, but they are perfect for gentle steaming. When the beets
are full size, the greens are usually over the hill, good only for
serving to the family iguana.
</P>
<P>
   Garden beets need not be round, nor even red. Formanova and
Cylindra are carrot-shaped beets, easy to slice into perfect disks
for pickled beets. There are white beets and golden beets, and the
delicious Chioggia beet, an Italian variety whose interior consists
of concentric red and white circles, like a bull's-eye.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Chioggia beets turn uniformly pink when cooked,
but they are so sweet that they can be sliced wafer thin and served
raw in salads, preserving the beauty of their interior rings.
</P>
<P>
   The advantage to white and golden beets is that they do not
bleed when cooked and can be mixed with other vegetables or used in
stir-fries without turning the whole dish carmine. Red beets must
be cooked unpeeled, with the root intact and an inch or so of the
leaf stems attached, to keep from bleeding their color out. You
peel them after cooking, as soon as they cool enough to be handled.
</P>
<P>
   The color is from betacyanin, a form of the same chemical
compound that gives color to red roses, red apples and red
cabbages. Some people are unable to metabolize betacyanin, which
passes intact through their systems. Urinating pink after enjoying
a big bowl of borscht is not necessarily cause for alarm.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difficulty in growing beets is getting them to
germinate properly. Beets can be grown all season long, but like
spinach they germinate best in cool soil. In summer, a sowing of
beets may fail to sprout because the soil is too warm.
</P>
<P>
   One trick for summer beets is to grow them from transplants.
Beets are among the few root vegetables that can be transplanted
successfully. Sow the seeds thinly in a nursery flat; set the flat
in a cool, shady place until the beets have sprouted, and then move
it into the sun. When the seedlings are large enough to handle,
transplant them into the garden.
</P>
<P>
   It's also possible to get an early start on spring beets with
indoor seedlings, but don't try transplanting the carrot-shaped
varieties. They will grow but will be malformed.
</P>
<P>
   Beets are content in average soil, but they like it to be evenly
moist. If the soil fluctuates between wet and dry while the beets
are sizing up, the roots may have white blotches inside, called
zoning. It doesn't affect the flavor, but it will cost you points
at county fair competitions.
</P>
<P>
   You can camouflage the blotches by cooking the beets, cubing
them and coating them in sticky magenta-colored sauce. But why
perpetuate the ranks of beet haters? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
