<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 16:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5191 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLERGYCOUPLES-TEX     05-28 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLERGYCOUPLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARRIED TO THEIR CHURCH AS WELL AS TO EACH OTHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TARA DOOLEY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HURST, Texas _ As far as Ginger and David Jarman are concerned,
there are clear advantages to having separate but married
personalities sharing the responsibility of running a church.
</P>
<P>
   Take the chore of finding a memo in an office.
</P>
<P>
   ``David's is neat and clean and organized,'' said Ginger Jarman,
half of the husband-and-wife pastor team at Richland Hills
Christian Church. ``Sometimes it's easier to come in here and say,
`Can I borrow your copy?' ''
</P>
<P>
   But alongside such incidental advantages, David and Ginger
Jarman also have offered their congregation the skills and the
talents of two people committed by vows to ministry and to each
other.
</P>
<P>
   As separate and equal co-pastors of the Disciples of Christ
church, the couple have learned to divvy up the tasks to accentuate
each other's talents. And although the Jarmans are one of two
clergy couples co-pastoring a church in Tarrant County, their
ministry is anything but a novelty, Ginger Jarman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of ways, we try to get along with the work of the
church and not make a big deal of being a clergy couple,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   As married co-pastors, they are a rarity in the area, joined
only by David and Diane Drach-Meinel of St. Andrew Lutheran Church
in Hurst.
</P>
<P>
   As more women become pastors in some Christian denominations,
they often are accompanied by husbands who have a similar calling
to the ministry. Although most of these couples do not find
themselves sharing the pulpit, they do share some of the pressures
of two-career couples _ finding time for the marriage, insisting on
time off and making sure they don't always talk shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is that you lose sight of time to nurture the
marriage and the family, and that is probably one of the biggest
dangers,'' said Joyce Coalson, vice president of the Christian
Church (Disciples of Christ) Center for Leadership and Ministry in
Homeland Ministries in Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the denominations that ordain women _ including the
United Methodist Church, the Christian Church and the Evangelical
Lutheran Church in America _ are most likely to have clergy
couples.
</P>
<P>
   Within Disciples of Christ, there are about 200 active clergy
couples among almost 7,000 ordained ministers in the United States,
Coalson said. Of those, 10 percent to 15 percent work in the same
congregation, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Texas-Northern Louisiana Synod of the Evangelical
Lutheran Church in America has three clergy couples, but two of
them are not active, leaving the Drach-Meinels to carry the torch,
Bishop Mark Herbener said.
</P>
<P>
   The Drach-Meinels, the second clergy couple to take the pulpit
at St. Andrew Lutheran, share 1 1/2 positions at the church.
Keeping work in its place can be a challenge, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when we're at home, we'll say, `Let's not talk about
church,''' Diane Drach-Meinel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you are always available,'' her husband said. ``Every
time you are together, it's a potential staff meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   But the setup has allowed the Drach-Meinels to spend time with
their children _ 8-year-old Paul and 5-year-old Mark _ who may well
be the ones who keep them honest with their work hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has given us a chance to be with our children quite a bit
and work on our careers,'' Diane Drach-Meinel said.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Jarmans, they divide church tasks.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Diane Drach-Meinel is in charge of the church's
Christian education programs, confirmation classes and social
ministries.
</P>
<P>
   David Drach-Meinel takes on many of the administrative and
financial responsibilities, designs the worship services and
coordinates the music. He also is the resident computer specialist,
working on the church's Web site, and has designed a 9:30 a.m.
Sunday service that makes use of computers for the music and the
message.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to youth retreats, Diane Drach-Meinel takes the
junior high school students to the beach and David Drach-Meinel
takes the high school students skiing in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it just feels a little bit like juggling,'' Diane
Drach-Meinel said. ``You are always passing the baton, and that
gets tricky.''
</P>
<P>
   However, splitting tasks has created an atmosphere in which
congregation members are encouraged to take initiative and start
projects, such as a Braille Bible ministry that was launched in
March at the church, the couple said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to be a permission-giving church rather than an
authority-driven church,'' David Drach-Meinel said.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the advantages come difficulties, many of which are
the same ones that women face when they become pastors, Coalson
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when the Jarmans' ministry began at Richland Hills
Christian Church, Ginger Jarman was occasionally introduced as the
pastor's wife _ a confusion that they were careful to clarify.
</P>
<P>
   But the confusion can run two ways.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Bryan Feille, a professor at Brite Divinity School
at Texas Christian University and a former pastor of South Hills
Christian Church in Fort Worth, has been introduced twice as the
``pastor's wife'' by members of his wife's congregation, Arlington
Heights Christian Church in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people have in their minds expectations of a minister's
wife, but no one has in their mind an expectation of the minister's
husband,'' said Feille, whose wife, Laurie, took the job in
November 1997 and is senior minister at the church.
</P>
<P>
   Though one benefit of having a spouse with the same career is
that he or she understands the 2 a.m. calls to come to the hospital
and the dinner plans that must be postponed for a funeral or an
emergency meeting, pitfalls sometimes can come with expecting too
much understanding, the Rev. Laurie Feille said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot of work and you have to be respectful of each
other's ministry,'' she said. ``Bryan's ministry is just as
important as my ministry. Just because I'm tired doesn't mean he
isn't also tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Though working in ministry with a spouse can be challenging
whether or not the couple shares the pulpit, success can offer an
example to many dual-career couples struggling with similar issues,
Coalson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the couple has worked this out well and has a strong
marriage and family life, there is a sense that they can model that
for other dual-career folks,'' she said. ``That it is not easy, but
it is doable and it is doable in light of one's faith.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
