<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING THE SPIRITUAL MESSAGE IN A MEGAHIT MOVIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``May the force be with you,'' said a Texas minister as he began
his sermon last Sunday. His congregation, of course, knew exactly
what he was talking about.
</P>
<P>
   He focused his sermon on the latest megahit movie: ``Star Wars:
Episode I _ The Phantom Menace,'' part of a film series loaded with
moral and spiritual symbols.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Chris Hughes said he and other ministers he knows are
using the new Star Wars film to reach out to those searching for
spiritual renewal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The movie is not from the Christian point of view, but that's
OK,'' said Hughes, pastor of United Methodist Church of the
Covenant in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a time when a huge part of the population is looking
for spirituality,'' he said. ``And we need to reach out to people
who are searching and help them understand that yes, there is a
force out there bigger than themselves. And for us that force comes
from one God.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said his sermon drew wide interest from all ages. The
fact that the spiritual symbolism touches on principles not
strictly Christian doesn't bother Hughes.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Christians we know that Jesus Christ has impacted our lives
with a force that is with us all the time,'' said Hughes. ``We also
have the force of the Holy Spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing the religious and theological themes of the ``Star
Wars'' series is not uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   Even an Internet site created by Eli Williamson-Jones of
Laporte, Colo., is based on the spiritual aspects of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ```Star Wars' _ the Religion'' is at
hamp.hampshire.edu/~elwF94/s_w_religion.html. It includes sections
about grace, fall from grace, the dreamer, the journey, friends,
devotion, trials, the master, the test, temptation, compassion,
darkest hour and home.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson-Jones writes that the films are ``like a religion
that teaches great wisdom about the nature of our lives in this
vast universe. From watching ... we can gain tremendous insight
into human nature. We see our deep longings to find adventure,
purpose and peace in our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet site discusses several main characters in moral or
religious terms, including Anakin Skywalker, a man of great promise
who evolves into the evil personage of Darth Vader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before he fell from grace, Anakin Skywalker was gifted and
blessed with many talents,'' the site narrative states. But he
becomes twisted and malevolent and mistakes good for bad and bad
for good.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Star Wars'' films have provoked theological discussions
since the beginning of the series, said Lonnie Kliever, professor
and chairman of religious studies at Southern Methodist University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the same old gods and goddesses, the same old conflict
between good and evil, virtue and vice,'' Kliever said.
</P>
<P>
   There's a provocative blending of classical mythology, elements
of Christianity, Hinduism and Buddhism with technological and
scientific forces, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all these extraterrestrials _ kind of angels in modern
garb _ struggling in a kind of world that transcends the everyday
world,'' the professor said. ``And all those persons are bound
together by this transcendent, impersonal force.''
</P>
<P>
   Kliever said interest in the spiritual accounts for much of the
appeal of all the ``Star Wars'' films.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the success of these movies can be laid simply
to their entertainment value, although they are entertaining,''
Kliever said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``force'' in the ``Star Wars'' films is a vast,
incomprehensible power that is more akin to Hinduism and Buddhism
than to traditional Christianity, said Kliever.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the films resonate with the problems that every religion
wrestles with,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   None of this spiritual talk surprises George Lucas, the creator
of the ``Star Wars'' series.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Lucas personally consulted with the late Joseph
Campbell, an authority on mythology who became the subject of a
popular Bill Moyers public television series. In several interviews
and television programs, Lucas reveals that he purposely sought to
involve religion and myth in the ``Star Wars'' series.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to encourage us earthlings to look beyond our
earthbound lives to a ``force'' much higher than ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
