<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKS TO THE INTERNET, THE TRADING PUBLIC GETS WHAT IT WANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Five years ago, when the idea of extended trading hours on Wall
Street was first broached, California brokerage houses rose up as
one to kill the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Most West Coast traders begin their days at 4 a.m. so that they
can work in sync with their colleagues in the Eastern time zone.
Working until 7 p.m. (Pacific Time), as extended trading hours
would require, promised them 15-hour workdays every day. That was
not their idea of the California lifestyle, and so the plan was
discreetly shelved.
</P>
<P>
   Today, West Coast brokerage houses have accepted that extended
trading hours will soon be a reality. They did not protest when New
York Stock Exchange Chairman Richard Grasso announced earlier this
week that starting in July, the NYSE would remain open for business
until 10 p.m. Eastern time. And they didn't even bother to contest
NASDAQ's decision to go forward with a similar schedule.
</P>
<P>
   What changed the equation was the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the markets did what the market makers told them
to do. Today, markets do what the trading public tells them to do.
</P>
<P>
   Extended trading hours are costly and inconvenient for Merrill
Lynch and Morgan Stanley, but that's their tough luck. What the
trading public wants, it now gets. That's why stock exchanges will
soon remain open until 10 o'clock at night.
</P>
<P>
   This power shift is illustrative of a much larger shift that is
occurring in what has come to be called the new economy. Simply
put, (itals)Internet technology transfers power to the
end-user.(unitals) The consequences of this fundamental shift are
profound.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, it means that the customer (or end-user) can never be
taken for granted. Businesses that do not understand this basic
tenet of the new economy will come to learn it the hard way.
They'll be eaten alive in the new e-commerce marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the business of Internet connections. The Regional Bell
Operating Companies could have owned this business and won
themselves a huge, devoted customer base if they had just done
three things end-users wanted done:
</P>
<P>
   Had they double-timed the launch of high-speed modems, offered
affordable T-1 Internet access and even more affordable ISDN
service, they could have owned the Internet access market forever.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they tried to gouge their customers, including their
best ones, by overpricing T-1 and ISDN service. To make matters
worse, they were unacceptably late in bringing high-speed modems to
market. As a result, end-users everywhere (and particularly best
customers) hate the Regional Bell Operating Companies.
</P>
<P>
   The mistake the RBOCs made was simple: They thought it was about
them (and their balance sheet) and not about the end-user. That is
not a mistake you will ever see AOL or Yahoo or IBM or Amazon.com
make. Their e-commerce models focus on one thing and one thing
only: How can we better serve our customers so they don't go
somewhere else? They understand that power has shifted to the
end-user.
</P>
<P>
   The second major consequence of the Internet power shift is that
companies can't raise prices unless they can save time or add value
for their customers. Companies that try to raise prices without
providing additional value (as the automobile manufacturers used to
do routinely) will find themselves stuck with acres of inventory.
Companies that provide that extra value (time-saving or personal
service) will be generously rewarded with repeat business and
positive word-of-mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The third major consequence of this power shift is that
mid-sized companies will find it hard to survive. Small companies
that fulfill the needs of niche markets (like high-end money
management firms and specialty law firms) will continue to thrive.
Large companies that can afford the most advanced technologies (and
continuously upgrade them) will be able to meet the demands of a
vast customer base. But mid-sized firms will be caught in a
squeeze.
</P>
<P>
   In order to compete with big firms, they will need to make huge
technology investments that will eat into their profit margins. In
order to provide the kind of service niche market firms offer, they
will need to dedicate additional resources for that purpose. That
too will eat into their profit margins. The squeeze will be
relentless as the technology advances and as end-users (and
particularly so-called best customers) grow accustomed to better
and better service.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Stock Exchange and the NASDAQ decided to extend
trading hours because they feared losing customers to Internet
after-markets. End-users demanded change and the wealthiest and
most powerful financial institutions in the world acquiesced.
Anyone who doubts the power of Internet technology should consider
that it has now brought the very emblems of American capitalism to
heel.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
