<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINGS THAT GO CREEP IN THE NIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Spiders get a bad rap, according to Ed O'Brien, an assistant
curator at Zoo New England. ``People get creeped out by them,'' he
says. ``They often have a real aversion to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wonder why? Just because most of them have eight eyes and eight
legs? Or because they liquify prey with digestive glands and then
slurp down the bug juice? Or because they so often spin
horror-movie-style webs?
</P>
<P>
   If we weren't so repelled, we'd be awestruck. There is a
phenomenal array of spider species all around us. ``While they can
be easily overlooked,'' O'Brien says, ``there are so many types.
Spiders are really diverse.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, you may feel there are times when you need a field
guide just to keep up with the creepy crawlies with whom you
begrudgingly cohabitate.
</P>
<P>
   The notion of a quickie field guide to the spiders around us
makes one of the sultans of spider biology chuckle. Herbert W.
Levi, now retired from Harvard's Museum of Comparative Zoology,
says, ``There are about 500 kinds of spiders in the area, many
without common names.'' There is still much to be learned in the
world of spiders. Their numbers, range, and behavior in many cases
are still mysterious. About 37,000 species of spiders have been
named, but that's probably only a fourth of those out there.
</P>
<P>
   Some things we know: For the most part it's females that build
webs. ``Males just hike around the world looking for females,''
says Dr. Greg Mertz of the New England Wildlife Center. And
certainly, not all spiders spin webs. Some go out hunting for
little bugs to eat. Also, Levi points out, ``A female does not
ordinarily feast on her mate, as many people believe, but males
usually die after mating.''
</P>
<P>
   In the quest to identify the spiders close at hand, we can at
least point out a few of the more recognizable characters.
</P>
<P>
   First on just about everyone's list are the little jumping
spiders. Yes, that's right, those extra petite spiders that hop are
called jumping spiders, and all arachniphiles love them. Mertz says
these little guys are ``among the most intelligent spiders.''
They've also been called the most entertaining and the cutest. (If
spiders had high school yearbooks, these guys would clean up on the
superlatives: ``best dressed spider,'' ``spider most likely to
succeed,'' etc.)
</P>
<P>
   Since they don't spin webs, they hunt prey. Not exactly simba on
the veldt, but they do stalk and ambush, using their jumping
abilities for the final, deadly pounce. Two of their eight eyes are
large and forward facing _ which inspired the writer of an article
in Audubon's Sanctuary magazine to assert that these spiders have a
``humanlike appearance.'' Hmm. Well, come to think of it, maybe I
can think of a few people . . . .
</P>
<P>
   With their terrific vision and charisma, jumping spiders seem to
invite interaction with people. ``You can box with them,'' Mertz
says. They will draw back and leap forward to spar with your pinky
if you're in the mood. O'Brien says you can wave a finger in front
of one and ``if you're lucky,'' the spider will hop on.
</P>
<P>
   Jumping spiders, as well as others, O'Brien says, often will
throw a line of silk out, like ``a bungee chord,'' as they leap.
</P>
<P>
   We all know cellar spiders too, being particularly familiar with
the daddy longlegs. These slender-legged spiders look other-worldly
and spin messy webs in and around our basements. Cellar spiders are
quite ``cosmopolitan,'' according to Levi's wonderful little
volume, ``Spiders and Their Kin,'' (Golden Books, $5.95). I don't
think he means that they summer on the Vineyard, collect Limoges,
or drink Pouilly-Fuisse with every meal. But they do live all over
the place, and often turn up in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The American house spider is aptly named. We see them around all
the time. They are members of the cobweb weaver group, a large
spider family. These spiders are pretty sedentary, hanging upside
down on the web, waiting for action. Levi tells us that cobweb
spiders ``have few or no teeth, and do not chew prey.'' Instead,
one bites its prey and ``sucks it dry.''
</P>
<P>
   Orb weavers: These common spiders with poor vision build
beautiful, complex-looking webs all over the world. The shamrock
spider is a familiar member of the family. Brown recluses and black
widows are the two biggies in the United States for venom. Neither
lives normally in New England, according to most sources. But they
are ``easily transported,'' Levi says. They may make it here in
suitcases or cargo shipments.
</P>
<P>
   That would explain the ``web of intrigue'' at Dudley Street
police station in Boston's Roxbury section in 1994. That's when a
brown recluse nested behind a file cabinet (complete with her
babies and eggs) and proceeded to bite two sergeants, who survived
the itching and swelling. While experts tell you these audacious
arachnids aren't found here, they often will tell you to keep
storage areas uncluttered and to shake out stored clothes before
wearing them.
</P>
<P>
   Several spiders deserve honorable mentions. Ed O'Brien likes
fishing spiders, which can walk on water, and nursery web spiders
that carry eggs with them (``a little bit of parental protection
that people might be surprised by,'' O'Brien says). Not to mention
how romantic the males are. When courting, he will often present
the female with a bug. Wolf spiders, low-slung and predatory, are
common. They have good vision and are sensitive to touch. Levi
alleges that they make ``nice'' pets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spider activity: Mertz reveals that striking a tuning fork
(middle c works well) near a web will bring out the host spider,
because it mimics the vibration of prey bugs hung up on the silk.
Mertz says you can also slip a piece of paper behind a web and
spray paint (in a contrasting color) as you lift the paper toward
you to capture the design. ``She'll have to spin a new web,'' Mertz
says. ``But that will give her something to do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 1656EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5212 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-DASH-AYN-BOS &LR;      05-28 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DASH-AYN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING ON THE EDGE, IN DOUBLE TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE PASSION OF AYN RAND 
Starring: Helen Mirren, Peter Fonda, Eric Stoltz, Julie Delpy 
Directed by: Christopher Menaul 
On: Showtime 
Time: Sunday at 8 p.m. 
Rated: TVMA 
 
 
DASH AND LILLY 
 
Starring: Judy Davis, Sam Shepard 
Directed by: Kathy Bates 
On: A&AMP;E 
Time: Monday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Authors may rival rock stars as the juiciest of movie subjects.
After all, the alcohol-soaked barbs of ``Dash and Lilly,'' A &AMP; E's
biopic of Dashiell Hammett and Lillian Hellman, aren't too far a
cry from the narcotic histrionics of ``Sid and Nancy.'' And all the
sexual posturing in Showtime's ``The Passion of Ayn Rand'' would
not be entirely unfamiliar to a few freewheeling rock bands. Unlike
actors, who at least try to craft a harmless, beloved persona,
rockers and writers don't bother much with good behavior or false
modesty. They're not afraid of a little extremity.
</P>
<P>
   Living on the edge is what fuels this excellent pair of new
made-for-cable TV movies. Both take on passionate, brainy writers
who willfully ignored the pressures of conventional thinking. Ayn
Rand, in particular, was a pioneer, living out her daring theories
on individualism, sex, and self-interest _ theories that are still
debated by armchair philosophers and in academia. Hammett and
Hellman were originals of a more ordinary stripe, leaning to
leftist causes, drinking themselves into oblivion, clinging to
integrity in the face of the House Un-American Activities
Committee. ``The Passion of Ayn Rand'' airs on Showtime Sunday at 8
p.m., and ``Dash and Lilly'' airs on A &AMP; E Monday at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The more fascinating of the two movies is ``Ayn Rand.'' Director
Christopher Menaul steeps his exotic drama in a New York filled
with mirrors and windows, as all the characters do a dance around
Rand's massive ego. Helen Mirren is absolutely wonderful as Rand,
cutting the writer's shamelessly judgmental personality with a tad
of fragility. She uses Rand's Russian accent (Rand escaped in 1926)
as a sort of weapon, spitting out lines with sharply edged
self-confidence. ``I don't like surprises,'' she yells at the
guests of an unexpected publication party. Later she immodestly
announces, ``I will have an influence someday, but not, I think, in
my lifetime.'' But when she hears her young lover has been sleeping
with another woman, she is shattered behind her controlled veneer.
</P>
<P>
   The plot of ``Ayn Rand'' turns on her open affair with that
young lover, psychologist Nathaniel Branden, and his wife, Barbara.
At first Rand treats Branden like a protege, but soon he is her
lover and her muse. ``Dis is not a threat to you,'' she assures _
or commands _ her husband, Frank O'Connor, and Barbara. But the
affair is a threat to all of them, as Nathaniel becomes
increasingly reckless in his arrogance. The melodramatic spin cycle
of this foursome inspires the weaker moments in the script,
particularly as it chronicles Barbara's victimization (the movie is
overly sympathetic to her, since it's based on the real Barbara
Branden's 1986 Rand biography). It doesn't help that she's played
by Julie Delpy, an expressive actress who makes a noble, but
distractingly unsuccessful, effort to purge her French accent. But
the movie gains plenty of intensity from Peter Fonda's ``Mr. Rand''
take on Frank, and from Eric Stoltz as the duplicitous Nathaniel.
</P>
<P>
   Mirren is a miracle of hard and soft edges, and she makes ``The
Passion of Ayn Rand'' entirely worthwhile, just as Judy Davis and
Sam Shepard lift ``Dash and Lilly'' well above its predictable
moves. Judy Davis: She's one of the best movie actresses right now,
a powerhouse who always acts with _ and not over _ the other actors
in a scene. To say she is ``in the moment'' is an understatement.
In ``Dash and Lilly'' her energy level is at a peak and her wit is
quick, but she drops the neurotic Annie Hall-with-a-PhD shtick that
she's used in Woody Allen movies. Her Hellman is bold, persistent,
insecure, and deeply in love. ``None of it means anything unless
you're there,'' she confesses to Hammett after he sneaks out of
``The Children's Hour'' opening for a night of carousing.
</P>
<P>
   The movie zooms in on the power balance between Hellman and
Hammett, which is ever-changing and seismic in its shifts. It's
never easy for two giant individuals to merge, especially when they
are in the same business and share a fondness for booze. Indeed,
``Dash and Lilly'' is explicit in portraying the role of the bottle
in the pair's relationship. At their first meeting at a movie
premiere in 1930, Hammett says to Hellman, ``I like the way you
drink,'' and for most of their courtship they are seen falling down
drunk together. Later in their 30-year affair, Hammett's dependency
becomes less of a romantic-comic potion and more gruesome, as his
health and talent deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dash and Lilly'' marks the film-directing debut of Kathy
Bates, and it's clear she is an actor's director. Not only does she
enable Davis to create a complex Hellman, but she helps Shepard
come up with one of his finest performances. He gives Hammett a
placid, pithy, remote exterior, but you can always see the fear
playing right beneath the surface. Shepard doesn't sentimentalize
the crime novelist, who could be violent and stubborn, but he
provides the movie with its lovely emotional climax, after the
couple moves to Martha's Vineyard. (They both deserve Emmy nods,
along with Mirren.) Bates also gives Bebe Neuwirth some choice
screen time, as a tart Dorothy Parker.
</P>
<P>
   The plotting of ``Dash and Lilly'' succumbs to biopic cliches,
particularly in the overfamiliar framing story about Hellman's
appearance before the House Un-American Activities Committee. But
the dialogue is always smart _ and miles above anything you might
have seen during the networks' May sweeps extravaganza. Indeed,
when TV despair visits upon us, and ``Noah's Ark'' just will not
do, it's important to remember that ambitious movies like ``The
Passion of Ayn Rand'' and ``Dash and Lilly'' are readily available
on cable TV.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 1702EDT &QL; 
