<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5263 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NITEOUT-FLYER-ART-$AD     05-28 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NITEOUT-FLYER-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOURING SPIN CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30)  
 (af)  
 By JULIA CHAPLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Surveying the crowd last Thursday night at Stylus, a
weekly party held at a Lower East Side sushi lounge called Never,
Hosi Simon nodded approvingly that few people were eating. ``If
people were eating and ignoring the music, that would be a bad
sign,'' said Simon, surrounded by hipsters in the latest Asian
dragon tank tops.
</P>
<P>
   They sipped sake, eyes fixed on the deejay spinning his
turntables from a perch in an aluminum-covered space. ``The night
definitely has potential.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon, 24, is the editor in chief of Flyer, a palm-size monthly
club listing guide that has become the equivalent of Zagat's for
the deejay set. Riding around the city on his mountain bike,
wearing khakis with oversize pockets for stuffing club invites,
Simon is an obsessional inspector, visiting as many as eight clubs
a night. Last Thursday, his first stop was at 10 p.m. at Never. By
10:20, he was out the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an after-work party for people that don't really work,''
said Simon, who can assess a scene in 10 minutes. He started Flyer
a little more than a year ago with fellow German expatriates
Florian Peter and Anselm d'Astner.
</P>
<P>
   Flyer's staff distributes 50,000 copies by hand and backpack to
choice hangouts like Urban Outfitters and the Paramount Hotel.
``Pretty much every bar in the city that has a CD player tries to
pass themselves off as a deejay party now,'' Simon said. ``We get
the grandiose claims like `Oh, Amber Valletta hangs out here.'
Sometimes, you can tell if they're exaggerating on the phone, but
stopping by is the only way to be sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon's criteria: ``a deejay who plays music that challenges,
and people who are having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Riding down Houston Street to check out a soiree called N'ice at
the 205 Club, Simon spotted a freshly painted bar called Frankie
Blue. Inside, he found a deejay with a shaved head trying to come
up with an alias for his Saturday debut. ``Deejay names can be so
silly,'' he said. ``What about calling myself Deejay Spaz or Deejay
Retard?''
</P>
<P>
   Simon gently broke the news that two guys on the West Coast had
those names already. Minutes later, at 205, an Icelandic deejay
manned the turntables as dry ice billowed over the crowded dance
floor. ``A little on the ratty side,'' Simon said, noting the worn
furniture and beer-stained cushions. ``But it has quality
underground music, and a crowd that's hip but not trendy.''
</P>
<P>
   Next was Vanity, a club on 23rd Street, for a weekly drum 'n'
bass party called Physics. It was empty except for a few kids
bobbing up and down by the speakers. Learning that the party had
moved on to Vinyl, Simon did, too.
</P>
<P>
   But first, a stop at Polly Esther's, a 1970s retro club chain in
Greenwich Village, for a party called College V.I.P. Under a strobe
light, inebriated frat boys hobbled about, trying to dance like the
rapper Snoop Dogg.
</P>
<P>
   An older tourist, a woman with a fanny pack, attempted some
lambada moves that looked like step aerobics. Simon was not put
off. ``This party is so mainstream that it is more underground than
some underground parties,'' he said. ``In this business, I've
learned that it's important to be open-minded.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after 2 a.m., he was outside Vinyl amid a crowd waiting to
get in and hear Deejay Zinc. A Lincoln Continental with New Jersey
plates pulled up, and a woman in a glittery bustier screamed out
the window, ``Do you know how to get to some club called Webster
Hall?''
</P>
<P>
   Simon stepped forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, actually I do.'' 4
</P>
</TEXT>
