<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, May 29, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mountain thunderstorms will erupt from southern California
across southern Nevada to Arizona and New Mexico as the uneven
heating of mountains and valleys promotes rising currents of moist
air. Farther north, mountain storms will also erupt across
northeast Nevada, northern Utah and southern Idaho as a pocket of
fast jet-stream winds enhances the lift of moist air. A few of
these storms could approach severe levels.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, scattered showers and thunderstorms will develop
along a cool front draped from Wyoming to western South Dakota.
Behind the front, broken areas of cool rain will fall on portions
of Montana, with temperatures in the upper 40s while steadier rain
falls in the northern part of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of thunderstorms will again burgeon across Texas. Heavy
rain, hail or gusty winds will result from some of these storms. A
few thunderstorms could become severe, particularly in west Texas,
where humid breezes from the southeast are forced to rise up the
sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered clusters of heavy thunderstorms will roam the Deep
South as the remnants of an old front shift northward, enhancing
the lift of humid surface air. Areas such as the Tennessee Valley
could receive heavy rains in a relatively brief time. Isolated
heavy storms will also flare across Florida in concert with moist
air being lifted by the leading edges of Atlantic and Gulf sea
breezes.
</P>
<P>
   Warmth will build in the Northeast, except for parts of the
northern Middle Atlantic and southern New England coasts, where
cooling sea breezes develop.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Mountain Thunder
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a month ahead of schedule, a swarm of thunderstorms
erupted over mountain peaks from southern California to New Mexico
on Thursday. Typically in the Southwest, mountain thunder begins
around July 1 as waves of Pacific moisture are drawn inland over
the hotter, lower-barometric-pressure land. As the morning sun
warms mountain summits, moist air in contact with rocky peaks also
warms and becomes less dense. Like a hot-air balloon, air then
rises to form storms. On Thursday, moisture aloft left in the wake
of upper-level disturbances teamed with the sun to incite mountain
thunder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
