<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-GUNS-$ADV30-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLETON FALLOUT FORCES GOP LEADERSHIP TO EMBRACE GUN-CONTROL
MEASURES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, May 30) 
 
By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After years of trying to block measures aimed at
stiffening gun control laws, the Republican House leadership
abruptly reversed course last week to embrace the concept of
mandatory background checks regardless of where handguns are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The decision was prompted by public pressure in the wake of the
Littleton, Colo., school shooting last month and ``the political
reality,'' as one Republican put it, ``that the votes are there in
the House to require background checks at gun shows and pawn
shops.''
</P>
<P>
   There also was a desire on the part of House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill., to avoid ``taking a political beating'' on the
issue that Republicans certainly would have received from the
Democrats and the public had they continued to oppose efforts to
attach modest gun-control measures to appropriations bills and
other legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Although a firm date for considering gun-control legislation in
the House has not been set, Republican leaders announced that they
intend to allow amendments in mid-June to the juvenile justice
bill, which was used by the Senate to pass several measures
designed to keep guns out of the hands of criminals and young
people.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed its version of the juvenile justice bill last
week, but only after GOP leaders were forced to make a series of
embarrassing concessions to the Democrats on background checks and
other gun-control issues. The Democrats were able to use the
Columbine High School shooting and bombing incident, in which 15
people were killed and 21 wounded, as a catalyst for action on
gun-control measures that otherwise would not have been considered
this year.
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats hope to at least match the Senate initiatives,
which would expand the current background check laws to include
handguns purchased at gun shows and pawn shops. The bill also
contains measures requiring that trigger locks or other child
safety devices be sold with all new handguns, and that the
importation of large capacity ammunition clips be banned.
</P>
<P>
   While embracing the general concepts of the Senate bill, House
Republicans have warned that what they end up supporting could be
different.
</P>
<P>
   For example, many Republicans and some Democrats don't like the
Senate measure requiring up to a 72-hour waiting period on gun
purchases as opposed to an instant background check. An expected
move to raise the age for gun ownership to 21, which is supported
by Hastert, also troubles some Republicans and Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``What comes out of the House bill could be less, it could be
more,'' said one Republican leadership aide. ``The whole game for
Republicans here is just to avoid the mistakes and the
embarrassment the Senate made.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be (background) checks at gun shows and pawn shops
because most members support some kind of background check. And
there will be gun locks in the (House) bill because that's not a
huge issue since most makers are already including them with their
guns. The question is how far will we go in accepting the Senate
language?'' the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   By giving ground on gun control, Republicans are hoping to win
support from Democrats on a few other issues they consider more
important in the fight to curb youth violence. Those issues include
stricter enforcement of current gun laws and tougher jail and
prison sentences for youthful offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Davis, press secretary to House Majority Leader Dick
Armey, R-Texas, also said Republicans want to focus more attention
on ``cultural issues,'' such as violence depicted in movies and
television, which they believe are contributing factors to
tragedies like the Colorado incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country as a whole knows that the answer to Littleton
involves much more than gun control ... and we want to make sure
that these other problems are addressed,'' said Davis, who accused
the Democrats of ``shamelessly'' using Littleton as a ``political
tool'' to help pass tougher gun-control measures.
</P>
<P>
   By trying to head off an extended fight in the House over
gun-control issues, she said, House leaders are hoping to avoid the
disaster that occurred during the Senate debate. In that debate,
the Democrats succeeded to some extent in portraying Republicans as
supportive of loopholes in the current laws that actually make it
easier for criminals and kids to get guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``After what happened in the Senate, we figured ... we want
things to be a little more orderly,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the House Republican leadership to endorse a set
of gun-control measures before a vote came in a meeting last week
in which Hastert, Armey and Majority Whip Tom DeLay of Texas agreed
that there would likely be enough votes among Republicans and
Democrats in the wake of Littleton to pass moderate legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than risk a split within their ranks over the issue, and
to head off a Democratic effort to portray them as weak on
gun-control issues, Hastert decided to announce that amendments
would be allowed to the juvenile justice bill when the House takes
it up in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech on the floor, Hastert acknowledged that recent
incidents of school violence had understandably shaken the nation
and that parents were right to demand that their representatives do
more to protect their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support common-sense legislation that keeps guns out of the
hands of unsupervised children,'' the speaker said. But he added
that passing gun-control measures ``is only part of the solution''
as he called for support of measures to ``reinforce positive
values'' in the nation's culture that will help ``create a safer
and more secure society.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Hastert's floor speech caught Democratic lawmakers by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they were clearly under a lot of pressure from the
public because of what happened in Littleton,'' said Rep. Ken
Bentsen of Texas, one of several Democrats who has been pressing
the Republican leadership to allow votes on gun-control amendments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican leadership doesn't want it to appear that
they're being pushed into this, knowing they'll have to accept
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The writing was on the wall,'' agreed one Republican aide.
``It was either give 'em what they want or go through weeks of hell
while the Democrats tried to use gun control as a political issue
against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite Hastert's decision, there were signs late last week that
some GOP members might revolt if pressed to accept the Senate
initiatives as written.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill., for example,
expressed support himself for ``common sense'' gun-control
measures, but warned that some measure in the Senate-passed bill
could conflict with the constitutional right to bear arms.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts by some Democrats to broaden the scope of the Senate
initiatives could cause problems for some of their own colleagues
who generally favor tougher gun-control measures, but only up to a
point.
</P>
<P>
   Bentsen, for one, said he would find it difficult to limit gun
purchases to once a month as some Democrats are proposing. He said
he would also be reluctant to go along with a proposal by Hastert
and others in both parties to raise the age limit on gun purchases
from 18 to 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be cautious in raising age restrictions too high,''
he said ``It's a question of responsible gun ownership.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats were trying to force a vote on the Senate-passed
bill before mid-June even as the House was adjourning last week for
its Memorial Day recess. At a news conference with Vice President
Al Gore, several Democrats demanded that the House consider gun
control ``an emergency measure,'' as Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee of
Texas put it, ``to deal with the crisis situation in the nation's
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans refused, insisting that more time is needed to
study the Senate initiatives and to give House members a chance to
draw up their own measures.
</P>
<P>
   Their refusal to hold a quick vote drew charges from Gore that
House Republicans are trying to delay consideration of gun-control
measures just to give the National Rifle Association more time to
build opposition to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NRA,'' he said, `` is hoping against hope that if they
slow walk this measure the public will lose interest.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gore said the Senate vote on the issue was ``a reflection of
the newly strengthened will of the American people'' to make sure
that Congress passes tougher gun-control laws.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
