<HEADER>
A5279 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STORE-RETURNS-2TAKES-     05-28 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORE-RETURNS-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU BUY IT, YOU KEEP IT, MORE STORES ARE SAYING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Virginia Sullivan was walking up Park Avenue not long
ago, her arms overflowing with purchases, looking every bit the
battle-hardened New York shopper. But there's one thing that Ms.
Sullivan, a professor at the Fashion Institute of Technology, no
longer has the strength to endure: returning unsatisfactory
merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime I've tried to return something, people in the store
make me feel embarrassed, dishonest, like I'm a criminal,'' Ms.
Sullivan said. She has a closet full of unwanted pants and dresses
with the tags still attached to prove it.
</P>
<P>
   As the shopping urge strikes many New Yorkers during the
Memorial Day sales, they may want to keep Ms. Sullivan's experience
in mind: 'tis easier to buy than return.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers and retail analysts say that at many boutiques in New
York, as well as at local branches of some regional and national
chains, return policies have gotten leaner and meaner in recent
years. The complaints mention chilly sales clerks who seem
instructed to intimidate customers out of making returns, return
periods of merely a week and return policies that give only credit
toward new purchases rather than a refund.
</P>
<P>
   Heaven forbid that a customer change her mind about a Prada bag
more than 10 days after she bought it and the bag is no longer
stocked _ it's hers to keep. At Daffy's, the off-price chain, if an
item is taken back without the price ticket attached, consumers
should expect to take it back home with them.
</P>
<P>
   Even some famously tolerant retailers like L.L. Bean, once known
for taking back 30-year-old Hudson Bay blankets with no questions
asked, have become more restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The policies started tightening up two years ago,'' said Rich
Donaldson, a spokesman for Bean, whose customers are now asked to
explain why they are dissatisfied. The company's policy is meant to
discourage the kind of shopper who showed up at the flagship store
in Freeport, Maine., last year and, as a kind of tongue-in-cheek
test, tried to trade in a pair of worn-out bluchers. The sales
associate looked dismayed. ``Dear, why don't you just throw these
away?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that as the retail industry has become increasingly
competitive, with profits squeezed by the growth in the number of
stores and competition from the Internet, many merchants have had
to tighten return policies to protect their bottom lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retailers are finding it difficult to be profitable because of
the increasingly competitive nature of the business, and as a
result have clamped down on everything, including return
policies,'' said Walter F. Loeb, publisher of the Loeb Retail
Letter, a trade publication.
</P>
<P>
   There seem to have been no surveys of customer attitudes toward
return policies, but interviews with shoppers on Madison, Park and
Fifth Avenues, the city's fanciest retailing strips, turned up many
tales of woe.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorkers may be particularly affected, because small
boutiques tend to be the most restrictive stores of all, and in
recent years they have become more prominent in the city, from
NoLIta to Madison Avenue, while department stores, which have the
most liberal policies, have been retreating.
</P>
<P>
   One woman recalled a trip to the Robert Clergerie shop on
Madison Avenue near 61st Street, where she tried to return a shoe
with a broken heel. The salesman dismissed her with a curt,
``Sorry, we have no responsibility,'' said the woman, who declined
to give her name.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the incident, Kim Gracianette, the store's
manager, said that Robert Clergerie's return policy had not changed
in recent years, and that the New York branches of the French chain
were more lenient than their foreign counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In France they say, `We're not Maytag,''' she said. ``They
say, `You buy it, it's yours.''' The store currently gives
customers credit on their credit cards for goods returned with a
receipt in 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Blake, a Manhattan resident, recently tried to return a
baby outfit she received as a gift shortly after giving birth. But
when she went to La Petite Etoile, on Madison near 65th Street,
about three weeks after the outfit was bought, the chic shop
rebuffed her. It accepts returns for only seven days.
</P>
<P>
   ``How was I suppose to run out after seven days?'' Ms. Blake
asked, standing outside the store, still holding the gift box. ``I
just had a baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillippe Edelman, La Petite Etoile's owner, stands by his
seven-day window for returns. ``The policy is correct,'' he said,
``The season is very short. We're not strict. We're like most of
the retail stores.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, in many clothing boutiques, even those for infants,
new styles are introduced more rapidly, so shop owners keep smaller
stocks. They limit the time for returns to avoid being stuck with
unsalable goods.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Stores bring in clothes and want to move them out to make room
for more merchandise,'' said Jennifer Maxwell Parkinson, an image
consultant with a personal shopping service in Manhattan and
Westchester County. ``So their return policies have become
stricter. The smallest boutiques are the strictest.''
</P>
<P>
   Several clerks at Madison Avenue boutiques, saying they had to
speak anonymously if they expected to keep their jobs, said they
were told to try as hard as possible to dissuade customers who
enter with merchandise to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tell us to discourage returning, but if the customer
really causes a fuss, we are told not to let them go out the door
without talking them into buying something else,'' one said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Gap, known for its generous rules, is clamping down in
some ways. The chain recently reduced its period for price
adjustment _ the time during which a customer who buys an item at
full retail price may claim a rebate if the item later goes on
sale. Now, the customer must return the item, with its receipt,
within 14 days, instead of the previous 30, and may do so only
once, rather than two or three times, as some once did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retailers had an open-door policy on returns,'' said Bruce Van
Kleeck, a vice president of the National Retail Federation, a trade
group. ``Unfortunately, a number of consumers began to take
advantage, returning items that would not normally be returned.
Returns are an expensive item.''
</P>
<P>
   Many retailers say their stricter policies are necessary to
protect them from less-than-honest customers. Marcia Wilson, the
president of Daffy's, which has 13 stores in the East, said that in
the last year she had decided to accept returns only when they are
presented within 14 days of purchase, with both a cash-register
receipt and a sales ticket still attached.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have ticket guns at home,'' Ms. Wilson said. ``They
wear the garments, take off the ticket and shoot the tickets when
they're done wearing it. Nervy, huh? They bring back clothes
pilled, stained and stinky.''
</P>
<P>
   Upscale shoppers are no better. In the world of parties on the
Upper East Side, it is an old trick to hide the price tag, wear
sweat pads underneath the arms and spend the evening treading
carefully around red wine. ``Evening wear tends to be rental
items,'' said Teri Hardin, a vice president and director of
merchandise for Saks Fifth Avenue in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   As a deterrent, Ms. Hardin said, the store has started hanging
price tickets on the front of dresses, at the breast. ``But you
never know,'' she said. ``They may call it a fashion accessory!''
</P>
<P>
   Clothing stores aren't the only ones tightening up. Jennifer
Roberts, a director at the International Mass Retail Association,
said stores ``have really tightened up on the electronics
returns.'' She cited abuse as the reason. ``People would buy
computers, use them for tests for school and then return them,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   But by some customers' accounts, such policies can fail to
distinguish the wheat from the chaff. Herberth Morales, a Manhattan
doorman, said he tried to return a VCR to P.C. Richard &AMP; Son in
Woodhaven, Queens, because it stopped working after five days. He
said he had the original packaging, but the store at first refused.
After he demanded to speak to a manager, Morales said, ``they
agreed to send it out to be repaired.'' Two months later, the VCR
was fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Gancio, a vice president of the P.C. Richard chain, said
the company's policy was to accept VCRs within 20 days as long as
they are ``like new'' and customers have receipts and the original
packing.
</P>
<P>
   A few retailers, like Lands' End, are seizing on customers'
frustrations over the tighter return policies to play up the fact
that they take back anything, even if it is worn or dirty. ``As so
many people are tightening, we're making a point of letting
everyone know that our policies haven't changed,'' said Anna
Schryver, a spokeswoman for Lands' End. The company's policy, as
its catalogs put it, is ``Guaranteed period.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schryver even boasted that Land's End is being sued by a
German trade group, the Association Against Unfair Competition,
because of its liberal return policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Germans feel it's unfair that we take back anything
anytime,'' she said, ``whether it's washed, worn or old.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
