<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 17:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOUTIQUE-HOTELS-$ADV3     05-28 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOUTIQUE-HOTELS-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PLEASURES OF A BOUTIQUE HOTEL, EVEN IF THE HELP IS PRETTIER
THEN YOU  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By FRANK DeCARO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One recent midnight, I found myself walking up to a White Castle
drive-up window on the fringes of downtown Nashville. After a
five-and-a-half-hour delay on a flight with no meal service, I was
forced to beg a teen-ager to disregard the ``No Walk-Ups'' sign and
sell me two double cheeseburgers, a small order of fries and a Diet
Coke.
</P>
<P>
   My hotel, a historic train station converted into a hotel in
1986, didn't have 24-hour room service, so dinner ended up costing
me $4.85 _ plus my last shred of dignity.
</P>
<P>
   This humbling experience _ strangely reminiscent of a
``Designing Women'' episode in which Dixie Carter is arrested for
being a pedestrian in a drive-through lane _ reminded me how
spoiled I've become. In recent years, I have gotten used to staying
at so-called boutique hotels _ lodgings that are long on style,
even when they're notoriously short on space; hotels like the
Mondrian in Los Angeles and the Delano in Miami Beach.
</P>
<P>
   These small hotels pamper guests with CD players and VCRs in the
rooms, designer bath products, food on demand day or night, and
mini-bars stocked with enough haute snacks to avoid nights like my
fast-food fiasco in Music City. Such modern amenities as Smart Food
popcorn and safe-sex kits cost hoteliers little, but they seem to
be winning over guests.
</P>
<P>
   The boutique hotel is the trend of the moment in the lodging
industry, so popular that even giant chains like Hilton and
Sheraton are hurrying to get into the game, which began when Ian
Schrager opened Morgans in Manhattan in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   I have a love-hate relationship with these places, which
invariably are staffed by men and women who are better looking than
you and 98 percent of the people you know. That's their job. They
couldn't care less if they ever see you again.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, guests do come back to soak up the ambiance,
rub elbows with the right crowd and then brag to friends that
they've done so. Hotels like these are inherently pretentious _
designed to be gorgeous but distant, much like the employees.
</P>
<P>
   Our parents' generation _ which stayed at the Delano when people
knew it was named for Franklin Roosevelt and pronounced it DEL-ano,
not de-LAN-oh _ would look at these tiny ``done'' rooms and say,
``You spent $250 a night for an all-white walk-in closet with a
boom box?''
</P>
<P>
   But they would miss the point.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers today know that it is not necessarily the size of the
room, but the attention to detail that makes the modern hotel
experience, even if it's not a boutique hotel. A single,
spectacular corn muffin, for instance, colored my entire stay a few
years ago at the Four Seasons in Milan.
</P>
<P>
   But my visit to the Bellagio in Las Vegas in October was nearly
sunk when I had to trot down to the Origins store in the lobby
before I could have a good soak in my room's tub. What kind of
hotel provides a bathtub but no bath gel?
</P>
<P>
   Not a boutique hotel, that's for sure.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, new boutique hotels have been rolling off the
assembly line faster than new models of sport-utility vehicles. The
Hotel _ formerly known as the Tiffany _ is an instant Miami Beach
destination, thanks to an interior design by Todd Oldham, the
fashion designer. Its restaurant, Wish, in which Oldham is a
partner, is the place to be seen in a town that thrives on such
trendiness.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in West Hollywood, the Standard is the place to stay
if you're in your 20s and cute. This ``boutique motel,'' owned by
Andre Balazs of Mercer and Chateau Marmont fame, looks like a page
out of Wallpaper magazine, with a groovy 70s lobby with shag
carpeting on the walls, vintage doughnut-shaped house phones and
egg chairs.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms, ranging from $95 to $200, have Andy Warhol-print
curtains and inflatable chairs, while around the pool, there are
electric blue Astroturf and white lounge chairs.
</P>
<P>
   I remember my first boutique hotel experience some years back at
the Paramount Hotel on 46th Street. Before it opened, I had seen a
picture of a suite with a Dutch Masters painting for a headboard.
When I checked in, however, my room had only a blank canvas above
the bed. I said to the bellboy, ``What is this _ `Day Without
Art?'''
</P>
<P>
   He explained that the painted headboards came with more
expensive rooms. But even in my more basic room, the charms of this
hotel soon revealed themselves. The pillow bolsters were
comfortable and the lighting glamorously dim, and there was a
perfect peanut butter and jelly sandwich on the room service menu.
</P>
<P>
   Such glamour has its price. Every time I stay at the Mondrian,
for instance, I leave with a sore foot. The hotel's mattresses are
very comfortable. But in these Philippe Starck rooms, the bed is
constructed so that you can't help but kick the frame if you dash
for the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Still, who cares? When you're sleeping at one of these places,
you're sleeping with the right people, even if you sleep alone.
They are velvet rope establishments _ no surprise, considering that
the pioneer, Schrager, ran Studio 54 in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Many travelers, myself included, will take snarky doormen and
designer furniture over free Sanka and a borrowed hot pot. An
all-white castle like the Delano beats a White Castle drive-through
any day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
