<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-MURDERS-2TAK     05-28 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-MURDERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT MURDER SAYS ABOUT THE SOCIETY IT EXISTS IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Ideas) 
(lb) 
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the heart of the analysis of the killings last month at
Columbine High School in Colorado has been a deceptively simple
question: Were the killers chillingly aberrant monsters or were
they a part, however perverse, of something in our culture as a
whole?
</P>
<P>
   But long before Columbine, this question and others were being
asked by professors as homicide became an increasingly conspicuous
slice of American scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Recent books have surveyed murder in the United States and the
world, explored the meaning of murder narratives and unearthed vast
detail and sociological significance in celebrated 19th-century
cases. There is a 3-year-old journal, ``Homicide Studies: An
Interdisciplinary Journal.''
</P>
<P>
   These and other projects suggest that just as ``true crime'' has
become a permanent fixture in publishing, murder may be
establishing itself as a valid course of study in academia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Homicide has always been the backbone of history _
`legitimate' homicide, which is war,'' said Roger Lane, a Haverford
College historian and author of ``Murder in America'' (Ohio State
University Press, 1998). ``It has only been in the past generation
that social historians have discovered how much homicide has to
tell us about the society in which it exists.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, historians have been drawn to celebrated murder
cases, and criminologists and sociologists have long studied the
incidence of homicide and how to reduce it.
</P>
<P>
   But only recently have scholars begun to focus so intensely on
murder as a window on society and a revealing subject for social
historians or intellectual historians. Lane's book, for example,
tracks the incidence of murder and the culture's response to it
from medieval England to modern times, using murder _ and which
murders are deemed to matter _ as a way to take the social
temperature on issues of race, class and attitudes toward children
and the sexes.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Cline Cohen of the University of California at Santa
Barbara and Amy Gilman Srebnick of Montclair State University each
examined different 19th-century cases of murdered women in New York
to analyze attitudes about women, sexuality and class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Murder Most Foul: The Killer and the American Gothic
Imagination'' (Harvard University Press, 1998) by Karen Halttunen
of the University of California at Davis tracks the way the culture
has imagined and portrayed murder.
</P>
<P>
   She argues that the depictions of murder reveal a shift from
values based in the Puritan religion to secular ones. In the first
case, murderers are seen as sinners in a community of sinners,
whose fall is a warning to everyone. In the second, the killer is
seen as an alien monster whose crimes reflect his separation from
the rest of society. She calls this the Gothic homicide narrative.
</P>
<P>
   Dwayne Smith, a sociologist at the University of North Carolina
at Charlotte and editor of the Journal of Homicide Studies, said
that it is natural for scholars to be drawn to murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a joke that if a total alien came and did a content
analysis of American literature and pop culture, he'd conclude that
we kill one another and we fall in love,'' he said. ``The culture
has such a tremendous fascination with homicide, you would expect
to find academic interest as well.''
</P>
<P>
   But until recently homicide was largely left to the
criminologists and sociologists, whose research tends toward the
pieces in Homicide Studies on topics like ``Suicide Following
Homicide in Canada'' or ``Murder as Self-Help: Women and Intimate
Partner Homicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Cohen, a historian at Florida International University
who wrote a survey of crime literature, cited two developments that
made homicide more appealing to historians and other scholars.
</P>
<P>
   The first, he said, was the development of the New Social
History in the 1970s, which argued for depictions of the poor,
minorities, women, religious and ethnic minorities and others who
had been often overlooked in histories geared toward the rich and
powerful. The second was a renewed respect for narrative rather
than quantitative or technical analysis in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Thus ``The Murder of Helen Jewett'' (Knopf, 1998) by Ms. Cohen
and ``The Mysterious Death of Mary Rogers'' (Oxford University
Press, 1997) by Ms. Srebnick take murders of women, the first a
prostitute in 1836, the second a 20-year-old descendant of
prominent New England settlers in 1841, and combine compelling
storytelling with bottom-up social analysis. (Edgar Allan Poe based
``The Mystery of Marie Roget'' on the Rogers case.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Cohen said newspaper accounts and trial transcripts _
usually kept unofficially by reporters rather than by the courts _
provide much material about the lives of ordinary and marginalized
groups that would otherwise be extraordinarily hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the best ways to hear from people who don't
normally publish books or get their words written down,'' she said.
``There were 20 different court reporters putting out transcripts
in the Helen Jewett trial. Normally you would not hear about the
life of a prostitute except through the eyes of moral reformers.''
</P>
<P>
   For some scholars homicide is most interesting not as a
reflection of cultural forces but as a subject in itself,
particularly given the consistently high murder rates in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Monkkonen, a historian at the University of California at
Los Angeles, has spent nearly 12 years studying 200 years' worth of
homicide in New York City. Monkkonen is part of a loosely knit
group of about 250 researchers from various disciplines called the
Homicide Research Working Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't usually get much of a long view of homicide,'' he
said. ``We're always thinking of the past 10 years and very seldom
looking at the past 200. If someone were to say to me, `Why 200
years _ it's not enough _ it should be 300?'' I'd say, `I agree _ I
just couldn't do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Monkkonen said his research more than anything convinces him
that the shifts in homicide rates reflect a web of social, economic
and technological factors, ranging from changes in policing and
weapons to shifts in employment that may take a generation to take
hold, rather than any single government policy. That leads him to
be wary of attributing credit for the current plunge in homicide or
expecting lower crime levels to be permanent.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Some aspects of homicide seem eternal, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Cases that get the most attention, like those of O.J. Simpson
and JonBenet Ramsey now or those of Mary Rogers and Helen Jewett,
often include salacious elements of passion and mystery that also
cross into the tense territory of race or sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   And despite widespread worries about the toxic effects of
tabloid media, murder has always sold. The sensational murders of
the 19th century were perhaps the greatest sales tools for the
fledgling newspapers of the time reaching out for a mass audience.
And before there was Geraldo Rivera pumping up ratings with daily
coverage of the Simpson case, there was Cotton Mather, the famous
preacher of Colonial America.
</P>
<P>
   ``As early as the 1680s you had ministers who realized that
murder cases provided them with a much larger audience than they
normally had,'' Cohen said. ``Usually sermons were reprinted with
maybe 200 or 300 copies. Cotton Mather used to brag how he could
print 1,200 or 1,500 copies of execution sermons, and they would
sell out.''
</P>
<P>
   One element that seems new to many scholars, however, is the
current wave of school shootings, which because of the age of the
killers and the way they strike at schools and schoolchildren, defy
most of the common conventions of American homicide.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Halttunen's book argues that some recent murder accounts,
like the book and film ``Dead Man Walking,'' veer back toward the
earlier Puritan sense of the killer who reflected society's sins
rather than an alien ogre. Yet she admits that the recent school
killings have elements of both.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very torn in the way we view them,'' she said.
``Something about these school shootings may be pushing us through
a wall. It's almost as if we are searching for a new language with
which to discuss them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen says that this has always been the case. In his 1993 book,
``Pillars of Salt, Monuments of Grace: New England Crime Literature
and the Origins of American Popular Culture,'' he argues that
accounts of and reactions to homicide show that killers have
traditionally been seen as insiders and outsiders simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the increase in scholarship began when murder rates were
soaring. Now they are plummeting. But Lane said homicide was
unlikely to disappear, either as a crime or as a subject of
scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave a talk to the Mystery Writers of America in January,
and I told them not to worry _ murder isn't going away,'' he said.
``The factors that appear to be driving down homicide, I think, are
short-term with clear downside boundaries, and homicide is going to
rebound. Sex and violence have always sold. The interest in murder
doesn't flag. We academics are finally catching up with it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
