<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5295 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-SOFTSHELLED-CRABS     05-28 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-SOFTSHELLED-CRABS-ART-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA FISHERMEN TURN TO SOFT-SHELLED CRABS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RON MATUS   
 Gainesville (Fla.) Sun   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HORSESHOE BEACH, Fla. _ Former mullet fisherman Teddy Kight
isn't getting much sleep these days. When his 22-month-old baby
isn't waking him up in the middle of the night, a mess of
soft-shell crabs are.
</P>
<P>
   Soft-shell crabs are just blue crabs that have shed their
shells, but they're worth many times more. Problem is, it takes
only a few hours before the new shells are too hard to eat, and the
crabs like to shed at night.
</P>
<P>
   So Kight, his wife and his three brothers have to check on his
crab tanks around the clock. Kight makes his rounds at midnight and
3 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad part about it: The baby doesn't correspond to this,''
he said with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   Kight, 44, would rather be catching mullet. But the mullet
industry sank in 1994 when Florida banned the use of nets in
commercial fishing. Kight and scores of other fishermen have turned
to soft-shell crabbing.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good. Soft-shell production is up 20 percent from
1996, according to the University of Florida Sea Grant Program. The
most recent statistics show that people new to soft-shell crabbing
harvested 21,000 dozen crabs worth more than $500,000 during the
first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And, fisheries experts say the fledgling industry has room to
grow. Blue crab populations are healthy and closely monitored, they
say. More soft-shell crabbers won't hurt it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Florida can supply restaurants and seafood markets
for several months every year before blue crabs begin shedding up
north. The spring season in Florida runs from February to June.
There's also a fall season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida's crabbers take the summer off when the rest of the
states get into their soft-shell production,'' said Paul Zajicek, a
seafood specialist with the Department of Agriculture and Consumer
Services. ``Florida farmers do the same thing _ hit the market
early. That's when they get the best prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, soft-shell crabbing in Florida had never taken
off. Commercial fishermen were too busy catching redfish and mullet
to set crab traps.
</P>
<P>
   But when Florida voters passed the net ban amendment in 1994,
putting 6,500 net fishermen out of work, some began to take another
look.
</P>
<P>
   Kight and his brothers burned their nets after the net ban and
reluctantly got construction jobs. Crabbing brought them back to
the water. Between that and clamming, they're able to make as much
as they did fishing, Kight said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're raised up on the water, it's hard to leave,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sea Grant program helped. It conducted 40 workshops around
the state, provided technical advice to fishermen and distributed
more than 100 starter kits for crab tanks worth $500 a piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of popped our eyes open,'' said Debbie Bryan at
Bryan Crab Farm. She and her husband, Vernon, have harvested blue
crabs and stone crabs for years, but never tried soft-shelling. ``I
don't know why we didn't do it before.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Jackson, who is coordinating the Sea Grant project, said 65
fishermen have put the starter kits to use. In Horseshoe Beach, a
Gulf Coast town of 300 people 70 miles west of Gainesville, there
are as many as 35 crabbers now _ up from seven or eight before the
net ban, Kight said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said soft-shell crabbing is more likely to be a
part-time job than clamming, another sector of the seafood industry
that blossomed after the net ban.
</P>
<P>
   Hard crabs are worth 15 cents before shedding, $2 after, Kight
said. Consumers are willing to pay much more for crabs that can be
fried whole for sandwiches or plopped into gumbos without messy
peeling.
</P>
<P>
   Kight said he has invested $25,000 in equipment for his crabbing
operation. His whole family is involved.
</P>
<P>
   His brothers check on hundreds of traps every morning to find
``peelers.'' Since blue crabs can't mate until they shed, a male
crab is placed in each trap to attract females, which then attract
more males, Kight said.
</P>
<P>
   Crabbers can tell which crabs are ready to shed by a line of
color on their flippers. The redder the line, the closer the crabs
are to shedding.
</P>
<P>
   Kight keeps the peelers in a briny-smelling building that once
housed the town's general store. Dozens of crab traps are stacked
outside.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, plastic pipes carry water from wooden beams overhead to
a dozen shallow, wooden tanks. Scores of crabs scuttle around in
each as water pours down.
</P>
<P>
   Every few minutes, another crab cracks its old shell and backs
out of it, like a snake sloughing off its skin.
</P>
<P>
   Kight weighs each shed crab, sorts them by size and stacks them,
still alive, in hay-lined cardboard boxes. He sells them to a
nearby dealer who ships them to Miami, New York, Philadelphia and
other crab-hungry cities in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Kight said this year's spring harvest is down from last year's,
although prices are still high. His brothers are bringing in about
250 crabs a day compared to 1,000 a day last year.
</P>
<P>
   The spring drought might be responsible, or the natural ebb and
flow of crab populations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, he said after a pause, ``There's more boats on the
water, too.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Gainesville, Fla., Sun is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
