<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5314 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TULEH-FASHION-NYT-ART     05-28 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TULEH-FASHION-NYT-ART-800(2TAKES)-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FASHION WORLD IN WHICH RUFFLES AND FANTASY COLORS RULE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ELIZABETH HAYT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Over lunch at a sidewalk table on Madison Avenue,
Josh Patner and Bryan Bradley took one look at a young woman
hurrying by in a navy blue pinstripe suit and shook their heads
sadly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women have been so oppressed,'' Patner said. ``They can be
successful and come from very enlightened backgrounds, yet they
still feel compelled to blend in. New York will not allow a woman
to look'' _ he pursed his lips and shimmied his shoulders _
`` &UR; ooh-la-la &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley then said, ``New York will not let her expose her
fantasy of being Tuleh!''
</P>
<P>
   Tuleh, a collection of luxurious and romantic clothes, including
1950s-style beaded dresses, lavishly printed cocktail pajamas and
sable stoles, was created by Patner and Bradley a year ago. But
Tuleh is more than just a label. The name refers to the designers'
fictional muse, as well as the desire for frilly femininity that
they believe has long smoldered under the dark, minimalist uniforms
of today's working woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The monochromatic wardrobe that was supposed to give women
freedom to move from the boardroom to the bedroom is actually
limiting,'' Patner said, waving a fork in the air at La Goulue,
between 64th and 65th Streets, an ideal perch from which to observe
some of the city's most put-together women. ``Tuleh releases the
pink in them. Tuleh is a persona that lives in every woman. Her
style is exaggerated. She might leave the house in her favorite
robe, but the cuffs are chinchilla because she can't help herself.
Life is her party. She dresses to please herself, whereas that
navy-blue-suit lady is dressing to be accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   As the two men studied the menu at the bistro, Patner, the more
gregarious of the pair, was suddenly distracted by an elderly woman
in a lime-green sweater, green embroidered shoes, green eye shadow
and green earrings, who was getting up from a nearby table.
``You've got to see this,'' he said, nudging Bradley, his more
contemplative partner. ``She's a friend of Tuleh's.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as the woman in green left, another in a long black skirt
and mandarin jacket passed by, her hair in a severe bun and face
made up Kabuki-style. She was all Patner needed to begin a screed
against the color black, as fashion uniform and symbol of
irreproachable chic in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a particularly New York look,'' he said. ``It's a
refusal. It's high Linda Dresner style, a very exclusive club. But
when women wear black, I don't see them anymore. They're
anonymous.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, that view has made Patner and Bradley darlings of a
certain segment of the fashion world. Their sparkly, ruffled
garments _ just right for a modern-day Auntie Mame _ have been
featured in high-end fashion magazines, and when the spring
collection was put out on racks at Bergdorf Goodman in March, about
40 of the 50 or so pieces disappeared in four hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're in touch with the end of the century,'' said Andre
Leon Talley, the editor at large of Vogue. ``There is a need for
glamour and sophistication. There has to be people who give women
ballgowns with yards of imaginative fabric. Tuleh has a Southern
Gothic feeling. There is a sophistication lacking in American
clothes. Everyone thinks it's enough to put a pale blue cashmere
sweater in six-ply with a terra-cotta skirt and call it fashion.
Tuleh is the antidote.''
</P>
<P>
   Patner, 37, and Bradley, 32, have been nominated for a Perry
Ellis award for new talent in women's wear by the Council of
Fashion Designers of America, along with Katayone Adeli and Rebecca
Danenberg. The honor, which will be announced at the American
Fashion Awards on Wednesday, has been won in the past by
stars-to-be like Marc Jacobs and John Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   But as other winners can attest _ like David Cameron and
Christian Francis Roth, each of whom went out of business shortly
after winning _ it is no guarantee of anything more than a burst of
attention.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, at least, the spotlight is shining on Patner and
Bradley, whose label is in touch with the desire for decoration,
bright color and froufrou that anticipates the kicking up of heels
in the coming season of millennial parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modern is not antiseptic,'' Patner intoned at the bistro, his
voice mounting. ``Why do people think the future looks so bleak?
Why do designers think modern women have to look like pod people?
Tuleh is a vehement reaction against techno sport fabrics that look
like heat repellent. We believe in violet, aqua and red. No stone,
pumice, earth and sky-malt colors. Modern is a pretty dress. That's
our manifesto.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such enthusiasm for eye-catching fashion, Patner, who
wears anonymous tortoise-shell eyeglasses, and Bradley, who sports
a half-grown goatee, are pretty unstylish characters themselves. In
washed-out, rumpled shirts and jeans, the two men, both from the
Midwest, are anything but sleek.
</P>
<P>
   As a twosome, they are a Bob Hope and Bing Crosby act: Patner
spouting droll, tongue-in-cheek observations; Bradley occasionally
blurting out witticisms but mostly laughing heartily at whatever
his partner says. In the studio, they collaborate on designs.
Playing straight man, Bradley runs the pattern-making and sewing,
while Patner takes his charm offensive to the press and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the pulse of what's going on,'' said Lillian
Hirshleifer, the owner of Hirshleifer's, a high-fashion store in
Manhasset, N.Y. ``When we had the first trunk show in March, it was
a huge success. The dresses flew out of the store.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Tuleh's focused look, so fresh-seeming to adventurous
retailers and customers, could end up looking dated a couple of
seasons from now. The death of black has been predicted before by
fashion insiders, who continued to make it a staple of their own
wardrobes, proving the enduring appeal of a go-anywhere, drop-dead
wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   Patner, a former women's fashion coordinator at Bergdorf Goodman
and freelance magazine stylist, and Bradley, a freelance designer
who had worked for Calvin Klein, conceived of Tuleh in April 1998
after meeting through mutual acquaintances in 1997. They created a
few samples, which they packed in a suite of vintage suitcases and
hand-carried to Bergdorf. Along with pastel voile blouses, a tulle
party dress and a purple wool suit, the suitcases included a pack
of Lucky Strikes, a diary, leather gloves, matchbooks with phone
numbers scribbled on them and a train ticket to New Orleans. They
presented the suitcases to Joseph Boitano, who was then the store's
executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a collection,'' recalled Boitano, who this week will
become the general merchandise manager for women's designer wear at
Saks Fifth Avenue. ``It was a concept. It was about the Tuleh
woman, her life style and what she wears. It was as if this woman
had been traveling and she'd popped open her suitcase. It was fun
and charming. So many companies have moved to simple sportswear,
Tuleh's idea of lady clothes seemed like a great option in the
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Tuleh was sold at only two stores, Bergdorf and
Neiman Marcus in San Francisco, with prices ranging from $300, for
a top, to $12,000, for hand-beaded creations. Six months later, the
business includes 20 accounts nationwide. At Ultimo in Dallas, half
the stock was bought after the store held a runway preview of the
spring collection, and a $4,000 feather-trimmed stole immediately
sold out, said Lynne Henry, the women's buyer at Ultimo.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Fischbein, a lawyer from New York, was so eager for a
strapless floral dress she saw in a newspaper last fall that she
hunted it down for months, finally locating one in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phone rings off the hook with women who want our
dresses,'' Patner said with obvious amusement. ``You can hear the
craving in their voice for color. They want the gaze of desire.
They want their boyfriends and husbands to look at them.''
</P>
<P>
   But despite these successes, Tuleh is still in the vulnerable
position of most new independent labels. The partners have borrowed
money from family members, cashed out IRA's and maxed out their
credit cards. They are eagerly searching for a financial backer,
because they lack sufficient cash flow and have even turned down
accounts, they say, because they cannot afford enough fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Their showroom and work space is Bradley's former apartment on
the Upper West Side, grandly named ``the atelier'' but in fact a
small, run-down, five-floor walk-up shared with two seamstresses.
(The designers live together downtown now.)
</P>
<P>
   The men seem perfectly happy amid the peeling paint, chipped
moldings and thread-bare furniture in the atelier. They serve pink
lemonade to a parade of women who seem to drop by regularly,
including fashion editors and clients like Cameron Diaz and Candace
Bushnell, borrowing dresses for parties or photo shoots.
</P>
<P>
   At La Goulue, Patner was explaining why Arnold Scaasi is a hero
_ a designer who accepted that fashion's first job is to make women
beautiful _ when a blonde in a black and white window-pane suit
with a Pucci blouse stopped to talk to the maitre d'hotel. ``She's
very Bill Blass,'' Bradley said. ``Bill's the master of snappy
clothes. We think he's the coolest American designer. He's cool the
way Tony Bennett is cool.''
</P>
<P>
   As the two men polished off their dessert parfaits (``Just the
word `parfait' is delicious,'' Patner sighed), a pair of tanned,
20-something women jumped out of a Range Rover. They both had long
straight hair and were wearing skinny black pants, tight T-shirts,
black sandals and Gucci sunglasses. Waiting outside the restaurant
for a table, one spoke into a cell phone while the other kept
looking at her Cartier watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're vulgar,'' Bradley said, turning away. ``They have far
too many accessories of the wrong sort with other people's names on
them. And why buy black shoes when you can buy purple? Shoes should
be amusing both for you and for your public.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking a glance up and down the street, Patner said, ``Cool
older women, and really insecure younger women who all look the
same _ that's Madison Avenue.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
