<HEADLINE>
CRITICS CHARGE OFFICIALS OVERREACTING TO POSSIBLE SCHOOL VIOLENCE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Colo., Mich., Texas, Wisc.) 
 
By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Could four 14-year-old boys really pull off a two-year plan to
hold a Texas high school ransom for $5 million?
</P>
<P>
   How about four Michigan youths who envisioned themselves ripping
off a gun shop, storming their middle school and ordering students
and teachers to the cafeteria, where they would then choose who
lived and died?
</P>
<P>
   Or the 13-year-old Wisconsin boy who scribbled bomb threats on
Popsicle sticks? To law enforcement agents, that infraction was
serious enough to arrest the Wisconsin boy.
</P>
<P>
   And while the teens from the Texas town of Wimberley pleaded
guilty to avoid being tried as adults, two of the Michigan boys are
being tried as adults and face an automatic sentence of life in
prison if convicted. The other two boys, both 13, could also be
tried as adults.
</P>
<P>
   While last month's violence at Colorado's Columbine High School
has yielded copycat threats across the United States, it has
likewise resulted in heavy-handed responses from school
administrators and authorities. Now critics are charging that
principals and police have gone too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are vilifying our kids,'' said Vincent Schiraldi, director
of the Washington-based Center on Juvenile and Criminal Justice.
``We're mistaking zero tolerance for zero intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Columbine tragedy in Littleton, Colo., and the myriad
threats that followed have touched off an almost hysterical
climate. Compared with May of last year, the Center on Juvenile and
Criminal Justice reports a 10-fold increase in reports of students
expelled for making threats.
</P>
<P>
   Around Houston, numerous threats in schools have been met with
dozens of suspensions and arrests, including one seventh-grader for
making terroristic threats. And in suburban Dallas, Allen school
district officials declared the school year canceled after 12 bomb
threats in less than two weeks, then reversed themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Allen school officials also suspended a 17-year-old student for
wearing a black arm band to protest new speech and dress policies
that took effect after the Columbine shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the preventive measures they are taking, school
officials and law enforcement agents may be overlooking the fact
that incidents such as Columbine are rare.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than 1 percent of child homicides occur in or around
schools, according to the Centers for Disease Control. And while
the number of school shootings with multiple victims has risen,
from an average of two to an average of five a year, the total
number of shootings has declined.
</P>
<P>
   To some, the horror of Columbine, in which two teen-age gunmen
killed 13 people, and then themselves, is reason enough to crack
down.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Houston, executive director of the American Association of
School Administrators, says administrators should be expected to
act forcefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question schools have overreacted,'' said Houston.
``The problem you have is that if they're not overreacting, they're
underreacting.''
</P>
<P>
   Three of the Texas junior-high boys were sentenced last week to
boot camp and juvenile probation after pleading guilty to
conspiracy to commit arson. Another received a lesser charge of
juvenile probation.
</P>
<P>
   Though Hays County District Attorney Michael Wenk admitted this
week that the plot involving Wimberley High school was not
imminent, he says the evidence suggests authorities thwarted an
attack. School officials agree.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many locals are skeptical. Searches of the Wimberley
boys' homes yielded what authorities initially described as crude
explosives. They turned out to be mostly fireworks, including
firecrackers stuffed into shotgun shell casings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly they talked more than they should have,'' said Ray
Green, a lawyer for one of the boys. ``But it's hard for me to
believe any 14-year-old has a long-range plan they're actually
going to follow through on.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether students, especially those in junior
high school and younger, should be prosecuted for what may simply
be acting like kids. In a class project that required Ohio
third-graders to provide fortunes for fortune cookies, one student
wrote, ``You will die an honorable death,'' a line he picked up
from a martial arts video. The boy was suspended.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, teachers in Littleton were criticized for failing to
pick up signs that Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, were
deeply troubled: Gothic music, black trench coats, even a video the
two killers made for a class project in which they act out a
terrorist attack on their school.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say most students, especially the younger ones, are
prone to acting inappropriately. Elaine Blechman, a professor of
psychology at the University of Colorado at Boulder, says the
recent trend toward zero tolerance ignores the fact that kids say
and do silly things.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the reason we have children in school,'' said Blechman.
``It's the reason parents are responsible for their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Blechman maintains that the crackdown, and in particular trying
kids as adults, is almost certain to force otherwise mainstream
youths to the fringes, creating the very types that might actually
wreak havoc on society.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to grow a whole bunch of monsters,'' said Blechman,
``let's just throw these kids in with a bunch of adult felons.''
</P>
<P>
   Houston says he expects the over-wrought responses to wane in
the coming months. If not, Houston says, then there will be reason
to worry.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not likely to mean much to the Port Huron, Mich.,
boys, who may have been out to mimic the Columbine massacre, or who
may have simply been enjoying a violent fantasy, not entirely
unusual for boys their age.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all hearsay, rumor, guilt by association,'' said Frank
Mitchell, the lawyer for one boy. Mitchell says his 13-year-old
client told him he thought the other three boys were joking about
the killing spree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next thing you know, he's in jail with $100,000 bond,'' said
Mitchell. ``He could go to prison for life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
