<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5321 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAPS-HISTORY-2TAKES-N     05-28 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAPS-HISTORY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAP MAKERS EXPLORE THE CONTOURS OF POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Wis.)  (rk) 
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The history of maps once seemed a quaint preoccupation. The
cartographer was a specialist in incomplete and antique vistas,
surveying terrains, boundaries and trade routes that were
decorously traced on tentatively shaped landmasses.
</P>
<P>
   Old maps _ with their compass roses, their illuminated borders
and their vast blank spaces _ were sought by collectors and
historians but were otherwise considered artful relics of
ignorance, faltering steps on the way to modern geography.
</P>
<P>
   No longer. In the past 25 years there has been a sea change in
the world of cartography. The study of maps has come to seem
urgently contemporary, taking on all the contours now familiar from
recent academic studies of history, literature and culture.
</P>
<P>
   In this realm, maps are not just a progressive record of
attempts to know the world; they are a record of attempts to
construct and control it. Maps are not innocent. They select the
data they wish to emphasize and ignore what is inconvenient. They
are being looked at as instruments of power.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, for example, cartographer Arno Peters argued that the
familiar Mercator map of the globe, in which a country's size
increases the further it is from the equator, gives undue
geographical emphasis to Europe and diminishes the size of third
world countries.
</P>
<P>
   His proposed replacement, adopted by many international
agencies, is an ``equal-area'' map in which shapes are distorted
but size is preserved. This argument has its problems: the Mercator
map was never meant to associate size with importance (Greenland
was never a world power); its advantage was that it preserved
bearings for sea navigation. But the controversy was a sign of
change.
</P>
<P>
   Since then scholars have analyzed the role of maps in imperial
conquest (``Mapping an Empire: The Geographical Construction of
British India, 1765-1843,'' by Matthew H. Edney); the misuse of
maps (``How to Lie With Maps,'' by Mark Monmonier); and the
ideological presuppositions of maps (``Maps and Politics'' by
Jeremy Black).
</P>
<P>
   The last book concludes that politics and maps are inseparable
and that ``there is no unchallenged or obvious basis'' for a claim
of a map's objectivity. This challenge to objectivity _ an almost
axiomatic position in contemporary scholarship _ has been widely
accompanied by assertions that the standard notion of a map, as an
attempt to accurately render geographic space, is also Eurocentric,
eclipsing and distorting other cultures' map-making achievements.
</P>
<P>
   An important scholarly enterprise, the History of Cartography,
by the University of Chicago Press, provides further signs of the
field's evolution. Conceived 22 years ago, it is the most ambitious
overview of map making ever undertaken.
</P>
<P>
   With annual budget costs of about $200,000 (excluding its
publication), it engages in extensive fund raising and applies for
grants. The fourth volume in the series has just been published,
and the final four are expected in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   In a review in the cartographic journal Imago Mundi, Paul
Wheatley of the University of Chicago proclaimed: ``It is permitted
to few scholars both to extend the boundaries of their field of
study and to redefine it as a discipline. Yet that is precisely
what the History as a whole is doing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first volume, published in 1987, one of the founding
editors, J.B. Harley, noted that ``by 1980 the history of
cartography was at the crossroads.'' By combining essays based on
original research by authoritative scholars with extensive
illustrations of rare and unusual maps, the project is an attempt
to illuminate the terrain beyond the crossroads.
</P>
<P>
   The History would, Harley suggested, move beyond ``a deeply
entrenched Eurocentricity'' and undertake ``a technical, a cultural
and a social history of mapping.''
</P>
<P>
   But Harley, who died in 1991, and his co-editor, David Woodward,
a professor of geography at the University of Wisconsin at Madison,
underestimated how much the field was changing, and to what extent
the project itself would affect the field being surveyed.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Woodward said the original plan was
for a four-volume history. The first was to include all non-Western
and pre-medieval materials, and then ``we would get on to the real
maps,'' as Woodward put it, in volumes devoted to the European
Renaissance, the European Enlightenment and the modern period.
</P>
<P>
   But the non-Western materials had until then been so cursorily
studied that ``it became obvious that we were in terra incognita,''
Woodward said. The planned single volume grew into four, which have
broken so much new ground that they are already having an impact.
</P>
<P>
   The History has inspired new interpretations of medieval
``mappaemundi,'' early Western maps of the known world, which often
appeared as geometrically divided circles. The third volume
(labeled Volume II, Book 2) awakened interest in the intricacies of
Asian mapping traditions. And the latest volume (labeled Volume II,
Book 3) provides, in the book's words, ``the first serious global
attempt'' to describe and explain the principles of cartography in
traditional African, American, Arctic, Australian and Pacific
societies.
</P>
<P>
   These volumes are not just accumulations of neglected materials.
Woodward said that the essays were written from a new perspective:
``We move beyond the idea of a map as a mirror of the world. The
emphasis is much more on the agendas people have when they make
them. Maps are treated less as representational devices than as
rhetorical devices.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   In discussing South American maps, for example, one contributor,
William Gustav Gartner, suggests that maps cannot be thought of as
flat surfaces geometrically rendering space: ``We will not
recognize Andean maps until we attempt to see through Andean
eyes.'' So an Andean ceramic vessel is described as a map because
its rendering of a house and a warrior's shield is accompanied by
sculptured images of the surrounding mountains, roads and canals.
</P>
<P>
   In another example, an Australian aboriginal painting of birds
on a cashew tree, an account of the tribe's mythic origins, is seen
as a map outlining the territorial landscape within which the tribe
dwells. A ``lukasa memory board'' from the Kabongo region of the
Congo that is decorated with shells and beads and is used in
initiation ceremonies is also a regional map.
</P>
<P>
   The authors point out that none of these cultures even had a
word for ``map'' before their contact with the West; a generation
ago, these objects might not have even been considered maps by
Western cartographers. But with the new view of maps as a
``cognitive system,'' a way of making sense of the world according
to a culture's customs, iconography merges into cartography. Maps
not only portray space but also display ritual and social
relationships within that space. ``Comparing maps,'' Woodward
writes, ``implies no less than comparing cultures.''
</P>
<P>
   This emphasis on cultural anthropology will also lead to the
remapping of more familiar territory as the maps of the West are
examined for their cultural contexts in forthcoming books. In the
next volume, scheduled for publication in 2003, Woodward said,
editors had planned to treat the Renaissance map as a ``metaphor
for science'' in which gaps in geographical knowledge are gradually
filled.
</P>
<P>
   But the emphasis has shifted from the accretion of knowledge to
how that knowledge is organized: what premises held in making maps,
what conclusions were drawn from them and what cultural and
political functions they served.
</P>
<P>
   For example, ``it is now possible to say that some of the major
map-making figures in the 16th century, like Mercator, were a lot
more religiously motivated than we once thought,'' Woodward said.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the project draws to a close with studies of
20th-century mapping, the 21st century will be well under way and
the great cartographic project of the West will have been
completely reinterpreted. Although Woodward is careful to distance
the series from radical questioning of the possibility of objective
mapping, the History still has radical implications.
</P>
<P>
   By suggesting that all understanding may be a form of mapping,
it places maps at the center of social existence, as an almost
archetypal example of human knowledge. Indeed, in discussing their
thoughts or feelings, people often invoke a cartographic universe.
</P>
<P>
   Feeling bewildered, one talks about ``terra incognita,'' about
``being at a crossroads'' or ``losing our way.'' Gaining
enlightenment, one speaks of ``putting things in perspective'' and
``being on familiar terrain.'' People come to know the world the
way they come to map it _ through their perceptions of how its
elements are connected and of how they should move among them.
</P>
<P>
   This is precisely what the History is attempting by situating
the map at the heart of cultural life and revealing its
relationship to society, science and religion. It is tracing new
routes of cartographic influence, for example from Europe to Asia
and back to Europe, and from American Indians to European settlers
and back to American Indians. It is trying to define a new set of
relationships between maps and the physical world that involve more
than geometric correspondence.
</P>
<P>
   It is in essence a new map of human attempts to chart the world.
Since this cartographic enterprise has yet to encompass the
Renaissance and its aftermath, it is a map with vast empty spaces
and clouded boundaries. What, after all, made Western mapping so
different from that of other cultures? How important is the notion
of the Western map as a metaphor for science? What made certain
forms of mapping more important and more powerful than others?
</P>
<P>
   The answers go to the heart of many contemporary controversies.
But in its ambitious attempts to map the maps of the world's
cultures, the project ends up affirming the principles of
observation, imagination and abstraction that gave birth to Western
cartography in the first place.
</P>
