<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-INHERIT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INHERIT THE WIND': TESTED FORUM FOR PIETY AND CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its decades of incarnations on and off Broadway and on big
and small screens, ``Inherit the Wind'' has attracted audiences
both by its righteous theme and its dramatic punch. Once again
Saturday night, the battle between benightedness and enlightenment
offers viewers of a liberal persuasion the satisfaction of sharing
in the play's assumptions and having their own advanced opinions
confirmed. The drama comes most forcefully in the climactic
confrontation between a spouter of the old-time religion and a
secular advocate of free speech.
</P>
<P>
   This time out, it's George C. Scott, exuding a narrow and at
moments ferocious piety, as Matthew Harrison Brady, facing off
against Jack Lemmon, representing science and open argument as
Henry Drummond. The case, of course, is the famous monkey trial
that agitated the town of Hillsboro, Tenn., in 1925; at issue was
whether a schoolteacher could introduce his pupils to evolution
despite a law against it. The champion of the fundamentalist locals
was William Jennings Bryan ( Scott); the voice of reason was
Clarence Darrow ( Lemmon).
</P>
<P>
   Scott and Lemmon make a strong pair of antagonists, right up
there with Fredric March and Spencer Tracy in Stanley Kramer's 1960
movie, and are the main reason for tuning into Showtime Saturday
night. Lawyer Darrow and politician Bryan had been allied in
Populist causes over the years, but on this issue there was no
meeting ground. When Drummond gets Brady in the witness chair as a
self-proclaimed expert on the Bible _ ``Everything in the Bible
should be accepted exactly as it is written'' _ the fundamentalist
self-destructs, and that makes the play.
</P>
<P>
   There is never any question about whose side the audience is
expected to take in a conflict between an earnest young teacher
(Tom Everett Scott) and a town full of nitwits. The script seems to
have been turned out by machine. ``What kind of life will we have
if I give up now?'' the teacher asks his fiancee. The issue is too
easy to be very interesting.
</P>
<P>
   But Scott and Lemmon invest their roles with a humanity that
cuts deeper than ideology. The show flags whenever they are off
camera, which happily is not often. Saturday night's treatment lays
on period atmospherics _ plenty of cardboard fans and straw hats _
and finesses current arguments over creationism by having Drummond
show respect for the Bible as well as for Darwin.
</P>
<P>
   As a newspaperman modeled on H.L. Mencken, Beau Bridges becomes
the play's heavy in an insufferably sarcastic performance that is
meant to stand as a contrast to Darrow's compassion for his
defeated foe. Mencken, whose reporting on the trial is a hoot and a
classic of journalism, deserves better. John Cullum as the
presiding judge brings a touch of credibility to the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   For plot convenience, the teacher's girlfriend, Rachel (Kathryn
Morris), turns out to be the daughter of the local minister (Lane
Smith), who seems half-crazed most of the time. The title, taken
from Proverbs, refers to this parent-child disagreement, but don't
worry about it.
</P>
<P>
   For the real pleasure of the evening, wait for the shirt-sleeve
exchanges over over how Joshua stopped the sun and the whale
swallowed Jonah and how Mrs. Cain got begat. ``I do not think about
things I do not think about,'' says Scott-Brady-Bryan. To which
Lemmon-Drummond-Darrow inquires, ``Do you think about things you do
think about?''  &QL; 
INHERIT THE WIND  &QL; 
Showtime, Saturday night at 8 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Teleplay by Nedrick Young and Harold Jacob Smith; directed by
Daniel Petrie Sr.; Dennis Bishop, producer; James Bartle, director
of photography; music by Laurence Rosenthal; Keith Addis and David
Lane Seltzer, executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   CAST: Jack Lemmon (Henry Drummond), George C. Scott (Matthew
Harrison Brady), John Cullum (Judge Merle Coffey), Kathryn Morris
(Rachel Brown), Tom Everett Scott (Bertram Cates), Lane Smith (the
Rev. Jeremiah Brown), Brad Greenquist (Tom Davenport), David Wells
(Mayor Carter), Peter MacKensie (Jesse Dunlap) and Beau Bridges
(E.K. Hornbeck). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
