A5332 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDER-JUSTICE-$ADV30     05-28 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-JUSTICE-$ADV30-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSECUTORS TO FOCUS ON COOPERATION AT BORDER MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 30)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Cross-border justice, including how to handle car
thieves, killers, money launderers and dead-beat parents, will be
on the agenda this week as 10 attorneys general from U.S. and
Mexican border states gather here to talk strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The 18th Border Attorneys General Conference, which begins
Wednesday, is seen as an opportunity for chief law enforcement
officials to navigate a 2,000-mile border that is a maze of local,
state and federal jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the maze snares criminals in an inescapable web. Other
times, officials say, it has proven a frustrating and nearly
impenetrable wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we do not have any choice but to interact and
hopefully cooperate with the Mexican government on matters of
mutual interest,'' Texas Attorney General John Cornyn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us have never met before, and as simple as it sounds,
this is a first step,'' said Cornyn, who is in his first term.
</P>
<P>
   They face a formidable task, as the U.S.-Mexico border is home
to almost 6 million people and is said to be the gateway for as
much as 80 percent of the cocaine and marijuana in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn's chief of financial crimes, Don Clemmer, testified
before Congress in April that approximately $30 billion a year in
Mexican drug cartel profits are laundered in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy de la Garza, a professor at the University of Texas at
Austin, said recent events show there is a lot of room for mistrust
among officials from both sides of the border.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect Mexicans are chafing at the arrogance with which the
United States has implemented his drug policy,'' de la Garza said.
</P>
<P>
   As for attorneys general from the United States, de la Garza,
said they are likely suspicious of their Mexican counterparts and
question how they were appointed to office as well as their
loyalties.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said the challenge will be tackling so many issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The risk in dealing with an issue as big as law enforcement,
health and environmental issues along the border is that everyone
comes to the table with their own perspective,'' said Cornyn, a
former state district judge in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Presentations also will include child support and child
abductions, the free trade agreement and how authorities from
American states can pursue justice in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most high-profile fights for international justice is
the case of Jose Luis Del Toro, who is accused of shooting and
stabbing to death Sheila Bellush, a mother of six, including
quadruplets born in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Bellush was killed Nov. 7, 1997, in her home in Sarasota, Fla.
Two men are imprisoned in Florida for their parts in the killing.
Del Toro was caught by police in Monterrey, Mexico, later that
year, but his lawyer has launched a protracted legal battle,
including an appeal to Mexico's highest court, to block his
extradition to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, local officials have been able to get around
complicated extraditions by requesting help from Mexican state
officials to prosecute citizens for crimes committed in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case border crimes is the 1993 murder of Joey
Fischer, a Brownsville, Texas, high school student who was gunned
down outside his home.
</P>
<P>
   The killers, both Mexicans, fled across the Rio Grande, but they
were later arrested, tried and sentenced to 15 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Fugitives also flee to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The director of a Reynosa, Mexico, university was arrested by
the FBI in McAllen, Texas, earlier this year and sent back to
Mexico where he is accused of having a rival academic killed for
having an affair with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the U.S. State Department, the Justice Department nor
the Mexican Embassy could readily provide figures on how many
extraditions are requested each year.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Antonio Zabalgoitia, a spokesman for the Mexican Embassy,
said law enforcement agencies are working together to the point
that, he contends, escaping the law by crossing the border is
rarely an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is just in the movies,'' he said from Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are constantly returning criminals,'' Zabalgoitia said.
``There is a continuous flow of cooperation.''
</P>
<P>
   California officials also are praising their partnership with
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is probably the most evolved law enforcement cooperation in
existence,'' said Nathan Barankin, spokesman for the California
attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   But Guillermo Margandant, a professor of law at the National
Autonomous University in Mexico City, contends Mexico is hesitant
to hand over its own citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a question of patriotism and public opinion being much
too strong in Mexico,'' Margandant said. ``The extradition business
between Mexico and the United States is not the most flourishing
business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
