<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5344 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GANG-VIOLENCE-HNS &LR;      05-28 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GANG-VIOLENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY QUESTIONS STEREOTYPES OF GANG MEMBERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KARISA KING  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A study of Mexican-American gangs has found that
their teen-aged members are not psychologically predisposed to
violence, providing hope that many could be turned from a criminal
path, researchers said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The still-unpublished study by researchers at the University of
Texas at San Antonio took aim at popular myths about Hispanic
gangs, said Avelardo Valdez, director of the Hispanic Research
Center at the University of Texas at San Antonio and investigator
for the study.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people think the most vicious kids are in gangs, but
it's not true,'' Valdez said.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers identified 26 active gangs in San Antonio, and
randomly selected 50 male members for extensive psychological
tests.
</P>
<P>
   The study examined whether gang members felt shame, guilt and
remorse _ qualities typically lacking in those with antisocial
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also looked at a comparison group of 25 non-gang
members with similar criminal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that only 4 percent of gang members could be
classified as antisocial, making them more open to violence. None
of the non-gang members could be so classified.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conclusion is that the majority of aggressive, antisocial
behavior that's perpetuated by Mexican-American gangs is not
because of personality disorders,'' Valdez said.
</P>
<P>
   To Valdez, that means gang members would benefit from
intervention and other community services.
</P>
<P>
   ``Psychopaths don't respond well to treatment. It (the study)
says these kids have hope. They shouldn't be locked up and thrown
in jail forever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The study also challenges the idea that gang members are more
likely to come from dysfunctional families and experience more
childhood abuse than youths who are not in gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Gang members did not report significantly higher levels of
physical, sexual and emotional abuse, compared to non-gang members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability of these families to provide for the basic
emotional needs of their children is an indication of the
resiliency and strength of the Mexican-American culture,'' Valdez
said.
</P>
<P>
   But gang members did show a higher level of physical neglect,
complaining that at home they had gone without food, clean clothes
or access to medical care.
</P>
<P>
   That suggests gang members may have joined the groups more out
of a need for material benefit _ not a desire to belong, Valdez
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
