A5347 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRILLING-PROTEST-NYT &LR;      05-28 0355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRILLING-PROTEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOLAR RESIGNS OVER TRILLING'S `DIAGNOSIS' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (rk) 
 By SARAH BOXER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last month, The American Scholar published ``My Father and the
Weak-Eyed Devils,'' an essay in which James Trilling, an
independent art historian, asserted that both he and his father,
Lionel Trilling, suffered from attention deficit disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the journal is feeling the fallout. Paul R. McHugh, the
psychiatrist in chief at the Johns Hopkins Hospital, quit the
editorial board of The American Scholar earlier this month over the
story.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a clumsily written, meanly written article about a
defenseless father,'' McHugh said in an interview, adding that the
diagnosis the son offers ``is not given anything like the
foundation a psychiatrist would give.''
</P>
<P>
   McHugh complained that the essay is merely ``sophisticated name
calling,'' and that James Trilling ``uses psychiatric principles to
settle personal scores.''
</P>
<P>
   McHugh, the only psychiatrist on the 15-member board of the
journal, was not consulted before the piece was published.
</P>
<P>
   The last board member to resign in protest, said Anne Fadiman,
the editor of The American Scholar, was Diana Trilling, who left in
1978 over an article that was also about Lionel, her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fadiman, who said she regrets McHugh's departure, explained
that she never sends articles to the board members unless she is
unsure about whether to accept them. ``This is not a peer-reviewed
journal, not a fact-checked journal,'' she said. ``But I had no
doubts about whether to accept this one. It was beautifully
written, carefully constructed. I would have published it even if
it had been by an unknown writer about an unknown writer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a piece about psychiatry,'' she continued. ``It's a
memoir.''
</P>
<P>
   McHugh, who said he was sad to resign, suggested that we have
become so accustomed to offering psychiatric judgments that a piece
like this seems not to require a scholar's eye. But what then is
the purpose of the editorial board? he asked. ``Were we there to
just meet and schmooze?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
