<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDREN-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SIGNS CHILDREN'S INSURANCE BILL INTO LAW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ At a ceremony Friday in which words of wisdom
from Dr. Seuss brought smiles, Gov. George W. Bush signed a bill
into law that promises healthier lives for hundreds of thousands of
low-income children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can think of no better use of tobacco settlement money than
for safeguarding and improving children's health,'' he said. ``I'm
pleased to sign this bill, and I congratulate you all for doing
what's right for Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also kicked off the Memorial Day weekend by signing a bill
to lower the legal blood alcohol limit for drinking and driving
from .10 to .08.
</P>
<P>
   The children's health issue took the spotlight, however, as
health officials &UR;  &LR; and lawmakers gathered around Bush for a round of
congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children's health insurance has been a priority this
session,'' said Bush, who some accused earlier in the session of
not taking a strong enough leadership role on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The new law creates the state's Children's Health Insurance
Program to provide health coverage for kids under age 19 whose
parents don't earn enough to afford private insurance but aren't
poor enough for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Although Bush had begun negotiations on the issue asking that
only children at 150 percent of the federal poverty level be
considered eligible, a recent decision from the U.S. Congress
allowing states to keep tobacco settlement money suddenly made more
aid possible.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says now he is pleased with the more generous program.
``It's hard to commit the state ... when we weren't certain that
the supply of money would be available.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, lawmakers decided to offer coverage for children in
families earning up to twice the poverty level or $33,600 for a
family of four.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Patricia Gray, D-Galveston, who sponsored the legislation
along with Democratic Sen. Mike Moncrief of Fort Worth, gave Bush a
photo of children with a Texas flag.
</P>
<P>
   On the back, she said, is her favorite quote from Dr. Seuss:
``That unless someone like you cares a whole awful lot, nothing's
going to get better, it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also provided state funds to insure 7,000 children of
immigrants legally residing in Texas and said they made sure
children with special health needs are covered. Both preventive and
corrective dental insurance is part of the package as well.
</P>
<P>
   Federal funds of $423 million a year will pay for the program,
combined with $180 million budgeted by the state from its tobacco
settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In signing the drinking and driving bill, Bush warned Texans to
play it safe behind the wheel on the Memorial Day weekend, although
the new law does not become effective until Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``This legislation will make our streets safer, and it sends a
clear signal to Texans that drinking and driving don't mix,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers partly said they want to ensure the safety of Texans,
who have led the nation with the highest number of alcohol-related
traffic deaths. Yet, the new law also makes it possible for the
state to collect an estimated $12 million in new federal highway
money.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 114 was sponsored by Sen. Mario Gallegos, a Democrat
from Houston who served as a paramedic in the Houston Fire
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``During my tour of duty at Ben Taub Hospital Emergency Room, I
saw the faces of families who lost loved ones to drunk-driving
accidents,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
