<SLUG> BC-PARTNERS-RULING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE BACKS SAN FRANCISCO EQUAL BENEFITS LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS and LARRY D. HATFIELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A federal judge, ruling in two cases involving
San Francisco's equal benefits ordinance, has backed the landmark
law that requires companies doing business with the city to provide
the same non-health benefits to employees with unmarried partners
as they provide to married couples.
</P>
<P>
   The rulings were cheered by city officials and gay and lesbian
politicians and activists, but the lawyers for a company in one of
the cases pledged an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is in fact a great, great day,'' Mayor Willie Brown said
of Thursday's ruling. ``Efforts to remove discrimination ... are
alive and well and have been upheld in San Francisco and it says to
the rest of the world, `Get with it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Claudia Wilkens ruled in Oakland Thursday that United
Airlines must provide the same non-health benefits to domestic
partners as it does for employee spouses. She also ruled that an
Ohio contractor choosing to ignore the city's domestic partner
ordinance was not entitled to a city contract.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides, however, claimed victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very good spin doctors, but (city officials) are
trying to cover a loss,'' said Sam Singer, spokesman for the Air
Transport Association, which sued San Francisco on behalf of United
and its other airline members. ``We're pleased with the judge's
ruling. We won 99 percent of what we wanted to win. And on the 1
percent we didn't get, we're going to see what steps we'll take
next.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Transport Association, the trade group for the nation's
big airlines, contended that only the federal government has the
authority to force requirements on the air industry.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkens upheld in April 1998 the basic tenets of the law, but
said airlines enjoy a special status. She ruled that the airlines
did not have to provide health and pension benefits because those
matters can be dictated only by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   But the question of whether they had to provide other benefits
was left open until Thursday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Carol B. Hallett, ATA president and chief executive, said:
``This ruling allows San Francisco's local law to interfere with a
nationwide collective bargaining process. ... We will examine all
of our options, including the possibility of an appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Center for Law and Justice, founded by the Rev. Pat
Robertson and the lawyers for the Ohio company, S.D. Myers, said it
would appeal the decision. S.D. Myers maintains transformers at a
city power plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ruling changes corporate America by creating a culture
shift that legitimizes same-sex relationships,'' said Jay Sekulow,
a lawyer for the ACLJ. ``The ordinance redefines the institution of
marriage and conflicts with the moral values of most Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sheehy, a gay activist who helped shape San Francisco's
law, said activists would continue urging consumers to boycott
United until it complies with the law.
</P>
<P>
   For the airlines to continue to fight, Sheehy said, ``defies
reason, is irrational and it's homophobic to continue with the
lawsuit. That's not a pretty picture: United Airlines dancing with
Pat Robertson all the way to the Supreme Court.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Equal Benefits Ordinance went into effect June
1, 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
