<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5381 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV30-B     05-28 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV30-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AFTERMATH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 30, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The China story is being explored in all its dimensions _
military, industrial, cultural, historical _ except the one in
which it is best understood: as the aftermath of the GOP's
impeachment campaign.
</P>
<P>
   It almost seems in bad taste to bring it up.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Cox (R-Cal.), who led the Congressional
committee that produced the long-awaited report on Chinese
espionage that was published last week, is not the most vociferous
of the GOP leadership. But the Orange Country Republican is among
the most conservative.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't make him a villain. Indeed, until he became
embroiled in the ill-fated crusade that was the ``Contract with
America'' and the follow-on fiasco of the impeachment campaign, Cox
was one of the most imaginative legislators on the Hill.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran staffer in the Reagan White House, he was first
elected to Congress in 1988, and managed to eliminate the federal
helium stockpiling program and close down the Interstate Commerce
Commission _ with Rep. Barney Frank (D-Mass.) as co-sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   But the portrayal of the work of the House Select Comittee that
Cox led as ``bipartisan'' is seriously misleading. Every step taken
by parties on both sides of the investigation was played with an
eye toward next year's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Much is at stake, including Chinese membership in the World
Trade Organization and its further integration into the system of
global markets. Sen. Majority Leader Trent Lott (R-Miss.) last week
forecast ``real problems'' with any trade agreement.
</P>
<P>
   True, four Democrats on the committee signed the report on U.S.
National Security and Military/Commercial Concerns with the
People's Republic of China. President Clinton praised the
committee's ``careful'' work. Nuclear secrets are serious business,
after all.
</P>
<P>
   And the sections of the report that deal with the activities of
the Chinese ``princelings'' _ children of the founders of the
communist party _ make fascinating reading. Wang Jun, chairman of
the China International Trade and Investment Corp., is son of the
late Chinese president Wang Zhen. Liu Shaoying, vice president of
China Aerospace International Holdings, which provides satellite
launch services, is the daughter of China's most powerful military
leader. Both were contributors to the Democratic Part in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Princelings such as Wang and Liu present a unique technology
transfer threat because their multiple connections enable them to
move freely around the world and among the different bureaucracies
(in China,)'' the report states.
</P>
<P>
   The more the world understands about the relative handful of
powerful families that are China's characteristic form of
industrial organization, the better. Likewise, their determination
to acquire prevailing technologies by fair means and foul.
</P>
<P>
   But the US House of Representatives, which is in the midst of
its most bitter session in 130 years, is hardly the place to
examine the deepest and most perplexing issues of national
security.
</P>
<P>
   The National Academy of Sciences wasn't involved in attempts to
assess the damage. Nor were attempts made to enlist the scientific
community in an evenhanded appraisal of China's ``make-or-buy''
decisions in building its nucleaer arsenal. Instead, the presidents
of the national Academies of Science and Engineering and the
Institutes of Medicine issued a statement of alarm at what they see
as an unwarranted crackdown on scientific openness.
</P>
<P>
   The current proceedings began about a year ago ``as a gleam in
Newt Gingrich's eye,'' as Jeff Gerth and Tim Weiner wrote in The
New York Times last week, though in fact it was Gerth's stories
about technique-sharing by US companies using Chinese rockets to
launch their communications satellites that attracted the
then-House Speaker's attention. To lead the investigation, Gingrich
chose Cox.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation shifted into high gear in October as the
Select Committee learned more about a history of lax
counterintelligence in four presidential administrations.
</P>
<P>
   After the impeachment trial concluded, the China story continued
to be prosecuted mainly in the press. If anyone has any doubts
about partisanship, let them look to what happened to John Deutch
in April.
</P>
<P>
   After Energy Secretary Bill Richardson tapped the former
director of Central intelligence to review the national
laboratories' foreign visitors program, Deutch was forced to
quietly withdraw by news leaks that he had mishandled classified
data while serving as director _ by taking work home.
</P>
<P>
   An investigation is expected to clear the MIT professor of
anything more than mild carelessness _ but not to restore him to a
position of public authority in the matter before the Congress. The
charges against a distinguished scientist-bureaucrat are presumably
another episode from a revolution on the eve of entering its
Thermidorean phase.
</P>
<P>
   When the story of the 1990s is written, the events of the year
1989 will be its starting point. That was the year that the Berlin
Wall came down, that communism capitulated to capitalism, that
history was said (by the proponents of its inner logic) to have
``ended.'' How many ways were momentarily lost in that sudden and
unexpected peace!
</P>
<P>
   Especially the Republicans. The party has spent most of the
1990s engaged in bitter internecine warfare, achieving solidarity
only briefly, and probably disasterously, in a common hatred of
Bill Clinton. As the conservative political commentator Andrew
Sullivan has written, ``They wouldn't take yes for an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the GOP is searching for a new foe. Strategists William
Kristol and Robert Kagan are urging Republican candidates to adopt
a strategy of bold confrontation with China, similar to Ronald
Reagan's 1981 ``Star Wars'' challenge to the Soviet Union, in the
expectation that Chinese communism too would quickly collapse.
</P>
<P>
   The next election is only 16 months away. Soon history will be
starting up again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
