<HEADER>
A5391 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AGL-COX     05-28 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AGL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AGL appointment raises merger questions
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The recent appointment of Robert S. Jepson, who has
bought and sold a number of companies, to the board of AGL
Resources Inc. raises the question: Is a merger or acquisition in
the future for the parent of Atlanta Gas Light Co.?
</P>
<P>
   Walter M. Higgins, AGL's board chairman, president and chief
executive, said Jepson was selected because of his general business
expertise and experience with mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took a company, built it into something more valuable ...
and then sold it as the logical extension of its future,'' Higgins
said in an interview this week. He was referring to Jepson's tenure
as CEO of Savannah-based Kuhlman Corp., which was sold to
Borg-Warner Automotive earlier this year for $750 million in cash,
stock and debt.
</P>
<P>
   Mergers and acquisitions are ``certainly one of our issues,''
Higgins said. But he denied that Jepson's appointment signals that
a particular deal is at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no relationship between him coming on the board with
any activities the company may be engaged in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Donato J. Eassey, a Houston-based utilities analyst with Merrill
Lynch Global Securities, called Jepson's appointment, announced by
AGL last week, ``a very appropriate step in today's environment''
in the fast-consolidating utility industry that has seen 20 major
mergers since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to get bigger or be part of somebody else,'' Eassey
said. ``If they (AGL) can't get bigger themselves, they'll be part
of another entity.''
</P>
<P>
   Higgins has been quite forthright, from the moment he arrived at
AGL from a Nevada utility last year, about the possibility the
company might acquire or merge with other companies or be acquired
itself. If such steps would ``create value for our shareholders,
then we're going to do it,'' he said in February 1998, following
his first AGL shareholder meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Higgins said he first met Jepson when they served together on
the board of Washington Water Co. several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jepson is currently chairman and CEO of Savannah-based Jepson
Associates, a private investment company, and CEO of Jepson
Vineyards, a Ukiah, Calif., wine maker.
</P>
<P>
   Jepson took over Kuhlman Corp. in 1993, moved the industrial
equipment manufacturer from Lexington, Ky., to Savannah, acquired
six other companies and grew profits 37 percent a year before
selling the company in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Jepson was founder and CEO of Chicago-based Jepson Corp. from
1983 until the manufacturer of airliner seats, playground equipment
and air conditioners was sold in 1989 to Great American Management
&AMP; Investment Inc. for $220 million.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
