<HEADER>
A5392 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-SECRETS-$ADV30-     05-28 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SECRETS-$ADV30-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME EXPERTS SAY DAMAGE FROM CHINA'S NUCLEAR SPYING IS OVERBLOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, May 30)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite dire consequences predicted by a House
report on China's theft of coveted U.S. nuclear secrets, several
arms control experts say Beijing is years away from fielding new
weapons and still will be no match for the massive American
arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in the surreal logic of nuclear politics the United
States may actually be more secure if China develops new atomic
weapons capable of surviving an attack because that would reduce
the chance that either side would launch a preemptive first strike,
these experts argue.
</P>
<P>
   But such views were drowned out last week by cries of alarm
triggered by the 700-page House report of a bipartisan panel of
lawmakers that detailed extensive Chinese espionage over two
decades and lax security at the nation's nuclear weapons
laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   The report said China stole U.S. nuclear warhead designs,
advanced radar know-how and missile-guidance-system-blueprints. It
concluded that an ``insatiable appetite'' for U.S. technology has
allowed China to leap from a 1950s nuclear weapons program to
state-of-the-art designs ``on a par with our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics charged that the Clinton administration, which first
learned of the security lapses in 1995, had appeased China and
failed to counter the Chinese spying quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   Even Democrats joined in the outcry. Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash.,
who cochaired the congressional panel, called the theft ``one of
the worst counterintelligence failures in the nation's history.''
</P>
<P>
   However, another Democrat who served on the panel, Rep. John
Spratt of South Carolina, said that the House report was based on
``worst case'' assumptions. Spratt said that the Chinese ``are not
on a par with the United States,'' but he added that they do have a
``capable'' nuclear force.
</P>
<P>
   While the report said China may have a mobile nuclear missile by
2002, some arms control experts insist that is highly unlikely
given the weapon's history of problems. ``I don't think it's likely
(to be tested) for several years,'' said Joseph Cirincione, a
nuclear weapons analyst with the Carnegie Endowment for
International Peace, a think tank here.
</P>
<P>
   Cirincione noted that the Chinese have had nuclear weapons
capable of striking U.S. cities for more than 30 years. But unlike
the Soviet Union, which placed a top priority on developing
thousands of nuclear warheads, China has not viewed the weapons as
the cornerstone of its security, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``China does not have an aggressive nuclear modernization
program under way, and nuclear weapons have never been a priority''
for its leaders, Cirincione added. ``There is basically nothing for
us to worry about. Even if all the spying allegations are true, the
impact is only marginal.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Norris, a nuclear weapons expert with the Natural
Resources Defense Council, an arms control and environmental
organization, said that ``it usually takes a long, long time for
the Chinese to introduce new nuclear weapons, and when they do,
it's often a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Norris pointed to China's failed attempt over the years to
develop a submarine like the U.S. Trident submarine capable of
firing intercontinental ballistic missiles (ICBMs) while submerged.
</P>
<P>
   Lisbeth Gronlund, a physicist and arms control expert with the
Union of Concerned Scientists, an anti-nuclear organization, said
Americans need to put the theft of atomic secrets in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``China has fewer than two dozen warheads that can reach the
United States, while the U.S. has more than 6,000 that can hit
China,'' she pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   Some arms control experts also stressed that the theft hasn't
tipped the nuclear scales in China's favor.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Aftergood, a nuclear weapons analyst with the Federation
of American Scientists, a nonpartisan military research
organization, said it was ``manifestly untrue'' that China could
now develop weapons as capable as those in the U.S. arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. intelligence agencies have also said China hasn't suddenly
leapfrogged and developed a modern nuclear force. In a damage
assessment of the Chinese spying prepared for Congress in April,
the agencies said China still has ``significant deficiencies'' in
its nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
   ``To date, the aggressive Chinese collection effort has not
resulted in any apparent modernization of their deployed strategic
force or any new nuclear weapons deployment,'' the assessment
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   All of China's ICBMs are in fixed silos, which makes them
vulnerable to attack, while the United States has many missiles in
Trident submarines prowling the ocean floors and virtually
impossible for an enemy to locate.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Intelligence officials say one reason China has sought U.S.
nuclear secrets is that it wants to develop a mobile nuclear
missile to counter those on the Trident subs. Currently, the United
States or Russia could destroy Beijing's entire ICBM force in one
strike.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the spying, these officials say, is that
China sees America's so-called star-wars effort to develop a
nuclear shield against ICBMs as a move that would nullify Beijing's
nuclear deterrent and make it more vulnerable to a first strike
from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The nuclear strategy that guided the United States and the
former Soviet Union during the Cold War held that the superpowers
weren't likely to start a nuclear war knowing that their enemy's
mobile or submarine-launched missiles would survive and fire back
in retaliation, thus destroying the aggressor.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, some see China's possible development of such a missile
as a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If China has greater confidence in its arsenal, that would
contribute to greater stability with the United States,'' said
Aftergood.
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at the email
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
