<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5393 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-FIGHT-BOS &LR;      05-28 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-FIGHT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PINEDA HOPING TO PROVE TRINIDAD HAS A GLASS CHIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerty Rico _ Felix Trinidad may have been born and
raised in Puerto Rico, but his chin was made in China. Or at least
it is made of china, which is the one thought that will buoy Hugo
Pineda Saturday night as he steps into the ring at Roberto Clemente
Coliseum to face the undefeated International Boxing Federation
welterweight champion.
</P>
<P>
   There are many who believe Trinidad is the best welterweight in
the world, an opinion supported not only by his 34-0 record but by
his 29 knockouts and 13 successful title defenses since he won the
crown from Maurice Blocker six years ago. There are some who will
go so far as to argue he is the finest pound-for-pound fighter in
the world, a position Trinidad himself favors. Yet although both
positions may be true, Pineda realizes every man has an Achilles'
heel, and Trinidad's is at the end of his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, Trinidad has been knocked down several times,'' said
Celso Chavez, Pineda's trainer, who notes Trinidad has been down
six times in his career. ``He's not the best at taking a punch, and
Hugo is a hard-hitting boxer. We have a strategy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   That strategy is self-evident. It is to hit Trinidad on the chin
the way Alberto Cortes did and Anthony Stephens did and Yory Boy
Campas did and Oba Carr did and Kevin Lueshing did. Hit him hard
enough to knock him flat.
</P>
<P>
   The difference, Pineda hopes, is that because he has packed the
power to knock out 27 of the 36 men he's beaten and to have dropped
former IBF junior welterweight champion Kostya Tszyu in the first
round of what turned out to be an 11th-round loss three years ago,
he can take it a half-step farther and finish the job five of
Trinidad's other opponents began. He hopes he can not only knock
him down but keep him down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can knock Trinidad out,'' said Pineda (36-1-1).
``That's my goal, and I am confident of it.''
</P>
<P>
   If he truly is, Pineda is in the minority. It is not surprising
that few people here give Pineda a chance to beat their native son
and that Trinidad scoffs at the notion, but gamblers in Las Vegas
feel the same way. Pineda is a 10-1 underdog to even make it to the
final bell, let alone dethrone Trinidad, and HBO, which is
televising the fight, is gambling they are right. If not, its
planned Sept. 18 welterweight showdown between Trinidad and Oscar
De La Hoya will go down the tubes at considerable cost.
</P>
<P>
   HBO has paid Trinidad nearly $6 million to fight first Pernell
Whitaker and now Pineda on its network for the sole purpose of
building up the IBF champion and creating an atmosphere that would
lead inevitably to a fight with De La Hoya, with whom HBO holds an
exclusive television contract.
</P>
<P>
   That fight has not been finalized because Trinidad's father
continues to argue with promoter Don King over the numbers,
believing an $8 million guarantee is not enough of a payday to risk
his son and meal ticket (not necessarily in that order of
importance) against De La Hoya. But the belief is that the showdown
will come off because the numbers have grown too big to be ignored
for long.
</P>
<P>
   If that is true, only one man can stop it, and if that man is
correct in his belief in himself and the weakness of his opponent's
jaw, there will be many people rubbing their chins Sunday morning,
not just Felix Trinidad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that's the fight he wants and everybody wants, but
first it's me,'' Pineda said. ``Trinidad can't talk about a fight
against De La Hoya when there's another fight first. Boxing is
unpredictable, as this situation is an example.''
</P>
<P>
   It's only an example, of course, if Pineda can land those shots
he's hoping for and succeed in keeping Trinidad on his back, a
place he has thus far refused to stay. While he has been down an
inordinate amount of times, Trinidad has always gotten up. Guys
like Pineda don't like to talk about what happens after that.
</P>
<P>
   Cortes dropped Trinidad twice in the second round of their 1992
fight in Paris. The next round, Trinidad hit him so many times in
the face that they had to stop the fight before somebody got
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens dropped him in the second round a year later. For his
trouble, he got knocked cold in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   After an eight-month layoff, Trinidad stepped in with undefeated
power puncher Campas, who was 56-0 with 50 knockouts. Again in the
second round, Campas appeared to be on the way to his 51st when he
stunned Trinidad and dropped him. Two rounds later, Trinidad broke
Campas's face, shattering his nose and cheek and forcing referee
Richard Steele to jump in and literally save face _ Campas's _ by
stopping the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Carr, who also dropped Trinidad in Round 2 (do we see
a trend here?), only to be stopped in the eighth round after twice
being knocked down.
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, there was the unheralded Lueshing, the only junior
middleweight Trinidad has fought. Second round, first knockdown.
Third round, Lueshing out cold.
</P>
<P>
   The message here is clear: If Hugo Pineda does crack Felix
Trinidad's chin, he had best finish the job immediately or rue the
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this sport, everybody goes down to the canvas,'' said
Trinidad. ``If you fight with power, you can go down. But Pineda
will visit the canvas, not myself. To hurt my opponent is my job.
It is what I am there for.''
</P>
<P>
   That's also what Hugo Pineda is there for. But he must do more
than hurt the china chin of Felix Trinidad. He must destroy it
before the man who carries that chin destroys him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The card, promoted by Don King, will include 11 fights, three
for world titles. World Boxing Association featherweight champion
Antonio Cermeno (35-2, 23 KOs) will risk his crown against former
champion Freddie Norwood (33-0-1), and WBA flyweight champion Leo
Gamez (31-6-1, 23 KOs) will seek the interim WBA super flyweight
title against former World Boxing Organization champion Josue
Dickie Camacho (16-6, 6 KOs).
</P>
</TEXT>
