<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERENA WILLIAMS SCOOPED AT FRENCH OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The Lady in Red was a troublemaker.
</P>
<P>
   She'd been around this block a few times and had the wiles,
will, and weapons to confuse and shake the young crusading
journalist named Serena Williams who was on her trail.
</P>
<P>
   This was bad news _ and no news fit to print _ for Serena, the
associate editor of the Tennis Monthly Recap. It was supposed to be
a day for banner headlines proclaiming that the pillars of the Palm
Beach Gardens, Fla., publishing family, Serena and sister Venus,
had together crashed the sweet 16 of the French Open. Alas, tear up
the front page.
</P>
<P>
   Venus, also associate editor, co-publisher, and fellow star
reporter of their home-produced newsletter, quickly completed her
assignment with a 6-3, 6-1 win over an Aussie, No. 97 Alicia Molik.
That was hardly stop-the-presses stuff since, aside from her
journalistic duties, Venus is the global No. 5 tennis player.
</P>
<P>
   The assignment for No. 10 Serena, getting the goods on the Lady
in Red _ Mary Joe Fernandez _ looked a little tougher. And it was,
6-3, 1-6, 6-0, as the newshound bit the bagel.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a series of wrist injuries, the rigors of age (she will
be 28 soon), and a ranking that has deteriorated to No. 37,
Fernandez still has the evasiveness and the spin-doctoring skills
to baffle a cub reporter. She had more answers than 17-year-old
Serena had questions. Most of them made the kid look uncomfortable,
as though she needed a dictionary or a thesaurus to figure them
out.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Mary Joe is sashaying about Stade Roland Garros for
the 13th year, a six-time quarterfinalist or better who barely lost
the 1993 title to Steffi Graf. But never had she been so
assertively and stridently turned out as Friday in a fire
engine-red frock that was appropriate for the blaze she caused.
</P>
<P>
   ``New. Special for this tournament,'' she beamed. ``Red hot,
huh?''
</P>
<P>
   It evoked lyrics of that old tune, ``The Lady in Red'' _ `` . .
. never saw you shine so bright . . . it took my breath away . . .
''
</P>
<P>
   The brick dust court . . . the dress . . . her own discomfort as
Fernandez outsmarted her by mixing attack and defense wisely and
surprisingly. There was plenty to make Serena see red, whack her
chair with her racket, and later declare, laughing at herself, ``I
should have been taken off the court and immediately asked to leave
the facilities, never to return again.''
</P>
<P>
   In this city of historically haute couture, it's very difficult
to outdress the Williams sisters: Venus in clinging semi-halter
creation and Serena in muscles-flaunting mini-gown. Both a lemon
hue, which doesn't necessarily mark them as exponents of yellow
journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Mary Joe in freshly tailored scarlet was in the
sartorial running while keeping Serena running about wildly and
vainly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was out of control,'' said Serena. ``Mary Joe attacked and
went ahead to take the match. It's difficult because in actuality,
I had planned on doing very well here, even taking the title. I
never even dreamed in my wildest nightmares that I would have went
out in the third round.''
</P>
<P>
   Venus earlier described the Tennis Monthly Recap as something
she and Serena do for fun on their laptops, circulation
unannounced. ``On the front page of our latest issue,'' she said,
giggling, ``are two famous players. Uh, me and Serena. Also,'' she
added, cracking up, ``on the back page, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Their favorite subject is Pete Sampras, whom they've interviewed
and written about.
</P>
<P>
   How come Venus, with so little experience on clay, appears to
handle the footing better than Pete?
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never criticize someone who has won so many more
titles than me,'' she said, diplomat as well as correspondent.
</P>
<P>
   After her defeat, Serena was asked cautiously by this reporter,
``Will you write about this match for the Recap?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm no longer worthy of being in the news.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you be fired? You, the co-publisher, associate editor . .
. ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not be featured in the Recap,'' she said, grinning
broadly. ``That's a big publication. You have to be a player to get
featured. I wasn't a player today. The editors don't want Serena to
be featured. I have to go home and practice to make sure there's a
great writeup after Wimbledon in the Tennis Monthly Recap.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So that there won't be an editorial shakeup?''
</P>
<P>
   Her reply was a cryptic smile.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady in Red had thwarted the power of the press (and no
journalist has more power than Serena). But Serena had been
scooped. It hurts, kid, but it's happened to all of us in this
game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
