<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5399 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUCHANAN-CAMPAIGN-2TA     05-28 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHANAN-CAMPAIGN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUCHANAN IS CAMPAIGNING CONFIDENTLY DESPITE THE ODDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: La.)  (lb) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONROE, La. _ Early in the quest, Pat Buchanan seems to be
sounding his patented campaign reveille as much for himself as for
his political ``pitchfork brigades.''
</P>
<P>
   ``January and February _ that's when the armies will meet!''
exulted the once and apparently constant presidential aspirant,
sitting in a catfish restaurant here and waxing nostalgic for the
merry field marshal's persona that was his signature in the 1996
Republican primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Buchanan scored such a stunning defeat over Bob Dole
in New Hampshire that he decided to return for the 2000 contest.
And in Louisiana, site of a caucus victory for Buchanan in 1996, he
worked in obvious contentment among the discontented in the
economically burnt-out cotton fields and in the nearby Pentecostal
churches, preparing for the wintry battles to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing like it,'' the 60-year-old candidate enthused over a
mug of nonalcoholic beer, the strict Spartan campaigner in these
early organizing months of dogged trail work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last time, with the momentum we had, thousands and thousands
kept showing at our rallies even after we were finished, he said.
``I felt like El Cid up there on that horse after I was dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's rich laugh pealed through the restaurant as he took
stock of how different the 2000 challenge will be. The field of
social and economic conservatives that he exploited so promisingly
four years ago is more crowded with candidates this time. He must
first prevail over them if he is to narrow things to another
showdown opportunity against ``the party establishment'' candidate,
as he puts it _ most likely Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, by
Buchanan's reckoning.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask who I'm most concerned about right now, and my answer
is Steve Forbes' checkbook,'' Buchanan continued. ``Not the
candidate _ the checkbook,'' he said of the millionaire rival he
beat four times in 1996, only to see him come on with zombielike
persistence as an eventual spoiler.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forbes had the money to stay in the game and wait down the
road,'' Buchanan said. ``When he finally won in Arizona, I lost the
momentum to beat Dole that I had won in New Hampshire.''
</P>
<P>
   Across his political decades as a superbly pugnacious polemicist
and late-blooming candidate, Buchanan has proved he is nothing if
not personally indomitable. He seems once more unfazed by the
assessment of political handicappers that, in his third time
around, the gleam has worn off his underdog candidacy as the irate
populist pleading for forgotten workers and impassioned moral
causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wonder whether Buchanan's heart is in it,'' said the
political analyst Charles Cook Jr. ``He got traction in '92
challenging President Bush, and he had a semblance of that in '96
with Dole as a pretty good foil. But I don't really see it this
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In his recent campaign forays across the country, Buchanan has
been tuning up small but dedicated crowds with his old energy,
sharpening an early stump speech firmly rooted in opposition to
abortion, free trade, the bombing of Yugoslavia and a national
``culture of death.'' He sees Hollywood, not easy access to
weapons, as the dominant factor in the recent surge of school
shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was about evil in the human heart,'' Buchanan boomed here
at a Christian Life Pentecostal church after joining in the choir's
rafter-thumping round of singing and hand-clapping for Jesus.
``We're going to make America a pro-life country again!'' the
candidate shouted.
</P>
<P>
   He moved on the church stage hesitantly, a rusty political
evangelist searching for the old fire, far from the CNN
``Crossfire'' program that is his Beltway sparring perch between
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   One big difference this time is that behind the scrim of his
busy schedule, much of Buchanan's battle-tested '96 cadre had
already been hired away by rivals before he took to the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``After '96, Pat went back to his old career on television and
didn't keep an infrastructure in place to capitalize on what he
accomplished,'' said one disappointed Buchanan veteran who has
moved on to another candidate. ``He lost a lot of the grass-roots
field operation that makes things happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes, whose checkbook so haunts the conservative commentator,
hired the entire Buchanan '96 staff in New Hampshire as well as
influential coordinators in Iowa and Louisiana, plus Greg Mueller,
a political operative from the first two Buchanan campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, insisting that he has found gifted ``rookies'' to
galvanize his new effort, is convinced that his early opposition to
the NATO attacks on Yugoslavia will make him the standout among the
second tier of conservative Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to dramatically underline this anti-war stance, in
contrast to Bush and other candidates, next week before the
National Press Club in a speech that his campaign director, Jay
Townsend, promises will be a crucial initiative in the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now in a foreign war that's none of our business,''
Buchanan has been telling audiences, drawing applause from New
Hampshire to Virginia and from Iowa to Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, he conceded that his economic-nationalism theme
of 1996 is a tougher sell this year, ``when the Dow's at 11,000.''
But he contended that his anti-war stance will be his definitive
rallying cry this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the American people's reflection on the fact
that I was right about that issue will convince them to look at my
candidacy and give me that extra momentum that I need to win,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan so obviously relishes the role of political guerrilla
fighter that some critics rate him as more a campaign addict than a
realist in his continuing quest for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should have been more people this time around,'' said
Moon Griffon, a conservative talk-show host here in northern
Louisiana who checked out the Buchanan crowds and found them
dedicated but wanting, considering Buchanan's dramatic victory here
in the Republican caucus three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have more momentum, but I don't see it,'' Griffon
said, pointing to the more crowded social conservative primary
field that is threatening Buchanan this time.
</P>
<P>
   This includes the religious conservative Gary Bauer, Sen. Robert
C. Smith of New Hampshire, Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, former Vice
President Dan Quayle and Alan Keyes, a fiery anti-abortion orator
who attracted enough conservative votes in the 1996 Iowa caucuses
to deny Buchanan the margin of victory over Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan insists that he would not be running if he thought he
could not win or if there were a more promising candidate carrying
the same party challenges. He smiles in noting that he expects, if
not yearns, to once more be denounced as too ``extreme'' for his
party _ ``just as soon as I break through the pack again and
they're saying, `Good Lord, old Pat can win this thing!'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's pleasure in being back on the trail is only
compounded, he said, by getting away from his television show's
monotony in having to focus on ``the Monica thing.'' ``Oh, I was
sick of it,'' he sighed before listening, as if in grateful
expiation, to the plight of some bankrupt cotton farmers who blamed
global trading. In a matter of minutes, Buchanan seamlessly wove
their troubles into his next stump speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the greatest game in the world,'' he happily declared
in an aside as the campaign trail opened anew for him. ``This is
fun. You're out of Washington, and you're up there with those
folks.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his bluff resolve, Buchanan, a passionate reader of
political history, already seems proud of his campaign record in
prodding his party away from the center. ``Archimedes said give me
a lever and a place to stand and I will move the world,'' he
declared. ``The presidential race is the real place to stand and
move the center of gravity in American politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're calling the whole Republican Party neo-isolationist
now, not just me,'' he beamed. ``That's very heartening.''
</P>
<P>
   The need for Buchanan to break out early from the social
conservative pack is critical in the view of such Buchanan doubters
as William Kristol, editor of The Weekly Standard. ``I'm struck
that Pat must have 95 percent name identity in the nation, but
right now he's only at 4 or 5 percent in the political polls,''
Kristol said, citing the multiple competition on the right.
</P>
<P>
   But Buchanan's knack for polemics and strategic timing, honed
since his days in Richard Nixon's White House, has no equal in the
field, said Lyn Nofziger, a political strategist for President
Ronald Reagan who is a Buchanan adviser now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat's different from the others because he doesn't weasel or
beat around the bush,'' Nofziger said, counting on an
anti-establishment wave in the primaries. ``What we're seeing here
is that Pat is not appealing to a broad spectrum of voters yet, but
he's kind of steadily picking off people who used to make up part
of the Reagan coalition, blue collars and the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Much the way Buchanan views Bush, the former president's oldest
son, as the ``inevitable'' candidate of the party establishment, he
sees himself as no less inevitably emerging from the conservative
pack as the governor's showdown challenger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a perfect foil for my campaign,'' Buchanan said with a
glint of his old lock-and-load instinct for targeting competitors.
``A globalist like his father,'' he added, his grin widening.
``He's perfect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
