<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5402 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HACKERS29-COX     05-28 0535
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKERS29-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HACKER STRIKE SHOWS VULNERABILITY OF PUBLIC WEB SITES
 &HT;    Eds: Note language in graf 5.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The FBI and Senate Web sites remained closed Friday
evening after hackers launched a series of powerful cyberattacks
against the government computers.
</P>
<P>
   The hackers' strike underscored the exposure of popular Internet
sites to rogue electronic assaults, despite ever more sophisticated
protective ``firewalls.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI's site (http://www.fbi.gov) was disabled by an attack
late Wednesday night, a spokesman said. The hackers ran a widely
available program that ``flooded'' the host IBM server with
requests for access, and the computer shut itself down. The result,
officials said, was similar to what would happen if millions of
Internet users were to seek access to a Web site simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   An FBI spokesman, Paul Bresson, said the Web site is used mainly
to distribute FBI press releases and other official texts and does
not contain any classified or essential data. He would not predict
when the site would be back in service.
</P>
<P>
   Following that assault, a group calling itself MAST3RZ 0F
D0WNL0ADING(cq) vandalized the official U.S. Senate site
(http://www.senate.gov) at 7:53 p.m. EDT Thursday, replacing the
welcoming page with a message to the FBI _ ``SKREW U GUYZ!''
</P>
<P>
   James Ziglar, the U.S. Senate's sergeant at arms, thereupon
closed the Senate's Web site, as well as senators' and committee
Web pages linked to it.
</P>
<P>
   Spokeswoman Sherry Little said the Senate site would be closed
indefinitely while the FBI sought to track the culprits through the
Internet's vast electronic plumbing. Congressional e-mail services
remained unaffected.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI has yet to identify any suspects responsible for the
twin attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But officials said they viewed the attack as retaliation for a
series of search warrants carried out earlier this week in Seattle,
Houston and Northern California in a ongoing probe of a group that
dubs itself ``Global Hell.''
</P>
<P>
   The combined attacks highlight the potential exposure of
critical computer networks to cyber-attacks.
</P>
<P>
   On May 12, President Clinton's Web site
(http://www.whitehouse.gov) was shut down for 24 hours after it
sustained a barrage of virtual assaults in protest of NATO's
bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1998, Clinton issued a broad presidential directive
ordering the FBI to mount a defense of the nation's electronic
central nervous system, including the ones used by the banking
system, power grid, telephone lines, and other vital services.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials privately acknowledge these systems could
easily be crashed by well-organized hackers in what would be an
``electronic Pearl Harbor.''
</P>
<P>
   Only ``this Pearl Harbor's going to be different,'' John J.
Hamre, the deputy secretary of Defense, told the Senate Armed
Services Committee on March 9. ``It is not going to be against Navy
ships sitting in a Navy shipyard; it's going to be against
commercial infrastructure, and we don't control that.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
