<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5409 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VETERANS-CELEBRATE-CO     05-28 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETERANS-CELEBRATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vets gather to remember World War II
 &HT;    By Joe Earle
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Pete Burnette examined a photocopy of the familiar,
grainy photograph of the U.S.S. Pope, a World War II destroyer, and
pointed to a spot at the stern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I literally stepped off this ship right about there,'' the
78-year-old man said. ``Into the water.''
</P>
<P>
   A Japanese photographer snapped the photograph moments later.
The image freezes the moment when giant plumes of water exploded
into the sky as bombs or shells struck the ship, sinking it.
</P>
<P>
   After the Pope sank, Burnette and his shipmates spent three days
and two nights in the water. Burnette never could find room in a
life raft, he said, so he just hung on to whatever floated. A
Japanese ship fished the American sailors from the Java Sea and
took them to a prisoner of war camp on Celebes, a nearby island.
Most, including Burnette, stayed there until the war ended. A small
contingent was taken to Japan to work. Thirty-one died.
</P>
<P>
   This week, a half-dozen survivors of the prison camp, now men in
their late 70s, joined about 80 veterans from across the country at
an Atlanta hotel to remember and celebrate their shipmates and
service in the Pacific. Their annual gathering concludes after a
formal banquet tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the men taking part in the annual reunion served on
``four-stackers'' _ destroyers with four smokestacks _ such as the
Pope, the U.S.S. Paul Jones, the U.S.S. John D. Ford and the U.S.S
Parrott, on the destroyer tender Black Hawk or on the submarine
U.S.S Perch. They served in the Navy's Asiatic Fleet, which
patrolled China and the Pacific islands from 1910 until 1942.
</P>
<P>
   Archie Eslick, now 83, served on the U.S.S. Barker in the 1930s
and remembers joining the search for missing pilot Amelia Earhardt.
``We never did find her,'' he said with a bit of a grin.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese Navy destroyed the Asiatic fleet in February 1942
in a battle for the Java Sea. After the battle, the ships that
remained serviceable were dispatched to other duties. The federal
government, these veterans say, wanted people to forget the battle.
Coming so soon after Pearl Harbor, they say, the losses in the Java
Sea were deemed bad for morale back home.
</P>
<P>
   The sailors took upon themselves to remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``As shipmates, we've now become a large family,'' said Charles
Ankerberg, 77, of St. Petersburg, Fla., a signalman on the Paul
Jones who now chairs the board of the Asiatic fleet organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a common bond,'' Burnette said. ``The people who were
in the prison camp were blood brothers and they always will be.''
Burnette nodded toward a Pope shipmate and fellow ex-prisoner who
lives half-way across the country. ``I'd go to his house in a
minute if it would help him,'' Burnette said. ``Mainly because we
helped each other at camp.''
</P>
<P>
   Prison life took a toll. Burnette lost use of an eye when a
guard struck him with a stick. When he finally reached the U.S.,
Burnette said he was a walking skeleton who weighed just 110
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Shipmate Lonnie McDuffie, 78, of La Place, La., recalled other,
less obvious scars. ``When I got out of prison, for 10 years I was
hard as a rock,'' he said. ``I'd let a (guy) beat me to death
before I'd cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbie Robinson, one of the prisoners taken to Japan, where he
worked in the Nagasaki shipyard and dug coal, scribbled a little
note to express his sentiments. ``Present feelings now are mixed:
grateful, humble, angry, guilty and hopeful,'' the note read. The
79-year-old, who lives in Seattle, thought a moment. Then he
pointed to the note and said, ``Hate. I left out `hate.' That's the
most important one.''
</P>
<P>
   He smiled slightly. ``Before I die, I'd like to forgive
everybody so I can go to heaven,'' he said. ``So I want to know a
few minutes before I go.''
</P>
<P>
   Earle writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
