<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5410 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIOLENCE-CURES-COX     05-28 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCE-CURES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Violence focus of gathering at Emory
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As carnage piles up in schoolyards and war zones, a
group of scholars is gathering at Emory University in Atlanta
Thursday through June 5 to look at the causes and possible cures
for violence.
</P>
<P>
   The Colloquium on Violence and Religion centers on the work of
Rene Girard, a French scholar retired from Stanford University who
is known for his work on scapegoating. He will speak at 7 p.m.
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Scapegoating ``is a dynamic that plagues our relationships from
nursery school to global affairs,'' said Theophus Smith, an Emory
religion professor who is coordinating the meeting. ``It is our
fallback, our default mode, for creating unity in groups. If all
else fails _ negotiation, diplomacy, law enforcement, litigation _
one sure-fire way is to target one of us as the cause of our
conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   In school violence, this comes out in the retaliation of
children who have felt victimized and who, in turn, target others
for blame and sometimes for bullets, said Smith. In international
affairs, he said, ``ethnic cleansing is the perfect example of
creating unity in a dominant group by targeting another group.''
And dropping bombs on the people blamed for the ethnic cleansing
shows how violence, once used, becomes contagious, he said.
</P>
<P>
   So what hope is there to overcome violence?
</P>
<P>
   ``The true alternative, instead of creating another scapegoat,
is to offer one's self as a substitute,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   African-American slaves often relied on their religion and the
principles taught by the Gospels as an ``antidote'' to the violence
they were experiencing, said Smith. And in the civil rights
movement, nonviolent marches eventually won over the court of world
opinion and changed laws and society, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Christians, ``the Crucifixion is an anti-scapegoating
event,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Nonviolent approaches take time, patience and courage, he said,
and people are not often willing to invest the time or take the
risk. ``We think violence is the faster, more efficient, more
thorough way,'' said Smith. ``We idolize violence as if it were a
godlike power for rescuing us. We keep using it over and over with
no evidence that it's working.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said scholars hope their studies will evolve into practice
so they can train leaders to help dismantle violence.
</P>
<P>
   Because this year's gathering of the colloquium will occur at
Emory, Smith attempted to take advantage of Emory-related
institutions, from the Yerkes Regional Primate Research Center to
the Carter Center.
</P>
<P>
   At Yerkes, Frans de Waal, a Dutch-born zoologist and ethologist,
examines ethics and morality in primates. Officials of the Carter
Center travel the world attempting to head off or reduce ethnic,
civil and international expressions of violence.
</P>
<P>
   De Waal will address the group at 11:15 a.m. Thursday on
``Violence Reduction Among Primates.'' Other speakers include Jim
Grote of the University of Louisville, co-author of ``Clever as
Serpents _ Business Ethics and Office Politics,'' and Regina
Schwartz, director of the Chicago Institute of Religion, Ethics and
Violence, who wrote ``The Curse of Cain: The Violent Legacy of
Monotheism.''
</P>
<P>
   For a complete schedule and information, call 404-727-5337or
visit the conference Web site: www.emory.edu/COLLEGE
</P>
<P>
   /RELIGION/VR/COVR99meeting
</P>
<P>
   .html
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
