<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5422 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBNQBRAVES-WOES-COX     05-28 1383
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBNQBRAVES-WOES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What's wrong with the Braves pitchers, if anything?
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The visiting clubhouse at County Stadium in Milwaukee was a
lonely, quiet place Monday night when Tom Glavine walked inside the
bearer of nine earned runs and his fifth loss, something he didn't
have last year until August.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 National League Cy Young award winner went to his
teammate, friend and four-time Cy Young winner Greg Maddux, who was
charting Glavine's pitches from television and feeling his pain.
Glavine was looking for some answers to a question both of them
have faced all too often this season: What went wrong?
</P>
<P>
   ``I honestly thought after the first inning that I was giving my
pitches away because they didn't even offer at any change-ups, and
they were pretty good pitches,'' Glavine said.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux told Glavine the same thing he's been reminding himself
through his own struggles: nothing's wrong. Which left the
cornerstones of the Atlanta Braves franchise scratching their
heads. Are two of the hardest-to-figure pitchers in baseball no
longer difficult to figure out?
</P>
<P>
   But even in that frustrating moment, they took some small
comfort, because the two of them were in there together, sharing
the opposite end of the spectrum from their Nike commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it eases my questions, or questions that people have
about me, in terms of, 'Is this the end of the rope?''' Glavine
said. ``I don't think that. But I guess it makes it a little bit
easier. I think you just try to deal with it on a game-to-game
basis and try to win each game that you pitch and hope that each
time you pitch well it leads to another one.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavine, 3-5 with a 5.54 ERA, will make his 11th start today
against the Dodgers. Maddux, who put together his best start of the
month on Tuesday night to hold at 4-3 and lower his ERA to 4.48
ERA, pitches Sunday. Neither one has been through a stretch like
this before _ not this long, not this ineffective and not when
they're supposed to be too young, both at 33, to be dealing with
such problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real easy to look at numbers and say, 'Ah, well, they're
throwing like crap,''' Glavine said. ``The hard thing to do is to
get into what's going on and try and really sit down and figure out
how bad are you and how far off are you. And when you've had the
kind of success that he and I have had for the last eight years,
obviously people are going to look at our numbers right now and say
that we're way off. I don't buy into that.''
</P>
<P>
   An easy answer would and could be the new, skinnier strike zone.
When two control pitchers who feast on and off the edges of the
plate are struggling at the same time, it seems too coincidental.
Neither will use it as an excuse, but Maddux's catcher will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any difference in the way they pitch,''
Eddie Perez said. ``It's the new strike zone. (Maddux and I) used
to go fastball away, fastball in, most of the time to get ahead.
Now we can't do that because it's got to be right in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Braves players have said privately that they think this
pitching staff, Glavine and Maddux in particular, have been
targeted by umpires, who are angry with the commissioner's office
for trying to change the way they do their jobs and have chosen two
of the highest-profile pitchers in baseball to point that out. It
even has been suggested to Braves by opposing coaches, who have
said their pitchers are getting better calls than the Braves'
pitchers in games against them. But that's not something players or
coaches are prepared to talk about publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Blame it on mechanics, that's all you can do,'' Glavine said.
``I still maintain (that Monday) night I felt good out there; my
mechanics felt fine. I'm not going to sit here and say that I
didn't make any mistakes, but I didn't make nine runs worth of
mistakes. It's frustrating because I feel like I'm on the verge of
getting where I want to be, and then you have a game like (Monday)
night, and you're like, 'All right, now what?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care so much about what my numbers are and how I feel
as much as I feel bad that I'm letting guys in here down, Bobby
(Cox), the coaches, everybody else. I'll deal with the fact that on
a personal level things aren't going all that well, but if we're
going to get things going in the right direction, I need to get
myself going in the right direction. But I think that will all
come.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux is hoping it's already here. His seven shutout innings
against the Brewers on Tuesday night rescued him from a four-game
stretch in which he was 0-3 with an 8.14 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did some things well in that game,'' Maddux said. ``I'm
going to try to do them again. That's what I take out of (Tuesday)
night. Just like the losses. Yeah, I lost those three games but I
took things out of those games that will make me a better
pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez was more specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was showing when he was throwing the changeup,''
Perez said. ``He made some adjustments (against the Brewers), and
he was throwing OK. It happened in Chicago and in San Diego.
Hopefully, that's what it is. They were looking for that pitch; he
threw a perfect one down and away, and they were taking it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the pitch that hitters are usually induced to swing
through. It's the pitch Maddux's former Cubs teammate Mark Grace
hit for a double on a 3-2 count on May 20 for only his eighth hit
in 33 career at-bats off his former teammate. It was Grace's second
hit in a row after he homered in his first at-bat to help the Cubs
take a 5-0 lead on Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a pretty good pitch, a 3-2 changeup. I just stayed on
it and hit it good,'' Grace said. ``That's usually the pitch he
gets me out with. Every once in a while, you get a hit. I wouldn't
worry about him. . . . His stuff is still sharp, believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   Dating back to Aug. 12, Maddux is 7-7 with a 4.51 ERA. But he
suggests that this year's struggles are different because he feels
better physically than he did last year when he was hampered by
some tenderness in his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been making too many mistakes,'' Maddux said, ``throwing
too many hittable pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux has coped by studying his mechanics and working and
thinking hard between starts. But he said it's also a matter of
trusting himself that he's still doing the right things, pitching
the right way. He wants to put the negatives behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deal with it, blow it off and go on,'' Maddux said. ``I go
home and be a dad again. Then I come to the ballpark and get ready
for the next game. . . . I care about my job. I care about what we
do. But once it's done, it's over with. I'm done with it. That's
easier said than done, I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's Jeff Blauser, a neighbor who shared a locker with
Maddux for five of his years when he was with the Braves, said
people need to cut Maddux some slack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people expect him to be superhuman, and he's human,''
Blauser said. ``One thing I think people fail to remember is he has
pitched a lot of innings in his career. I think if you saw a guy
who was missing up in the strike zone, it'd be one thing, but he's
keeping the ball down. He's changing speeds. More than anything,
from what I've seen, if he does make a mistake, he's getting hit,
where in the past if he made a mistake a lot of time he was getting
away with it. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is this team certainly still respects what he can
do,'' Blauser said. ``I personally feel sorry for the rest of the
league when he gets going, because he's certainly going to get
going. He's too smart and he's too good for this, No. 1, to affect
him and, No. 2, for this to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux and Glavine are counting on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still maintain that somewhere along the line I'll get on a
roll, Doggie will get on a roll, and all this will be forgotten,''
Glavine said. ``It doesn't make right now any less frustrating. The
only good thing about it is, he and I haven't pitched well, we're
playing about as bad as we can play right now as a team, and we're
still in first place. So you try to focus on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
