A5423 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSTERS-COX     05-28 1314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSTERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Most of Division I male college tennis players are foreign
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ On Court 1 in the quarterfinals of the NCAA Tennis
Championships here, Baylor's Johann Jooste of South Africa played
Georgia's Hisham Hemeda of Egypt. On Court 2, Baylor's Pawel
Gajdzik of Poland faced Georgia's Talito Corrales of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   The Baylor squad also featured Johannes Michalsky of Germany,
Fanda Stejskal of the Czech Republic, Csongor Bibza of Hungary and
Frederic Blaise of France, among others. Of the 10 players on the
Bears' roster, only Jorge Aldrete of San Diego was born in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of Division I male college tennis players are
foreign, says Stanford coach Dick Gould, one of the few coaches to
resist the influx of foreign talent in American college tennis.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest college rankings, 12 of the top 20 and 28 of the
top 50 were born outside the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   What happened to all of the Americans?
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has bastardized the system that I'm aware of, and as
long as the system is not taken advantage of, I don't have a
problem with (bringing in foreign players),'' said Gould, in
college tennis for 32 years. ``It makes my players better, but I
feel sorry for the American players who miss out (on scholarships).
And the number of foreign players is even higher at the Division II
level and at junior colleges.''
</P>
<P>
   Division 1 offers approximately 1,400 scholarships for male
players. American players receive about 400, meaning that foreign
born players are taking some 1,000 scholarships that could be going
to native U.S. players.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign players are nothing new. The first foreign-born player
to win the NCAA title was Edward Dewhurst from Sydney, Australia.
He did it in 1903 and repeated in 1905. He was 34 years old when he
won it the second time, taking time from his study of dentistry at
the University of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get a good foreign player, they have a friend,''
retired Georgia tennis coach Dan Magill said. ``Pretty soon, you've
got a pipeline started. If you're not good enough to go on the pro
tour, the place to go is an American college. You know you're going
to play fall, winter and spring. The competition is going to make
you better, and you're going to get a free education.''
</P>
<P>
   Tennis isn't the only college sport to be influenced by strong
foreign talent. Track-and-field rosters read like a United Nations
roll call. Cross country, golf and baseball all have been affected.
Even college basketball has become international.
</P>
<P>
   Magill said the influx of college tennis players began after
King Gustav of Sweden hired American Bill Lufler to install a
system to help young talent get better. Lufler, an excellent coach
at Presbyterian and Miami, was successful, and other nations copied
his system.
</P>
<P>
   In the pro ranks, most of the top 100 players are foreign. Pete
Sampras, Andre Agassi, Jim Courier and Michael Chang are getting
older, and no one stands poised to step in.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Tennis Association is well aware of the situation.
``Five years from now, we don't want two Lithuanian players playing
in the finals of the U.S. Open,'' said past USTA president Harry
Marmion.
</P>
<P>
   Marmion and other top USTA officials installed a five-year, $32
million plan to bolster junior tennis and develop top-notch
American players. It hired Davis Cup captain Tom Gullikson to
oversee the ambitious undertaking.
</P>
<P>
   While some see no harm in college tennis becoming international,
Gullikson disagrees. ``I don't think it's good,'' he said. ``I
would be for limiting the number of foreign players. But I think
there's so much pressure on the coaches to win, the athletic
department at each school would have to support it.''
</P>
<P>
   Grover Hinsdale, the track coach at Georgia Tech, has been
outspoken about developing homegrown talent first. The longtime
Jacket coach never has recruited a foreign athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at the national championships in the late '80s, and I
couldn't believe it,'' Hinsdale said. ``Where were the Americans? I
started thinking about it after that. Then in 1991, Tennessee won
the NCAA outdoors with an all-American team. They showed it's
possible with all-U.S. athletes. I made up my mind then that we
were going to try to develop our own players. No matter how much or
how little you give (in aid) to a foreign athlete, that's how much
you're taking away from an American athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   There was talk several years ago about limiting the number of
foreign scholarships, Magill says, but it stopped when the U.S.
State Department reacted disapprovingly. Four years ago, Hinsdale
said, coaches took a vote at the annual U.S. Track Coaches meeting
to limit scholarship aid to one foreign athlete, but the motion was
defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Diaz, whose team won the NCAA title Tuesday, has three
foreign-born players. ``The international players bring a lot to
the table, and our American kids benefit from being exposed,'' said
Diaz, who was recruited from Puerto Rico by Magill. ``We're a
nation of immigrants. Isn't the American way to enterprise? We're
so bottom-line. I just think there are more good, hungry, capable,
ambitious young coaches now who aren't willing to sit on the
sidelines and compete for the top U.S. players who are going to
Stanford, UCLA and Southern Cal.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor coach Matt Knoll took over the Bears' program three years
ago when Baylor was ranked No. 300 in the country. This year,
Baylor finished in the top eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes America great,'' said Knoll, who has no
patience with those who question his almost all-foreign lineup.
``That's outdated thinking,'' Knoll said. ``It's prejudice. How
many years ago did Kentucky's all-white basketball team get beat by
an all-black team in the NCAAs? Now, guess what. Kentucky's team is
almost all black. Our foreign players stay four years and take
their academics seriously. We've had the highest GPA in the
athletic department for the past two years. An argument could be
made (that) the hardest-working students are first-generation
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come to me and ask, 'Why aren't you recruiting more
players from this country?''' Knoll said. ``I say, 'Why aren't you
making (the U.S. player) better?' Don't bring me some player who
can't beat my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My take is, tennis is played all over the world,'' Florida's
No. 1 player, Jeff Morrison, said. ``In football, you don't have
that. The problem I have with foreign players coming in is with the
23- and 24-year-old guys. They just passed a rule last year that a
foreign player could only have five years to complete his
eligibility after graduating from high school, but I don't think
they're really enforcing that.
</P>
<P>
   ``One problem is the American players have gotten so spoiled,''
Morrison said. ``Nobody wants to go to Starkville or Oxford, Miss.,
or Baylor. Everybody wants to go to Stanford or UCLA or Florida or
Georgia. So some schools have been forced to look for foreign
players.''
</P>
<P>
   Morrison concedes that the U.S. has a way to go to bring up its
tennis standards. ``The depth in American tennis isn't there,'' he
said. ``In the past, the U.S. Tennis Association had a chosen few.
A lot of people are very bitter toward the USTA. But now they're
trying to do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   One international player who has benefited from the system is
Georgia's Corrales, who completed his eligibility this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thankful for the system that allowed me to play, but if I
would be an American, I would not like it,'' Corrales said. ``I
think the solution is to limit the numbers of foreign players on
each team to two or three. The way it is, it's taking away
privileges to American players.''
</P>
<P>
   Arey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
