A5426 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LADN-BUDGET &LR;      05-28 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LADN-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Saturday, May 29, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   LA-GLOOM (Los Angeles) _ The bothersome weather phenomenon
marked by colder-than-normal Pacific waters is taking one last shot
before she leaves _ dropping sea and air temperatures a few degrees
below normal for the summer, extending the June gloom through the
summer, and increasing the smog level in Southern California. By
Steve Carney. (Will move in the ``n'' California news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LA-AIRLINE (Los Angeles) _ The Los Angeles City Council meets
and is expected to vote to reject a 23-year lease with United
Airlines and send the lease back to the Airport Commission for
revisions. The council is demanding the contract be rewritten to
include protections _ that already exist in federal law _ for an
airline subcontractor's workers who are in a union organizing
drive. By Rick Orlov. (Will move in the ``n'' California news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-DISNEY (Los Angeles) _ The bitter dispute between Jeffrey
Katzenberg and The Walt Disney Co. took a bizarre turn this week as
five news organizations filed a brief telling a judge that
documents about Katzenberg's DreamWorks SKG should be kept secret,
then reversed course a day later. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the
``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   UNIVERSAL-BACK (Los Angeles) _ Universal, after enduring a year
and a half of flops and a messy series of high-level dismissals,
has finally managed to get its film business back in
order.``Universal has really rebounded,'' noted Drew Devlin, an
executive with Clark Film Buying. ``And their upcoming schedule
looks pretty strong.'' By Dave McNary. (Will move in the ``f''
financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LITTON-MERGER (Los Angeles) _ The Pentagon on Friday torpedoed
Litton Industries Inc.'s proposed $1.9 billion acquisition of
Newport News Shipbuilding Inc., saying the potential cost savings
to the government are not big enough to justify less competition
among shipbuilders. By Gregory Wilcox. (Will move in the ``f''
financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
