<HEADER>
A5442 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNIVERSAL-KIDS-LADN     05-28 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSAL-KIDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSAL STUDIOS HOLLYWOOD ADDS NICKELODEON ATTRACTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS PARKER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Universal Studios Hollywood will unveil a series
of new attractions and events this summer that will allow young
Nickelodeon fans to participate in a live ``Blue's Clues'' game and
eat pancakes with Woody Woodpecker.
</P>
<P>
   The amusement park's Kids Fun Fest could propel its name to the
top of the ``to do'' list of every under-4-foot kid in Southern
California. That's because in addition to its stable of Universal
and Marvel cartoon characters, the park has the added attraction of
Nickelodeon's top cable television characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really wanted to get more families up here,'' said Pat
Moloney, director of entertainment for Universal Studios Hollywood,
``and make this a special thing for kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, amusement parks have always wanted to attract kids
and their money-spending parents. But in previous years, parks did
that by building the biggest, scariest ride.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, Southern California's amusement parks are turning
their attention to the under-4-foot crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Preteens are ``certainly a large segment of the marketplace,''
Moloney said. ``I think we accommodate them pretty well already,
but this extends the options.''
</P>
<P>
   The new attractions, which open July 2, are led by ``Blue's
Clues Live,'' an auditorium version of the popular Nickelodeon TV
show. Kids will be able to solve puzzles, play games and sing songs
along with Blue and her friends.
</P>
<P>
   Universal's character breakfasts will offer the youngest guests
a chance to meet some of the most popular Nickelodeon, Universal
and Marvel characters before heading into the park.
</P>
<P>
   Other new attractions include Woody Woodpecker's Clubhouse and
an updated Chipmunks Show.
</P>
<P>
   Tying the whole package together for Universal's pint-sized
guests will be a treasure hunt. Kids will receive a special map
when they enter the park that highlights the kid-friendly
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   As they wander from attraction to attraction, they'll receive
stamps, like a tourist having her passport stamped as she enters
each country. Kids who collect the entire set of stamps will get a
prize.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
