<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-POWER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIA FACES TOUGH REFORMS UNDER ELECTED PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ Nigeria inaugurates its first elected president
in two decades Saturday amid cautious hopes that Africa's most
populous nation will finally break its long and devastating cycle
of corruption, military repression, and decay.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no honeymoon for Olusegun Obasanjo, the retired
general who ruled for three years while in uniform in the late
1970s and was elected in February as a civilian. Years of debauched
military rule have left the nation and its economy in tatters.
</P>
<P>
   Cities suffer from shortages of water and electricity, roads
crumble, and the country's oil refineries _ the pistons of its
economy _ lie in disrepair. Nigeria's currency is worth a penny and
the country is $31 billion in debt, according to the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of weakness, and Obasanjo runs the risk of another
hostile takeover from a military that has shown it preference for
palaces over barracks too many times in the past 40 years. ``We are
optimistic. We are basking in the excitement of a return to
civilian government,'' said Felix Morka, a human rights activist in
Lagos, Nigeria's sprawling commercial capital. ``But people are
impatient. Obasanjo must take control immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   The guest list at Obasanjo's swearing-in provides a measure of
how anxious the international community is to see Nigeria succeed.
Last year, when the West African giant was still under the boot of
General Sani Abacha, its most ruthless and corrupt dictator,
President Clinton conspicuously avoided the West African giant on
his tour across the continent.
</P>
<P>
   Since Abacha's sudden death last June, however, his dovish
successor, General Abdulsalami Abubakar, has won plaudits for
honoring his promises to hold elections and hand over power.
President Nelson Mandela of South Africa and Susan Rice, US
assistant secretary of state for African affairs, are part of a
long entourage of foreign dignitaries who will be on hand.
</P>
<P>
   The transition is good news on a continent so badly shaken in
the past year by the multinational conflict in Congo, a return to
civil war in Angola, and renewed fighting between Ethiopia and
Eritrea. A country rich in ill-managed natural resources, Nigeria a
potential economic engine for all of West Africa. The change also
opens an important new diplomatic axis between democratically
elected governments in Abuja and Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
   But observers are loathe to make too much of the moment.
Obasanjo's rise marks only the third time since independence from
Britain in 1960 that the military has stepped aside gracefully. The
last civilian government was thrown out in 1983 after just four
years in power, and military control has changed hands three times
since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hesitate to give this much historical significance in the
continental sense because there have been so many fits and
starts,'' said Makau Mutua, a visiting professor at Harvard Law
School. ``This is a tortured transition, engineered by the
military. It does not threaten the military's interests. But what
is important is that the most powerful nation on the continent now
says that democracy is essential.''
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria won't make a clean break from its troubled past, and
Obasanjo comes in with mixed credentials. He rose to power
indirectly, first as the second in command in a new military
government installed after the 1967-70 civil war against the
secessionist state of Biafra, then to the helm with assassin ended
the rule of Brig. Murtala Muhammad seven months later. He
suppressed democratic protests with violence, but three years later
became the only military leader in Nigeria's history to yield power
to an elected government.
</P>
<P>
   He retired to raise chickens and pigs, and over the years
cultivated his faith in the Methodist Church and became an
increasingly vocal advocate for human rights. He was considered for
secretary-general of the United Nations in 1991, and spent the last
three and a half years of Abacha's reign as the dictator's
political prisoner.
</P>
<P>
   But Obasanjo is not without ties to his former military
colleagues. He most prominent campaign supporter was Ibrahim
Babangida, the general who toppled the civilian government Obasanjo
installed. Babangida is a recent convert to democracy, becoming a
critic of military rule only in the face of Abacha's brutality.
Obasanjo also enjoys warm ties with the outgoing general, Abubakar,
and so far has not demanded that the military's top brass resign _
a tradition that has marked previous transitions.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo was vague during the campaign, vowing only to attack
corruption and promising that ``whatever we do in economic terms,
not only will it be transparent, we will provide level ground for
all.'' In the months since the February ballot he offered few more
clues about how he will lead.
</P>
<P>
   He faces urgent and difficult choices. Abubakar laid claim last
year to recovering $800 million that Abacha stole from the public
purse. It has never surfaced, and is believed to have been
distributed to senior military leaders to buy their cooperation in
the transition. More public funds, looted over the years and
estimated to be in the billions, lie in offshore accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo needs to call the military to account for stolen money
and human-rights abuses to gain the public's confidence. But he has
vowed not to conduct ``a witch hunt,'' and if he digs too deeply he
could alienate the already twitchy ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obasanjo was recruited by a small clique with military ties.
If he ignores that constituency, he runs the risk of being
overthrown,'' Morka said. ``But he must weigh in on the side of the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   If he does, Morka says, he may buy some valuable time to begin
sorting out Nigeria's destroyed economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
