<SLUG> BC-RAC-MASSCAP-BAFFERT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT IN THE RUN FOR THE MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- No mapmaker could measure the true distance from the
Arizona desert and white cowboy hats and quarterhorses to the
backstretch of Suffolk Downs in East Boston, a quarter-mile or so
from the Atlantic Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Bob Baffert, who has traveled that route, arrived late
Thursday afternoon, his first time in Boston, sidekick Mike Pegram
in tow, the two fun lovers here to watch their Real Quiet go to the
post odds-on Saturday in the 60th Massachusetts Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   Pegram, direct as always, said there was reason enough to come
to Boston. ``If they put up $600,000,'' said Real Quiet's owner,
``I'm going to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   From shortly after 5:30 Saturday afternoon to shortly after 5:30
next Saturday afternoon, from the Massachusetts Handicap to the
Belmont Stakes next week, Baffert and Pegram will be at the center
as one of the more remarkable weeks in the history of American
horse racing unfolds. Heat, lightning, and thunder all will clash
and crash, no matter what the gods of weather deign to provide.
Baffert and Pegram have unleashed the forces.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet would have won the Triple Crown last year if it
weren't for jockey Kent Desormeaux's ride in the Belmont, where he
came up short by a whisker, and Charismatic will be going for the
Triple Crown next week. But Baffert and Pegram have decided to play
hardball with Charismatic's trainer, D. Wayne Lukas; they have
entered their spectacular filly, Silverbulletday, in the Belmont to
run against the big boys.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the plot is flush enough _ the best girl against the best
boy _ but the subplots are even more fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert and Lukas are rivals, to use a genteel word. ``Foes''
might be more apt, while ``nemeses'' could be the best fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Lukas and the rivalry is good for the sport,'' said
Baffert. ``It gives me something to shoot for. I mean, I think
we're good for each other. If it wasn't (for Lukas), I'd probably
get bored.''
</P>
<P>
   Boredom may be the greatest foe of all for Baffert and Pegram.
And while any quest for the Triple Crown is electric enough,
Baffert and Pregram have ensured that no electric meter can measure
the kilowatts of the coming week. So while he schmoozed outside
Barn 20 at Suffolk, observing that ``the barns here are pretty
nice,'' Baffert joked about the rivalry, which he said has cooled
in intensity in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been getting along with the guy pretty good recently,''
said Baffert. ``I really respect him and what he's done. I don't
want to take anything away from Wayne.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Baffert had quipped and wisecracked about the
rivalry, which has grown since Baffert burst upon the national
scene when his Silver Charm and Real Quiet won the 1997 and 1998
Kentucky Derby and Preakness and just missed the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Wayne, he's a very competitive guy and his deal is he
strives to be the No. 1 guy,'' said Baffert. ``I actually got there
without striving, just fell into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he took a couple of Belmont barbs at his archrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne Lukas doesn't like the fact that I'm running her
(Silverbulletday) in there,'' said Baffert. ``He won't say that,
but I'm sure he doesn't like it. Like if it was me going for the
Triple Crown, you'd probably see five Lukas horses in there. But
that's not me.''
</P>
<P>
   He also addressed the matter of training philosophies and
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bought an $85,000 horse, Silver Charm, and I win the Derby
and almost a Triple Crown,'' said Baffert. ``I buy a $17,000 horse
(Real Quiet) and I almost win the Triple Crown. Lukas was one claim
slip away from (losing a shot at a Triple Crown horse).''
</P>
<P>
   For the non-horse crowd, owner Bob Lewis and Lukas had
Charismatic entered in a claiming race as recently as February at
Santa Anita. But no horseperson submitted a claim slip to buy him
for $62,500; now Charismatic is one race from immortality.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Baffert put the rivalry on a personal _ or, more
accurately, personality _ level.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne is serious and he comes across as a workaholic and he's
focused,'' he said. ``But you can still be like that and have fun.
I'm focused but I like to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Baffert said he couldn't sleep at his Boston hotel Thursday
night because of his comments. Friday he said he wants everybody
``to enjoy the Belmont'' and didn't want his quips to ignite any
fires. The rivalry has cooled, he went on, and his respect for
Lukas has grown, especially with the training expertise Lukas has
demonstrated with Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   Another subplot is that Baffert trains some 15 horses for Lewis.
This is most sensitive, Baffert conceded, entering his horse to
possibly ruin the Triple Crown chances of one of his prime owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little bit awkward,'' said Baffert, ``but I told Bob,
`We're not trying to spoil your deal. We're just trying to win the
Belmont.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Overshadowing all of this is that Baffert, according to his
critics, has metamorphosed into the Lukas who was so roundly
criticized in years past, the Lukas whose ego seemingly demanded
that he always have a horse in Triple Crown races. Lukas himself
just might point out in the next week that if he had done what
Baffert did with Baffert's Triple Crown horses this year, he would
have been hashed by the critics.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting, Baffert's other fine filly, pulled up in the
Preakness, unable to finish, while Prime Timber suffered a minor
injury and General Challenge was not up to the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what's coming,'' said Baffert of the critics-to-be,
``but we're going for it because we've never won the Belmont.''
</P>
<P>
   Pegram, for his part, had his take on the hardball being thrown
at the Belmont. Charismatic ``wins the Belmont and he's Horse of
the Year,'' said the owner of Silverbulletday, who otherwise might
be Horse of the Year. ``But we know we've got an exceptional filly.
She's a great athlete, and you hate to run her a mile and a half,
but at the same time, great athletes do great things.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Baffert and Pegram talked, Real Quiet was a mere few feet
away, there in Suffolk's Barn 20. Pegram said he still has a ``hole
in his heart'' from Real Quiet's loss by a nose to Victory Gallop
in last year's Belmont. ``We were sure,'' said Baffert, ``that he
was going to win that race.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet did not win because Desormeaux made a premature move
on the colt and, as Baffert tells the tale, went against prerace
instructions. It was not until weeks later that Baffert and
Desormeaux talked about the ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him before the race, `Just cruise around there; you
only have one horse (Victory Gallop) to beat,' '' recalled Baffert.
`` `Just sit there and sit and sit and sit' '' _ running like a
turf race _ ``but Kent rode him like he did in the Derby and the
Preakness, where he made this huge half-mile move. But going a mile
and a half, you can't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   And when ``we talked two weeks later,'' recalled Baffert, ``I
wasn't that upset by the move, I was upset by the way he came out
in front of (Victory Gallop right at the wire), and I told Kent
that. I had told him that `whatever you do, don't do anything to
get your number taken down.' And when he saw (Victory Gallop)
coming and got in front of him, intentionally tried to impede him,
he could easily have been disqualified, and that would have been
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   If Victory Gallop hadn't won by a nose, the unthinkable might
have happened; the Belmont stewards might have disqualified Real
Quiet, taking down a Triple Crown winner. ``I think he would have
been DQ'd,'' said Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Stevens is riding Real Quiet now, and the MassCap will be
the jockey's last in the United States. Less than two hours after
the MassCap, Stevens will be at Logan Airport for a flight to
England, where he will relocate . . . at least for a while. ``I
think Gary'll be back in 45 days max,'' wisecracked Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The irreverent Baffert now is well known to the public, who have
embraced the trainer as racing's true ambassador. His popularity
has grown and grown, but he obviously is a horseman first _ his 16
stakes wins in the recently concluded Santa Anita meet eclipsed the
late Charlie Whittingham's record.
</P>
<P>
   He came from Nogales, Ariz., and 13 years ago, Baffert and
Pegram first met and hit it off immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the spring of '86, I bought a quarterhorse with a
partner,'' recalled Pegram. ``That horse was running and Bob had
him, so I went over to Los Alamitos (a quarterhorse track outside
Los Angeles) and I said, `How am I going to know you?' He said,
`I'm the guy with the white cowboy hat.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So I get to Los Alamitos and everybody in the place has got a
white cowboy hat on. Then we're out in Ruidoso (N.M.) at a sale and
there's no plane out and I tell Bob, `No way I'm staying in
(nearby) El Paso for the night.' So we end up in Las Vegas for the
night.''
</P>
<P>
   The two have been winning since. Their horses are better, the
purses are larger, and the egos are greater. As racing will see
this coming week, when their Silverbulletday will take on D. Wayne
Lukas's Charismatic, filly to colt, ego to ego.
</P>
</TEXT>
