<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SCHOOLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINESE CRAMMING TO GET INTO THE US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ While thousands of Chinese students were hurling
chunks of concrete and abuse at the US embassy earlier this month,
tens of thousands more were otherwise occupied: They were busy
boning up at ``cram schools'' dedicated to going to America.
</P>
<P>
   At Beijing's most famous cram school, the recent protests over
NATO's bombing of the Chinese embassy in Belgrade seemed as far
away as Yugoslavia itself. While renewed US allegations that China
has been stealing military secrets prompted another round of
official tirades against Washington this week, there is scant talk
in the school's hallways of America as imperialist enemy. The
chatter is all about exam scores, scholarships, and who got into
Harvard Business School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may dislike the American government, but American people are
very nice to us, and we all want to go there to study,'' said
Shirley Zhu, 21, a student who has came from distant Guangdong to
cram for the business school exam.
</P>
<P>
   At the famed Beijing Oriental School, where 50,000 students took
crash courses last year, the message is clear: forget politics _
study, study, study, and learn to think the American way.
</P>
<P>
   That mantra seems to work; the school boasts that 1 in 5 pupils
scored over 600 out of a possible 677 on the Test of English as a
Foreign Language. They claim half the students who went to America
for an MBA last year prepped here.
</P>
<P>
   But a Stanley Kaplan cram school this is not. The tricks
students learn to ace exams include advice like use ``American
reasoning'' when solving logic problems _ imagine you're foolish.
Another teacher's tip: If an American visa officer seems ready to
reject you because he thinks you're out to find a husband and stay
in America, tell him you're a lesbian.
</P>
<P>
   In the last academic year, 46,958 Chinese nationals studied at
American universities (2,023 of them in Massachusetts), making them
the second-largest group of foreign students in the United States _
close behind the Japanese. That's a phenomenal rise from the 1,000
Chinese students who went to America 20 years ago, in the first
year of communist China's ``Open Door Policy.''
</P>
<P>
   For America, overseas students offer not only intellect, but
cash. Foreign students contributed $7.5 billion in tuition and
living expenses to the US economy in the last academic year alone,
making education America's fifth-largest export. In Massachusetts,
the fourth most popular academic destination, foreign students
spent $618 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   For China, the impact of sending students abroad is even more
dramatic: Exposure to America is reshaping the mentality and goals
of a new generation.
</P>
<P>
   Many students may believe their government's line that
Washington is trying to thwart a rising China, but they still dream
of an American education as their ticket to success. And as
fiercely nationalistic as Chinese students may be, many never come
back. The government admits that more than two-thirds of the
320,000 students who went abroad in the last 20 years have not
returned.
</P>
<P>
   Wang Zhihong, 26, a biophysics student who is cramming at
Beijing Oriental School and dreams of attending Harvard, says he is
practical in his patriotism. ``The US has the best education in the
world, and after graduation, I can serve my homeland much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Wang insists he will return even if others do not. China may
seem backward after living in the United States, he said, and many
might find it hard to readjust. But that is changing, ``and in the
future they will come back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese government is trying to make sure of that. In recent
years, they have forced students who receive government
scholarships to study abroad to sign a paper promising to return,
or pay the money back.
</P>
<P>
   For most students, however, the main concern is not whether to
return, but how to get to America in the first place. A monthlong
course on the Graduate Record Examination, or GRE, is $100, which
is costly in a country whose per capita income is about $3,000.
Parents save up and students take extra jobs because studying
abroad is seen as an investment with a huge payoff.
</P>
<P>
   In rented classrooms scattered across the city, teachers at
Beijing Oriental coach students to memorize 1,000 English words a
day. They suggest sleeping four to five hours a night and taking
breaks only to eat. One teacher tells his students to ``treat the
GRE like your lover. You must have the passion to overcome it. If
you hate it, how can you do it?''
</P>
<P>
   There are special lectures on how to write a personal essay, how
to apply to universities, how to face a visa interview. There are
movies at night to hear conversational English and learn American
customs.
</P>
<P>
   Some teaching methods may seem slightly unorthodox, but they
seem to work. The school claims that 1 in 5 students scored above
2,000 out of 2,400 on the GRE last year. And at least one in every
class got a perfect score on the English language exam.
</P>
<P>
   One teacher advises students that if they don't know the answer,
choose ``D,'' the most likely choice based on his study of old
tests. Another counsels that when solving logic problems, ``Don't
use Chinese logic. You have to learn American ways of thinking.
Remember, Americans are foolish. Choose the most direct answer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the US, if you need one step to get a conclusion, it's
called logic. If you need two steps, that's philosophy,'' he
quipped.
</P>
<P>
   What may seem like an insult to Americans is really just
training in shedding ``convoluted Chinese ways of thinking,'' said
Yin Zi, 28, a former student who crammed for the Graduate Record
Examination. ``If they ask a simple question, we think too much and
have a thousand reasons why.''
</P>
<P>
   For many bright students, getting into school is the easy part.
Getting an American visa and adjusting to a new life are far more
daunting tasks.
</P>
<P>
   Yin, for example, has been rejected three times for a student
visa, but now is equipped not only with admission to New York
University, but with the confidence to answer questions from
notoriously tough visa officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think you're not going to study, (but) just to find some
guy and get married. So my teacher told us if a visa officer asks
if you're unmarried, you can say, `Sorry, I'm not interested in
men.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Teacher Guan Weidong also tries to prepare his students for
surviving and working hard once they get to America. ``They think
life there is heaven,'' he said, shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added with a laugh, some cultural shocks have nothing to
do with school: ``I tell them that in America, the most difficult
thing is to borrow money from others, and the easiest is to
divorce.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
