<SLUG> BC-RAC-MASSCAP-BEHRENS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BEHRENS, IT'S ALL COMING DOWN TO THE WIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- When trainer Bob Baffert announced early last week
that Kentucky Derby winner Real Quiet was coming to Saturday's
$600,000 Massachusetts Handicap at Suffolk Downs, he stole the
spotlight from fellow conditioner Jim Bond and handicap star
Behrens.
</P>
<P>
   Bond, who had been pointing for the MassCap since Behrens won
the Oaklawn Handicap April 3 to take the lead in the National
Thoroughbred Racing Association Champions series, went on the back
burner as soon as Baffert, racing's quotable quipster, showed up
for his first visit to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   While Baffert has been meeting and greeting, Bond has been up at
Saratoga, keeping a low profile and preparing Behrens over the
Oklahoma training track. The Oklahoma surface is deep, but Behrens
has put together a top string of works, most recently a 5-furlong
move in a sizzling :59 3/5 Sunday. Behrens has been idle for two
months, while Real Quiet ran an outstanding race to win the Pimlico
Special May 8. But if the stopwatch means anything, Behrens will be
one tough customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll find out if he's ready at post time,'' said Bond Friday.
``He's been training very good. It's fair to say that his works
would have been even faster on the main track. I take it one day at
a time. I'm hoping to keep things rolling along. We hope he's
peaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is going according to plan. Horses just do well up
here in the offseason. It's quiet. We have our own private barn and
we're out of the way. No agents. No racing secretaries to bother
you. The Oklahoma training track is a little more consistent. It
tends to stay in better shape when you don't have to run races on
it. The better stakes horses just seem to do really well over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Behrens, a 5-year-old son of Pleasant Colony, has made a great
comeback from a dismal 1998 in which he lost all four starts after
a promising sophomore season. Last year Behrens was beaten twice by
Horse of the Year Skip Away at Gulfstream, then ran fifth behind
Silver Charm, trained by Baffert, in the $4 million Dubai World Cup
March 28. Bond put Behrens on the shelf until the Brooklyn at
Belmont June 13, but when he ran ninth in that event, veterinarians
went over him with a fine-tooth comb and discovered he had a
hairline fracture of the left hock. They stabilized the fracture
with a pin, and Behrens was back.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a real good 3-year-old (he won the Pegasus and lost the
Travers by a nose to Deputy Commander), but he was a little lacking
in experience,'' said Bond. ``He's getting better now with every
start. Last year there was a horse named Skip Away who put quite a
few horses on the sidelines. When Behrens came up with the hock
injury, we gave him a lot of time off. The owners (Rudlein Stable
and William Clifton) deserve credit. They could have retired him,
but the doctors gave us a pretty good prognosis. He went to Florida
and blossomed.''
</P>
<P>
   On paper, the MassCap lacks early speed. It appears Behrens, who
has a nifty turn of foot, can just fall out on the lead. If jockey
Jorge Chavez so chooses, Behrens can easily dictate the pace, which
is always an advantage. However, Bond is loath to discuss strategy.
``We'll see what develops,'' said Bond. ``I'm going to leave that
up to Jorge. We'll watch and see how the races go. Behrens is very
versatile, but you never know how things are going to come up.''
</P>
<P>
   Bond, 41, is the son of a trainer. He took out his trainer's
license when he was just 16 and has had some nice horses, including
Will's Way, who won the Travers in 1996 and the Whitney in '97.
Bond entered Will's Way in the 1997 MassCap, and while he ran well,
he could do no better than third behind Skip Away and Formal Gold.
This year there is a special buzz to the 60th running of the
MassCap because Real Quiet is the first Derby winner to run at
Suffolk since Riva Ridge, Secretariat's stablemate, won New
England's premier race in 1973. But Bond is less impressed with
having a horse who has worn the garland of roses in the field than
the media or the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really, personally, a big thing to me,'' said Bond.
``It would be a big thing to some people, but running against Skip
Away was more exciting. That's just my feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert and Real Quiet have won the week, but Bond and Behrens
can still win the race and take back the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some ideas on where I would like to run Behrens next,''
said Bond. ``Nothing is etched in stone, but the bottom line is the
Breeders' Cup (at Gulfstream Nov. 6). Saturday, Behrens gets the
acid test, and we'll see if he's as good as we think he is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Behrens will be vanned down to Suffolk this morning. Real Quiet
and British invader Running Stag, considered the other legitimate
MassCap threat, continued to stretch their legs over the East
Boston oval Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet was on the muscle and galloped 1 1/2 miles strongly
under exercise rider Larry Damore. ``He was very aggressive this
morning,'' said Baffert, who watched the move. ``He's a difficult
horse to ride, but Gary (Stevens, who will ride in the MassCap)
knows how to handle him.''
</P>
<P>
   Running Stag went a mile in the traditional European style,
under a tight hold from assistant trainer Roger Teal. ``My horse
just looks super today,'' said Richard Cohen, owner of Running
Stag. ``He just went out for a little trot this morning, and he
went real easy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
