<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5457 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICAN-HEBREWS-BOS &LR;      05-28 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICAN-HEBREWS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACK HEBREWS FIND REDEMPTION IN ISRAEL'S SELECTION FOR FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Sweet and soulful, the voices of Gabriel and Eddie
Butler resonate with a sound straight out of Chicago's South Side.
</P>
<P>
   The two brothers' now live here far from their Chicago roots and
are proud to be representing Israel Saturday night in the
international Eurovision song contest, a kind of Super Bowl of
Euro-pop watched by 300 million television viewers worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   But there's this one little problem. Even though the Butlers are
good enough to be crowned Israel's ambassadors of pop, the Israeli
government doesn't recognize them as citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The Butlers are members of the African Hebrew Israelites of
Jerusalem, a community of African-American families who made their
exodus out of Chicago's South Side in the late 1960s through
Western Africa to the Holy Land.
</P>
<P>
   The roughly 2,000 members of this community who live in Israel
today are strictly observant followers of Orthodox Judaism and see
themselves as the ``true children of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   But Israel's Interior Ministry doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the 1970s and 1980s the group, commonly known as the
Black Hebrews, was labeled a cult by the Israeli government. It was
accused of running a criminal enterprise that included credit card
fraud. In the 1990s its image slowly improved and Israeli officials
now tolerate the group enough to provide tourist or temporary
resident visas.
</P>
<P>
   American government officials here speak glowingly of how the
Black Hebrews have transformed their community and the US Agency
for International Development has provided development grants to
assist them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I live here and I have a strong love for this country. We are
Israelites,'' said Gabriel Butler, 34, who came with his family to
Jerusalem from a South Side ghetto when he was 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are Israeli in the soul. Yes, over the years there have
been problems. We haven't always been treated right,'' he said,
sipping lemonade in the executive lounge of a five-star hotel next
to the sound stage where Eurovision will be held.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's all water under the bridge,'' he added, flashing a
serene smile.
</P>
<P>
   On the 30th anniversary of the Black Hebrews arrival in
Jerusalem _ which they see as fulfilment of a divine prophecy _ the
community is brimming with pride that Israel is represented in
Eurovision by two of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Many Israeli cultural commentators and the community itself see
the brothers' band, ``Eden,'' as an expression of acceptance in a
part of Israeli culture, if not a part of its citizenry.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the intolerance the Israeli government has
shown his community and a history of Israeli opression of millions
of displaced Palestinians, Gabriel shrugs his shoulders and smiles.
``A lot of those images come from CNN, but are not necessarily the
truth. We have Arab friends, and Jewish friends, and we see people
working together. I've seen both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``The image of Israel is of bullets whizzing by, but it's not
like that. Look at America. The image on CNN is that it's a great
and peaceful country. But we know that is where the bullets are
whizzing by in poor neighborhoods in Chicago,'' said Gabriel, his
voice rising to a preacher's cadence.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Hebrews arrived in Jerusalem in 1969 after passing
through two years in Liberia. To avoid an international scandal of
trying to deport them, the Israeli government gave them tourist
visas and dumped them in Dimonah, a dusty town next to a nuclear
facility on the edge of the Negev desert.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Hebrews claim descendency from the tribes of
Israelites. They believe their ancestors were forced out of the
Holy Land by the Roman Empire to Western Africa before they were
sold as slaves to America.
</P>
<P>
   The sect emerged out of the fires of rioting in Chicago in the
mid 1960s and the fiery tradtion of ``Black Hebrewism.'' In Black
Baptist and Methodist churches many slaves and their descendants
identified with the biblical stories of the exodus. It was a belief
echoed in yearning Christian spirituals that sang of the Jordan
River and the Land of Canaan.
</P>
<P>
   The Butler brothers' father, Prince Gabriel Butler, is one of
the community's founding fathers. As a busdriver in Chicago in the
1960s, the senior Butler loved Sam Cooke, the Persuasions, and
gospel music. He began attending the South Side storefront church
of Ben Ammi Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Following Carter to Israel, the Butler patriarch, now 62,
brought his old record player and R&AMP;B albums with him. So the
younger Gabriel and Eddie and their seven siblings were raised in a
home that observed the Torah, but moved to Motown.
</P>
<P>
   The children sang in a choir that the community formed at its
own schools. Five siblings formed a band that performed at weddings
and parties to earn money for a community that struggled in poverty
since members were not granted work visas.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Butlers formed Eden. The band, which also
includes two Sabras, or Israeli-born Jews, describes itself in
promotional material as ``a blending of cultures, black and white,
Israeli and American.''
</P>
<P>
   After winning the Jewish state's spot in the annual Eurovision
contest, Eden will compete against 23 other contestants. Although
Eurovision draws a blank for most Americans, it can be a
career-maker to win; at least it was for Abba, Julio Iglesias, and
Celine Dion.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Israel's Dana International, a transvestite, won the
contest with a pulsating club tune called ``Diva.'' This year Dana
_ whose stardom has stirred the ire of Israel's ultra-Orthodox _ is
hosting the event.
</P>
<P>
   Eden, which sounds a bit like Boyz2Men, sings in Hebrew and
English and will be performing their song ``Birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   The song title, Butler says, is an almost mystically vague
reference to the 50th anniversary of Israel, the turn of the
millennium and the 30th anniversary of the Black Hebrews' arrival.
The song's theme is appropriate for the backdrop to the stage,
which is done up in a sureal millennial motif that features a
laser-lit sun at center stage and 7,000 blinking lights to create a
canopy of stars in the desert night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
