<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-ROOKIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rookies ready to roll at Indy
 &HT;    By Dave Lance
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS - It was his first start in the Indianapolis 500
and one of Jack Hewitt's main concerns during last season's race
was getting in a veteran's way and having a negative impact on the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, who lives in Troy, managed to avoid hitting anyone and
finished 12th.
</P>
<P>
   John Hollansworth Jr., who will be making his first Indy 500
start on Sunday, hopes to at least match Hewitt's success, but
isn't overly worried about keeping a low profile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike Jack, this isn't my first IRL (Indy Racing League)
race,'' Hollansworth Jr. said. ``We've had the good fortune of
being able to run in Orlando, Phoenix and Charlotte. With three
under my belt, I hope that's a calming force.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollansworth Jr., 35, is the oldest rookie in the race and also
the fastest, having qualified in 221.698 mph (12th starting
position). He will be joined in the race by three other rookies:
Jeret Schroeder (220.747, 21st position), Robby McGehee (220.139,
27th) and Wim Eyckmans (220.092, 29th).
</P>
<P>
   All four agreed they've never been so excited for a race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say that I've never been so darn excited to qualify
so far back in a field,'' McGehee said. ``This is the race, the
biggest race. It means everything to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Qualifying for the race was especially gratifying to
Hollansworth Jr., whose experience at the Indianapolis Motor
Speedway the last two weeks has been a family affair. One of his
brothers is his spotter and his dad has been here everyday,
watching his son's every move.
</P>
<P>
   Hollansworth Sr. knows a little bit about racing, having driven
Indy cars in 1966 and '67, but never qualifying for the
Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   In his honor, Hollansworth Jr. is racing in car No. 42, just
like his dad did.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be here is obviously the pinnacle of my motorsports career
to date,'' Hollansworth Jr. said, ``and hopefully it will only be
eclipsed by ... what happens on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   After a talk with Indy 500 qualifier Steve Knapp, Schroeder is
setting his sights high Sunday. Knapp told Schroeder he doesn't
have to be in the front row to do well at Indy and he should know.
As a rookie last season, Knapp started the race in the 23rd
position and ended third.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier to start in the front, but this is a race of
attrition,'' Schroeder said. ``Anyone can win it. There's a lot of
car breakdowns and there's a lot of accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to treat this like any other event and not let
myself get too excited. If I do, it'll be difficult to get any
sleep and that's dangerous to your chances. I'm going to try to
have a clean race. If I do that, I know we'll finish well.''
</P>
<P>
   If Eyckmans finishes well, he'll have teammate Eddie Cheever Jr.
to partially thank. Cheever Jr. won Indy last season and over the
past two weeks has shared his knowledge of the racetrack with the
rookie.
</P>
<P>
   But like the three other newcomers, Eyckmans is on his own
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never so nervous before in my life like I was last
Sunday (Bubble Day),'' Eyckmans said. ``I'm so happy that I made
the race and I will see how it feels in the race on Sunday. It's
only my fourth race in three years and it's my second oval race.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I will see how it works and where we finish.
</P>
<P>
   Lance writes for the Dayton Daily News
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
