<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-LAWSUIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coke seeks class-action dismissal
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Coca-Cola asked a federal judge Friday to dismiss
parts of a racial discrimination suit that would enable the
plaintiffs to seek class-action status.
</P>
<P>
   A ruling in Coca-Cola's favor would mean four current and former
workers who filed the suit would not be able to add another 1,500
black salaried employees as plaintiffs in a class-action case.
</P>
<P>
   They could still continue the lawsuit on their own behalf, but
class-action status is crucial to expanding the case into a broader
review of Coca-Cola's record as a minority employer.
</P>
<P>
   In their lawsuit, the plaintiffs allege the beverage giant has
engaged in a companywide practice of discriminating against
African-Americans in pay, promotions, performance evaluations and
terminations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite these broad brushstrokes and general references to
discriminatory practices, the named plaintiffs' and prospective
class members' claims have virtually no commonality, other than the
race of their proponents,'' Coca-Cola argued in its dismissal
motion.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the company said, the case would break down into a
``series of mini-trials'' with a wide variety of circumstances that
are inappropriate for class-action treatment.
</P>
<P>
   But plaintiffs' attorney Cyrus Mehri suggested the company's
motion shows Coca-Cola's insensitivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The class-action device has been an important tool to advance
civil rights for a long time,'' Mehri said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will fight to the bitter end to protect the rights of our
clients and other African-Americans to bring employment
discrimination class actions against employers. We will do
everything in our power to prevent Coca-Cola from turning back the
clock on the rights of African-Americans and others.''
</P>
<P>
   Mehri will soon file a formal challenge to the company's motion.
Then U.S. District Judge Richard Story of Atlanta will decide the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   The company also asked Story to postpone discovery, or
information gathering in the case, until he rules on the dismissal
request, which could take weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the judge rules against Coca-Cola, the plaintiffs still
must convince him later that the suit, filed April 22, merits
class-action status. That decision would only be made after months
of information gathering by both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the plaintiffs filed a motion asking the
judge to order Coca-Cola to notify all employees that the company
cannot retaliate against them for participating in the suit.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs in the case are administrative assistant Motisola
Malikha Abdallah, security officer Gregory Allen Clark, consumer
information specialist Linda Ingram and former director Kimberly
Gray Orton.
</P>
<P>
   Unger writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
