<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5467 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHICAGO-HOUSING-NYT &LR;      05-28 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICAGO-HOUSING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHICAGO REGAINS CONTROL OF PUBLIC HOUSING FROM U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The city of Chicago regained control of its Housing
Authority this week, four years after widespread mismanagement in
the agency caused the federal government to take it over.
</P>
<P>
   The change comes at a time when public housing across the
country is facing a dramatic overhaul, as cities tear down decrepit
and dangerous high-rises and try to move residents into better
housing in better neighborhoods. Nowhere is that goal more daunting
than in Chicago, where the high-rises have become poverty-plagued
and drug-ravaged ghettos and the city wants to demolish 11,000
apartments, nearly 40 percent of its public housing for families.
</P>
<P>
   With the withdrawal of the Department of Housing and Urban
Development, Mayor Richard Daley is seeking to take control of the
public housing system in much the same way as he has the city's
public school system, where he has restructured failing schools in
a relatively successful effort to raise student achievement.
</P>
<P>
   He has appointed as chief executive officer of the Housing
Authority a high-ranking school board official, and is filling key
positions at the agency with staff from City Hall. He will also
nominate seven of the 10 Housing Authority board members (the
remaining three will be nominated by public housing residents).
</P>
<P>
   Daley will also try to persuade HUD to relax certain rules so
that Chicago can have even more autonomy over its public housing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central thing we're trying to do is to get as much
flexibility as possible,'' John Camper, the mayor's deputy press
secretary, said Friday. ``What we want to do is be able to use the
money to solve the problems, rather than meet specific federal
regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   One proposal in a plan that will be presented to HUD in a few
months could involve asking HUD to allow Chicago to change the way
that rent is calculated in the housing projects, Camper said. For
the last 30 years, tenants have paid a percentage of their income,
a policy that caused thousands of working families to leave public
housing rather than see their rents continually increase while
tenants on welfare paid nothing. Chicago may ask to place a cap on
rent to keep working people as tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Daley is also considering leasing public housing buildings to
private developers, who would manage them. And, at a news
conference on Thursday, he said he wanted to provide residents with
more social services, like day care, job training and drug
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most difficult challenges will be relocating families
who live in the buildings slated for demolition. The goal is to
break up the huge concentrations of poor blacks and move them to
working-class and middle-income neighborhoods in the city. But so
far, most people who have moved out have simply settled in other
poor, predominantly black neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   While the Chicago Housing Authority's fiscal accountability and
management operations were considerably improved during its four
years of federal stewardship, the city still inherits a lumbering
bureaucracy. And given the Housing Authority's history of
corruption and mismanagement, the return to city control is fraught
with potential minefields. In fact, the Housing Authority's Police
Department is under investigation by the Justice Department for
possible misuse of federal grants.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge task,'' Daley said of the changeover at a news
conference on Thursday. ``It won't happen overnight. It will take
years to complete. We all must be willing to experiment and learn
as we go.''
</P>
<P>
   The new chief executive officer, Phillip Jackson, 48, grew up in
public housing. He worked his way up from a stock boy to vice
president for store operations at the now-defunct bookstore chain,
Kroch's &AMP; Brentano's. He served in the city's budget department
before becoming chief of staff for the Chicago public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Given his accomplishments, Jackson said at the news conference,
``Some people may look at me and say, `You did pretty good. CHA
must be OK.' But I didn't succeed because of CHA. I succeeded in
spite of CHA.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Success no longer is going to be accidental.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 1942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
