<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No Personal Advice To the Donor Intended &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Microsoft announced that Melinda French Gates, wife
of Bill, had given birth to the couple's second child.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Johns Hopkins University announced that the couple
had donated $20 million for family planning in the developing
world.
</P>
<P>
   An adviser to a Gates family foundation said that the timing of
the family planning announcement, so close to the birth
announcement, was accidental. Approval of the grant to train
foreign health workers at Johns Hopkins had been made some time
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the grantee is notified of the award, they choose the
time to announce it,'' said Dr. Gordon W. Perkin, a global health
expert at the William H. Gates Foundation in Seattle. ``It becomes
entirely disconnected to any event, certainly, in the personal
lives of the Gateses.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of Gates said he has taken a ``paternity leave''
of about a week to be with his family _ now including Rory John, an
8-pound, 12-ounce boy, and Jennifer, the baby's 3-year-old sister _
at their sprawling lakeside home in Medina, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, the founder and chairman of Microsoft, holds company
stock worth about $80 billion. He has said that his children will
get only a small part of his wealth and that most of it will be
given away.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Kelley &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nourishing the Mungers &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like his friend Gates, Warren E. Buffett, the chairman of
Berkshire Hathaway, plans to give away most of his wealth. Charles
T. Munger, the vice chairman of Berkshire, has a different plan.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett _ estimated to be worth $36 billion, second in America
only to Gates _ has said that he will use most of his assets to set
up a private foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``With regard to inheritances: I'm a big believer in
meritocracy,'' Buffett said at the company's annual meeting in
Omaha recently. ``I don't believe that people should get a big head
start on life because of what womb they came from.''
</P>
<P>
   Munger, on the other hand, pointed approvingly to the
Rockefellers and what they have done with large inheritances. As
for his smaller but still not inconsiderable wealth, Munger, who
holds $1.3 billion in Berkshire stock, said that he would give his
money to his children.
</P>
<P>
   The facts of each family are different, Munger said. For
example, he said in a telephone interview, Buffett has ``got three
children, and I have eight.''
</P>
<P>
   David Barboza &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Upper East Side Story &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When you're Robert A.M. Stern, dean of the Yale School of
Architecture, and someone plans a condo tower blocking the view
from your Upper East Side apartment, what do you do? First, you
join Tony Randall and others to protest.
</P>
<P>
   When that fails, you design your own high-rise nearby and move
there. Stern will live in the 34-story Chatham condominium on 85th
Street, at Third Avenue, when it is completed in about a year.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Stern nor the project's developers would say what he was
paid for designing the building or what he is being charged for his
own sixth-floor apartment, with a garden view. At 1,700 square
feet, the standard price would exceed $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't shop around for apartments elsewhere. ``Why would I?''
he said. ``I have the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Rachelle Garbarine &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the Name Alive &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Edsel B. Ford II, who ran the Ford Motor Co.'s car loan division
from 1991 until he stepped down a year ago, is now working on
museums and charities.
</P>
<P>
   One of his projects, the $25 million Spirit of Ford museum,
opens this weekend near the company's headquarters in Dearborn,
Mich., and it emphasizes the future.
</P>
<P>
   Theater seats shake and tilt violently, as the screen follows
the progress of a car through a modern Ford assembly plant. A laser
draws a Mercury car in the air while a crash dummy discusses how
cars are designed.
</P>
<P>
   Ford, 50, carries the name of his late grandfather, for whom an
unsuccessful car was named in 1957. Active in more than a dozen
charities, he remains on the Ford Motor board. A cousin, William C.
Ford Jr., 42, won the chairmanship late last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my main areas of focus right now is to do what I can to
celebrate the heritage of Ford Motor Co.,'' Edsel Ford said. Next:
more preparations for Ford's centennial in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Bradsher &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
