<HEADER>
A5477 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PRINCIPALS-VIOLENCE-A     05-28 1211
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRINCIPALS-VIOLENCE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 HIGH SCHOOL PRINCIPALS ADJUST TO LIFE AFTER LITTLETON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEDFORD, N.Y. _ Dick Kraemer, the principal at Fox Lane High
School here, was on the phone in his office when his worst
nightmare suddenly flared to life: An assistant principal rushed in
to say there was a ticking bomb in a student's locker down the
hall.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, Tom Readyoff, the principal at Mahopac High
School, 12 miles north of Fox Land High School, was handed an
anonymous note, found on the floor by a student, warning that bombs
had been planted throughout the school.
</P>
<P>
   And about a week later, Bill Colavito, the principal at White
Plains (N.Y.) High School, came face to face with this message
scrawled in chalk on a classroom blackboard: ``A bomb is going to
go off at 12 o'clock.''
</P>
<P>
   None of the threats turned out to be real: The ticking at Fox
Lane High was from a toy, and the two bomb warnings were pranks.
But the schools' principals _and their counterparts around the
country _ point to incidents like these as clear signs that after
Littleton, Colo., their jobs may never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the April 20 massacre at Columbine High School in
Littleton and other tragedies in recent years were aberrations,
high school principals say that instances of school violence have
made them fundamentally rethink what it means to be a principal. No
longer just academics and administrators, the principals say they
are now acting more like psychologists, drill sergeants, prison
wardens, even field medics.
</P>
<P>
   They deal swiftly and harshly with even the most innocuous
student misbehavior, enforcing ``zero tolerance'' campaigns to
confront insensitivity and diagnose any potential for violence.
They have also broadened their schools' missions, creating programs
to encourage teachers to befriend and counsel their pupils, not
just drill them, all the while keeping a wary eye out for whoever
might be the next unnoticed mass murderer.
</P>
<P>
   Until a month ago, Kraemer of Fox Lane High said, the trend in
American high schools was to treat principals like product
managers, teachers like foremen and students like high-end product.
``In some ways, we innocently believed that schools could be purely
focused on academics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But academics were far from Kraemer's mind when he ordered all
930 Fox Lane students onto the school's football field while police
investigated the ticking-toy incident. All he could think about
then, he said, was, ``I've got kids on a football field who are
sitting ducks for someone in the woods with a long-range rifle.''
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, he said, such dark thoughts were the province of
guerrilla leaders, not high-school principals.
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone. ``What may have been taken in the past as
hyperbole we now take very seriously,'' said Colavito, slowly
making his rounds through White Plains High's teeming hallways
during a lunch hour.
</P>
<P>
   At Mahopac High, Readyoff has imposed a virtual lockdown at the
hint of the simplest student misdeed, instructing teachers to
challenge lunch-room line cutters or any foul language muttered in
passing. One student's desktop doodle about a bomb, just the kind
of foible that not long ago would have been treated with a sponge
and shake of the head, provoked Readyoff to call the student's
parents and a school psychologist, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the usual routines of many principals have
been disrupted. After catching wind of a rumor that the sister of
an unnamed male athlete at Mahopac High had found a black rose with
a note that read ``you're next'' stuffed into her locker, Readyoff
spent his day methodically tracking down and interviewing every
female student with a brother on a school sports team, only to
discover the rumor to be nothing more than that: a rumor.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the while you're doing this you have this sense that
there's nothing there,'' Readyoff said, voicing a common sentiment
among high-school principals. ``But it all ties into this fear in
the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Many school officials say that Littleton struck a raw nerve in
suburban high schools that have long felt immune to the violence
and threats of violence that are facts of life in many city
schools. While the Arkansas and Kentucky school shootings that
preceded Littleton were passed off as aberrations, after Littleton
``It was really logical for us to say, `God, that could happen
here,''' Kraemer said at Fox Lane High, an affluent school set into
the sylvan hills of northern Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   ``The previous ones did not capture the attention of our
students and our faculty,'' Kraemer said.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing like community fear, Colavito said, to motivate
principals to change how they do their jobs. ``Any time there is a
crisis in a society, schools are the first place people look to
solve the problem,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted how, in the 1950s, school-based driver education
started as a way to curb rising traffic fatalities among young
people. In the 1980s, schools became conduits for a national
antidrug campaign. To address the current crisis, Kraemer, a former
physics teacher whose experience in the 1970s included a real bomb
that blew up part of a school roof, plans to foster closer
relationships between teachers and students.
</P>
<P>
   At Mahopac High, Readyoff shook his head as he recalled how one
of the teachers in the high school he attended made bad students
wear dunce caps and sit in the corner. Soon he plans to implement a
classroom program to allow teachers and the 1,400 students at his
school to discuss the importance of respect for one's peers, no
matter how different they may be. ``There has to be time set aside
for teachers to talk about these things,'' he said. ``That
awareness is out there now among young people, and we have to help
that keep going. We can't just let it die off.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be other ideas and programs to help principals in the
post-Littleton era, no doubt. Indeed, many school administrators
are already being flooded with direct-marketing fliers offering
books, software and seminars, all with same theme: stemming school
violence.
</P>
<P>
   But no software or seminar will be able to recoup what many
principals believe could be a permanent loss of innocence in
American high schools. At Fox Lane High, evidence of that loss was
evident in the image of armor-plated bomb squad specialists
tiptoeing up to a student locker packed with a harmless toy.
</P>
<P>
   In Mahopac, the evidence lay in the harsh punishment given to
the student who wrote the anonymous bomb threat: suspension from
school the remainder of this year _ and all of next year, too.
</P>
<P>
   And in White Plains, a lost age of innocence was the subtext of
the school's decision to hand over the investigation of the
spurious bomb threat to the city's Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be joy in school,'' Kraemer said. ``If you can't
have joy in school, you can't have a human connection,'' he said.
``I have a feeling that those two boys in Littleton did not have
joy in school.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
