A5479 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-AR     05-28 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN INTEL BE AS NIMBLE AS IT IS BIG? 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
(af) 
By KENNETH N. GILPIN  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors who have chosen to leave the stock of Intel Corp. out
of their portfolios have missed a lucrative ride.
</P>
<P>
   Figure: By the end of 1998, a $100 investment made five years
earlier in Intel, the semiconductor giant, was worth $805. If the
investment had been made in 1988 instead, the '98 total would have
been $4,210. And day traders take note: anyone who bought $100
worth of Intel at its initial public offering in 1972 and held on
would have seen the investment grow to $162,338 by the end of last
year.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers have shrunk since then, because Intel's stock
has stumbled over the last few months. The shares are down nearly 9
percent so far this year amid rumblings on Wall Street that Intel's
days as a bellwether technology stock may be numbered.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Slater, principal analyst at Cahners Microdesign
Resources, a Sebastopol, Calif., firm that publishes technology
industry newsletters, took some time last week to discuss the
company and the challenges it faces. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)For years, Intel has been one of the stock market's
most visible, most successful growth stocks. Is that likely to
continue?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. One of the dichotomies about Intel is that its ability to be
the world's most successful semiconductor company and its ability
to have a monotonically increasing stock price are separate.
</P>
<P>
   If Intel's profits dropped by one-third, the stock would go in
the tank. But they would still be the dominant force in the
industry.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty in maintaining the stock price is that the market
wants increasingly higher rates of return. There is no question
that Intel is in an incredibly strong position, but it is also
facing more challenges and underlying change in the environment in
which it does business than it has in a long time. I'm not going to
lose any sleep over Intel's success as a company. But I would not
make any bets on the price of its stock. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)What sort of changes are you talking about?(end
italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Five years ago, the company was totally focused on personal
computers. They are still interested in driving that market, but
they are looking beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   The steady decline in the price of personal computers and
movement toward lower-cost systems is putting pressure on Intel to
maintain its average selling price of $225 for microprocessors.
Microprocessors that go into personal computers that cost under
$1,000 sell for $60 to $70, at most.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Intel has been able to maintain enough demand for
high-end microprocessors that they have been able to maintain their
average selling price. But there has to be a lot of concern the
average price will drop. And on a grander scale, there is the
question of how big a part of the world personal computers will be
in the future. I think personal computers will be successful, but
not so dominant as they are today. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Why is that?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Today, about half the homes in this country have personal
computers, and if you want access to the Internet, you buy a
low-cost personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   I think the day is not far off when lots of other products, like
palm organizers or televisions with built-in Web browsers, will
offer lots of access to the Internet. That has the potential to cut
into the future growth of the personal computer market.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Internet access will be as widespread as telephone
and television. I don't believe the personal computer as we know it
today, or as it will evolve over the next five years, can possibly
be the device to provide that sort of access. It has to be far
easier to use, and cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   These are developments which seem to play to areas where Intel
seems weakest. For example, when you look at portable devices,
which I think will be more important, they are not competitive at
all. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Is this to assume that Intel can't make up for a
drop in personal computer demand for microprocessors by supplying
them to another business?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. They are making a big play to become the dominant
microprocessor supplier for servers and work stations. Servers in
particular are a long-term, high-growth market, one that will be
profitable for them.
</P>
<P>
   With the introduction in 2000 of Merced, the first generation of
the IC64 family, they will begin to make a move into the larger
server business. And they have a good chance to become a dominant
supplier in that business. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Looking at the string of Internet-related
acquisitions Intel has made over the last year or so, do you think
they will be able to molt into a different kind of company?(end
italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I wouldn't count them out, but it is a higher-risk strategy.
When they were focusing on just being a supplier of
microprocessors, they could concentrate on a fairly narrow range of
things. Now they are going further and further from their core
competency. But they have great assets, not the least of which is
$10 billion in cash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
