<HEADER>
A5481 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-WITH-ALBERS-AR     05-28 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-WITH-ALBERS-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARLES E. ALBERS: OPPENHEIMER MAIN STREET GROWTH AND INCOME FUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic of Oppenheimer Main Street Growth and Income is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30)  
 (af)  
 By VIRGINIA MUNGER KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In April 1998, Charles E. Albers moved his computer models from
Park Avenue to Main Street. Or, to be more exact, from the Guardian
Park Avenue fund, where he had been manager for 26 years, to Main
Street Income and Growth, managed by the Oppenheimer Funds.
</P>
<P>
   Having beaten the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index by an
average of 3.7 percentage points a year at Guardian, where he was a
pioneer among fund managers in using quantitative methods to pick
stocks, Albers was hired by Oppenheimer to turn around Income and
Growth, which had fallen on hard times.
</P>
<P>
   How is he doing? So far, the results from his Oppenheimer office
in the World Trade Center in Manhattan are encouraging, if not
overwhelming. In the 13 months since he and his associate, Nikolaos
Monoyios, have been in charge, the fund is up 18.2 percent,
substantially ahead of the 13.9 percent average for its peer group
of large-company blend funds.
</P>
<P>
   But the fund _ whose name has been reconfigured to Main Street
Growth and Income, to reflect the managers' emphasis on total
return, not just income _ has trailed the S&AMP;P by 1.4 percentage
points. Performance has weakened in 1999; the fund is up 6.3
percent through May 21, versus 7.2 percent for its peers and 8.7
percent for the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Albers said the gains slowed because he had positioned the fund
to take advantage of the historically strong first-quarter
performance of value-oriented stocks, a phenomenon that failed to
develop this year. ``Although our models are good, they are not
infallible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When Albers started managing money in the 1960s, most stock
pickers had no data-based system, he said. But after studying
econometrics at Columbia University and working at Value Line, he
developed a ranking system that, while primitive, imposed a logic
on his moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like a one-eyed man in the land of the blind,'' the
professorial-looking manager told a recent Morningstar conference
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   That initial model ranked stocks on three factors; he now
considers 15 to 20, from price and earnings momentum to valuation
and special events like stock buybacks. In 1990, when Guardian Park
Avenue was foundering because it was tilted toward small-cap and
value stocks, Albers started using some broad, macroeconomic
factors in his system, to help choose stocks both by market
capitalization and their growth or value bias.
</P>
<P>
   He is still updating his method. ``We're making midcourse
corrections every week,'' he said. ``It's a combination of science
and art.'' The Main Street fund's turnover is 81 percent, versus 63
percent for the average large-cap blend fund.
</P>
<P>
   His recent trimming of his position in Microsoft illustrates how
the system works. Through the end of April, Microsoft was the
fund's biggest holding, at more than 5 percent of the portfolio.
Since then, he has cut it to 3.6 percent, roughly equal to
Microsoft's weighting in the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   He made the change for various reasons: Microsoft is no longer
scoring in the top 10 percent in his screens for likely
outperformers. And his model indicates that a genuine market sea
change may be in the works, finally giving value stocks an
advantage over growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to try to align ourselves with the way of the
universe,'' he said, using a phrase he often repeats.
</P>
<P>
   Among the signals, he said, are an improved picture for
corporate profits; a steepening of the yield curve, which indicates
stronger business conditions ahead, and the very high valuations on
growth stocks like Microsoft, which has a price-to-earnings ratio
of more than 50.
</P>
<P>
   Albers also thinks that the outcome of the government's
antitrust case against Microsoft will be a negative for the stock.
</P>
<P>
   It is too early to tell whether the outperformance of value
stocks over the last month and a half will last, so, Monoyios said,
he and Albers are not making major changes to the fund. ``We want
to see a persistence of factors over the long term,'' Monoyios
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Technology remains a major focus of the fund; IBM is the biggest
holding, at about 4 percent of the portfolio. Albers also finds
Hewlett-Packard attractive. He first bought it in March at $71.35 a
share, and at $94.3125, where it now trades, he still considers it
cheap.
</P>
<P>
   Another big part of the portfolio is in consumer cyclicals,
primarily retailers. Demand remains strong, while many retailers'
costs for labor and goods are flat or falling, he said, resulting
in wider profit margins. Wal-Mart Stores and Home Depot, both of
which had positive earnings surprises recently, are among his top
10 holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Other stocks that he finds attractive in his favorite sectors
are BellSouth in telecommunications and Merck in pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   As Main Street's returns indicate, the big challenge for Albers
and Monoyios will be lifting this leviathan _ with $15 billion in
assets, counting all share classes _ above market averages.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fund is not going to be the No. 1 fund in any one year,
because we don't take those kinds of risks,'' Monoyios said. Still,
he added, ``being consistently good in the short run makes you
excellent in the long run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
