<HEADLINE>
FOR AD AGENCY GIANTS, THE WEATHER IS JUST RIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30)  
 (af)  
 By JOANNE LEGOMSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beneath the patina of economic abundance, business competition
is intensifying. Hard-pressed to fatten profits by cutting costs or
raising prices, companies are pursuing a time-honored alternative _
trying to bolster sales by shoveling money into advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``Businesses hate sinking money into advertising,'' said Mark
Greenberg, manager of the Invesco Leisure fund, which counts some
big ad agency companies among its core holdings. ``But they can't
afford to underspend the other guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year was the fifth in a row that the growth in advertising
spending in the United States outpaced the growth of the economy,
rising 7.1 percent, to $200.8 billion, against a 3.9 percent
increase in the gross domestic product.
</P>
<P>
   That story has not eluded the stock market: The average total
return of the Big Four global agency holding companies _ Omnicom
Group, Interpublic Group, Young &AMP; Rubicam and WPP Group _ was 37.7
percent for the 12 months ending Friday, versus 18.6 percent for
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say there is reason to believe that the stocks haven't
finished their climb. ``Ad stocks have a consistent record of
expanded earnings outperformance late in the economic cycle,'' said
William Bird, an analyst at Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Bird attributes the outperformance to several factors, including
the big agencies' global scope, which limits exposure to any single
country's economy. He also cites flexible cost structures _ meaning
that with staff representing about 60 percent of costs, the big
companies can readily economize by trimming their work forces _ and
their ability to grow through acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, he thinks some of the stocks are relatively cheap, as
illustrated by their PEG ratios _ the projected price-to-earnings
multiple for 2000, divided by longer-term projected earnings growth
rates.
</P>
<P>
   Interpublic, Omnicom and Young &AMP; Rubicam have PEG ratios of 1.8,
2.0 and 1.2, respectively, versus 5.4 for the S&AMP;P 500, Bird said _
much greater discounts than usual. He expects Omnicom, which closed
on Friday at $70, to rise to $83 in 12 to 18 months; Interpublic,
now at $75.75, to hit $88, and Y&AMP;R, now at $38.25, to hit $50.
</P>
<P>
   There are worries, certainly. Lauren Rich Fine, an analyst at
Merrill Lynch, said that any weakening of the global economy could
pose a big risk to ad agency stocks, because corporate advertising
budgets are tied to sales forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   But what some investors do not realize, she added, is that more
agency revenue is coming from recession-resistant services like
public relations and direct marketing. Those businesses now account
for $200 billion of the $417 billion in industry revenue worldwide,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The economic downturn of 1990-91, which contributed to the worst
advertising recession ever, was an aberration, according to Robert
J. Coen, senior vice president and forecasting director at
McCann-Erickson U.S.A., which is owned by Interpublic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies abandoned marginal brands and waged a no-win
strategy of slashing prices to move inventory,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fine is especially bullish on Omnicom. Excluding its growing
portfolio of Internet agencies, she expects the company's earnings
to keep growing 15 percent to 20 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Greenberg, the Invesco manager, also expects agency stocks to
keep generating double-digit earnings growth for the foreseeable
future. Omnicom represents 4 percent of his fund's assets; WPP, 3.3
percent, and Y&AMP;R, 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Whether marketers favor cable, billboards or the Internet, he
said, ``advertising will always be important.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
