<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-5-QUESTIONS-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING CHILDREN FIRST IN A TOY INDUSTRY SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30)  
 (af)  
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week, Toys ``R'' Us and two major toy makers agreed to pay
$50 million in cash and merchandise to settle one of the largest
antitrust cases the toy industry has ever faced. Attorneys general
in 44 states had accused Toys ``R'' Us of using its clout with
manufacturers to keep popular items like Barbie's Dream House and
Fisher Price Nursery Monitors out of warehouse and discount stores.
</P>
<P>
   The office of the New York State attorney general, Eliot L.
Spitzer, took the lead in bringing the case, and Linda Gargiulo, an
assistant attorney general in the antitrust division, was one of
the principal negotiators of the settlement, in which hundreds of
thousands of toys, books and other educational materials will be
distributed to needy children over the next three holiday seasons
through the Marine Corps ``Toys for Tots'' program. None of the
companies admitted any wrongdoing in the settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Toys ``R'' Us agreed to contribute $27 million in toys and pay
$13.5 million, which will be used to buy more toys and educational
products. Mattel agreed to pay $8.2 million in toys and cash, and
Little Tikes will pay $1.3 million in toys and cash. Another
defendant, Hasbro, agreed last December to pay $6 million in toys
and cash.
</P>
<P>
   Next comes the fun part for Ms. Gargiulo's division: monitoring
the settlement, including overseeing which toys are chosen for
distribution. Last week, she discussed the unusual settlement and
how it came about. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Why wasn't the settlement structured to benefit
directly the parties you said were injured _ the warehouse clubs,
discount stores and their customers?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. In a situation like this, it would be very difficult to track
down specific purchasers _ unlike high-ticket items, where there
might be warranty cards or other records.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the amount of alleged overcharge to individual
consumers would be a relatively small amount, and it would be very
costly to the settlement to implement a refund-type program, even
if we could find the purchasers. So in these kinds of situations it
is not unusual to do this type of recovery, to benefit a class as a
whole. We viewed it as a very appropriate way of benefiting the
class to get toys to children. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Why is most of the settlement made up of toy
donations rather than cash penalties?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't know that we would have characterized it that way.
The companies can characterize it as donations or toy
distributions, but what it is is damages: we are recovering damages
for consumers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Given that the damages are tax deductible for the
companies, is there any assurance that they have learned a lesson
from this case?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. They are being required to pay out, in cash and in toys, what
we view as a substantial sum of money. We certainly think that will
have an effect on their future conduct.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there are injunctive provisions in the settlement
which govern their conduct going forward, and require them not to
participate in the type of conspiracy that was alleged here. For
instance, Toys ``R'' Us is enjoined from orchestrating any type of
conspiracy among its manufacturers to limit the supply of products
to clubs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)What were the negotiations like?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. We negotiated on and off over a period of about 10 months. We
did have several mediation sessions, which were conducted by a
former federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement discussions were certainly long and arduous.
Obviously, we started from very different places. When we started,
the defendants were saying they did nothing wrong and were not
really interested in any type of meaningful settlement.
</P>
<P>
   In any settlement process, each side weighs the strength of the
case, the likelihood of prevailing and the length of time and
expense of litigation, and a determination is made whether it makes
sense to end the dispute. Then, after a period of time, an offer is
made. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)How will you oversee the mix of toys that will be
donated and distributed?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. My office will review the toys they specify and make a
determination as to whether they meet the criteria in the
settlement agreement.
</P>
<P>
   We will look for a mix of toys, for quality, currently sold
toys. We will make sure none have been recalled, or any of those
things.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there have to be toys that appeal to both boys and
girls between 3 months and 12 years. The settlement also
specifically provides that no guns be included in the toy
distribution, or any other violent toys.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
