<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5490 &Cx1f; taf-z
s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-L.A.-BILLBOARDS-ART-$     05-28 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-BILLBOARDS-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF BILLBOARDS MAKE IT HERE, THEY'LL MAKE IT ANYWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30)  
 (Eds: This is an added story)  
 (af)  
 By FRANCES ANDERTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For 16 years, the brooding Marlboro Man made of plywood and
paint was the colossus of the Sunset Strip in Los Angeles. But now
that most prominent billboard on the curving avenue of nightclubs
and hotels is gone.
</P>
<P>
   In his place is a parody of Marlboro's icon of machismo: a
cowboy puffing on a limp cigarette, with a vertical message
proclaiming ``Impotent'' and underneath the warning, ``Smoking
Causes Impotence.''
</P>
<P>
   Impotent Man rode into Marlboro Man's territory last month, part
of the agreement by tobacco companies to take down cigarette
billboards across the country in a settlement of lawsuits brought
by 46 states.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-smoking message on a boulevard that has long been a
destination for sinners and sybarites (think John Belushi; think
Hugh Grant and Divine Brown) is the latest in a tradition of
eye-opening billboards in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The city is ground zero for drive-by messages, and the art of
attracting motorists' attention with sharp humor or shock value is
more lustily pursued here than anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often, if an advertiser wants to experiment with something,
they'll run it in L.A. first,'' said Stephen Freitas, the vice
president for marketing of Eller Media, which creates billboard
ads.
</P>
<P>
   Car-bound Angelenos are an affluent, captive audience, and
billboards are tightly woven into the urban fabric, part of the
city's collective memory and conversation. People still talk about
the day last year when traffic was brought to a halt on the 405
freeway by what appeared to be a meteor-shape patch of blue sky in
a 14-story office building. It turned out to be a clever, if
unauthorized sign for the movie ``Armageddon,'' and was soon taken
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billboards and L.A. go together like smog and traffic jams,''
said Bradley Johnson, an editor in Los Angeles for Advertising Age,
the trade magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The sunset of cigarette ads on billboards has meant a new dawn
for the billboard industry, especially in Los Angeles. The
settlement has freed hundreds of prime-location billboards at a
time when the fragmenting of television audiences has drawn
marketers back to outdoor ads.
</P>
<P>
   Rental rates for billboards, which the industry feared would
drop after the loss of tobacco clients, are rising because of new
demand, said Allen Rossi, operations manager of Outdoor Systems
Advertising, which owns the old Marlboro Man billboard.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most eye-catching recent ads promotes a morning radio
DJ named Big Boy. Big Boy is indeed big. Actually, he is hugely
fat, which he celebrates in self-mocking advertisements parodying
Calvin Klein underwear ads.
</P>
<P>
   They show him posing like a sultry model in silk shorts, with
his rolls of fat displayed in all their glory. The billboard reads,
``Morning Obsession,'' echoing a perfume ad. It is simple, funny
and provocative in its unashamed grotesqueness.
</P>
<P>
   Dianna Obermeyer, director of marketing and promotions for Big
Boy's radio station, Power 106 (KPWR at 105.9 FM), designed the ad.
She said the station makes fun of Los Angeles every day on the air.
So what better way to mock the city's ``obsession with image and
body size,'' she said, than to have Big Boy flaunt his 450 pounds?
</P>
<P>
   Poking fun at the Los Angeles life style is also the message of
the local chapter of the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to
Animals. Its billboards mock the dating scene. A big basket of
kittens carries the legend, ``Not Every L.A. Female Is Looking for
an Agent.'' An image of a bulldog embracing a kitten says, ``Some
L.A. Males Just Want to Cuddle.''
</P>
<P>
   Critical Mass, the agency that designed the campaign, also came
up with one for gang-plagued neighborhoods, showing a puppy and a
kitten tussling.
</P>
<P>
   The message is, ``No Kid Ever Shot a Friend While Playing With
One of These.'' Animal adoptions have almost doubled since the
campaign began three years ago, the Los Angeles chapter of the
humane organization says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing more Californian that can tell the story
better or more clearly than the billboard,'' said Scott Svonkin, a
deputy city councilman in West Hollywood, who should know. A month
ago he rented a billboard on Sunset Boulevard proposing marriage to
Jennifer Shapiro. She accepted.
</P>
<P>
   On the Sunset Strip, where boards rent from $30,000 to $100,000
a month, rival movie and television studios show off their latest
hit or star to one another on adjacent boards. And one of the most
famous local celebrities is Angelyne, who first rented a billboard
in Hollywood in 1984, put an image of her voluptuous baby doll self
on it and has never looked back.
</P>
<P>
   Angelyne, who can occasionally be spotted driving around
Hollywood in one of her three pink Corvettes, does not act, sing or
dance but has become a celebrity solely by her cleverly
orchestrated 15-year billboard campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The future is rosy in Los Angeles as far as billboard companies
are concerned. Digital technology promises new signage
possibilities. Under construction now on the Sunset Strip,
incorporated into a newsstand and cafe development, is a
large-screen, 25-by-18-foot video monitor, like a huge television
screen, which will broadcast round-the-clock ads.
</P>
<P>
   Other innovations include ``tall walls,'' which are giant images
_ more than 5,000 square feet, and many stories high _ that are
hung or painted on the sides of buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the city's outdoor signs, as brash and
self-promoting as Los Angeles itself, are cherished by some, to
many others they are simply eyesores.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great if they banned them all,'' said Richard
Holguin, the executive officer of the city's Building and Safety
Department.
</P>
<P>
   No law prohibits signs on commercial streets, although there are
rules regulating size, height and materials. This month, the city
council passed his department's measure to ban ``inflatables,'' the
jolly blowup dinosaurs, balloons, hippos and other creatures that
advertise auto dealerships and the like and are synonymous with Los
Angeles car culture.
</P>
<P>
   John Chase, the urban designer for West Hollywood, the city that
controls the Sunset Strip, said, ``In Southern California, there's
a real confusion about how to deal with the commercial
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   While some see the proliferation of head-turning billboards as
urban blight, others defend them as a car-based culture's authentic
art. ``Personally, I think I've glamorized billboards,'' Angelyne
said. ``I've made them dreamy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
