<HEADLINE>
INVESTING DIGEST, WITH FUNDS WATCH AND MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30)  
 (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No Rush To Upgrade Internet Stocks &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's been a black spring for Internet stocks, with the Bloomberg
Internet Index falling 26.5 percent since its high on April 13. But
are Wall Street analysts slapping ``buy'' signs on the
reduced-price merchandise? Not especially, according to the First
Call Corp. of Boston, which tracks analysts' recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, First Call looked at the changes in analysts'
recommendations for 10 large Internet stocks since April 13. They
found that of the 19 changes since then, 9 have been positive and
10 negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite these stocks' being down, analysts don't appear to be
ready to pull the trigger and get more aggressive on these
stocks,'' said Chuck Hill, the director of research at First Call.
``And that's probably because they're already quite bullish on
these stocks to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10 stocks First Call examined were Amazon.com, America
Online, Mind-Spring, Lycos, Excite, Yahoo, Ebay, At Home, CMGI and
Doubleclick. According to Hill, the 10 stocks now carry an average
recommendation of 1.6, on a scale of 1 to 5, with 1 representing a
``strong buy'' and 5 a ``strong sell.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 13, the average consensus recommendation on the 10
Internet stocks was 1.7. (By contrast, he said, the average
consensus recommendation for stocks in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 is
2.2.)
</P>
<P>
   Zacks.com, a Chicago research firm, said the ``strong buys''
that analysts have on the Internet stocks it tracks have remained
flat since the end of March at about 37 percent of total Internet
stock recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Sana Siwolop &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An Irish IPO Is Smiling As a Nation Lines Up for Shares &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ireland, it seems, is one nation that needs no lessons when it
comes to working up an appetite for a hot new issue.
</P>
<P>
   One-third of the Irish population is seeking to buy shares of
Telecom Eireann, the country's largest phone company, a person
familiar with the sale estimated.
</P>
<P>
   By Friday's deadline, according to that estimate, 1.2 million
people out of the population of 3.7 million would have
preregistered to buy shares of the state-controlled company.
Preregistration entitles individuals to a preferential allocation
of shares when they are sold later this month in an offering worth
about $2 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The share sale is scheduled to start in mid-June, with the order
period for individuals closing on June 30. If the government sticks
to this timetable, the shares will be priced on July 6 or 7, the
person said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts, however, said no more than 45 percent of those
registering for shares were likely to buy them once a price was
announced.
</P>
<P>
   (Bloomberg News) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUNDS WATCH
</P>
<P>
   Domini's Proxy Votes Are an Open Book &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ever wonder how your fund manager voted on proxy issues that may
or may not have a direct effect on a company's bottom line? Domini
Social Investments, a New York money management firm and adviser to
the $995 million Domini Social Equity fund, has begun providing
such information over its Web site, www.domini.com.
</P>
<P>
   The site details the firm's pending and past proxy votes as they
pertain to each of the 400 companies in the fund's portfolio.
Visitors can click on any of the stocks listed, read a description
of the issue being voted on and see where the fund stands. Domini
plans to post its intentions about two weeks before each company's
annual meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of proxy vote disclosure has been something of pet
cause for Domini. In 1992, it began disclosing in semiannual
reports how it would vote its proxies on a variety of issues. And
in 1996, it published guidelines for its proxy voting procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is shocking that proxy voting decisions are generally not
disclosed to shareholders,'' said Amy Domini, managing principal of
the firm. ``We believe that shareholders have an absolute right to
know how their fund managers are voting their shares. Fund managers
are not the ultimate owners of the assets.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund has been evolving into something of a corporate gadfly,
helping to file eight resolutions this year alone. And the fund is
persistent. Since 1996, it has filed a resolution every year asking
the H.B. Fuller Co., the specialty chemical maker, to stop sales of
glue to the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Teitelbaum &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
