<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS CAUTIOUS AS DOW DROPS 2.5 PERCENT FOR WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By EDWARD WYATT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After rising relentlessly for more than two months,
the Dow Jones industrial average has given up a portion of its
gains in the last three weeks as investors begin to worry that
cyclical stocks that seemed underpriced at the end of winter might
be heading into the summer having risen too far or too fast.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect that the Federal Reserve Board might raise interest
rates in a pre-emptory move against an overheating economy, and the
inflation that it might bring, has also put a crimp in some
investors' hopes for industrial companies like Alcoa, International
Paper and Caterpillar.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a gain of 92.81 points Friday, the Dow Jones industrial
average lost 2.5 percent of its value this week, finishing at
10,559.74. That was the worst one-week decline in the Dow since
mid-January, and it left the industrial average roughly 5 percent
below its peak of 11,107.19, reached on May 13.
</P>
<P>
   Even after those declines, however, the bellwether market index
was still 15 percent ahead of where it started the year. Trading
was relatively slow Friday on the New York Stock Exchange, with
657.8 million shares changing hands, among the lowest totals this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Other market indexes, which did not benefit as much from
investors' spring obsession with cyclical stocks, also fell this
week. The Nasdaq composite index, which gained 51.37, to 2,470.52
Friday, nevertheless dropped 2 percent of its value this week as
Internet-related stocks continued their recent declines. The Nasdaq
index is up 12.67 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 20.43, to 1,301.84,
Friday but also lost 2.1 percent for the week. And the Russell 2000
index, which gained 5.76 points, to 438.68 Friday and which had
risen 14 percent the previous two months, fell 2.3 percent this
week. Those indexes have gained 5.9 percent and 4.5 percent,
respectively, since Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a fairly remarkable run over the last eight
months,'' said Michael Clark, head of U.S. equity trading at Credit
Suisse First Boston. ``I always find it a little peculiar when
people then try to search for an answer when we're off 5 percent.
The market has been very efficient over the last three to four
years at backing off when things got a little too far ahead of
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark acknowledged that several factors seemed to be weighing
heavily enough on investors that they were not eager to go into the
three-day Memorial Day weekend without some hedges against
potential losses. Among them is continued uncertainty about the
progress of the battles in Yugoslavia, including the possibility of
a ground war involving American troops.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a plentiful supply of new stock offerings has
continued to come to market, tipping the balance for some investors
to an oversupply of shares and not enough buyers, Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   The recent declines in the Dow industrials and most other
indexes retrace only a portion of recent gains. After rising in
nine of 10 weeks from the end of February through mid-May, the Dow
industrial average has fallen in each of the last three weeks.
Those declines date to the May 13 announcement that Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin would resign and include last week's
announcement by the Federal Reserve that it might raise interest
rates if it continues to see signs of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   The list of Dow stocks that gained the most this spring almost
perfectly matches the list of losers in the last three weeks.
Alcoa, for example, rose from $40.50 to $63.875 from Feb. 28
through May 7, a gain of more than 57 percent; in the last three
weeks, the shares have fallen back to $55, a 14 percent decline.
Shares of Allied Signal, DuPont and Goodyear Tire and Rubber have
followed similar trajectories.
</P>
<P>
   Interest rates, which have generally been climbing since the
beginning of the year, have risen more sharply in recent weeks. On
Friday, the price of the 30-year Treasury bond rose 9/32, to 91
29/32. The bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction,
fell slightly, to 5.82 percent from 5.84 percent on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most active stocks on American markets Friday,
Microsoft gained 2 5/16, to 80 11/16, making it the single biggest
contributor to the day's gain in the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo gained 14 5/8, to 148, with most of the gain coming after
the company announced that in completing its purchase of Geocities
it had dismissed about 200 of that company's employees, or 63
percent of the Geocities' total. Yahoo will take a $68 million
pretax charge in the second quarter related to the acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Paine Webber, which will become part of the S&AMP;P 500 index after
the close of trading on June 4, rose 2 9/16, to 47. Paine Webber
will replace Bankers Trust, which is being acquired by Deutsche
Bank, in the index. The announcement of its addition to the popular
index usually bolsters a company's stock price, as buyers and
speculators rush to buy the shares in the hope that more buying
will come from large investors who track the index.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest stock in American markets continued to be Starmedia,
which Friday gained 13 3/8, to 58 7/8. Starmedia, an online network
whose content is aimed at Spanish and Portuguese speakers in Latin
America, completed an initial public offering of 7 million shares
on Wednesday. The shares, offered at $15, finished the first day at
just over $26. On Thursday, the shares gained another 75 percent,
to $45.50.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
