<SLUG> BC-NEC-EARNINGS-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPANESE CHIP MAKER NEC REPORTS A LOSS FOR THE YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ It's been an especially rough year for NEC Corp., one of
the world's largest makers of semiconductors and a symbol of
corporate Japan.
</P>
<P>
   NEC announced Friday that it had lost 157.9 billion yen, or $1.3
billion at current exchange rates, in the fiscal year that ended
March 31, compared with a profit of 41.3 billion yen the year
before.
</P>
<P>
   Its famous chairman, Tadahiro Sekimoto, and his
second-in-command were forced to resign after a military
procurement scandal. In February the company announced an extensive
overhaul that if completed would eliminate more than 12,000 jobs,
one of the most sweeping employment cutbacks ever undertaken by a
Japanese corporation.
</P>
<P>
   NEC has said it wants to become a company that integrates
telecommunications and computer technology into systems for
customers, rather than remain just a vendor of the components that
go into those systems.
</P>
<P>
   That means moving employees into new jobs and exiting businesses
that are no longer profitable, like making commodity components and
home appliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those businesses that are positioned farther and farther from
our core businesses of computers, telecommunications and
semiconductors may be closed or sold off,'' Kouji Nishigaki, NEC's
new president, said in an interview. ``Of course, given the
cultural importance of lifetime employment in Japan, we won't go
into any widespread cutting of jobs, but we will make changes.''
</P>
<P>
   How far-reaching those changes are, however, is the pivotal
issue. Company after company has signaled an intent to change but,
so far, has laid out few concrete plans.
</P>
<P>
   A similar wave of intended restructuring swept Japan in 1993 and
1994, but few plans ever became reality once the economy picked up
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   NEC will provide more details of its plan this fall, having
already said that it would eliminate 10 percent of its work force
and vacate unprofitable businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Nishigaki promises that this time around, the changes are real.
``I think Japanese managers have learned a lot, and one thing
they've learned is that the Japanese economy is part of a global
economy and that we simply can't stick to Japanese ways only,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he cautioned against expecting a revolution,
explaining that Japan's labor practices will prevent one.
``Lifetime employment is a tacit agreement that most employees _
except for young recruits _ take for granted, and they plan their
lives around that idea,'' Nishigaki said. ``I think Japanese
managers feel a great responsibility to secure employment for them,
so their lives won't fall apart.''
</P>
<P>
   That sense of obligation will not stop NEC, Nishigaki said. He
noted that the company had already cut almost two-thirds of the
6,000 positions it promised to eliminate from international
operations.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, a combination of shrunken recruiting and retirement
will result in the elimination of 6,000 jobs, he said, while
another 3,000 jobs will disappear as the company sells off or
merges unwanted businesses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Nishigaki was less precise about the future of Packard Bell,
NEC's troubled U.S. operation, which lost $500 million last year
and was largely responsible for NEC's poor showing in the last
fiscal year. NEC moved to isolate the unit's European business by
taking full control of it in February, but the U.S. business
continues to suffer from falling prices in personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   Nishigaki is himself perhaps the biggest sign of change at NEC.
He is not an engineer, which itself is a distinction in the world
of large Japanese industrial companies. Although as a graduate of
Tokyo University he has the appropriate academic pedigree, he
studied economics and has held marketing and business-management
roles within NEC.
</P>
<P>
   He considers that an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is required more now is a broad perspective based on an
understanding of economics and social affairs,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
