<HEADLINE>
ELTON JOHN RUNS THROUGH A MARATHON OF SONGS IN SEATTLE
PERFORMANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Elton John was the color purple Thursday night at
Seattle's KeyArena.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a flamboyant, purple-and-white plaid suit (with
rhinestone trim), purple T-shirt and purple sunglasses, the British
rock star mixed songs that were alternately hot and cool, buoyant
and bittersweet.
</P>
<P>
   The English knighted singer-pianist (who also wore a
skull-and-crossbones earring) ran a marathon for fans, performing a
nearly three-hour retrospective solo concert of songs from the
beginning of his career through the present. Fans responded with
whoops, cheers and standing ovations.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the show, a large crowd gathered close to the stage,
some holding cell phones in the air so that friends and family at
home could hear. Others clamored for autographs, which John was
only too happy to provide between songs.
</P>
<P>
   Selections came from early albums ``Tumbleweed Connection'' and
``Captain Fantastic and the Brown Dirt Cowboy,'' as well as ``The
Lion King'' soundtrack and his new, rather poorly received
``Aida,'' written with lyricist Tim Rice (the only song from
``Aida'' was ``Written in the Stars,'' originally a duet with LeAnn
Rimes).
</P>
<P>
   With stage fog swirling around him, John opened with ``Your
Song,'' which launched his career in the early '70s. Several early
songs followed, among them ``Skyline Pigeon'' and ``Talking Old
Soldiers'' (from ``Tumbleweed Connection'') and ``Daniel.''
</P>
<P>
   Seated at his black Yamaha grand, the singer-songwriter
refrained from his acrobatic feats of the past, but his playing was
vigorous and impassioned. The crowd often cheered as he tore into
the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   Sure-fire crowd-pleasers included a rousing ``Honky Cat'' and a
stratospheric ``Rocket Man,'' with reverberating vocal effects.
Among the rarities were ``Sacrifice'' and Bernie Taupin's ``The
Great Discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   Above the stage hung three giant video screens that captured
many of the small details of John's virtuoso performance, including
the reflection of piano keys in his sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   Behind him were five ornate mesh screens. The stage was also
decorated with three giant reels, each with a Versace emblem in the
center.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, John did not perform ``Candle in the Wind 1997,''
which he sang at Princess Diana's funeral to a worldwide audience.
Nor did he do ``Goodbye Yellow Brick Road,'' one of his best songs.
But he included such old favorites as ``I Guess That's Why They
Call It the Blues,'' ``Don't Let the Sun Go Down On Me,''
``Crocodile Rock'' and ``Levon.''
</P>
<P>
   John sipped from a can of Diet Coke throughout the concert, as
if he were doing a commercial. Occasionally he hoisted the can into
the air with a grin, as if to toast his fans.
</P>
<P>
   In the show's final moments, John thrilled the crowd with a
teasing, explosive ``Bennie and the Jets.'' He began by pounding
out a single note, bringing a roar from fans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
