<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALBOTT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH INDICTMENT, VOICE OF MILOSEVIC EVEN LESS LIKELY TO BE HEARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   SERGE SCHMEMANN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott,
President Martti Ahtisaari of Finland and Viktor Chernomyrdin of
Russia sat down to talk about Kosovo this week at Stalin's old
dacha outside Moscow, they pulled up an empty chair. The fourth
chair, according to an American official, was to remind them at all
times that the key figure in their endeavor was not there.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, since his indictment on Thursday on charges of war
crimes by the international tribunal in The Hague, it is virtually
certain that President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia will never
sit in that fourth chair, at least not with an American present. As
an indicted war criminal, he is unlikely to join in negotiations
with NATO.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration would like the indictment to impress
on the Yugoslavs that their options are narrowing as long as
Milosevic remains their president. They hope, too, that the
Russians might use the charge as a way to distance themselves from
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But the empty chair stands as a stark reminder to the American,
the Finn and the Russian that even as they try to steer through the
deep differences among them in search of a diplomatic conclusion to
the bombing of Kosovo, none of them _ not Ahtisaari, who represents
the European Union, and not even Chernomyrdin, the self-appointed
counsel for Serbia _ can speak for Milosevic, or even really gauge
his thinking.
</P>
<P>
   After the talks this week in Moscow, Chernomyrdin, President
Boris Yeltsin's personal envoy for the Balkans, made his fourth
journey to Belgrade on Friday to meet with Milosevic. As in the
past, no specifics of his mission were made public, but it seemed
certain that the indictment and its impact on Milosevic's readiness
to deal would be among the topics.
</P>
<P>
   Talbott flew back from Moscow to Washington Friday. ``We don't
know the effect of the indictment,'' he said in a telephone
interview from his plane. ``We have a strong view that the
indictment is justified, that it is a confirmation, a vindication
of one of the premises of our policies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
