<SLUG> BC-MA-BIGDIG-POLITICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REP. MCGOVERN DENIES BIG DIG CRITICISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A day after receiving a scolding from the head of
the Massachusetts Turnpike Authority, US Representative James P.
McGovern fired back, denying Friday he had ever criticized the
authority's pet project, the Big Dig.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern, a Massachusetts Democrat, had attacked directors of
the Big Dig earlier in the week, after the release of an audit that
said the project was improperly funneling federal money into a
trust fund, which was then used as an insurance policy for the
construction project.
</P>
<P>
   The audit by the inspector general of the US Transportation
Department concluded that the Big Dig was required to return as
much as $150 million to the federal government. State officials
denied the charges, saying they had developed an innovative way to
protect their finances.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern, along with several other Democrats in the
Massachusetts congressional delegation, seized on the audit and
criticized the project's directors for being reckless with
taxpayers' funds. That sparked a battle with MTA chairman James J.
Kerasiotis, who wrote a biting letter Thursday imploring McGovern
to ``stop whining.''
</P>
<P>
   McGovern wrote back Friday, thanking Kerasiotis for his letter
and saying he was ``eager to work closely'' with Republican state
officials, including Governor Paul Cellucci. McGovern defended his
concerns about the audit findings. ``Only by supporting aggressive
oversight of these funds that the delegation can have the
credibility in Congress to request additional funds,'' his letter
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moreover, it's important to note that I have never been, nor
will I ever be, a critic of the Big Dig itself,'' McGovern
continued. ``But the Big Dig must not preclude or exclude other
vital transportation projects throughout the Commonwealth, and the
federal funding used in the Big Dig must always be used properly
and in accordance with federal guidelines.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
