<SLUG> BC-WORKSCAPE-EDIFY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASS. CONSULTANTING GROUP BUYING CALIFORNIA UNIT OF EDIFY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A Massachusetts company is making an acquisition in
California's Silicon Valley, reversing a general pattern of late.
</P>
<P>
   Workscape Inc. of Natick said it plans to buy another
human-resources consulting group, based in Santa Clara, Calif.,
which will add about 70 employees to Workscape's current staff of
90.
</P>
<P>
   Privately held Workscape declined to disclose how much cash it
spent to buy the business unit from Edify Corp., but said the unit
had revenue of about $20 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   Workscape is the successor company to what was once Employee
Communications Services, which Workscape's principals bought out
last fall with backing from Warburg, Pincus &AMP; Co. LLC in New York.
</P>
<P>
   To date Workscape has grown by operating databases and Websites
for companies which want to make benefits information available to
employees over the Internet. Clients include Fleet Financial Group
Inc., Citigroup Inc.'s Travelers units, and Cigna Insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Now it will add Edify's Employee Relationship Management Group,
which operates more extensive benefits-consulting services, such as
installing software at the employer's own facilities. Its clients
include the US Postal Service and Warner-Lambert Co.
</P>
<P>
   Workscape will also take control of a small Edify sales office
in Waltham, with about eight employees.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the purchase will help Workscape offer a wider range
of services, said Workscape president Tim Clifford. ``We're taking
on a lot of the mundane tasks and making them more self-service,''
he said. ``That allows employers' HR and benefits departments to be
more strategic partners of employees rather than having to spend
more time answering questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Workscape said it will gain about 200 new clients as a result of
the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the Edify unit comes as the company is being
purchased by Atlanta-based Security First Technologies Corp.
</P>
<P>
   BancBoston Robertson Stephens analyst Jon Ekoniak said the
relationship-management unit didn't really fit the the rest of
Edify's business, primarily aimed at the financial industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unit deals more with the human-resources side,so they're
really going after a different group of customers than what
Security First wants,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
