<HEADER>
A5511 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-74     05-28 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-PAKISTAN-ART-745&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA STRIKES AT GUERRILLAS IN KASHMIR FOR THIRD DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ India on Friday launched a third day of
airstrikes against hundreds of Muslim guerrillas who have dug into
icy, barren mountainsides in the contested territory of Kashmir.
India says the men are backed by its bitter adversary, Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict between India and Pakistan over Kashmir _ a
gorgeous region caught in a 51-year-old tug of war between the
nations _ showed no signs of abating. And the images of the prime
ministers of Pakistan and India embracing in February, as they
promised to seek peace, faded a little more.
</P>
<P>
   After announcing that the guerrillas had shot down an Indian
helicopter Friday morning with a heat-seeking, shoulder-launched
Stinger missile, Indian officials said their military might use
even more potent weaponry to counter the guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The downing of the helicopter followed India's loss of two jet
fighters in combat on Thursday. Four soldiers died in the
helicopter, and one of the jet pilots died. India on Friday
demanded the release of the surviving pilot, who is being held by
Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a war, and they have no basis to keep him,'' said
Air Vice Marshal S.K. Malik.
</P>
<P>
   For a conflict that is not a war, this one certainly has the
bellicose language and the body counts that go along with one.
India on Friday tallied 24 of its men dead and 131 wounded in its
three-week campaign to evict the militants from mountain ridges. It
said it was making progress in retaking the rugged terrain.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Russia, Japan and China _ worried about this
conflict between the world's newest nuclear powers _ have urged
India and Pakistan to avoid letting their dispute spin out of
control.
</P>
<P>
   But the fighting is going on perilously close to the boundary
that separates the Indian- and Pakistani-controlled parts of
Kashmir, a boundary that was established in 1949 and redrawn in
1972. The guerrillas are holed up on the Indian side, four to five
miles from the cease-fire line.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians are using jet fighters in Kashmir for the first time
since 1971, when they had their third war with Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   India, which is predominantly Hindu, claims Kashmir, which has a
Muslim majority, as one of its 25 states. Pakistan, an Islamic
nation, contends that the Kashmiris should have the right to decide
in an election whether to join India or Pakistan. This festering
disagreement is the great unfinished business of the moment in 1947
when British India was sundered into two nations.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistani officials have ominously said in recent days that
Kashmir could become a ``nuclear flash point'' and pressed for the
United Nations to mediate, a step that India has always rejected.
</P>
<P>
   But Indian officials said Friday that their country was acting
with restraint by confining its air and ground campaign to the
parts of Kashmir it controls in a completely justified drive to
reclaim its own territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``No civilized democracy in the world would tolerate this kind
of armed intrusion,'' said Maj. Gen. J.J. Singh.
</P>
<P>
   But Pakistani officials said that they had given no military or
financial support to what they say are indigenous Kashmiri freedom
fighters battling what they describe as Indian occupiers.
</P>
<P>
   And on Friday, on the first anniversary of Pakistan's nuclear
tests _ a day when a celebratory 21-gun salvo sounded in each
provincial capital _ Pakistani officials said it was up to India to
defuse the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are urging India to de-escalate the present situation and
try to find a solution to a local problem at the local level rather
than try to expand it in the area and escalate into a much bigger
conflict,'' Pakistan's foreign minister, Sartaj Aziz, told
reporters in Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
   He said India had violated Pakistani airspace by flying into the
Pakistani-controlled part of Kashmir, prompting Pakistan to shoot
down the two fighter jets on its side of the cease-fire line. On
Friday, Pakistani army officials escorted reporters to the wreckage
of one of the MiGs strewn across a mountainside about seven miles
inside Pakistani territory.
</P>
<P>
   India gave a different explanation for the jet's location.
Officials said one of the jets had developed engine trouble on the
Indian side of the cease-fire line and suggested that it might have
flown into Pakistani-controlled territory as the pilot ejected from
the cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   India maintains that the other pilot, trying to spot where the
ejected pilot landed, was shot down on the Indian side of the line.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   So far, the elected leaders of India's government, which has
been in limbo since the coalition led by Hindu nationalists lost a
vote of confidence in Parliament last month, have largely left it
to military officials to brief the press and define the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition Congress Party, which will face the Hindu
nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party in September elections, has
supported the military campaign to drive out the militants even as
it criticized the intelligence lapses that had allowed the
infiltration to happen in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The infiltrators have to be pushed out on the Indian side,''
said Manmohan Singh, a senior Congress Party leader. ``We're all
united on that point.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Hindu nationalists, who have staked their political
reputation on their ability to defend the nation and often boast of
the government's decision to test nuclear weapons a year ago,
cannot afford to be seen as weak in this conflict, political
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear at the briefings that the army and air force have
clear orders: Get rid of the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   They make no bones about the fact that it will not happen
overnight. Just locating the hideouts in the mountainous terrain is
very difficult. And attacking them from below would entail many
casualties. So the military's strategy is to attack them from the
air, and only then to overrun them. ``We'll clear these positions
in very careful, deliberate operations, which could take some
time,'' said Malik.
</P>
<P>
   Officials and analysts have already begun thinking about what
will happen after the militants are gone. Will India do what it has
done for the last 15 years on the Siachen Glacier: permanently
occupy frozen, treacherous territory at tremendous human and
financial cost in an unending standoff with the Pakistanis?
</P>
<P>
   K. Subrahmanyam, a member of the government-appointed National
Security Advisory Board, said that intelligence failures had led to
the current problem, and that rigorous surveillance of the area by
air and satellite might be enough to prevent future trouble. On the
other hand, he said, it might be necessary for India to occupy the
heights.
</P>
</TEXT>
