<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV31-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCH BULLETIN WRITERS NEED FORGIVENESS
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, May 31)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Lord works in mysterious ways, but not nearly as
mysteriously as the writers of these (supposedly) actual
announcements gleaned from (supposedly) actual church bulletins.
(Thanks to Dan Wychor of Bradenton, Fla., Internet joke purveyor
and Little League coach extraordinaire.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Thursday night is Pot Luck Supper. Prayer and medication to
follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like somebody left the pot sitting out in the sun too
long. Next time, they might want to consider praying before supper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember in prayer the many who are sick of our church and our
community.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about the community part, but maybe people would be
less sick of the church if they didn't keep getting food poisoning
from the Pot Luck Suppers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those of you who have children and don't know it, we have
a nursery downstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds to me like we're talking about some seriously forgetful
people here. Better come up with better directions to the nursery
than simply ``downstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thursday at 5 p.m. there will be a meeting of the Little
Mothers club. All wishing to become Little Mothers, please see the
minister in his private study.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like the minister is doing all he can to boost membership
in the Little Mothers club. It's a thankless job, but someone has
to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This being Easter Sunday, we will ask Mrs. Murphy to come
forward and lay an egg on the altar.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Murphy must absolutely dread Easter Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next Sunday, a special collection will be taken to defray the
cost of the new carpet. All those wishing to do something on the
new carpet will come forward and get a piece of paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Isn't this how the old carpet got ruined?
</P>
<P>
   ``The ladies of the church have cast off clothing of every kind
and they may be seen in the church basement Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm betting this draws at least as many people as come to watch
Mrs. Murphy lay her egg. For those of you who have children and
don't know it, the ladies will be on display in the room adjacent
to the nursery.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bean supper will be held on Tuesday evening in the church
hall. Music will follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Problems with food seems to be a recurring theme in church news
bulletins these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the evening service tonight, the sermon topic will be,
`What is Hell?' Come early and listen to our choir practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly a rousing endorsement of the choir's abilities.
Perhaps members had sampled the Pot Luck Supper before their
practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Montgomery will be entering the hospital this week for
testes.''
</P>
<P>
   And when she comes out, would you all be so kind to address her
as ``Mr. Montgomery?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Scouts are saving aluminum cans, bottles, and other items to
be recycled. Proceeds will be used to cripple children.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the worst arguments against recycling I've heard yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eight new choir robes are currently needed, due to the
addition of several new members and to the deterioration of some
older ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the new robes will make the older members' deterioration
seem less noticeable. Or something.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weight Watchers will meet at 7 p.m. at the First Presbyterian
Church. Please use large double door at the side entrance.''
</P>
<P>
   Those of you who are unable to squeeze through the double door
can gather outside by the truck scale. Tonight's lecture topic:
``Losing Weight the Pot-Luck-Supper Way.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
