<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CHALK TALK BY PARCELLS, THE KNICKS FAN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The theme of the chalk talk was versatility, and the speaker was
Bill Parcells, the Jets' head coach. This was Day 2 of the Jets'
minicamp at Hofstra University this week and Parcells, who led the
Jets to the AFC championship game last season, was discussing the
theme of his coming 1999-2000 campaign: versatility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe that's one of the keys to having a chance to
be more successful, in any sport,'' Parcells said. ``If you've got
guys who can do more things and you really emphasize that with your
team, I really think you have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, the coach made an unexpected leap onto a topic that
has consumed every basketball fan in New York for the past week:
the Knicks and their playoff series with the Indiana Pacers. The
hype has been comparable to the buildup before the Super Bowl: a
week's worth of speculation, heated debate and controversy before a
single minute of action ever takes place. Parcells admitted that he
has been caught up in it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Knicks fan,'' he said. ``I've always been a Knicks fan.
I know some of the other coaches coaching for other teams, but deep
in my heart I'm a Knicks fan.'' And then, in a brief, but
compelling, display of a coach's insatiable appetite for tactics,
Parcells dissected the series, turning over strategy and matchups
and counterstrategy as he spoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been thinking about this Indiana-Knicks thing,'' he said.
``I'm thinking, `Nobody thinks they can beat Indiana.' But I'm
thinking, `Rik Smits is hurt a little bit, maybe he's not going to
be at top form.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a way for the Knicks to do this,'' he continued, ``but
I'm trying to figure out: `Well, who can guard this guy? We need to
guard this guy, we need to guard this other guy. Now we need to
guard this third guy here.' Indiana has a lot of guys you need to
guard, and that worries me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, they're not great at guarding, themselves,'' Parcells
added, ``so they've got a few guys they've got to guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Just when it seemed Parcells was hopelessly out on an
improvisational tangent, he returned to the theme: versatility.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why Indiana's a threat,'' he said. ``If you look at
their basketball team, they've got a guy they can bring in who can
do things _ they got Rose, he comes in, he can do things. They got
those Davises _ they do certain things for their team. Then they
got Mullin, he can still do something. Then they got this Best,
what a pain he is. Then they got Miller. I'm telling you, they've
got versatility.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said he wasn't looking at the series as a mere fan, but
as a coach who closely monitors why a team wins and loses. ``I look
at it from that perspective,'' he said. ``I don't look at it from,
`Oh, gee, I hope Sprewell gets 30 tonight.' I don't look at it like
that. I look at it like, `Here's where I see some problems.'
Whether I'm really right about that, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   When someone remarked that the Pacers created matchup problems
for opponents, Parcells brought the conversation full circle.
``That's what I'm trying to do,'' he said of his full-time job with
the Jets. ``I'm trying to create matchup problems for people, and
the more guys you got that can do it, the better we are.''
</P>
<P>
   As Parcells ended his news conference, I asked him about Jeff
Van Gundy, an issue as central to Knicks fans these days as is the
fate of their team against Indiana. Four months ago, Parcells
responded to a similar question about John Calipari, then the coach
of the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten to know this John Calipari a little bit in the
last year or so,'' Parcells said at the time. ``I kind of always
liked the way this guy did things, and now he comes over here and
watches practice. And I've talked to him about coming to a Nets
practice when the season is over. I like something about him, and I
want to watch this guy coach because I could probably learn
something from him.''
</P>
<P>
   That endorsement didn't carry much weight with the Nets' brass,
which fired Calipari midway through a painfully disappointing
season. But for better or for worse, Parcells was even more
enthusiastic when asked about the Knicks' head coach. ``I really
like Van Gundy,'' he said. ``I think he's a heck of a coach. I
don't know him _ I never met the guy _ but I watch him. I think
he's working hard.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as all the off-court intrigue surrounding the Knicks,
Parcells said: ``I don't know what the politics are. I don't know
what's being forced and what's not. I think he's got a lot out of
Camby, got a lot out of Sprewell. Some of the old guys like him and
they respond to him. I don't know what else you want from the guy.
I mean, these aren't the Chicago Bulls.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. These are the New York Knicks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
