<SLUG> BC-NIGERIA-INAUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGERIANS HOPEFUL BUT JITTERY ON RETURN TO CIVILIAN GOVERNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABUJA, Nigeria _ At the U-Fine Barbers Shop in the slum of
Nyanya here, Nigeria's final day under military rule registered
with a mixture of great hope for the future and last-minute jitters
about a return to civilian government _ long promised, yet often
postponed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a day we have been looking forward to,'' said Thomas
Idoko, a 29-year-old teacher, who was getting a trim. ``We thought
it would never take place, but now I am expecting great changes
both in the economy and society.''
</P>
<P>
   The barber, John Agbo, 21, wished that the long-awaited day
would bring a more personal change. ``I pray to God that I can get
a richer shop,'' he said, mentioning air conditioning, sharper
clippers, a bigger waiting area. He said he would settle, though,
for reliable electricity from the government so that his old
clippers would not stop working in mid-hum.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria, whose 122 million people make it Africa's most populous
nation, changes governments on Saturday; the generals who have
ruled it since 1983 are giving way to a civilian government elected
in February. Since the departing president, Gen. Abdulsalami
Abubakar, announced last July that a civilian government would take
over on May 29, the date has loomed before Nigerians as the
finishing line of a political marathon.
</P>
<P>
   And only 24 hours before the big day, there were doubts in
Nyanya, amid the expressions of optimism, that the line would be
crossed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm highly elated that the handover will take place,'' said
Friday Nathaniel, 18, who was waiting for his turn at the
barbershop. ``We are praying that it should happen as it has been
promised. I expect the incoming administration will do something in
the area of job opportunities. I am now just like a beggar with no
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Nyanya is on the outskirts of this capital's center, a world
away from the five-star international hotels, where Nigerian and
foreign lobbyists were furiously slapping backs this week, and a
dinner was held to honor Stella Obasanjo, the wife of
President-elect Olusegun Obasanjo, the retired general and one-time
military ruler.
</P>
<P>
   Nigeria, ruled by the military for all but 10 years since
independence from Britain in 1960, teetered on the edge of collapse
under the extremely repressive and corrupt government of Gen. Sani
Abacha. But after five years in power, Abacha died suddenly last
June, setting off a series of political reforms that is culminating
in the inauguration on Saturday. The Rev. Jesse Jackson, President
Clinton's special envoy to Africa, is to lead the American
delegation at the inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday morning, the dirt road outside U-Fine Barbers was
flooded after a night of heavy rains. A block away, in a heap of
uncollected garbage, a baby goat could be seen butting a rooster
over an apparently tasty morsel.
</P>
<P>
   Nyanya came into existence in the 1980s after Nigeria, its
coffers flush from the oil boom, decided to move its capital to
Abuja from Lagos. Over the years, Nigerians from seemingly every
corner of this country gravitated to Nyanya, divided by religion
and ethnicity but seemingly united in their concept of a better
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the new government to increase the salaries of the
workers and to help the poor,'' said Ezekiel Oyeleru, 13, who was
milling around with other children outside the barbershop. The
children have not attended school in months, since unpaid teachers
began striking.
</P>
<P>
   ``To repair our roads,'' said Charles Jeremiah, 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our homes,'' Ezekiel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``To repair our schools and to reduce our school fees,'' Charles
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lazarus Mohammed, 26, struggled to push his wheelbarrow around
water-filled potholes in front of the barbershop. It was laden with
plastic containers that he had filled with water from a tap and
that he was going to sell in a remote corner of Nyanya for 5 cents
each.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mai ruwa!'' a woman cried to him in Hausa, the dominant
language and ethnic group in northern Nigeria. ``Water boy! Your
jerrycans are leaking.''
</P>
<P>
   The water boy stopped. ``Nigeria will be great a year from
now,'' he said before going on. ``We are suffering now. But after
suffering is enjoyment.''
</P>
<P>
   Elegant Ukpong, 35, was not ready to celebrate yet. Ukpong was
one of the hundreds of men in Nyanya, called okada-men, who ferry
passengers on their motorcycles for a living.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still have doubts that the handover will take place,''
the okada-man said. ``They are afraid of all the rumors.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week we heard that Obasanjo was killed,'' he said,
referring to rumors that suddenly swept the country and caused
riots in Lagos. ``So we still have doubts. Until I see the new
government here _ 24 hours from now _ I will not go out and
jubilate.''
</P>
<P>
   But then, the okada-man said, he will party. ``Anything my hand
can reach,'' he said, ``I will eat to make my mind happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
