<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5524 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      05-28 1435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO PATROL RELEASED AFTER 8-HOUR YUGOSLAV GRILLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN AND SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST _ Six NATO soldiers patrolling the border between
Bosnia and Yugoslavia were captured at gunpoint by Yugoslav
soldiers and interrogated for eight hours before being released,
military spokesmen disclosed Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of several tense episodes along the borders between
Yugoslavia and its neighbors as NATO kept up its intense
bombardment of targets across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, the capital, Russia's special envoy for the
Balkans, Viktor Chernomyrdin, renewed his call for a halt to the
NATO strikes as he arrived for a new round of talks seeking a
peaceful resolution to the conflict. He met with Slobodan Milosevic
one day after the Yugoslav president was indicted for war crimes by
an international tribunal in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, Yugoslav officials sought to portray the meeting
as a breakthrough, and a source close to a cabinet minister said
Milosevic had accepted the principles for an end to the war
outlined last month by the so-called Group of Eight industrialized
countries.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response from NATO. State Department
spokesman James Foley was cautious. ``We're going to have to talk
to Mr. Chernomyrdin before we can assess what was agreed to. NATO's
conditions in order to stop the air campaign remain the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, US Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott said in
Brussels that Chernomyrdin was speaking only for his own
government, not negotiating on behalf of the alliance nor acting as
a mediator.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Friday:
</P>
<P>
   -- The Macedonian government indicated Friday that it will
approve the proposed deployment there of 14,000 additional NATO
troops if the Western alliance starts paying for the wear and tear
on local facilities and reiterates a pledge that the troops will
have only defensive or peacekeeping responsibilities. The added
troops would bring the total to 30,000 in Macedonia. Albania would
host another 15,000 to 20,000 troops under the new NATO plan.
</P>
<P>
   --Albanian forces conducted artillery exercises with live
ammunition along the border of the Yugoslav province of Kosovo in a
region that has been the site of fighting between Yugoslav soldiers
and the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   --Officials in Macedonia, which has been a reluctant host to
thousands of Kosovar refugees, complained that the United National
High Commissioner for Refugees was not paying attention to the
alleged ``vice, prostitution, drug abuse, criminal behavior, unrest
and political pressures on deportees'' in the refugee camps there.
</P>
<P>
   --In the Yugoslav republic of Montenegro, tensions remained high
between the republic's government _ which opposes Milosevic's
regime _ and Yugoslav army forces under Milosevic's command. The
border with Croatia remained closed and Montenegrin officials said
they were worried that two ships carrying food for needy citizens
would not be allowed to unload.
</P>
<P>
   --In Belgrade, conditions were increasingly grim. The city was
completely blacked out Friday, a result of damage done to power
grids by NATO missiles. The Western military alliance conducted yet
another record-setting bombardment Thursday night, flying 792
missions, including 310 attack sorties, said NATO spokesman Jamie
Shea.
</P>
<P>
   Two critical and beloved staples of the local diet _ Serbian
bread and hot, Turkish-style coffee _ were unavailable Friday.
Locals lined up to buy bread, but there was none to be had.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of power, there was relative order in the
capital. Cars were on the roads, negotiating traffic even without
stoplights.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin and Milosevic had what aides described as a
``jubilant dinner'' to conclude what they described as successful
talks. Chernomyrdin then left Belgrade, promising to return on
Tuesday or Wednesday with Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari, the
European envoy, to try to get more concrete agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav government has previously given vague assurances
that it accepted the G-8 nations' principles for a settlement,
which call for withdrawal of Serb forces from Kosovo and deployment
of an international peacekeeping force, but Milosevic insisted that
the peacekeepers be a lightly-armed United Nations force. However,
Yugoslav sources said he was willing to let the UN Security Council
decide the makeup of the force.
</P>
<P>
   One source said that prior to the Chernomyrdin-Milosevic
meeting, a senior western diplomat met with a Yugoslav cabinet
minister, Bogoljub Karic, and promised that ambassadors still
working in Yugoslavia would guarantee the safety of Serb forces
withdrawing from Kosovo. Karic, one of Yugoslavia's most successful
businessmen, is close to Milosevic, and has been urging him to cut
a deal to save the country from further ruin.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin said that after next week's visit, he would return
to Belgrade only ``as a tourist.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident on the Bosnian border involved six soldiers on a
reconnaissance patrol for the Stabilization Force, a NATO-led force
charged with keeping the peace in Bosnia. The team spotted a
detachment of Yugoslav soldiers on the Bosnian side of the border _
a violation of the Dayton peace agreement of 1995 that ended the
Bosnian war _ and asked them to leave, said SFOR spokesman Colonel
Lee Hockman.
</P>
<P>
   As the Yugoslavs appeared to leave, more of their compatriots
showed up, and the group of 20 disarmed the Stabilization Force
soldiers, tied them up, and forcibly took them back to a village
inside Yugoslavia, Hockman said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident between the Yugoslav forces and SFOR troops in
Bosnia was a first, Hockman said. While Yugoslav soldiers had
wandered over the border before, they had always left when
confronted.
</P>
<P>
   He said, ``it's hard to say'' whether the detention and
harassment of the NATO troops was directed from Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no way of knowing whether this was planned, or a
spontaneous decision by a low-ranking'' officer, Hockman said.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers were mistreated while in custody and suffered minor
bruises, Hockman said. He said he could not detail the nature of
the interrogation. NATO would not reveal which member countries the
soldiers came from.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation occurred about 7:30 Wednesday night in Rudo
but was only disclosed Friday. Rudo is in Republika Srpska, the
ethnic Serb area of Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
   There is an ongoing territorial dispute over the Rudo area, but
the land is now considered part of Bosnia. The peace-keeping troops
will use force, if necessary, to maintain the integrity of the
border, Hockman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't going to happen again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The episode was a disturbing reminder that while one war is
raging on the Yugoslav side of the border, tensions from the
1992-95 war on the Bosnian side are still high.
</P>
<P>
   In Albania, President Rexhap Meidani watched from a hilltop as a
force of about 1,200 troops, 645 shells, artillery, tanks and
missiles performed for about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to perfect our military capabilities so that the Serbs
will get the right response,'' said Albanian General Kudusi Lama.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations' refugee agency said it feared the exercise
would provoke fire from Yugoslav forces across the border,
imperiling the safety of some 100,000 ethnic Albanian refugees in
northern Albania.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, outgoing artillery tends to draw incoming
artillery, and we are extremely concerned that this could draw fire
from the Serbian side into an area which has a huge concentration
of refugees,'' said Kris Janowski, spokesman for the UN High
Commissioner for Refugees, in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   In Macedonia, the UN agency was criticized by Defense Minister
Nikola Kijusev, who called on the agency to stop ``bureaucracy and
irresponsible behavior'' and to pay attention to the needs of the
106,000 refugees there.
</P>
<P>
   UNHCR spokesman Ron Redmond said he knew nothing about Kijusev's
charges, and noted that it was the responsibility of the Macedonian
government to maintain security at the camps.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonia, itself a breakaway former province of the Yugoslav
republic, is nervous about the impact of so many ethnic Albanians,
since they could swell an already restless Albanian population
there. Refugees have been hemmed in with barbed-wire fence to keep
them from wandering deeper into Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe reporter Anne Kornblut contributed to this article from
Washington. Wire service material was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
