r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROSTATE-STAMP-COX     05-28 0329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSTATE-STAMP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Postal Service's new stamp promotes cancer awareness
 &HT;    By Mary Ann Roser
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buy a stamp, save a prostate.
</P>
<P>
   That's the hope of health-care workers, U.S. Postal Service
officials and others who unveiled the 33-cent Prostate Cancer
Awareness stamp in Austin on Friday. World champion cyclist Lance
Armstrong of Austin, a survivor of advanced testicular cancer,
helped introduce the stamp, which went on sale here Friday _ a day
ahead of the rest of the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The stamp is aimed at making people aware of a leading killer of
men. The cancer strikes the gland below the bladder and initially
develops without symptoms, making early detection critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more we talk and the more we educate, the more success we
will have in battling this deadly disease,'' said Austin Postmaster
Dennis Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   Experts estimate this year that 180,000 new cases of prostate
cancer will be diagnosed and that 40,000 men will die. U.S. Rep.
Lloyd Doggett of Austin said at the ceremony that his father and
uncle suffered with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stamps are a wonderful vehicle for public awareness,'' said
Virginia Noelke, chairwoman of the Citizens' Stamp Advisory
Committee and a history professor at Angelo State University.
``They reach millions of people.''
</P>
<P>
   The stamp includes the male gender symbol and the words ``annual
checkups and tests.''
</P>
<P>
   The unveiling coincided with the ``Ride for the Roses,'' an
Austin and Hill Country bike tour Sunday featuring Armstrong and
other champions. Proceeds will go to the Lance Armstrong
Foundation, which raises money for cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   ``I commend the Postal Service for drawing attention to health
issues that aren't often talked about,'' said Armstrong, who also
mentioned last year's breast cancer research stamp.
</P>
<P>
   Roser writes for the Austin American-Statesman
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
