<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHUTTLE-STATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE CREW PREPARES TO DOCK WITH SPACE STATION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The Discovery astronauts Friday prepared their
cargo-laden shuttle for a late-night rendezvous with the new
international space station.
</P>
<P>
   With the four-man, three-woman crew docked on its six-day visit,
two of the astronauts will take part in a lengthy spacewalk
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttle commander Kent Rominger's crew was to be the first to
dock with the new station, though not the first to float aboard.
</P>
<P>
   That distinction went to the shuttle astronauts who initiated
the six-year effort to build the station by joining the first two
components in orbit last December.
</P>
<P>
   The 750-mile gap that separated the shuttle and the space
station early Friday dwindled quickly. The astronauts filled the
early hours of their second day in space by checking out their
spacesuits, the shuttle's 50-foot robot arm and the radio equipment
needed for the spacewalk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no problems with any of those,'' said Jeff Bantle, NASA
mission operations director. ``Overall, the shuttle and the station
are working like well-oiled machines.''
</P>
<P>
   On the ground, Russian and American flight control teams in
suburban Moscow issued remote commands to warm to 70 degrees the
station's unstaffed, 68-foot-long Zarya and Unity modules. While no
one was aboard, the temperature had been permitted to fall below
freezing.
</P>
<P>
   Observing a day-for-night schedule, the astronauts will move
into the station Sunday night with the first of nearly two tons of
supplies they plan to leave behind.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday, astronauts Tammy Jernigan and Dan Barry will
embark on their 6 1/2-hour spacewalk.
</P>
<P>
   Their primary task will be the assembly of small hand-operated
cargo cranes that will be installed on the exterior of the space
station.
</P>
<P>
   The spacewalk promises to hold challenges for both Jernigan, a
40-year-old physicist who is flying in space for the fifth time,
and Barry, a 45-year-old medical doctor and electrical engineer who
is on his second mission.
</P>
<P>
   After the docking, the station's Unity docking and Zarya
propulsion modules will jut more than seven stories out of the
shuttle's cargo bay.
</P>
<P>
   The astronauts inside the shuttle will rely on videocameras
positioned inside the cargo bay to keep tabs on the spacewalkers.
</P>
<P>
   Jernigan will position herself on the tip of the shuttle's robot
arm so that arm operator Ellen Ochoa inside Discovery can move her
and the bulky crane segments into place. But Ochoa will have to
rely on radio commands from Jernigan.
</P>
<P>
   Barry will scale the outside of the outpost, using footholds and
handrails.
</P>
<P>
   While Discovery circles the Earth several times during the
excursion, the spacewalkers will be cycling between sunlight and
darkness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a real challenge to guide ourselves around the
station in low light conditions,'' said Barry, who logged a
previous spacewalk in 1996. ``I will be very deliberate and very
cautious because I am a little concerned about not touching
anything I should not.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another danger. While docked, Discovery will be unable
to fly instantly to the rescue if one of the spacewalkers drifts
away. For that reason both will be double-tethered to the outpost.
</P>
<P>
   They will wear back-mounted jet packs filled with a small amount
of fuel to propel themselves back to safety if both tethers snap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not very pleasant to talk about,'' Rominger said of the
risk. ``If someone gets away, first of all you have to recognize
that maybe you could get to them with the arm. If you don't, and we
didn't train formally for it, it's pretty simple to undock and get
away. So within a matter of minutes we can be undocked and on our
way to rescue a crew member.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
