u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-PIRACY-680&AMP;A     05-28 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-PIRACY-680&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STAR WARS' SAGA IS JUST ANOTHER PIRATE STORY IN ASIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ If you wanted to be the first on your block in New
York to see the new ``Star Wars'' film, you had to line up three
days in advance for tickets or buy them from scalpers for $100
apiece.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to be first on the block in Hong Kong, you just have
to duck into a seedy shopping arcade in Kowloon, where you can pick
up the most eagerly awaited film in history for less than $3.
</P>
<P>
   Illegal videotaped copies of ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The
Phantom Menace'' are doing a brisk business throughout Asia, barely
a week after it opened in the United States and more than a month
before it is to open here.
</P>
<P>
   The illicit copying of Hollywood films is such a pervasive
problem that industry executives took it for granted that ``Phantom
Menace'' would turn up here on video compact disc. But the warp
speed with which it flew from American cinemas to Asian streets has
left people whipsawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, that didn't take long,'' said Barbara Robinson, the
managing director of Columbia Pictures Film Production Asia. She
added, ``It would have been naive to think that ``Star Wars''
wouldn't have been pirated.''
</P>
<P>
   Most major films from the United States are illegally copied and
sold within a week of their release. ``Phantom Menace'' set a
dubious record, according to industry experts, with copies hitting
the streets in Malaysia two days after the release. They have since
turned up in Singapore, Indonesia, Macau and Hong Kong, where the
movie does not open until July 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not some small fly-by-night organization doing one-off
copies; this is a very well-organized international conspiracy,''
said Rigo Jesu, the managing director of Intercontinental Film
Group, a local film distributor.
</P>
<P>
   The latest chapter of the ``Star Wars'' saga is considered such
a juggernaut that most industry executives said illegal knockoffs
would not doom it at the box office _ as it has done to some Asian
films. But the abysmal quality of the copies could drive potential
customers away, these people said.
</P>
<P>
   Piracy experts said the copies were probably produced by someone
who surreptitiously filmed the movie off the screen of a theater in
the United States. In a copy that was playing in the arcade, the
bobbing heads of moviegoers, including a man's bald pate, obscured
the bottom of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not good for the movie, and it hurts video sales if
everyone already owns a copy,'' said Sam Ho, the director of the
anti-piracy division at the Motion Picture Association, a trade
group that represents Hollywood studios, including 20th Century
Fox, which is distributing ``Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives at 20th Century Fox, a unit of News Corp., did not
return calls.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Radley, president of Lucasfilm Ltd., the company founded
by the ``Star Wars'' creator George Lucas, said in a statement that
the latest film ``is not unique in suffering the problems of
piracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Piracy throughout the world is an extremely serious problem
for the whole motion picture industry,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Radley said Motion Picture Association officials had been
``extremely aggressive in combating any piracy in any way they can;
however, without the support of local governments and authorities
it's difficult to overcome this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The purloining of movies is a flashpoint in trade relations
between the United States and several Asian countries. Hong Kong
was removed from a watch list by the United States in February
after it intensified efforts to raid factories that produce
illegally copied material. But other Asian countries, including
Indonesia and Singapore, are on the list of copyright violators.
</P>
<P>
   The surge of piracy also alarms filmmakers here, who say that it
is strangling the region's once-thriving movie industry. The
box-office revenue of Hong Kong films declined from $168 million in
1993 to $54 million last year _ largely because of the blizzard of
bootleg copies, according to executives.
</P>
<P>
   ```Star Wars' happens to be a massive phenomenon,'' Jesu said.
``But piracy can devastate a more run-of-the-mill movie.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Hong Kong Customs Department has assigned 250 officers to
raid shops that sell illegal material, and said it would add
another 48 this year. ``We don't care what the movie title is,''
said a spokesman, Richard Law. ``We are carrying out actions every
day to enforce laws on pirated films.''
</P>
<P>
   But piracy is so profitable that it seems to defy even the most
vigilant efforts. In the case of ``Phantom Menace,'' studio
executives were so nervous about illegal copies that they warned
even reviewers for news organization not to record the film at an
advanced screening.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas had also taken extraordinary security measures to prevent
prints of the movie from leaking out. Yet industry executives said
that in the last two days, a higher-quality copy of the film had
turned up in stores and that the copy might have been reproduced
from a print.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is the lag time between the release of films
in the United States and overseas. Executives said the delay was
caused by the difficulty of running simultaneous marketing
campaigns. Studios have tried to close the gap in recent years,
notably in 1997, when the James Bond film ``Tomorrow Never Dies''
opened on the same day around the world.
</P>
<P>
   An even bigger hurdle is the low price. Video compact discs sell
for $20 (Hong Kong), or about $2.58 (United States). Customers can
buy a package of six for $100 (Hong Kong), or $12.90 (United
States), and choose from other new releases like ``The Matrix,''
``Entrapment,'' and ``The Mummy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People line up overnight in the States to see this,'' said a
shopkeeper, waving a copy of ``Phantom Menace'' that came with
Chinese subtitles. ``Have you seen it yet? You can have it for only
20.''
</P>
<P>
   The shopkeeper said he was selling 200 copies a day, which made
``Phantom Menace'' a popular choice but not his top seller. That
title belonged to ``The Ring,'' a Japanese horror film that was
selling 500 copies a day.
</P>
<P>
   There is still hope that Lucas' epic fantasy will draw people
into theaters. Two young women who were browsing through the
shelves of illegal copies stopped to look at ``Phantom Menace,''
but moved on. ``I'm not going to buy it,'' said Janice Ng, 25.
``I'll save this one for the theater.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5533 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TVYEAR-INREVIEW-AZR &LR;      05-28 1933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRUEL SEASON FOR NETWORKS AS VIEWERS CONTINUE TO FLEE  
 (ADV: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
 YEAR-IN REVIEW-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVE WALKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The HBO drama ``The Sopranos'' changed everything.
</P>
<P>
   An amazingly well-done series about a New Jersey mobster and
family man, ``The Sopranos'' launched in January and demoted TV
that once looked pretty good into TV that looks just OK.
</P>
<P>
   In an era deep in excellent TV dramas, only the gritty squad
from NBC's ``Homicide: Life on the Street'' can stand side-by-side
with Tony Soprano's crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Practice?'' ``Law &AMP; Order?'' ``ER?'' All once pretty good.
Now, OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sopranos'' severely dented the TV grading curve.
</P>
<P>
   Premium cable standards helped the storytelling, true, but the
stories were so well told and the acting so fine, the series' 13
installments transcended the medium. If you missed it the first
time, HBO will offer a second chance to meditate on transcendence
starting June 9, when ``The Sopranos'' begins repeats.
</P>
<P>
   Emmy Award nominations are a lock for stars James Gandolfini
(Tony Soprano) and Nancy Marchand (his evil mom, Livia), among
several others involved. Unless Emmy voters opt to again reward
``NYPD Blue'' star Dennis Franz, who turned in yet another
heartfelt season as beleaguered grunt Andy Sipowicz, Gandolfini
can't lose come awards time.
</P>
<P>
   Emmy nominations will be announced July 22, or almost exactly
halfway between the 1998-99 TV season, which officially ended last
week, and the start of the 1999-2000 season, which officially
begins in September.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike almost all other cable or over-air networks, HBO doesn't
have to rise and fall with ratings or ad dollars. Its pay-for-play
status allows it to freely use adult themes and levels of sex,
violence and language not often seen outside of R-rated movies.
Because there are no commercials, there also is no concern with
specific demographics as a measure of success. It allows the
series' writers to be as unencumbered as it is possible to be in
television writing.
</P>
<P>
   The six broadcast networks (seven if you count Pax, nine if you
count Spanish-language networks), on the other hand, have revenue
and ratings masters to serve. Excellence isn't necessarily or often
a guarantee of success. Last season, ABC, NBC, CBS, Fox, WB and UPN
launched a total of 36 new shows. Only a handful are surviving;
only one was a ratings success.
</P>
<P>
   That lone winner was ``Providence,'' a midseason replacement for
NBC that earned the season's only signs of hit status. NBC's
``Jesse,'' one of the 10 new shows renewed for next fall, gets
counted as a hit thanks only to its cushy Thursday night time slot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' ``That 70s Show'' and ``The Norm Show'' _ all
OK-to-pretty-good new shows _ survived to see another season
without making such ratings breakthroughs. We TV critics have
special terminology to describe such a circumstance. We call it ``a
lucky break.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long weeks between seasons, however, loyal viewers should
ask themselves: Which, of all the prime-time series aired during
the TV season just done, would you want to watch, start-to-finish,
season premiere to season finale, all over again?
</P>
<P>
   It'd be easy with ``Wind on Water,'' after all. That one lasted
just one episode.
</P>
<P>
   Or ``Conrad Bloom,'' ``Costello, The Secret Lives of Men'' or
``Buddy Faro.'' (On second thought, re-viewing whole seasons of
those shows, however mercifully abbreviated, would be very, very
hard.)
</P>
<P>
   The answer, of course, is none, save one. Rhymes with Bonannos,
kinda.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe two. Rhymes with fortnight. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A lackluster year &QL; 
 &QL; 
The major networks have to be disappointed in their very lackluster
year, shedding overall audience by 7 percent year-to-year. CBS
dropped 8 percent for the season, but still won the ratings race
for total households. NBC was down 15 percent overall. ABC was down
4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The youth-appeal WB grew its audience by 13 percent, which is
why so many new shows next fall will look like something you'd see
on WB. CBS won the overall ratings race, but still skewed so old
that ``mummy'' is its strongest demographic category. In the
advertiser-desired 18-49 demographic, CBS finished fourth. NBC won.
</P>
<P>
   TV's down trend wasn't confined to financial returns.
</P>
<P>
   Although each delivered memorable episodes, even high-quality
stalwarts such as ``NYPD Blue'' and ``Frasier'' suffered uneven
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The fall departure of Jimmy Smits' Bobby Simone was
unforgettable, one of the TV year's dramatic highlights. Rick
Schroder's subsequent arrival was a pleasant surprise, although
there appears to be a risk that his inarticulate character will
suffer week-to-week sameness. Let him have some fun, and fast.
</P>
<P>
   The show's biggest weaknesses now are its serial abuse of the
Sipowicz character _ jeez, does this guy need a break! _ and the
ongoing misuse of female cast members, who provide eye-pleasing
window-dressing while remaining seeming dramatic afterthoughts.
</P>
<P>
   For example: Sharon Lawrence, who played Sipowicz's wife, Sylvia
Costas. Aside from her wonderful work in earlier seasons, she exits
the series as one long missed opportunity. Meanwhile, Medavoy
(Gordon Clapp) and Martinez (Nicholas Turturro), whose quirks and
goofy byplay grow thin in a big hurry, eat up hours and hours of
screen time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frasier,'' suffering by ratings comparison to its time-slot
ancestor ``Seinfeld,'' stumbled through the first half of the
season in an uncharacteristic slump. A series that will be
remembered as one of TV's best and brightest, ``Frasier'' improved
as the season moved on, yet the luster is off of NBC's
once-impenetrable Thursday night ratings champion. With George
Clooney's exit from ``ER,'' only ``Friends'' regularly hit highs
you could classify as must-see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whose Line Is It Anyway?,'' which ABC in the fall will
schedule against NBC's fading Thursday night, became must-see in a
hurry. No show this season packed as many laughs, and there were
few TV thrills to match watching those improv aces, especially
previous TV unknowns Wayne Brady and Colin Mochrie, turn themselves
into instant stars.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's ``Futurama'' came online at midseason and quickly became
one of the few hopeful new series on TV. It's not ``The Simpsons,''
although it was developed by ``Simpsons'' creator Matt Groening.
Then again, the phrase ``It's not `The Simpsons' '' could go for
everything on TV, ever. In the context of everything else on TV
right now, ``Futurama'' leapt immediately onto my 20-best list.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports Night'' was, no question, the most daring new series of
the year, and its renewal by ABC almost makes up for the early
cancellation of ``Cupid,'' a clever romantic comedy that never
found much of an audience. Of all the new shows, ``Cupid'' was the
only near-miss really worth mourning.
</P>
<P>
   Among the established shows that left or were ousted,
``Homicide'' will be the most missed. ``Home Improvement'' had its
fans, few of them TV critics. ``Mad About You'' and ``The Nanny''
also faded into rerun history this spring, surprising many viewers
who didn't know they hadn't died years ago. ``NewsRadio,''
mercilessly bounced around NBC's schedule, was never really given a
chance at viewer vitality.
</P>
<P>
   Next May's big send-off: ``The X-Files.'' The Hype is Already
Out There.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
The violence factor &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the same season where the most critically acclaimed series
was ``The Sopranos,'' the biggest reverberations continue to be the
controversy over violence on television. It's a contradiction
impossible to resolve in a capitalistic nation whose airwaves are
mostly free of government control. But that doesn't keep the battle
from raging.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing the possible cultural culprits in the Columbine
massacre is healthy. Be wary, however, of anybody rushing to place
blame or proscribe instant remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Quick explanations are the only thing that offer any feelings of
security for the future. And so they multiply: It was the video
game, it was the German music. It was the access to guns, or the
lack of enough guns. It was the hatred, or the Internet, or the
parenting.
</P>
<P>
   Out of all of that, television continues to be the easiest
target for culture cops, despite confusion over just how much
violence makes its way to prime-time viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Most TV violence today comes from Hollywood movies viewed on
tape or rebroadcast on cable, newscasts, sports and in reality
programs. Are we willing to prosecute bean-ball pitchers? Make
anchormen serve hard time? Sentence Jean-Claude Van Damme to
eternal VanDamnation? Not likely.
</P>
<P>
   On prime-time series _ the heart and soul of broadcast
television _ evil seldom triumphs, not even the cartoon bad guys on
``Buffy.'' (Evil may be winning on ``The X-Files,'' but how could
you tell?)
</P>
<P>
   Sex is a different story, and maybe the culture cops have a
point here. Broadcast TV continues to bust the boundaries in this
regard, in a futile attempt to compete with cable. Considering how
much time we've all invested in the president's sex life, however,
do you blame the networks for testing limits?
</P>
<P>
   Once you've seen the Starr Report, the naughty jokes on
``Friends'' or the PG-13 nudity of ``NYPD Blue'' seems pretty tame.
</P>
<P>
   True, the TV set is the delivery device for ultraviolent
Hollywood movies (allowing underage kids to bypass multiplex age
restrictions) and video games. Maybe that's where the confusion
starts.
</P>
<P>
   When you're periscoping through pop culture for scapegoats, keep
in mind that advertisers pay a premium for commercial time in shows
that reach young males, primarily because young males just don't
watch much TV.
</P>
<P>
   Violence-prone or otherwise, young males are taking their
cultural cues from sources other than network TV.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Disgust for talk shows
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ``Jenny Jones'' verdict can be read as a collective
expression of disgust for TV talk show standards, or as an
overreaction to an overheated courtroom. Although almost every
legal analysis I've seen or read predicts a reversal and/or
reduction in damages, the subtext is pretty clear: A significant
percentage of Americans evidently believe that a significant
percentage of TV is bad for America. Why, then, does the average
home consume seven hours of it every day?
</P>
<P>
   For a change, although probably not for long, TV executives
appear to be listening to what parents, politicians and culture
critics are saying. (Ratings always tend to speak louder, however,
reflecting reality instead of emotional rhetoric.)
</P>
<P>
   The company that owns ``The Jerry Springer Show'' announced,
again, that the daytime ratings dynamo will retreat from its
attack-TV conventions. In Littleton's wake, blustery talk from
Washington sparked a few TV execs to step back from programs that
could inflame censorship sentiment. A mafia series titled
``Falcone'' probably would've made CBS's fall lineup in other
years. Too violent, at the moment. And in any other spring, WB
wouldn't have hesitated over its ``Buffy'' season finale built
around a high school graduation erupting in mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   A clever fantasy about demons and vampires, ``Buffy'' isn't the
problem. Neither are mob dramas, when well done. Even when they
revel in chillingly casual violence, like a certain spectacular HBO
series.
</P>
<P>
   If violent TV were outlawed, ``The Sopranos,'' a show about
outlaws, would no doubt be, um, outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   You'll take my clicker only by prying it from my cold, dead
hands.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dave Walker can be e-mailed at dave.walker(at)PNI.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
