<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5536 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-GM-DELPHI-ART-     05-28 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-GM-DELPHI-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READING THE SPEEDOMETER OF GM'S SPINOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic of
Delphi vs. S&AMP;P vs. S&AMP;P truck index is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30)  
 (af)  
 By ROBYN MEREDITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, Mich. _ Roughly a million General Motors shareholders will
get an unexpected present when they open their brokerage account
statements for this month: about 70 shares of Delphi Automotive
Systems for every 100 shares of GM they hold, the second part of
GM's divestiture of Delphi, its parts division.
</P>
<P>
   The question, of course, is whether to hold onto an untested
auto parts company or to bail out by selling the shares and
investing the money elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as a choice between racing to your destination in a
cherry-red Corvette or taking a bus: You don't want Delphi if speed
is what you're after, but Delphi is cheap and it should get you
there _ it just might take longer, and the ride could get bumpy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite possible labor troubles and Delphi's overwhelming
dependence on a single ailing customer, many investors are bullish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delphi can be a terrific investment,'' said Thomas F. Marsico,
chairman of Marsico Capital, who holds about four million GM shares
in the various mutual funds and pension accounts he manages.
Marsico likened GM's spinoff of Delphi to AT&AMP;T's spinoff of Lucent
Technologies. ``As it was able to sell its products to other
telecommunications manufacturers,'' he said, ``Delphi should be
able to see a lot of business.''
</P>
<P>
   Others see beauty in a bargain. ``It is hard to find liquid,
large-cap companies that are this cheap,'' said Scott F. Merlis, a
managing director at Wasserstein Perella Securities. Merlis rates
Delphi a ``buy'' and expects it to rise to the high $20s in the
next year. It closed on Friday at $19.625.
</P>
<P>
   Still, because Delphi lacks much of a track record as a public
company, a primer may be in order. Until Friday, when GM spun off
80.1 percent of it to GM shareholders and contributed an additional
2.2 percent to a nonpension retirement plan, Delphi was the 20
percent of GM that made auto parts _ from spark plugs to radios. It
is the nation's 36th-largest company in revenue, and its stock was
recently added to the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index.
</P>
<P>
   In early February, GM sold 100 million Delphi shares _ about
17.7 percent of the company _ in an initial public offering,
raising $1.7 billion. Shares were sold at $17 and closed their
first day at $18.4375.
</P>
<P>
   Some advise caution. ``There are many unknowns,'' said Maryann
N. Keller, an analyst at ING Baring, an investment bank. ``Delphi
right now is going through its coming-out party.''
</P>
<P>
   Delphi's rivals, including Lear, Dana, Johnson Controls and TRW,
have longer track records. But Delphi trades for just 10.3 times
analysts' estimates for 1999 earnings. Johnson Controls, by
contrast, trades for 15.5 times 1999 earnings.
</P>
<P>
   So some say Delphi is a keeper. ``Delphi is attractive,'' said
Nancy T. Dennin, a manager for Legg Mason Total Return Trust, which
owns about 310,000 GM shares. ``The stock is very undervalued.''
</P>
<P>
   Delphi has two big challenges, one short-term and one long-term.
First, analysts worry that Delphi may face a strike this year. The
company's three-year labor contract with factory workers expires
this fall and must be renegotiated.
</P>
<P>
   A strike at GM last year resulted in a special charge of $450
million for Delphi, one of three that contributed to its 1998 net
loss of $93 million. Without them, Delphi would have earned $889
million, down 36 percent from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Longer term, Delphi must win new customers as it holds onto its
business with GM, whose share of the automotive market has been
decreasing. Just $6.2 billion of Delphi's $28.5 billion in sales
last year came from non-GM business.
</P>
<P>
   J.T. Battenberg III, Delphi's chief executive, has set ambitious
goals. By 2002, he wants Delphi to have a return on net assets of
12.5 percent, up from a pro forma 10 percent at the end of 1998,
and to hit a net income margin of 5 percent, up from a pro forma
3.1 percent. He wants earnings per share to grow more than 10
percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   The company may also buy some rivals. But Battenberg promises to
be on the lookout only for those that would add to earnings in the
first full year. ``We're a growth stock at the right price,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In part to help convince investors to keep their shares, Delphi
is spending about $1 million on an ad campaign, starting Sunday, to
introduce itself to people who have never heard of it. In one ad,
an announcer says, ``We're probably in your garage right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Some GM shareholders will be surprised to find Delphi in their
portfolios, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
