<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5545 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-WORLD-BAKU-$ADV30     05-28 1069
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-WORLD-BAKU-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT A CROSSROADS OF AN OIL BOOM, EVERYONE COMES TO CHARLIE'S  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: La.)   (af)  
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAKU, Azerbaijan _ Night is falling over Baku, and Charlie
Schroeder is upset that there aren't any nutshells on the floor of
his bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who comes in gets a free basket of peanuts, and they
throw the shells on the floor, just like they should,'' Schroeder
groused over a glass of imported beer. ``But I can't get my people
to understand that the shells create an atmosphere. They think it's
just a mess, and they go right over and sweep it up. What can you
do?''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the foreigners who are here to ride the great
Caspian oil boom, life without Schroeder is hard to imagine. He has
been in Azerbaijan for eight years, almost as long as the country
has been independent, and his bars and restaurants are temples
where the expatriate community worships.
</P>
<P>
   Boom towns always seem to have someone like him. He is a beacon,
a pillar, a taste of home. He makes money by giving people what
they want, and they love him for it.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of his customers, Schroeder, 58, is a lifelong oil
gypsy. He has worked in most places where oil is produced, always
playing a role similar to the one he fills here. He spent 20 years
in the Middle East, and when rumors about big Caspian Sea oil
strikes began to emerge in the early 1990s, he grabbed the chance
for a new adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder is a supplier by trade. His company, Caspian Sea
Ventures, specializes in obtaining whatever foreign firms here need
but don't have the time or expertise to find and import. He likes
to say that there isn't a product or service he can't provide.
</P>
<P>
   Whether an oil company needs industrial lubricants or computer
disks, whether it wants to commission an underwater survey or
arrange catering for workers on an offshore platform, he can see to
it.
</P>
<P>
   When Schroeder arrived in Azerbaijan, it was a grim place,
spiraling toward anarchy and racked by civil war, hyperinflation
and despair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody held their head up,'' he recalled. ``You never saw a
local person smile. Toilet paper, food, whatever _ they couldn't
buy it and they didn't have it. The government was a mess. When I
say bleak, I mean it was (italics)really(end italics) bleak.''
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder wrought one of the first visible changes in Baku.
Hearing foreigners complain that there was no place for them to eat
or drink, he opened a restaurant and bar that served what he called
``good ol' American food'' like hamburgers and fried chicken, as
well as jambalaya, gumbo and other specialties from his native New
Orleans. The place was an instant hit, and he soon opened a second,
a third and a fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder gives much of the credit for the restaurants' success
to his wife, Marie, who oversees their day-to-day operation. But it
is Schroeder who has established himself as the life of Baku's
party.
</P>
<P>
   At his newest place, Finnegan's, done in an Irish-pub motif,
Schroeder cannot shoot a game of pool without being interrupted a
dozen times by greetings or slaps on the back. Everyone seems to
have a good word for him, right down to the casually dressed fellow
at the bar whom he described as ``the CIA _ I mean, the security
guy at the American embassy.''
</P>
<P>
   Over blackened fish at Schroeder's Ragin' Cajun, or burritos and
refried beans at his Margaritaville, or malt whiskey and peanuts at
Finnegan's, much of the talk is about oil. These are the places to
hear the latest speculation about which wells look good and which
are dogs, or to share the hot gossip about who's up and who's down.
What Schroeder doesn't know about the Caspian oil business is
mostly what he doesn't want to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a living legend,'' said Kerry Karvas, who heads a
geological research firm, as he finished a drink at Finnegan's on a
recent evening. ``Everybody knows him, and everybody respects him.
His handshake is golden. For him to have created what he's got in
Baku is just an outstanding achievement.''
</P>
<P>
   In Azerbaijan, as in much of the former Soviet Union, it is
difficult for businesses to function without judicious applications
of what Westerners might call bribery.
</P>
<P>
   Moving cargo through the Baku airport normally requires the
payment of emoluments, and since both Schroeder's supply business
and his restaurants depend on imports, it is universally assumed
here that he has longstanding financial relationships with many
customs officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' he said with a grin when asked about such practices,
``no comment.'' But he did agree to tell how he persuaded the
airport authorities that there were limits to what he would pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a big shipment of frozen fish and shrimp come in one
time, and they wanted to charge me so much,'' he said. ``Finally I
just said, `OK, you've got the shipment,' and walked out of there.
After a couple of days the stuff began stinking to high heaven.
They didn't know how to get rid of it, and I wouldn't take it. That
cost me a bit, but I loved it. They learned how to get reasonable
after that.''
</P>
<P>
   During the mid-1990s, oil companies and world strategists were
in a frenzy over the Caspian region, sensing that huge fortunes and
the interests of empires were at stake here. A few dry holes and
pullouts by several companies, together with falling oil prices,
have tempered that enthusiasm. Schroeder, however, scoffs at the
doubters.
</P>
<P>
   ``What made everyone nervous is that there was so much hype
here,'' he said. ``The media had it that anywhere you'd pick a hole
in the ground, you'd find oil. But oil men know better. They're
riding this thing out just fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rest assured, there's oil here, from the top of this Caspian
right down to the bottom. All the big players are here. It's all
going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   As he rose to greet yet another customer, Schroeder winced to
see a waitress busily sweeping away a small pile of peanut shells
from under the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just won't listen to me,'' he shrugged. ``And why should
they? These kids are way overqualified. Most of them speak anywhere
from 4 to 13 languages, which makes me sick to my stomach because I
can't even speak English. I speak New Orleans and a little bit of
Texan.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's enough to get along in this world,'' he added,
``and I'm having a hell of a good time doing it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
