r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SPURS-BLAZERS-MAT     05-28 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-BLAZERS-MATCHUPS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN CONFERENCE FINALS MATCHUPS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeds: 1. San Antonio Spurs vs. 2. Portland Trail Blazers
</P>
<P>
   Season series: Spurs, 3-1. All were close games, with Portland
winning by five at home before the Spurs took the last three _ by
one and by eight (in overtime) in San Antonio and 87-81 at the Rose
Garden on May 4 in a game that clinched home-court edge throughout
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Spurs update: This is their fifth appearance in a conference
finals ('79 in the East; '82, '83, '95 in the West) but they are
still looking for their first NBA Finals berth. ... They are glad
to see Portland and not Utah, which eliminated them in '96 and last
season. ... Off since Sunday, they went 8-1 during the season after
at least two days' rest. ... They are 38-6 since March, including
7-1 in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Blazers update: They are in the West finals for the first time
since '92. ... Only reserves Stacey Augmon and Greg Anthony had
ever been on a playoff-series winner before this season. ... They
are a league-best 27-3 at home, including 5-0 in the playoffs. ...
The Blazers reacted as if they had won the NBA championship after
eliminating Utah, with several players taking off their jerseys and
jumping around in a jubilant mosh pit.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Blazers F Stacey Augmon is nursing a sore knee
but is expected to play. The Spurs are healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Point guard: San Antonio's Avery Johnson is responsible for
getting the ball to Tim Duncan, but he has also started making open
jumpers. He has increased his scoring to 15 points per game in the
playoffs and upped his free-throw percentage from 54 to 68.
Portland's Damon Stoudamire is both electric and erratic, and is
often replaced down the stretch by defensive specialist Greg
Anthony. Stoudamire and Anthony are not counted on for scoring,
going a combined 1-of-14 in the Game 6 clincher against Utah. Edge:
Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting guard: A crucial battle between Portland's offensive
leader Isaiah Rider and San Antonio defensive stopper Mario Elie.
The tenacious Elie often frustrated Kobe Bryant in the semifinals,
but will have to deal with a surprisingly strong and focused Rider
on the low blocks. Elie isn't afraid to take the key 3-pointer, but
Rider has flourished under late-game pressure by making his past 22
free throws. Edge: Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Small forward: San Antonio's Sean Elliott has his quickness and
shooting touch back, and is more likely to drive the lane than
Portland's Walt Williams. Basically living on the perimeter,
Williams is averaging only 5.0 points per game and is on the bench
in favor of Rasheed Wallace or Jim Jackson down the stretch. Edge:
Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Power forward: Portland's Brian Grant got the best of Karl
Malone last series despite scoring only 22 points the last three
games. He's a ferocious rebounder and decent passer out of double
teams, but the Spurs have the luxury of playing him straight up
with David Robinson. The former MVP is concentrating more on
defense and rebounding these days, but must avoid the foul trouble
he consistently found against the Lakers. Edge: Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Center: San Antonio's Tim Duncan is the new kid on the blocks,
dominating Shaquille O'Neal to the tune of 70 points in the last
two games of the Spurs' sweep. Portland's Arvydas Sabonis had room
to operate against the Jazz as Utah was forced to double-team Grant
in the low post. But Sabonis will probably settle for top-of-the
key jumpers against San Antonio and get into early foul trouble
against Duncan. Edge: Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Bench: Portland goes nine deep, but counts on just defense from
Anthony and Augmon. Forward Rasheed Wallace, who could start in
this series, dominates smaller defenders in the paint while Rider
backup Jim Jackson made the extra pass and knocked down key free
throws against the Jazz. Because of Malik Rose and Will Perdue, the
Spurs have the bodies to bang with the Blazers inside. San Antonio
needs another good-shooting series from Jaren Jackson, who produced
42 points in the last two games against LA. Edge: Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching: Gregg Popovich resurrected the Spurs from a 6-8 start
by handing the keys to the car over to Duncan. Portland's Mike
Dunleavy was named the NBA coach of the year by juggling
personalities and unprecedented depth. Dunleavy has more options
and isn't afraid to try peculiar lineup combinations in key
situations. Edge: Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Defense wins championships, and, in this case, the
Western Conference finals. The Spurs can play at any pace, winning
games against the Lakers with point totals of 79 and 118. The Spurs
block an average of seven shots a game and will not wilt against
Portland's inside tenacity like Utah did. The Blazers put unmatched
pressure on the ball and have the luxury of a defender in Wallace
who can guard Duncan one-on-one. Portland is on a roll, but
Duncan's emergence has him headed to the Hall of Fame, and his team
into the Finals. Spurs in six.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
