<SLUG> BC-LEGISLATURE-RDP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATIVE BILL MAY BE BIG WINNER WITH TEXAS LOTTERY PLAYERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Friday was a day for legislative compromises
under the Capitol dome, and among the likely winners were Texas
lottery players.
</P>
<P>
   Though final votes remain to be taken before Monday's
adjournment, a bill designed to increase some lottery prizes later
this year was reworked to the satisfaction of both lottery
officials and lawmakers who had alleged that the advertising budget
of the Texas Lottery Commission was excessive.
</P>
<P>
   The deal that was struck will allow scratch-off prizes to
increase in fiscal 2000, which starts Sept. 1, and doesn't require
changes in advertising spending that year. But come fiscal 2001,
for every 1 percent increase in prize payouts for the instant win
games, a reduction of $1 million will be required in advertising
spending the following year, said Rep. Ron Wilson, D-Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's House Bill 844, which was filed in January, has been
pending in a House-Senate conference committee for two weeks to
resolve a dispute that developed when the Senate amended his bill
to place new constraints on the agency's $40 million advertising
budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate wanted the agency, beginning Sept. 1, to reduce
advertising by $1 million for each 1 percent increase in prizes
over the fiscal year 1999 average prize payout.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery officials, who opposed the reduction in advertising
spending, have been hoping for authority to increase prizes since
1997, when lawmakers placed a cap on prizes in the appropriations
bill. The agency has blamed sagging sales in part on the prize
reduction.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1997, there were no specific legal caps on lottery
prizes, though rules were imposed by the commission to limit prizes
to 57.45 percent of proceeds. The 1997 law forced the commission to
lower from 62 percent to 52 percent the total prize payouts for
instant games. It also created a formula that capped online game
prizes at 52.95 percent in fiscal 1998 and 52.45 percent
thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's bill would replace the 1997 law with a new formula. The
cap for online games would not be affected. The overall purpose is
to help the lottery reverse a trend of declining ticket sales by
allowing bigger prizes that could attract more players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first year, the lottery can raise the prize payout up to
the level it was before last session's change, so they can go back
to 57 percent as the total amount for prize payout _ without any
loss in advertising funds,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   After fiscal 2000, ``the advertising will be based on the amount
of prize payout over and above the 52 percent,'' he said. ``So if
they go from 52 percent to 53 percent payout, then the next year,
the budget decrease will be $1 million.''
</P>
<P>
   The lottery bill was one of about 150 measures in House-Senate
conference committees _ the last bills standing as the 76th
Legislature on Saturday entered the 138th day of its 140-day
session. Parliamentary rules require that compromises be put into
writing by midnight Saturday so that members can read the revisions
before final votes as late as Sunday. Monday is devoted to
technical corrections only.
</P>
<P>
   School finance and tax relief measures were the most significant
issues still unresolved, but dozens of other topics were the
subject of feverish bargaining sessions, mainly behind closed
doors.
</P>
<P>
   Unfinished were bills to increase some rural speed limits;
revamp annexation laws; create more district courts; force Austin
to leave open the airport that was closed last weekend; and create
the gang database sought by Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, meanwhile, carried through with his threat to veto a bill
that would have imposed a 2-percent sales tax on fireworks to
establish a Rural Volunteer Fire Department Assistance Program.
Bush said he killed the legislation because it imposed an
``unwarranted tax increase.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the program duplicated the efforts of the
Commission on Fire Protection.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
