<SLUG> BC-JETSKI-POLLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL WATERCRAFT GET POLLUTION RAP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOWE AND CAROLINE LOUISE COLE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAMPTON, N.H. _ When he's jumping waves at 50 mph aboard his
Yamaha Waverider, Marty Melucci knows he isn't the most popular guy
on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``They definitely love to hate us,'' said Melucci, 28, of
Atkinson, N.H. as he waved to other beachgoers Friday while
dismounting his two-month-old jet ski.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it for the speed,'' said Melucci, a salesman for Zales
Jewelers in Salem, N.H. ``I think jet skis have gotten a bad rap.
Sure, you're always going to have some jerks who hug the beach and
cause accidents, but the rest of us who are responsible have a
right to be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Already the scorn of many beachgoers and picnickers who are
annoyed by the noise of their two-cycle, lawnmower-type motors, jet
skis have given the public an additional reason to hate them with a
new report issued this week.
</P>
<P>
   In just three hours of operation, the typical jet ski emits as
much smog-causing unburned gasoline as a new car driven 100,000
miles, according to California Air Resources Board figures cited by
the Izaak Walton League of America, a Maryland conservation group.
</P>
<P>
   And in waters across the country, each year the 1.3 million
personal watercraft (Jet Ski is actually a Kawasaki brand name) in
operation _ which include about 6,600 registered in Massachusetts _
collectively leave an amount of petroleum equivalent to 15 times
the 10.8 million gallons of the 1989 Exxon Valdez disaster, the
conservation group said, citing industry data.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly not against all forms of recreation, but the
issue is whether regulations concerning personal watercraft have
kept up with the pace of technology,'' said Laurie C. Martin, the
study author. ``I don't think a lot of the users have any idea that
they are so highly polluting.''
</P>
<P>
   But an industry leader sharply disputed the figures. ``There
isn't any science to support any of these numbers,'' said John
Donaldson, state affairs director for the Personal Watercraft
Industry Association. ``What we're dealing with is advocacy
organizations that have no responsibility to support facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson said manufacturers have cut emissions levels by 25
percent on this year's models and are on track to meet a federally
mandated 70 percent reduction by 2006.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody would argue that anything we can do to
make the waters of the country cleaner is not a bad goal,''
Donaldson said.
</P>
<P>
   Out at Hampton Beach for a three-hour ride, Melucci concurs with
Donaldson's assessment, claiming that his 1998 Yamaha has the most
recent emissions controls and he doesn't think it is doing much
damage to the Earth's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a scuba diver so the environment's a big deal to me,''
Melucci said. ``That's why I make sure to use special oils that
don't pollute the water as much.''
</P>
<P>
   While noting that the chainsaw-like whine of a personal
watercraft ``drives you crazy after a while,'' the Massachusetts
Environmental Police director, Richard Murray, said since Colonial
times state law has stipulated that everyone has a right to ``fish,
fowl and navigate'' in public waters, including in personal
watercraft. ``We can't restrict jet skis outright, but we can
regulate them,'' said Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last 10 years, personal watercraft _ which can reach 70
mph and provide users with exhilarating opportunities to jump over
waves _ have boomed in popularity. More than 200,000 are sold each
year in the United States, about a third of all new boats.
</P>
<P>
   But two-cycle engines of the kind found on personal watercraft,
snowmobiles, lawnmowers and other devices are far more polluting
than tightly regulated automobile engines and have only recently
come under federal scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials acknowledge that the typical two-cycle engine
emits unburned 25 to 30 percent of the gasoline it uses. Paul
Hansen, executive director of the Izaak Walton League, said US
regulators should demand manufacturers move immediately to adopt
European technology that can cut emissions 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond issues of air and water pollution, the noise, wake and
wildlife impacts of personal watercraft have led to growing moves
to restrict their use or ban them outright.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of complaints we receive has increased markedly,''
said Environmental Police Lt. Larry Chenier, head of its boating
safety bureau. ``A lot of the complaints from the public have to do
with the nuisance factor as much as safety-related concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Since May 1997, Vermont has banned use of personal watercraft in
any body of water smaller than 300 acres, limiting their use to
about 30 of the state's 285 lakes and ponds. Maine has a 200-acre
limit, and use on Lake Tahoe in California and Nevada will be
banned outright next year.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts regulations forbid personal watercraft in lakes
and ponds smaller than 75 acres and forbid high-speed operation
until they are 150 feet offshore.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, the Environmental Police director, said communities that
have recently imposed restrictions beyond state rules on personal
watercraft include Edgartown, Halifax, Lenox, Mashpee, Phillipston,
Tisbury and Webster.
</P>
<P>
   To date, four people have died in Massachusetts personal
watercraft accidents, including, earlier this month, an off-duty
police officer killed at Salisbury Beach.
</P>
<P>
   James Gomes, head of the Environmental League of Massachusetts,
said, ``There are many smaller water bodies in Massachusetts that
are inappropriate for jet skis. They're too polluting, they're too
noisy, and they're too disruptive.''
</P>
<P>
   But Donaldson, of the industry group, said personal watercraft
are ``a reasonable recreational pursuit. We're not saying we demand
unlimited access, but we don't think it's reasonable for people to
call for an outright ban when they haven't tried intermediate
steps. We do realize there has to be flexibility in managing
waterways.''
</P>
<P>
   David Marley, 27, who rode along with Melucci for his first-time
experience Friday, said he can't wait for another chance to try to
try the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you a great sense of freedom,'' said the Haverhill
nutritionist. ``Definitely, I will be back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
