u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HACKERS-U.S.-SITES-NY     05-28 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HACKERS-U.S.-SITES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKERS SHUT DOWN FBI AND SENATE WEB SITES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A cat-and-mouse game between federal agents and
computer hackers took a twist this week as the hackers turned on
their pursuers by disrupting the Internet Web sites of the Federal
Bureau of Investigation and the U.S. Senate, forcing them to remain
shut down Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Both Web sites serve public relations functions, so no
classified, confidential or personal material was compromised.
</P>
<P>
   But as the latest in a series of attacks against government Web
sites, the disruptions underscored the growing concerns of
government investigators that computer systems in many federal
agencies, including those dealing with sensitive material, are too
vulnerable to outside interference.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a critical risk,'' said Jack L. Brock Jr., an official
at the General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of
Congress, who has studied computer systems throughout the federal
government. ``We found that most agencies have weak computer
security systems in place. This is a serious problem,
government-wide.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, the hacking proves to be more annoying than
compromising. This week, for example, vandals succeeded only in
overloading the FBI Web site Wednesday night with requests for
electronic information and in posting inappropriate pictures and
text on the Senate home page.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the authorities said, hackers were retaliating
for raids this week conducted by federal agents against computer
hackers in several states. As a result of the attacks, both sites
were almost immediately shut down as government officials
investigated how the breaches occurred.
</P>
<P>
   But as GAO investigators found by testing government computer
systems in recent years, including those of the Defense Department
and the State Department, hackers can easily do more serious
damage.
</P>
<P>
   At one of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's 10
field centers, investigators reported to Congress that they
``successfully penetrated several mission-critical systems,''
including one that calculates positioning data for earth-orbiting
spacecraft and another that processes data from the spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded, ``We could have disrupted NASA's ongoing
command and control operations and stolen, modified or destroyed
system software and data.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has taken steps to combat threats to
the nation's civilian and military computer systems, including a
directive last May ordering all major departments to develop a plan
to protect their computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Clinton proposed spending $1.46 billion to develop a
``Cyber Corps'' of computer security experts to deal with the same
issues.
</P>
<P>
   But Brock said that while government agencies have been
responding quickly to specific problems, like those encountered
this week by the FBI and the Senate, managers have been slower to
implement long-term solutions that would deny unauthorized access
to their computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   The incidents this week reflected a new aspect of the hacking
wars _ the tenacity and fearlessness of a group of cyber-vandals
who have taunted the investigators trying to track them down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the online version of a tantrum,'' said John
Vranesevich, founder of AntiOnline, a Web site that educates the
public about computer security. ``It's like a parent with a
rebellious 16-year-old who sneaks out of the house, gets punished
and sneaks out again. It's a constant back and forth.''
</P>
<P>
   By Friday afternoon, the FBI and Senate sites were still
inaccessible to the public, and officials at both places said they
did not know when they would be reopened.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Carter, an FBI spokesman, said the bureau shut down its Web
site before the hackers could penetrate so-called firewalls that
protect sensitive information. ``When we detected their activity,''
he said, ``we took the appropriate action.''
</P>
<P>
   But hackers made deeper inroads into the Senate computer system,
leaving an obscene message on Thursday that said the intrusion was
in response to the FBI raids.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Little, a spokeswoman for the office of the Senate
sergeant at arms, which operates the Senate Web site, said
unauthorized pictures and text appeared Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the very latest protective software installed and
updated as recently as two weeks ago,'' Ms. Little said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Web site provides general information on members,
bills before Congress and historical information. The FBI site
contains news releases, crime statistics and general information
about bureau activities, including the FBI's list of the 10 most
wanted fugitives.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   FBI agents declined to discuss bureau activity that might have
precipitated the vandalism.
</P>
<P>
   But Vranesevich said that his organization, which closely
monitors hacking and communicates with hackers through their
computer names, has heard from at least six hackers in four states
_ New York, New Jersey, Texas and Washington _ who said they had
been raided this week by federal agents investigating their
activities. The six, he said, all claimed to know each other.
</P>
<P>
   Vranesevich said the attempts to penetrate the FBI Web site were
led by a hacker known as ``Israeli Ghost'' and came in retaliation
for those raids as well as for the grand jury indictment earlier
this month of Eric Burns, a 19-year-old northern Virginia man known
by his Internet name, Zyklon, which was the name of the gas used by
Nazis to exterminate Jews during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Burns was indicted on three counts of ``computer intrusion'' for
breaking into computers operated by the U.S. Information Agency and
two companies. Federal authorities say he is also believed to be a
member of a group that vandalized the White House public Web site
last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Lloyd, a spokeswoman for the FBI regional office in
Washington, said Burns is scheduled to be arraigned next month in
Alexandria, Va.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
