<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-CHEEVER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEEVER RELIVES THE MOMENT HE WON THE 500 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The words, which came so easily and effortlessly
and served him so well on so many other occasions, escaped Eddie
Cheever Jr. when he arrived in Victory Circle after winning the 82d
Indianapolis 500 last year. Cheever had a microphone shoved in his
face and was asked to describe the range of emotions he felt as a
laurel wreath was draped over his shoulders and a cold bottle of
milk placed in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Emotions? There were so many.
</P>
<P>
   The words to describe them? There were so few.
</P>
<P>
   A man of letters and languages, capable of speaking English,
French, and Italian fluently, Cheever was rendered speechless in
the crowning moment of his racing career after he piloted the car
he owns to victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point in time, I had a team that was vastly
underfinanced, I had a very talented group of people, and I had to
have a good Indy 500,'' Cheever explained. ``I had no choice. I
mean, our company's future depended on it. There was an
unbelievable amount of stress. Throughout the whole 500, I kept
smelling the opportunity, but over 25 years of racing, that had
happened so many times, and so many times I had the rug pulled out
from underneath me that you almost cease to believe that something
good can happen to you.''
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps that was it.
</P>
<P>
   Cheever could scarely believe his good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got down to the last 20 laps and I had the opportunity
to win the race and I knew it was there, the buildup of pressure
was so big,'' he said. ``You focus so hard on what you're doing
that when I actually crossed the start/finish line, I had a hard
time believing it. I mean, I had a very hard time believing it, and
I had all these things going through my mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk about being pumped up on adrenaline. You've been
pumped up on adrenaline for 3 1/2 hours and you've been dodging
bullets and cars are crashing and somebody bumps you from behind
and I almost dragged the fuel pump down the straightaway. I mean,
it's a never-ending roller coaster of emotions, and you have to
keep on being focused.
</P>
<P>
   ``So when I won the race and came into the pits, I was . . . I
had nothing left. I gave everything I had. I had absolutely nothing
left.''
</P>
<P>
   He arrived at Indy this year as a conquering hero, but Cheever
nearly had his triumphant return ruined when he almost suffered the
same fate as Al Unser Jr., who won the 1994 Indy 500 but failed to
qualify the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Cheever averted that embarrassment when he made the field on his
third and final attempt during the first day of qualifications a
week ago. Talk about time trials and tribulations. Cheever was
subjected to a hellish pole day when he was the first to take the
track and turned three quick laps that averaged 221.3 miles per
hour before waving off the fourth and final go-round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we win the village idiot award by not taking that
first run,'' said Cheever of the initial attempt that would've
placed him solidly in the fourth row.
</P>
<P>
   He also waved off his second qualifying attempt, leaving him
with one chance to make the race. With a little less than 1 hour 15
minutes left before the track's closing, Cheever set out on his
third attempt and turned four laps in an average of 221.315 m.p.h.,
good for the No. 16 starting spot in the 33-car grid, just on the
inside of Row 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not at all worried about starting off in the middle of the
pack,'' he said. ``We won last year from the 17th position. But it
was a very difficult day. We were like a dog chasing its tail. We
have a much better team than last year, but we still have a lot of
work to do. The most important thing about the 500 is to be in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely my toughest day as a team owner. But when
I'm out there in my car, it's turn left and go fast. Of all the
open-wheel fans, Indianapolis fans know racing best. There is so
much more attention from the fans. It feels like a family, and I'll
try to win another one for them.''
</P>
<P>
   And maybe this time he'll have something profound to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was way too powerful of an emotion,'' Cheever said,
recalling that glorious moment in Victory Circle. ``It was very
hard. It was like seeing your first child born. It's hard to
define, but I was very happy. I still am. So I told the story of my
dad (who had told Cheever that if he was going to win only one
race, the Indy 500 should be the one), which was on my mind. That
was what I said. But I'd rather be remembered for the good driving
I did in the Indy 500 than for something I said afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   Or didn't say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
