<SLUG> BC-KIDDIE-RIDES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHLAND THEME PARKS   THINKING SMALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Sidebars slugged UNIVERSAL-KIDS and KIDDIE-PARKS)  
By CHRIS J. PARKER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Six Flags Magic Mountain has discovered that
teen-agers have little sisters and brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe the brain trust at Scream Central just noticed that
most of their customers are 5-, 6- and 8-year-olds before they turn
into thrill-seeking, money-spending teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   That's the only conclusion possible after spending a day at the
all-new Bugs Bunny World, which opened Thursday. It is Magic
Mountain for the under-4-foot crowd, complete with mini-thrill
rides and interactive zones. Even the drinking fountains are
kid-sized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll never lose site of the fact that we own the thrill
market in Southern California,'' said Andy Gallardo, spokesman for
the Santa Clarita park. ``What we wanted to do was add an area that
brought thrills to the younger guests.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Magic Mountain has always had an area for the prepubescent
sect. But what began as a rather sad little troll village nearly
three decades ago had never gotten much better than a carnival
sideshow.
</P>
<P>
   Until now.
</P>
<P>
   The new Bugs Bunny World has more rides, better attractions and
just more stuff for the Nickelodeon generation than anything Magic
Mountain has done before.
</P>
<P>
   There are eight new rides and a handful of new attractions,
including a petting zoo and a new animal show. All of it is wrapped
up in a Bugs Bunny-themed bow, from the ties worn by ride operators
to the cartoonish-looking flowers and plants. Even the shrubbery
islands have been kid-sized so the youngsters can sit down without
needing a lift up from mom or dad.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the new kids zone is Looney Tunes Lodge, a
6,000-square-foot, two-story-tall hall filled with thousands of
foam balls. Kids can throw the balls at their friends. Kids can
throw the balls through hoops and holes. Kids can put the balls in
toy cannons and shoot them across the lodge. It's a
Colossus-strength ball pit; bigger, louder and more entertaining
than any fast-food play area.
</P>
<P>
   Magic Mountain also has upgraded its mini-roller coaster from
previous incarnations, ratcheting up the highest points and
twisting the curves a little tighter. In fact, many of the new
rides at Bugs Bunny World are either juiced-up kids' rides or
smaller versions of Magic Mountain's big-kid rides, depending upon
your perspective.
</P>
<P>
   Canyon Blaster is a small version of Psychlone (OK, a much
smaller version). Sylvester's Pounce and Bounce is a two-story tall
version of Freefall, only Pounce and Bounce drops slower and
bounces as it drops, making it feel like riders are sitting on a
big spring.
</P>
<P>
   One thing the younger crowd will appreciate is that all the
rides are big enough for parents to ride along, too. If the ride
gets too intense, Mom or Dad is just a bucket seat away.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's rather ingenious of Magic Mountain to give its kids'
rides some adrenaline. Once they've graduated from Sylvester's,
they can bounce over to Freefall or maybe the 41-story-tall
Superman: The Escape, which towers over Bugs Bunny World.
</P>
<P>
   For kids who want tame rides, Bugs Bunny World has a new
pint-sized train and its long-running small carousel. There's also
Yosemite Sam's Flight School, an airplane ride not unlike
Disneyland's Dumbo ride; Pepe Le Pew's Tea Party, which is a lot
like Disney's tea cups; and Taz's Trucking Company, a miniature
Autopia with 4x4 trucks instead of those Ramblers at Fantasyland.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but it's hard to walk through the kids' section of an
amusement park without thinking about The House The Mouse Built.
How do Bugs' new digs stack up? It's fair to say Magic Mountain
does kid stuff about as well as Disneyland does thrill rides _ not
great but certainly not bad.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Magic Mountain isn't the only Southern California
amusement park hoping to attract the entire family. Disney
practically invented the bait-the-kid-and-hook-her-dad's-wallet
trick, and it's spent the last 40 years or so perfecting its small
kids' world.
</P>
<P>
   Now, other amusement parks realize that the best way to steer
minivans into their parking lot is from the car seat in the back.
Children control their family's spending habits and amusement park
choices as sure as there's a ``Rugrats'' video in the VCR and
Disney sheets on the beds.
</P>
<P>
   Legoland wasn't built in north San Diego County to attract
Marines from Camp Pendleton. It opened this spring a few plastic
blocks away from Interstate 5, within shouting distance of the car
loads of vacationers shuttling between San Diego and L.A. Shouting
distance, as in, ``Mommy, I wanna go there!''
</P>
<P>
   Universal Studios Hollywood is unveiling new attractions this
summer for Nick kids, literally. They include ``Blue's Clues
Live,'' a live version of the hugely popular Nickelodeon cable
television show, and an eating area where kids can have breakfast
with their favorite Rugrats, Marvel and Universal cartoon
characters.
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes Magic Mountain's new Bugs Bunny World both
impressive and imperative. Magic Mountain had always been able to
attract teen-agers looking for a good scream; now, as its
competition diversifies, it also figured out a way to get the rest
of the family out of the car. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
