<SLUG> BC-BOEING-ISRAEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING SWEETENS DEAL TO TRY TO LAND ISRAELI ORDER FOR FIGHTER
JETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In a last-ditch effort to improve its chances of
winning a crucial order, The Boeing Co. has sweetened its bid to
build fighter jets for Israel by offering companies in that country
an additional $500 million in subcontracting work, a Boeing
spokesman confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   The latest offer was delivered personally to the Israeli Defense
Ministry by John Boyle, vice president for international
development for Boeing's military aircraft division.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is expected to decide soon whether to buy about $2.5
billion in new fighters from Boeing or Lockheed Martin, and it has
been pressing both defense contractors for steep discounts.
</P>
<P>
   The competition is between Boeing's F-15 and Lockheed Martin's
F-16.
</P>
<P>
   The fighter plane order, the largest ever by Israel, is
considered critical for Boeing, which recently announced that it
will cut up to 7,000 jobs by 2001 at its fighter plant in St. Louis
because of a lack of orders for its F-15 and F-18C/D fighters.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Israel ordered 25 of the most advanced version of the
Boeing fighter, the F-15I. The last of those planes recently was
delivered. The only F-15s still in the production line are
replacement planes for the U.S. Air Force and the last of a
72-plane order for Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing decided to cut its St. Louis work force after Greece last
month opted to buy Lockheed's fighter. Boeing had been counting on
Greece to order more than 35 F-15s, which could have extended
production of the fighter for another two years.
</P>
<P>
   The F-15 line will shut down early next year, and the F-18C/D
line later in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Boeing wins new orders from Israel, deliveries would not
begin until 2001, and that means a break in the F-15 line when the
last plane now on order is delivered early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The F-15 has been a highly profitable fighter for Boeing, and
company executives are doing all they can to win the competition
with Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Israel is an important strategic customer of Boeing,'' said
Jim Schlueter, spokesman for Boeing's international fighter sales.
</P>
<P>
   He confirmed that Boeing, in its latest proposal to Israel, had
offered to provide an additional $500 million in so-called offset
work. Boeing already provides companies in Israel with about $1.7
billion in contract work.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's air force reportedly recommended earlier this month
that the government award the $2.5 billion fighter-plane contract
to Lockheed Martin.
</P>
<P>
   At about $60 million to $80 million apiece, the more advanced
F-15 from Boeing cost twice as much as Lockheed's F-16. That means
Israel could get more more F-16s for its money.
</P>
<P>
   There is still a possibility Israel will split the order between
Boeing and Lockheed Martin, according to defense experts.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Moshe Arens was expected to announce the winner
of the competition a couple weeks ago. Instead, Boeing and Lockheed
Martin were asked to sweeten their respective bids.
</P>
<P>
   The deal has been complicated by the recent election of the
Labor Party's Ehud Barak to the prime minister's post. Arens, of
the Likud Party, has not indicated if he will make a decision on
the fighter plane order before he leaves office when Barak takes
over as prime minister next month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
