r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDDIE-PARKS-LADN     05-28 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDDIE-PARKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S NEW FOR THE UNDER-4-FOOT SET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking for something a bit more, well, MORE for your Rugrat?
Forget the neighborhood park _ here's where loaded minivans are
going this summer: &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE ATTRACTION: Club Disney, 1205 S. Westlake Blvd., Thousand Oaks.
(805) 777-8000.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCOOP: ``Honey, I shrunk Disneyland ... and put it in a
strip mall.'' A 25,000-square-foot multimedia fun zone that
includes a 30-foot-tall climber with tubes and slides; an Internet
exploration room dubbed the Mouse Pad; and Fantasy Fashion Show,
where kids can dress up as their favorite Disney character.
</P>
<P>
   THE UPDATE: Tarzan's Jungle Club opens in mid-June. What a
coincidence! ``Tarzan,'' the Disney animated movie, opens in
mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   THE COST: $4 for adults, $8 for children 2 to 11. Party rates
and special packages also available.
</P>
<P>
   THE BOTTOM LINE: Kids love it for birthday parties, parents love
it because they don't have to walk from Bear Country to
Tomorrowland and back. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE ATTRACTION: Disneyland, 1313 Harbor Blvd., Anaheim. (714)
781-4560.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCOOP: It's a small kids' world, after all.
</P>
<P>
   THE UPDATE: Tarzan's Treehouse, which replaces the 37-year-old
Swiss Family Treehouse, opens in late June. What a coincidence!
``Tarzan,'' the Disney animated movie, opens in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   THE COST: $39 for adults, $37 for seniors 60 years old and over,
$29 for children 3 to 11 and free for children under 3.
</P>
<P>
   THE BOTTOM LINE: Mickey Mouse, Snow White, Pluto ... . You know
these names better than the names of your kids' friends. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE ATTRACTION: Knott's Berry Farm, 8039 Beach Blvd., Buena Park.
(714) 220-5200.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCOOP: Orange County's !ital!other amusement park includes
Camp Snoopy, a six-acre section with more than 30 rides and
attractions.
</P>
<P>
   THE UPDATE: ``Snoopy's Extremely Cool Summer,'' a loose tie-in
for this summer's extreme sports displays and Wild West stunt shows
(hence, ``Extremely'') and for the annual summer ice show (hence,
``cool'').
</P>
<P>
   THE COST: The regular price is $36 for adults, $26 for children
3 to 11 and seniors over 60. But all summer, Southern California
residents get in at a reduced price: $29 for adults, $13 for kids 3
to 11.
</P>
<P>
   THE BOTTOM LINE: If your kid likes Snoopy, the Old West, extreme
sports or jelly, she'll like Knott's. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE ATTRACTION: Legoland, 1 Legoland Drive, Carlsbad. (760)
918-5346.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCOOP: Southern California's newest amusement park is built
for kids, one plastic brick at a time. The 128-acre park features
40 attractions, rides and shows. Approximately 30 million Lego
bricks were used to build 5,000 Lego models.
</P>
<P>
   THE UPDATE: Opened in March, it's already San Diego County's
favorite attraction sans animals.
</P>
<P>
   THE COST: $32 for adults, $25 for seniors over 60 and children 3
to 16. Children under 3 are free.
</P>
<P>
   THE BOTTOM LINE: Try not to calculate how many Lego blocks you
could buy at Toys R Us for the $25 kids admission. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
THE ATTRACTION: Six Flags Magic Mountain, 26101 Magic Mountain
Parkway, Valencia. (661) 255-4111.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCOOP: Southern California's roller-coaster king turns its
attention to the under-4-foot crowd.
</P>
