u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAGAN-KIDNAP-645&AMP;ADD-     05-28 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAGAN-KIDNAP-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEA DEAL APPROVED FOR KIDNAPPER OF TWO DAUGHTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Fla., Va.)  (lb) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Stephen Fagan, the Massachusetts father who
absconded with his two daughters nearly 20 years ago and raised
them in Palm Beach-style prosperity until he was caught last year,
clinched a plea deal on Friday that lets him off with no jail time.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon, a Massachusetts Superior Court justice
approved the bargain: Fagan pleaded guilty to kidnapping and must
serve 2,000 hours of community service in a Florida hospital and
donate $100,000 to the New England Home for Little Wanderers, which
helps at-risk children, in his ex-wife's name. He also received a
suspended three-to-five-year sentence and five years of probation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Fagan's guilty plea, to which his ex-wife agreed, he
exhibited no regret: ``I believed at the time it was the right
decision,'' he told reporters outside the courthouse, referring to
his 1979 decision to steal his daughters, then 5 and 2, from an
ex-wife he described as dangerously neglectful. ``I still believe
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone hoping for the ultimate satisfying conclusion to the
Fagans' tale _ a moving reunion between the two daughters, now 25
and 22, and the mother they had long been told was dead _ would
have been deeply disappointed by day's end.
</P>
<P>
   The mother, Barbara Kurth, now an immunologist at the University
of Virginia Medical School, did not see her daughters sitting far
across the large hall when she entered the courtroom, and appeared
never to make eye contact with them. She left immediately after the
judge's decision, and her relatives said that the daughters have
yet to respond to her overtures toward a reconnection.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the daughters, Rachael and Lisa Martin, kept up the
solid wall of loving support for their father that they have
maintained since he was arrested and the case gained national
attention last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wish to thank our father for the many sacrifices he has
made on our behalf,'' they said in a statement to the court. ``For
the past two decades, he has forgone his identity, his profession,
and the comfort of family and friends for our well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference, the daughters refused to discuss any plan
to reconcile with their mother, and said they had been thinking
only of their father. Asked whether they were condoning kidnapping,
Rachael Martin said: ``We're not here to judge the law or the
people who apply it. We're simply here to say we support our father
and love him very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kurth and her relatives described the daughters' reaction as
typical for kidnapped children who bond tightly with the abductor
who becomes their only anchor in the world. And though prosecutors
said that Dr. Kurth had agreed to the plea bargain, there was no
joy in the Kurth camp on Friday, in contrast to the celebratory
dinner-cum-photo-op that Fagan held with his daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only victory here would have been for my daughters to have
known and loved me for the past 20 years,'' Dr. Kurth said in a
written statement.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the case offered no easy out to either side. A lengthy,
media-ridden trial could have harmed the daughters, prosecutors
said; and yet Fagan was accused of serious crimes: two counts of
kidnapping and one of contempt of court, potentially enough to net
him more than 20 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he claimed that he had feared for the girls'
safety with his wife, and his lawyer accused her of getting into an
accident with them while driving drunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no perfect sentences that can be imposed,'' Judge
Peter Lauriat said in a statement. At best, he said, the sentence
``may allow the Fagans' two daughters to move forward with their
lives and begin to reconnect, free of the burden of participating
in a highly charged and surely an emotionally draining criminal
trial that would have no doubt been surrounded and enveloped by the
ever-present media.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   No doubt. The Fagan case splashed repeatedly across national
television shows last spring, a real-life drama with several strong
elements: the amazing amount of time Fagan managed to live under an
assumed name and various false guises in Florida; the fact that he
was ultimately caught; the unswerving loyalty of his daughters and
the long nightmare of his ex-wife.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kurth did not speak on Friday, but in an article due to
appear in the July issue of Good Housekeeping magazine, she says:
``A lot of people have asked me how I feel. It's a question that
absolutely stumps me, because I feel many, many ways. If you felt
it, what I feel, this house would be in a shambles from the force
of it. It is so beyond `saddened' or any other word.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
