u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURKEY-POLITICS-445&AMP;A     05-28 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-POLITICS-445&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURKISH PREMIER ASSEMBLES RULING COALITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit, who has headed
a caretaker government since elections last month, said Friday that
he had assembled a three-party coalition to govern Turkey for the
next five years.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition is based on an alliance between two parties that
have traditionally been bitter rivals. Their street battles in the
1970s cost more than 5,000 lives and led to such chaos that many
Turks welcomed the military coup of 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Ecevit heads the Democratic Left Party, and his new partner in
power, Devlet Bahceli, heads the Nationalist Movement Party, which
for years embraced far-right politics and violence. It says it has
matured and embraced democratic principles.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their differences, both Ecevit and Bahceli are strong
Turkish nationalists. Both oppose any compromise with Kurdish
rebels, or with Greece over issues relating to Cyprus or the
Aegean.
</P>
<P>
   ``I beseech God to put this government at the service of the
Turkish nation,'' Bahceli said at a news conference at which the
coalition agreement was announced.
</P>
<P>
   The junior partner in the new coalition is to be the
center-right Motherland Party, which is headed by former Prime
Minister Mesut Yilmaz. It will control the Finance Ministry, a
signal to financial markets and foreign lending institutions that
have confidence in Yilmaz.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats were encouraged to learn that Foreign Minister
Ismail Cem, whose diplomatic skills and pro-Western orientation are
widely respected, will remain in office. The coalition is subject
to a parliamentary vote expected next week, but since the three
parties composing it hold 351 of the 550 seats, the vote is
expected to be a formality.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether the two principal coalition
leaders, Ecevit and Bahceli, will be able to put aside the hatred
that separated their parties in the past. This month Ecevit's wife,
Rahsan, voiced the doubts that many members of her party have about
their new coalition partners.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past they put pressure on adolescents and armed them,''
Mrs. Ecevit said. ``They told them, `Either you will be on our side
or you will die.' They sponsored gangs that took so many lives over
the years. Is it easy to forget that pain?''
</P>
<P>
   Turkey has been troubled by political instability, with five
governments in the last four years. Some politicians predicted that
the new coalition would not survive for its full term. ``I doubt
that this government will last two years, much less five,'' said
Recai Kutan, leader of the Islamic-oriented Virtue party.
``governments formed on the basis of contradictions do not survive
long.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ecevit, a poet and Sanskrit scholar who turned 74 on Friday, has
been a figure in Turkish politics for more than 40 years. He is
best known for ordering Turkish troops to land on the contested
island of Cyprus when he was prime minister in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Although he shares the view of most Turkish leaders that Kurdish
fighters are no more than terrorists, Ecevit may play a crucial
role in the case of the imprisoned Kurdish guerrilla leader
Abdullah Ocalan.
</P>
<P>
   Ocalan's trial for treason is to begin on Monday. His conviction
is widely considered a foregone conclusion, and he will probably be
sentenced to hang. But Parliament must approve all death sentences,
and Ecevit, a lifelong foe of the death penalty, has said he will
do whatever he can to prevent an execution.
</P>
<P>
   In another indication that he is concerned about foreign
reaction to the Ocalan trial, Ecevit urged this week that the trial
be postponed until the military member of the three-judge security
court is replaced by a civilian. The European Court of Human Rights
has called Turkey's security courts illegitimate because of the
military judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ocalan's trial may be postponed by a reform of the security
courts,'' Ecevit said in a newspaper interview published on
Thursday. ``We are considering a constitutional amendment to
replace the military judge with a civilian one. This amendment will
be the first proposal the new government will present to
Parliament. All the other parties have pledged to support us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
