<HEADER>
A5582 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-CITIES-TECH-ART-2     05-28 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-CITIES-TECH-ART-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURING (WIDELY) FORTH WITH CITY HALL CAPITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Conn., N.J.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30)  
 (af)  
 By MICHAEL BRICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cities and states everywhere long to be the next Silicon
Someplace. Many have used tax money to set up business incubators
and promote their attractions to entrepreneurs; some even throw
subsidies and tax relief at technology companies to lure them to
set up shop, create jobs and join the local tax rolls.
</P>
<P>
   But as a piece of civic boosterism, the Prospect Street NYC
Discovery fund is a strange animal.
</P>
<P>
   It was created in 1995 by the city of New York to invest in
fledgling technology companies, using tax money and contributions
from several of the city's utilities. At the time, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani said the city expected the fund's activities to generate
4,000 new local jobs, foster a hot new business sector and maybe
even earn a decent return on the investment.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the fund's returns have indeed been decent,
though far from stellar. But the fund has sometimes strayed from
its other goals. Few new jobs have been created directly, and
several of the fund's investments have been in companies with a
tenuous connection to high technology and none at all to the city.
</P>
<P>
   Among the major beneficiaries of the fund's activities have been
the people who run it. Executives at Prospect Street Ventures, the
New York-based venture capital firm paid by the city to operate the
fund, have also been compensated in cash and stock option grants by
companies in which the fund has invested, for serving on their
boards of directors.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's initial capital of $30 million in equity _ $10
million of it from city coffers _ and $26 million in Small Business
Administration loans has since grown to $76 million, with $48.3
million invested in 11 companies and the rest in liquid investments
awaiting deployment.
</P>
<P>
   Prospect Street executives now sit on the boards of nine of
those companies, positioning them to reap windfalls if the
companies prove successful.
</P>
<P>
   It is common for major early investors in a start-up company to
get seats on the board, so they can keep a close watch on their
investments and help the company grow. Prospect Street, which also
invests for private-sector funds, routinely asks for such
representation when the Discovery fund invests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a hard-and-fast rule,'' said Stephen G. Hall, a
principal at Prospect Street. ``But getting a board seat is
typically a prerequisite.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Discovery fund's case, it is public money that the
managers are investing and risking, while they personally reap the
rewards of the board seats. ``We're aware of this arrangement,''
said Bernadette O'Leary, a spokeswoman for the city's Economic
Development Corp., which oversees the fund. ``It's very standard
for the industry and it's in keeping with our agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   John F. Barry, the managing partner of Prospect Street, is
himself on the boards of eight companies that have received money
from the Discovery fund, including two that reported the
compensation of their directors to the Securities and Exchange
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Those documents show that Barry has personally received cash,
stock and stock options for his services _ for example, 18,750
shares of 24/7 Media, a New York-based Internet advertising company
whose stock has risen sharply since its initial public offering in
1998 and closed on Friday at $28.50.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said the compensation is justified because ``there needs to
be appropriate incentives to take on that liability'' of being a
director, and added that Barry holds such stock and options on
behalf of his firm, Prospect Street Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the executives work for the money. A new Internet
company can consist merely of a couple of sharp programmers with a
bright idea but no management experience. Experienced directors
like the Prospect Street executives often help shape business plans
and recruit crucial employees. (Prospect Street highlights on its
Web site the hands-on role of its executives in companies in which
it invests.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   That kind of work has helped the fund post a cumulative return
of 108 percent over four years _ not bad, though many
technology-stock mutual funds have gained far more during the same
period.
</P>
<P>
   City officials say the fund's activities have helped accelerate
the creation of Silicon Alley, a district in Manhattan extending
roughly from the Flatiron Building to the financial district where
Internet companies congregate. They say they are pleased with the
results, though they acknowledge that Silicon Alley grew mostly on
its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if somebody in city hall said, `Hey, I know, let's
get a bunch of kids in their 20s with shoulder-length ponytails,
give them computers and see what happens,'' said Charles Millard,
the director of the city development agency, who is resigning to
become a managing director at Prudential Securities. ``They simply
try to help the market that has occurred on its own function more
powerfully.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund's managers estimate that its investments have created
600 jobs so far.
</P>
<P>
   Prospect Street was selected from among four bidders to manage
the fund. Its mission was to find suitable New York City technology
companies for $1 million to $6 million investments. Almost
immediately, records of the fund's investments indicate, Prospect
Street began to stray from the target.
</P>
<P>
   Some $3 million went into Bondnet Trading Systems, a Connecticut
operator of an Internet securities trading service. Barry was named
chairman and chief executive of Bondnet, and Hall was named to the
board. Investing in a Connecticut technology company was
appropriate, Hall said, because most of its business was done in
New York. The company's assets were bought by the Bank of New York
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The fund also invested in All Service Computer Rental, an
Englewood, N.J., company that seems to fit none of the fund's
stated purposes: It is not in New York, has no direct ties to
Internet commerce and, having been in business since 1985, is not a
fledgling. ``The most important goal of the fund is to receive a
return,'' Hall said. ``It's our most profitable company.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund's very first investment was also of questionable
relevance, and has performed terribly. In July 1995, when the fund
was less than two months old, Prospect Street bought 1.09 million
shares of Skyline Multimedia Entertainment, which operates a
virtual-reality ride at the Empire State Building and an arcade
near Times Square, at $2.75 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Barry joined Skyline's board and by November 1996 had been
personally granted options to buy 10,000 shares of Skyline stock at
$3.50 to $5 a share.
</P>
<P>
   The next month, the company began work on a new virtual-reality
ride in Sydney, Australia, and sank nearly $1 million into film
footage for it; the project collapsed when a lease fell through.
Around the same time, the company made substantial loans to one of
its executives.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Discovery fund pumped in capital, $500,000 more in
1997 and a further $435,000 in 1998, while the stock was losing
nearly all its value; on Friday, it traded for 6.25 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very common for a venture capital firm to continue
investing in a company that we think has potential,'' Hall said.
``We have some investments that are all-stars and some that are
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, the fund has also found successful Internet
companies in which to invest, including Multex, Miningco.com (since
renamed About.com) and 24/7 Media. Dean Margolis, chief executive
of Comet Systems, which has grown to employ 40 people in New York,
said Prospect Street chipped in $2.4 million of the company's $2.5
million in start-up capital.
</P>
<P>
   But of the 14 Manhattan technology companies that planned public
offerings in the second quarter of 1999, only one, Juno Online
Services, has received money from the Discovery fund. Juno went
public last Wednesday at $13 a share and closed on Friday at
$12.25.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really in the business of looking into the future,''
Barry said. ``Unfortunately, no one has given us a crystal ball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5584 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-CABINET-600&AMP;ad     05-28 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CABINET-600&AMP;add-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S FINANCE MINISTER QUITS, AFTER 3 DAYS ON THE JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MICHAEL WINES    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Russia's finance minister, who was recently elevated to
the post of first deputy prime minister for financial matters, quit
Friday night after only three days in his new job, the apparent
casualty of an extraordinary struggle between advisers seeking the
blessing of President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of Mikhail Zadornov was a clear blow to Russia's
new prime minister, Sergei Stepashin, who has staked much of his
reputation on his power to choose the top officials of his
two-week-old government.
</P>
<P>
   Zadornov, an economist, had been elevated by Stepashin from
finance minister to first deputy, a post in which he was to oversee
macroeconomic issues and Russia's dealings with international
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview Friday night, Zadornov said he had
quit because Yeltsin had refused to combine his new job with his
old duties as finance minister. Stepashin seemed to confirm that
arrangement earlier this week, only to see Yeltsin reverse it and
appoint a new finance minister, Mikhail Kasyanov, Friday. ``To keep
doing our task, we need to have a single-minded bloc,'' Zadornov
said. ``My proposal on this didn't get support from the Kremlin.''
</P>
<P>
   But an underlying explanation widely accepted by political
experts here, though with no direct proof, is that Zadornov was
shoved out of the government by supporters of Boris Berezovsky, the
supposed multibillionaire businessman and political tactician.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky is said to be very close to Yeltsin's daughter and
senior adviser, Tatyana Dyachenko. Under indictment and written off
as a political has-been just a month ago, Berezovsky seems to have
staged a comeback and is now fighting for control of key posts in
Yeltsin's government.
</P>
<P>
   In that view, the losers Friday were the supporters of another
Yeltsin adviser who is bitterly opposed to Berezovsky, Anatoly
Chubais.
</P>
<P>
   Chubais, one of the original planners of Russia's transition to
capitalism, resigned from the government following last year's
economic collapse. But he has remained close to Yeltsin and, like
Berezovsky, has been battling to retake a share of his lost power.
</P>
<P>
   Zadornov, 36, was an original member of Chubais' economic team
and enjoyed his backing as finance minister. Interfax, the Russian
news agency, suggested Friday night that the apparent new finance
minister, Kasyanov, has the support of Berezovsky.
</P>
<P>
   Were that to prove true, it would leave Stepashin in nominal
control of the government, but would place much of the real power _
control over most government finances _ in the hands of
Berezovsky's allies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The finance minister's post is among the most important in the
government because of Russia's delicate relations with western
lenders. Kasyanov is not inexperienced in fiscal affairs. He has
managed Russia's place in the London Club, the group of nations
that is owed debt by commercial entities of the former Soviet
Union.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he clearly was not Zadornov's choice as a successor.
Speaking on the NTV television network Friday night, Zadornov said
Kasyanov's duties are but a small part of the Finance Ministry's
portfolio, and that the critical job _ negotiating with the Russian
legislature and the International Monetary Fund on measures to
shore up Russia's shaky finances _ is ``not his field.''
</P>
<P>
   The IMF has frozen a recent decision to begin doling out a $4.45
billion loan to the Russian government until the political
situation becomes clearer. Zadornov said talks with leaders at the
fund on a new lending package are close to completion, and that it
will be discussed at a meeting of top government officials that
Stepashin has called for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Zadornov said he still plans to attend that session, and he
expressed concern that talks with international lenders will be
delayed by the latest change. ``We've been coming out of a very
difficult six months,'' he said. ``We're ready for the last step.
It's not all as difficult as the press has indicated it might be.
But it's a very important step for the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The larger question may be what happens now to Stepashin, who
also enjoys Chubais' backing. Another Berezovsky ally, Nikolai
Aksyonenko, is nominally first deputy prime minister for industrial
policy, but he has repeatedly insisted that his job includes the
government's entire fiscal portfolio, including the broad
macroeconomic duties that Zadornov has now given up.
</P>
<P>
   One leading American analyst of Russian politics, Thomas Graham
of the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, said Friday
night that Berezovsky's hand was clearly reflected in Zadornov's
resignation. ``It's very much a struggle over who is going to be
the presidential candidate in the year 2000,'' he said, referring
to the candidate who will enjoy the government's backing. ``And
neither Berezovsky nor Chubais has a horse in this race.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, until recently an American diplomat in Moscow, said the
question may be whether Stepashin remains prime minister or whether
Aksyonenko eventually replaces him.
</P>
<P>
   Neither is well known, and neither has any proven campaign
skills. But merely being prime minister confers an advantage on any
candidate, because of the enhanced visibility in Russia and the
resources of the government are at his disposal.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin already has been suggested as a potential candidate
backed by the Yeltsin team. But Yeltsin stirred much speculation
earlier this month when, in conversations with two legislators, he
said that Aksyonenko _ not Stepashin _ was his first choice as
prime minister. He later changed his mind and asked the parliament
to confirm Stepashin in the post.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night, Russian legislators were writing Stepashin off
within minutes of Zadornov's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Grigory Yavlinsky, the head of the liberal Yabloko Party and a
likely presidential candidate himself, said Zadornov's departure
``indicates that Sergei Stepashin is not independent in forming the
government and that puppeteers continue to lead the government
personnel selection process.''
</P>
<P>
   The communist speaker of parliament's lower house, Gennadi
Zyuganov, told Interfax that the resignation means that
``everything depends on the sentiments of somebody hard to
identify, most likely on the sentiments of the presidential or
next-to-presidential team.
</P>
<P>
   ``When two bears mess about in the same pit, we get such a
result,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
