<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SPURS-JOHNSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN ANTONIO GUARD AVERY JOHNSON EARNS RESPECT IN SPURS' TITLE
DRIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ He was the guy nobody wanted. Even the team that
currently signs his checks gave up on him _ twice.
</P>
<P>
   In Avery Johnson's first seven NBA seasons, he played for five
organizations. That includes three separate stints with his current
employers, the San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   A lesser man might have given up basketball and moved on to
another profession. But Johnson, a self-made basketball player,
doesn't question why his NBA journey was paved with so many broken
dreams now that he is the point man _ and even at 6-foot-2 a
pivotal player _ for the Spurs' NBA title run, which continues
today with Game 1 of the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think those situations happened for a reason,'' said
Johnson, the Spurs' starting point guard and a devout Christian.
``I needed those situations to happen, mainly to make me a better
man rather than a better basketball player.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has been a catalyst for a Spurs team that has advanced
to the Western Conference finals for the second time in the past
five years. His 15.1 points per game in the playoffs is second on
the team to Tim Duncan, and Johnson's steady outside shooting has
helped a Spurs attack that rides the inside play of Duncan and
David Robinson. He is also dishing out 7.5 assists per game and
committing just 2.7 turnovers per contest.
</P>
<P>
   Since signing with Seattle as a free-agent rookie in 1988,
Johnson has played for Denver, San Antonio, Houston, San Antonio,
Golden State and San Antonio again. Moving his wife and two
children across the country came with the territory, if Johnson
wanted to realize his dream.
</P>
<P>
   During Johnson's rookie season with Seattle, then-Mavericks
point guard Derek Harper who now plays for the Lakers, served as a
mentor.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the guy that used to come out on the court early before
the games and work out and tell me what I had to do to improve in
this league,'' Johnson said. ``I spent time with him off the court
when he was in Dallas, and throughout the years.
</P>
<P>
   ``So he's always been one of my role models with his toughness
and his professionalism. Guys like that who've been instrumental in
my success, I really want to make them proud of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider Harper proud, although he wasn't too thrilled that
Johnson and the Spurs eliminated the Lakers on Sunday to cap a
four-game sweep in the Western Conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``A.J. is one of those guys who's been forced to pay some
dues,'' Harper said. ``He went down and worked his way back up.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you get an opportunity to play, you find confidence in
yourself and you continue to grow, and I think that's all he's done
as a player. He's gotten an opportunity, and he's taken advantage
of it and proved that he belongs in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson parlayed his patience into a three-year, $9 million
contract, which expires after next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``My role for this team is, number one, to get assists,''
Johnson said. ``If I can't get assists, then I need to break the
defense down. And when I'm wide open, make shots, and just be a
leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've felt I've always been a mentally tough player, but one
guy can't do it. I just try to fulfill my role with this team.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, his 11th, Johnson averaged 9.7 points and 7.4
assists. But he has stepped up in the playoffs, where both the
Minnesota Timberwolves and Lakers doubled down on the post and
baited Johnson to beat them with his quirky left-handed jump shot.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson promptly obliged, averaging a team-high 19.5 points and
6.3 assists and shooting 59.3 percent from the field in four games
against Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Harper has admired what his 34-year old protege has
accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take your hat off to a guy like Avery, because he
worked his way up,'' Harper said. ``I think everyone in the league
not only likes him, but respects him, because he had to start from
scratch, and he's still here.
</P>
<P>
   ``People double off of him and make him beat them, yet Avery
finds a way to be successful on the court night in and night out.
He's very, very solid.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't try telling that to Portland point guard Damon Stoudamire,
who went against all NBA protocol by saying the Spurs will never
win an NBA title with Johnson as their starting playmaker. In the
final two San Antonio-Portland meetings during the regular season,
Johnson outscored Stoudamire, 42-20, and the Spurs won both games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he makes their team go,'' said Lakers guard Derek
Fisher, who played Johnson in the Western Conference semifinals.
``People have been asking about Tim Duncan and David Robinson, but
Avery is the key to their success.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
