<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE DISCUSSES HIS RELIGIOUSNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forty-five minutes is really not much time to explore the
religious convictions of a man who wants to be the leader of the
world's most powerful nation _ and who is also as publicly reserved
as Vice President Al Gore. But the seven religion reporters who met
with Gore Friday at the White House did their best.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was a follow-up to the vice president's proposal,
spelled out in a speech last Monday at a Salvation Army center in
Atlanta, for a ``new partnership'' between government and
``faith-based organizations'' that would give those groups more
opportunities to receive federal money for social programs.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore, like Republican advocates of the concept, insists on
safe-guarding the separation of church of state, his speech
contained some dramatic phrases, observations that stretched far
beyond his immediate policy proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``National leaders have been trapped in a dead-end debate'' on
church-state questions, Gore said, faced with a false choice
between ``hollow secularism or right-wing religion.'' He said he
regretted ``the allergy to faith that is such a curious factor in
much of modern society.'' And he pledged, ``If you elect me
president, the voices of faith-based organizations will be integral
to the policies set forth in my administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's conversation at the White House touched on technical
and constitutional issues, but also stretched well into Gore's
personal faith as well as his views on religion and modernity.
</P>
<P>
   Gore acknowledged the enormous power of a modern science-based
civilization but added that it had stripped away an appreciation
for ``many of the most important meanings that are found only in
the whole.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no great blinding insight from moi,'' Gore said with a
laugh, but many other people ``have noticed this strong
intellectual strain that at times has difficulty in disguising
contempt for belief in God.'' He said it ``became a belief system
in itself with a kind of seeming arrogance toward alternative views
based on faith.''
</P>
<P>
   That view ``peaked some time ago,'' Gore said, although he noted
that the bias against religion still lingered.
</P>
<P>
   The journalists did not stop with this historical analysis, but
asked how Gore's Christian faith worked itself out in his daily
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faith is the center of my life,'' he replied. ``I don't wear
it on my sleeve, but I'm happy to respond to your question by
affirming my faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that when he returned from his Army service in Vietnam
he went to divinity school for about a year ``to intensively
explore the questions I had which seemed then and seem now to be
the most important questions about what's the purpose of life,
what's our relationship to the Creator, what's our spiritual
obligation to one another.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't find all the answers that I thought I might,'' he
said, ``but I found better questions, and I found a process for
living out better answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the purpose of life is to glorify God. I turn to my
faith as the bedrock of my approach to any important question in my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's father was a Southern Baptist, his mother a member of the
Church of Christ, and the family alternated the churches it
attended. Gore attended an Episcopal school; his wife, Tipper, was
an Episcopalian, although she switched to his Baptist congregation
after their marriage at the Episcopal National Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   What one sensed in the White House conversation was a
Christianity that is ethical and intellectual but not especially
doctrinal. Gore's passing references were to the virtues of
compassion and kindness, and to an impressive array of thinkers _
the American political moralist Reinhold Niebuhr, the Jesuit
paleontologist Pierre Teilhard de Chardin, the phenomenologist
Edmund Husserl, the existentialist Maurice Merleau-Ponty _ whose
writings bore more on the very possibility of religious belief and
morality in an age of science and power politics than on specific
Christian doctrines, especially of the sort that divide
denominations.
</P>
<P>
   (To hear the name ``Merleau-Ponty'' trip off the tongue of a
major American politician is surely extraordinary. Whether it is a
qualification to be president is an entirely different matter.)
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Gore showed his evangelical roots with a
confident exegesis of Bible texts that he said had helped him
understand events like the killings last month in Littleton, Colo.,
and the consequences of violent images in the mass media.
</P>
<P>
   And when a reporter asked whether in times of trial he was more
apt to turn to the religious part of his brain than the rational,
he was quick to deny, in a manner that might please Pope John Paul
II, that the two should be considered so separate.
</P>
<P>
   Is it worth noting what has been frequently noted before _ that
the private Gore, unlike the public image, was animated,
intellectually serious but not solemn, and more than occasionally
spontaneous? Indeed, he could not have been more spontaneous than
when asked whether he was trying to recapture religion from
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' the vice president shot back. ``I'm just trying to be
who I am.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
