</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-BABY-SELLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN SAYS BABIES WERE SMUGGLED INTO U.S. WITH FALSE DOCUMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ A Mexican woman who worked with a lawyer accused
of smuggling babies from Mexico has admitted that the infants were
sent to the United States under false documents, but insisted that
the Mexican mothers gave them up for adoption voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   Margarita Soto de Smith, a 28-year-old resident of the Mexican
border- crossing town of Agua Prieta, was arrested by Mexican
federal police in Agua Prieta on October 27, 1998. In her
testimony, which was recorded on videotape, Mrs. Smith told how the
attorney, Mario Manuel Reyes Burgueno, found struggling mothers
willing to part with their newborns and then used false documents
to rush the babies through the normally tedious process of
clearance for adoption in the Mexican courts.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes, a dual citizen of Mexico and the United States, was
arrested on Wednesday night at his home in Douglas, Ariz., just
across the border from Agua Prieta. He is charged with conspiring
to violate U.S. immigration laws and with mail and wire fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Soto testified that she received about $40 a week from
Reyes to take babies into her home in Agua Prieta and care for them
while they were waiting to be taken across the border, said a
Mexican federal agent with knowledge of the case. Police were led
to Mrs. Soto in part by complaints from her neighbors, who noticed
that she always had three or four baby seats in the back of her car
and wondered where the infants came from. Mrs. Soto did not have
any license to handle adoptions or care for children.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning, Mrs. Soto reluctantly admitted that she also
acted as what is known in Mexico as a ``name-lender' _ that is, she
allowed Reyes to put her name on at least three babies' birth
certificates as the mother. Mrs. Soto refused to say whether she
was paid for posing as the babies' mother.
</P>
<P>
   Based on what they learned from Mrs. Soto and other witnesses,
police believe that Reyes instructed the mothers to give false
names right after their babies were born, when hospital officials
came to gather information for birth certificates.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Soto acknowledged that she had taken at least six babies
across the border at Douglas using documents, many of them false,
supplied by Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   Police found one six-week-old baby girl in Mrs. Soto's care at
the time of her arrest. The child was sent by police to a homeless
children's shelter run by the federal government in Agua Prieta.
Mrs. Soto was jailed and, in November, she was indicted on a
federal charge of child-trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Soto insisted that the young Mexican women who turned over
their newborns to Reyes did so out of need. In many cases, she
said, they were not married and had no way to support themselves or
their babies. Some had not even told their families that they were
pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases they apparently heard of Reyes by word of mouth.
He was known as a lawyer who could help them offer their babies for
adoption quickly and easily, with no questions asked.
</P>
<P>
   New York prosecutors said that Reyes and his partners in Long
Island, N.Y., Arlene Reingold and Arlene Lieberman, received as
much as $22,000 from parents for each adoption. But it does not
appear that much, if any, of this money was paid to the birth
mothers or associates of Reyes like Mrs. Soto.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases Reyes paid for the mother's hospital expenses and
other medical costs. But so far there is no sign that the mothers
received large payments directly for the children. Police found no
evidence that Mrs. Soto had grown rich from her work with Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   According to accounts in El Imparcial, a daily newspaper in the
Mexican state of Sonora, in November the birth mother of the baby
girl found in Mrs. Soto's care traveled across Mexico from her home
in the Mexican state of Veracruz to see her child and make sure she
was being cared for. But the mother, a 17-year-old teenager who
gave her name only as Aracely, said she had no wish to take her
baby back. She said she had been abandoned by the baby's father and
could not keep the child in her parents' home.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes had attracted the suspicion of Mexican police since 1997,
because of the unusually large number of adoptions he steered
through the courts in Agua Prieta. In 1997 and 1998 alone, Reyes
presented papers for 16 adoptions.
</P>
<P>
   Ernesto Garcia Guerrero, the Mexican attorney general's
representative in Sonora, where Agua Prieta is located, said Friday
that a warrant for Reyes' arrest had been issued after Mrs. Soto
was detained last year. Reyes had apparently not returned to Mexico
since then, and was considered a fugitive from justice.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said Mexican investigators had found irregularities in 17
adoption cases Reyes moved through the Mexican courts. He said his
agents had been sharing information with American law enforcement
officials in an effort to track down Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said Friday that he had asked the Mexican Foreign
Relations Ministry to seek Reyes' extradition to Mexico to stand
trial here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
