u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NANTUCKET-CRUNCH-BOS &LR;      05-28 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NANTUCKET-CRUNCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ROOMS FOR THE HELP ON TONY NANTUCKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER BABSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTUCKET, Mass. _ They manicure million-dollar lawns, serve
tuna tartare, and dispense mountain bicycles adorned with wicker
baskets.
</P>
<P>
   Without their services, wealthy part-time residents of this
island might find themselves toiling behind a hot stove or worse,
clipping the hedges.
</P>
<P>
   As the summer season officially begins this weekend, locals are
contending with a problem that threatens to undermine the
foundation of their booming seasonal economy.
</P>
<P>
   There's no place to put the help.
</P>
<P>
   Even some small cottages with views of dirt roads and scrub
brush are fetching $3,000 a week, while the most modest
three-bedroom home for sale here is listing for $332,500.
</P>
<P>
   In a place where homes once shunned by rich visitors now have
weekly waiting lists, few would prefer to rent to the estimated
3,000 college students and immigrants who flock to an island that
has morphed from a sleepy whaling village to a haute outpost _
teeming with corporate jets and more than 60,000 people at the
height of summer.
</P>
<P>
   Now help-wanted signs are intertwined with handwritten ``Help Me
Find Housing'' flyers on the bulletin boards scattered along the
town's cobblestoned main boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   Noah Learner, 25, who repairs and rents bikes at Young's Bicycle
Shop on Steamship Wharf, pays $420 a month to share an overheated
attic room with his brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's considered a deal; it's the best anybody has heard
of,'' Learner says. ``My girlfriend has been looking since
February, and she can't find anything.'' Another Young's employee,
Alison Trebby, 18, is fortunate that her family owns a house on the
island. ``I knew 14 people who lived in one house last summer,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of affordable housing has also made it more difficult
for working- and middle-class Nantucket residents to remain
on-island, despite the intense demand for workers. The average
price of a single-family home on Nantucket jumped 27 percent in the
last quarter of 1998 compared to the year before _ from $673,000 to
$920,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young people, they are getting married and coming of age
and they are going out there and trying to buy something and
there's nothing left,'' said Edward Sanford, a real estate broker
with Island Properties. ``It's a gold-rush mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   Town officials, however, haven't been able to win approval for a
handful of initiatives to build dormitories or other facilities.
Fierce community opposition erupted over one developer's recent
proposal to locate dorms in a residential neighborhood, while town
meeting voters wouldn't provide the two-thirds needed to approve a
plan that would have allowed the town to assume control of 27
properties with title or tax problems.
</P>
<P>
   Planners _ now in the midst of completing a ``comprehensive
plan'' aimed at providing some solutions to the island's
affordable-housing problem _ have turned to a consultant who helped
the pricey resort town of Aspen, Colo., cope with its own shortage.
Aspen acquired land and built units restricted to buyers and
renters of certain income levels; the town also now earmarks about
70 percent of new private housing for moderate income residents.
Some of the options Nantucket planners are considering:
establishing ``residents-only'' housing for year-rounders, and
requiring special building permits for the construction of communal
housing for seasonal workers.
</P>
<P>
   For Francis Papps, owner of Valley Trasportation, which has a
contract to operate the town's seasonal shuttle-bus service, the
housing drought means it's three weeks until the season is in full
swing and he's 14 drivers short.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a tremendously hard time first of all finding
drivers,'' Papps said. ``One of the reasons we have such a hard
time is that it's so expensive for the drivers to live here.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, it cost Papps $16,500 to secure a house for three
months for his managers to live in. This summer, the same sized
house rents for $27,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going to happen eventually if it keeps going this way
is you will have all the wealthy here and when they want to go to a
fancy dinner or get their car fixed, there won't be any services
because nobody can afford to live here,'' Papps predicts.
</P>
<P>
   A number of employers on the island _ desperate to retain
reliable help _ have either purchased or rented houses for their
employees. Many of those who cannot afford to do that _ smaller
retailers, for example _ are being forced to curtail their hours,
says Maia Gaillard, executive director of the Nantucket Island
Chamber of Commerce. Some firms, such as those in the high-paying
building trades, are actually flying workers in each day.
</P>
<P>
   Cate O'Connor, owner of The Atlantic Cafe on South Water Street,
says building housing for her employees was strictly a business
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't do this, then I wouldn't be open seven days a
week, and if I'm not open seven days a week, I'm not a successful
business,'' O'Connor says. ``In return we get a loyal staff, and
they come back next year.''
</P>
<P>
   For workers, the price of island living _ if they are lucky _
often means living cheek-by-jowl with coworkers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you find your own place to stay you can pick any job you
want,'' says Ged Morris, of Manchester, England, who delivers
tourists during the day for Terrapin Taxi and pizzas for a local
restaurant in the evenings. Morris's night job at Mid-Island Pizza
offers a key fringe benefit _ a shared room _ for which he
reimburses his employers $100 a week. It's a deal on an island
where sharing a room usually runs around $150 a week for each bed.
Actually, town officials do not really know how many houses are
crammed to the gills with workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gone underground,'' says Richard Ray, the town's health
inspector. ``Housing for the college kids, by the employers, is
spoken about in whispers.'' For his part, Ray says he will only
investigate written complaints of unsanitary living conditions.
Telephone tips, because of budgetary contraints, fall by the
wayside.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Ray: ``This is nothing more than the greed factor, which no
matter how you slice it, is one of the driving factors behind the
economy on Nantucket.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5599 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BANKERS-TRUST-ART-2ND     05-28 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKERS-TRUST-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: $1.1 billion.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1994, though, Bankers Trust's highfliers were grounded by
scandal. The bank, one of the most loosely managed on Wall Street,
came under fire from clients and regulators who accused it of
misleading customers about its risky derivative products. Tape
recordings, later made public in court hearings, captured the
bank's sales force snickering about the naivete of the clients.
</P>
<P>
   The fallout was brutal. In just a year, the bank's earnings
plummeted to $686 million; a federal investigation eventually
concluded that senior management had suppressed efforts by
compliance officers to rein in questionable practices.
</P>
<P>
   Before the government's investigation was completed, Shanks and
Sanford, both of whom declined to comment for this article,
retired. Frank N. Newman, a former Treasury Department official,
was appointed the new chief executive _ a switch engineered by the
New York Federal Reserve to help restore the bank's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   But while derivatives were making headlines, trouble was quietly
brewing in Kingdon's domain. It was also in 1994 that three New
York state auditors started asking questions about the bank's
unclaimed-funds accounts, setting off a chain of events that led to
Kingdon's resignation in early 1997 _ and the bank's guilty plea
two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few days of Kingdon's resignation, which Newman at the
time attributed to personal reasons, Bankers Trust said it would
add $20 million to its reserves to reconcile ``accounting
differences'' in the global assets unit.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors had a harsher term, however, for what went
on under Kingdon's watch. In court papers filed in March, they
declared that the bookkeeping irregularities were part of a
criminal conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors said several executives in Kingdon's unit, whom
they declined to identify, treated unclaimed accounts like a vast
slush fund. And far from being a rogue operation to fill their own
pockets, the prosecutors said in a statement in March, the Bankers
Trust scheme was initiated because senior executives ``placed
severe pressure'' on underlings to enhance the bank's dismal
performance from 1994 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   According to lawyers and Bankers Trust employees familiar with
the federal investigation, Kingdon, although not named in court
papers, orchestrated the fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Kingdon, who is the chief target of the federal investigation,
declined repeated requests for an interview. His lawyer, Stanley
Arkin, has not disputed Kingdon's involvement in the scheme, but
argues that his client's actions did not amount to a criminal
fraud. Laws governing unclaimed funds are murky, Arkin said, adding
that Kingdon would contest any charges filed against him.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the United States attorney's office said that when
the bank's management first alerted federal investigators to the
scam, it played down the involvement of Bankers Trust employees.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Bankers Trust said it minimized its executives'
culpability at first because it did not realize the scope of the
fraud. What it has not said, however, is that state auditors were
pressing it for answers to questions about a possible conspiracy
two years before the bank notified federal authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Auditors at the New York State Comptroller's office _ which
audits banks for unclaimed funds originally owned by New York
residents or institutions _ are known to be unusually dedicated,
yet loath to see their names in print. True to their reputation,
none of those involved in the Bankers Trust investigation would
comment for attribution.
</P>
<P>
   When the auditors noticed in 1994 that Bankers Trust's
unclaimed-funds accounts had dropped from $10.2 million in 1993 to
$3.9 million in 1994, they asked for records explaining the plunge.
But despite repeated requests, the documents were not forthcoming.
Because banks were ordinarily quick to assist them, the auditors
were bothered by the fact that Bankers Trust was not.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bank initially wasn't very cooperative and indicated that
records couldn't be located,'' Comptroller H. Carl McCall said in
an interview. Bankers Trust's diversion of unclaimed funds ``is one
of the more egregious abuses my auditors have uncovered,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   Again and again, for more than two years, the auditors were told
that the records had been transferred from New York to a warehouse
in Nashville. The audit moved ahead slowly, partly because the
auditors' resources were stretched thin but also because they
failed to use stronger measures available to them, like issuing
subpoenas or fining the bank, in the hope that it would cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, even as the state auditors were in the bank raising
questions about unclaimed funds, several Bankers Trust executives
were blatantly foraging through those same accounts to locate money
they could withhold from the state, according to allegations in an
unsuccessful civil lawsuit filed in 1996 by Let W. Lee, a managing
director who reported to Kingdon, against Bankers Trust in federal
court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring of 1995, Lee asked two of his employees, Harvey
Plante and Gerard Callaghan, to identify unclaimed funds that could
be kept on the bank's books, according to the lawsuit. The suit
said Lee and Callaghan directed Plante to set up a reserve account
for unclaimed funds _ the same account that federal prosecutors
would later label a slush fund.
</P>
<P>
   The suit said Kingdon and Paula C. Gabriele, head of Bankers
Trust's retirement services business, knew about the reserve
account. It also said Lee cleared all of his actions, which he
believed to be legal, with Bankers Trust's compliance officers.
(The bank's compliance officers notify senior management of routine
requests like Lee's only if they believe a problem has arisen,
according to a bank spokesman.)
</P>
<P>
   Lee's suit, which claimed that the bank libeled him in a
disclosure to federal authorities, was dismissed by an appeals
court in February, on technical grounds; Bankers Trust was never
called upon to respond to its allegations.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Bankers Trust said 13 employees involved in the
diversion of unclaimed funds resigned between 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Messrs. Kingdon and Plante, along with Kenneth Goglia, a former
managing director for financial controls who worked for Kingdon,
have all been formally notified that they are under investigation
by federal authorities, according to lawyers and Bankers Trust
employees involved in the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Messrs. Goglia, Plante and Lee declined to comment.
Ms. Gabriele's lawyer said she was not a target of the
investigation and had left the bank on good terms. Callaghan, also
not a target and still employed by Bankers Trust, declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
