<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5601 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-BILL-800&AMP;ADD-     05-28 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-BILL-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW POLITICAL DANCE FOR THE FIRST COUPLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (lb) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   YULEE, Fla. _ Behind closed doors on Sunday, Bill and Hillary
Clinton will be the featured speakers in one of their favorite
forums, a talkathon on globalization, social investment and the
``third way'' of governing that they have long promoted.
</P>
<P>
   But interestingly, it is Mrs. Clinton who will occupy center
stage for a longer period, speaking and fielding questions from
Democratic insiders and money people for an hour in the morning,
and then addressing the group jointly with her husband later.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule reflects the subtle shift of internal dynamics
emerging now that the end of Clinton's presidency is in sight and
Mrs. Clinton's race for the Senate from New York appears all but
certain. To be sure, he is still leader of the world's only
superpower. But in this, their 28th year as a couple and a
political team, she represents the future.
</P>
<P>
   This was evident a couple of weeks ago in one of their rare
public appearances together, when the Clintons went to Littleton,
Colo., to talk with families of those who had been killed in the
school massacre. Clinton and his entourage waited for half an hour
on the tarmac at the Denver airport while Mrs. Clinton flew in from
Arizona, where she had been promoting the treasures of the
Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Clinton arrived, the crowd swelled around her; the
president hung back on the fringe. She led the way to their
helicopter, with him a few paces behind. When she extended her
hand, he literally had to skip to catch up with her.
</P>
<P>
   They have been completely secluded here at the White Oak
Plantation, a gated 7,500-acre animal preserve set two miles back
on a dirt road. They have had no visitors, are cooking dinners on
their own and reading. While Clinton has been playing golf, and
losing to the local 25-year-old pros, Mrs. Clinton has been working
the phones and strategizing on her Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Her candidacy, once a mind-bending fantasy, no longer seems a
question of if. It has moved on to the when and the how and the
political ramifications of such a precedent-shattering move.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really wants to do this,'' said a New York Democrat close
to the process, ``and she has her staff out looking at all these
logistical issues. They are coming back with a plan, and they are
going to be saying, `Is this doable? Is this doable?' It sounds
like she'd have to be talked out of it at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Judith Hope, the state Democratic chairwoman, said Mrs. Clinton
called her the other day and talked about doing some upstate
travel. ``As you go around and talk to folks,'' Ms. Hope said Mrs.
Clinton told her, ``gather ideas and suggestions about where they
think I ought to go and what I should be doing.''' Officials are
searching for an upstate, centrally located home base from which
Mrs. Clinton could make day trips during the summer to meet people.
This is separate from the Clintons' search for a permanent
postpresidential residence in Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's supporters are playing down the milestone aspects
of an incumbent first lady running for office and leaving her
husband home alone in the White House. What message does this send?
And will her striking out on her own reverse her favorability
ratings, which climbed when she curbed her independence and stood
by her man?
</P>
<P>
   One Democrat said that the trickier consideration was leaving
her official duties as first lady, not leaving her husband. While
another official close to Mrs. Clinton pointed out that the first
lady had few prescribed duties beyond presiding at state dinners,
conflicts will inevitably arise. State dinner in Washington or
Democratic dinner in Utica, N.Y.?
</P>
<P>
   The conflicts will not be just logistical but also political.
Although she and the president see eye to eye on virtually every
policy matter, what happens if, say, the Republicans'
transportation budget proposal, which eliminates $160 million in
federal mass transit aid for New York, reaches the president's desk
for his signature?
</P>
<P>
   The White House has stopped short of a veto threat. Presumably
the first lady would argue for a veto, but if this killed an
otherwise acceptable bill, the president could be portrayed as
jeopardizing the national interest for his wife's political career.
</P>
<P>
   Another consideration is security. Asked how Mrs. Clinton could
shuck the protective Secret Service shell that surrounds her, one
Democratic aide said the first lady did not perceive this as an
obstacle, and hoped the public would be sympathetic about it.
</P>
<P>
   It still provides an easy target for her critics, who are
already complaining that taxpayers have unfairly had to pay for her
New York trips, which are obviously political. She will almost
certainly form an exploratory committee to help her raise money to
pay her own way.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Others are scrambling over how to manage the press corps _ not
just its ferocity but its size. On her New York visits, the
noncandidate has already been overwhelmed by the sheer quantity of
reporters, who come from across the state and around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that is the expanding size of a previously tight circle
of aides devoted to doing things as Mrs. Clinton wants them done.
``There are a lot of people talking to the press who aren't part of
the Hillary machine,'' said one Democrat who fits that description.
``It's a problem that she doesn't have the control over them that
she has over the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is puzzling over some of these questions herself,
but is also working on what she wants to say. She will get some
practice on Sunday, when she and the president meet with about 50
members of the Democratic Leadership Council, the centrist group
that helped Clinton tone down the liberal image of the Democratic
Party.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is planning to talk about her notion of a ``civil
society,'' a longtime preoccupation that aides suggested could be
tailored to contrast with the behavior of New York City Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, her likely opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the president is pitching in too. Although Clinton
has the war in Kosovo to worry about, he has been keeping a close
eye on the special election for a state Senate seat in Rockland
County, a swing district north of New York City that could prove a
bellwether for Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton had taped a radio commercial for the Democratic
candidate, Kenneth Zebrowski, a county legislator, and the
president had written a letter to local communities on his behalf.
By 11:30 Tuesday night, it was clear that Zebrowski had lost the
hard-fought race, and Clinton, who had just arrived here for
vacation, called him on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Bill, and I wanted to tell you how sorry I was that
things didn't work out,'' Zebrowski recalled the president saying.
``He was sort of somber,'' Zebrowski said, ``quieter than I might
have expected,'' perhaps reflecting on what could lie in store for
his wife, who did not come to the phone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
