<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. HUNTS FOR QUID PRO QUO IN MICROSOFT WITNESS' ACTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  (rk) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ The Justice Department's chief trial lawyer
in the government's antitrust suit against Microsoft Corp. Friday
closely questioned a Microsoft witness about whether he had
benefited as a result of his decision to defend the software
publisher and to testify in its behalf.
</P>
<P>
   The questioning was one of a series of depositions taking place
in preparation for the resumption of the trial in Washington on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Eubanks, a veteran software developer, who until recently
was chairman and chief executive of Symantec Corp., frequently
responded to the Justice Department lawyer, David Boies, by saying
that he did not recall the details of his communications with
Microsoft executives.
</P>
<P>
   Eubanks, a pioneer in the personal computer industry, once
worked for Digital Research, a company that competed with Microsoft
in software products, notably operating systems and programming
languages. But he has long been a defender of the Redmond, Wash.,
software giant.
</P>
<P>
   He is now the chief executive of Oblix, a Mountain View, Calif.,
software company.
</P>
<P>
   The deposition, which took place Friday afternoon in a hotel
room here, began with Boies asking Eubanks what Bill Gates,
Microsoft's chairman, had said when Microsoft asked Eubanks to
serve as a rebuttal witness in the antitrust trial.
</P>
<P>
   Boies then referred to a February 1998 electronic mail exchange
between Eubanks and Brad Chase, a Microsoft marketing executive, in
which Chase asked Eubanks to write an opinion piece in defense of
Microsoft's role in the computer industry.
</P>
<P>
   In messages sent on Feb. 21, 1998, Eubanks said he would be glad
to write an op-ed piece supporting Microsoft, and he then asked
Chase if Microsoft would be willing to drop an anti-virus product
that competed with Symantec's product from a supplement Microsoft
was releasing for the Windows 95 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Boies asked if there was a tie between Eubanks' willingness to
write a supportive op-ed piece and his decision to raise the
question of the inclusion of the competitor's product as part of
the Microsoft operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand what you're asking, and the answer is absolutely
not,'' Eubanks said. He said that the two issues were ``disjoint''
and that he had consistently discussed the issue with Microsoft
executives because he felt strongly that it was wrong for
Microsoft, which has a de facto monopoly with its Windows family of
operating systems, to ``anoint one competitor's product in favor of
another.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our customers routinely told me that supporting Microsoft was
extremely important,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset of the deposition, Boies had asked Eubanks if
Gates had asked him to testify to help with ``damage control.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he tell you that he wanted to help control the damage and
that he felt the case was lost?'' Boies asked.
</P>
<P>
   Eubanks said he did not recall any such questions.
</P>
<P>
   During the deposition, Boies and Eubanks fenced over a quote in
a newspaper article in which Eubanks was reported to have
criticized Microsoft's business practices.
</P>
<P>
   Eubanks said he believed that he had been misquoted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember consistently telling our employees that our job was
to serve our customers and that to get involved in disputes with
Microsoft, Apple, Oracle or anyone else was not productive,''
Eubanks said.
</P>
<P>
   Boies' questioning was continuing Friday evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
