<HEADLINE>
`PHOTO OF CENTURY' TO BE TAKEN JULY 4TH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE GOENS   
 Florence (Ala.) TimesDaily   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KILLEN, Ala. _ You can hardly blame Ashley Wallace for feeling a
little left out every year when her birthday rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   Being born on the Fourth of July can have its drawbacks,
especially for children who have to schedule their birthday parties
so as not to compete with traditional celebrations on the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   This year will be different for Ms. Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   She will spend her birthday in Philadelphia, and her big present
will be taking part in the ``Photo of the Century.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wallace is one of 98 people nationwide selected to take part
in the photo. The participants share a common birth date and will
represent each year during the 20th century from 1900 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Every state will be represented.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wallace, who will represent 1988, will be 11 years old July
4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't been bad to have a birthday on the Fourth of July,
but you can't have your birthday party on the same day,'' she said.
``Everybody is doing other things on the Fourth of July and don't
always have time to come to a birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't mind it this year. Being part of this is a really big
honor.''
</P>
<P>
   The historic photograph, which will be taken in front of
Independence Hall, will mark the start of Philadelphia's millennium
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Hosefros, chief photographer for The New York Times'
Washington bureau, will snap the official photo at 7:04 a.m. July
4. Like the people in the photo, Hosefros, who will be celebrating
his 52nd birthday, was born on July 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``The significance of a still photo is that it is at once many
parts but at the same time, it is a whole and complete expression
of who we are,'' he told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, participants in the photo will be guest
marshals for the city's Independence Day parade.
</P>
<P>
   More than 25,000 people submitted photographs, application forms
and essays in an effort to earn a place in the ``Photo of the
Century.'' Among the winners were descendants of signers of the
Declaration of Independence, a woman from Texas named Liberty Bell,
an actress, a mayor, a nun and a cowboy.
</P>
<P>
   (The TimesDaily in Florence, Ala., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
