A5616 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIRUS-VIRUS_SFCHRON &LR;      05-28 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRUS-VIRUS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Malevolent New Computer Program Seen  &HT;     By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Computer security experts yesterday said they have uncovered a
Trojan Horse program disguised as spam that allows hackers to
purloin or destroy the files of its victims from anywhere on the
Internet.
<P>
   The BackDoor-G program arrives in e-mail as a screen saver or PC
game update that, when downloaded, exposes a user's PC to remote
Net connections. It is also virtually undetectable to users.
</P>
<P>
   ``This literally opens holes in the security of a PC. It can be
incredibly damaging,'' said Sal Viveros, a group marketing manager
at Network Associates, which discovered the program Wednesday. He
said it would be several days before the Santa Clara company could
accurately assess damage.
</P>
<P>
   The malicious code attack _ which uses ``remote administration
tools'' to puncture a computer system _ is similar to a Trojan
Horse program unleashed last year. That program, derisively called
Back Orifice after Microsoft's BackOffice software package, was
created by a group calling itself the Cult of the Dead Cow.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear, however, who is responsible for BackDoor-G, which
already has spawned a copycat program in France, called
``Armageddon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As more and more people are connected and have access to
technology, we will see an increase in viruses and Trojan Horse
(applications),'' Viveros said. ``It's just a function of the
bravado hacker underculture of trying to see how far they can go
with their programs.''
</P>
<P>
   BackDoor-G is the third cyber- attack to bedevil computer users
in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
   A pair of well-known viruses, Chernobyl and Melissa, have
infiltrated computers via e-mail messages, wiping out data and
paralyzing computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The more severe Chernobyl _ a ``space filler'' virus that
secretly fills space on computer disk drives _ invaded an estimated
240,000 PCs in South Korea alone on April 26.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Melissa, meanwhile, choked e-mail servers worldwide in March
with a deluge of e-mail messages, forcing some major businesses to
shut down their e-mail systems for days.
</P>
<P>
   Computer security researchers have several suggestions for
minimizing hacker and virus attacks.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail users should be especially careful when opening
attachments with ``.exe'' in the address, according to Carnegie
Mellon University's Computer Emergency Response Team.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Network Associates and other anti-virus software
companies offer free software patches over the Internet that can
detect and eradicate BackDoor-G and viruses. These patches are
updated whenever new malevolent programs are unleashed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
