<HEADER>
A5618 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-28 1526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRAFT EXPECTS TO GAIN FROM SPEEDY STADIUM DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Kraft told his fellow NFL owners this past week at a league
meeting that he plans to have his own space ``trip'' in 2001: a new
Patriots stadium in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   If Kraft can pull it off, it will be the fastest any stadium has
been built in the NFL since . . . 1970, when the present Foxboro
Stadium went up in one year. That stadium was built on the cheap,
with no frills.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft told his peers he wants to build a stadium his family and
friends would be proud of and that he can pull it off if he gets
the necessary approval from the Town of Foxborough and the
continued support of the local business community.
</P>
<P>
   Said one owner close to Kraft, ``His family has owned the
stadium for years and knows how to run the business. They own the
land. They can get it built a lot faster and for a lot less money
than if the city or state were involved. This is why it made sense
for him to get out of Connecticut when he did, because that wasn't
going to open until 2003. This way, if he gets it done in 2001,
he'll be operating for two years at a higher income than he would
have been waiting around for Connecticut to get finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft reportedly told friends that he would take the best from
the four newest NFL stadiums _ Cleveland, Baltimore, Tampa, and
Carolina _ and incorporate these ideas into Foxboro.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft was given a big boost behind closed doors in an
owners-only meeting by Pittsburgh's Dan Rooney, who said, ``He has
done a tremendous service to the league by keeping the team in the
Boston area. He gave up a lot to do it, but it is very important to
all of us that he did.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reversal of Fortunes I:
</P>
<P>
   When the Red Sox first announced plans for a new stadium in the
same Fenway Park area, two of the most vocal local critics were
Steve Mindich, owner of the Boston Phoenix, and Robert Sage, owner
of the Holiday Inn. Both emphasized how valuable their property in
the area is and maintained they would fight before giving it up for
the new Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Mindich was even a guest on Channel 4's ``Sports Final'' last
Sunday night with Buddy LeRoux. This is the same show that brought
us Jersey Red. Can Jimmy Myers be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, research has revealed that Mindich, Sage, and others
applied for tax abatements from the City of Boston since 1995,
though Mindich claims it was done by the trust that owns his
buildings _ of which he is a principal _ without his knowledge.
Yeah, sure.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine asking for a tax break one year because you believe the
city overvalued your land, then the next year shooting your mouth
off in public about how valuable your land is and vowing that you
will never give it up. How are they going to explain talking out of
both sides of their mouths when they face eminent domain
proceedings? Which time were they being honest?
</P>
<P>
   Reversal of Fortunes II:
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers for Donna Harris Lewis are expected to finish their
arguments in her malpractice lawsuit next week. Then the defense
lawyers for Dr. Gilbert Mudge and his associates go on the
offensive. What puzzled me was hearing this week from alleged
experts how much money the late Celtics captain Reggie Lewis would
have been worth had his basketball career continued. Well, how was
it going to continue if he was dead? We keep reading that he died
during a ``casual'' workout. If a ``casual'' workout was fatal, how
could he have survived training camp and the rigors of the NBA
schedule? And, given his heart problem, who would have insured
another contract? At any rate, there's no way the Celtics would
have given him a contract extension after the heart trouble
surfaced.
</P>
<P>
   Reversal of Fortunes III:
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's tribute to Bill Russell at the FleetCenter was
heading for an all-time embarrassment until the Rev. J. Donald
Monan, S.J., former president of Boston College, used all his
muscle down the stretch to bail it out.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, when only 2,400 tickets had been sold after some
of the greatest publicity anyone could get, a meeting was convened
to call off the tribute and prevent a financial disaster. Enter Fr.
Monan, who had talked Russell into having the tribute as a
fund-raiser for the National Mentoring Partnership, which both are
involved in. Fr. Monan, who played a major role behind the scenes
in getting the FleetCenter built and in getting the business
community to join with the NFL and the Massachusetts Legislature to
keep the Patriots in Foxborough, personally made the calls to save
the Russell night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Father called me up and said it was really, really important
that I come through for him in this Russell thing,'' said one of
the top business leaders in Boston. ``I wasn't going to give
anything. I'm not a big Russell fan. But I gave it for Father. In
all the years I've known him, it's the first time he ever called
personally to ask me for the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there is no official word yet, early returns said about
8,000 people paid and almost another 2,500 were given free tickets.
Perhaps the biggest surprise was that 2,200 supposedly bought the
cheap seats on the day of the event. Those are the real sports fans
who wanted to salute Russell. The others were returning business
favors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The way Ramon Martinez has been throwing, the Red Sox now expect
him to pitch for them before the All-Star Game, well ahead of
projections. His ailing arm is coming along faster than expected .
. . Message to Kraft: Get Chris Canty on the road. In case you
missed the latest, Canty, the Patriots' first-round draft choice of
two years ago who simply can't play, can't practice, either,
because he reportedly developed a ``rash'' from the dye in his
uniform. Really? How come no other players in Patriots history have
come down with the same ``rash''? Are they throwing away all their
uniforms? I don't think so. And if you believe the ``rash'' story,
you must have also believed Mo Money when he said it wasn't about
the money, that he'd play for $5 million, or the Texas Con Man,
Roger Clemens, when he said he wanted to play closer to home. Canty
was the personal pick of Bobby Grier. The coaches wanted to dump
him in the expansion draft. Grier protected him. He should be gone
in a hurry because he can't play and has shown through some of his
off-field antics that his social life is more important to him. The
team was hurt last year when Jimmy Hitchcock, a much better player,
was traded for no other reason than to try to force Canty into the
lineup. It's time for the Patriots to cut their losses with the guy
and move on . . . Did you catch the piece on Mo Money in ESPN
Magazine this week or hear all the talk about it on radio? Vaughn
says the Red Sox were the reason his father needed surgery for a
urinary infection because he got so upset when Mo was booed. Vaughn
added that he would never forgive the Red Sox. I never knew Mo went
to medical school, did you? Maybe when he retires, he'll want s to
come back as the Red Sox doctor. If boos caused people to get sick,
there wouldn't be enough quarterbacks left to field teams in the
NFL. And he calls the Boston fans ``stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you missed it, Eddie Andelman and Dale Arnold had a good
interview with Rick Pitino this week. The Celtics coach defended
the deal in which he sent Boston's first draft pick to Cleveland
for Vitaly Potapenko. ``There is no one available in this draft
where we would have picked that is as good as this kid,'' siad
Pitino. ``He is the hardest worker on our team and gave us a big
lift when we got him.'' Perhaps the most interesting part of the
interview was when Pitino said he would favor high school stars
going directly to the NBA rather than simply staying in college a
year or two honing their skills to get ready for the pros . . .
Brian Rose is a great story. Last year when he was having arm
trouble, he was told by the Red Sox that the injury might be a
figment of his imagination. Instead of letting words defeat him, he
rebuilt his arm, signed a contract for the minimum, and showed in
his last two outings for the Sox that he is a big league pitcher
with a large upside because he has guts and control . . . We told
you last week that the people who wanted to preserve Old Fenway
Park offered two suggestions for what the Sox could do while the
park was being renovated. The first suggestion was to take a season
off. The second was to inquire about Foxboro Stadium. Now comes the
suggestion that they play at Harvard. Or consider playing all of
their games on the road for a full season. Or rotating their games
between Pawtucket and Lowell. Are we having a month of full moons
around here? . . . If the Patriots get rid of Zefross Moss, the
highest-rated offensive lineman on the team last year, and Todd
Rucci, who started all season at guard, pray for Drew Bledsoe. John
Friesz might get to play sooner, and more, than he bargained for
when he signed as a backup.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
