 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONSUMER SPENDING IN APRIL INCREASED 0.4 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Consumer spending on goods and services rose four-tenths of a
percent in April on top of an increase of half a percent in March,
the Commerce Department reported. And, personal income rose half a
percent in April, up from a gain of three-tenths of a percent in
March.
</P>
<P>
   In another report, the National Association of Purchasing
Management said its index of regional manufacturing fell to 57.9 in
May from 63.3. Analysts expected a reading of 60.1. Index readings
above 50 mean the number of manufacturers saying business had
improved was greater than the number saying it had deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   NEC LOST $1.3 BILLION IN FISCAL YEAR
</P>
<P>
   NEC, one of the world's largest makers of semiconductors, lost
157.9 billion yen, or $1.3 billion at current exchange rates, in
the fiscal year that ended March 31, compared with a profit of 41.3
billion yen the year before.
</P>
<P>
   HACKERS DISRUPT 2 U.S. WEB SITES
</P>
<P>
   Hackers disrupted the Internet sites of the FBI and the U.S.
Senate this week, forcing them to shut down. The sites serve a
public relations function, so no classified, confidential or
personal material was compromised.
</P>
<P>
   KPMG ACCUSED IN MEDICARE LAWSUIT
</P>
<P>
   The accounting firm KPMG was accused in a federal whistle-blower
lawsuit unsealed Friday of aiding some hospitals in Florida in a
scheme to defraud Medicare through the use of bogus expense claims.
</P>
<P>
   A PACT WITH SWEEPSTAKES PROMOTER
</P>
<P>
   American Family Publishers, one of the two largest sweepstakes
promotion companies, agreed to changes in its practices and to a $4
million settlement with four states that the company deceived
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ITALIAN BANKS FIND MERGERS DIFFICULT
</P>
<P>
   Italian banks, like those across Europe, are struggling to
merge, to cut costs and create the larger capital bases they will
need to finance customers on the euro market. Yet recent efforts
have failed. Earlier this month, Banca Commerciale Italiana, the
No. 4 bank in Italy, rejected a $14 billion takeover offer from
Unicredito Italiano, the No. 3 bank, after having concluded that
the nation's central bank would block the bid. It did so because
the central bank's president, Antonio Fazio, said he would not
approve hostile bids for banks.
</P>
<P>
   A MICROSOFT DEFENDER IS QUESTIONED
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Eubanks, a longtime software developer, was questioned by
the Justice Department's chief trial lawyer in the government's
antitrust suit against Microsoft about whether he had benefited as
a result of his decision to defend the software publisher and to
testify in its behalf. The Microsoft trial is expected to resume
Tuesday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES AGREE ON ACCIDENT LIABILITY
</P>
<P>
   The world's major airlines have agreed to provide better
protection and compensation to victims of international air
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   ARM FINANCIAL HIRES AN ADVISER
</P>
<P>
   ARM Financial Services Group, a provider of insurance-based
retirement saving plans whose stock has languished, hired Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter Inc. to ``evaluate strategic alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   CONCERN RAISED ABOUT FALLING EURO
</P>
<P>
   Germany's top central banker expressed alarm at the depressed
value of the euro against the dollar, hinting at a shift in the
hands-off policy toward exchange rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
