<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5630 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAXTER-BOOK-ART-935(2     05-28 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-BOOK-ART-935(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: S.C.)  
 FROM DOMESTIC WORKER TO UNLIKELY AUTHOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By BARBARA STEWART   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shortly after her mother's death, when she was barely
17, Freddie Mae Baxter left her home in rural South Carolina. She
settled in Harlem during the final months of the Depression and
found work cleaning rich people's houses and taking care of their
children.
</P>
<P>
   Black, female and uneducated, she was pretty much limited to
low-paying, unskilled work. But she shared her food and lodgings
with each of her seven brothers and sisters when they followed her
north in search of jobs and apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Baxter, who is 75, retired in 1988 after spending nearly 50
years as a domestic worker. A large, energetic woman with
gregariousness to spare, she lives by herself in a one-room
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Now she is an author with one of the world's most famous
publishing houses.
</P>
<P>
   To an outsider, Miss Baxter's life might seem hopelessly
ordinary and even dreary _ certainly nothing that would catch the
attention of someone outside her circle. But she sees her life as
so eventful and colorful that, in her opinion, the details should
be broadcast far and wide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always just knew I had a story to tell,'' she said one
afternoon last week, in her memento-crammed apartment outfitted
with stylish 1940s furniture. ``I knew if I could tell my story _
and I don't mean write, I mean tell _ that mine would be a best
seller.''
</P>
<P>
   The memoirs of an elderly, unschooled domestic worker a best
seller? Her chances of hitting the jackpot on one of the Atlantic
City slot machines she loves to play seemed greater.
</P>
<P>
   But this month the impossible may be within her grasp. A
hardcover edition of her stories and opinions, titled ``The Seventh
Child: A Lucky Life,'' was released on May 4 by Alfred A. Knopf.
With an announced print run of 125,000, Knopf is touting ``The
Seventh Child'' as one of its biggest books of the year.
</P>
<P>
   While a print run of 125,000 would be impressive even for a
nonfiction work by a well-known author, for the memoir of an
ordinary life by an unknown, it is highly unusual. Equally
remarkable is the fact that Miss Baxter received an advance of
``more than $100,000,'' according to Joseph Spieler, her agent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Knopf's confidence, the book is clearly a risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long shot,'' acknowledged Martin Asher, editor in chief
of Vintage Books, which bought the paperback rights at the same
time that Knopf acquired the hardcover rights.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 33,000 hardcover copies have been sold, Asher said,
adding that the paperback version is scheduled to come out next
year. ``What completely knocked us out is the voice, the warmth,
the humor of the person. To me it was saying: If you live right _
if you have luck and grace and humor _ you get better when you get
older.''
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes, like Miss Baxter, you get luckier.
</P>
<P>
   Her streak of luck in the publishing world began three years ago
aboard a Metro North train to Port Chester. An elderly former
employer of hers had been transferred to a nursing home there, and
Miss Baxter was on her way to pay a visit. Among the passengers was
a woman named Gloria Bley Miller, a semiretired writer who was a
friend of the employer. The two struck up a conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a great storyteller,'' recalled Ms. Miller, who is 78.
``It was like turning on a tap. I enjoyed the trip more than the
actual visit.''
</P>
<P>
   Several train rides later, Ms. Miller suggested that the two
women get together to tape Miss Baxter's thoughts. Eventually, the
meetings became a Friday afternoon ritual at Ms. Miller's Greenwich
Village apartment. Ms. Miller sat in the leather chair, and Miss
Baxter sat in the rocking chair, discussing everything from her
days picking cotton after school to her present-day aversion to
churchgoing.
</P>
<P>
   Though she never married or had children, she talked at length
of the dozens of children in her life _ her nieces, nephews and
godchildren, and the children she helped to raise as a care giver.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1997, after nearly a year of talk, Ms. Miller began
transcribing her notes on her manual typewriter. ``During typing,
the shape of the subjects became clear,'' she said. Instead of
creating a narrative, she divided the material into categories:
``Coming North,'' ``Brothers and Sisters'' and ``Keeping Up With
the Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The rhythm of her speech got into my head,'' Ms. Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   In the section called ``Money and Gambling,'' for instance, Miss
Baxter says of her occasional trips to Atlantic City: ``When I go
in there, something grabs me. I want to go right in and start
playing .... If you're lucky, you win. If you're not lucky, you
won't win. That's all. The point is that in your mind it's gonna be
your day. And one day it's gonna be your day.''
</P>
<P>
   After spending nearly a year arranging the material, Ms. Miller
began to pursue a publisher. Although she had been a professional
writer, because of her motley collection of works, which ranged
from stories for a '50s comic called Plastic Man to ``The Thousand
Recipe Chinese Cookbook,'' she did not know anyone in book
publishing who could help her. She did not even have an agent.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the project went nowhere. After sending the
manuscript to an array of agents and publishers, Ms. Miller had
received 30 rejections, including one from Knopf. Others were on
the way.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in May of 1998, Ms. Miller got lucky herself. Through an
acquaintance, she made contact with a woman whose husband worked in
publishing. He turned out to be Spieler, and the manuscript soon
reached his hands. A few weeks later, when he got around to reading
it, he was bowled over.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   ``At the seventh or eighth page, something happened,'' he said.
``Instead of just reading with my head, I was reading with my whole
viscera. I was totally floored by it, by what I thought was the
originality of the story.''
</P>
<P>
   He promptly sent the work to two friends, Asher at Vintage and
Robin Desser, a senior editor at Knopf. Both had similarly
enthusiastic responses. ``It was no holds barred,'' said Ms.
Desser, who quickly acquired the book, one of about 150 that Knopf
bought that year. ``There was something so honest about her
voice.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, ``The Seventh Child'' was published. In it Miss
Baxter recounts memories from her life _ everything from her hurt
when her father deserted the family to recollections of listening
to Billie Holiday singing at the Apollo and of greeting Duke
Ellington as he strolled down 125th Street.
</P>
<P>
   Early reviews have ranged from respectful to enthusiastic.
Publishers Weekly described it as a ``plain-spoken narrative that
crackles with energy'' but added, ``The book's nonlinear structure
makes for occasionally bumpy reading.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Seventh Child'' was one of several books that received
prominent placement in Barnes &AMP; Noble stores over Mother's Day, in
exchange for a paid advertisement in the chain's newsletter. Sales
representatives for the book were supplied with audiotapes and
videotapes on which Miss Baxter talks about herself and her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people pick it up, they'll love it,'' said Sheila O'Shea, a
publicist for Knopf. Miss Baxter, she added, is her own best
publicist. Ms. O'Shea's current task is to persuade television
producers deluged with pitches to consider the book and take time
to meet the author.
</P>
<P>
   Despite recent fame and new-found wealth _ Miss Baxter split her
advance with Ms. Miller _ the new Knopf author has barely changed a
thing about her life. She has made her first will, which includes
bequests to members of her large extended family. Other than that,
all she has done is buy a videocassette recorder so she can watch
the video made to promote her book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I change?'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
