</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PENTAGON-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COHEN, 4 NATO COUNTERPARTS DISCUSS POSSIBLE INVASION PLAN
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secretary of Defense William Cohen met with four of
his NATO counterparts in Germany on Thursday in an unpublicized
meeting and discussed what it would take to mount a ground invasion
of Kosovo, U.S. and European officials said Friday. Cohen and the
defense ministers of Britain, France, Germany and Italy received a
preliminary assessment by NATO's commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, that
projected that a ground invasion would involve a force of as many
as 150,000 NATO troops, one NATO official said.
</P>
<P>
   They came to no consensus on whether ground troops were needed,
but Britain's defense minister, George Robertson, indicated his
country was prepared to contribute as many as 50,000 British
soldiers, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and other NATO members, including Germany and
Italy, have strongly opposed mounting a ground invasion to drive
Yugoslavia's army and paramilitary police from Kosovo if President
Slobodan Milosevic continues to refuse to withdraw his forces and
allow the province's ethnic Albanians to return to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   But Britain has pressed the Clinton administration and the other
allies to at least begin planning for the possibility of a ground
invasion, saying that time is running out to build up the necessary
forces before winter.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's secretary general, Javier Solana, last month ordered
Clark to draft preliminary assessments on what forces would be
involved. Those assessments have not yet been made public, and
officials have refused to discuss them in any detail.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and his colleagues, representing the five most influential
NATO allies, met on the sidelines of a conference of European
defense ministers in Bonn. That conference focused on the subject
of integrating the European Union with its defense organization,
the Western European Union.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen's spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, confirmed the meeting took
place, but offered no explanation of why Cohen's trip was not
disclosed. Cohen flew to Germany on Thursday and returned to
Washington that night. He said it was a convenient gathering of
most of NATO's defense ministers for a review of NATO's strategy.
It was not clear why ministers from the other, smaller NATO
countries did not attend.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said Cohen and his counterparts agreed to support plans by
Clark to widen and intensify the airstrikes in Yugoslavia and to
move immediately to put into place a peacekeeping force of nearly
50,000 troops on Kosovo's border.
</P>
<P>
   ``They reviewed the whole situation,'' Bacon said. ``They came
out with an agreement that the air campaign is working.''
</P>
<P>
   That campaign continued Friday with yet another withering
barrage made possible by clear weather and the addition of still
more warplanes, including 18 American F-18s that took part in the
strikes for the first time from a base in Hungary, one of NATO's
three new members.
</P>
<P>
   NATO announced Friday afternoon that it had carried out 310
strike missions in the previous 24 hours; the day before there were
308. In the last two or three days alone, NATO and Pentagon
officials said, NATO has conducted more missions and struck more
targets with greater intensity than in the entire first week of the
war.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has focused its latest attacks on Yugoslavia's electrical
grids and its telephone service. Large parts of Serbia, the
country's dominant republic, remained without electricity and
water, including most of the capital, Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had planned on intensifying the air campaign,'' Cohen said
in an interview with reporters at the Pentagon Friday, in which his
trip to Germany did not come up. ``And that intensification is now
well under way.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said that after more than two months of bombing he was
``increasingly confident'' that NATO's campaign would prevail and
force Milosevic to relent. He said repeated strikes were taking a
toll on Yugoslavia's Serbian-led Army and paramilitary units.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each day that goes by more and more damage is being
inflicted,'' he said. ``I think we're reaching the point now where
you're going to start seeing a much different reaction on the part
of Serb forces.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He and other officials acknowledged that, however battered,
Yugoslavia's armed forces were still able to carry out operations
against the ethnic Albanian rebels fighting for independence in
Kosovo. They also continued to put up resistance to NATO's
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   An American A-10 narrowly missed being hit by a burst of
anti-aircraft artillery, Maj. Gen. Charles Wald, the director of
strategic planning on the Pentagon's Joint Chiefs of Staff, said
Friday. Only two allied aircraft have been shot down in the
conflict, along with a number of pilotless drones, but Wald said
that several have been hit by enemy fire.
</P>
<P>
   A day after the International Criminal Tribunal in The Hague,
Netherlands, indicted Milosevic and four aides on charges of war
crimes, Pentagon and administration officials expressed confidence
that the external and internal pressures on the Yugoslav government
were having an effect.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department on Friday stepped up the diplomatic
pressure by displaying photographs turned over to the tribunal's
investigators for use as evidence. The images taken from satellites
show villages before and after attacks by Yugoslav forces, and
include the locales mentioned in the tribunal's indictment. The
department's spokesman, James Rubin, said the photographs help to
corroborate evidence that the Serbs are making efforts to cover up
killings.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs taken of a mass grave at Poblek, near Glogovac,
illustrate one pattern. Yugoslav forces were believed to have later
exhumed the bodies there and reburied them in individual graves at
a cemetery near Sikatova, Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The second pattern corroborated by photos is the burning of
victims, also to conceal evidence, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The president's national security adviser, Sandy Berger, said in
an interview Friday that the Yugoslav unity that coalesced around
Milosevic early in the campaign had turned into ``a grim
foreboding,'' especially after the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic is a sinking ship,'' he said. ``If you were around
him in Belgrade, I'm not sure you'd hitch your star to a sinking
ship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
