</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICH-MUSIC-WARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTAL ALERT ON CONCERT TICKETS IS SOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Michigan state Senate has passed a bill requiring music
promoters to print warnings on tickets for concerts by performers
whose music is considered inappropriate for minors. It is believed
to be the first such bill to pass a legislative chamber.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which passed by a vote of 25-11 on Tuesday and must be
approved by the state House of Representatives before becoming law,
requires a warning on tickets and advertisements for concerts by
any musical act whose recordings have been given a parental-warning
sticker by the music industry.
</P>
<P>
   Such warnings alert parents to recordings with sexually explicit
or violent lyrics. Failure by a concert promoter or the owner of a
concert hall to do so would be a misdemeanor with a fine of as much
as $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the bill, including the Recording Industry
Association of America, note that the advisory stickers on compact
discs are voluntary and arbitrary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
