 UNDATED: an autopsy.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Doctor, before you performed the autopsy, did you check for a
pulse?
</P>
<P>
   A: No
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you check for blood pressure?
</P>
<P>
   A: No.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you check for breathing?
</P>
<P>
   A: No.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So, then it is possible that the patient was alive when you
began the autopsy?
</P>
<P>
   A: No.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can you be so sure, Doctor?
</P>
<P>
   A: Because his brain was sitting on my desk in a jar.
</P>
<P>
   Q: But could the patient have still been alive nevertheless?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is possible that he could have been alive and practicing
law somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; signs that you've had too much of the 90's &LR;
</P>
<P>
   .
</P>
<P>
   You tried to enter your password on the microwave.
</P>
<P>
   You now think of three espressos as `getting wasted.`
</P>
<P>
   You haven't played solitaire with a real deck of cards in years.
</P>
<P>
   You have a list of 15 phone numbers to reach your family of 3.
</P>
<P>
   You e-mail your son in his room to tell him that dinner is
ready, and he e-mails you back `What's for dinner?`
</P>
<P>
   Your daughter sells Girl Scout Cookies via her web site.
</P>
<P>
   You chat several times a day with a stranger from South Africa,
but you haven't spoken to your next door neighbor yet this year.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't give your valentine a card this year, but you posted
one for your e-mail buddies via a web page.
</P>
<P>
   Your daughter just bought a C.D. of all the records your college
roommate used to play.
</P>
<P>
   You check the ingredients on a can of chicken noodle soup to see
if it contains Echinacea.
</P>
<P>
   You check your blow dryer to see if it's Y2K compliant.
</P>
<P>
   Your grandmother clogs up your e-mail Inbox, asking you to send
her JPEG file of your newborn so she can create a screen saver.
</P>
<P>
   You pull up in your own driveway and use your cell-phone to see
if anyone is home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   I boarded a sardine-can subway train going from Lexington and
68th Street to 14th Street and couldn't even move my briefcase.
After Grand Central the car emptied, and I sat down and
instinctively checked my trouser pocket for my wallet. It was gone!
I felt fortunate because I only carry a few things _ money ($40),
garage ticket, etc. _ in it, but no credit cards or licenses. On
the way back, I stopped at a police station inside the 14th Street
station and related the incident to a desk officer who told me to
file a report or simply let it go _ my choice. I decided not to
waste the time. The officer seemed appreciative and wrote down the
number of Lost and Found, which he suggested I call later on. As I
was putting the paper in my jacket pocket, I felt my wallet. It was
intact, except for the $40. I went back to the desk officer with
the great news that the pickpocket had put the empty wallet back.
He said he had never heard of such a thing in 15 years on the force
and clearly didn't believe my story. I can't make up my mind if
returning the wallet was an act of kindness, professional courtesy
or sheer chutzpa.
</P>
<P>
   _MICHAEL J. SAMEK
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Isler was at a Thai restaurant in SoHo when he
overheard an exchange between a couple in their mid-20's and their
waiter.
</P>
<P>
   Woman: ``Do you know any low-key places around here where we can
get a drink and relax?''
</P>
<P>
   Waiter: ``Oh, you're not from around here? Connecticut, perhaps?
That's where I'm originally from.''
</P>
<P>
   Man, looking embarrassed: ``Actually we're from the Upper East
Side. We usually don't go south of 14th Street.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Christie's exhibition of Impressionist art, and a
father was walking his young son through the galleries. Trixie E.
Dorsett listened to the father explaining their provenance. ``A lot
of these paintings were painted around Nice,'' he said. The boy
seemed uninterested. ``Oh,'' he said. ``You know Nice,'' the father
explained. ``That's where the airport is.''
</P>
<P>
   Leda Goldsmith's 3-year-old granddaughter, Jessica, was watching
``Peter Pan'' on video. Soon after it started, she told her mother
that she was scared and asked that it be turned off. ``I'll watch
it tomorrow when I'm older,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Raab and his wife, Judy, of Fort Lee, N.J., were
enjoying a brief New York vacation. Every morning, they left their
hotel and walked a few blocks up Broadway to breakfast in their
favorite cafe. A panhandler always stood in the same spot, next to
a supermarket. One morning, Mrs. Raab noticed a few pennies on the
sidewalk in front of the market, not more than a few feet from the
panhandler. She bent down to pick up the coins and muttered some
comment about it obviously being beneath the dignity of the
panhandler to stoop for pennies. He apparently made out what she
was saying, looked flustered but quickly recovered. ``I'm
conducting an experiment to see what type of person will bend to
pick up a few pennies,'' he announced with aplomb. ``You'd be
surprised at what I've learned.''
</P>
<P>
   Herbert Weissenstein has observed that the fiercest corporate
competitors can be drawn together by a common enemy _ city parking
enforcement agents. One morning he saw a U.P.S. man with an
overnight package under his arm dashing up to a Fedex man loading
his hand truck. ``Watch my truck for a minute,'' the U.P.S. man
said. ``No problem'' was the immediate response.
</P>
<P>
   Susanne Fischer was amused at the hours of operation sign she
saw posted at a dry cleaner on the Upper East Side. The days Monday
through Saturday were each listed as 7 A.M. to 7 P.M.
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday? ``Go to church,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   My husband, Elmer, and I were stopped for a red light at the
entrance to the West Side Highway at 57th Street.
</P>
<P>
   A young man appeared in front of our car with posters made from
corrugated cartons.
</P>
<P>
   He waved to us and proceeded to unfold each one of five. They
read:
</P>
<P>
   1. Relax
</P>
<P>
   2. I will not clean your windows
</P>
<P>
   3. (a smiling cartoon face)
</P>
<P>
   4. What do you call a female deer?
</P>
<P>
   5. A doe _ and I can use some.
</P>
<P>
   We gave him some to honor his creativity.
</P>
<P>
   _CYNTHIA PADER
</P>
<P>
   After 43 years, I finally had a New York experience. I was
walking to Pennsylvania Station and stopped at a greengrocer to
surprise my wife with a bunch of flowers. As I was crossing Seventh
Avenue, a convertible pulled up next to me. The driver pointed to
his female companion, said he was losing an argument, and would I
consider selling him my flowers. I nodded, and when he asked how
much, I thought quickly and said $20. He pulled two 10's out of his
pocket and exchanged them for the flowers. I returned to the
greengrocer, bought another bunch for $10 and walked away $10
richer.
</P>
<P>
   -JOHN F. HELLDORFER
</P>
<P>
   Alison Goodwin Schiff was looking for wrapping paper at a party
store when she passed a little girl and her mother standing in
front of the party favors section. The youngster, about 4 years
old, asked for one of the party toys, and when her mother said no,
she replied loudly, ``You'll have to speak up, I can't hear you.''
</P>
