<HEADER>
A5641 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-460&AMP;A     05-28 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 EVIDENCE OF WAR CRIMES SOUGHT FROM REFUGEES AT FORT DIX 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Human rights investigators have begun interviewing Albanian
refugees from Kosovo at Fort Dix, N.J., making the Army
base-turned-refugee center into an important site in the efforts to
document evidence of war crimes against President Slobodan
Milosevic and other top Yugoslav officials.
</P>
<P>
   State Department investigators have been interviewing refugees
at the center since Sunday. They are gathering testimony about
specific atrocities, collecting the names of Yugoslavs accused of
carrying them out, and delivering lists of potential witnesses for
any future prosecution to the international war crimes tribunal in
The Hague, Netherlands, a State Department official said.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Amnesty International has been interviewing refugees
for its own report on the Serbian campaign to rid Kosovo of
Albanians, said Sean Crowley, a spokesman for the human rights
group.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, David W. Scheffer, the U.S. ambassador at large for
war crimes issues, visited Fort Dix, now the main location for
interviewing Kosovar refugees about their experiences at the hands
of Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is also arranging formal overseas
interviews with Kosovar refugees, probably at locations near, but
not in, refugee camps in Macedonia, the State Department official
said. Scheffer made no statement at Fort Dix.
</P>
<P>
   The official said investigators were learning about previously
unknown human rights violations through the interviews at Fort Dix.
But the official would not specify their nature.
</P>
<P>
   At the military base that has become their temporary haven,
Kosovar refugees _ who crossed the world for safety, but appeared
to have given up on justice after all they had witnessed _ took
heart upon learning that Milosevic had been indicted this week for
crimes against humanity. The charges against him read like a
catalog of their nightmares: murder, persecution and forced
deportation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people all over the world will smile when they hear
the news: that the 21st century won't belong to Milosevic or people
like him,'' Azad Cubai, a 53-year-old miner from Pristina, said
through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Though many are far less optimistic than Cubai, noting that
Serbs indicted for war crimes in Bosnia years ago remain at large,
the mood at Fort Dix appeared brighter, as families and friends
gathered under the trees to discuss the significance of the
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Rudi Rubik, a 23-year-old student from Jakova, said he thought
the Yugoslav president should have been called before the Hague
tribunal ``five or seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has done many war crimes, not only in Kosovo, but in
Croatia, Bosnia,'' Rubik said.
</P>
<P>
   Ramadan Sulejman, 44, agreed. ``Every day he's doing more and
more massacres,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Sulejman's friend, Liman Fazliu, 39, said he did not put much
stock in the tribunal. Fazliu said he saw in his own living room a
Serbian policeman slash half his neighbor's face because the man
did not give money on demand. Fazliu said he harbored no illusions
about the Serbs' handing over Milosevic for trial. ``It's
important, but only as a gesture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cubai's wife, Jezida, 45, said that indicting Milosevic and a
handful of government and military officials was not enough.
``There's not only one Milosevic,'' she said. ``There are many of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Cubais moved toward the Macedonian border, Serbian forces
rushed them down narrow paths along with thousands of other Kosovar
Albanians and Mrs. Cubai said they saw a mother drop her infant,
who was crushed by the stampede. They saw Serbian housewives, their
former neighbors, throw open their windows to shower them with
curses and spit on them as they were being forced from town, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rubik said that not only the leaders and the laws, but also the
Serbian people had changed in the last decade, as the government
demonized and disenfranchised ethnic Albanians. It stripped them of
jobs and access to education, health care and other services.
</P>
<P>
   Rubik remembered one Serbian teacher who taught him the Serb
language when he was about 10. Her name was Vera, and he thought
she loved children. But as her son went into the army, ``she
couldn't be so nice to Albanians anymore,'' he said. ``Not even to
the children.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
