<HEADLINE>
BRIEF SUMMARY OF EVENTS CONCERNING THE CRISIS IN KOSOVO  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; DIPLOMACY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --In Belgrade, Russia's Balkans envoy, Viktor Chernomyrdin, met
Slobodan Milosevic a day after the Yugoslav leader was indicted on
charges of war crimes and said he was pleased with the talks so far
but cautioned that difficult negotiations lay ahead.
</P>
<P>
   --In Brussels, Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott briefed
NATO officials on discussions that he conducted this week in Moscow
with Chernomyrdin and added that the Russian representative spoke
only for his own government with Milosevic, and not for NATO.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMBAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --American planes began bombing runs from Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   --Yugoslav forces entered Bosnia this week and temporarily
detained six soldiers with the NATO-led peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   --NATO missiles hit more of Serbia's electricity network,
knocking out two major power-distribution stations in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; REFUGEES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   --The U.S.-based International Rescue Committee said it planned
to begin airdrops of food soon to help displaced people in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ON THE WEB &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Continuous coverage of the conflict is available from The New
York Times on the Web: http://www.nytimes.com
</P>
