<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0396 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5643 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TISCH-LOEWS-ART-3TAKE     05-28 1302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TISCH-LOEWS-ART-3TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIKE FATHERS, LIKE SONS: A MANAGEMENT STYLE REMAINS AT LOEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Mass.)   (ART ADV: Graphic of holdings of Loews Corp. is being sent to NYT
graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30)  
 (af)  
 By HILARY ROSENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ James Tisch's Manhattan office is surprisingly
cramped, abounding with family photos and the detritus that comes
with a 23-year investment career. Two high shelves are crowded with
acrylic-encased tombstone ads memorializing stock and bond
offerings past.
</P>
<P>
   There's a bubble-gum machine, a shiny megaphone that Michael
Milken's junk bond department once sent to clients, and a can of
New Coke, which Tisch had thought might become a collectors' item.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want to touch base?'' he asks puckishly, and then pulls
out an actual baseball base from behind his desk. Next, he
excitedly shows how a photograph of the Paradise and the Orpheum,
the first two supertankers he bought, appears exactly the same
upside down as it does right-side up, because of the reflection on
the water's surface.
</P>
<P>
   Is this lighthearted 46-year-old who, with his wire-rimmed
glasses and flyaway hair, could pass for a young Woody Allen really
the offspring of that incessantly pessimistic master investor,
Laurence A. Tisch?
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes _ son and successor both. In a momentous transition at
the Loews Corp.,, the $21 billion New York-based conglomerate
controlled by the Tisch family, James S. Tisch took the reins of
leadership from his father, now 76, and his uncle, Preston R.
Tisch, 72, becoming chief executive on Jan. 1. He was joined by his
older brother Andrew and his cousin Jonathan, who both oversee
Loews businesses, in a new office of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors are hoping that this will be a time of transition
in how the company is run as well.
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio of businesses and investments that make up Loews,
one of the market's most storied long-term bets, has floundered
over the last couple of years, groaning under the weight of its
out-of-favor tobacco, insurance and oil industry holdings and
burdened by a relentlessly bearish investing stance.
</P>
<P>
   Loews stock, of which the senior Tisches hold 31 percent, has
lately lagged far behind the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   But if some people think that the ascent of a new generation of
Tisches might signal not just a lighter tone but also a shift to a
more bullish, mainstream investment stance, they are bound to be
disappointed. In an era of turn-on-a-dime management shifts,
continuity is Loews' hallmark.
</P>
<P>
   For five full years before taking the top office, James Tisch
was the company's president. And for several years all three
younger Tisches, each of whom has made a career at Loews, worked
together with their fathers on the management committee.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the younger crowd of Tisches at the Loews helm is
defiantly sticking to the craft their fathers honed so well,
pursuing an investment and business discipline that is deeply
focused on value, extremely long-term in its outlook and
unabashedly contrarian.
</P>
<P>
   James Tisch's high spirits may reflect the fact that, as his
generation takes control, some of Loews' beaten-down businesses and
investments may be starting to rebound.
</P>
<P>
   First-quarter earnings of $45.4 million, reported on May 5,
contrasted with a loss of $83.7 million in the comparable period a
year earlier. The CNA Financial Corp., Loews' 85 percent-owned
insurance company, seems to be making progress in cutting costs and
sharpening its strategy. Oil prices have rebounded 39.2 percent
this year, improving the prospects for Loews' energy holdings. And
the company has made an unexpectedly sudden killing in one of the
year's hottest stocks, Global Crossing Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the responsibility for Loews' current state goes to
James Tisch, who around the office is called Jimmy. The third of
Laurence Tisch's four sons, he was the one who inherited his
father's talent for investing in out-of-favor businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Scarsdale, N.Y., he spent two summers working in
Loews businesses: When he was 10, he helped the bellmen at the
Americana Hotel in Miami Beach, now the Sheraton Bal Harbour; and
while a student at Cornell University, he was a route salesman for
Lorillard tobacco. ``It was never said that I was to work at Loews,
but I always assumed it was something I would do,'' Tisch said.
``It was instinctive.''
</P>
<P>
   After he received a master's degree from the University of
Pennsylvania's Wharton School of Business and completed a stint in
CNA's training program in Chicago, his father brought him back to
New York to work in the investment department at Loews.
</P>
<P>
   As the younger Tisch tells it, his father neglected to tell
Joseph Rosenberg, the longtime head of the department, about the
new trainee until the day before he arrived. And then, all the
elder Tisch said was: ``Do me a favor. Take an hour and teach him
the business.''
</P>
<P>
   The story says something about Laurence Tisch's freewheeling
style as well as Loews' enduring culture. Meetings and memos are
few, but there is constant personal interaction. ``With Larry, you
get your day in court for about five minutes, and then it's over;
no endless meetings,'' said Howard Stringer, whom Tisch made
president of CBS News, and later of the broadcast group, when Tisch
was the television company's chief executive. ``He's instinctive in
his decision-making process,'' added Stringer, now chairman and
chief executive of the Sony Corp. of America.
</P>
<P>
   With James Tisch, decisions may take a bit longer. Bernard
Hengesbaugh, chief executive of CNA, said: ``His approach is to
make sure he understands an issue before he takes it anywhere. He
invites lots of discussion, what I call loud reasoning.''
</P>
<P>
   But the most important lesson the son took from the father was
the value of patience in investing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, James Tisch, then vice president at Loews, bought seven
supertankers for the scrap-value price of $42 million. But it
wasn't until shipping rates improved in 1986 that Tisch set the
ships under way. Loews sold a 51 percent interest in the tanker
operation for about $150 million in 1990; today, its 49 percent
stake is worth around $85 million, and Tisch believes the business
has good long-term prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Such wildly successful bottom-fishing became almost routine in
the 1980s and into the '90s, as James Tisch and Rosenberg managed
the company's investments. Among the company's most lucrative deals
was its acquisition in 1989 of what is now Diamond Offshore
Drilling, which Tisch built into one of the world's largest
offshore drilling companies.
</P>
<P>
   Loews also has done very well with its $120 million investment
in the Canary Wharf Group's giant office complex in London in 1995.
For that investment, Loews has received $120 million in cash and
retains a stake worth more than $600 million.
</P>
<P>
   The family's management methods haven't always been popular.
There were howls of protest over cost-cutting at CBS Inc. when
Laurence Tisch took over as chief executive in 1987. But owning
about one-fifth of the network was a bonanza for Loews:
Westinghouse bought CBS in 1995 for $5.4 billion; James Tisch says
Loews realized an after-tax return of 15 percent to 20 percent a
year, bettering the market's performance during the period.
</P>
<P>
   The two other Tisch scions at Loews share James Tisch's
long-term perspective, and much more. Growing up, their two
families lived near each other in Westchester and took vacations
together, often at Loews-owned hotels. ``Our parents taught us,
your first responsibility is to your family,'' said Andrew H.
Tisch, 49.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's natural, then, that when asked why he was the one
who ultimately became chief executive _ and not Andrew or Jonathan
_ James Tisch became irritable. ``While I may be CEO, Jonathan,
Andrew and I operate collegially in any or all decisions that are
made,'' he snapped. ``This works because there's a bond that's been
built up not over the short term or even over a career, but over
entire lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Loews' conglomerate structure has allowed all three men ample
room to find something they can call their own _ and helped keep
them out of one another's way. ``We have very different skill
sets,'' said Jonathan M. Tisch, 45.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew added, ``I've always enjoyed running companies, Jimmy
likes the investing and Jon always loved the hotels.''
</P>
<P>
   All three started at Loews in earnest during their 20s. Andrew,
Laurence's oldest son, a graduate of Cornell's School of Hotel
Administration and Harvard Business School, began with stints at
Lorillard and Bulova, the watchmaker.
</P>
<P>
   He incurred the ire of anti-tobacco groups when, as chief
executive of Lorillard in 1994, he was among the industry leaders
who testified before a congressional subcommittee that there was no
conclusive evidence that cigarettes cause fatal disease. Today, he
is the chairman of Bulova and corporate liaison for the Lorillard
unit. He also oversees the Loews corporate office staff.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Tisch, a graduate of Tufts University, began his career
outside Loews, as a TV cameraman and producer at WBZ in Boston,
then an NBC affiliate. He joined Loews Hotels in 1980, becoming
president in 1986 and chief executive three years later.
</P>
<P>
   Like his cousin James, Jonathan brings a cornball sense of humor
to the job. A few years ago, as part of a Loews proposal aimed at
winning approval from Miami Beach officials for building a new
hotel, he videotaped himself, wearing a blond wig, skirt, high
heels and fake fingernails, interviewing residents about the need
for a new hotel. (It worked; the Loews Miami Beach Hotel opened in
December, part of an aggressive expansion program. Loews now has 15
luxury hotels and resorts, and four more in development).
</P>
<P>
   Outsiders say they are struck by how the family feeling
permeates the business. ``They don't do things autocratically,''
said Scott M. Black, president of Delphi Management, a money
management firm in Boston, who has known the family for years and
who has invested on and off in Loews stock. ``They sit down and
discuss things as a family.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul J. Fribourg, chief executive of the privately owned
Continental Grain Co. in Manhattan and a Loews director, added that
``there is open give-and-take'' among all five Tisches on the
board.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a fundamental love between them that transcends the
day-to-day business,'' Fribourg said. Among the younger set, he
added, ``there'll be a healthy challenging of each other, but never
tension or disagreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Fribourg said he has often observed the two elder Tisch brothers
watching their sons handle the discussion, content not to
intervene. Although they have stepped back from day-to-day
management, the co-founders remain in the picture as very active
co-chairmen.
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Tisch, for example, was the point man earlier this
month when John W. Meriwether, chairman of Long-Term Capital
Management, approached Loews, an early investor in the hedge fund,
about the possibility of Loews' investing more money. (No decision
has been made.)
</P>
<P>
   The co-chairmen's business bond goes back over half a century,
to 1946. That year, Laurence, just out of the Army, spotted a
classified ad for a small winter resort, Laurel-in-the-Pines, in
Lakewood, N.J., and convinced his family to buy it for $125,000,
forming Tisch Hotels Inc. The brothers have since built a
collection of disparate businesses, with $73.3 billion in assets at
the end of March. The Loews name came from the 1959 acquisition of
Loews Theaters, which the company sold in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   While Preston excelled at management, Laurence was the brother
with the nose for value investing. He has often been compared to
Warren E. Buffett, another famed investor who has assembled a
portfolio of large stakes in companies and who also has a giant
exposure to the property-and-casualty business.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the comparison is a bit awkward: Buffett's Berkshire
Hathaway, despite recent weakness, has risen 35.4 percent on an
annualized basis for the five years ended May 21. Loews has
returned an annualized 14.1 percent in that time, and suffered as
the stock fell from its 52-week high of $106.0625 in November to a
low of $69 on April 12. The stock closed on Friday at $81.3125,
well below its book value of $96 a share.
</P>
<P>
   That divergence was perhaps inevitable: although both Buffett
and the Tisches ostensibly share a value-oriented stance, the
similarities end there. Buffett invests in market leaders like
Coca-Cola, Gillette, and Disney, while Loews has preferred to buy
truly down-and-out businesses, including some that have suffered
most heavily over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   Loews has still beaten the market in the long term. From 1960
through 1998, Loews stock delivered a 20 percent average annual
return, versus 12 percent for the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the last few years have been particularly trying, as the
company's major businesses have suffered. James Tisch is adamant
that Loews is mostly a victim of circumstance, that the cycles that
have pummeled the profits of both its energy and insurance holdings
have been unfortunately synchronized recently. And he says there is
precious little that can be done to shake investor perceptions
about the lawsuit-plagued tobacco business.
</P>
<P>
   But it's clear that the Tisches have compounded Loews' poor
performance by placing enormous bets, using index futures and
options, that stocks in general would fall.
</P>
<P>
   The slump has prompted complaints from analysts and investors.
Some investors are particularly critical of Loews' short position.
``I really don't think they should be gambling with the
shareholders' money,'' said one portfolio manager, who used to hold
Loews stock and spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some analysts are put off by James Tisch's obvious
disdain for those whose views are not as long-term as his own. ``He
has a tendency to be pretty brusque,'' said Kevin Simpson, an
energy analyst at Merrill Lynch, who nevertheless said he admired
Tisch's achievements at Diamond Offshore.
</P>
<P>
   Patient as he is as an investor, Tisch has not sat idly as
problems festered. CNA, the insurer that contributed 29 percent to
Loews' 1998 net income (excluding Loews' investment losses), had
tried to beat down expenses since acquiring Continental Insurance
in 1995 amid a price war in the property-and-casualty business. As
results languished in 1997 and 1998, Tisch began calling for a
formal reorganization program.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, CNA announced a turnaround plan: discontinuing
unprofitable business lines, consolidating operations and laying
off 2,400 employees. And in February, Hengesbaugh, the chief
operating officer, was promoted to chief executive to carry out the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   CNA expects savings of more than $300 million a year starting in
2000, though Tisch concedes that criticism of the slow pace of
change at the insurer is ``not unjustified.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the problems at Lorillard _ 43 percent of Loews'
1998 net income (excluding investment losses) _ appear immune to
any short-term solution. Hopes were high last fall that the master
settlement agreement between the tobacco companies and 46 states
would bring an end to much of the litigation against the industry.
But new attacks, along with some big courtroom losses, have come in
recent months. At year-end, Lorillard was a defendant in 520 suits.
</P>
<P>
   Although there has been speculation lately that Loews will spin
off Lorillard, Tisch says that isn't an option. ``Spinoffs don't
work,'' he shrugged, saying they don't necessarily rid a company of
potential liability. How about a sale? ``People say you could sell
it, but to whom? It's a bucking bronco we're on.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tisch says he does not regret that his father and uncle
bought Lorillard in 1968. Even in a declining market, Lorillard's
brands _ including Newport and Old Gold _ are gaining market share,
he noted. Last year, tobacco generated $352 million in net income
on $2.87 billion in revenue, down from $363.1 million on $2.4
billion in revenue in 1997, even including legal settlement costs
of $346.5 million and $122 million, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, he said, the lawsuits will die down and the market
will accept settlement payments as a cost of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Tisch is doing some characteristically
Loews-style, contrarian investing: He's buying Loews stock. Loews
bought 2.4 million shares in 1998, and one person with knowledge of
the matter said it has bought 3.3 million shares so far this year _
a hefty 3 percent of the stock. Tisch has also bought some CNA
stock and has made sure that the insurer and Diamond Offshore are
buying their own shares.
</P>
<P>
   What remains a mystery to some _ given the company's historical
aversion to risky investments _ is why Loews has made such
high-stakes bets on a market decline. The company has lost $1.7
billion since 1997 on market futures and options. And the loss
would have been even greater if it hadn't been for the stock
market's bungee jump last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Loews eliminated about half of its short positions in the fall;
it meant to cover more, but the market shot up before it could do
so. As the market was falling last week, Loews declined to comment
on whether it was taking off more of its short position.
</P>
<P>
   Tisch argued that a value investor in companies can gauge value
in a market. ``The benchmarks you use to determine value are
ringing alarms,'' he said, referring to price-to-earnings multiples
and other value measurements.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``We shouldn't have done it,'' he said of the company's
bets against the market. ``Our entire short enterprise has been an
example of poor investing.''
</P>
<P>
   The three co-presidents clearly have more work ahead.
Fortunately, they have also inherited their fathers' interest in
maintaining a sense of balance in their work lives. James Tisch
limits his workday to no more than 12 hours. He starts at 6:15
a.m., when his father-in-law, who has breakfasted with the family
for years, picks him up at his apartment on East 79th Street to
drive him to work, and is done by 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other Tisches, he does charitable work in his off
hours. He is the president of the UJA-Federation of New York, a
Jewish social services organization, and is on the boards of the
Mount Sinai-NYU Medical Center Health System and FEGS, a human
services agency based in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the stock price of Diamond Offshore, up 34.6 percent
since its low this year on March 1, the brightest spot in the Loews
portfolio has been the company's stake in Global Crossing, the Los
Angeles fiber optic company that is seeking to merge with U S West,
the Baby Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Hillel Weinberger, one of 15 Loews professionals who manage
portfolios of Loews and CNA, bought $20 million of Global Crossing
debt in a private placement in 1996. With the debt came warrants
that allowed the holder to buy shares of Global Crossing stock at a
specified price.
</P>
<P>
   Weinberger sold the debt and bought more warrants, eventually
giving CNA a 9.8 percent stake in Global Crossing _ now worth $1.9
billion.
</P>
<P>
   What will Loews do next? It had $2.6 billion in excess cash at
year-end. ``The reason we haven't made many investments in the past
few years is we worry much more about our downside than our
upside,'' James Tisch said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Loews is looking at possible acquisitions, Tisch said,
the family feels no pressure to move _ and its track record of
wanton disregard for market conventions certainly confirms that
contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got asbestos-lined pockets,'' he said. ``We don't let
cash burn a hole in them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
