<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELTON FRUSTRATES GALAXY COACHES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At the end of practice Wednesday, Los Angeles
Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid and assistant Ralph Perez pulled Welton
aside as the other players left the field.
</P>
<P>
   Schmid wouldn't reveal the content of that conversation, but it
was clear that he's not happy with his Brazilian striker, who
hasn't scored this season.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Welton was among the MLS leaders in points, notching
17 goals and 14 assists. Many of his goals, however, weren't the
result of dazzling finishes. They were more of the opportunistic
variety, a result of being in the right place at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   Welton's rhythm, flow and finishing was missing in action during
the Galaxy's 1-0 victory over New England last Saturday, forcing
Schmid to pull him from the game.
</P>
<P>
   And it appears Schmid may bench Welton again in favor of New
Zealand midfielder Simon Elliott when the Galaxy (5-5) visits
Columbus (6-3) this afternoon at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had an injury earlier this year that may have set him back,
but he's healthy now,'' Schmid said of Welton. ``He's starting to
work harder at training but it seems his timing is off.''
</P>
<P>
   The other problem with Welton is understanding his body
language. Former Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano had problems with
him last season, especially when he disciplined the 24-year-old
from Rio de Janeiro.
</P>
<P>
   Welton may be going through the same pouting phase with Schmid,
but as long as he doesn't produce, he isn't going to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Ralph and I) have talked to him about what is it that will
motivate him,'' Schmid said. ``No player likes to sit on the bench
for motivation, but sometimes that becomes the motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   It may just be that Welton's lackluster play is the result of
the Galaxy trying to trade him. Schmid noted that other MLS teams
have expressed interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miami has expressed (interest) in Welton,'' Schmid said. ``We
haven't had direct contact with Miami, but we have been looking at
ways to improve our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles may see a glimpse of its future when it enters the
new, 22,500-seat Columbus Crew Stadium -- the first soccer-only
venue in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Columbus is 2-0 in its new stadium, built primarily to
strengthen its season-ticket base and provide fans with a
European-type soccer environment.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy officials have hinted that if the team leaves the Rose
Bowl, they would build a new stadium. Schmid is hoping that the
excitement of playing in a hostile environment will motivate his
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our players will get pumped because it's a new
field,'' he said. ``I think it's going to be a good situation. If
we win, it makes it a big thing for us to beat a sound Columbus
team on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   A win would mark Los Angeles' second consecutive victory and
could be the first sign that the Galaxy is turning the corner. And
Mexican standout Carlos Hermosillo should be training with the team
late next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any win is nice at this point, but a good result would give
this team a great feeling going home for two games at the Rose
Bowl,'' Schmid said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
