his fund. ``It is a combination of science and art.'' (Mike
Peters/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) SEBASTOPOL, Calif. -- May 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY
30 -- INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A, 5-28 -- Michael Slater, principal analyst
at Cahners Microdesign Resources, which publishes technology
industry newsletters. ``I'm not going to lose any sleep over
Intel's success as a company,'' he says. ``But I would not make any
bets on the price of its stock.'' (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) KUKES, Albania -- May 28, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RECONSTRUCT-5,
5-28 -- After Serbs rampaged through his village, Bekim Duraku, 21,
of Velika Krusa found his father's bullet-riddled body in a
riverbed. He still carries a crumpled pack of Marlboro cigarettes
that he took from his pocket. His father's burial was cut short by
mortar fire. (Edward Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) BOJANE REFUGEE CAMP, Macedonia -- May 28, 1999 --
KOSOVO-RECONSTRUCT-4, 5-28 -- Like tens of thousands of residents
of Kosovo's capital, Ramadan Osmani, 63, was force-marched past
lines of armed, masked Serbs to spend the night in a jammed
railroad station. He and his family had to wait 12 hours for a
train to Macedonia. (Andrew Testa/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) UNDATED -- May 28, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RECONSTRUCT-3, 5-28 --
A 70-year-old retired policeman, Hafez Berisha tried to hide in
Pristina for two months, but he fled after he saw Serbian policemen
pull two men from a bread line and march them off to an unkown
fate. ``You can't even buy bread,'' he says. (Andrew Testa/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) TIRANA, Albania -- May 28, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RECONSTRUCT-2,
5-28 --Hani Hoxha from Djakovica displays photos of his
grandchildren in Germany - his only surviving family since the
Serbs killed all his other relatives in Kosovo. ``That night I saw
an old man, about 80, killed and burned and a 15-year-old boy as
well,'' he says of the March night when Nato bombs began to fall
and black-masked Serbs swaggered through town. (Heidi Bradner/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- May 28, 1999 -- KOSOVO-RECONSTRUCT-1, 5-28 --
Bored with hiding inside her home in Pristina, Luljeta Jarina
stepped into the backyard garden one day and was shot at by a
Serbian sniper. This week the police rounded up 18 men, including
her father, and took away all but him and two others. (Andrew
Testa/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) LOS ANGELES -- May 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 30 --
LA-BILLBOARDS-2, 5-28 -- ``Tall walls'' like this promotion for the
movie ``Tarzan,'' are a recent billboard innovation. Car-bound
Angelenos are an affluent, captive audience, and billboards are
tightly woven into the urban fabric, part of the city's collective
memory and conversation. (Edward Carreon/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) LOS ANGELES -- May 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 30 --
LA-BILLBOARDS-1, 5-28 -- Angelyne's Los Angeles billboard made her
a celebrity. The city is ground zero for drive-by messages, and the
art of attracting motorists' attention with sharp humor or shock
value is more lustily pursued here than anywhere else. (Edward
Carreon/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- May 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 30 --
ABOUT-GM-TRUCKS-4, 5-28 -- With more room and better controls, the
Silverado's cabin sets new truck standards. The classy interior
makes GM's competition look, well, truck-like. (New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- May 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 30 --
ABOUT-GM-TRUCKS-3, 5-28 -- Even up front, styling differences
between the '98 GM C/K, left, and GM's Silverado are subtle. Prices
for the Silverado start around $16,000 for a plain two-wheel-drive
model. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- May 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 30 --
ABOUT-GM-TRUCKS-2, 5-28 -- After a 10-year run for the C/K series,
GM put all its might into making the Silverado line a success. It
came up with new engines, a new frame and new brakes. (New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- May 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 30 --
ABOUT-GM-TRUCKS-1, 5-28 -- The Pontiac-GMC Division is intent on
carving out an upscale niche distinct from Chevy trucks, but
differences from the Sierra, shown as a Sportside 4WD extended cab,
remain mostly cosmetic. The sheet metal is different from the
windshield forward. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- May 28, 1999 --
STARTUP-EXPERIENCE-BOS, 05-28 -- At Cignal Global Communications
are, from left, Andrew Perlman, president, Neal Isaacson, chief
financial officer, Christopher Rooney, chief executive officer, and
Mark Land, executive vice president and chief technology officer.
Many young entrepreneurs, like Perlman and Land, actively seek
experienced employees like Rooney to help them run their company.
(Barry Chin/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- May 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 30 --
NITEOUT-FLYER, 05-28 -- Hosi Simon in front of the sushi bar/lounge
Never on Manhattan's Lower East Side. Simon, 24, is the editor in
chief of Flyer, a palm-size monthly club listing guide that has
become the equivalent of Zagat's for the deejay set. (Miles
Ladin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- May 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 30 --
TULEH-FASHION, 05-28 -- Bryan Bradley, left, and Josh Patner,
partners in Tuleh, watch for well-dressed women at La Goulue.
Tuleh, a collection of luxurious and romantic clothes, including
1950s-style beaded dresses, lavishly printed cocktail pajamas and
sable stoles, was created by Patner and Bradley a year ago.
(Jeffery Salter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- May 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 30 --
BIZ-CITIES-TECH, 5-28 -- Prospect Street NYC Discovery was set up
with help from New York City to foster the technology industry but
has created few jobs. John F. Barry, its managing partner, is on
the boards of eight companies that have received the fund's help.
(Thomas Dallal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SAN FRANCISCO -- May 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 30 --
BIZ-TECH-HOTELS, 5-28 -- The W Hotel in San Francisco offers all
the high-technology comforts of home, like E-mail and fax machines,
but glitches can crop up. V. Calamur, right, arrives from the front
desk to provide technical support for the malfunctioning wireless
keyboard in Matt Richtel's room. (Darcy Padilla/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) TUSCALOOSA, Ala. -- May 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 30
-- INVEST-GM-DELPHI, 5-28 -- Delphi workers putting the finishing
touches on an integrated cockpit module assembly in Tuscaloosa.
Analysts wonder if Delphi Automotive, being spun off from GM, will
face a strike. (Delphi Automotive/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- May 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 30 --
BIZ-5-QUESTIONS, 5-28 -- Linda Gargiulo of the New York Attorney
General's office helped negotiate a toy settlement. Toys ``R'' and
two major toy makers agreed to pay $50 million in cash and
merchandise to settle one of the largest antitrust cases the toy
industry has ever faced. ``We are recovering damages for
consumers,'' she says. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) COSTA MESA, Calif. -- May 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY
30 -- BIZ-KINGSTON-TECHNOLOGIES-2, 5-28 -- The Kingston Technology
Co.'s employees received bonuses that ran as high as six figures
when the company was sold. Darin Farriola put his toward a start in
filmmaking. (Jill Connelly/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) FOUNTAIN VALLEY, Calif. -- May 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.,
MAY 30 -- BIZ-KINGSTON-TECHNOLOGIES-1, 5-28 -- The Kingston
Technology Co.'s employees received bonuses that ran as high as six
figures when the company was sold. For Jaime Chavez, the
maintenance and warehouse supervisor, the bonus led to the purchase
of a house and a foothold in the middle class. He sends his parents
in Mexico up to $1,000 a month from his paycheck. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
