<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 05/28/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) BEDFORD, N.Y. -- May 28, 1999 -- PRINCIPALS-VIOLENCE,
5-28 -- Dick Kraemer, the principal at Fox Lane High School, which
was subjected to a false bomb threat. Until a month ago, Kraemer
says, the trend in American high schools was to treat principals
like product managers, teachers like foremen and students like
high-end product. ``In some ways, we innocently believed that
schools could be purely focused on academics,'' he says. (Susan
Farley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) ROCKFORD, Ill. -- May 28, 1999 -- KOSOVO-VOICES, 5-28 --
Leonard Hahn, left, Brad Hyland and Duard Bennett are among those
discussing Kosovo in Rockford. ``I thought we'd go in, drop the
bombs and he'd quickly back down,'' says Hahn of Slobodan
Milosevic. (Steve Kagan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NYANYA, Nigeria -- May 28, 1999 -- NIGERIA-INAUG, 5-28
-- As John Agbo gives Thomas Idoko a trim at the U-Fine Barbers
Shop in Nyanya, the men share hopes for a Nigeria reborn under
civilian government. ``It is a day we have been looking forward
to,'' says Idoko, a 29-year-old teacher. ``I pray to God that I can
get a richer shop,'' says Agbo, 21. (Norimitsu Onishi/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- May 28, 1999 -- FAGAN-KIDNAP, 5-28
-- Stephen Fagan addressing the press with his lawyer, left,
following his appearance in Massachusetts Superior Court on Friday.
Fagan, the Massachusetts father who absconded with his two
daughters nearly 20 years ago and raised them in Palm Beach-style
prosperity until he was caught last year, clinched a plea deal that
lets him off with no jail time. (Mark Wilson/Boston Globe Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) SAN FRANCISCO -- May 28, 1999 -- FRISCO-BATHS, 5-28 --
Michael Petrelis, right, promoting a bathhouse petition in San
Francisco. Despite the fact this city is still in an official state
of health emergency after 26,000 reported cases of AIDS and 17,800
deaths, a movement is growing to allow the reopening of bathhouses
where men can meet and have sex in private cubicles. (Darcy
Padilla/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) GURPINAR, Turkey -- May 28, 1999 -- KOSOVO-REFUGEES,
5-28 -- Ismail Bolukbasi, a Kosovo refugee, resettled his family in
a concrete colony outside Istanbul. ``Life was beautiful in Kosovo
until 1989,'' says Bulukbasi, 45. Now he finds himself responsible
for an extended family of 23 people, ranging from small children to
his 67-year-old mother. They are jammed into a small apartment in a
dreary cement colony outside Istanbul. (Staton R. Winter/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) UNDATED -- May 28, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MAY 30 --
