<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SOCCER MUST LOWER ITS SIGHTS TO SUCCEED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On television from Barcelona, Spain, this week, we
saw how good soccer can be. On television from Columbus, Ohio,
today, we'll see how good American soccer can be.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is as wide as the Atlantic Ocean _ give or take
an English Channel.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's game in Barcelona, matching Manchester United and
Bayern Munich for the European Champions Cup, featured one of
sports' all-time miracle finishes, in an atmosphere thick with the
kind of historical context that only the international sport can
produce.
</P>
<P>
   Manchester United trailed 1-0 after 90 minutes, was not merely
on the ropes but flat on the canvas, before a pair of substitutes
scored during the three minutes of injury time, giving the English
club a 2-1 victory and its third championship of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Even the riot police on the sidelines might have cracked a
smile, if they'd been free to turn around and watch. A London
headline writer called it ``The greatest 2 minutes in the history
of sport,'' and even a John Elway fan might concede that argument.
</P>
<P>
   On its most technical level the game was a lesson to the
American wise guys who miss the dramatic possibilities in a 1-0
game. If Man United had trailed 4-3 and scored precisely the same
tying and winning goals at exactly the same desperate juncture, it
would have merely been dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, it was a case of utter frustration turning to
boundless joy _ or, as an English tabloid would describe it the
next day, ``football's equivalent of turning water into wine.'' A
French paper cited a still-higher power: ``God is English.''
</P>
<P>
   It was more than merely the biggest soccer match that will be
played in this non-World Cup year: It marked England's first
Champions League title since the nation's teams were banned for
five years following the 1985 hooligan riots in Brussels. It
stirred elder Man United fans' memories of the 1958 Munich air
crash that killed eight players. It evoked the best and worst of
the World War II emotions dredged up by any England-Germany
contest.
</P>
<P>
   Our isolationist American souls might find such emotions hard to
embrace, even ghastly. We've got the U.S. ``Miracle on Ice''
Olympic hockey victory over the hated Soviet Union, and otherwise
the notion that sports can represent something greater than
themselves is too much for us to grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why we'll never enjoy soccer quite the way the rest of
the world does.
</P>
<P>
   So how good can soccer get in this country, as we view it from
the crossroads at the end of the 1990s, the third consecutive
decade of which it was to be the sport?
</P>
<P>
   It can get as good as tonight's game between Major League
Soccer's Los Angeles Galaxy and Columbus Crew in the 22,500-seat
stadium that opened last weekend as the league's lone soccer-only
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two thousand might not sound like much, but if you've
attended a Galaxy home game, wracked by agoraphobia in a virtually
empty Rose Bowl, you know why the MLS needs more of the atmosphere
that cozy soccer-specific stadiums can provide.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the day is far off when 22,000 will turn out to be too
small, and it's more likely that day will never arrive. For
American soccer, smaller will be smarter, and the sooner it lowers
its sights the better.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the sport's popularity goes, the signals are decidedly
mixed these days.
</P>
<P>
   MLS is reporting a 12-percent rise in season-ticket sales but
only a half percent increase in overall attendance, leaving the
league in range of its third overall decline in as many
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   This was to be the league's breakout summer, too, without a
World Cup or Olympics to siphon off players or interest.
</P>
<P>
   But with the quality of play showing no sign of general
improvement ... with the MLS office stubbornly refusing to dump the
unpopular tiebreaking shootouts that have decided more than 40
percent of games... and with stadium-availability conflicts forcing
the league to stretch out a seven-month schedule over parts of all
four seasons ... even an optimist can find reason to fear for the
league's future.
</P>
<P>
   But on a positive note, officials of the Women's World Cup,
which will open three weeks from today in New Jersey's Giants
Stadium, are reporting that ticket sales continue to run ahead of
projections, with more than 42,000 purchased already for the July
10 final at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Can it be the sport of the '00s? (Wise guys, feel free to recast
that as ``the sport of the 0-0s.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great decade,'' Women's World Cup president Marla
Messing said this week, citing the 1996 birth of the MLS, the
success of the 1994 World Cup in the United States and the rising
profile of the men's and women's national teams. ``But we still
have a ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Barcelona, and the kind of excitement we saw this week, is an
unrealistic destination as U.S. soccer seeks its place in the
world. Columbus is the way to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
