<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRCRASH-COMPENSATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVISED RULES ADVANCE FOR AIR-CRASH COMPENSATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world's airlines moved a giant step closer on Friday to
providing better protection and compensation to victims of
international air accidents, with an agreement that would replace a
system in place since 1929 _ two years after Lindbergh made the
first solo nonstop trans-Atlantic flight.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting in Montreal, members of the International Civil Aviation
Organization developed new rules calling for unlimited liability
when a carrier is found at fault in case of death or injury to
passengers on international flights and allowing victims to claim
damages up to $135,000 regardless of whether the carrier is at
fault.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the new rules permit damage claims resulting from a
passenger death or injury to be filed in the country where the
victim lived and call upon the airlines to provide immediate
financial assistance to victims' relatives, deducted later from the
final settlement.
</P>
<P>
   When ratified, as expected, by at least 30 of the organization's
185 member states, the rules would probably be effective no later
than 2001, replacing the 70-year-old Warsaw Convention, which set a
limit of about $8,300 for death or injury.
</P>
<P>
   Long a matter of contention in the United States, the Warsaw
Convention has endured because airlines from poorer nations, their
governments, and airplane manufacturers from developed nations
blocked repeated attempts to change it.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1995, the Air Transport Association and the International
Air Transport Association teamed to develop a consensus among major
airlines to raise the limit.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese airlines were among the first to raise the limit, and
many other foreign carriers became concerned that by holding out
they might lose business.
</P>
<P>
   So not only did they lessen their resistance to the proposed
changes but by 1996 more than 50 had signed a statement of intent
to adopt them eventually. In 1997, 12 U.S. carriers voluntarily
waived the $75,000 liability limit, paving the way for Friday's
agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
