<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTING FIRM IS NAMED IN MEDICARE FRAUD LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)  (mk) 
 By KURT EICHENWALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KPMG Peat Marwick, the giant international accounting firm, was
accused in a federal whistle-blower lawsuit unsealed Friday of
aiding some hospitals in Florida in a scheme to defraud Medicare
through the use of bogus expense claims.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed under seal last year, was publicly disclosed by
court order after a discussion of its contentions on Thursday
during a criminal trial of hospital executives who the government
says participated in the scheme. Though such whistle-blower suits
are usually unsealed only after federal prosecutors decide whether
to join them, the relationship with the other case led to its
disclosure before the government had made such a decision.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is an outgrowth of the multiyear criminal investigation
of Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corp. Federal investigators have said in
court records that they believe Columbia engaged in a
corporate-wide scheme to defraud the government by misrepresenting
certain of its hospitals' expenses in order to receive
reimbursement from Medicare and other health programs.
</P>
<P>
   The whistle-blower suit unsealed Friday contends that KPMG Peat
Marwick played a prime role in that scheme, by assisting certain
Florida hospitals owned by Columbia in setting up secret reserves,
which were maintained in the event that government auditors
discovered the deception and demanded money back.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are the workings of a complex, little-understood part
of modern hospitals known as the federal cost-reporting system,
under which the government has paid billions of dollars to
hospitals and other health care providers over the years, including
hundreds of millions of dollars in payments each year to
Columbia/HCA alone.
</P>
<P>
   Through the system, some costs associated with patient care are
reimbursed by programs like Medicare at different rates. But the
government contends in the suit that KPMG Peat Marwick aided
Columbia in intentionally misrepresenting costs to increase the
reimbursement rate or receive payment for costs that were not
eligible for reimbursement.
</P>
<P>
   George Ledwith, a spokesman for KPMG Peat Marwick, said the
accounting firm ``believes it acted appropriately and in a
professional manner regarding that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the government's critical evidence in the cost-reporting
cases comes from secret, second sets of cost reports and work
sheets maintained at the hospitals that contained significantly
lower expenses than those in reports submitted to the government.
In this case, those records were reviewed, and in some cases
compiled, by KPMG.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 1993, auditors from KPMG found a discrepancy in
a cost report filed by a Columbia hospital, Kissimmee Memorial
Hospital in Kissimmee, Fla. The hospital had classified $81,000 of
interest expense as ``old capital'' _ meaning it involved a project
before 1990. In truth, as KPMG discovered, more than one-third of
the cost was for ``new capital,'' which is reimbursed at a lower
rate.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter obtained by The New York Times in 1997, KPMG did not
suggest correcting the number. The firm advised Kissimmee to
include the expenses in a reserve fund on the chance that Medicare
would select the hospital as one of the few that receive extensive
audits each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the reserve cost report,'' KPMG wrote of the expense, ``we
will reflect $33,054 as new capital costs as identified by the
hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kissimmee hospital is one of the institutions cited in the
lawsuit as having been aided in an illegal scheme by KPMG. The
other hospitals include Southwest Florida Regional Medical Center
and Gulf Coast Hospital, both in Fort Myers, and Fawcett Memorial
Hospital in Port Charlotte. The criminal trial of four Columbia
executives now taking place in Tampa, Fla., involves cost-reporting
procedures from Fawcett.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was brought by John Schilling, who had worked on
reimbursement issues for Columbia/HCA, both as an employee from
1993 through 1995 and later as a consultant to the company. The
case was brought under the False Claims Act, which allows
whistle-blowers to file suit on behalf of the government. If
federal prosecutors choose not to join a given suit, the
whistle-blower, who stands to receive a large part of any judgment
or settlement, can still take the suit to trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
