<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GUNTHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANK GUNTHER, 91, DEVISER OF TWO-WAY RADIOS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.J.)  (lb) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Frank A. Gunther, a radio pioneer who helped create shortwave,
two-way and FM systems, died on Monday at Bon Securos Hospital in
Venice, Fla. He was 91 and lived in New York and Nokomis, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Gunther often worked with the military, as well as with police
and fire departments, devising some of the first radio
communications devices. In 1932, for example, he built for the
police department in Bayonne, N.J., what is believed to be the
first two-way mobile police radio system.
</P>
<P>
   In 1928, Gunther also installed one of the first one-way radios
used on an aircraft, and in 1931 he took part in the first public
broadcast from an aircraft. A year later he installed the first
two-way radio system on an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Gunther was born on February 3, 1908, in New York. He attended
Wagner College and Columbia University. In 1925, he joined REL
Radio Engineering Laboratories, based in New York, and helped
construct and operate an experimental station that was one of the
first shortwave broadcasting systems.
</P>
<P>
   In 1935, Gunther, along with Edwin Armstrong, gave the first
public demonstration of frequency modulation, or FM transmission, a
signal far superior in clarity to AM or shortwave. The next year,
he designed and manufactured the early transmitter components for
FM radio, and from 1939 to 1942, he designed and built more than 25
FM stations nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   In 1939, Gunther demonstrated the first FM mobile transmitter to
the U.S. military, and during World War II, in which he served as a
major in the Army Air Force, he began designing the first Loran
navigational systems for the U.S. Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Gunther, who was also a commercial pilot, became president of
REL in 1960 and retired in 1982. Most recently, he worked as a
consultant with his son, Robert, president of Highpoint
Development, a developer of wireless communication towers, in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   He was a former president of the Radio Club of America, which
established the Frank A. Gunther Award in 1996. The award is given
annually to people who make major contributions to the advancement
of wireless military electronic communications systems. In 1992, he
was featured in a Public Broadcasting Service documentary, ``Empire
of the Air: The Men Who Made Radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Gunther's wife, Lillian Madden, died in 1997. In addition to his
son Robert of Shrewsbury, N.J., he is survived by a son Frank M.,
of New York; five grandchildren; six great-grandchildren, and five
step-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0411 </DOCNO>
