A5673 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-AIRTRAIN-NYT &LR;      05-28 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-AIRTRAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AN AIRPORT LINK WITH POTENTIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, May 29:
</P>
<P>
   Although the trip from midtown Manhattan to Kennedy Airport by
car or taxi is supposed to average 61 minutes, savvy travelers set
aside as much as 90 minutes to compensate for congestion and other
unforeseen difficulties. There is not much the New York City
Council can do about road delays. But it can at least give harried
travelers a fail-safe alternative by endorsing AirTrain, the Port
Authority's proposed rail link to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1960s, community opposition, multibillion-dollar price
tags and other forces have derailed every effort to build a system
that would allow travelers to board a train in Manhattan and ride
directly to Kennedy or La Guardia _ a ``one-seat'' ride like those
in London, Paris and other major cities. Set against that standard,
AirTrain is a rather modest proposal. It would involve taking two
trains, thus creating a two-seat, 45-minute ride. Travelers would
take the Long Island Rail Road or one of several subway lines to
Jamaica, Queens, where they would switch to AirTrain for the ride
to Kennedy's terminals.
</P>
<P>
   In the near term, AirTrain would offer a reliable alternative to
the uncertainties of negotiating the Van Wyck Expressway and other
congested highways. But AirTrain's most attractive feature is its
convertibility. The 3.1-mile light-rail line between Jamaica and
Kennedy could easily become the final leg of a one-seat rail link
that could be up and running by 2010, provided the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority agrees to build the segment from Manhattan
to Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   By August, the MTA will choose between a Long Island Rail Road
line or a subway line to connect Manhattan to the AirTrain in
Jamaica. Under an agreement signed by Gov. George Pataki, Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, the Port Authority and the MTA last July,
AirTrain's light-rail line must be strong enough to support
whatever heavy-rail option the MTA selects. It must also have
compatible railroad gauges, electrical current and platforms. The
Council's hearings next Tuesday should be an ideal forum for
reviewing these issues.
</P>
<P>
   As the City Council reviews AirTrain, it should avoid being
sideswiped by special interests. For example, much of the funding
for AirTrain would come from passenger facility charges levied at
the airports. But the Air Transport Association, which represents
major airlines, generally opposes the use of revenue from the
passenger facility charge for train-to-the-plane projects and other
off-airport uses. The association's real fear is that the use of
such revenues in New York could set a precedent for other cities.
</P>
<P>
   Barring the discovery of a fatal flaw in the project or the
emergence of a better one, AirTrain should proceed. The City
Council's larger mission should be to ensure that AirTrain becomes
a down payment on the one-seat ride the New York region deserves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
