<HEADER>
A5674 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NURSING-HOMES-NY     05-28 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NURSING-HOMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TOWARD NURSING HOME REFORM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, May 29:
</P>
<P>
   In California, a struggle is playing out over nursing home
reform. Embarrassed by hearings in Congress about needless deaths
in California nursing homes, and spurred by Kevin Shelley, the new
Democratic majority leader of the state Assembly, who started
looking at nursing homes when his mother had a stroke, the
legislature is now wrestling with the most comprehensive attempt to
improve care in a decade and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Other states should pay attention. The debate is about the most
basic problems in the field, and the forces in play in California
are the ones that shape the issue in the nation at large. The
state's population is aging. Nursing homes are big business. They
are also expensive, and about two-thirds of the residents in them,
their own assets exhausted, are paid for by tax dollars through
Medicaid. It is the aides at the bottom of the pay scale, averaging
only $7 an hour, who bathe, change, feed and attend to those
residents. The care given depends on the number of those aides,
their attitude and training.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993 alone, according to an activist lawyer, more than 3,000
people died as a result of unacceptable care in California nursing
homes. A subsequent federal study of a sampling of those cases
found that in half, the charges might have been true. When the
Senate Special Committee on Aging aired the study in hearings this
spring, it stirred anger in California, and efforts at reform. The
state Legislature, virtually all of whose members get campaign
contributions from the nursing home industry, soon faced a
coalition of senior citizens' organizations led by the American
Association of Retired People, with 2.8 million members in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Shelley's bill would appropriate an additional $35 million in
state general funds for nursing homes, and direct that the money be
spent on wages, an increase of perhaps 15 percent for the nurses'
aides. It would also mandate additional training for them. It would
allow the state to send in a professional manager to shape up homes
that seem to threaten the welfare of their residents _ something
Michigan has begun to do. It would raise civil fines for causing
the death of a resident from a maximum of $25,000 to $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   A nursing home trade group, the California Association of Health
Facilities, opposes some of these provisions as violating its
members' rights to operate their own businesses. But with political
pressure building, and new criminal grand jury indictments this
week against a nursing home chain for severely neglecting its
residents in San Jose and Los Gatos, reform in California seems to
have an even chance of passage this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
