<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABY-SELLING-880&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO WOMEN IN BABY-SELLING CASE WERE KNOWN BY AUTHORITIES FOR
DECADE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Fla.)   (See also: MEXICO-BABY-SELLING)  
(rk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ State regulators knew as early as a decade
ago that two Long Island women were placing foreign-born children
with adoptive parents in New York, even though they lacked the
permits to do so.
</P>
<P>
   But the women appear to have hit upon an easy way of avoiding
trouble, according to government officials and court filings: Over
and over again, they simply went out of business, then reopened
under a new name.
</P>
<P>
   But the two women, who were charged on Thursday with smuggling
at least 17 Mexican infants into the United States with promises of
easy and legal adoptions, and selling them to unwitting adoptive
parents for up to $22,000, also may have benefited from lax
enforcement, officials suggested Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1995, state regulators who had discovered that the women
were back in business again referred their findings to the attorney
general's office for civil prosecution. But they never heard back.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, after new complaints against the women,
Arlene Lieberman and Arlene Reingold, appeared in The New York
Post, state Attorney General Dennis Vacco's office finally began an
investigation, according to a spokesman for Eliot Spitzer, who
succeeded Vacco in January.
</P>
<P>
   And last fall, after Mexican authorities arrested a woman they
said was involved in a baby-trafficking ring along the Arizona
border with the Mexican state of Sonora, the Immigration and
Naturalization Service began its own inquiry into the activities of
a prominent border lawyer who was believed to be arranging the
children's entry into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the lawyer, Mario Manuel Reyes Burgueno, and the
two Suffolk County women were arrested and charged with conspiring
to violate various immigration laws and to commit mail and wire
fraud. They face maximum prison sentences of up to 10 years for
each child smuggled into the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Spitzer's office filed a civil lawsuit seeking to
permanently bar the women, their company and their husbands, who
escorted many of the babies from the border to New York, from the
adoption business.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lieberman and Ms. Reingold _ known to friends, clients and
law enforcement agents alike as ``the Arlenes'' _ first came to the
attention of the New York state Department of Social Services
sometime in 1989, according to an official at the department, since
renamed the Office of Children and Family Services.
</P>
<P>
   According to a federal affidavit released on Thursday, the women
set up a nonprofit company, Stork International, ostensibly only to
provide information and counseling to would-be adoptive parents.
But the state official said reports began trickling in that Stork
International was doing much more _ placing children in exchange
for cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met with these people, and informed them that they could
not place out children and charge fees without a license,'' the
state social services department official said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, his office had received complaints about a
lawyer in Miami to whom the women had referred a number of couples,
who promised to obtain children for them from Central and South
America. The New York regulators contacted Florida officials, who
eventually suspended the lawyer's license.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1992, according to the court filings, Ms.
Lieberman and Ms. Reingold resigned from Stork and set up a new
company, Adoption Choice Inc. They were apparently a step ahead of
the state regulators. In 1993, the Department of Social Services
ordered Stork International to stop placing children, and referred
the matter to the Suffolk County district attorney's office. The
company agreed to a settlement, and later that year, the official
said, Stork was dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the official said, the Department of Social
Services learned about Adoption Choice. ``They came to us with an
application for an adoption license,'' the official said. ``While
we're looking at their application, we get information that they're
placing children.'' Agency workers found advertisements to that
effect in phone books and pennysavers.
</P>
<P>
   Another employee called Adoption Choice posing as a parent. In
early 1995, the official said, the department denied the company's
application. And on May 24, 1995, the department sent a letter to
the attorney general's office requesting civil enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I know,'' the official said Friday, ``they didn't
file any papers. We never heard anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The official said the attorney general's office may simply have
decided that enforcement action was unnecessary. ``What happened
around then was that Adoption Choice just went away,'' he said.
``Our primary concern as a state supervisory agency was to get them
to stop. They did.'' The attorney general's office may have made
the same calculation, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Spitzer, Paul W. Larrabee, said Friday he was
unable to determine why the office had not acted in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   But Aaron Britvan, chairman of the adoption committee of the New
York state Bar Association, said state officials have generally
shown little interest in tough enforcement of adoption laws, or in
strengthening the laws themselves. ``They do not act,'' he said.
``They react. Something has to happen for them to become active.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Britvan, who is representing the adoptive parents of six of the
17 smuggled Mexican children, noted that it was not until March,
when Nassau police charged a Hungarian mother and an associate with
trying to sell her baby for $60,000, that ranking state legislators
in both houses proposed bills that would make the first such an
offense a felony instead of a misdemeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Few couples who are involved in illegal adoption schemes come
forward, often out of fear of prosecution or fear that they would
lose their children. And Friday, several of the parents who adopted
children with the help of Ms. Reingold and Ms. Lieberman declined
to discuss their experience.
</P>
<P>
   But Jacqueline Falick, a Brooklyn woman who last year complained
to the attorney general's office about her experience with Ms.
Reingold and Ms. Lieberman, agreed to an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Falick said she and her husband, Irwin, paid about $11,000
to the Long Island women, a Miami lawyer and others to obtain a
baby for adoption, but never received a child. ``I believed them,''
said Mrs. Falick, whose experience with the two women was the
subject of several articles last year in the New York Post. ``It's
very hard when you meet these two individuals to think you can't
believe them. It's just not obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you want something so bad,'' she said, ``you don't want
to see the bad angles, and you keep hoping it's going to turn good.
And these people kept me hoping and hanging on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
