<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Man Accused of Threatening to Kill Mbeki
</P>
<P>
   A 50-year-old man was arrested and accused of threatening to
kill Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, who is expected to take over
from President Nelson Mandela when he retires after next week's
elections. A police spokesman said the arrested man had made five
telephone calls in a week to Mbeki's home and to a Cape Town office
of the governing African National Party. The spokesman said he
could not give any more details without ``jeopardizing'' the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Botha Appeals Sentence
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for former President P.W. Botha called his sentence for
refusing to testify before the Truth and Reconciliation Commission
``shockingly inappropriate'' as they began his appeal before the
Cape Town High Court. Botha, 83, was convicted of contempt last
year and sentenced to pay about $1,600 or spend a year in jail.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa: Cricketer Convicted of Rape
</P>
<P>
   Makhaya Ntini, the first black African player on the national
cricket squad, was sentenced to six years for rape. Spectators in
the courtroom booed as the sentence was translated into Xhosa and
followed Ntini out singing and dancing when he was freed pending
appeal. His conviction is a setback for cricket, which is trying to
get black Africans, who comprise 77 percent of the population, to
play the game.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Fugitive Aide Found Dead
</P>
<P>
   A former attorney general of Quintana Roo state, Miguel
Peyrefitte Cupido, was found dead in Morelos, south of Mexico City,
after an anonymous phone call to his wife, according to a Morelos
government spokeswoman. There were no signs of foul play, she said.
Peyrefitte served under Gov. Mario Villanueva Madrid, who has been
a fugitive since his term ended in April and federal authorities
issued a warrant for his arrest on drug and racketeering charges.
Peyrefitte was also wanted on money laundering and trafficking
charges.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Japan: A Scolding for Top Politician
</P>
<P>
   Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu Nonaka, one of Japan's most
powerful politicians, was scolded at a Cabinet meeting after he
urged the Cabinet's only woman to have children. The Kyodo News
Service said that in a meeting discussing how to address Japan's
falling birthrate, Nonaka asked Post and Telecommunications
Minister Seiko Noda, who is single, why she did not set an example
for the country. Nonaka's duties include responsibility for Japan's
Office for Gender Equality.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Ireland: IRA Victim's Body Found
</P>
<P>
   Acting on information from the IRA, the police found the body of
a man who was one of nine IRA members executed as traitors in the
1970s and 1980s by the outlawed guerrilla group. The disclosure was
widely seen as an attempt by the IRA to improve its image and that
of its political wing, Sinn Fein, in the stalled Northern Ireland
peace effort. A protest group called Families of the Disappeared
has campaigned for the recovery of the bodies for the past five
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
