<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 22:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-BEES-NYT &LR;      05-28 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AT THE HIVE'S ENTRANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By VERLYN KLINKENBORG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On April 28, the postmaster called. A package for me had come
from Claxton, Ga. _ 4 pounds of bees in a wooden crate.
</P>
<P>
   Late that afternoon, at home, I removed from the crate a small
cage just large enough to hold the queen bee and a few attendants.
I set the queen-cage in a wooden box called a deep super, the base
of a new hive. Then I shook the rest of the bees into the hive and
drove them down into the super with a few puffs of smoke. A wooden
feeder went on top, filled with sugar-water, and then the cover.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the shadbush has bloomed and so have the elderberry
and the crab apple. The leaves on the trees have nearly all
emerged, except for the honey locust, which is always late. I'm
late too, still digging garden beds in a patch of soil near the new
hive, which sits beside the hive I started last year.
</P>
<P>
   Several times a day I take a seat nearby and watch the bees. To
the old hive, workers come steadily, profusely, their legs clubbed
with pollen. That hive contains comb the bees built last summer,
ready now to be filled with eggs, pollen, nectar and honey.
</P>
<P>
   But when the new bees settled into their hive in late April, all
they found was 10 framed sheets of plastic, each embossed with a
honeycomb pattern. The workers had to release their foreign queen
from her cage by eating through a candy plug blocking the entrance,
a delay that would give them time to adopt her. Some workers began
building honeycomb for a bee nursery and larder. Others made
foraging flights and repeated trips through the hive to the feeder
above them.
</P>
<P>
   One warm afternoon recently, I opened the new hive. A little
smoke, and the bees scurried down into the frames. The queen-cage
was empty. From the middle of the hive I lifted a frame covered
with fresh comb, and in the uncapped cells saw eggs and coiled
larvae. The queen was laying steadily.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the brood cells, where pupae awaited their final
transformation into workers, had been capped, turning the wax a
soft, rich yellow. In the corners, comb was filled with honey,
capped in pure white. There were four such frames, and wax cells
were already being raised across a fifth.
</P>
<P>
   The abruptness of spring, its riotous biological opportunism, is
always surprising. One day there is bare earth, and the next day
the asparagus is 4 feet tall. But there is no surprise quite like
that of new comb, new brood, in a new hive. Every form replicates
itself in this season _ every leaf coming true to ancient pattern _
but that replication is nowhere as pure as it is in a hive. The
comb is perfect geometry, a field of hexagons raised with
unimaginable cunning, and the hive is perfect prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The scent of new beeswax drifts downwind to where I sit. Bees
plummet onto the entrance board, overweighted with pollen,
overburdened with spring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
