A5684 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT &LR;      05-28 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS TUNE UP IN A KNICKS-FREE ZONE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ The standing ovation began as soon as Reggie
Miller emerged from the tunnel, swaying his arms from side to side
like wheat blowing in a Midwest field. It grew as the team members
sprawled on the floor and stretched their ankles toward their
opposite knees.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd at Market Square Arena roared during layup drills.
They sang along with a rap number that rhymed the various
basketball skills of Miller, Rik Smits, Mark Jackson and Pacer
after Pacer down the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The coach had his own number, of course. It had a country beat,
lyrics about a home-grown hero and an oft-repeated chorus that
everyone seemed to know: ``Larry Bird,'' shouted more than 12,316
people as they clapped their hands.
</P>
<P>
   The 5 p.m. scrimmage hadn't even started. But this is what they
call happy hour here in the heart of basketball country. For the
record, the Gold squad of backups beat the Blue squad of starters
by the score of 116-111. The exhibition was part rust remover, part
fan appreciation, as the Pacers got ready to play the Knicks in the
Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in situations where we had eight or nine days off
and it's hard to get geared back up for the game,'' Bird said. ``We
wanted to make it as real as possible so the guys would be moving
out there. Believe me, it's hard to restart after you've been off a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird was worried that his team might be flat after registering
seven straight playoff victories over Milwaukee and Philadelphia,
followed by a week off. The coach had seen it happen to the Boston
Celtics in the 1981 playoffs. They eliminated Chicago in the
conference semifinals and had to wait 11 days for the finals. They
lost their first game against the Philadelphia 76ers and ended up
going seven games before finally winning the series.
</P>
<P>
   So the mascot, the Pacer dance team and two referees from the
Continental Basketball Association were brought in to give both
players and fans a lift.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear from the tip-off that the Pacers, a veteran team,
have adopted their coach's legendary competitiveness. Bird has
matched up his first and second teams before. During the
pre-season, the starters needed a last-second basket from Smits to
defeat the second unit.
</P>
<P>
   Before the scrimmage Friday, Jalen Rose, the Pacers' voluble
bench scorer, mixed caution with his trash talk, saying, ``I don't
think anyone wants to see us beat on each other.''
</P>
<P>
   But they did, to the delight of Bob and Sarah Johnson and their
boys, who were seeing the Pacers up close for the first time and in
style. The Johnsons arrived at Market Square Arena when the doors
opened at 3:30 p.m. to secure courtside seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole place is a Knicks-free zone,'' said Bob Johnson,
who wore a jersey with Smits' number on it. On the weekend of the
Indianapolis 500, there was neither a blue and orange jersey nor a
New York accent to be found in the arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't even worried about them,'' 14-year-old Tim Johnson
said. ``They are lucky to have even gotten this far.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers and Knicks will tip off here Sunday at 5:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   After the slow-motion first half that Bird had feared, the Gold
and Blue squads mixed it up in the second half. With the score
tied, 89-89, for the final period, the Pacers' second team, behind
point guard Travis Best, opened up a lead. Best made six straight
baskets in the period and finished with 23 points and 14 assists.
That was good news for the Pacers, because Best has struggled with
foul trouble and has averaged only 3.1 points a game in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Best may have outplayed Jackson (eight points and 11 assists),
but it was Jackson, a New York-born point guard and former Knick,
who scored with the crowd by talking the hardwood game like a true
Hoosier. When the final buzzer sounded and another standing ovation
commenced, Jackson took a microphone and quieted the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to see free, for no money, the two best teams in
basketball play here tonight,'' he said. ``We've been going all
around the country. We had tour stops in Milwaukee and
Philadelphia. Those crowds got crazy. It would bother another team,
but not us. It would really help if you step it up a notch, because
that's what we plan on doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he made a prediction that until now he has avoided uttering
to members of the news media. Jackson reminded the crowd that next
year, the Pacers will move to a new home, Conseco Fieldhouse. ``And
we're going to open it up with a championship banner,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the perfect toast to end the happiest of hours in
Indiana. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
