<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-DOCTOR-SUICIDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR WHO FACED QUESTIONING IN DEATH HANGS HERSELF 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (lb) 
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ A Jersey City podiatrist apparently hanged
herself on Thursday in her Pennsylvania jail cell minutes before
she was to be returned to New Jersey to face questioning about her
sister-in-law, whose decomposing body was found this month stuffed
in a picnic cooler.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Elaine Witterschein, 48, was found hanging from shredded and
knotted bed linens in her 9-by-9-foot, single-person cell in the
Luzerne County Prison in Wilkes-Barre, Pa., at about 10:35 a.m.
Thursday. Her death was first reported Friday in The Star-Ledger of
Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Witterschein was arrested on May 21 after leaving a
substance-abuse clinic in Wilkes-Barre, where she had been
sentenced as part of a conviction on May 12 for passing bad checks
in Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   On May 17, Dr. Witterschein's roommate, Stanley Eldridge,
dragged a large cooler with wheels on one end out of the storage
area next to the basement apartment they shared in a four-story
brownstone in downtown Jersey City.
</P>
<P>
   When a friend of his opened the cooler and found the body, they
called the police. Inside the cooler was a black plastic garment
bag and inside the bag was the 100-pound body of the podiatrist's
sister-in-law, Mary Ann Witterschein, fully clothed with her hands
handcuffed behind her.
</P>
<P>
   Terrence Hull, the first assistant Hudson County prosecutor,
said the woman had died of a blow to the head and asphyxiation. He
said a pathologist estimated that she had been dead for six months.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Witterschein's death was ruled a suicide by the Luzerne
County coroner, according to Detective Capt. Michael Dessoye, an
investigator with the district attorney's office there. He said
that Dr. Witterschein had not been deemed a suicide threat.
</P>
<P>
   She had last been seen by jail officials at 10 a.m. Thursday,
when they stopped by her cell to tell her to get dressed for her
scheduled extradition hearing later in the day in the County Court
of Common Pleas.
</P>
<P>
   A note was found in the cell, but Dessoye would not disclose its
contents. However, Hull, whose office is investigating the apparent
murder of Dr. Witterschein's sister-in-law, said that it shed no
light on the murder case.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no admission in the note, which did not state
anything about the homicide,'' Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ann Witterschein, the sister-in-law, was the widow of
Edward Witterschein, a retired Jersey City policeman who died last
year. Hull said that investigators were looking into the
possibility that someone during the last few months had been
fraudulently cashing the monthly checks that she had been receiving
as part of her husband's pension benefits.
</P>
<P>
   According to Jersey City investigators, both Edward and Mary Ann
Witterschein had alcohol-abuse problems over the years, and about
five years ago state child-welfare agencies removed their two
children from the home because of those problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 2256EDT &QL; 
