u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT     05-28 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS HOPE `LOCKBOX' IS KEY TO POLITICAL GAINS  
 WHOM TO BLAME FOR CHINESE ESPIONAGE?  
 MAKING THE CASE FOR TERM LIMITS  
 SOUTHERN CHILDREN STILL HURT BY POVERTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Fla., La., S.C., Pa.)  (mk) 
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House members are patting themselves on the back,
boasting that they have taken a giant step toward protecting Social
Security. A Republican bill that keeps the retirement trust fund in
a so-called lockbox, tucked away from spendthrift lawmakers, sailed
through on a 416-12 vote.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact is, lawmakers routinely violate their own limits on
spending and their own pledges to leave the Social Security surplus
alone. All they have to do is declare an emergency and then nothing
is off limits. That's just what happened with the $15 billion
package lawmakers recently approved to pay for the war in Kosovo
and a host of pet projects. Much of that package was paid for by
dipping into the Social Security reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that little inconsistency didn't stop lawmakers from
proclaiming that they had saved Social Security via the ``lockbox''
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this effort, we are working to ensure that not one dime
of America's Social Security tax dollars are spent on big-spending
programs,'' said Rep, John Linder, R-Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Cox Wait, president of the non-partisan Committee for a
Responsible Federal Budget, applauded Congress for vowing to
safeguard the Social Security surplus, but she was a bit skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be more form than substance,'' she said, noting that
lawmakers didn't have to pass any new bill to safeguard the Social
Security reserves. They could just curtail their spending. By doing
so, they would help to pay down the federal debt, which Wait
described as the most fiscally responsible thing lawmakers could
do.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA CLIPPERS
</P>
<P>
   The China spying documented in the new congressional report
dated to the Carter era, but Republicans seem intent on heaping
most of the blame on the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush, the Texas governor and presidential hopeful
whose father occupied the White House as vice president or
president for 12 of the 20 odd years of spying, was tough on
President Clinton. Congressional Republicans piled on as well,
saying the White House was slow to respond when it learned of the
pilfering of nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Cliff Stearns, R-Fla., gathered 75 signatures on a letter
calling for the resignation of National Security Adviser Sandy
Berger, saying he misled Congress about the security lapse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our most sensitive nuclear and military technology has been
stolen by the communist Chinese and no one in this administration
is being held responsible,'' complained Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, sought to emphasize how the spying covered
``the past several administrations,'' as Sen. John Breaux, D-La.,
put it. Even some Republicans shared that view.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's enough blame to go around on a bipartisan fashion,''
said Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   LIMITED SUCCESS?
</P>
<P>
   Promising a kinder, gentler approach to term limits, a group of
10 House members who have vowed not to make a career in Congress
are banding together to highlight the advantages of term
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the new Citizen Legislator Caucus hopes to
show how term-limited members are more responsible with tax dollars
than veteran lawmakers interested in extending their careers. The
group also hopes to counter U.S. Term Limits, a private
organization that has harshly criticized lawmakers for their
half-hearted support of limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are here to help members, not to bash members who don't
limit their own terms,'' said Rep. Jim DeMint, R-S.C., a freshman
who intends to leave the House after three terms and serves as
chairman of the caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, he has helped to organize a foundation that will
raise money to promote the idea of term limits.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN SHAME
</P>
<P>
   Despite reduced infant mortality and improved education,
Southern children still lag the nation in several key measures,
according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the Children's Defense Fund found that poverty
remains a big hurdle for children in the South, and it called on
Congress and the president to spend more money on the health and
education of America's youth.
</P>
<P>
   Southern states continue to have large concentrations of poor
children. The report included a list that ranked states by
percentage of children in poverty, from lowest to highest.
Louisiana came in 49th, Mississippi 48th, Arkansas 46th, Alabama
44th, South Carolina 39th and Florida 37th. North Carolina rated
the best of the South at 30th.
</P>
<P>
   The worst state was New Mexico, while the state with the lowest
percentage of children in poverty was New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse and Sean Loughlin work in the Washington Bureau of
the New York Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
