<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5792 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COMMUTER-TAX-480&AMP;A     05-28 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COMMUTER-TAX-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO COMMUTERS SUE OVER STATE'S REPEAL OF TAX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Conn.)  (lb) 
 By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two men claiming that changes in New York City's
commuter tax illegally discriminate against residents of other
states filed a lawsuit Friday to eliminate the tax.
</P>
<P>
   The men, both out-of-state commuters, claim that the new law,
which taxes commuters from New Jersey and Connecticut but not those
from suburbs in New York, is unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they know it is unconstitutional,'' said Richard Swanson,
one of the men filing the lawsuit. ``The one thing they can't do is
repeal it for New York state residents and leave it in place for
non-New York state residents.''
</P>
<P>
   Swanson, a partner in a Manhattan law firm, Thelan Reid &AMP;
Priest, lives in New Jersey. The other plaintiff, Thomas Igoe Jr.,
is also a partner in the firm and lives in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The two men filed suit after Gov. George Pataki signed a law on
Thursday that repeals the city's commuter tax for suburban
commuters within the state. The tax, which has been in place for a
generation, is 0.45 percent of earned income for most people. Taxes
paid by all commuters generate as much as $360 million for the city
each year.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey and Gov. John Rowland of
Connecticut have sent a joint letter to Pataki urging him to veto
the selective repeal and instead repeal the taxes for all
commuters. Whitman recently said that New Jersey would sue to stop
the revised tax, and has directed the attorney general to do so.
</P>
<P>
   City political leaders have condemned the repeal as an attempt
to curry favor with suburban voters, and have said it will be a
severe blow to the city. But supporters of the measure have held it
to be a valid attempt to ease the tax burden on commuters,
particularly at a time when the city will have a substantial budget
surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Swanson said Friday that he would prefer that New York keep the
tax for all commuters.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I got sick, the city would send an ambulance; if I had a
fire, the city would send a fire truck,'' he said. ``I have no
problem paying for my fair share of New York services.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, which was filed in state Supreme Court in
Manhattan, asks the court to declare the new law unconstitutional.
The plaintiffs are not seeking money. They are asking for costs and
legal fees incurred by their law firm, but Swanson said the firm
would argue the case free if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Swanson said that the Supreme Court has repeatedly found that
states cannot levy discriminatory taxes against residents of other
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Constitution is intended to prohibit one state from
discriminating against another in taxes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has often taken a dim view of states' attempts
to levy taxes that they do not apply to their own residents. In
1975, the court ruled that New Hampshire could not subject
out-of-state residents to a commuter tax when New Hampshire
residents paid no income tax.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a narrow decision in 1997, the court struck down a
40-year-old Maine property-tax law that granted tax-exempt status
to charities but denied it to those ``operated principally for the
benefit of persons who are not residents of Maine.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year the court ruled that New York state unconstitutionally
discriminated against out-of-state taxpayers by denying them the
right to deduct alimony payments from their New York income tax _ a
deduction available to New York state residents.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the majority in the case, Lunding vs. New York Tax
Appeals Tribunal, Justice Sandra Day O'Connor said that the court's
decisions had established a rule of ``substantial equality of
treatment'' for residents and nonresidents. She said the states
must provide ``substantial justification'' for any differences in
treatment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 2308EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
