<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS FALL TO DIAMONDBACKS; AGBAYANI'S POWER DOESN'T MAKE UP FOR HIS
DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Benny Agbayani belted a homer off Omar Daal for the
only run the New York Mets managed to score against the Arizona
Diamondbacks Friday night. Agbayani failed to corral a mammoth fly
ball to center field, which helped the Diamondbacks score their
only two runs against the Mets. Is there any way Agbayani can tote
his trusty bat to center field for luck?
</P>
<P>
   Because Andy Fox went deep off Agbayani's glove and because
Agbayani was the only Met to go deep or to do much of anything off
Daal, the Diamondbacks edged New York, 2-1, at Shea Stadium. The
Diamondbacks continued to prove that they are a real threat for at
least a wild-card berth, while the Mets continued to play sometimes
inspiring and sometimes exasperating baseball.
</P>
<P>
   With the crowd chanting, ``Ben-ny, Ben-ny,'' and runners on
first and second and one out in the ninth inning, Agbayani had an
opportunity to leave even more of an imprint on the game. Agbayani
grounded to third baseman Matt Williams, who got the force play at
second. Jay Bell's throw skidded past first, but Mike Piazza
tripped halfway down the line as he tried to score and had to
retreat to third.
</P>
<P>
   After Gregg Olson walked Matt Franco to load the bases, he fell
behind 3-0 on Luis Lopez. But Olson rebounded to pump three
straight strikes by Lopez to secure the dramatic victory for
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Daal dominated the Mets with his off-speed pitches before
leaving the game after seven innings with tightness in his left
shoulder. Daal gave up Agbayani's homer in the seventh, but he
stifled the Mets on no hits in four at-bats with runners in scoring
position. Rick Reed pitched a commendable game in allowing two
earned runs in seven innings, but he lost and still has only one
victory since May 4.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Agbayani's best position might be designated hitter,
manager Bobby Valentine has to squeeze him into the lineup because
of his hot bat. Basically, Valentine puts Agbayani in the outfield
and hopes a fly ball is not hit to him at a critical juncture.
Friday night, one was, and now the 2-year-old Diamondbacks (28-21)
actually have a better record than the Mets (27-21).
</P>
<P>
   Fox's booming fly ball in the second inning kept drifting, and
Agbayani, who was playing center field, immediately seemed to be in
trouble. He started late on the ball, then turned to his left and
finally lunged for the ball near the warning track. But the ball
nicked off his glove for a triple that scored the only two runs
Arizona would need.
</P>
<P>
   On the mound, Reed stared at the dirt. The pitcher knew he had a
problem once Fox hammered a pitch 400 feet, but he also knew that
he had helped create the mess by walking Steve Finley and by
allowing a two-out single to Kelly Stinnett, who entered the game
with a .141 average on 11 hits in 78 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Reed might have sneaked into the dugout unscathed if
Brian McRae was in center field. While Fox drilled the ball to the
track, it was in the air long enough for a competent center fielder
to catch it.
</P>
<P>
   A pivotal confrontation occurred in the sixth inning, but it
might as well have been the ninth. It was Daal against Piazza with
the potential tying runs on first and second base. Piazza did not
turn a disappointing night into an exciting evening as his
one-handed swing produced a fly ball to left. Alfonzo then flied
out as Daal kept the 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had runners in scoring position against Daal in the
first and second innings, and they failed to score both times.
Agbayani finally solved Daal in the seventh, but only after he had
helped Arizona already. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
