<SLUG> BC-BBC-LONGBEACH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG BEACH ST. BEATS MISSISSIPPI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Something special, something clutch,
that's what it'll take to win, Long Beach State coach Dave Snow was
saying just before the start of the NCAA baseball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about knowing the script.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Dirtbags got a series of clutch performances in
their regional opener at Texas A&AMP;M against Mississippi and won in
10 innings, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Pinch hitter Scott Redfox singled home the winning run with one
out in the bottom of the 10th, sending the Dirtbags into the
winner's bracket of the four-team, double-elimination tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Today at noon they'll meet powerhouse Texas A&AMP;M, a 6-0
first-round winner Friday night over Monmouth University.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a little life, we good a little confidence,'' said
Snow, who's been slow all season to endorse this Dirtbag club, just
the other day going as far to say, ``We haven't done anything to
suggest we can win a regional.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to need that confidence, too,'' Snow added,
alluding to the matchup with the host Aggies (47-14), the
top-seeded team here and one of the eight nationally seeded clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Ole Miss (33-28), which will take on Monmouth (26-23) this
morning in an elimination game, out-hit the Dirtbags, 12-8. But the
Rebels stranded a dozen base runners, nine of them in scoring
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the most frustrating thing,'' said Ole Miss coach Pat
Harrison, ``not getting key hits. We didn't get the hits when we
needed them, they did.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Gallo, Darren Merrill and Jeremy Ward combined to restrict
Ole Miss to just two hits in 16 at-bats with runners on second or
third base.
</P>
<P>
   The Dirtbags (34-23) were held in check by Ole Miss right-hander
Jeff McAvoy, who went the distance, and actually pitched better
following a one-hour rain delay in the middle of the sixth inning,
retiring 10 batters in a row at one point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped settle me down,'' McAvoy explained. ``I was rushing
things the first five innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Greg Dobbs got to McAvoy quickly, slamming his
eighth home run with two outs in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Ole Miss right fielder Michael Rosamond hit a solo homer in the
second off of Gallo, just the fifth home run he's given up this
season but the fourth in his last four games.
</P>
<P>
   Rosamond's homer snapped a string of 18 scoreless innings by the
Rebels, who are appearing in only their second regional in 22
years. The Rebels followed the homer with a double by catcher Carl
Lafferty and successive singles by Jude Voltz and Justin Huisman to
take a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers tied the score in the third on a leadoff double by
second baseman Curt Lee, who was starting for only the second time
in 16 games, a sacrifice bunt by A.J. LaBarbera, who started at
shortstop in place of injured Bobby Crosby, and an infield out by
Terrmel Sledge.
</P>
<P>
   They went ahead, 3-2, in the fifth on a two-out double by
Sledge, then a triple down the right field line by Mike Hota.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo pitched the first six innings, but didn't return following
the lengthy rain delay.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd thrown 97 pitches at that point,'' Snow explained, ``and
he was having trouble with a blister, and it got worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rebels tied the score, 3-3, in the seventh against Merrill
when LaBarbera let Brad Henderson's one-out grounder roll through
his legs for an error, enabling Robert Shelton to score from third.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of rolled the dice there,'' said Snow, who played his
infield in. ``I had the feeling this game wasn't going to be
decided with a big inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Snow got what he wanted, a ground ball, just not the result he
was looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``A.J. did OK,'' Snow said of his backup shortstop. ``He made
the plays ... when he was playing back.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 10th, Abel Orozco led off with a single, Lee sacrificed
and Redfox pinch hit for LaBarbera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the dugout, waiting for a shot to get in there,''
said Redfox. ``(McAvoy) was pitching just about everybody away, so
that was what I was looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Redfox got it, driving a line single to right-center, easily
scoring pinch runner Michael Luera with the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   DIRTBAGS NOTES: Right-hander Jeff Leuenberger (5-2), who has a
string of 15 consecutive scoreless innings, will start today
against A&AMP;M ace left-hander Casey Fossum (10-5). ... Crosby's left
toe, fractured a week ago, got worse following Thursday's workout
and he's now doubtful for the tournament. ... Catcher Bryan Kennedy
snapped an 0 for 12 skid with an eighth-inning single. ... Jaeme
Leal returned to first base after being restricted to DH duty the
previous 10 games because of a sore hamstring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
