<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SCHOOL BILL TALKS RUN LATE INTO NIGHT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY WALT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ While the two key negotiators on the $3.8
billion plan for funding public schools said they made ``good
progress on all fronts'' toward reaching an accord, no deal had
been struck by late Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some concepts,'' said Republican Sen. Teel Bivins of
Amarillo. But he would not specify what concepts he and state Rep.
Paul Sadler, D-Henderson, finally agreed on.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether both sides had given a little bit, Bivins replied:
``Well, one side gave a helluva lot.''
</P>
<P>
   If House conferees were willing, Bivins planned to schedule the
first public meeting of the conference committee early Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, House Democrats drew a line in the sand Friday
on school finance, refusing to give up even $1 for education
programs for the sake of more tax breaks and threatening to block
passage of any plan that does.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate negotiators remained deadlocked over how to
settle major differences between the two chambers' proposed funding
of public schools contained in Senate Bill 4, despite phone calls
from and meetings with Gov. George W. Bush and Lt. Gov. Rick Perry.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Bivins &UR;  &LR; has refused to call a public meeting of the
conference committee, opting instead to carry on in secret all
negotiations about how to re-allocate the largest school funding
bill in history.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins and most Senate conferees have refused to specify even
what options are being discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are totally opposed to taking money away from education
programs ... in order to fund additional tax cuts,'' said Rep.
Kevin Bailey, D-Houston. ``We have passed already in this session
significant tax cuts. ... The benefit to most Texans of those tax
cuts is very minuscule. However, the benefit to children with these
education programs is very significant.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey is chairman of the liberal Legislative Study Group, one
of three House caucuses that said Friday they would not budge on
their educational spending plan. That $3.8 billion proposal would
give all teachers a $3,000 across-the-board raise, increase the
state's per-pupil funding and provide the basis for about $1
billion in local property tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins, the chairman of the Senate Education Committee, had
proposed carving $250 million out of a $300 million plan the House
developed to create full-day kindergarten, pre-kindergarten, Head
Start and ninth-grade dropout prevention programs. The Senate
proposed using that $250 million to increase the overall tax cuts
granted this session to close to the $2.6 billion mark that Bush
set last year during his re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said Education Commissioner Mike Moses had told senators
that the entire $300 million could not be spent on the new programs
in the next two-year budget period anyway because they are new and
could not be operating by Sept. 1, when the fiscal year starts.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted Rep. Rene Oliveira, D-Brownsville and head of the
House Mexican American Caucus, to respond: ``I've never met a
school district that couldn't spend all the money it was given.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason to take $1 away,'' said Rep. Sylvester
Turner, D-Houston. ``So from our vantage point this is a silly
discussion to be having at this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in Texas. We're not in Iowa, we're right here in
Austin. We're going back to Houston, to the valley. We're going
back to San Antonio. We're going back to Beaumont. We're not going
to New Hampshire And the kids that we're fighting for are right
here in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   His comment was a jab at Bush, who is scheduled to head to Iowa
and New Hampshire, the first states to hold presidential nominating
contests, in mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor says that, well, if we don't finish up our
business, he may call a special session,'' Turner added. ``Well,
governor, bring it on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the choice is between fighting for our kids and their
education, and fighting for the tax breaks to business, that's a
fight well-taken.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler, chairman of the House Public Education Committee, had
said earlier Friday that he countered Bivins' suggestion with one
shifting money between two different funding formulas, but he was
vague about the exact proposal. Negotiators spent a good part of
the day reviewing analyses of how that would affect districts.
</P>
<P>
   Perry said the Senate is committed to maintaining the balance it
believes it achieved in its finance proposal and wants to make
certain that any compromise treats all areas of the state and all
types of school districts the same.
</P>
<P>
   He chafed at the suggestion that the Senate was taking money
away from school children. Public education, Perry said, got 75
percent of the new money in the state budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a rather substantial commitment to the children in the
state of Texas,'' he said. ``Any hard number that `We've got to
have this amount of tax cut' is secondary to having those public
schools and those children's issues addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Bivins had said earlier this week that if the Legislature could
not complete its work by noon Friday there would not be time to do
so before session's end on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers in both chambers acknowledged Friday that while they
still hoped to reach a compromise, time was getting short.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
