<SLUG> BC-NJ-HARASSMENT-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALE GUARD WINS DAMAGES IN SEXUAL HARASSMENT SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HACKENSACK, N.J. _ A jury awarded a male state prison guard
$3.75 million in damages on Friday after he charged that prison
supervisors had failed to protect him from sexual harassment by a
female guard whose advances he had rejected.
</P>
<P>
   The guard who filed the lawsuit, Robert Lockley, 39, a
corrections officer at the Mid-State Correctional Facility in
Wrightstown since 1985, was awarded $750,000 for emotional distress
and $3 million in punitive damages, said one of his lawyers, Daniel
Fleming.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a rare case,'' Fleming said. ``It's extremely rare for
a man to claim sexual harassment by women, and it's even rarer for
a man to win such a case. And to do that they have to overcome a
generation of thinking that men can't be sexually harassed.''
</P>
<P>
   A Burlington County jury of three men and three women granted
the award in state Superior Court in Mount Holly before Judge Jan
Schlesinger. Lockley sued the Department of Corrections and its
commissioner at the time, William Fauver, in October 1994. Fauver
was not found personally liable in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Malley, a spokeswoman for the state attorney general's
office, which defended the Corrections Department, said Friday that
the state was considering its options, which include a request for
a new trial and a request that the award be reduced or thrown out.
``We respect the jury's decision, but we disagree with it,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, according to Linda Wong, one of Lockley's lawyers, a
female corrections officer, Ronda Turner, began following Lockley,
complimenting him on his looks and his clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Lockley, who lives in Burlington County with his wife and two
children, tried to rebuff the officer politely, Ms. Wong said, but
the advances became more aggressive. ``She started following him
around everywhere he went, physically touching him,'' Ms. Wong
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the unwelcome advances turned to vicious verbal
assaults, Ms. Wong said. ``When he started turning her down, it
became a source of embarrassment for her, so she started ridiculing
him'' in public, Ms. Wong said. At times, she added, the taunts,
which often involved vulgarities, were heard by some of the 600
inmates at the prison.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wong said that after Lockley's verbal complaints were
ignored by supervisors, he filed an internal discrimination
complaint in July 1993, and in September the warden, Robert Barker,
asked Fauver to approve a transfer for Officer Turner, but the
request was denied. She was later brought up on administrative
charges, which were dismissed after a hearing in May 1994, Ms. Wong
said.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from being reassigned briefly, Officer Turner was never
disciplined, Ms. Wong said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Turner could not be reached through telephone calls to the
prison, her lawyer or the Corrections Department. Mary Ellen
Bolton, the chief of staff for Commissioner John Terhune, referred
inquiries to the attorney general's office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
