<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-HESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HESS EXCLUDED FAMILY FROM FUTURE OWNERSHIP OF JETS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The will of the late Jets owner Leon Hess never
explains why he did not wish his family to assume control of the
team, but he outlined the exclusion of his beneficiaries from any
roles under a new owner.
</P>
<P>
   Hess barred the sale ``of any interest, directly or indirectly,
to members of my family, as it is my intent that my interests in
the Jets be disposed of unaffected by any desire of family members
to participate in the club's future ownership.''
</P>
<P>
   Hess signed the will on March 26, six weeks before he died May 7
at the age of 85. The will was filed Friday in Surrogate Court in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In an indication of his determination to prevent family
involvement, Hess said, ``I do not want anyone interested in my
estate to question or in any way challenge the negotiations toward
the sale or the structure of or parties to the sale.''
</P>
<P>
   The will states that if any of Hess' beneficiaries or their
descendants challenge the team's sale, their bequests will be cut
by 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some NFL officials and fellow owners have said that Hess did not
want to burden his heirs with a decision over whether to sell or
retain the team, which a mandate to sell the team would avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Jets announced that the team would be sold, with
the negotiations to be handled by Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. The
investment firm helped the NFL sell the expansion Cleveland Browns
last September for $530 million.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are expected to sell for at least $500 million because
of the attractiveness of an NFL team in the nation's largest
market, and the league's television contracts.
</P>
<P>
   According to the will, Steve Gutman, the Jets' president, will
earn a small percentage of the sale price. He will receive 0.25
percent of the first $100 million of the sale price, 0.5 percent of
the next $100 million and 1 percent of any sum above $200 million.
At $500 million, Gutman would receive $3.75 million.
</P>
<P>
   The will does not offer suggestions to Goldman, Sachs about how
to structure the sale or about any buyers Hess preferred for the
team.
</P>
<P>
   Hess said he anticipated that selling the Jets would raise
enough money to pay most of the estate's debts, expenses and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   If the proceeds fall short, Hess offered three categories of
stocks and assets to sell, the last one being shares in the Amerada
Hess Corp., which he founded and which he ran until 1995. His son,
John, is now the chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Hess directed the executors of his estate to ``maximize the
value received and minimize the tax cost'' from the Jets' sale.
</P>
<P>
   The five executors include John Hess, Nicholas F. Brady, the
former Treasury secretary, and Thomas Kean, the former governor of
New Jersey, who are board members of Amerada Hess. John Hess will
receive $8.25 million as an executor, and Brady and Kean will
receive $1.5 million each. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-28-99 2330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990528.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-28 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
