<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDNAP-FAGAN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTAL KIDNAPER PLEADS GUILTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Stephen Howard Fagan Friday pleaded guilty to
kidnapping his two toddler daughters 20 years ago from a mother he
said was alcoholic and neglectful in exchange for a suspended
prison sentence, five years probation, and a $100,000 donation to a
children's charity.
</P>
<P>
   Ending a family saga marked by decades of deception, Fagan
walked from Middlesex Superior Court to enjoy a celebration dinner
with the two grown daughters who have steadfastly supported him
despite learning last year that he lied to them, telling them their
mother was killed in a car accident and raising them under the
false names of Rachael and Lisa Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was the first time the girls' mother, Barbara Kurth, has
been in the same room with her daughters since Fagan picked them up
for what was supposed to be a routine weekend visit in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Seated at opposite sides of the courtroom, mother and daughters
did not speak to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Richard Egbert told the court that his client
had responded to complaints from three North Adams neighbors who
telephoned Fagan 20 years ago to tell him that Kurth had left her
daughters, then 2 and 5, barely clothed in winter and fending for
themselves. Egbert told the court that Kurth had been stopped three
times for driving while drunk.
</P>
<P>
   Kurth, whose attorneys said she suffered from a rare form of
narcolepsy and severe depression during her divorce, slowly shook
her head side to side as Egbert portrayed her as unfit.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was the dedication of Fagan's daughters that
weighed most heavily in the minds of Middlesex County prosecutors
who knew the sisters could not be presented to a jury as victims
unless they conceded to the roles.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan created false identities for himself and the two girls,
and raised them in posh Palm Beach surroundings. As they have
before, the sisters publicly declared their faith in their father
Friday, telling Superior Court Judge Peter M. Lauriat that they
believe he acted as any responsible parent would have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the court to know that if we could retroactively give
our father the consent needed to take the action he did 20 years
ago, we would do so without hesitation,'' said Lisa Martin, sharing
in a prepared statement with her sister.
</P>
<P>
   Their mother, whose siblings said she has repeatedly tried to
contact her daughters in hopes of a reunion since Fagan's scheme
was uncovered last year, showed little emotion.
</P>
<P>
   Kurth declined to address the court, but submitted a written
statement saying in part: ``Some days I believe that Stephen fagan
would have been kinder to really have murdered me rather than
having done so only in the minds of my children. At least there
would have been no question as to his punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   At the afternoon press conference, the girls left open the
possibility they might some day speak with their mother, the woman
who named them Rachael and Wendy, and whose last photographs of
them showed two girls smiling at a family birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't acknowledge her Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Kurth's mother, clearly distraught, left her daughter's side
during the testimony, and family members later said she could not
bear the idea that Fagan, though convicted for parental kidnapping,
was allowed to walk free.
</P>
<P>
   Kurth's brother, Peter, said his family was not in favor of the
plea bargain but was aware of the challenges prosecutors would have
had convincing a jury that Fagan, 57, deserved prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not our deal,'' said Peter Kurth. ``This was Stephen
Fagan's deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Fagan was given two suspended sentences of 3-5 years at
MCI-Cedar Junction, and while on probation will be required to
perform 2,000 hours of community service with ailing veterans. He
will also donate $100,000 to the New England Home for Little
Wanderers in the name of Barbara Kurth, who chose the charity.
</P>
<P>
   Following his sentencing, Fagan issued a brief statement to
reporters, said he chose his parental duties over the letter of the
law when he abducted his children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I left Massachusetts some 20 years ago with two infants, two
suitcases, and a paper bag full of diapers,'' Fagan said. ``I was
raised in a home where the best interests of the children always
came first, and that is still the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Fagan, who was raised in Newton and met Barbara Kurth at a
Kenmore Square bar, was greeted in the courtroom by local friends
and family, including his current wife Harriet, who has helped
raise his daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Fagan, who has never apologized for his actions, declined to
answer questions about whether he feels any remorse or regret, and
said he could not predict whether his daughters will ever choose to
reunite with their mother.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Lauriat acknowledged that this unique case offered no
happy endings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a tragic, difficult and wrenching case for
everyone who has been victimized by Mr. Fagan's unlwaful conduct.
However, there are no perfect sentences that can be imposed, no
sentences that will satisfy all concerned as an ideal
representation of justice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Middlesex District Attorney Martha Coakley, who inherited the
case, said the daughters' belief that their father acted properly
was crucial to the plea agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a one of a kind case,'' Coakley said. ``And we believe
that it is not likely to happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   She continued, ``Perhaps more importantly, this sentence secures
a just result without subjecting the victims to the potential
trauma of trial.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear how many people Fagan confided in about the
abductions, but last year a relative allegedly told an attorney who
reported that Fagan was living under an assumed name in Palm Beach
to Massachusetts state police.
</P>
<P>
   A master of disguises, Fagan told friends and neighbors that he
was, among other things, a presidential advisor and a Harvard
graduate. But Friday Fagan acknowledged to the court that though he
graduated Suffolk Law School, he had not worked in 20 years. Those
who knew him in Palm Beach say he spent his days watching his
younger daughter, Rachael, win swimming competitions and
shepherding his eldest to a career in philanthropy, like her
stepmother's.
</P>
<P>
   The plea arrangement did not prevent any of those involved from
selling their stories to filmmakers or authors, though both sides
said Friday their primary concern was to remove the couple's
daughters from the media glare. Egbert declined comment about any
book or movie deal. Coakley said it was out of her control.
</P>
<P>
   Kurth, now a university researcher in Virginia, has no other
children. In her statement to the court, she defended her search
for her daughters, saying that law enforcment officials 20 years
ago were ignorant to pleas that her former husband had abducted her
children and brushed it off as merely a domestic dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Kurth urged family courts to develop a system for bringing
parental abducters to justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell you that after having met and received hundreds of
letters and E-mails from parents across this country and the world
that I am one of the lucky ones to finally know where and how my
chidlren are today,'' Kurth wrote. ``I can only say at this point
that I will always love them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
