<SLUG> BC-BKN-RADOJEVIC-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM MONTENEGRO TO THE NBA, RADOJEVIC HAS HIGH HOPES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Kan., Ohio)  (rk) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is just one more month left in Aleksandar Radojevic's
hurried odyssey to the NBA _ a month filled with tryouts in one
city after another, with four-hour training sessions and with
thousands of calories in protein shakes.
</P>
<P>
   And the pace of the final push is wearing on the gangly
22-year-old who did not start playing basketball in his native
Montenegro until he was 16, and who did not take the sport
seriously until he sprouted to nearly 7 feet by 19.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when the 7-foot-3-inch Radojevic lopes into a room,
shoulders hunched , he looks weary. This week alone, Radojevic,
with just two years of junior college experience to his credit, has
worked out in front of officials of the Knicks and Nets, and there
are at least seven more auditions to go, including one this weekend
for the Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   But the effort, Radojevic said, is more than worth it, for there
is much within his grasp and much to at last put behind him.
Radojevic's skills are rated so highly that he is expected to be
selected in the first round of the NBA draft June 30, and he may
well become the highest-drafted Yugoslav player. And with the
riches that will come, Radojevic will be able to pluck his family
from a part of the world that is once again convulsed by war.
</P>
<P>
   ``His skill level is off the charts,'' said Leo Papile, the
director of scouting for the Boston Celtics. Papile, figuring it to
be a thin year for big men, said Radojevic, who weighs 244 pounds,
could be one of the first two centers taken. ``He has a high
basketball IQ. He can move all the way up to the top half-dozen. He
is no secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, his availability in the draft is a surprise, to Radojevic
as much as anyone. As one of the nation's top junior college
prospects after averaging 15.4 points and blocking 153 shots last
season at Barton County Community College in Kansas, Radojevic had
signed a letter of intent to play for Ohio State next season.
</P>
<P>
   But on May 11, the NCAA ruled that because Radojevic received
$13,000 for playing a total of 19 minutes for a Yugoslav club team
two years ago, he was ineligible to play at Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   While speculation had swirled even before the ruling that
Radojevic's draft status was climbing so high he would forgo the
rest of his college eligibility, Radojevic says he was disappointed
by the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was eligible for Ohio State, I wouldn't have entered the
draft,'' said Radojevic, who added that he had wanted to polish his
talents and play for Jim O'Brien, the Ohio State coach. ``In your
life,'' he said, ``you've got your goal. You don't jump from one
step to the last step.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Radojevic has taken many steps very quickly over the last
several years. He did not give up his first passion, water polo,
until he was 16 and stood 6-5. And while the Balkans have long
produced outstanding basketball players _ Vlade Divac, Drazen
Petrovic and Toni Kukoc _ Radojevic didn't take his prospects
seriously until he grew another five inches by the time he was 19.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Semi Pajovic, a family friend and a former Yugoslav
national team player who helps other Yugoslavs find places to play
in the United States, had sized up Radojevic's potential. For
someone who had begun playing the game so late, Radojevic displayed
natural gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one tall, big kid,'' said Pajovic, who lives on Long
Island and is the host for Radojevic while he prepares for the
draft. ``He's unbelievably agile.''
</P>
<P>
   And as he advanced, coming to play for a club team, Radojevic
managed to avoid being drafted into the military. Montenegro is a
republic of Yugoslavia, and Pajovic suspects a sympathetic
basketball coach helped Radojevic stay out of the Yugoslav army
until he could go to the United States. The decision to leave, in
the end, was simple.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly a decade of war in the Balkans, Montenegro's
economy is a shambles. Radojevic's late father was a security
guard, and his mother worked in the fields. Together, they earned
about $2,400 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Radojevic, who was 20 when he left Montenegro, spoke no English,
making junior college his only option. Barton County, one of the
nation's premier junior college teams, already had a Yugoslav
player who had transferred from Connecticut. That player, Predrag
Materic, introduced Steve Forbes, then Barton's coach, to Pajovic.
Pajovic told Forbes he wanted to bring a 7-3 player over. Forbes
offered Radojevic a scholarship without even having met him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes walking into this airport in Kansas and says, `Hello,
how are you?' and that's all he could say,'' Forbes recalled. ``We
drive to Burger King, and he just pointed to chicken sandwiches and
orange juice. You could talk to him and he could understand it, but
there was no way he could talk to you.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just a tall, tall skinny kid with a great demeanor.
We're having a barbecue and he's out in the backyard chasing my
son, who's probably 2, playing cowboys and Indians. I have a
picture of him holding my son straight up in the air, and my son is
dunking on a 10-foot hoop and Alek is standing flat-footed.''
</P>
<P>
   Former St. John's coach Fran Fraschilla was one of the first
coaches to see Radojevic in the United States when the center
briefly stayed with Pajovic before leaving for Kansas. Now,
Fraschilla predicts he will be taken around 15th, and that it will
take a few years of strength training before he makes an impact on
the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed that a kid that big and that young had such a
good skill level,'' Fraschilla said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the war in the Balkans, Radojevic has not gone home
since coming to the United States, and he stayed in Kansas even
when his father died last season. When the NCAA ruled him
ineligible, the draft was the only viable option because a return
home would have surely meant being conscripted into the army and
perhaps being sent to fight in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would probably be the first on the front to be shot,'' he
said, alluding to his height. ``Going there would be jeopardizing
everything I built here. I'm focusing on something I'm going to be
doing for the next 15 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The war has left his small hometown on the Adriatic, Herceg
Novi, intact, but Radojevic, who learned his now-flawless English
from classes and television, worries that the scene of the conflict
could shift at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   He tries his best to block out reports of bombings, and their
attendant misery. As long as his mother keeps assuring him that his
family is fine, he said, he will continue to focus on basketball.
But as soon as he can after the draft, he will move his mother, his
twin brother and sister here.
</P>
<P>
   Where Radojevic will be drafted is still a question. Jeff Bower,
the Charlotte Hornets' scouting director, is less certain than
Papile of the Celtics. He said Radojevic is still something of an
unknown because he has faced only junior college competition, which
infrequently features anyone over 6-8.
</P>
<P>
   Radojevic, for his part, does not like to discuss his own
talent, saying he will let the scouts decide. There are seven
tryouts and a pre-draft camp in Chicago before this last, hectic
chapter in his journey ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought it would be this close,'' he said of his shot
at the NBA. ``My friends told me, `You're tall, you have to bend
over to take your money.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
